<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF MISSOURI SYSTEM CONSIDERS SCHOLARSHIP CUTBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The University of Missouri system is considering cuts in
scholarships as part of a larger plan to head off potential budget
problems in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say they must increase revenue and cut spending
because the university is squeezed by growing health-care costs,
smaller-than-requested inflationary increases from the General
Assembly, and a commitment to better faculty and staff raises.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of scholarship money had been on the rise at the main
campus in Columbia, contributing to MU's recent choice as the
nation's No. 1 ``Best Buy'' in the latest college rankings from
U.S. News &AMP; World Report.
</P>
<P>
   But now MU has begun trimming scholarships in a crusade to
balance the budget, including lowering the value of minority
scholarships by $1,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Without financial changes including additional unspecified
scholarship cuts, university system officials say, the campuses
could suffer multimillion dollar deficits within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   University system President Manuel Pacheco asked the chancellors
at each of the university's four campuses to determine how they
could spend less money and bring in more.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellors have given Pacheco their ideas, which he will
present Thursday (Sept. 2) to the university's nine-member
governing Board of Curators for approval.
</P>
<P>
   University officials have said that student scholarships
probably will have to be trimmed. Also, professor positions left
vacant by retirements or resignations may have to stay open.
</P>
<P>
   They have also suggested several ways to bring in more money.
The first is increasing enrollment 3 percent in the next five
years. Overall enrollment for the four campuses has increased
almost 2 percent in the last five years, but had fallen 7 percent
in the five years before that.
</P>
<P>
   The second is getting more grants and contracts, as well as
gifts from corporations and alumni. The third is undertaking more
entrepreneurial activities, such as opening research parks or
making money from campus research discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for budget changes was this year's flat $400 salary
increase for university professors and staff members.
</P>
<P>
   For many professors, that increase was less than 1 percent.
Professors and department heads on the campuses complained that
such meager increases would hamper efforts to attract the best
professors and would cause some professors to leave for better pay
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco said such poor raises could not be repeated, and he
wants to give 4 percent increases each year for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Faculty members say Richard Wallace, chancellor of the
University of Missouri-Columbia campus, told them the campus
probably would cut more than $2 million from the roughly $26
million in financial aid it hands out to undergraduate students.
</P>
<P>
   MU's ratio of money given back in financial aid to money brought
in through tuition is higher than at many other public
universities.
</P>
<P>
   That ratio, called a ``discount rate'' is about 32 percent at
MU, compared with an average of about 20 percent for public
universities.
</P>
<P>
   UMKC's discount rate is about 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Students are upset about the potential cutback, saying that they
once again are being asked to bear the brunt of fixing budget
problems at the university.
</P>
<P>
   When the curators wanted to improve the university in the early
1990s, they chose to pay for it partly by raising tuition 68
percent from 1992 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Sugg, legislative director for the Associated Students
of the University of Missouri, said students want officials to
seriously consider alternatives other than cutting back on
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the faculty raises were ridiculous. But we hope they
consider all possible resources, instead of taking it from the
financial-aid budget.''
</P>
<P>
   UMKC administrators would not disclose all the details of the
UMKC plan, but interim Provost Marjorie Smelstor said they include
increasing enrollment in certain programs, especially high-tuition
areas such as medicine and dentistry, leaving faculty positions
unfilled, and possibly trimming the amount of money given in
scholarships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
