<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-CORRECTING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' DEAL BRINGS A.C. BACK TO L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 GREEN'S STATS FROM LAST SEASON-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The Lakers finally dipped into the free-agent pool
Wednesday and added a big man, but the return of A.C. Green _ six
years removed from his glory years here, his numbers in decline _
is unlikely to fill their vacuum at power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who won championships with the Lakers in 1987 and '88,
was obtained in a sign-and-trade deal with the Dallas Mavericks,
who acquired reserve center Sean Rooks. Green, who played the last
two-plus seasons in Dallas, signed a three-year contract before the
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Lakers' decision to trade for Green, who turns 36
next month, rather than sign him as a free agent, indicates they
are still looking for help _ the one-for-one trade leaves the
roster at 11 players.
</P>
<P>
   The trade also reflected the Lakers' frustration with Rooks, who
signed a seven-year, $13.2 million contract with them three years
ago but never became a consistent backup to Shaquille O'Neal. The
Lakers unloaded the remaining four years and $9.12 million on his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The trade sends Rooks, a seven-year veteran, back to the team
that drafted him in 1992. And it brings Green back to his original
team, just in time to make another run at a championship or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the final result,'' said Green, who also
considered the Sacramento Kings and Miami Heat. ``There's just so
much history here. I have a long-term relationship here more than
with any other organization. It's just really something to be able
to come back and hopefully complete where you started a career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an answer to many close friends' prayers, to be sure.
I'm close to home (near Culver City) and to my home church and the
community here in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the devout Green is the answer to Laker fans' prayers,
the ones asking for a starting power forward, remains to be seen.
Green joins Robert Horry and Travis Knight in the mix, with no
clear starter among them.
</P>
<P>
   Though Green has averaged 10.4 points and 7.8 rebounds in his
14-year career, those figures dipped to 4.9 points and 4.6 rebounds
during the lockout-shortened 1999 season, and he was replaced in
the starting lineup by Gary Trent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm more than capable of playing whatever the position
might be or the minutes that might be required,'' said Green.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers also announced they have signed special consultant
Walt Hazzard to a two-year contract extension.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
