</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD AT LOSS FOR RIGHT WORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ (begin ital)I lost(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   Such a tiny phrase. Two little words. Five letters and a space.
If you wrote newspaper headlines in the era of pencil and paper,
you remember it's smaller than that, really just four letters,
because I, l, t and a space count a half-width.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the tabloid headline Evander Holyfield could write if
he said it.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)HOLY: I LOST(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   Think of the reaction.
</P>
<P>
   He'd be a rarity, a professional athlete willing to admit the
officials erred in his favor. He'd be hailed as unique, the last
honest man in big-time boxing.
</P>
<P>
   He'd be a bigger hero than he is already as a three-time
heavyweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   But Holyfield cannot bring himself to say it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't lose the fight,'' he said of the 12-round ``draw''
with Lennox Lewis last March in New York in which just about
everybody but Holyfield and two of the three judges saw Lewis
winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually think it was a draw,'' he said. ``I didn't take
anything away from him and he didn't take anything away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   And so on, as if he really believed what the rest of the world
does not.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were in Los Angeles on Wednesday, a day after
announcing they'll fight again Nov. 13 at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center
in Las Vegas, with Holyfield's IBF and WBA titles and Lewis' WBC
belt at stake and sharper judges at ringside.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who does not need the $15 million, said he's going
back into the ring for one reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a chance to redeem myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like a hint that in his heart, he feels Lewis
defeated him last time.
</P>
<P>
   So does his acknowledgement that he misjudged Lewis as a
one-dimensional puncher, his description of March 13 as ``one bad
day out of 365,'' and his excuse that he experienced stomach cramps
off and on throughout the day of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear, in a roundabout way, he's admitting he lost the fight
by saying he made mistakes,'' Lewis said in his turn at the
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   But coming right out and saying it is something Holyfield
apparently is unwilling to do.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's pride.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's Don King.
</P>
<P>
   If Holyfield acknowledges that the judges were wrong, that might
be interpreted as saying the judges were corrupt, and re-arm those
who think _ to put it bluntly _ King fixed the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing is the mere fact they would (begin ital)say(end
ital) that,'' King said with hurt in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   King, too, will not acknowledge the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who am I to second-guess the judges?'' said the man who's been
known to second-guess referees. ``I cannot say Holyfield lost the
fight. I can say this: It was a very, very unpopular decision. But
it was not a corrupt decision.... That (bribing judges) is not my
forte.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the unpopularity of the decision, Holyfield could score
points on the public scorecard by renouncing it, by saying his
record should read 36-4 instead of 35-3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The fact he won't do the popular thing, his camp argues, is a
sign of his integrity.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Jim Thomas, a Holyfield adviser, if it had been
difficult for the fighter to decide what to say about the
gift-wrapped draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been _ if Evander cared about saying the right
thing,'' Thomas said with a righteous smile.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, like Holyfield and King, thinks it was a draw.
</P>
<P>
   So why do so many people think Lewis pounded him?
</P>
<P>
   ``They were misled by the so-called experts,'' Thomas said,
contending the HBO commentators were biased toward Lewis, who has a
contract with HBO. ``It became a bandwagon because (writers) want
to bash boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans, he argued, are ``not sophisticated enough to judge what
they see for themselves. It's like if you're watching figure
skating, and Dick Button says, `That was a great triple toe-loop!'
You're going to say, `That must have been a great triple toe-loop.'
What do (begin ital)you(end ital) know?''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, we know what the computer statistics tell us _
that Lewis connected with 348 punches (and 65 percent of his power
punches), while Holyfield connected with 130 (and 36 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield offers a lame reply to those stats, suggesting the
fact the Englishman landed that many blows without knocking him
down is a sign of weakness rather than dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like tortured logic to an unsophisticate like me.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the kind of logic it takes to defend Eugenia Williams
and her fellow judges.
</P>
<P>
   You have to laugh at the informal title King has attached to the
Nov. 13 promotion: ``The Search for the Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Holyfield might be the only ones who haven't found it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
