<SLUG> BC-BAJA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZ. BIKER, 2 OTHERS DIE IN BAJA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - After years as a biker, Lloyd Hall discovered an
answer to tough situations: Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   From his home base in Topock, along the Colorado River, Hall
traveled the Southwest highways with his wife, Celina, spreading
the Lord's message to outlaws from the Hells Angels, Dirty Dozen
and other gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Deacon,'' Hall joined the national Christian
Motorcycle Association and organized a local group known as
Born-Again Riders.
</P>
<P>
   But, on Sunday, at a new home in Baja California, the
62-year-old Arizonan ran into someone who couldn't be swayed with
Bibles or bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican and U.S. authorities said Hall was stabbed and
bludgeoned to death by home intruders.
</P>
<P>
   The grisly episode in a community known as Punto Bandera was one
of two murder-robberies on Baja's Gold Coast, a retirement mecca
for U.S. citizens between Tijuana and Ensenada.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, officials said, Timothy Kusler, 60, and his
wife, Joanna, were beaten to death in their home at Playa de
Rosarito, a few miles down the beach. Little information was
available about the Kuslers, who also were listed as Arizona
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Lorena Blanco, a press officer with the U.S. Consulate's Office
in Tijuana, said the couple's home was ransacked. The Associated
Press, quoting Baja California state police, said the Kuslers were
attacked with an iron bar and a bricklayer's trowel. No suspects
have been arrested in that case.
</P>
<P>
   The Halls were victimized three nights later. They were living
in a trailer along the coast while their new home was under
construction. Mexican authorities said Lloyd Hall had stepped
outside to investigate a suspicious noise when at least two men
attacked _ again with a metal bar and other sharp objects.
</P>
<P>
   Hall managed to fire two shots, wounding an assailant in the leg
and torso. His wife got away after being slashed on the leg by the
intruders. Police later arrested gunshot victim Jose Luis Leon
Ramirez, who reportedly gave a confession.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Topock, across the California border from Needles,
expressed sorrow over the Halls' misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody just loved 'em,'' said Nicki Mellette, who served
them regularly at a Topock diner. ``They were the type of people,
even when they were eating in a restaurant, they said their
grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellette said there is talk of a motorcycle parade through town
in honor of the fallen biker.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Liston, Arizona coordinator for the Christian Motorcycle
Association, said he frequently came across the Halls on
proselytizing missions around the state.
</P>
<P>
   He said Lloyd Hall had owned a motorcycle business in Needles,
which he also used as an impromptu church.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a lot of ministry out of that shop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Liston said bringing the gospel to bikers is occasionally
dangerous, but road preachers have a maxim: ``When we're out there
doing God's ministry, he'll take care of us.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Hall had a special way of dealing with combative
road rogues: ``He taught us something that usually works with the
bikers. He'd say, `Are you the leader of this group?' If they said,
`No,' he'd say, `Well, I'm the leader of my group, and I only talk
to leaders. Hit the road.' They respected that.''
</P>
<P>
   No information was available on funeral services for any of the
homicide victims, or on Celina Hall's medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mexican and American officials emphasized that the
attacks were not part of a crime wave against tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Angel Isidro, Mexico's deputy counsel general in Phoenix,
described the homicides as random criminal events. He said U.S.
citizens who take normal travel precautions need not worry while
visiting Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, the media has a responsibility not to scare the
public,'' Isidro added. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from Alicia A. Caldwell. &QL; 
Dennis Wagner can be reached at (602) 444-8874 or at
dennis.wagner(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
