<SLUG> BC-PTA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY PTA GROUP IN SEATTLE MAY BE FIRST OF ITS KIND IN NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Heather's two mommies now have a PTA _ as does anyone
else who cares about gay and lesbian students or their families.
</P>
<P>
   Succeeding where another state failed, a Seattle-area group has
organized what is apparently the nation's first gay and lesbian
Parent Teacher Association.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say the group is meant to address the ``unique
challenges and difficulties'' often faced in schools by students,
educators and families who are gay, lesbian, bisexual and
transgendered.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington State PTA is expected to formally grant a charter
to the group as soon as its final paperwork is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Some 50 people have signed on so far to join the group, called
the Gay Lesbian Parent Teacher Student Association of Greater Puget
Sound. Like many PTAs, the group added ``Student'' to its name and
is known as a PTSA.
</P>
<P>
   Goals include fighting the problems that studies show homosexual
students are more likely to face: harassment, abuse, higher dropout
rates and increased suicide risks.
</P>
<P>
   Members say the group is open to everyone: parents of gay or
lesbian students, straight students with gay or lesbian parents, or
anyone else who supports their mission, regardless of sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to form a similar group last year in Dade County, Fla.,
were rebuffed by the Florida State PTA, where leaders saw the
proposed group as a special interest organization that would either
duplicate or detract from the work of traditional school-based
PTAs.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle activist Linda Jordan, representing a group called
Parents and Teachers for Responsible Schools, raised similar
concerns Wednesday. She called the local gay PTSA an ``exclusive''
group set up by homosexual activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another way to carry out an agenda, and I think it's
totally inappropriate,'' she said, asking whether educators or
students who consider homosexuality wrong will be labeled bigots.
</P>
<P>
   But Gay Lesbian PTSA President Susan Carmel, a straight parent
who said her now-grown gay son was miserably harassed in middle
school, countered that the group is far from exclusionary.
</P>
<P>
   She said the group has many straight members and a mission that
will benefit all schools and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The learning stops when kids feel threatened like this,'' she
said. ``They do not feel safe in schools, and there is no reason
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, some Gay Lesbian PTSA projects might have nothing
to do with gays or lesbians, Carmel said. One early idea is for the
group to help a school without its own PTA with needed projects,
such as cleaning the playground.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Bond, a regional PTA director whose territory includes
Seattle, thought that would be a good way to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take away the demonization of homosexuality, that somehow
these people are different and strange,'' she said. ``They're
people who care just like everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond expects the group to complement rather than drain local
school-based PTAs.
</P>
<P>
   Parents have said in surveys that they weren't comfortable
bringing up issues surrounding gay or lesbian students at their
regular PTA meetings, and felt uneasy bringing gay or lesbian
partners to school, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to have a place where people could be open and
comfortable,'' Bond said in welcoming the new group.
</P>
<P>
   The gay PTSA is starting off as a regional group, not attached
to any one school or district, although it may split into chapters
as it grows.
</P>
<P>
   State PTAs, rather than the national organization, have sole
authority over approving or declining new Parent Teacher
Associations and Parent Teacher Student Associations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't anything that limits what you can form a PTA
around,'' said Jim Carpenter, executive director of the Washington
State PTA. The PTA mission is broad, encompassing children's
health, safety, and education in and out of school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nontraditional'' PTAs, such as senior citizens PTAs, already
exist and are probably the wave of the future, Carpenter said. The
state group has fielded questions about PTAs based on ethnic and
cultural groups, and such groups will likely follow the Gay Lesbian
PTSA's lead, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National PTA has offered no public direction on which
state's approach _ Florida's or Washington's _ was in line with the
national organization's goals. The Florida state PTA, however, said
it researched the issue with National PTA attorneys before
rejecting the Florida group.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the National PTA wasn't familiar with the
issue, but said PTAs wouldn't normally represent a specific segment
of the community. The National PTA director did not return phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Even with support from the Washington State PTA, the gay Puget
Sound group is braced for controversy as the school year starts.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Public Schools faced an outcry in 1997 after accepting a
grant to distribute books to elementary schools about gay and
lesbian families, such as ``Heather Has Two Mommies.'' The ruckus
led to the formation of Parents and Teachers for Responsible
Schools, the group Jordan leads.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado in 1994, one PTA chapter announced plans to disband
after the state PTA recommended a resolution that schools teach
tolerance of gays and lesbians. The measure was defeated, and the
disbanding branch said such issues were beyond the PTA's scope.
</P>
<P>
   But they're vitally important to new Gay Lesbian PTSA members
like Greg Stair, an art teacher in the Everett School District.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the group partly because of the bullying and insults
he sees directed toward gay and lesbian students _ or students who
are rightly or wrongly perceived as gay.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, he said, people think it is acceptable to use
demeaning slurs or ``to pick on anybody they see as having a
questionable sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that can help out in getting the word out that that's
not OK, that there are resources available (for students), to me is
a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmel said she hopes membership will grow as word spreads about
the new group.
</P>
<P>
   One likely candidate is parent Gabi Clayton, who applauded the
gay PTSA's formation from her Olympia home and said she hopes to
join.
</P>
<P>
   Her 17-year-old son, Bill, who was bisexual, committed suicide
in 1995 afer he was beaten in what was regarded as a hate crime on
a high school campus during spring break.
</P>
<P>
   All the teenager could see ahead, Clayton said, was ``a lifetime
of facing a world filled with hate and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   She's worked to eliminate such hatred in the years since his
death.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said, ``I know and hear every day the horror stories.
Honestly, we still have a long way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
