<HEADLINE>
VALDES' BAD LUCK CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers lost 5-4 to Milwaukee in the finale of
a three-game series Wednesday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Dodgers lost a close one. Right-hander Ismael
Valdes pitched, so that has to happen. Valdes is 9-12, and nine of
those losses have come by one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a frustrating year,'' Valdes said in echoing
statements that seem to accompany nearly every one of his starts.
``Maybe next year I'll have better luck. My luck could change next
season.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a number of things that hurts Valdes, from fielding errors
to lack of hitting in the clutch to ill-timed pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers scored three unearned runs in the first inning when
shortstop Mark Grudzielanek booted what should have been the third
out. The offense ``helped'' in the misery by going 1 for 15 with
runners in scoring position. Grudzielanek's three-run triple in the
seventh was the only hit while Gary Sheffield failed to score a
runner from third with less than two outs on three occasions.
</P>
<P>
   And there was also Valdes, who hung tough for six innings but
gave up two runs on a two-out single in the seventh when the
Brewers went ahead 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``The killer was the last two,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``(Valdes) got behind (Mark Loretta), and not wanting to walk
him... he's a pretty good fastball hitter and hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charting 20: The Dodgers have their rotation set up for Kevin
Brown to get seven more starts in his quest for 20 wins. To
accomplish that, Brown, who is 15-6, would be slated to pitch the
last game of the season in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is on a six-game winning streak and hasn't lost since July
5, a span of 11 starts. In that time, Brown has a 2.56 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's next start will be Saturday against the Chicago Cubs at
Wrigley Field. He flip-flopped with Darren Dreifort, who will start
Sunday. Brown is also scheduled to pitch against Montreal and close
out his home season against San Diego. Those three teams are a
combined 54 games under .500.
</P>
<P>
   The other four starts are against the Mets, San Francisco
(twice) and Houston, which are a combined 61 games over .500. But
the task isn't as arduous considering Brown's success against the
Giants. He's 1-0 with a 2.46 ERA against them this season, and 7-0
with a 0.78 ERA in his career.
</P>
<P>
   For all his success, Brown hasn't won 20 games often. The only
time he's accomplished the feat was when he went 21-11 for Texas in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Cromer activated: After spending nearly two months on the
disabled list with an irregular heartbeat, utility infielder Tripp
Cromer was activated. He was the only one activated with rosters
expanding from 25.
</P>
<P>
   Cromer, who's hitting .208 in 29 games, played all four infield
positions during a rehab assignment with Single-A San Bernardino.
He went 9 for 18 with a homer and eight RBI.
</P>
<P>
   But what Cromer does in the last month could determine where he
winds up next season, either with the Dodgers or another
organization. A middle infielder by trade, there is interest in the
31-year-old because of his versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a team like this, it helps you to be able to do
everything,'' Cromer said. ``I know there's been some interest
(from other teams), but I'd like to stay here and win here.''
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Right-handers Robinson Checo (groin) and Antonio Osuna
(elbow) were scheduled to make rehab appearances for San Bernardino
on Tuesday.... The Dodgers are 19-23 in one-run games.... The
23,616 in attendance was the smallest crowd at Dodger Stadium this
season.... Grudzielanek extended his hitting streak to nine games.
</P>
</TEXT>
