<SLUG> BC-BEANIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEANIE BABY BYE-BYE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN CRENO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix - The Beanie Baby world is buzzing with rumors.
</P>
<P>
   The company that makes the fuzzy little plush toys said it's
``retiring'' its current crop of Beanies at the end of the year,
sending collectors into a panic and flooding stores with buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are flocking in to buy up what they can,'' said Mark
Besler, owner of Dolls Bears &AMP; Surprises in Phoenix. ``They want to
make sure they have them. People who procrastinated before are
picking them up now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ty did nothing Wednesday to clarify things. It did not return
calls, and some Beanie-savvy observers thought that made plenty of
sense, calling the uproar a calculated piece of hype that worked
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Ty Warner knows exactly what he's doing in marketing,''
said Linda Burner, co-owner of Bears &AMP; More in Glendale. ``He's a
genius. Why would you stop making a product that sells for $5 that
everybody wants?''
</P>
<P>
   Burner, a Beanie collector, said the announcement couldn't have
been better timed. She said it came when a new line of the Furby
toy called Furby Babies was hitting the market and overshadowed
that launch.
</P>
<P>
   Ty Inc., the Illinois company that makes Beanies, posted its
``retiring'' Beanies announcement on its Internet site Tuesday,
then removed it. The announcement ran at the end of a list of new
Beanies that included ``The End'' black bear - an apparent
reference not only to the end of the century but the conclusion of
the current line of Beanies.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to set off bombardment of Beanie rumors, fueled
in part by media speculation that Ty was getting out of the Beanie
Baby business entirely. Web sites for Beanie fans were loaded with
grief-stricken postings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just totally shocked that Ty is quitting with the
Beanies. It's just hard to believe,'' one writer said on Ty's chat
page.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was so out of hand by the end of Tuesday that
company owner Ty Warner tried to clear up things with his own
message on the chat page.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the millennium is coming to an end. I assure you the
beanies will not end,'' the message said.
</P>
<P>
   Beanie collectors weren't calmed. The phone started ringing at
Millie's Hallmark in the Ahwatukee-Foothills at 8:30 a.m.
Wednesday. The store opens at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``All day long it's been people coming in and calling,''
assistant manager Cheryl Dekker said.
</P>
<P>
   But one large collector said Tuesday that the speculation among
dealers is that Ty simply planned to introduce dozens of new
beanies next year and that the retirement was simply manufactured
to help the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secondary market has collapsed the market in the last six
months,'' said George Papania of Georges Video Games and
Collectables in Las Vegas. ``What we did was retaliate for the fact
that they kept these things out too long without retiring them.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally intended to be a cheap toy for kids, Beanie Babies
retail for about $5. But collectors have taken over a big part of
the market and some hard-to-find Beanies can fetch thousands of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors call stores constantly to find out exactly when the
new, most sought-after ones will hit the shelves, and sometimes
camp out for hours to snare one.
</P>
<P>
   Sari Powazek, owner of The Doll House in Scottsdale, has seen
toys come and go, but nothing to rival the Beanies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never ever seen anything as crazy as this and we have
been in the toy business for 22 years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Healis of Glendale has Beanies piled on her side of the
bed when she's not sleeping in it. She finds them irresistibly
cute.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just adorable,'' she said. ``For the price you can't
beat them. They make a beautiful gift.''
</P>
<P>
   But some are puzzled by the Beanie phenomenon. Jonathan Adolph,
executive editor of ``Family Fun,'' a general-interest family
magazine based in Northampton, Mass., said frenzied bidding for
Beanies and for such hot Christmas toys as Tickle Me Elmo sends a
bad message to kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``For kids, it's one of these classic lessons of supply and
demand,'' he said. ``We see the same lessons every year. It's kind
of a sad commentary on social values when you turn something not
inherently valuable to a hugely inflated price.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Glen Creno can be reached at (602) 444-7483 or at
glen.creno &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
The New York Times contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0010 </DOCNO>
