<SLUG> BC-TIMBER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLICKMAN DEFENDS MUCH-ASSAILED NORTHWEST FOREST PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT MCCLURE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's been called ``a demonstrable failure'' by a U.S.
senator from Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   A key environmentalist this week deemed the Northwest Forest
Plan ``broken.''
</P>
<P>
   And the timber industry insists the plan ``will never work.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, visiting Seattle
Wednesday, said the effort to protect old-growth forests, spotted
owls and other threatened species is fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may remember eight or nine years ago, people were at the
proverbial loggerheads,'' said Glickman, whose agency oversees the
U.S. Forest Service. ``There was almost a revolution between timber
interests and environmental interests. That is no longer the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments were the first by a high-ranking Clinton
administration official since U.S. District Judge William Dwyer, in
a strongly worded ruling last month, halted dozens of federal
timber sales from Washington to Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer said the government approved logging on federal lands
without looking hard enough to see whether sensitive plants and
animals would be harmed.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer ruled that the government's shortcomings were ``unlawful
... far from being minor or technical violations'' and were
``contrary to the plain language'' of the Northwest Forest Plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read the (judge's) decision. The decision in no way says
the plan is a failure or that our compliance is a failure,''
Glickman said. ``In fact, I think the decision assumes that the
plan is substantially a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said the Forest Service believes it has done enough to
seek out the sensitive plants and animals, even though Dwyer
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the issue is expected to be raised again in
Washington, D.C. A vote is expected on a maneuver by Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., that would undercut Dwyer's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton inserted a provision into a spending bill that would give
the government full discretion in deciding how hard to look for the
sensitive plants and animals, no matter what federal judges say.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration opposes that measure. Instead, it is
planning to readjust the rules governing the Northwest Forest Plan
early next year, including the requirements to seek out the
sensitive plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said scientists are learning more all the time about
how to seek out the protected plants and animals, which are
primarily secretive creatures such as small rodents and salamanders
and hard-to-find plants such as lichens and mosses.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have said the surveys for the plants and
animals they originally agreed to in the 1993 plan are too
difficult or, in some other cases, too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``At most, the judge's ruling reflects his desire to see us
comply with his interpretation of some of the language in the
plan,'' Glickman said. ``This is not in any way, shape or form a
condemnation of the plan or our efforts to comply with it. I really
am convinced of that.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way environmentalists see it, though.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, several dozen environmental groups, including some
of the same ones that sued in Dwyer's court to stop the federal
timber sales, are sending a letter to President Clinton expressing
``deep disappointment'' over administration policy on Pacific
Northwest forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The required wildlife surveys are the bare minimum mitigation
for continued destruction of old-growth,'' says a draft of the
letter to Clinton. ``If the surveys are in fact not feasible,
old-growth logging is no longer ecologically or legally
justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the signatories is the Oregon Natural Resources Council,
the lead plaintiff among 13 in the case before Dwyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is broken,'' said Doug Heiken of the ONRC. ``The plan
is a failure. The plan may never have been viable because it's
based on the logging of old growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., told an audience in rural
Douglas County that the plan is ``a cruel hoax ... a demonstrable
failure.'' Smith supports Gorton's effort to undercut the judge's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Northwest Forest Plan was hammered out,
environmentalists had virtually stopped logging of old-growth
forests. The plan allows some limited logging of old-growth forests
to continue, on the theory that if the cut is slowed down, some
other, medium-age stands will grow into the kind of forests needed
by spotted owls and hundreds of other kinds of animals and plants.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists challenged the plan immediately after its
adoption in 1993, saying it allowed a third or more of the region's
old-growth forests to be logged. Dwyer rejected that challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists' letter to Clinton cites a recent study by
an Oregon economist that found that logging is becoming less and
less important to the economy of the region. It accounts for 3.1
percent of Pacific Northwest employment. And, as Dwyer noted in a
ruling last week, most of those jobs are based on logs coming from
private lands, or those owned by the state government _ not federal
timber sales.
</P>
<P>
   The timber industry has long said the Northwest Forest Plan is
unworkable, said Jim Geisinger, president of the Northwest Forestry
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton administration has placed so many restrictions on
the Forest Service that it's impossible for them to deliver even
the small amount of timber that is called for in the Northwest
Forest Plan,'' Geisinger said.
</P>
<P>
   He said environmentalists, by shutting down timber sales
expected when the plan was hammered out in 1993, ``have moved the
goal post again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind that the Forest Service did not
do what the plan said it was supposed to do,'' Geisinger said.
``... There's not enough money in Fort Knox or enough experience in
the scientific community'' to conduct the thorough surveys
contemplated in the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Geisinger said several small family-run timber mills in Oregon,
because of Dwyer's rulings, have no lumber supply for 2000 and the
first part of 2001 and will probably have to be closed.
</P>
<P>
   He could provide no estimate for how many jobs, overall, may
eventually be affected. He said it could be a few hundred or even
as many as 1,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
