<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACHINISTS APPROVE CONTRACT OFFER FROM BOEING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Boeing Machinists endorsed a three-year contract offer
Wednesday, a move that buys the company three years of labor peace
and provides a competitive wage increase to 44,000 Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   The contract covers the largest union at the Seattle-based
aerospace giant and serves as a model for other union contracts
within the company. It also stands to inject more than $100 million
into the local economy from bonuses paid to workers for endorsing
the pact.
</P>
<P>
   Workers weighed a package that offers a 4 percent raise in each
of the first two years, a 3 percent increase in the third year and
a 10 percent lump-sum bonus this year. Equally important to many
Machinists is what the company didn't push: a seven-day workweek
and new health care premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers welcomed the package, saying it was a fair offer
that they were unlikely to improve by striking.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, workers felt they were able to secure concessions
from Boeing because the company is attempting to rebound from two
years of production and financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think the company had to put its best foot forward,''
said Maureen Allen, who has worked at Boeing for 22 years, after
she cast her vote at the Renton union hall. ``The company was fair
on all the important issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing needed ratification of the contract to eliminate its
greatest labor threat because competition with rival Airbus
Industrie for new customers is intensifying. It also couldn't
afford a disruption in production in a year it's scheduled to
deliver a record 620 airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives decided ``a good relationship with its work
force was critical in a very competitive industry,'' said Harley
Shaiken, a professor of labor relations at the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will pay a price for peace with its most powerful labor
union, the International Association of Machinists. For example,
the company will pay nearly $200 million in bonuses to the
Machinists this year under the contract proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the company couldn't afford a strike,'' said Bill
Johnson, the president of the union's District Lodge 751 and a key
negotiator. ``We capitalized on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Chairman Phil Condit had a different take on the
contract. He held it up as another step in the company's effort to
boost productivity and become more competitive in the aerospace
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``With ratification, we can move forward and bring the full
measure of our skills and productivity to the workplace,'' Condit
wrote in an open letter to employees. ``It's more than fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The broad support for the offer stands in stark contrast to the
last round of negotiations in 1995, when Machinists struck for 69
days after rejecting a contract offer and their union leaders'
endorsement of the language. In fact, union members struck during
two of the past three contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was pleased with the offer this time either. Some
workers charged that negotiators failed to protect their jobs from
being sent outside to independent contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want any more money. I just want a job,'' said Beverly
Wickham, an 18-year Boeing employee, after she cast her ballot
against the contract in Renton.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials argued they secured additional job security for
their members. They pointed to a provision that stated Boeing won't
lay off employees because of either subcontracting. In addition,
the contract would allow a joint union-company committee 180 days
to review subcontracting initiatives and to suggest alternative
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, however, retained the right to hire outside contractors
and to lay off workers in other circumstances, such as a downturn
in airplane orders.
</P>
<P>
   Other workers were upset the company only offered to boost
monthly pension benefits by 25 percent. They added that the
contract didn't offer a cost-of-living adjustment for Boeing
retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the criticism, union leaders were optimistic since
ending negotiations early Saturday morning that their members would
ratify the proposal when they voted in union halls in Puget Sound,
Spokane, Portland, Ore., and Wichita, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Under union rules, a contract must win support of a simple
majority of those voting. However, if less than two-thirds of those
voting support the second question on the ballot _ whether to
endorse a strike _ the contract also goes into effect.
</P>
<P>
   The latest information on the contract vote is posted on the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer's Web site (www.SeattleP-I.com) as well
as the union's site, (www.IAM751.org). Information from the company
can be found at its Web site (www.Boeing.com).
</P>
<P>
   The current contract expired Thursday at 12:01 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, some Machinists said they didn't think they could
gain much more by putting their tools down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably as good as we are going to get,'' said Wayne
Ward, who has worked at Boeing for the past three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
