<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8172 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      09-02 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. STILL WAGING WAR ON OLD VET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - One day last week, after listening to a prosecutor and
a defense attorney argue about evidence and disclosure for about 20
minutes, U.S. Magistrate Morton Sitver suddenly decided the trial
scheduled to begin that morning would be postponed until October.
</P>
<P>
   Sitver then picked up his gavel and adjourned the court, his
mallet landing squarely between the shoulders of Bob DeHeer.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   The old veteran slumped forward in his chair, leaning on the
cane he held with his hands, his head shaking slowly from side to
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``All rise,'' declared the clerk as Judge Sitver strode from the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   DeHeer pushed hard on the walking stick, wearily lifting himself
from a chair at the defense table. He is 77 years old and suffers
from arthritis, bad hearing and other maladies of an aging warrior.
</P>
<P>
   Standing up would be a lot easier for him if he also didn't have
the full weight of the U.S. Department of Justice on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable,'' DeHeer said afterward. ``Who would
have guessed that all this would happen over a parking spot?''
</P>
<P>
   In May, DeHeer drove to the Carl T. Hayden Veterans Affairs
Medical Center to have his hearing aids adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   When he got there, DeHeer says he couldn't find an available
handicapped parking space nearby, so he decided to park in one of
several vacant spots marked temporarily with ``VIP'' signs. &QL; 
BUREAUCRATS VS. VETS &QL; 
Federal inspectors were visiting the hospital that day, and VA
administrators apparently believed the convenience of bureaucrats
was more important than the convenience of World War II vets like
DeHeer.
</P>
<P>
   What happened after DeHeer tried to pull into one of the VIP
spaces became the subject of his trial.
</P>
<P>
   One of the federal officers patrolling the parking lot told
DeHeer that he couldn't park in a VIP spot because he wasn't a VIP.
This didn't sit well with DeHeer, and after an angry exchange, the
elderly man was hauled off in handcuffs and locked in a cell.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of hours later, he was released, but not before being
issued two citations, a $50 disorderly conduct charge and a $25
ticket for failing to comply with a federal officer.
</P>
<P>
   DeHeer could have paid the fines and walked away and that would
have been the end of it.
</P>
<P>
   But he chose to fight.
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago, when his country asked him to stand and fight
rather than turn and walk away, DeHeer stood his ground and fought.
</P>
<P>
   Old habits are hard to break.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time machine-gunner with a Bronze Star and a Purple
Heart and bad hearing and arthritis refused to pay the fines and
demanded his day in court.
</P>
<P>
   The government could have backed off. &QL; 
CASE NOT DISMISSED &QL; 
Even better, the government could have recognized that Bob DeHeer
and every veteran like him has earned the title VIP, qualifying him
to park in a space reserved for such individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The case could have _ and should have _ been dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the U.S. Attorney's Office decided to drag DeHeer into
court.
</P>
<P>
   I've asked Justice officials why they're doing it, but I've
never gotten an answer. Maybe it's only because they can.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, DeHeer found himself in the federal courthouse in
Phoenix watching attorneys argue complicated legal issues until his
case was postponed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been very hard on Bob,'' said his attorney, Michael
Rooney. ``I believe it's tragic for a fellow of his age and
background to have to go through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tragic, and confusing.
</P>
<P>
   You can see it on Bob DeHeer's face. Not the anger he felt that
day in the parking lot. Not the outrage he felt over having been
fined. Just _ bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   And who could blame him?
</P>
<P>
   A man like DeHeer, a soldier, a patriot, an old-fashion
idealist, never dreamed he'd one day do battle against the country
for which he'd help win a war. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT     09-02 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS STILL LEADS YANKEES IN QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Yankees' players and manager, Joe Torre, talked as if the
Roger Clemens issue was largely a creation of the public's
imagination before Wednesday night's game against the Oakland
Athletics. They said that Clemens had been pitching well lately and
that the perhaps unrealistic expectations that have been heaped
upon his burly shoulders were responsible for the perception that
he is struggling mightily in the historic pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   They seemed to be hoping that the Clemens they disbanded a
proven rotation for had finally arrived, that his splendid
performance in Friday's victory over the Seattle Mariners was
evidence that he was back to being the intimidating hurler who had
won five Cy Young Awards.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently that Clemens is not back, even if the Yankees,
who stuck to their story after Clemens was tagged by the A's, are
unwilling to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   For what seems like the umpteenth time this season, Clemens
followed an outstanding outing with a poor one. He was not horrible
Wednesday night, just mediocre enough to walk four batters, hit
another, and be ripped for 5 runs on 6 hits in 7 innings in the A's
embarrassingly thorough 7-1 victory over the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in four meetings this season that Omar
Olivares (13-9, 3.84 era) has beaten the Yankees and enabled the
A's to stay within two games of Boston in the American League
wild-card race, a race that if the A's win could land them opposite
the Yankees in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern to the Yankees, however, was the work of
Clemens, who for the eighth time faltered badly in the immediate
aftermath of a sparkling performance. In the eight starts after a
game in which he has allowed zero or no earned runs, Clemens has
surrendered 33 earned runs in 43 1/3 innings. He is 1-2 in those
games with a 6.85 ERA. Following the four games in which he allowed
no runs, Clemens has a 7.94 ERA (20 runs in 22 2/3 innings) and an
0-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   While it would seem that Clemens' almost predictable ebbs and
flows would dash the beliefs within the organization that his
troubles are over, that is not the case. Torre and the catcher, Joe
Girardi, raved about Clemens' pitching afterwards, and even the
notoriously dissatisfied Clemens said he had good stuff. ``I don't
think the score tells you about his stuff,'' Torre said. ``His
fastball tonight was better than it has been all year. His stuff
was terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Girardi said: ``If he has that stuff nine out of 10 times, we
win. Tonight just happened to be that one time. I'm baffled by it
to be honest.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the wicked velocity on his fastball, Clemens'
control was a problem _ two of the batters he walked scored _ and
all five of the runs he surrendered came with two outs. When a
pitcher of Clemens' stature is on, that does not happen.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling heading into the game was that Girardi, who caught
Clemens' 8-inning, 0-run gem against Seattle last week, had
developed a chemistry with Clemens. Last week's game was the first
time in two-and-a- half months that Girardi caught Clemens. With
Clemens responding positively to the experienced Girardi, Torre
went with the battery again.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the move looked like it would pay off, as Clemens
threw with power in recording four strikeouts and allowing no hits
through the first three innings. But then he began to unravel. He
walked Rich Becker to start the fourth, then, after striking out
Randy Velarde, was hit hard for a single to center field by Jason
Giambi. Next, he walked Olmedo Saenz before Ben Grieve, who was
3-for-4, laced a ground-ball double down the third base line and
past a lunging Luis Sojo to score Becker and Giambi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had good stuff so I wanted to be aggressive,'' said Clemens,
who dropped to 12-7 with a 4.54 ERA. ``The first two runs they got
was just a good pitch and he fired it inside the line and that
really doesn't get you upset as much as the one where they kind of
broke the game open with the two other runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Those came in the sixth inning, when Clemens allowed Giambi to
single, walked Saenz and then was foiled again by Grieve after
serving up a two-run forkball for a single. Boos from the crowd of
34,468 came raining down on Clemens after that, and after watching
his pitcher walk Becker in the seventh and allow another run on a
Velarde double off the left field fence (just past the outstretched
glove of Ricky Ledee), Torre let Clemens finish out the inning and
then went to his bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a good job hitting the forkball,'' said Clemens, who
got a blister on the middle finger of his right hand late in the
game. ``He didn't try and pull it. I think if he gets anxious and
tries to pull it, I get the results I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   CHILI DAVIS &UR;  &LR; retired the league's longest streak without a
triple, a span of 2,216 at-bats, when he drilled an offering by
OMAR OLIVARES &UR;  &LR; high off the right-field fence. It was Davis' first
triple since May 11, 1994, when he played for the California
Angels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
