<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-POOCHES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SICK ANIMALS FIND FRIEND IN MONICA'S DAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOMINIC BERBEO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In an only-in-L.A. confluence of national
celebrity and pampered pets, Monica Lewinsky's father has announced
plans to use his L.A. cancer clinic to help cure sick animals.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Lewinsky is teaming with Dr. Rodney Ayl, a
veterinarian oncologist, to treat animals of all sizes, including
their latest patient, a snow leopard from Moonridge Animal Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many things happen in Los Angeles,'' Lewinsky said Wednesday
as he watched Ayl treating Chago the snow leopard for a cancerous
growth on the mouth. ``L.A. sets the pace for novel ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky said he was glad to be in the spotlight for something
other than the Monicagate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as hard as last year,'' he said. ``A total intrusion
and scrutiny of every aspect of our family was the last thing we
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Monica is ``doing fine'' in New York, and he expects her
to do well at her new business of selling handbags over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the focus was on pets as patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is coming to expect at least the same level of care
for their pets that they can get for themselves because they
consider them a member of the family,'' said Ayl.
</P>
<P>
   There are other locations offering cancer treatments for pets,
including UCLA Medical Center's new Veterinary Radiation Oncology
Facility, which treats dogs and cats.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ayl's clients, Steve Kokinis, said the therapy on his
9-year-old Samoyed named Gorbachev for a precancerous growth on his
jaw was well worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider Gorby to be like a member of the family,'' he said.
``The other alternative would have been to cut half his jaw off,
and I never would have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kokinis said he came from Eagle Rock for the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Ayl said he uses chemotherapy to treat an average of eight to 10
pet patients a day, mostly dogs. He also has worked on more exotic
animals, such as the snow leopard, a boa constrictor and an
orangutan.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost: $3,000 for a full treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Ayl calculates the success rate for curing pets to be as high as
50 percent, depending on the type of cancer and stage of illness.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky said the idea to treat pets at the Western Tumor
Medical Group clinic came from several of his patients with pets,
who then put him in contact with Ayl.
</P>
<P>
   He said he rents equipment, including a $1 million linear
accelerator used for radiation treatments, to Ayl for treatment.
Sometimes he informally lends his expertise.
</P>
<P>
   More and more people are willing to pay the $3,000 for cancer
therapy for their pets, he said, roughly the same price as for
human treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Herron brought his 5-year-old Labrador retriever named
Cinder from Malibu for treatment of a cancerous growth on the nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't cheap, but it's worth it,'' he said. ``She's a great
dog, and she picks up my ducks when I go hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   As pet owners are increasingly willing to spend big money on
their animals, a new industry is blossoming in the form of
veterinary medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Ayl said many of his clients' pets are covered by insurance, and
Lewinsky said sometimes the animal policies pay higher
reimbursements than HMO policies for humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad comment on our society,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BOEING-UNION-NYT &LR;      09-02 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGEST UNION AT BOEING VOTES TO ACCEPT PROPOSED CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Ore., Kan.)  (js) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boeing &UR;  &LR; Co.'s largest union voted overwhelmingly Wednesday to
accept a proposed new three-year contract, averting a strike that
would have dealt a blow to Boeing's efforts to recover from an
embarrassing financial downturn.
</P>
<P>
   The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers, which represents 44,300 Boeing employees, mostly in the
flagship passenger jet division, said that the contract won the
endorsement of 86 percent of those who voted. A simple majority was
required for passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this is a great contract, our work is far from done,''
said Bill Johnson, the president of the Seattle-area local that
represents 31,000 Boeing workers. ``We need to work hard on behalf
of our members to enforce this contract and continue to protect the
jobs of our members.'' Workers in Spokane, Wash.; Wichita, Kan.,
and Portland, Ore., also participated in the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The union's leadership had strongly endorsed the proposed
contract, which Boeing put forward early Saturday morning after
nearly two weeks of intense bargaining at a hotel outside Seattle.
Johnson and other union leaders had predicted a strike only a few
hours before Boeing submitted its final offer, which included
concessions to the union.
</P>
<P>
   But an opposition faction within the union campaigned against
the contract, complaining that it did not secure strong enough
guarantees of job security and did not win cost of living increases
for retirees. In 1995, Johnson endorsed a proposed contract that
was later rejected by the membership, extending a strike that
eventually lasted 69 days.
</P>
<P>
   Had two-thirds of the union members voted against the contract,
a walkout could have begun as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract makes Boeing workers among the best paid in the
country, raising their hourly wages nearly 16 percent over three
years to an average of $24.35 an hour. The contract also raises
retirement benefits 25 percent and contains a one-time 10 percent
bonus that amounts to an average of $4,400 per worker.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing abandoned an attempt to introduce weekend
shifts that would have reduced overtime payments and it failed to
get the union to agree to have its members shoulder some of the
cost of health insurance. The company agreed not to lay off any
workers as a result of a decision to subcontract work to
third-party manufacturers, though even the union leaders admitted
that the language they agreed to was not as firm as they had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors have expressed doubt that the new pact's
estimated cost of $600 million will be more than made up for
through increased productivity, as Philip M. Condit, Boeing's
chairman, has said.
</P>
<P>
   But the new agreement does give the company three years to work
with the union to raise profits following a production foul-up two
years ago that forced it to halt production of many of its jets
resulting in Boeing's first annual loss in 50 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
