<HEADLINE>
CRUISING TO MEETING, L.A.'S TOP COP BUSTS TAGGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It may have been a few years since LAPD Chief
Bernard C. Parks patrolled the streets, took radio calls and nabbed
(italics) perps (end italics), but the 30-year cop showed Wednesday
that he still can protect and serve.
</P>
<P>
   The city's top cop and his driver spotted and cuffed a tagger at
a traffic pole at Vernon Avenue and Leimert Boulevard _ Parks'
first arrest since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were driving to a 10 o'clock meeting and we saw all this
graffiti, and I remarked to myself that you never see the person
doing it,'' Parks said after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were about a mile from my house and when we got to the
intersection, we saw a guy up on a concrete light stand. By the
time we pulled up to the light, he came down and was oblivious to
everyone and kept writing on the pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said let's call it in to get a Southwest unit out there,
when he started to walk away. We had to make a U-turn and then he
was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said he and his driver, Andrea Balter, were looking up and
down the streets when they spotted the suspect, Herlindo Rodriguez,
using a marking pen with silver ink to tag buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said let's stop him. He'll escape before the unit gets
here,'' Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief and Balter, both in casual civilian clothes, ordered
Rodriguez to stop when the 19-year-old suspect started to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grabbed his backpack and stopped him,'' Parks said. ``It
was when we got one cuff on him that he began to struggle.
Fortunately, a bystander came by and the three of us were able to
contain him.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said he never identified himself as the chief of police to
Rodriguez, although he suspects the suspect later learned the
identity of the man who caught him.
</P>
<P>
   The chief said he was pleased he hadn't forgotten his basic
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the instincts just kicked in,'' Parks said, adding he
was now preparing for the possibility of testifying in court as the
arresting officer.
</P>
<P>
   It also will cost Parks some.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got that ink all over my clothes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
