<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8183 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      09-02 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Just to be on the safe side, Astros manager Larry Dierker should
consider getting an MRI on his right shoulder. Considering how many
times he waved a pitcher in from the bullpen Wednesday, there's at
least a slight chance of tendinitis.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Mets punished Chris Holt and most of the Astros'
bullpen in a 9-5 victory at the Astrodome. The Mets pumped out 18
hits _ eight of them for extra bases _ in taking the rubber game of
the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to give up 18 hits and win,'' Dierker said. ``On the
other hand, it's not often we score five runs and lose. That's
usually enough in this building.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza led the Mets' attack with four hits, and John
Olerud, Roger Cedeno and Robin Ventura had three each. Ventura
drove in four runs, contributing to the Astros' second horrid
pitching performance in three days.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorkers piled up 21 hits in Monday's 17-1 lashing and
outhit the Astros 46-19 in the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very frustrating series,'' Astros left fielder Bill
Spiers said. ``We didn't control them very well. They got a lot of
hits and a lot of runs. They have a good offensive club.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, humbled yet again by an upper-echelon opponent,
should be pleased to see the bottom-feeding Expos on the schedule
after today's day off.
</P>
<P>
   By losing Wednesday, the Astros dropped the season series
against the Mets and assured themselves of having a losing record
against the four other playoff-contending teams _ Arizona, Atlanta,
Cincinnati and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's 8-7 victory over Cincinnati kept the first-place
Astros from losing any ground in the National League Central race.
The Astros maintained their 1{-game lead over the Reds. Atlanta
leads the Mets by 3{ games in the East.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to head-to-head meetings, the Astros can't
claim to be a leader: They are a combined 12-24 against the Braves,
Diamondbacks, Mets and Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little concerned about it,'' Dierker said. ``But not
that concerned. There are precedents of teams beating a team in the
playoffs that they didn't play well against during the regular
season. So I'm not worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt has been fairly consistent since the All-Star break, but
Wednesday's outing was reminiscent of his first-half struggles. The
Astros stayed close to the Mets early in the game and tied the
score at 3 in the fourth inning, but Holt gave it right back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the part that killed me,'' said Holt, who allowed six
runs on 10 hits in four innings _ his shortest start of the season.
``We scored two runs to tie the game, and I didn't hold it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets starter Octavio Dotel (6-1) wasn't razor-sharp, but
considering the way his teammates carved up Astros pitching he
could have been as dull as a butter knife and still earned the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's two-run homer opened the scoring in the second, but
the Astros cut the lead in half in the bottom of the inning with an
immediate contribution from newcomer Stan Javier.
</P>
<P>
   After drawing a one-out walk, Javier stole second, went to third
on Piazza's throwing error and scored on Paul Bako's chopper to
first base.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets reclaimed a two-run lead in the third when Olerud hit a
leadoff single and scored from third on Darryl Hamilton's
fielder's-choice grounder. The Astros tied the score in the fourth
on Jeff Bagwell's 39th homer and Javier's RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell is four homers shy of matching his career high.
</P>
<P>
   But as they did all night, the Mets answered the Astros' rally
with RBI singles by Ventura, Shawon Dunston and Cedeno to make the
score 6-3 in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Holt (3-13) didn't retire any of the three batters he faced in
the fifth inning and was replaced by Brian Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cabrera, Doug Henry, Trever Miller and Jay Powell also took
turns on the mound. Sometimes it takes Dierker a week to use that
many relief pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the day off, we could use up the whole bullpen,''
Dierker said. ``It's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel was replaced by Pat Mahomes after the Astros loaded the
bases with no one out in the sixth inning. Mahomes yielded a
sacrifice fly to Javier and coaxed Bako into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets added two more runs in the eighth, and Derek Bell's
ground ball plated the Astros' final run in the bottom of the
inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
