<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8184 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     09-02 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
STEVE Francis' welcome visit to Houston this week happened to
coincide perfectly with the news that a deal on a new downtown
office for him and his future Rockets playmates had come to pass,
the obligatory late snag or two notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   And on Nov. 2, the day when Houston voters will go to the polls
to decide whether the palatial arena can actually be built, Francis
will make his Rockets debut against Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   An accidental convergence, perhaps, but a most fitting one,
isn't it? Bless the Rockets for their timing and their knack for
making big headlines exactly when they must have them.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, buffeted by a summer of angst and discord, was
seeking a tangible link to its future and a reason to get recharged
about the present. The Francis trade, another in what is becoming a
series of Rockets offseason blockbusters, works on both counts. It
should assist to some degree in turning the $160 million arena into
a reality and, ultimately, assist in justifying its existence.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley _ and probably Scottie
Pippen, too _ won't be around to represent our fair city when the
facility opens in the fall of 2003. If, however, the basketball
experts are right about Francis, the reluctant Canuck turned
rejoicing Rocket, he will be Houston's showcase performer when the
gala grand opening is staged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tapes we've seen of him,'' said coach Rudy Tomjanovich,
looking about 10 years younger himself, ``are just unbelievable, as
impressive as any I've ever watched of a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe himself, Francis suggests he is a cross
between Stephon Marbury and Allen Iverson. Should he prove to be _
admittedly something of a tall order _ we won't remember the price
the Rockets had to pay to get him. Michael Dickerson and Othella
Harrington are would-be NBA stars themselves, but neither possesses
the sky's-the-limit upside Stevie Wonder does.
</P>
<P>
   He figures to be the point guard in a couple of types of
transition games. With the Rockets' Hall of Fame frontcourt loping
toward the sunset, they needed a young gun to re-energize them, to
pick their plodding tempo way up. We only hope the old codgers,
particularly Olajuwon, can keep pace with him. The 15 seasons'
worth of mileage on Hakeem's knees don't bode well for his easily
adjusting to how the Rockets will have to play to maximize Francis'
exuberant, go-to-the-hole offensive style.
</P>
<P>
   Also, will Olajuwon accept the lad's leadership? Francis' first
appearance before the local media Monday night proved at once
disarming and disconcerting. His charming smile and polite,
respectful responses to questions countered the spoiled-brat image
that his refusal to accept Vancouver's money had cloaked him in
since the draft. But it caused no small measure of concern as well.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, he looks really, really young. Like about 16 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Once he proves he can play old, though, everything will be fine.
Barkley, assuming he re-signs (and all indications are he will),
can be the big brother Francis sorely needs to adjust to the NBA
whirl. Much about Sir Charles' fun-loving, night-prowling spirit
may suggest his being a wayward influence on Francis, but exactly
the opposite will be the case. Assuming Francis deigns to listen,
of course.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley will be watching Francis' every move, from how he
dresses to with whom he hangs. If Charles doesn't approve of what
he sees, be it related to hoops or Francis' boys from the 'hood,
there will be animated discussions regarding same.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame the last All-America point guard from Maryland that
the Rockets landed didn't have a Chuckster in his sphere during his
most impressionable years. John Lucas' wayward, largely squandered
NBA career, although it would be eventually redeemed in part,
remains one of Houston's ranking sports tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, in tandem with Moses Malone, should have led the Rockets
to at least one NBA championship. But remember, his downward spiral
didn't begin until the NBA arbitrarily sent him to Golden State as
compensation for the Rockets' signing Rick Barry. He never got a
chance to finish what he started in Houston until it was much too
late, until cocaine already owned his soul.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Lucas' long-ago sins need not be revisited upon Francis,
who wasn't yet born when Luke was drafted first by Houston in 1976.
Although he hails from a rough background, and his petulant
rejection of Vancouver, a beautiful and cultured city, did raise a
small red flag regarding his attitude, Francis deserves to start
with a clean slate here.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you will find him likable, as both a person and a
player. But can he be the next franchise cornerstone, a talent
worthy of the mansion the team and the city hope to build around
him? Come Election Day, we start finding out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
