<HEADLINE>
USC'S RIDEAUX OUT OF OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Highly regarded freshman defensive back Darrell Rideaux will
miss Saturday's game against Hawaii with a lingering back injury
that could put him out indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Rideaux is still bothered by a stress injury suffered at the
state track championships in June, when he got tangled with another
runner on a relay, and was accidentally kneed in the back. There
has been speculation that Rideaux might have to consider
redshirting, if the injury does not improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those injuries that's been plaguing me,'' Rideaux
said. ``It stiffens up. There's sharp pain. I think it's premature
to make assumptions. At this point, I'm on pins on needles.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett said Rideaux will rest next week, when
USC has a bye, and then see if he can play Sept. 18 against San
Diego State. If he's still not ready, Hackett said he would play
the following week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly a blow,'' Hackett said. ``(But the doctors)
seem to think it's not super serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said the injury is similar to one suffered by Chad
Morton last season, when he was hit in the back against Florida
State.
</P>
<P>
   Rideaux wasn't sure how long he would be out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they find the problem, we can address it and go from
there,'' Rideaux said.
</P>
<P>
   With Rideaux out, Eric Reese and Tanqueray Clark will be used at
the nickel back, and freshman Kevin Arbet will also play.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 tailback update: Hackett said sophomore Malaefou MacKenzie
will be USC's No. 2 tailback in goal-line situations, with either
Frank Strong or Sultan McCullough the second-string back in normal
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Newbury makes move: Sophomore David Newbury seemed to take a
step forward in the kicking battle with junior David Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Newbury made three field goals between 47-50 yards while Bell
was one for three on his attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided to do what I knew I could do,'' Newbury said.
``They brought me out here for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said a decision would likely come today, when the team
arrives in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Trojans take 80: USC will take 80 players to Hawaii, leaving
behind only injured players and walk-ons.
</P>
</TEXT>
