<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS SEND GREEN TO LAKERS FOR ROOKS, DRAFT PICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Don Nelson acquired former Dallas Mavericks center Sean
Rooks and a second-round draft pick next year in a sign-and-trade
deal Wednesday with the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson signed free-agent forward A.C. Green, then traded him to
the Lakers for Rooks, who also can play power forward. Green
returns to the team that drafted him in the first round (23rd
overall) in 1985, while Rooks returns to the franchise that drafted
him in the second round (30th overall) in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very fortunate to have acquired Sean Rooks,'' said
Nelson, the Mavericks' coach and general manager. ``Sean will be a
replacement for Samaki Walker and A.C. Green, whom we lost through
free agency, and he will beef up our front line.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-10, 260-pound Rooks, who turns 30 on Sept. 9, is
scheduled to earn $1.9 million in the 1999-2000 season. His
seven-year, $13.4 million contract expires after the 2002-2003
season.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Rooks averaged 2.7 points, two rebounds and 8.8
minutes in 36 games. In 410 NBA games with four teams, the six-year
veteran has averaged 8.0 points and 4.6 rebounds in 20.3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rooks ``will play two positions for us _ backup center and power
forward,'' Nelson said. ``Sean has the ability to score in the low
box, is an excellent passer, and is a fine addition to our young
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rook's most productive years were with the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie, Rooks averaged 13.5 points and 7.4 rebounds, and
shot 49.3 percent from the field. He appeared to be the center the
Mavericks needed since the days of James Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   However, after Rooks averaged 11.4 points and 5.5 rebounds and
shot 49.1 percent in his second season with the Mavericks, they
traded him to Minnesota on Nov. 1, 1994 for a conditional
first-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Rooks stayed less than two seasons with the Timberwolves before
he was traded to Atlanta on Feb. 22, 1996, for Spud Webb, Christian
Laettner and Andrew Lang. The Lakers signed Rooks as a free agent
on July 16, 1996, and he spent the past three seasons with the
Lakers, where he was unhappy with his playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Green averaged 4.9 points and 4.6 rebounds in just
18.5 minutes per game and was one of the team's most popular
players after arriving on Dec. 26, 1996 from Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Green helped the Lakers win back-to-back NBA titles in 1987 and
'88, and has played in an NBA-record 1,028 consecutive games. He
also has a clothing company located in Compton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' only remaining free agent is forward Ansu Sesay,
who has worked out for Philadelphia 76ers coach Larry Brown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
