<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8189 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      09-02 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS SWEEP BACK OVER .500 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Gil Meche ate junk food but didn't get a stomachache.
He ran with scissors but didn't stab himself. He bought a BB gun
but didn't shoot his eye out.
</P>
<P>
   Or the baseball equivalent, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners rookie right-hander picked a dangerous way to pitch
the Chicago White Sox Wednesday night. He walked eight hitters, the
most by a Mariner this season, but did not suffer for his sin.
Meche beat the White Sox, 3-2, and the Mariners completed a
four-game sweep that put them over .500 for the first time since
July 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got confused with his stats _ he walked eight and struck
out one, instead of vice versa,'' pitching coach Stan Williams
said. ``Vice versa is what he's capable of. But thank God for four
double plays and the pickoff at second base. It wasn't easy, but it
turned out all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams thought Meche had his best bullpen warmup of the season
Wednesday, locating his pitches and throwing very hard. If he had
carried the same stuff into the game, Williams said, the White Sox
wouldn't have touched him.
</P>
<P>
   When he took the mound, Meche said he felt he would have a good
day. But soon after Mike Caruso bunted for an out on the game's
first pitch, Meche realized something had changed. Liu Rodriguez
walked on a borderline full-count pitch, and a long night had
begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got it in my head that I was walking people,'' Meche said,
``and it just took off.''
</P>
<P>
   Magglio Ordonez also walked, but Paul Konerko grounded into a
double play, ending the inning. That foretold the rest of the
night; Meche used double plays to survive the third, fourth and
sixth innings, and he picked Mark Johnson off second to stifle a
rally in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The final double play was spectacular, to use manager Lou
Piniella's word. Second baseman David Bell, who was covering second
with Ordonez running, fielded Konerko's grounder just to the
shortstop side of the bag. Falling down, he slapped the base with
his glove, then threw from his knees to get Konerko easily at
first. Bell said he'd never made a play quite like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really don't work on a play like that,'' he said. ``It's
just kind of a freak play.''
</P>
<P>
   And Meche's victory was a freak outcome. He said he could not
remember the last time he walked eight in a game, and was
frustrated that he was still fighting himself on the mound, as he
did in a blowout loss at New York last week. Meche has allowed
three runs or fewer in seven of his 10 starts, but he has 41 walks
to 29 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if (I'm) just trying to do too much or just
falling out of rhythm,'' said Meche. ``I'm just not making good
pitches. If Meche sounded down, Piniella was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw exceptionally hard today, and he pitched mostly with
his fastball,'' Piniella said. ``He's got a good arm. He's got to
harness it and throw more strikes, naturally. But it was
impressive. He got out of it when he had to.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of the Mariners hitters. Handcuffed by
Mike Sirotka's cut fastballs for six innings, Seattle got all its
runs in the seventh. Edgar Martinez homered on a 3-and-2 fastball
that caught too much of the plate, and Jay Buhner followed with
another full-count homer, on a changeup. With two outs, Russ Davis,
Brian Hunter and Bell singled for the Mariners' third run.
</P>
<P>
   Sirotka (8-12) walked none in his seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Meche left the game in the seventh, after Craig Wilson walked
and Johnson singled. Jose Paniagua came in and struck out Caruso,
whose two-strike bunt rolled foul, then faced Frank Thomas, who was
batting for Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas had been heckled all series at Comiskey Park, and was
hitless in 11 at-bats over the first three games. He had a
25-minute early batting practice session Wednesday and was held out
of the starting lineup to ``ease his mind,'' manager Jerry Manuel
said.
</P>
<P>
   Batting as the go-ahead run, Thomas had a chance for something
dramatic but never swung the bat. Paniagua fell behind 3 and 1,
then nicked the bottom inside corner of the strike zone twice with
called-strike fastballs. Thomas argued, and was booed heavily as he
slowly retreated to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was looking for something outside,'' Paniagua said, ``so
(catcher Dan Wilson) told me to throw him fastballs middle-in.''
</P>
<P>
   Magglio Ordonez singled in a run, but Konerko grounded into a
fielder's choice to end the inning. Paniagua worked a scoreless
eighth, again striking out two, and Jose Mesa earned his 31st save
with a 1-2-3 ninth.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
