r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-TIGERS-TE     09-02 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TIGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS OVERCOME EARLY DEFICIT TO BEAT TIGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Detroit's Dean Palmer and Tony Clark punished the
facade of Tiger Stadium's upper deck with mammoth, first- and
third-inning home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers' Damion Easley deposited another home run into the
left field's upper-deck seating bowl on the first pitch after
Clark's third-inning blast, and yet no one stirred in the Rangers'
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a long man out there tonight,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates explained.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't need one.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Rick Helling battened down the hatches and retired
13 of the next 16 batters, and the Rangers rallied for a 14-7
victory Wednesday night at Tiger Stadium. Helling, who hasn't lost
since June 21, is 6-0 in his past 13 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for me was Rick being able to right himself after
those back-to-back home runs,'' Oates said. ``If he continues to
struggle out there, I don't know what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's game depleted the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Mike Morgan, who pitched himself out of the
rotation with Tuesday's start, threw 55 pitches and could not be
used in long relief.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Danny Kolb threw 41 pitches in relief of Morgan and
could not be used in long relief. Left-hander Jeff Fassero threw 19
pitches Tuesday in what was his second appearance since Saturday
and could not be used in long relief.
</P>
<P>
   That made the Tigers' 5-1, third-inning advantage all the more
troublesome unless you're last name rhymed with shelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great out there,'' Helling said. ``I really wasn't in
any trouble. It's not like they were (hitting) me to death. I was
pitching pretty well. I honestly felt like I only made four or five
mistakes during those first three innings, and three of those four
or five mistakes were hit out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew things would get better if I kept making good pitches,
and eventually they did. Then, I was able to throw some zeros up
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers countered with a barrage of clutch, two-out hits
that accounted for four of their first six runs. Second baseman
Mark McLemore produced the first with his two-out, third-inning
single that scored center fielder Tom Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve catcher Gregg Zaun, who hit a home run and drove in a
career-best four runs, and Goodwin delivered consecutive two-out,
run-scoring singles in the fourth inning before right fielder Juan
Gonzalez tied the score with his fifth-inning, solo home run.
</P>
<P>
   Tigers right-hander Jeff Weaver (8-10) surrendered the lead when
Goodwin delivered a two-out, sixth-inning triple that scored
shortstop Royce Clayton and gave the Rangers a lead that never
would be relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just happened to come through and get some clutch hits
tonight,'' said Goodwin, who went 3-for-6 with a double and triple.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Helling (12-7) continued to record outs en route to a
seven-inning appearance, and the Rangers finally popped
right-handers Doug Brocail and Masao Kida for eight runs, which
included Luis Alicea's home run, in the final two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give up six earned runs sucks,'' Helling said, ``but to get
a win out of it makes it a little more bearable.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
