<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS SIGN FORWARD PROSPECTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Stars yesterday drew closer to pulling
together their training-camp roster when they signed forward
prospects Warren Luhning and Keith Aldridge to new contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The signings leave only goalie Manny Fernandez and defenseman
Richard Matvichuk unsigned heading into the beginning of training
camp Sunday in Vail, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk is in Edmonton, Alberta, working out with the Fort
Saskatchewan Traders, a Tier II team, as his negotiations have
moved slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be with the guys, but I'm not going to be there
without a contract,'' said Matvichuk, who is a restricted free
agent. ``I'm just going to work hard and keep myself in shape and
be ready whenever this deal gets done.''
</P>
<P>
   Aldridge and Luhning will be tossed into a dogfight to grab one
of the Stars' open forward positions.
</P>
<P>
   Aldridge (5-foot-11, 192) is an interesting prospect as a
defenseman whom the Stars hope to convert to forward _ the same way
they did with Blake Sloan last season. Aldridge had 15 goals and 28
assists, along with 130 penalty minutes, in 66 games with the
Vipers last season. He played at Lake Superior State University and
was a finalist for the Hobey Baker Award, given to the top player
in NCAA hockey, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Luhning, 24, was acquired by the Stars from the New York
Islanders in the off-season for a third-round draft pick. The 6-2,
185-pound right winger has played 11 NHL games with no points and
last season scored 20 goals and added 20 assists in 56 games with
the Kentucky Thoroughblades. Luhning played four seasons at the
University of Michigan, where he helped win two NCAA championships
and was a teammate of Stars players Sloan and Marty Turco.
\Nsubheds:Ludwig retires Craig Ludwig said he has officially
retired as a defenseman and taken a position within the Stars
organization that will be focused primarily on scouting.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig, 38, finished his 17-year NHL career a member of two
Stanley Cup championship teams ('86 Montreal Canadiens and '99
Stars).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great ride and I'm ready to step into another part of
life,'' he said. ``I think what it came down to was I really wanted
to be a part of this organization and continue to build what
they're building here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig had been told by the Stars he would not be offered a new
contract this season, but had discussions with the Chicago
Blackhawks and Detroit Red Wings concerning one-season deals. He
said he decided against playing for another team because he said he
felt he would be ``betraying'' the Stars. \Nsubheds:Hull changes
number Brett Hull officially changed his number from 22 to 16
yesterday. Hull had worn 16 his entire career before coming to the
Stars as a free agent last season. He wore No. 22 because Pat
Verbeek already had No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek is not returning to the Stars this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, with this change, maybe I'll get 80 \Rgoals\S this
year,'' Hull joked. ``I can feel the difference already.''
\Nsubheds:Rookie camp set The Stars have scheduled a two-day rookie
camp today and tomorrow at the Dr Pepper StarCenter. Eighteen
players are expected to participate, including top prospects Jon
Sim, Marty Turco, Richard Jackman, Roman Lyashenko, Steve Gainey
and Brenden Morrow.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
