<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITRUN-SEARCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIT-AND-RUN LEAVES TRAIL OF HEARTACHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was every motorist's nightmare: Yvette
Villalobos was driving with her 5-year-old daughter when the car
stalled in the slow lane of the Hollywood Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Villalobos got out to investigate and stepped in front of her
car when a hit-and-run driver slammed into the rear of her car,
bouncing her off the windshield and onto the ground, authorities
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Villalobos' daughter was in the front seat wearing her seat belt
and suffered only minor injuries, but she saw her mother get hit.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds after the 8:40 p.m. crash Tuesday, the Lincoln Town
Car's driver walked over to Villalobos' mangled car, saw her lying
on the pavement, saw the girl in the front seat _ and then ran,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators looked for a suspect until a 19-year-old man,
identified as Armen Tagvoryan of Panorama City, surrendered to them
around 7:30 p.m. Wednesday at the California Highway Patrol office
in Woodland Hills, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After the crash Tuesday evening, the girl, Lauren Gutierrez,
squeezed out of the wreckage, sat by her mother briefly and then
desperately tried to stop cars, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally a good Samaritan and her son stopped and found
Villalobos unconscious and the child in shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was asking my son, Is my mom dead? And she said she wanted
her daddy,'' recalled the first person to stop, Lucia Vargas
Velasco.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Villalobos, a resident of Los Angeles, died
about 4 p.m. Wednesday of her injuries. ``She was in very bad
shape,'' Velasco said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, with her husband at her side, Villalobos' family
allowed her to be removed from life support at Providence Holy
Cross Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The girl is extremely traumatized. ``She was very upset. She
knows what happened and the condition of her mom,'' said California
Highway Patrol Officer Richard Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators searched through the day for Tagvoryan, who they
first described as a ``possible suspect'' who might have been
driving the car.
</P>
<P>
   Tagvoryan's wallet and identification and other paperwork was
left in the silver convertible blue-top Lincoln. Additionally, hair
and blood evidence from when the driver hit the windshield likely
will be taken from the Lincoln, officers said.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-hour after the crash, Mger Tagvoryan, who is Armen
Tagvoryan's brother and the Lincoln's registered owner, reported
his vehicle stolen, said CHP Lt. Bruce Moncher.
</P>
<P>
   At least one witness gave authorities a description of the
driver who plowed into Villalobos' Nissan Sentra.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Lincoln's driver) walked to the victim's vehicle and
observed her there, helpless, with the child left to see her mother
dying on the ground. It really upsets me,'' said California Highway
Patrol Capt. Les Fritz.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol investigators issued a statement Wednesday
evening thanking Armen Tagvoryan's family and friends who assisted
the Highway Patrol in efforts to have the suspect surrender.
</P>
<P>
   If the driver had remained at the crash scene, he might have
faced minor charges or none at all, said CHP Sgt. Steve Munday.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol officials said Wednesday night that the
suspect was taken into custody on suspicion of hit-and-run driving
and that he might face other charges.
</P>
<P>
   Officers and civilians at the West Valley CHP office struggled
to understand how the driver could leave the mother and child
behind without attempting to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's barbaric and inhumane to watch a person dying there and
not do anything,'' said CHP Sgt. John Lago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 0123EDT &QL; 
