r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-MORGAN-TE     09-02 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MORGAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OATES HUNTS STARTER AS MORGAN DEMOTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Johnny Paul 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ A gruesome August doomed right-hander Mike Morgan to
the Rangers' bullpen for September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Mike, and he will not start Sunday,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said yesterday. ``I don't know who will.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan pitched himself out of the rotation with Tuesday's
performance in the Rangers' 14-6 loss to Detroit at Tiger Stadium.
Morgan did not figure in the decision, but the 39-year-old veteran
surrendered six runs (four earned) on seven hits and two walks in
his 31/3-inning appearance.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the sixth time in as many starts during August that
Morgan (12-8, 6.23) failed to pitch more than five innings, and his
10.80 earned-run average for that period forced Oates to make a
change.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will require a fifth starter only four times for the
remainder of the regular season, and that turn in the rotation
could become what Oates described as the ``pitcher du jour.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will require that ``pitcher du jour'' for the first
time Sunday against the Chicago White Sox at The Ballpark in
Arlington, and right-hander Danny Kolb appears to be the leading
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Kolb is 1-1 with a 4.24 ERA in nine relief appearances spanning
231/3 innings this season, and opponents are hitting .233 against
the 24-year-old rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox entered last night's game with a 15-7 record
during games in which their opponent started a left-hander on the
mound and 47-64 against right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   That could eliminate left-hander Jeff Fassero, whom the Rangers
acquired Friday from the Seattle Mariners. Fassero went 0-2 with a
6.23 ERA during two starts this season against the White Sox while
pitching for the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's record against left-handers also could prevent
left-hander Matt Perisho of Triple-A Oklahoma from starting that
game. Perisho, who won his 15th game Sunday for the RedHawks,
likely will be recalled from Oklahoma this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Ryan Glynn also could be an option, but the
24-year-old rookie took the loss during the Rangers' 7-4 loss to
the White Sox Aug. 13 at Comiskey Park. Glynn surrendered seven
runs (six earned) on nine hits and three walks in that five-inning
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he plans to discuss the alternatives with his
coaching staff, general manager Doug Melvin and Oklahoma manager
Greg Biagini before making a decision.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8197 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK     09-02 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOWERS BACK FOR THIRD STINT WITH MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Mike Blowers will have a whole new vantage point when
he goes to Safeco Field today.
</P>
<P>
   The Hanshin Tigers of Japan's Central League released Blowers in
early August, and he was home in Graham, Wash., waiting out the
Japanese waiver process during a recent Mariners homestand. So
Blowers and his wife attended a game, watching from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The ballpark was ``perfect,'' he said, and as the starting third
baseman for the 1995 M's, Blowers couldn't help feeling a small
sense of ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody that was a part of that team does,'' said
Blowers, before making his debut with the '99 Mariners Wednesday
night. ``I certainly do, absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I probably wanted it more than most guys, just because
I'm from there and that's where I'm going to live the rest of my
life. I was glad to see it done, and it was a fun time of my life
to be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Blowers, who attended Bethel High School, Tacoma Community
College and the University of Washington, signed with the Mariners
Saturday and will give the team a right-handed-hitting first
baseman for September. In 73 games in Japan, he batted .251 with 10
homers and 43 runs batted in. He made more money than he could have
if he'd signed with a major league team last winter, he said, but
the experience was not fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really enjoy it,'' Blowers said. ``It's an experience
_ I went over there, and I'm glad I'm back in the States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese game focuses more on pitching and defense, Blowers
said, and teams typically play for one run at a time. The
atmosphere was exciting _ the Tigers drew 50,000 fans a game _ but
the style of play did not suit Blowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization over there treated me great,'' he said.
``They did everything first-class for me and my family. I just
couldn't really ever get into the flow of the game over there. It's
a little different brand of baseball, and I didn't enjoy it. And
for the first time in my career, the manager and I didn't get along
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Blowers, who played third base in Japan, was with the Mariners
from 1992-95 and again in 1997. He spent last season with the
Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   STARK REALITY: The Mariners promoted right-hander Dennis Stark
from Class AA New Haven when rosters expanded Wednesday. Stark, a
24-year-old sinker/slider pitcher who will work out of the bullpen
for the M's, will be the Mariners' 28th pitcher this season when he
makes his debut. The major league record is 29, set by the 1996
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finished up strong in double-A,'' Piniella said. ``He's got
a good, young arm, and the organization wants to give him some
experience. We like his future.''
</P>
<P>
   Stark, 24, pitched complete games in two of his last three
starts, finishing 9-11 with a 4.40 earned run average for New
Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Also promoted Wednesday was outfielder/infielder Charles Gipson,
who had rehab assignments at three minor league levels after
separating his shoulder on July 11.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING A LOOK: The Mariners are evaluating their interest in
right-hander Sean Bergman, who was released by Houston Tuesday.
Bergman, who is 29 years old and still a year away from free
agency, was 12-9 with a 3.72 ERA as a starter for the Astros last
year. He slipped to 4-6, 5.36 this season, missing more than a
month with shoulder tightness and losing his spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   FEELING BLUE: Piniella has had plenty of run-ins with umpires,
but he said he was saddened to learn that baseball had accepted the
resignations of 22 umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad, it really is,'' Piniella said. `` ... Some of those
guys are my friends, and I hate to see them lose their jobs like
that. I have sympathy for them, because a lot of them have been on
the job a long time, and there are some good umpires. I hope this
thing gets resolved we get some of these people back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
