<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN PRESIDENT PROMISES A CLEANER ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert 4 new grafs before last graf of original text to
add reporting on disruptions during Zedillo's address. ) (mk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ President Ernesto Zedillo, in a state of the union
address delivered as the race to choose his successor reaches full
swing, promised to insure a ``climate of freedom'' for the vote and
to prevent government funds from seeping into political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can all be confident that a democratically legitimate
government will emerge from these elections,'' Zedillo said
Wednesday night in the packed chambers of the lower house of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   His words conveyed the promise of an enormous step forward for
Mexico, which has been ruled for most of the last 70 years by a
single authoritarian party that has renewed its dominion every six
years in often-tainted elections.
</P>
<P>
   The speech is the culminating rite of the annual political
calendar. This address, the fifth in Zedillo's six-year term, was
especially important. It was his last before the election in July,
and therefore it was his final chance to speak above the racket of
the most competitive presidential campaign modern Mexico has seen,
and to put forth his achievements.
</P>
<P>
   But true to his down-to-earth, almost anti-political style,
Zedillo made no effort to give a stirring performance and limited
himself largely to a bland recitation of facts and figures.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, who strikes many Mexicans as a hard-working,
unpretentious and relatively honest politician, is enjoying the
highest popularity of his term. A national poll in in the newspaper
Reforma on Wednesday showed that 66 percent of those interviewed
approved of his performance in office. His ratings have
consistently climbed since he hit a low in December 1995, in the
midst of a crushing economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   A Yale-educated economist, Zedillo used the central passages of
his speech to highlight the sustained growth that his disciplined
fiscal policies have produced despite economic tumult in Asia,
Russia and Brazil and the plunge in world oil prices earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   He said Mexico would meet its goals of 3 percent growth and 13
percent inflation this year. He once again rejected any form of
currency controls and said the peso would continue to float freely.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, even though Mexico will be in a campaign year, when
past governments could not resist the temptation to send a little
extra money to vote-getting social programs, Zedillo intends to
reduce the budget deficit, from 1 1/4 percent to 1 percent of the
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes without saying that no public funds will be diverted
to campaigns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo had sharp though indirect words for presidential
aspirants from the opposition, but also for figures in his own
party like Roberto Madrazo Pintado, who have criticized his
economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Destruction is what inevitably happens, and is what we
Mexicans have experienced again and again, when irresponsibility,
demagoguery, populism and an unhealthy desire for easily won praise
become the rule in economic management,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not discuss his role in the elections. Many observers
wonder whether he will intervene with his still-vast powers to
favor a candidate whom he likes. But Zedillo did promise that he
would ``scrupulously respect all parties and all candidates'' and
do what he could to guarantee a clean vote.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition lawmakers who spoke before his speech expressed
skepticism about Zedillo's commitment to a fair election and to
refraining from exercising his presidential clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This president still wants us to believe that there is no
other power than his, as in the old days,'' said Pablo Gomez
Alvarez, a leader of the left-of-center opposition.
</P>
<P>
   He and other opponents criticized Zedillo for blocking an
electoral reform that would have made it much easier for opposition
groups to form coalitions against the president's party.
</P>
<P>
   Most Mexicans believe that Carlos Salinas de Gortari won the
election in 1988 by fraud. Even Zedillo's rise to power in 1994 was
shadowed by the assassination in mid-campaign of the man who had
been his party's candidate, Luis Donaldo Colosio.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment of candor, Zedillo conceded that his anti-crime
programs have not worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is with great regret that I must acknowledge that the state
has not yet met this demand of the Mexican people,'' he said. He
detailed a series of legal changes that have made it slightly
easier for police to arrest and jail criminals, as well as purges
of local and federal police forces intended to encourage a greater
focus on fighting crime.
</P>
<P>
   In an unabashed effort to upstage Zedillo before the television
cameras, Vicente Fox Quesada, an opposition presidential candidate,
marched out in the middle of the president's speech saying he had
``more important things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo had to stop speaking several times because of catcalls
from opposition lawmakers, especially when he said that he had
never used government funds to help his own political party.
</P>
<P>
   But mayhem broke out on the floor during the rebuttal by Carlos
Medina Plascencia, a leader of the right-of-center opposition, who
accused Zedillo of covering up ``an enormous plundering of the
national treasury'' in the finances of his 1994 presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's supporters drowned out Medina's speech with deafening
shouts.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuous for their absence from Zedillo's address were
references to other pressing issues like the four-month-old student
strike that appears to be permanently injuring the National
Autonomous University, Latin America's largest; the strife with
Zapatista rebels in the state of Chiapas, and the congressional
struggle to shore up the banking system.
</P>
</TEXT>
