<HEADLINE>
FINAL PRESEASON GAME CRITICAL TO MANY DALLAS COWBOYS PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ There has never been a mystery about the last
game of the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   For entrenched stars such as Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman and
running back Emmitt Smith, it doesn't mean much. And with the
team's regular-season hopes riding on their health, they usually
see little action. Exhibition games like Thursday night's matchup
between the Cowboys and Jacksonville Jaguars at Texas Stadium are
for guys on the roster bubble.
</P>
<P>
   Players like former TCU receiver Jason Tucker, defensive tackle
Brandon Noble and linebacker//fullback Robert Thomas know it's
their last chance to impress the coaches. The Cowboys have to
reduce their roster from 70 to 53 by Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some positions and people we are looking at,'' said
coach Chan Gailey, who said the starters will play about one
quarter, leaving the reserves three quarters to make a final
impression. ``This game will weigh heavily on them making it or not
making it.''
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, it's the game of their football lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just hope you do good enough to impress the coaches,''
Noble said. ``Or you hope to get good film to hook on somewhere
else. If not, you go home and get a good job and your first dream
dies.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gailey wouldn't go that far, he acknowledged the necessity
to make tough decisions to help the team that aren't always fair to
the individual. With the uncertain status of injured cornerbacks
Deion Sanders and Kevin Smith and defensive tackle Leon Lett's
suspension, Gailey said that being the best player might not mean
making the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chess game right to the end,'' Gailey said. ``You would
hope that everyone is healthy and you can take the best player. But
sometimes you got to cut a good football player because you need to
keep someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker finds himself caught in such a numbers game at receiver.
</P>
<P>
   He's had a solid preseason, catching five passes for 106 yards,
including a 55-yard touchdown pass. His average yards per catch of
21.2 is the most on the team for anyone with more than one
reception.
</P>
<P>
   And he amazed the coaches by quickly grasping Gailey's intricate
offense despite spending the spring in NFL Europe. Ernie Mills and
Jeff Ogden are the only other receivers to know all four wide
receiver positions. But both of them played last season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Tucker may be the odd man out behind Mills, Ogden, Michael
Irvin, Raghib Ismail and Wane McGarity if the Cowboys keep five
receivers. If they keep six, they may opt for rookie MarTay
Jenkins, who has blazing speed and could be a better special teams
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all part of the business,'' said Tucker, who was
drafted by the Giants in 1998 but was released in training camp.
``It's something you can't control. I feel I've done pretty well
for myself. I hope I've done enough. I'm just going to go out and
do the best I can do and let them decide on who they want to
keep.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookies and free agents are usually guys who dot the bubble
list. But occasionally a veteran player finds himself fighting for
a roster spot on the last day of the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   That could be the case for three three-year veteran safeties _
Omar Stoutmire, Kenny Wheaton and Singor Mobley. With neither
threatening for a starting spot, the Cowboys will be hard pressed
to keep all three, considering they could use one of the salary
spots to finance a practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be naive to the fact,'' Wheaton said. ``It
could very easily happen. I can't worry about it. I just have to go
out there and play. If it doesn't work out and I would love for it
to work out here, I have enough confidence in myself I can play
somewhere in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   It all could come down to how they play Thursday night.
\Nsubheds:Last chance to shine
</P>
<P>
   Roster spots are on the line Thursday against the Jaguars for
several Cowboys players, including:
</P>
<P>
   Receivers: Jason Tucker, MarTay Jenkins
</P>
<P>
   Running backs: Beau Morgan, Denvis Manns
</P>
<P>
   Fullbacks: Ryan Neufield, David McCann, Robert Thomas
</P>
<P>
   Tight end: Brian Waters
</P>
<P>
   Offensive linemen: Oliver Ross, Ben Fricke, Freddie Childress
</P>
<P>
   Safeties: Omar Stoutmire, Kenny Wheaton, Singor Mobley
</P>
<P>
   Cornerbacks: Marvin Love, Zebbie Lethridge
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers: Myron Smith, Joe Phipps, Robert Thomas
</P>
<P>
   Defensive linemen: Robert Newkirk, Brandon Noble, Darren Benson,
Chance McCarty
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is being evaluated at fullback and linebacker
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
