<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO SORT THE TRUTH FROM THE MESSAGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go ahead, believe what they say. Who knows, it might even be the
truth. Sometimes it does work out that way, but other times ...
</P>
<P>
   Sorting through a variety of mostly jock-world voice messages, I
came up with this:
</P>
<P>
   Deion Sanders: Never mind the usual down-talking arrogance,
Nine-Toed was at his me-me-me best when pontificating for the
Channel 11 camera last weekend. Don't even think, Deion revealed,
about him playing cornerback until he could also return punts.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Cowboys have a severe shortage of bodies and
experience at the corners. But punt returns provide more
opportunity for personal glory than do passes rarely thrown in
Deion's direction. ``Toe-gate'' continues at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Police chief Darrell Fant: Nobody would want to be walking, or
driving, his Highland Park beat this week. The media frenzy has
been ``overwhelming'' since Jerry Jones tried to make it to the
church on time.
</P>
<P>
   But what about that police department quote that Jones was
``definitely agitated'' in his dealings with the officers?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched \Rthe video\S several times and it appears he was
mostly frustrated at the situation about being late,'' Fant said
yesterday. ``I didn't sense Mr. Jones was being abusive to the
officers in any way. The Joneses are a great family. Nothing like
this has ever come up before.''
</P>
<P>
   Fant also wanted to stress that he totally stands behind the
officers involved in the Jones case, but that dealing with the
media madness has been rather shocking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like we keep saying, there was no slow-speed chase involved at
all, but most of the media continues to ignore that,'' Fant added.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, his department is under media siege to release, yes,
the mug shot taken of Jones when he was booked into the jail.
``Everybody has a hundred pictures of Mr. Jones, but I suppose this
one would provide a shock element,'' Fant said.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, Chief Fant, to the world of Cowboys coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates: Last week in Arlington, the suggestion that Mike
Morgan be yanked from the rotation produced a perturbed Oates
answer of ``media conspiracy'' against Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   This week in Detroit, Oates let it be known he was looking for a
pitcher to replace Morgan in the rotation. It must have become a
``managerial conspiracy'' after Morgan was bombed again, this time
by the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Morgan: An amazing first half of the season success story,
who now has an empty tank. You did well, old-timer, but September
is no place for sentimental gestures by the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Bradshaw: Come again, Terry. What's this you say about
Chan Gailey's offense being ``boring?'' Actually, Gailey gives us a
thrill-show compared to the Norv-Ernie offense that helped win
three Super Bowls. Both are supposed to be run-first, although
Gailey seems to stray from that at times, as did Ernie Zampese.
</P>
<P>
   But Gailey's offense provides many more opportunities for
down-field theatrics. It's only boring if it doesn't work, not in
concept.
</P>
<P>
   School presidents at TCU and SMU: This is your last chance to
explain those initial comments of ``knowing nothing about'' future
membership in Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   Mack Brown: Two days before the North Carolina State game, the
Texas coach said, ``Darrell \RRoyal\S came by the office this week
and told me I had really screwed up. I asked why. He told me to
never schedule a team in the home opener that can beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates, Part II: Not so quick there, Johnny, on your
public endorsement of Pudge Rodriquez for American League MVP. Two
weeks later, and (personal opinion), Rafael Palmeiro will win it.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Bradley: The NBA big man guru, Pete Newell, said it: ``I
made a comment that \RBradley\S looked to me like he needed a good
conditioning program, and he said, ``You know what, I read that,
and you're exactly right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn, did it really take six years in the league for you to
figure that out?
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Franchione: The whole truth and nothing but the truth,
came from TCU's own. ``I don't think this is the ideal time to be
playing them,'' reasoned Coach Fran. He meant, of course, the
Sunday night visit by Arizona after last week's blasting at Penn
State.
</P>
<P>
   Believe what you want, but I think you can trust in that last
one.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
