<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-QBS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO QBS BETTER THAN ONE AT ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playing two quarterbacks _ and keeping both happy _ is easy. All
you've got to do is win.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's tandem quarterbacks _ senior Keith Smith and junior
Ortege Jenkins _ shared time and led the team to a 12-1 record last
season, including a Holiday Bowl victory against Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact we were winning made it easier,'' Arizona coach Dick
Tomey said. ``If you lose, nobody is happy.''
</P>
<P>
   An unhappy bunch of Wildcats will come to Fort Worth to play TCU
Sunday night. And even though Arizona opened the season with a 41-7
loss at Penn State in last Saturday's Pigskin Classic, Tomey has no
intention of altering his two-headed quarterback creation.
</P>
<P>
   When Arizona takes the field against the Horned Frogs, Smith is
expected to start and play at least the first quarter, with Jenkins
playing the second quarter. Who plays the second half is determined
by first-half performances.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback competition or controversy can rip a team apart. At
Arizona, it brought the team together.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Smith started as a redshirt freshman and passed for
1,450 yards and 11 touchdowns. As a sophomore, he suffered a
shoulder injury and Jenkins, a redshirt freshman, took over and
passed for 1,669 yards.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a tense situation going into spring practice in
1998. Smith believed Jenkins would start; Jenkins believed Smith
would start. There were rumors that both would transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them both that if they wanted to transfer to transfer
right then so we could move on,'' Tomey said. ``I challenged them
both. I told them they'd both get an equal chance to win the job.''
</P>
<P>
   However, before last season's opener against Hawaii, Tomey knew
he had a dead heat. Neither had played well enough for the coaching
staff to designate one as the starter and the other a reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a quarterback system. We just have two
exceptional people who both deserve a chance to play,'' Tomey said.
``The fact they've handled it so well has been part of the
chemistry of our team, the unselfishness of our team. Obviously,
they would both love to play every snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sat down last season and decided they wouldn't let it be
a distraction or problem for the team. They deserve all the credit.
It's the two of them that decided they would make this work.''
</P>
<P>
   Making it work wasn't much of a problem. Smith and Jenkins have
been friends since the day Jenkins arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here, Keith took me under his wing,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterbacks were united by what they had in common. Both
are Californians and both are proficient in sports other than
football. Smith was drafted by the Detroit Tigers and played one
season in the minor leagues as a shortstop. Jenkins came to Arizona
hoping to play football and basketball; he played 13 games for the
Wildcats basketball team in 1997-98, but has given up hoops.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Jenkins are road roommates. They have a ritual of
watching an in-room, pay-per-view movie the night before games.
They prefer action flicks such as ``The Rock'' and ``Con-Air,'' but
they might watch the ``The Buddy System'' if it was available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of football, we hang out together,'' Smith said.
``We're similar in a lot of ways. He just dresses better than me;
I'm kind of a slob. I enjoy being his roommate on the road. He's
one of the funniest guys I've ever met. He's an all-around good
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said the two share so well because of mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some doubts in my mind when I first heard we were going
to do this,'' Jenkins said. ``But I knew how good he was and how
good I was. When you've got confidence in the next guy going in
there, the bottom line is you want to win. If I had been the
quarterback all year and we had gone 8-4 or 7-5, I would have
turned that in for the record we had last year in a second.
Whatever guy doing the best is the guy who needs to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins made the play of the 1998 season when he somersaulted
into the end zone over three Washington defenders to give the
Wildcats a 31-28 victory. After the game, though, Jenkins gave
credit to Smith for a key completion during the winning drive. And
last Saturday against Penn State, when Smith suffered a sprained
ankle in the second half, Jenkins was one of the players who helped
Smith hobble to the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes it work so well is our relationship,'' Jenkins
said. ``We have a great friendship. We both can help this team win.
When you're winning, nothing can go wrong.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
