<HEADLINE>
HARDLUCK QB RICK MIRER HOPING FOR LAST LAUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Rick Mirer is with his fourth football team in
four years, and you could have expected to find the hardluck
quarterback dazed and confused at his new digs with the New York
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer, however, has borne the travails of his travels
exceedingly well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I don't recognize myself in the mirror. I've worn so
many different jerseys,'' Mirer said, bemused.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, maybe this is the place where Rick Mirer gets the last
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Jets' playbook in hand, blue eyes bright and a smile on his
face, the 28-year-old Mirer stood at his locker Wednesday and gave
up no clues that he, in some circles, has been viewed as one of the
NFL's poster children for serious underachievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about what people say,'' Mirer said, undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair. It's not right. I think my peers understand
where I was and the circumstances, especially in Seattle after my
first year, or in Chicago, which was somehow even worse. Guys in
the league say, `You had no chance.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the former Notre Dame sensation may have landed in
a good spot to turn things around.
</P>
<P>
   After being drafted by the Seahawks in 1993, getting traded to
the bad news Bears in '97 and then signing with Green Bay on Sept.
2, 1998, Mirer has been plucked to AFC Championship land by Jets
top Tuna, Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday night, when the Jets play the Vikings in their
preseason finale, Mirer will have had a chance to show Parcells
whether or not he is a worthy back-up for Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   Like Testaverde, whose career was on the scrap heap, Parcells
has told Mirer that his career can turn around in a hurry, if he
can do what Parcells asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything about Rick that concerns me,'' Parcells
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells scouted Mirer back in '93, when the Patriots wound up
taking Drew Bledsoe as the No. 1 pick and Mirer fell to the
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's in the past, and I don't care. I've seen
good things from him. I like his feet. He's bright. And to tell the
truth, I'm a little surprised by his arm strength,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than I thought. So I'm glad he's here. And I'm
sure there's a lot of other teams that would like to have a guy
like this right now, from what I've seen out there.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Mirer, as a music-loving 20-something who
scouted Seattle clubs and hung out with Pearl Jam, really was a
good fit for the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   But during his waning tenure there, the snake-bitten Mirer
seemed so prone to snap misjudgments and disastrous happy feet, you
wondered how he ever emerged from Notre Dame so highly regarded.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer hopes his troubles are behind him. He said he does not
want to blame anyone but would have performed better had Tom Flores
remained as coach instead of Dennis Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt better with Tom Flores than Dennis Erickson. Just
the style. My first year wasn't a make-or-break season. That's
probably the only season I've had that was like that. Every other
one, the coach is on the hot seat,'' Mirer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot to learn when I came into the league. I'd be the
first one to say that. I didn't come from a school where we dropped
back and threw the ball 40 times a game. I needed that coaching,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trust also became a factor, when Erickson dumped the struggling
Mirer in favor of John Friesz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the situation with Brett (Favre in Green Bay). They
stuck with him and that was pretty ugly. But the coach wasn't
caving into what people were saying and things turned out all
right, and he wound up with three MVPs,'' Mirer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that would have happened to me, but I firmly
believe you have to give your guy confidence so he can take
chances, make a mistake or two and he's not coming out of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking across the country to Seattle, Mirer said he is a little
envious. Jon Kitna, another young, mobile quarterback, has the
chance to learn under Mike Holmgren, with a lot of talented players
around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a good spot. He's in a spot where he can excel. Not
everybody gets that, so I hope he knows what he's got, because Mike
Holmgren is going to get it done,'' Mirer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks and Jets do meet again this season, although not until
the finale on Jan. 2 at the Meadowlands. No one is predicting
whether Mirer will be with the Jets then, although you can't help
but wish him the best of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, how can you not appreciate a good-natured, nomadic,
seven-year pro who, when asked whether he is renting or buying a
home now that he is on Long Island with the Jets, Mirer posted a
huge grin and said, emphatically:
</P>
<P>
   ``Renting.''
</P>
<P>
   He's got the right attitude. Here's hoping he can win the job.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
