<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEUP'S RELIABLES DELIVER FOR METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Mets have uncovered heroics from some rather
unglamorous spots this season. Steely infield defense and the best
bullpen in the league may delight a manager, but it isn't exactly
the stuff of big-type headlines and video retrospectives.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the Mets went old school. One night after they
struggled to score and lost to the Houston Astros' ace Jose Lima,
the Mets got exactly what they needed: eight extra-base hits and
plenty of offense in the final game of their road trip from exactly
the hitters they would expect. John Olerud, Mike Piazza and Robin
Ventura, the 3-4-5 hitters in the order, took a game into their
hands, not with dramatic last at-bat home runs but with a series of
well-placed and perfectly timed hits that led the Mets to a 9-5
victory over Houston in New York's last appearance in the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura slugged his 200th career home run as part of a three-hit
night with four runs batted in, which gives him 108 r.b.i. for the
season. Piazza added four hits and Olerud had three hits and scored
three runs as the Mets remained three and a half behind the Atlanta
Braves, who beat the Reds, in the East Division race. Cincinnati
fell four games behind the Mets in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   This trip was all about learning how the Mets fare against
potential playoff opponents. Here's one positive indicator: They
have played the Astros six times in 10 days and won four, and they
split six games with two teams that are almost certain to make the
playoffs. Wednesday, they did it with an offense so effective that
they left 15 runners on base and Manager Bobby Valentine could
laugh it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit the offense for having them on base,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   After two thrilling games in this series _ one that the Mets won
with the long ball and one in which they were victimized by a grand
slam _ this game was marked more by the twin struggles of the
starting pitchers and the hitters who abused them.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Octavio Dotel, the rookie who has been alternately
masterly and dreadful for New York, nor Chris Holt of Houston could
locate his pitches early in the game. That made for a walk-laden,
frequent-hit start.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored first, when Ventura, hitting just .222 on this
trip and in danger of slipping below .300, smacked a two-run home
run to right field, his 29th.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could have had more, but they stranded Roger Cedeno at
third and Rey Ordonez at first when Holt, in his best piece of
pitching in the game, caught Rickey Henderson looking at a pitch
and then got Edgardo Alfonzo to swing for strike three.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel has made just 13 major league starts and his inexperience
has shown, seemingly, in alternate appearances.
</P>
<P>
   In his last one, at Arizona, he held the Diamondbacks to one run
on four hits in eight innings. But that only meant he was due for
an off game. In the second inning, Dotel walked Stan Javier, who
stole second base and, when Piazza's throw went into center field,
advanced to third. He scored on Paul Bako's groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel easily retired the side in the third, allowed two more
runs in the fourth when Jeff Bagwell homered and Javier drove in
Ken Caminiti, but then retired the side again in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the sixth did Dotel lose the curveball he relies upon.
He gave up singles to Bagwell and Caminiti and walked Derek Bell to
load the bases. He left and Pat Mahomes came on in fantastic
relief, allowing only a fly ball that scored Bagwell and pitching
two perfect innings of relief before giving way to Dennis Cook and
Armando Benitez. In five-plus innings, Dotel (6-1) had allowed five
hits and four runs, not as impressive as some starts, but good
enough for a victory , and enough for Valentine to say that he was
sure Dotel would remain in the rotation, even after Rick Reed is
likely to be activated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got an offense like that behind me, you feel
comfortable,'' Dotel said. ``I feel like when it's my game to
pitch, I'm going to win because of what I have behind me. I just
have to make good pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory came hours after Bobby Bonilla rejoined the Mets.
Bonilla, who has not played in the majors since the first week of
July, was 3 for 13 (.231) as a designated hitter at Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a rash of injuries _ and his strained relationship
with Manager Bobby Valentine _ Bonilla has appeared in just 45
games this season and has hit just .159. But upon his return, he
said he would do whatever was asked of him. That may not be much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see him starting,'' Valentine said. ``I can't foresee
a future where he might play.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder DARRYL HAMILTON left the game in the third inning
after he strained a left patella tendon while running hard to first
base. It is much like the injury that has plagued him all season.
... RICK REED, making his second rehabilitation start, allowed one
hit _ a home run _ and one walk while striking out five in five
innings for Class AA Binghamton. ... Among the Mets' Sept. 1
call-ups were JORGE TOCA, the minor league player of the year who
will provide depth at first base, and JAY PAYTON, the oft-injured
outfielder who has been sidelined with a strained muscle in the
abdomen. In 49 games with Norfolk, Toca hit .335 with 25 runs
scored and 29 r.b.i. Payton, in 38 games, hit .389 with 27 runs, 35
r.b.i. and eight home runs. He will most likely play in the
outfield and be a pinch-runner.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
