<HEADLINE>
NEW GUYS PITCH IN FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ROYALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In case you missed it, the Red Sox are no longer the
same team that limped home last week after series in Texas and
Minnesota. As if by magic, they have become a dangerous ball club,
aggressive and well balanced. They can beat you in a dozen ways.
</P>
<P>
   At first it seemed as though timely hitting and strong starting
pitching would carry the Olde Towne Team to its sixth straight
victory. Instead, the Red Sox called upon stingy defense and a bona
fide closer to preserve a 4-3 victory over the Kansas City Royals
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. A crowd of 31,743 at Fenway Park went home
cheering the offense that produced a 4-0 lead, starter Kent Mercker
(1-0), and reliever Rod Beck, a breath of fresh air and confidence
missing since the loss of Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-2-3 ninth inning by Beck was actually frosting on the cake
for a team that has won six straight games and eight of its last
nine. But Fenway fans are very astute. With Beck around they know
the Red Sox can look forward to some torrid finishes in the final
month-plus of the season. Playing for the wild card no longer has
to be the goal. Suddenly, there are bigger fish to fry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really appreciate the crowd,'' said Beck, who arrived for
work Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night following a flight from Los Angeles after
being acquired from the Cubs Tuesday. ``It made me feel good. I'm
happy to be here. It's a great situation for myself. Being back in
a race means a lot to me. You always want to play in games that
mean something.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's game started like it was just another stroll
around the nearby Fenway gardens. The Royals seemed perfectly
content to absorb their third straight loss and seventh in eight
games against the Red Sox this season. Boston scored single runs in
the first and third innings and two more in the fourth. Mercker
allowed only two hits and no runs through six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The most exciting activity seemed to be scoreboard watching.
However, wild-card competition Oakland beat the Yankees, 7-1,
keeping Boston's lead at two games.
</P>
<P>
   The game grew interesting with a three-run rally by Kansas City
in the seventh. Mercker lost his touch and walked two of the three
batters he faced. The third reached base on a fielder's choice and
throwing error by Mercker. Rheal Cormier relieved and gave up a
single to Jed Hansen that scored a run. An error by Jeff Frye,
subbing for Jose Offerman, on a double play attempt resulted in two
more runs. After a sacrifice bunt, the Royals had the tying and
go-ahead runs on second and third. A walk to Jermaine Dye loaded
the bases, and Cormier was removed in favor of John Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sweeney then hit a rocket toward left, but rookie third
baseman Wilton Veras, making his first start since being recalled
from Double A Trenton, made a sensational leaping catch to end the
inning. Wasdin breezed through the eighth, and Beck did his thing
in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we have to get ready for tomorrow,'' said Red Sox
manager Jimy Williams, ``but I think I'll savor this one a little
bit. I thought we got good pitching out there from everybody. Beck
did a nice job. Why was he there? To me he was the right guy to put
in there even though he traveled across country. Mercker did a good
job with his fastball, changing speeds. He was really pitching out
there to help us win. I know I went out to see him in the seventh
after the first walk. But I still felt he could get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman and Nomar Garciaparra teamed up for the first two
Boston runs. Offerman was hit by a pitch to lead off the first and
scored on a single by Darren Lewis and a ground out. In the third,
Offerman reached on a single to right and scored on a Garciaparra
single to right. But Offerman left after six with a bruised
forearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a big factor in winning that game, but we had Frye
available and I didn't hesitate to put him in,'' said Williams.
``As for Jose, we'll have to see how he is tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   For Beck, this was a night he won't soon forget. ``I've never
been to Boston. I've never been to Fenway,'' he said. ``I planned
on coming here for the All-Star Game, but I blew out my elbow, so
that didn't work out. But I get to see it after all. I'm pretty
excited about being in the (pennant) race again. That's usually
when I do my best work. We were pretty much biding time in Chicago,
not having a whole lot of fun. I'm looking forward to having fun
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
