<HEADER>
A8212 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-NY-RAPE-ART-NYT &LR;      09-02 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-RAPE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA EVIDENCE SECURES RELEASE OF MAN CONVICTED IN '82 RAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note)  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEVE STRUNSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Accompanied by the 78-year-old woman who worked more than a
decade to overturn his rape conviction, Vincent Jenkins walked out
of prison Wednesday, 17 years older and two surgeries frailer than
when he walked in.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, a lawyer from Manhattan named Eleanor Jackson Piel,
used DNA evidence to persuade a federal judge in Buffalo to order
her client's release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful thing,'' said Jenkins, who sat between Ms.
Piel and his other lawyer, Barry Scheck, at a news conference
Wednesday night. ``It's like walking into a whole new world.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins has no immediate plans. He cannot work, he said, because
he had part of his lung removed when he learned he had lung cancer
in prison; he also had a hip replaced. For now, he is going to live
with his sister in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell how I feel,'' he said, ``because your heart
is like your toe. It grows skin on it and it gets hard. ``But,'' he
added, ``people like Mrs. Piel soften it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Piel and Jenkins have had a long relationship. She defended
him in a manslaughter case in the 1970s, and though Jenkins was
convicted, she continues to defend him, saying that he stabbed the
victim in self-defense. Ms. Piel was not Jenkins' trial lawyer in
the rape case, but he wrote to her following his conviction in
1983, asking if she would handle his appeal. She agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after discovering that there was still physical
evidence from the rape trial, she contacted Scheck, who is
co-director, with Peter Neufeld, of the Innocence Project at the
Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law in Manhattan. Jenkins is the 65th
person in North America to be freed by DNA evidence, Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jenkins was ordered released on Monday, the judge in
the case, John T. Elfvin, has not announced his reasons. He has
promised to issue a written opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins was living in Buffalo in May 1982 when a young woman was
raped in a nature conservancy there. More than four months after
the rape, Jenkins was picked up by police in Buffalo who, his
lawyers said, convinced the victim to identify him as the rapist
despite her initial response that he was not the one. He was
convicted and sentenced to 20 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the DNA evidence that would free him two decades
later, Ms. Piel said, the conviction was surprising in that Jenkins
was five inches shorter and several years younger than the
attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Piel said the first of two DNA tests was conducted in 1993,
after she was joined in the case by Scheck. But that test was
inconclusive, and she said there was not much progress in the case
for several years.
</P>
<P>
   A second, more refined test was conducted in April by Edward T.
Blake, a criminologist who runs a lab in Richmond, Cal., Forensic
Science Associates. The test showed that Jenkins' DNA did not match
the attacker's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, great,'' Blake said, when he learned Wednesday that
Jenkins had been released. He praised Ms. Piel: ``She's someone
who's been there, done that and is still fighting the good fight,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
