<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT AT RELIEF! BECK ON HAND 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BECK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ First came the commute to work. A six-hour flight from
Los Angeles. A 45-minute cab ride from the airport. It was Rod
Beck's first day on the job, but there was no time for orientation.
The newest Red Sox reliever arrived during the early innings of
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's game against the Kansas City Royals and took his
place in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   He took the field at 9:39 p.m., in the ninth inning, and was
greeted with a standing ovation as he headed to the mound. The
noise grew even louder when his name blared over the public address
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, I'm Jason,'' said Red Sox catcher Jason Varitek, as the
two shook hands before Beck warmed up. ``What do ya got?''
</P>
<P>
   He had virtually unhittable stuff. Beck needed just 11 pitches
to carry out his first-day assignment. He retired Scott Pose on two
pitches, a fly out to center fielder Damon Buford. He retired
Johnny Damon on a ground out.
</P>
<P>
   Beck put Jeremy Giambi in a 0-2 hole before throwing three
consecutive balls, the second in the dirt. Then he struck out
Giambi swinging to seal a 4-3 Red Sox victory and collect his first
save in a Boston uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the end of the work day, Beck introduced himself to the
rest of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went pretty darn good. I just have to keep it going,'' said
Beck, whose arrival Wenesday &UR;  &LR; night marked his first visit to New
England. Acquired from Chicago Tuesday, he will be counted on to
bolster a bullpen that has seen much change since closer Tom Gordon
went down with an elbow injury.
</P>
<P>
   Beck, a Los Angeles resident, got up Wednesday at 7 a.m. to
catch a 9 a.m. flight, during which he mostly slept. He arrived in
Boston at 6 p.m. and caught a cab for the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Beck was dropped off in front of Fenway with his luggage, not
knowing where to go next. Officials directed him to the clubhouse,
but by then the game had started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got here late, around the second or third inning, and I got
in the bullpen around the fifth. I didn't have a chance to talk to
anybody about how I was going to be used,'' said Beck. ``They just
said they were down to a four-man bullpen, so get out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been to Boston. I've never been to Fenway. I
planned on coming here for the All-Star Game, but I blew out my
elbow, so that didn't work out. But I get to see it after all. I'm
pretty excited about being in the (pennant) race again. That's
usually when I do my best work.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck's first effort impressed manager Jimy Williams, who said he
spoke briefly with Beck when he arrived. ``To come in the game and
get three outs after traveling across the country . . .,'' said
Williams. ``He probably hadn't even met all those guys on the field
when he was pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck said he doesn't want to step on any toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done pretty darn good without me all year,'' he said.
``Whatever they want me to do, I'll do, I'll be happy. I know what
I'm capable of doing. The only thing different is getting used to a
new uniform. I've pretty much done everything in this game except
win a ring. That's ultimately what we all play for.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had ever before faced any of the three batters he
retired Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, Beck said, ``We played Kansas City in
interleague play, and Giambi, we see him in spring training in
Arizona. I would say I'm not going to know most of the guys, but at
the same time, they're not going to know me.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, Rod, did you know that was Jeremy Giambi, brother of
Oakland's Jason Giambi?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't,'' he said. ``I thought it was Jason. So I lied.
I didn't face him in spring training. But I threw to him like I
throw to his brother.''
</P>
</TEXT>
