<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-UMPIRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIA AT A LOSS OVER COMPROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Richie Garcia had a plane to catch. He just
didn't know where he was going.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa or Detroit? As Garcia perused the airline schedules, he
pondered the alternatives. The last flight to each city would be
leaving at 9:25 Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, but the 25-year veteran American
League umpire figured there was a world of difference. If he went
to Detroit, he would be rejoining his crew and working Thursday
night's game, his job spared. If he wound up in Tampa, he would be
headed home to Clearwater, Fla., unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia discovered that the situation wasn't so clear-cut. At
7:26 in the courtroom of US District Judge J. Curtis Joyner, the
umpires' union won satisfaction with an asterisk. According to a
compromise forged with Major League Baseball, 22 veterans whose
resignations were supposed to take effect at midnight Wednesday
will be allowed to keep their jobs, at full pay and with full
benefits, through Dec. 31, when the collective bargaining agreement
expires. But, per edict of baseball commissioner Bud Selig, they
will not be allowed back on the field for the remainder of the
season. Their places will be taken by the 25 minor leaguers MLB
promoted, effective Thursday, back on July 27. As part of the
settlement, the umpires' appeal for injunctive relief to the
National Labor Relations Board was dropped, and the matter will
proceed to arbitration. If the union is stymied there, its 22
members in limbo will be left at the mercy of new collective
bargaining, their futures in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the fallout from the 68-member union's quixotic
attempt to assert its bargaining power by submitting mass
resignations July 14, only to see the ploy backfire 13 days later
when it attempted to rescind them and was informed that MLB had
arbitrarily accepted 22 and filled those positions.
</P>
<P>
   Now Garcia, 57, who has four children and four grandchildren,
still has a job, just no place to do it.
</P>
<P>
   He had feared as much some two hours before the ruling when he
emerged from an eighth-floor waiting room in James S. Byrne US
Courthouse, where he and four fellow umpires had been marking time
for almost eight hours while union attorneys continued protracted
negotiations with MLB that spanned some 16 hours over two days.
After checking the possible itineraries, Garcia headed back into
the stifling anteroom to continue the vigil with AL colleagues Mark
Johnson and Ed Hickox and union president Jerry Crawford and Eric
Gregg of the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``This must be like the world's longest rain delay,'' he was
told.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's (expletive) worse,'' he muttered. ``It's the worst thing
I've ever been through.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal had begun six weeks ago in an airport hotel not 20
minutes from the courthouse here. Union general counsel Richie
Phillips had called a meeting of the membership the day after the
All-Star Game in Boston in an effort to forestall a one-day strike,
which would be illegal under the umpires' pact with MLB. That bid
was stifled. But Phillips still feared that the commissioner's
office was trying to consolidate authority over the umpires,
commandeering that power from the individual leagues, and that it
might try an unprecedented move to dismiss lowly rated umpires.
Sandy Alderson, the executive director for baseball operations in
the commissioner's office, had assured Crawford that was not MLB's
intention, but the rank and file remained unconvinced. So Phillips
suggested the alternative strategy _ mass resignations, effective
Sept. 2, as a show of solidarity and a preemptive measure against
MLB. It was approved unanimously, or so the union _ including
Garcia, the organization's vice president and perhaps the most
vocal propoent of the move _ thought.
</P>
<P>
   But within 48 hours, the campaign began to unravel. Umpires who
retained individual counsel were advised that their resignation
letters left them without recourse should baseball choose to accept
them. Defections began occurring in the form of letters of
rescision, and with union ranks sundered, the remaining umpires
tried unsuccessfully to void their letters, leading to MLB's
selective acceptance policy and ultimately to the doomsday
negotiations here.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his defiant public stand, Garcia was anxious when he
flew here from Detroit Monday night for the climactic
confrontation. ``I really didn't know what to expect after all
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His hopes were buoyed during Tuesday's seven-hour session, which
had been conducted at Joyner's urging in lieu of a formal hearing.
An agreement seemingly had been reached: The 22 umpires could keep
their jobs and MLB would employ some or all of them as it saw fit
during the final month of the season and the playoffs. ``All it
needed was Bud Selig's signature,'' said Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   So confident was Garcia that he checked out of his downtown
hotel Wednesday morning. And when he arrived at the courthouse,
resplendent in an open-collared bright red shirt and black pants,
Garcia held out hope that he would be spending Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night in
his blue work clothes at Tiger Stadium. Instead, he discovered that
the negotiations had taken a devastating twist overnight. Instead
of approving the agreement, Selig decreed that the 22 veterans
could not return to duty this season; furthermore, he wanted them
removed from the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, today it's no deal,'' said Garcia. ``We
didn't even have time to put it to a vote. They gave us 15 minutes,
take it or leave it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes became nine hours as attorneys for both sides
scurried back and forth from Joyner's fifth-floor chambers. After
one last round of caucuses, the compromise became official.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia sat grimly in the back of Court Room 8-B as the decision
was announced. And after Joyner adjourned the hearing, the umpires'
de facto spokesman stood and shook his head as he assessed the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm not going to work but I'm going to get paid,'' said
Garcia, his voice brimming with sarcasm. ``It's a situation where
Major League Baseball has decided that instead of having 345 years
of experience on the field during the most important part of the
season, it would rather have us go home. Now if that makes sense to
you . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips stepped in and held court, condemning Selig's action as
``absolutely shameful'' and ``punitive.'' Meanwhile, the remaining
four umpires _ minus Gregg, who had headed home _ slipped out of
the room and headed down the corridor to a water cooler at the far
end, where they huddled for some five minutes. As they dispersed,
they embraced and Garcia told Crawford, ``We did the best we
could.''
</P>
<P>
   But he clearly felt that wasn't good enough. The union
entourage, headed by lead attorney Susan Davis, swept up Garcia and
swarmed into a waiting elevator. Garcia put his arm around Davis
and said as the doors closed, ``Just because I'm pissed doesn't
mean I'm pissed at you. We're not done yet, we're not done yet,
we're not done yet . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, he was off, racing to catch the last plane to
Tampa. Ultimate destination unknown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
