<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SAD ENDING FOR BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Baseball's sorriest drama of 1999 won't star Kevin
Costner as an aging pitcher battling power hitters and the power of
love.
</P>
<P>
   Even if ``For Love of the Game'' is a washout on par with
``Waterworld,'' baseball will have done it one worse. Just ask the
middling crowd that wandered into Dodger Stadium on Wednesday to
see a baseball game and saw a movie unfurl. Introducing scenes from
``The Beware Richie Project,'' starring Richie Phillips. It's a
comedy of errors that would be funny if not for all the people
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   THE ESTABLISHING SHOT: A panoramic shot of Dodger Stadium. The
diamond is pristine; the weather, postcard perfect. A slight breeze
tickles the flags in centerfield.
</P>
<P>
   VOICE OVER: This is my office. Has been for the past 14 years.
Since June of 1985 I've been proud to serve Major League Baseball,
proud to be an arbiter of the Boys of Summer. ``My name is Tom
Hallion and (voice cracking) on the first of September I umpired
what could be my final game. I love baseball. Right now, I hate
baseball. I really hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   MOVE IN ON REPORTER NEAR DODGERS DUGOUT, DELIVERING A LIVE
STAND-UP:
</P>
<P>
   ``POX News has just learned that Major League Baseball and the
umpires' union have reached a deal after two days of intense
negotiations. It's Weeping Wednesday for 22 umpires whose
resignations were accepted last month by the American and National
leagues. They will be unemployed as of 6 a.m. after their pleas for
reinstatement fell on the deaf ears of a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The umpires' union withdrew its lawsuit in return for full pay
and benefits the remainder of the year for the deserted 22 and a
$1.36 million postseason bonus payment that amounts to roughly
$20,000 for each of the league's umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides decided the arbitration route is the way to go to
put an end to this tumultuous journey. It will be November,
probably, before the first rulings are handed down. Now, back to
the studio. ''
</P>
<P>
   PAN SHOT OVER SHOULDER OF REPORTER, TO HOME PLATE WHERE SECOND
BASE UMPIRE HALLION, TERRY TATA (HOME PLATE), RON KULPA (FIRST
BASE) AND BILL HOHN (THIRD BASE) ARE AWAITING THE EXCHANGE OF
LINEUP CARDS BETWEEN THE DODGERS AND MILWAUKEE BREWERS. TIGHT SHOT
OF THE FOUR MEN.
</P>
<P>
   Hallion: ``OK, I know this is gonna be hard, but we're
professionals and we've got a job to do. If this is indeed Terry's
last game after 40 seasons, let's make sure we send him out
right.''
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHERS, TOO EMOTIONAL TO SPEAK, NOD THEIR HEADS AND SCUFF AT
THE DIRT WITH THEIR SHOES. CUT TO TWO FANS SITTING SIDE-BY-SIDE IN
THE BLEACHERS IN THE SECOND DECK, ON THE THIRD BASE SIDE. ONE IS
EYEING THE UMPIRES THROUGH BINOCULARS. HE TURNS TO THE OTHER AND
SPEAKS:
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of those dudes are gone after this game. Hallion, Tata,
Hohn; Man, I'd be bitter if I were them. Richie Phillips, he's
their union head, he's supposed to have their backs, right? And
what does he do? He sells them out for chump change from the
postseason bounty and the tin hope some arbitrator will rule the 22
have to be rehired.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan 2: ``It's a major bummer. If I were them, I'd be really
peeved at the 24 American League umpires who caved before Phillips'
strategy even had a chance to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, the umpires on the whole have no one to blame
but themselves. They're the ones who followed Phillips like
sacrificial lambs to slaughter when he advised them in July to
tender their resignations as bait to lure commissioner Bud Selig to
the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe not a single one of the 68 was smart enough to
see they could end up killing their careers long before their
collective bargaining agreement expires at the end of December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I hope they use their free time to read ``An Idiot's
Guide to Negotiating.'' If the book doesn't already exist, they can
write it. They certainly know now what not to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan 1: ``Yeah, I've seen a lot of the umpires quoted as saying
they thought Phillips was just posturing, that he wasn't really
going to follow through on the plan. And then, when the majority of
the umps rescinded their letters of resignation eight days later,
they seriously expected baseball to forget the whole thing? Get
real!
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to try that: Go into my boss at H&AMP;R Block in
mid-February and say, `I resign, effective on April 1,' so he'll
sweeten my situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan 2: ``Yeah, like that would work! If you ask me, never trust
a man who emerges from an umpires' meeting chomping on a doughnut.
I saw a picture of Phillips doing that and I thought, `that
capsulizes these guys perfectly: When they're not feeding their
egos, they're feeding their faces.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Eric Gregg. He's big, with a strike zone as expandable
as his waistline. But no way are any of them bigger than the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   DISSOLVE TO PIVOTAL SHOT OF DANK ROOM INSIDE DODGER STADIUM.
ZOOM IN ON HALLION AND HOHN SITTING SLUMPED BEFORE A PHALANX OF
CAMERAS AFTER THE GAME, a 5-4 BREWERS' WIN.
</P>
<P>
   Hohn: ``I'm really upset what those 24 AL umpires did to my
family. They didn't do anything but stab us in the back and keep
pushing the knife in.
</P>
<P>
   `` I can't even explain how my heart's so badly broken by
baseball. My God, we're good people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallion (clearing his throat): ``This situation has devastated
me. I'm physically and mentally exhausted. I buried my dad earlier
this year (his voice breaks) and I (pause) just (pause) want to go
home (pause) with (pause) my (pause) family.''
</P>
<P>
   FADE TO OUT. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
