<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY EARNS SHARE OF FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ While others missed easy chances Wednesday night, Roy
Myers made the most of his, scoring twice to lead the Galaxy to a
3-1 victory over San Jose _ moving Los Angeles to the top of the
Western Conference standings for the first time this season in
front of 8,662 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The three-point victory moved the Galaxy (16-9, 42 points) into
a first-place tie with Colorado (16-8, 42 points), though the
Rapids have a game in hand. Still, for a team that trailed Colorado
by 12 points earlier in the season, it's been a rewarding chase
back to the top _ at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been something we've fought long and hard for,'' said
Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid of the tie with the Rapids. ``Our emphasis
going into the game is that we wanted to show a Galaxy that could
play with some heart, spirit and play intelligently. I thought we
did all three tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles had a chance to share the Western Conference lead
Saturday, but their 1-0 loss to Dallas snapped a four-game winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   `We can lose a game occasionally, but we're not going to lose
more than one in a row,'' said Schmid. ``That's what we've been
talking about. We're going to bounce back from losses and take care
of business the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers, who had a bad performance against the Burn over the
weekend, gave Los Angeles a 2-0 lead, working a give and go with
Carlos Hermosillo. Actually, Hermosillo's first touch from Myers
skidded away to the right side, but San Jose goalkeeper Joe Cannon
came out to challenge. That left Myers open in front of the net.
Hermosillo simply crossed it back in front and Myers finished with
the inside of his left foot to an open net in the 58th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles saw its lead cut in half a minute later.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's Alejandro Sequeira took a long pass from defender
John Doyle and barely beat L.A.'s offside trap, finding himself
one-on-one with Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman. Sequeira beat
Hartman to the near post, cutting the Galaxy's lead to 2-1 in the
59th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Defender Greg Vanney finished San Jose in the 71st minute. San
Jose defender Wade Barrett tripped up Clint Mathis, setting up a
penalty kick, which Vanney delivered to the near post.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely effective on set plays, the Galaxy took the lead in the
second minute, starting on a Vanney corner kick and finishing with
Myers' one-touch strike.
</P>
<P>
   Vanney's cross was tipped away to the right side by Cannon. Cobi
Jones gathered it and sent a delicate chip toward the penalty spot
for Danny Pena. Pena headed the ball back to the top of the penalty
area for Myers, whose one-touch to the far post ricocheted and
bounced in for the early goal.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo missed the best opportunity to give the Galaxy a
two-goal lead in the 28th minute. The Mexican striker chested down
a nice cross from Jones 5 yards in front of San Jose's goal. And
with only Cannon to beat, Hermosillo blew an easy finish, chunking
his left-footed shot straight to the Clash keeper.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's best opportunity came earlier in the match. Dario
Brose sent a corner to the far post for John Doyle. Doyle's header
looked like it would beat Hartman to the near post, but Hartman got
a finger on it to knock it away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
