<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS ENTER UNCERTAIN OFFSEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sparks cleared their lockers and autographed a bunch of
items at the Forum Wednesday before saying their good-byes for
about eight months.
</P>
<P>
   They departed in relatively good spirits after completing their
best season ever, far exceeding many preseason predictions by
finishing the third WNBA season one victory short of the
championship series.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks were 20-12 in the regular-season, finishing with the
second-best mark in the league, went 2-2 in their first playoff
appearance, and forced the two-time defending champion Houston
Comets to three games in the Western Conference finals before
ending their year.
</P>
<P>
   They were the only team to win more than one game against the
Comets. They split with them during the season, and opened the
conference finals with their third win over Houston. But the Comets
won the last two games to move onto their third championship
series.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks are gone, but several questions regarding the team
remain to be answered during the off-season. For instance, will the
Buss family retain ownership of the team or will the league take
over because of lagging attendance? Will Orlando Wooldridge's
contract be renewed? Will the Sparks play in the Forum or the
Staples Center next season? How many players will the Sparks be
able to retain in the expansion draft? Will Buss hire a new general
manager or continue assuming the responsibilities?
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks, who averaged 7,625 in attendance, are among a few
teams (Utah and Charlotte are the others) to be reviewed by the
league in the off-season to decide whether to take over ownership
or grant contract extensions. The Busses have until Sept. 30 to
make a case for keeping the Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Buss and his father, Laker owner Jerry Buss, would like
to retain the team. But Johnny Buss said he would like the league
to be more lenient when it comes to sponsorship, broadcasting
rights, and marketing concepts. The league and Buss have had a
contentious relationship from the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make some adjustments,'' he said. ``I think they
are ready and willing to talk now. They wanted to go by the books
and that was great. They have for three years. Now I think it's
time for a little ease of restrictions, at least for Los Angeles,
but hopefully for the rest of the league.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Sparks will most likely remain at the Forum in 2000,
because the Democratic Convention cuts right into their season, but
will join their fellow NBA counterpart, Lakers, into the Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   As for Woolridge, he will enter negotiations with the Busses
after the business with the league is resolved. Woolridge was the
Sparks' third head coach and the first to finish a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to get this situation taken care of as soon as
possible,'' said Woolridge, who came in third for Coach of the
Year. ``It is my feeling and my understanding that they want me to
coach this basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   The league will also decide in the off-season how many players a
team can protect for next year's expansion draft. Buss would like
to protect six, but said the league is leaning toward five. For the
time being, he is inclined to remain general manager until he finds
a suitable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   SPARKS NOTES: Center Lisa Leslie was fined $500 for shoving
Houston's Tina Thompson in the final game of the Western Conference
series Monday. Thompson was dealt a $300 for taunting Leslie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
