<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-SALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE OF ANGELS, DUCKS REPORTEDLY NEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walt Disney Co. officials declined comment Wednesday on reports
the organization has a deal to sell the Angels and Mighty Ducks to
Orange County-based billionaire Henry T. Nicholas III for $650
million.
</P>
<P>
   According to published reports, Disney has ``completed the
parameters of a deal'' to sell the baseball and hockey clubs to
Nicholas. The report, by baseball analyst Peter Gammons, was
written for Disney-owned ESPN.com, but corporate officials were
silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're declining comment on all speculation about the Angels
and the Ducks,'' said Disney spokesperson Christine Castro.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Disney-ESPN link, Castro responded: ``We don't get
involved with the operations of our communications division.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcom officials also refused to disclose the nature of their
talks with Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not commenting on that _ at least at this point,'' said
Broadcom corporate spokesperson Bill Blanning.
</P>
<P>
   The $650 million price tag for both teams might be a bit steep.
Industry analysts have valued the Angels-Ducks package at $375
million to $425 million, but Nicholas ``stepped up and closed the
deal,'' Gammons wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Any deal would need the approval of Major League Baseball.
Disney has not yet sought permission from the commissioner's office
to share financial information with Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Disney signed an agreement with then-owner Gene
Autry to pay $140 million for the Angels. Autry died last year. The
company also spent $100-120 million to renovate Edison
International Field and paid a $50 million franchise fee to the
National Hockey League for the Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Disney investors, both teams have been money
losers.
</P>
<P>
   The potential sale of the teams comes on the heels of a Disney
sell-off. Last week, the corporation sold Fairchild Publications
for a reported $650 million. Analysts have said Disney's recent
sell-off efforts have been an attempt to cut costs and boost
dropping stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels entered the season with a payroll of $53 million, a
franchise record. The team, which is 51-81, is on pace for its
worst season ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Mighty Ducks have never made it beyond the second round of
the NHL playoffs. This year, they were swept by Detroit in the
first round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 0222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0049 </DOCNO>
