<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ By very early Thursday morning, the
optimism of Israeli and Palestinian negotiators had soured, and it
seemed unlikely that a new agreement on the peace initiative would
be reached before Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's arrival
in Egypt later in the day. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Washington) _ The Clinton administration said
Wednesday that it wants assurances that international financial aid
already sent to Russia has not been lost to corruption, but stopped
short of calling for a halt in future loans to Moscow from the
International Monetary Fund. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-INAUG (Panama City, Panama) _ Mireya Moscoso, a
schoolteacher's daughter who grew up in rural poverty, was sworn in
Wednesday not only as Panama's first woman president but also as
the first president who will lead a completely sovereign country,
once the United States withdraws its remaining troops and hands
over the Panama Canal on Dec. 31. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ZEDILLO (Mexico City) _ President Ernesto Zedillo, in a
state of the union address delivered Wednesday as the race to
choose his successor reaches full swing, promised to insure a
``climate of freedom'' for the vote and to prevent government funds
from seeping into political campaigns. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Kursumlija, Yugoslavia) _ This southern Serbian
town of 14,000 people is now struggling to host 7,000 displaced
Serbs from Kosovo, increasing the population by a half. With the
school year starting, Serbs who had been living in Kursumlija's
schools are being moved to a tattered local cultural center;
thousands more live with host families or relatives or in any
apartment they can find. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WACO-INQUIRY (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno on
Wednesday ordered U.S. marshals to the FBI's headquarters to seize
a previously undisclosed tape recording of voice communications
between FBI commanders and field agents during the 1993 tear gas
assault at the Branch Davidian compound, Justice Department
officials said. By David A. Johnston and Neil A. Lewis. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-ZEALOTS (Houston) _ Michael McNulty and David Hardy refused
to let go. In the six years since the Branch Davidian compound went
up in flames on April 19, 1993, the two men have waged an obsessive
quest to discredit the official account of what happened. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SMART-MICE (Undated) _ In a major test of how learning works
at the level of nerve cells, a scientist has created a smarter
strain of mice by manipulating a gene involved in memory formation.
He believes his work lays the basis for eventually doing the same
in people, whether to help patients with memory deficits,
counteract the loss of memory in older people or even make healthy
individuals smarter. By Nicholas Wade. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MARCH (New York) _ A federal appeals court on Wednesday
emphatically rejected the city's final legal challenge to a Harlem
youth rally and, in an unusual step, explicitly ordered the Police
Department not to oversee the event with ``undue rigidity.'' By
David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   NY-RAPE-DNA (Undated) _ Accompanied by the 78-year-old woman who
worked more than a decade to overturn his rape conviction, Vincent
Jenkins walked out of prison Wednesday, 17 years older and two
surgeries frailer than when he walked in. The woman, a lawyer from
Manhattan, used DNA evidence to persuade a federal judge in Buffalo
to order her client's release. By Steve Strunsky. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TURTLE-RESCUE (Topsail Beach, N.C.) _ For the more than 100
volunteers in the Topsail Turtle Project here, sea turtles are like
family. They spend much of their summer helping turtles through
birth, sickness and even death. They patrol the 26-mile-long beach
of Topsail Island every day, all summer, to protect the more than
180 sea turtle nests laid this season. By Emily Yellin. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-TAXES (Washington) _ White House chief of staff John
Podesta on Wednesday urged the Republican majority in Congress to
send President Clinton its $792 billion tax cut bill so that he
could promptly veto it. Congress passed the tax measure in early
August but has refrained from forwarding it to the White House,
where it faces certain rejection. Republicans have been stumping
across the country for their tax plan during the current
congressional recess. By John M. Broder. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-SCIENCE (Undated) _ No one questions the need to
emphasize computers in education these days. Nor do they deny the
plethora of high-paying jobs that the computer world offers. Few
suggest that basic sciences are disappearing from the classroom.
But a sense is growing in some business quarters that the sheer
ubiquity of computers has deflected attention from more traditional
sciences and skills. By Claudia H. Deutsch. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ In a sign that strong consumer spending
continued to power the American economy last month, automakers
announced Wednesday that their sales soared in August. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-INVEST (Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia) _ Taking a major stride
back into the world's financial mainstream, the Malaysian
government on Wednesday lifted a steep tax on the repatriation of
foreign capital. The move is expected to uncork a stream of capital
out of Malaysia, as overseas fund managers withdraw money that had
been effectively locked in the country since it imposed sweeping
capital controls last September. By Mark Landler. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   COMMODITIES-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The regulator of the
nation's commodities markets is proposing a rule change that would
allow commodity trading advisers to smooth out past returns in the
performance records they present to prospective investors. The
proposal could bolster business by making commodities trading look
less prone to wild swings, which have been known to frighten away
potential investors. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   BEANIE-BABIES (Undated) _ As word spread that the maker of
Beanie Babies would ``retire'' all the pint-sized stuffed animals
by the end of the year, many consumers were outraged. Some were
disappointed at the thought that the toys might actually be
discontinued. More, though, said they were furious at being
manipulated by Beanie maker Ty Inc. for what they believed was a
publicity stunt to ratchet prices even higher. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Ecuador produces less output in a
year _ about $15 billion _ than the United States produces in a
day. The financial travails of such a pint-sized economy would not
ordinarily threaten anyone beyond the country's borders. Yet the
Treasury Department and International Monetary Fund remain fixated
on Ecuador's problems. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (New York) _ The mayor and the police
commissioner would like you to believe that the bullet-riddled
Gidone Busch had been some monstrous, hulking figure _ a big man
armed with a claw hammer that he was ready to embed in the skulls
of all and sundry. The idea, of course, was to make Busch seem as
menacing, as dangerous, as possible, and thus take some of the heat
off the police officers who killed him. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
