<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLUENTIAL IOC MEMBER'S SON INDICTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the second criminal charge to emerge from the Salt Lake City
Olympics bribery scandal, the son of one of the most influential
members of the International Olympic Committee was indicted
Wednesday on federal charges that he fraudulently obtained U.S.
residency and then lied about it to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say that Kim Jung Hoon , the son of Kim
Un-Yong, a power broker in the world of international sports,
illegally received a green card and then used it to enter the
country numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Utah businessman admitted helping the younger Kim,
who goes by the name John Kim, obtain residency by providing a
bogus job at his company. The businessman, David E. Simmons, a
former chairman of Keystone Communications, told a federal court on
Aug. 3 that he set up the job with his Salt Lake City-based company
as a way of influencing Kim's father, a South Korean national who
sits on the Olympic committee's executive board.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's indictment, John Kim was charged with accepting
$104,000 as part of the no-show job at Keystone. Investigators say
the company was reimbursed by the Salt Lake City bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have charged the committee with using an
elaborate gift-giving scheme to court IOC members who would vote on
the site of the 2002 Winter Games. Salt Lake City, which made its
first Olympic bid in 1966, was awarded the Games in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Since December, an investigation by the Justice Department and
other federal agencies has examined allegations that Salt Lake
City's committee spent up to $3 million on expensive gifts like
jewelry, tuition payments, overseas junkets and cash.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has led to the expulsion or resignation of 10
members of the IOC and undermined the committee's credibility. In
the past, Kim Un-Yong denied any involvement in the scandal, but
the IOC nevertheless issued him a severe warning and said he could
still be expelled if he was found to have knowledge of his son's
business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Florman, a spokeswoman for the Justice Department, said
she could not comment on whether Kim Un-Yong was being
investigated. ``We will, however, go wherever the facts and
evidence lead,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kim's lawyer, Howard Graff, denied the allegations, saying
they were based on the accusations of Simmons, which he called
``inconsistent, illogical and untenable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Schechter, a spokesman for the Kim family, said that Kim's
employment with Keystone was legitimate. He added that Kim, who is
now visiting South Korea, was told by the Salt Lake City committee
that if he had any trouble obtaining his green card, Sen. Orrin G.
Hatch of Utah would provide help. In a statement Wednesday, Hatch
denied promising to intervene on Kim's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Schechter said that Kim, who lives on Long Island, was visiting
South Korea and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pound, a Canadian who is a member of the IOC's executive
board, said he was disturbed by news of the charges, although he
said he did not know the details of the indictment. ``It sounds
serious,'' he said. ``This is the first charge that has a direct
connection to the IOC We'll be looking at it closely.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal with Keystone, Kim was placed on the
company's payroll between October 1990 and March 1992 and was paid
$50,000 a year, which later increased to $70,383, according to the
indictment. The Salt Lake City committee later reimbursed the
company through phony consulting contracts and $10,000 from Kim
himself. Kim was granted legal residency by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service in September 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
