<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 03:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8251 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-SMART-MICE-SFCHRON &LR;      09-02 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-MICE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EXTRA-SMART LAB MICE RAISE HOPES FOR BRAINIER PEOPLE  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Genetic manipulations targeting a single protein in the brain
have produced a strain of extra-smart laboratory mice, scientists
reported Wednesday, suggesting it may someday be possible to boost
human memory in much the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Princeton University said they have engineered a
strain of mice with abundant amounts of a memory-enhancing
substance called NR2B in their brains.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments show that the mutant mice, nicknamed ``Doogie''
after the brainy title character in the ``Doogie Howser, M.D.'' TV
series, have much better long-term memory and learning ability than
ordinary mice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does raise some specific options for the pharmacologic
treatment of memory disturbances in humans,'' said Dr. Marsel
Mesulam, a neurologist and director of Northwestern University's
Cognitive Neurology and Alzheimer's Disease Center in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, he added, experimental results point to ``a
serious possibility that we could have memory-enhancing drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, medical and legal experts raised a slew of
questions about the potential dangers of brain-enhancing drugs
based on genetic alterations, emphasizing that it will take many
years of research before any human uses might be attempted.
</P>
<P>
   The NR2B protein is incorporated into a larger molecule known as
the NMDA receptor, a gatekeeper that sits on the membrane of nerve
cells, controlling the flow of charged particles that determine
when nerves fire.
</P>
<P>
   Nerve cells with receptors built mostly with NR2B are more
active than other receptors in the same family. As a result, cells
with the overactive receptors seem to be more likely to form
connections with other neurons.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying NR2B as a ``molecular switch in the memory
process,'' the authors conclude, ``has indicated a potential new
target for the treatment of learning and memory disorders. This
study also reveals a promising strategy for the creation of other
genetically modified mammals with enhanced intelligence and
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   However, hyperactive brain machinery also may increase the risk
of serious side effects, notably stroke and epilepsy. And while
mice and people have much the same basic neurochemistry, the links
between particular genes and higher-order brain functions in people
are still very much a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long way from mice to men,'' said Stanford University
law professor Hank Greely, co-director of a Stanford program on the
ethical dimensions of genetic research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding extra copies of a gene to improve mouse memory may work
in mice, but it may not work in people, or it may have adverse
effects in mice that don't show up in these experiments, or it may
have more adverse effects in people,'' he added. ``It will be a
long time before we understand how genes and memory are related in
humans.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts said it came as no great shock to discover that genes
and proteins are involved in important brain functions, just as
genes help determine physical traits.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the latest results the first time a transgenic mouse
mice  &LR; has been produced that shows a hint of extra brainpower.
</P>
<P>
   But experts credited the Princeton research team, led by
molecular biologist Joe Z. Tsien, for producing by far the most
convincing evidence that the NMDA receptor is the key player in a
so-called ``unifying mechanism'' of learning.
</P>
<P>
   Test-tube results strongly suggested that the structure and
activity of the NMDA receptor might be driving the learning
process. That led to an elaborate series of memory and learning
tests in the mice to see how the gene-altered receptors affected
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Results of experiments involving recognition of novel objects,
among several other tests, left little doubt that the ``Doogie''
mice, which otherwise seemed normal, had superior intellects, the
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   The study caps several decades of scientific detective work
aimed at revealing the core dynamics of a brain at work _ and how
medicine might tackle problems not easily treated through
conventional approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The genetic alterations, performed on the ``Doogie'' mice in the
womb, was aimed at producing extra quantities of what is formally
known as the ``NMDA receptor 2B'' subunit.
</P>
<P>
   This NR2B subunit protein is normally found in large quantities
only in younger brains. As animals reach adulthood, a less active
subunit comes to dominate, which the scientists said could explain
why children often learn more readily than adults.
</P>
<P>
   Greely, the Stanford law expert, said it would be a mistake to
rush to judgment about the practical value of the early-stage
experiments in mice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are things that improve intellectual performance
in humans already,'' he said, ``like getting enough food to eat and
education and so on. It's important not to overly focus on the sexy
issue of the day. Both genetics and environment play a role in
almost everything we do, and I suspect memory ultimately will turn
out to be not very different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
