<HEADLINE>
WNBA FOCUSES ON YOUNGER PLAYERS, BUT VETERANS HAVE BEEN KEY FOR
FINALISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before Game 3 of the WNBA's Eastern Conference final, New York
center Kym Hampton needed one more shot to relieve the pain, one
more shot to play another day.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-inflammatory injection into her swollen 36-year-old
right knee did the trick as she scored eight points and had 11
rebounds in the Liberty's 69-54 victory against Charlotte. With the
victory, New York (18-14) advanced to the best-of-three WNBA Finals
against Houston (26-6), beginning tonight at 7 in New York's
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact the WNBA might promote its younger players such
as Chamique Holdsclaw and Rebecca Lobo, it's the league's older
players who have carried the Comets and Liberty to the finals. For
those older players who look at the opportunity to play in the
United States as an open layup. Playing in the finals is like
making the title-winning jumper as time runs out.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who averages 9.2 points and 5.6 rebounds, recently
announced that she is retiring at the conclusion of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just never thought that my career would have lasted so
long,'' Hampton said. ``It's nice to postpone retirement. Now, I
need to get my nails done. Don't you think I need a ring on this
finger?''
</P>
<P>
   Along with teammates Teresa Weatherspoon (33), Sue Wicks (32),
Venus Lacey (32) and Carolyn Jones-Young (30), who is on the team's
injured list, the Liberty appears to be a team closer to playing on
shuffleboards than on backboards.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that age doesn't matter, the quartet combines to average
25.1 points, 17.1 rebounds and 8.6 assists. In the Eastern
Conference finals victory against the Sting, Weatherspoon wore down
her younger counterpart, Dawn Staley, limiting her to 2-of-9
shooting and passing for 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season, 36-year-old Cynthia Cooper said she was
concerned that maybe she was too old and wouldn't be able to play
up to her status as defending two-time Most Valuable Player. She
need not have worried. Cooper led the league in scoring for a third
consecutive season. Perhaps all she needed for inspiration was to
realize where she was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, I was playing in Italy and thought that would
be where I would retire,'' Cooper said. ``To play in the great
arenas all across this nation _ Madison Square Garden, the Forum,
America West _ it's an emotion that's really hard to describe. And
not one moment do we take it for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Cooper, the Comets have five players at least 30 years
old _ Cooper, Tammy Jackson (37), Monica Lamb (35), Polina Tzekova
(31) and Janeth Arcain (30) _ who combine to average 40.9 points
and 16 rebounds and 7.7 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten or 12 years ago, the opportunity to play in America hadn't
presented itself,'' said Jackson, who played overseas for 13
seasons. ``I am really grateful the WNBA has arrived and the
country has accepted it and supported it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hampton, ``I never play with it \Rretirement\S over my
head. Let the chips fall where they may because if you worry about
this being your last game, then you are worried about things you
should not even worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   She just wants to keep shooting.
Old is beautiful New York's Lady Liberties Player Age Stats Kym
Hampton 36 9.2 ppg., 5.6 rpg. Teresa Weatherspoon 33 7.2 ppg., 6.4
apg. Sue Wicks 32 6.8 ppg., 7.0 rpg. Venus Lacey 32 1.9 ppg., 1.2
rpg. Houston's Continuing Comets Player Age Stats Cynthia Cooper 36
22.1 ppg., 5.2 apg. Janeth Arcain 30 5.8 ppg., 2.8 rpg. Tammy
Jackson 37 2.6 ppg., 3.3 rpg. Polina Tzekova 31 6.1 ppg., 5.1 rpg.
x-Monica Lamb 35 4.3 ppg., 2.0 rpg. x _ on injured list
</P>
