<HEADLINE>
NASCAR FANS HAVE THEIR BOOING PRIORITIES ALL MIXED UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the NASCAR Winston Cup Series rolls into Darlington, S.C.,
for the most revered of its summer holiday weekends, ]one would
have thought that Dale Earnhardt had shot the President.
</P>
<P>
   With their voices and via e-mail, NASCAR fans have registered a
resounding thumbs down for Earnhardt and the bump pass that sent
race-leader Terry Labonte spinning and ``The Intimidator'' into
Victory Lane at Bristol (Tenn.) Motor Speedway on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   And what was that strange sound raining down on Earnhardt as he
exited his black-and-banged Chevy?
</P>
<P>
   Boos? For the sport's second seven-time Winston Cup champion?
For the driver who typically receives more cheers during pre-race
introductions than any Cup driver, and more than Miss Winston? Boos
for the anti-Jeff Gordon? For doing precisely what has made
``Ironhead'' the richest driver in motorsports history _ and in the
eyes of many _ its prototypical competitor?
</P>
<P>
   ``The race fans are critics, and everyone has their opinion of
what they saw last week,'' Earnhardt said in his ongoing defense.
``It happened. I wasn't trying to wreck Terry. I hate that it
happened, but it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Two issues stick out in the aftermath of Earnhardt vs. Labonte:
</P>
<P>
   What do NASCAR's brand-loyal fans really want from Earnhardt, or
any driver, in the sport's premier division? Do fans want the
``boulevard racing'' that superspeedway mogul Bruton Smith so
detests, or do fans want the type of racing that has made NASCAR
the runaway success that it is today?
</P>
<P>
   And, can any NASCAR official define what constitutes a
proper/improper bump pass?
</P>
<P>
   That certainly was not the case Saturday night, when Jerry
Nadeau got penalized two laps for rapping Dale Jarrett in the rear
end _ long before Earnhardt launched Labonte into the spin cycle.
Why was Nadeau nabbed and Earnhardt let off? The appearance is that
Earnhardt, as Labonte and several drivers suggested postrace,
received preferential treatment equal to his stature.
</P>
<P>
   That also could be the interpretation when the case of Rudd vs.
Allison is reviewed. Ricky Rudd was involved in a similar last-lap
incident with Davey Allison at Sears Point (Calif.) Raceway in
1991. NASCAR accused Rudd of spinning Allison out of the lead as
the two headed to the white flag. Rudd was penalized 15 seconds,
and finished second.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling then was it was every man for himself on the final
lap,'' said Rudd, who finished third Saturday in a battered Ford.
``NASCAR said that wasn't the way it was. I didn't agree then, but
I took what they said and moved on. Maybe it's changed since then.
I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the veiled threats of retaliation mumbled by Labonte after
the race, NASCAR senior vice president Mike Helton needs to address
that issue before they drop the green flag and the chicken wings at
the Pepsi Southern 500 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As for the issue of booing Earnhardt, perhaps a quick review of
NASCAR's first 50 years is in order. The hoopla surrounding
NASCAR's golden anniversary in 1998 produced any number of top-10
lists, including 10 best races. ``Sports Illustrated's'' list was
typical, and it was topped by the 1976 Daytona 500. That race
featured a last-lap exchange of fenders between leader David
Pearson and arch-rival Richard Petty in the 31-degree Turn 4
banking, sending both cars careening into the concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson won the race only because he pushed in the clutch and
kept his Mercury running during the spin, allowing him to limp
across the finish line _ which Petty's stalled Dodge fell 50 feet
short of passing.
</P>
<P>
   It has been called the greatest race in NASCAR history, and both
drivers emerged as cult heroes and even respectful friends.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Earnhardt joined Labonte as only the second driver
with 600 career Cup starts at Watkins Glen (N.Y.) International
last month. They are proud members of the Class of 1979, with nine
championships between them. They know the written and unwritten
rules of NASCAR better than you or me or Helton, or anyone who
never has driven a Cup car. And they know the rules as well as
Jimmy Spencer and Bobby Hamilton and anyone currently driving a Cup
car.
</P>
<P>
   And so, on Saturday night, Labonte overtook Earnhardt for the
lead as the two took the white flag. The damning contact took place
as they barged through the 36-degree banking in Turn 2. Seconds
before, all of Earnhardt's loyal fans were on their feet _ begging
their hero to do whatever it took to win the race, just like he
used to in his glory days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I not supposed to try to pass him back?'' Earnhardt asked,
incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   If he had not, then Dale Earnhardt should have been booed.
Spotlight On... Ray's crowing glory looms as perfect match for TMS
Armed with the Indy Racing League points lead, Greg Ray dialed up
Eddie Gossage at Texas Motor Speedway on Tuesday and got an earful
of advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him not to clinch it in Las Vegas,'' said Gossage,
referring to the penultimate round of the Pep Boys IRL season at
Las Vegas Motor Speedway on Sept. 26. ``I don't think he'll listen
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage, the executive vice president and general manager of
TMS, obviously has ulterior motives. He is banking on a points race
that has 13 drivers mathematically eligible to win the championship
to carry over into the season-ending Lone Star 500 at TMS on Oct.
17. Ray, who scored his third victory in the past four races at
Pikes Peak International Raceway on Sunday, leads Scott Goodyear by
44 points.
</P>
<P>
   Ray will win the Pep Boys Million as season champion if he
finishes third or better in each of the last two events.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities for Ray, on a personal and promotional level,
promise to keep Gossage and his staff hopping during the next
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about this and wondering how many people
were there when the Cowboys won their first Super Bowl,'' Gossage
said. ``And it's still fresh in our minds about the Stars winning
the Stanley Cup, and Lance Armstrong winning the Tour de France.
We've got a unique opportunity here _ and maybe it's destiny _ that
the season finale for the IRL is in Greg Ray's back yard. I do
equate it to those kinds of monumental sports occasions in this
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, he's made an impression on us here, and you always
want the hometown guy to do well. Dale Earnhardt grew up in
Kannapolis /RNorth Carolina/S in the shadow of Charlotte Motor
Speedway. That's been a nice fit. Likewise, Greg Ray came along at
just the right time at Texas Motor Speedway. It's a mutually
beneficial relationship. What could be finer than for him to win
the race and his championship at his home track?''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Gossage said he has hired Jay Howard, who puts
together the annual NASCAR Winston Cup season-ending program at
Atlanta Motor Speedway in November, to handle the extravaganza in
north Fort Worth next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do something where the car and driver are in some
fashion put up on a stage and before the fans with fireworks going
off,'' Gossage said. ``We've even got a design with dancing water
fountains around the cars. We want to do something like that. We're
asking, `What can we do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ray has promised that he will not drive any differently during
the final two events. In fact, he admittedly feels uncomfortable as
favorite after struggling the first two seasons of his IRL career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing anything different than I did in January,'' said
Ray, who gave car-owner John Menard his league-record seventh
victory in the No. 2 Glidden-Menards Dallara/Aurora. ``I know who I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said that was not the case the first time Ray strolled
into his office for a visit one Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He introduced himself and proceeded to tell me what to do to
this racetrack,'' Gossage said. ``Here's a guy that had run
Toyota-Atlantic, had started racing in 1990 ... and I listened to
him and thanked him and kind of showed him the door. He's always
been this intense guy. People can mistake him for being cocky, but
the truth is, he's a supremely confident person. We've become good
friends and I really enjoy being around him. And I have seen
personally that he's toned down his intensity level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked about his intensity after Indy. I told him to relax
and it would come to him. He was forcing it too much and he's told
me he's becoming a smarter race car driver. He's done something
since Indy, and won some races.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS Crushed at Indy Pro Stock driver Bruce Allen of
Arlington is a two-time runner-up in the U.S. Nationals, the
National Hot Rod Association's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Pro Stock honor roll at Indianapolis Raceway Park in
Clermont, Ind., includes 10-time series champion Bob Glidden,
Ronnie Sox, Wayne Gapp, Don Nicholson and the late Lee Shepherd,
also of Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who replaced Shepherd at Reher-Morrison Racing in 1985,
understandably has classified his second runner-up finish at IRP in
1986 as the biggest disappointment of his career. At that time, the
rivalry between Glidden's Ford Thunderbirds and Reher-Morrison's
Chevrolet Camaros was hot stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was racing Bob Glidden and I totally had him covered,'' said
Allen, driver of the Outlaw Fuel Additives Pontiac Firebird. ``I
got the jump at the starting line and I was outrunning him until my
engine exploded in high gear, and he drove right by me for the win.
It just crushed me.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was back in the days when Indy was the only race where
every single pro would compete. If you won Indy, you knew that you
were the best of the best. Plus, we got extra points for winning,
so it really meant a lot to win the race back then. It's still the
one race you want to win. I guess it always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The event, which carries a $2.6-million purse, is scheduled to
begin today and conclude Monday. Jarrett tops ballot Dale Jarrett
dropped 101 points off his NASCAR Winston Cup points lead over Mark
Martin on Saturday night at Bristol (Tenn.) Raceway, where he
finished an uncharacteristic 38th.
</P>
<P>
   But Jarrett had a near-bulletproof run heading into Bristol,
which resulted in his selection as winner of the third-quarter vote
for Driver of the Year. Jarrett received 10 first-place votes and
four runner-ups from a panel of 15 motorsports journalists,
including this reporter, for a total of 114 points. Jarrett
outdistanced second-place finisher Juan Montoya, rookie star in the
Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya earned one first-place vote and 59 points. Third went to
NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series points-leader Greg Biffle, who earned
two first-place votes and 56 points. World of Outlaws star Mark
Kinser earned two first-place votes en route to tying CART's Dario
Franchitti for fourth with 36 points.
</P>
<P>
   Plano's Greg Ray, who scored two of his three Pep Boys Indy
Racing League victories during the quarter, earned one vote.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's Jeff Burton won the first quarter vote, and Montoya
prevailed during the second quarter. Two more rounds of voting
remain. Schumacher a slow healer Ferrari's Michael Schumacher
probably will miss at least the next two races on the Formula One
schedule because of persistent pain in the leg that was broken
during the British Grand Prix in July.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher, a two-time World Driving Champion, made the decision
yesterday after his second practice drive since the crash, and
canceled plans to continue testing at Monza, Italy. He had planned
to return for the Italian Grand Prix on Sept. 12 on the same track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a test, and the problems in my leg are too big to do a
proper job,'' Schumacher said at a news conference. ``It is
basically impossible for me to run more than five laps at the
moment, and especially on this circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   The German said he would consult with his doctors Sunday.
Schumacher likely also will skip the European Grand Prix on Sept.
26. The final two races are in Malaysia on Oct. 17 and Japan on
Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher first returned to the cockpit on Aug. 20 at Mugello,
Italy, 40 days after breaking both bones in his lower right leg at
Silverstone, England. Last laps The management of Darlington
Raceway reportedly is ready to spend $3 million to add a lighting
system at NASCAR's oldest superspeedway, and run at least one of
its two Winston Cup races on the 1.366-mile oval at night.
</P>
<P>
   Roush Racing has released Johnny Benson from his contract as
driver of the No. 26 Cheerios Ford Taurus. Benson will complete the
season with the team, which does not have a primary sponsor for the
2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup veteran Ted Musgrave has been selected to replace
Butch Miller in the No. 40 Channellock Chevrolet Monte Carlo for
the Dura-Lube 200 at Darlington Raceway this weekend. Last words
``Who would have ever thought we'd need a race at Darlington,
especially the Southern 500, to calm everybody down?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ricky Rudd, on the mood of the NASCAR Winston Cup garage
exiting Bristol Motor Speedway
</P>
