<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG-12-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKE 1996, A&AMP;M WON'T BE MESMERIZED BY THIS AERIAL CIRCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Within two days, Texas A&AMP;M embarks on a season that could
include a fairy-tale journey from the No. 6 position to the top
spot in the college football rankings by the time all tortoises and
hares reach the finish line in January.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, we offer this reminder about fairy tales.
Few come true. Some, with apologies to Aesop and Mother Goose,
unfold like this:
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, a maroon-clad football team awash in preseason
expectations opted to play its first game on the road against a
renowned gunslinger. And, lo, the strong-armed slinger they called
Steve Sarkisian surgically dissected an overmatched maroon
secondary, giving the home team a stunning upset.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to regroup, the maroon-clad warriors opted to visit a
small school in Louisiana, where the home team surely would serve
up a feel-good victory, as well as a side order of gumbo. But, lo,
the locals held firm and paddled the invading maroon marauders,
sending them tailspinning toward a .500 record.
</P>
<P>
   Any similarities between A&AMP;M's fairy-tale dreams of 1999 and its
nightmarish reality check in 1996 should be purely coincidental.
But we offer this sobering update, from a historical perspective:
The Aggies open their season Saturday night in Shreveport, La.,
against the nation's top gunslinger (Tim Rattay), who is the
quarterback for a small school in Louisiana (Louisiana Tech).
</P>
<P>
   Could this be a double whammy that threatens to undermine the
Aggies' run toward a national championship before they reach the
first turn on the track?
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Hugh Grant, who admittedly struggled with the
line during the filming of ``Mickey Blue Eyes'': ``Fuggitaboudit.''
</P>
<P>
   These Aggies, unlike their predecessors who belly-flopped
against Brigham Young and Southwestern Louisiana, should be able to
smirk their way through a double-digit triumph despite a hostile
crowd, a Rattay air show or _ worst of all _ a shortage of Tabasco
sauce for the pregame crawfish.
</P>
<P>
   In three years, A&AMP;M has gone from a young team in search of
playmakers to an experienced juggernaut, with 16 returning starters
and seniors dictating the on-field mood swings in most situations.
Coming off an 11-3 season and a Big 12 championship, these guys
won't panic in times of trouble, as the 1996 team did.
</P>
<P>
   Randy McCown and Sedrick Curry can testify to the
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of guys on this team who won't let us have
another letdown like that,'' said McCown, a senior who suited up in
both of A&AMP;M's stunning losses to begin the 1996 season. ``I can see
the similarities \Rin early opponents\S. But we all know if we lose
to Louisiana Tech, there goes the national championship. We
shouldn't have any problem with a letdown like that this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor should the Aggies be vulnerable to an all-out air raid, as
they were against BYU in 1996. That day, Sarkisian shredded a young
secondary for 536 yards and six touchdowns while under little
duress from the A&AMP;M pass rush. Three years later, A&AMP;M is eight-deep
in quality defensive linemen and features what coach R.C. Slocum
considers his best secondary since NFL draftees Aaron Glenn, Ray
Mickens and Patrick Bates patrolled the deep zones in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about this game,'' said Curry, a third-year
starter at cornerback who was a well-scorched freshman at BYU in
1996. ``We know going in we're facing an all-out passing offense.
But that gives us more opportunities to make plays and get our
hands on the ball. We're comfortable and confident about what we
need to do. That comes with experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. Rattay is the real deal. After throwing for 240
yards in last week's 41-7 loss at top-ranked Florida State,
Seminoles coach Bobby Bowden called Rattay ``the best passer I've
seen on this field'' in his 24 seasons in Tallahassee, Fla. Such a
list would include lots of luminaries.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these Aggies, unlike their predecessors, have the talent,
depth and ball-control abilities to survive a road date against an
aerial circus. By January, A&AMP;M's fairy-tale season may not come
true. But it should survive a trip to Louisiana.
\Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON
Eric Gay Concern about using starters on special teams runs high at
Kansas State, where David Allen, the nation's leading punt returner
in 1998, has emerged as the starting tailback.
Longhorns' horror sets off a wave of paranoia
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, selected outtakes from season-opening losses by
Texas (three blocked punts) and Kansas (blocked field goal) have
made for required viewing throughout the Big 12 this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns surrendered 16 points on blocked punts in a 23-20
loss to North Carolina State. Kansas' blocked field goal swung the
third-quarter momentum toward Notre Dame, turning a potential
four-point game into a 48-13 runaway.
</P>
<P>
   To a man, rival Big 12 coaches said they are using the video
clips to remind their players of the importance of special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, there's 300 paranoid coaches around the country
after watching what happened to Texas. Me, included,'' Colorado
coach Gary Barnett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want any team to have those kind of misfortunes,''
Oklahoma State coach Bob Simmons said. ``But it illustrates a point
and it's gotten our guys' attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the league, coaches are wrestling over the choice
between playing starters on special teams or reserving those roles
for backups. The toughest choice belongs to Kansas State coach Bill
Snyder, who has seen David Allen _ the nation's leading punt
returner _ emerge as his starting tailback.
</P>
<P>
   ``David made his mark at that position. He's close to some NCAA
records,'' said Snyder, who watched the former Fort Worth resident
average 22.12 yards per return, with four touchdowns, in 1998.
``But is it in our best interest for him to keep returning punts?
That's a difficult decision.''
\Nsubheds:QUICK HITS Safety shuffle Because of injuries, Texas
safety Lee Jackson will make his second career start at a second
position in Saturday's game against Stanford (11 a.m., Austin).
Jackson opened at strong safety in last week's 23-20 loss to North
Carolina State but was shifted to free safety in workouts this week
because of injuries to Quentin Jammer (shoulder) and Chris Butcher
(knee).
</P>
<P>
   Greg Brown, Jackson's backup, will start at strong safety. That
means the biggest adjustment this week falls on the shoulders of
Jackson, a sophomore, as the Longhorns prepare to face a team that
returns every significant player from a team that threw for 3,516
yards and 22 touchdowns last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be a little nervous, but I was nervous in the first game,
too,'' Jackson said. ``I just have to fill Jammer's shoes and
that's what I plan to do.''
\Nsubheds:Open auditions at A&AMP;M Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum has yet
to settle on a replacement for inside linebacker Dat Nguyen, the
1998 Lombardi Award winner, in the Aggies' lineup. Playing time
distribution for four potential successors ``is still up in the
air,'' said Slocum, with two days remaining before the season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said he probably will start senior Chad Frantzen against
Louisiana Tech, with significant playing time possible for freshman
Brian Gamble and sophomores Amon Simon and Harold Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's asserted himself, in my opinion,'' Slocum said.
\Nsubheds:Steele to script QB action Baylor coach Kevin Steele said
backup quarterback Odell James will see some action in Saturday's
opener at Boston College (11 a.m., ESPN), but it will not depend on
the performance of starter Jermaine Alfred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll script it and have a specific place for Odell to go
in,'' said Steele, who reiterated his commitment to Alfred as the
starter. ``It'll be more a time-of-the-game thing than \Ra
situational substitution\S. If you put guys in just to run certain
plays, you can get things out of sync.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:BURCH'S PICKS Staff writer Jimmy Burch picks (against
the line) this week's Big 12 football games:
</P>
<P>
   Stanford (plus 11) at Texas. Pick: Texas. Longhorns rebound with
a vengeance while Cardinal players melt in Texas heat.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M at Louisiana Tech (plus 14 1/2). Pick: A&AMP;M. Aggies
control both lines, limit the air strikes of Tim Rattay.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (plus 41/2) at Boston College. Pick: Baylor. A coin flip
says the Bears keep it close, if not pull an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana-Lafayette (plus 34) at Oklahoma State. Pick: ULL.
Cowboys win handily but not by five touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama-Birmingham (plus 23) at Missouri. Pick: Missouri.
Tigers' turnaround is legitimate. An opening romp should prove
that.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado vs. Colorado State (plus 13). Pick: Colorado. Buffaloes
rule this series, should send statement in Gary Barnett's debut.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska at Iowa (plus 24). Pick: Nebraska. Rebuilding Hawkeyes
are no match for reloading Cornhuskers.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana State at Iowa State (no line). Pick: Iowa State.
Cyclones start quickly against Division I-AA foe.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech (plus 6 1/2) at Arizona State. Pick: Arizona State.
Red Raiders find a way to lose another heartbreaker on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's record: 2-0. Season record: 2-0.
