<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 08:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8279 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBN-ASTROS-TEX     09-02 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS OUTFIELDERS SEEM CURSED IN HOUSE OF PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Astrodome is doomed as a baseball venue, but the
Eighth Wonder of the World refuses to go quietly.
</P>
<P>
   As an act of vengeance against the last team that will abandon
it, the Dome seems to have placed a curse on the Houston Astros
outfielders. From the time Moises Alou fell off a treadmill before
spring training and ripped up his knee to Sunday, when Alou fell
off a bicycle and re-injured himself, the Astros have been
clobbered by a series of injuries to their outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm in my second year of medical school,'' Astros
general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``I never wanted to be a
doctor. I'm ready to resign my post.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou was just the start of troubles for the outfield. Since the
All-Star break, the Astros have lost Richard Hidalgo, Derek Bell,
Glenn Barker and Carl Everett to injuries that required time on the
disabled list. Hidalgo is done for the season after knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The situation reached an absurd point this week when the Astros
outfield consisted of three players _ veteran Bill Spiers and
rookies Daryle Ward and Lance Berkman _ who were once considered
infielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pitching staff has saved us,'' second baseman Craig Biggio
said. ``If it wasn't for our pitching, we'd be in real trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching and the usual superb play and leadership of Biggio and
Jeff Bagwell have allowed the Astros to fend off _ for now _ the
surprising Cincinnati Reds in the National League Central. But it
has been a much tougher fight for a team that walked away with the
division title by 12 1/2 games last year.
</P>
<P>
   The outfield has only been a part of the team's hospital unit.
Third baseman Ken Caminiti, shortstop Ricky Gutierrez and catcher
Mitch Meluskey have also missed significant time because of
injuries. Meluskey is out for the season. Manager Larry Dierker was
out one month because of brain surgery after he suffered a seizure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has been through a lot,'' Caminiti said. ``The last
two weeks have been really bad. But there's a lot of good character
on this team. You just can't dwell on (the injuries).''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have some hope the curse may be lifting. Bell was
activated from the disabled list Wednesday, and Everett could be
back in seven to 10 days. Hunsicker, who picked up outfielder Matt
Mieske last month, added more depth Tuesday by acquiring veteran
outfielder Stan Javier from the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   That gives the Astros hope they'll have a veteran outfield in
place for the stretch run and the playoffs. It would keep them from
having to rely on their two prized rookies, Ward and Berkman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are a big part of our future,'' Hunsicker said. ``But
down the stretch, when you're in a pressure situation and every
game counts, experience plays a big factor. To ask those kids to
step into that kind of situation is asking a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   During spring training, the Astros were hoping Alou would return
in time for the stretch run. They announced then he would miss five
months because of a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left
knee. His goal was to return in mid-August, but that eventually
proved too optimistic. Then he fell off a bicycle playing with his
3-year-old son Sunday _ ``Poor judgment,'' Hunsicker said _ and now
the Astros have all but given up hope he'll be back for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the Astros outfield can a guy suffer two season-ending
injuries in one season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing that really hurts,'' Dierker said. ``It
seemed like we were trying to hold the line until mid-August,
late-August until he got back. Then when he rejoined the club (for
rehabilitation) in August, you could see the desire to get him back
became tangible, you could almost feel it in the clubhouse. This
hurts, but there hasn't been anything easy about this season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros expected to do some serious bashing this year after
they added Caminiti to a lineup that led the National League with a
club-record 874 runs last year. Hunsicker said in spring training
that the Astros wouldn't need an Atlanta Braves-type pitching staff
because the offense was so good.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out it has been the reverse. The Astros began September
with 660 runs, ninth-most in the league. But the pitching staff has
saved them.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton (17-3, 2.97 earned-run average), Jose Lima (18-7,
3.35 ERA) and Billy Wagner (1.90 ERA, 33 saves) were All-Stars, and
Shane Reynolds (14-11, 3.80 ERA) has been almost as good. Scott
Elarton (7-4, 3.12 ERA) has pitched well enough to show why the
Astros didn't want to give him up in a possible trade for Roger
Clemens. The Astros, despite losing Randy Johnson in the
off-season, are second in the league in pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate the pitching staff, especially the starting
staff, stepped it up big,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros don't expect the Reds to go away, and a two-game
series against them Sept. 28-29 at the Astrodome could decide the
division. But the Astros also believe much could change before then
with the addition of Javier and by getting Bell and Everett back.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep the ship afloat for the next seven-10 days and
have everybody healthy, I believe we have the best team in the
division,'' Hunsicker said. ``We can win it.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 0803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
