<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 08:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8280 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-OKLAHOMA-PREVIEW-     09-02 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OKLAHOMA-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOONERS PLAYERS, FANS, STOOPS IS TALKING THEIR LANGUAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ Perhaps Bob Stoops has not been a head coach
long enough to learn the verbal two-step, though during his
eight-month tenure at the helm of the Oklahoma football program
he's already established a reputation for plain-speak _ in marked
contrast to many college football coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been incredibly impressed with both coach Stoops
and his staff,'' OU Alumni Association director Paul Massad said.
``He relates extremely well to people. He doesn't put them off when
he gets a direct question. He doesn't use excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoops has openly informed a rabid OU following that longs for a
return to the thrilling days of yesteryear that indeed it is all
right to expect the Sooners to win on Saturday. Any Saturday.
Beginning now. Forget any long-range rebuilding plan to bring the
program out of the depths of the first three consecutive losing
seasons since the university first fielded a football team in 1895.
</P>
<P>
   Stoops, defensive coordinator at Florida last season, figured
what the heck. No harm in telling them what they want to hear. And
no point in not doing it, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't think they'd think that no matter what I say?''
Stoops said with a laugh on a recent afternoon. ``We've won too
many championships here and had too many great teams that these
people shouldn't want \Rto win every game\S. We're no different
from a lot of tradition-rich programs _ they all want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a gaudy past, Oklahoma has not won as much as a
conference championship since 1987. Nor have the Sooners won as
many as 10 games in a dozen seasons. In three seasons under Stoops'
predecessor, John Blake, the Sooners were 12-22.
</P>
<P>
   But Stoops' message of immediate returns has not been only for
public consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has impressed me,'' said quarterback Josh Heupel, a
junior-college transfer who wasn't around during the John Blake
era, ``is that these coaches really and truly believe they can do
it quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't they all? What makes this brash young coach in his first
job any different than Blake or his flash-in-a-season predecessor
Howard Schnellenberger? At this juncture _ less than 10 days before
Stoops' first kickoff on the OU sidelines _ everything. And that's
according to someone who should know.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth-year senior Jay Smith has experienced something no other
player in OU history has _ four head coaches. Before the former
Lamar High School offensive lineman arrived in Norman, OU had gone
28 years with four head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a different story,'' Smith declared.
``This is a different era. You can see that just in our practices.
There's not a lot of standing around in line. Everyone is involved,
everyone is getting their reps in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches are working us hard and teaching us how to win
games. The players' attitude is so much better. Last year, we
weren't mentally or physically prepared. We didn't even have an
offensive playbook. It seemed we didn't even have a game plan. You
can't go out and win games like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustration goes back to Schnellenberger's lone season
(5-5-1) in 1995. OU lost four of its last five games, failed to
score in its last two and lost to archrival Oklahoma State for the
first time since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Recall that Schnellenberger was going to be the coach that would
once again make Oklahoma a big winner, after Gary Gibbs compiled a
44-23-2 record during six seasons that included probation
limitations after succeeding the legend-in-his-own-time Barry
Switzer in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   As Schnellenberger's only season went on, ``the players lost
respect for him,'' Smith said. ``There were several on and
off-the-field things that happened to cause that, and the team
spiraled downhill because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   OU is 2-5-1 in the past four years against Texas and Oklahoma
State, 0-3 against Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   How soon the Sooners hope to forget. Fans and students have
flocked to the ticket windows to purchase more than 50,000 season
packages for the first time since 1992. The surge has been such
that ticket manager Tom Blubaugh is still holding individual
tickets for the season-ending OSU game to ensure he can fill those
season ticket orders still coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 200 calls for season tickets in the 48 hours after Bob
Stoops was hired,''` Blubaugh recalled. ``People are definitely
excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoops' staff has worked as hard at changing this team's psyche
as it has at bringing structure to its offensive and defensive
schemes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team that hasn't won for a few years, there's reasons why,''
Stoops said. ``Often, it's the mental approach _ the tenacity they
don't have. Their mental approach to winning needs to improve.
Their expectations need to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got a good nucleus of players we should be able
to win with. The thing we've got to do is get the most out of the
talent we have. If we do that and we have a few guys who
overachieve, we've got enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoops' straightforward approach early won over a team
desperately searching for leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Stoops is a great guy,'' senior safety Rodney Rideau
said. ``He preaches discipline, getting the job done and he
preaches excellence. That's what we want to hear, what it takes to
win. There's no doubt he's brought structure and organization back
to the team. He sets goals and encourages us to set goals _ and to
live by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came from a winning tradition. And hopefully, he'll bring
it back to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 0804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0062 </DOCNO>
