<HEADER>
A8282 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-NHRA-SCHDULE-TEX     09-02 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-SCHDULE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHRA, TEXAS TRACK AIM AT MEMORIAL WEEKEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Hot Rod Association is preparing to enter the
crowded Memorial Day weekend racing schedule with a national event
at the Texas Motorplex next year.
</P>
<P>
   Motorplex owner Billy Meyer said he has been working with NHRA
president Dallas Gardner to move the 3-year-old Castrol Nationals
from its late-April/early May slot to Memorial Day weekend. Meyer
said Tuesday that he has not seen a draft of the 2000 schedule,
which is expected to be released during the 45th annual U.S.
Nationals at Indianapolis Raceway Park on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that would make me believe that it is not
going to happen,'' said Meyer, referring to the date switch. ``But
until there is actual confirmation in writing ... it's better to
take the approach it's our assumption it's going to happen. I think
it will be a huge benefit to the spring race and give NHRA the
ability to be highlighted in the national market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to associate Memorial Day weekend with the
Motorplex and the Castrol Nationals.'' If the dates are switched
and follow the typical NHRA professional format, the fourth annual
Castrol Nationals would be run at the Motorplex in Ennis from May
26-28. That will put the event's final day up against two
established races. The 84th Indianapolis 500, the world's most
famous auto race, runs at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. And the
Coca-Cola 600, NASCAR's longest race, is a tradition at the Lowe's
Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a desire to move to Memorial Day weekend for some
time, and we don't consider it `competition' by any means,'' Meyer
said. ``We consider it the fact that the NHRA is the only one of
the three major motorsports that doesn't have a spectator event on
one of the biggest holiday weekends in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said the weather in late May in North Texas is similar to
conditions in October, when the track plays host to the NHRA's
O'Reilly Fall Nationals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us an automatic rain date that is a positive for
the spectators,'' Meyer said. The third annual Castrol Nationals
drew approximately 112,000 spectators over a three-day schedule.
</P>
<P>
   A former NHRA Funny Car driver, Meyer said the sanctioning body
most recently raced on Memorial Day weekend in 1990 at State
Capitol Dragway in Erwinville, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that event went away, it was never replaced,'' Meyer
said. ``Our sales pitch was a little bit different. We felt that
with the reputation of the Motorplex _ and taking the assumption
there's going to be a new Motorplex in the future _ it would be a
perfect place to showcase NHRA on one of the biggest holiday
weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer is negotiating with the Grand Prairie City Council to move
the Motorplex to a new $74 million facility in 2001. The proposed
site is the intersection of Interstate 30 and MacArthur Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said he was not certain how the race's TV rights would be
handled. The Indy 500 (ABC) and Coca-Cola 600 (TBS) are televised
live.
</P>
<P>
   ``That somewhat depends on the new NHRA TV package that is close
to being put together,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a source said that Houston Raceway Park in Baytown
will retain both its spring and fall races next year; that the
Winston Showdown all-star event will be staged for the second
consecutive year at Bruton Smith's revamped Bristol (Tenn.)
Dragway; and that the only new event will be at Smith's Las Vegas
Motor Speedway in early April. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
