A8399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CHANGING-IMMIGRANT-$A     09-02 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHANGING-IMMIGRANT-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMPLOYER-PROVIDED HOUSING DRAWS MANY HISPANIC WORKERS
 &HT;    With CHANGING-SOUTH. For release Sunday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MT. OLIVE, N.C. _ At the largest turkey processing plant in the
nation, Juvencio Rocha Peralta holds two key positions _ associate
housing manager and resident compadre.
</P>
<P>
   At Carolina Turkeys, it's hard to tell which job carries more
weight.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to managing 120 housing units, Peralta has become an
important resource for a growing number of Hispanic employees,
already 65 percent of the plant's work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask me _ 'Juvencio, how can I get my child enrolled in
school? Juvencio, where is the closest church? Juvencio, I got this
ticket, what should I do?' `` he said with a chuckle. ``I guess
after time, they realize that I know all these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Peralta graciously assumes the role of community liaison after
20 years of working in North Carolina, including long stretches in
farm and construction jobs. He organizes Latino festivals, plans
soccer tournaments and has become involved in local and state
health care and education issues.
</P>
<P>
   Having lived through the migration experience, he has strong
empathy for the plant's 2,800 workers, many of whom recently
arrived and are going through the same culture shock that he felt
at 16 when he came from Veracruz, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He knows, for example, that it is very hard to rent an apartment
without established credit, rent history or even a checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Turkeys' solution: employee housing. Peralta makes the
arrangements and guides the workers step by step.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy _ if you work, you pay,'' Peralta said, describing
the company's policy of deducting rent directly from paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   The housing _ almost completely rented by Hispanics _ is a
five-minute car ride from the plant, which is open 24 hours a day.
The white and cream-colored trailer homes are well maintained and
fully furnished.
</P>
<P>
   The housing sports some unexpected amenities, such as a cement
basketball court and a large soccer field. Carolina Turkeys has
also donated nearby land for Catholic and Baptist churches with
Hispanic ministries.
</P>
<P>
   Esperanza Valdez, 41, lives in one of the homes with her five
children. She pays $320 a month in rent, plus the electric bill.
Hourly salaries at the plant range from $6.90 to $9 an hour and
employees have full benefits, including health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Two walls of Valdez's home are decorated with family photos and
certificates that her children won in school. Originally from the
Dominican Republic, Valdez arrived in North Carolina after living
in Puerto Rico for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, I feel good. I have a job, a safe place to live _ things
I didn't have before,'' she said, gazing down at her brightly
colored dining room tablecloth.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez and other renters do not have to sign a lease, Peralta
said. They can leave at any time if they find a better or cheaper
place, and the company will give them a good credit rating if they
have been there for a while. Peralta said he suspects Carolina
Turkeys may expand the housing if the company continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   As he walks through the plant, where 80,000 birds are processed
daily, workers on all parts of the assembly line greet him warmly.
Wearing hair nets, white smocks, and rubber boots, some wave to
Peralta as the turkeys go by.
</P>
<P>
   Roel Cantu, who hails from Chiapas in southern Mexico, says the
plant is a wonderful place to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so much better,'' he said, referring to his previous
stint as a farm hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't sweat and get dirt all over your clothes and your
face. This is a clean job.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
