<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8402 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV05-C     09-02 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: WHAT DOES GEORGE II STAND FOR?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Historians say that for a British monarch, Charles
I had exquisite manners and few vices. But he lacked the common
touch and in 1649, after quarreling with Parliament, he got his
head chopped off.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing for changes in customs over 350 years, the sad fate of
the Stuart king resonates in the forced exit of George I from the
White House in 1993. The electorate felt that President Bush had
run out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   The analogy to the Stuarts continues with the rise of George II,
the Texas governor who would succeed his father, as Charles II
succeeded to the throne a decade after his daddy's departure. The
younger Charles was admired for his political adaptability but
accused by detractors of lacking core beliefs. The years of his
reign are known in English history as the Restoration period.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, there has been a persistent theme in the coverage of
the 2000 campaign that the younger Bush hasn't put a lot on the
table in terms of what he believes or where he wants to take the
country were he to win. One hears widely that, if he may not be
guilty of substance abuse, then he's certainly guilty of a lack of
substance.
</P>
<P>
   But for a politician criticized by Beltway insiders as being
inexperienced, untested and vague, Bush has molded a surprisingly
precise social doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   His stance, which hasn't been widely reported: The goal of the
current prosperity must be to leave nobody behind. Taxes should be
cut to spur growth but not, as happened during the Reagan era, to
gut federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush notes how fellow Texan Lyndon Johnson once sought to forge
a secular Great Society. LBJ's pitch, he says, has ``become a
warning, not an example. We found that government can spend money,
but it can't put hope in our hearts or a sense of purpose in our
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   George II chucks aside constitutional strictures separating
church and state. His pitch: ``It is not enough for conservatives
like me to praise these (faith-based) efforts. It is not enough to
call for volunteerism. Without more support and resources _ both
private and public _ we are asking them to make bricks without
straw.''
</P>
<P>
   Major passages in Bush's social policy manifesto, titled ``The
Duty of Hope,'' read as if they could have been drafted by the Rev.
Jesse Jackson. When I pointed this out to Jackson the other day, he
looked at me over his half-moon glasses and said: ``He's not the
first politician to imitate Jesse Jackson. There's a gap between
the right language and reality.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson is mistaken, George II would try to put the politics
of faith in the policy saddle by pressing Congress to alter the tax
laws to favor religious charities. He would also nominate judges
inclined to reinterpret the Constitution in ways that would give
religion far greater prominence in public life.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, polls show that these views hardly serve as the
basis of Bush's political appeal. His strength derives instead from
his seeming electability as an all-around nice guy than from what
he might actually seek to accomplish in the new millennium _ were
there to be a reprise of the Stuarts' Glorious Restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
