<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Road ahead is clear for the
Roadhouse
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ A nice lady phoned the other day,
concerned about the fate of the Lost in the '50s Roadhouse, that
little cafe north of town just this side of the river bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Awhile back I'd written that the route of the new interstate may
come right through the front door and out the back, leaving nothing
but a greasy spot in the road.
</P>
<P>
   Hereabouts, Lost in the '50s is important to lots of folks, from
the down-home good ol' boys to the uptown well-to-do. People you
run into at Sunday brunch at the country club you're likely to see
most any other day of the week munching juicy cheeseburgers at the
roadhouse.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time I entertain visiting journalists from the big
city. Invariably they'll want to have a meal at Lost in the '50s.
They like the decor especially, posters of James Dean, Clark Gable,
Marilyn Monroe, along with classic cars of the same era.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there are the framed magazine ads from all those
years ago. My favorite promotes Chesterfields as the brand
recommended by more doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can smoke in the roadhouse, even big cigars. Just
don't go asking for decaffeinated coffee. The same goes for booze.
</P>
<P>
   The roadhouse is not a juke joint, this being a dry county, but
it has probably the best honky-tonk jukebox you'll find most
anywhere _ music from the 1950s at a price from the 1950s, 12 plays
for a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   With the original knotty pine paneling and wooden booths, it's a
museum for memories of the way cafes used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us have been worried that the Lost in the '50s may end
up a memory itself, lost to progress.
</P>
<P>
   The final decision for the route for the interstate has yet to
be announced. But I've been asking around.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow I know just up the highway, whose home is so close to
the bridge that he figures to lose his property regardless of which
way things go, has been keeping in touch with the highway
department as close as most anybody.
</P>
<P>
   And he says without a doubt the roadhouse will survive.
</P>
<P>
   Which is good enough for me. I'm the kind of reporter who stops
asking questions once he hears what he wants to hear.
</P>
<P>
   I passed along that word to Miz Sharon, who runs Lost in the
'50s along with her husband. She said that was good news, but she's
still waiting for official word.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm hoping it'll come soon, and the roadhouse can
then proceed with a bit of progress of its own.
</P>
<P>
   From some time now Miz Sharon has been talking about adding a
dance floor, a project I'm much in favor of.
</P>
<P>
   It's the very dickens to listen to Little Jimmy Dickens or Hank
Williams or Carl Perkins and manage to sit still. If nothing else
it must be bad for the digestion, juicy cheeseburgers
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Franchise places across the country spend hundreds of thousands
of dollars trying to fake the kind of atmosphere that Lost in the
'50s comes by naturally.
</P>
<P>
   It'd be a shame to lose such a landmark. The roadhouse is worthy
of a historical plaque. Or, at the very least, it's own on-off
ramp.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
