<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Pillow talk and the bomb
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, Sept. 5, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider the scene: It is a lovely night along the Seine River
in Paris. An American posted there in U.S. government service has
met a beautiful Ukrainian woman working as an interpreter at the
Louvre. They share wine and chit-chat.
</P>
<P>
   One thing leads to another and that leads to the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we start,'' the American tells the Ukrainian, ``I have
to fill out some forms and I need your help.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you are talking about?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he begins, ``there's a new rule from the U.S.
Department of Energy that requires me to notify them if I have a
sexual liaison with a person from a country that is thought to have
nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, she is pulling up her stockings and looking for
the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninotchka, don't go,'' the American pleads. ``It's just a
formality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you formality, my friend,'' she answers angrily.
``I am formally breaking relations with you. How's that for
formality?''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a scene from the classic Garbo East-West movie
``Silk Stockings.'' It's a real-life stance taken by the U.S.
Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   It is amazing how many candidates are being elected to office
crusading for government to get off our backs and how government,
instead, not only stays on our backs but gets under the sheets as
well. Unable to keep track on its own, the department is requiring
67,000 workers to report any such liaisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``MEMO
</P>
<P>
   ``To: Department of Energy
</P>
<P>
   ``From: John Doe, Israel
</P>
<P>
   ``Subject: Sexual liaison
</P>
<P>
   ``Basha Horowitz, an Israeli, had a sexual liaison with me three
days ago, but she swears that Israel does not have nuclear weapons.
She says Israel always has denied having nuclear weapons and she
believes it. As we lay there in that quandary, we decided it was
silly to waste the moment on something we could not resolve. The
remainder of the evening was eventful, if you know what I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Through history _ particularly in novels and films _ females
have been used to lure testosterone-packed males into giving up
secrets. And, of course, James Bond got just about everything he
ever wanted out of vivacious Russian female agents.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a reality to this, the department claims, and that
is Americans on overseas assignments often look in the direction of
a woman whose country may or may not be suspected of having the
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, madam, I was admiring you from my table and would
appreciate you joining me for an espresso.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, sir, that is very nice of you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But first I must ask. Do you come from a country that the U.S.
believes has nuclear weapons?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiter! Check please.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, do not think DOE is inflexible. The notice allows that if
the sexual encounter is a one-time-only and the female does not ask
for classified information, then just go ahead and enjoy yourself.
But, I presume, if in the midst of the liaison, she starts asking
about the thickness of the walls at Hoover Dam, report her
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Curran, counter-intelligence chief for the Energy Department,
was quoted by the Albuquerque Journal: ``There are many, many cases
of this. The 50-, 60-year-old person stationed overseas for months,
away from family and children, that person could be especially
vulnerable to this kind of effort.''
</P>
<P>
   And the 30- and 40-year-olds wouldn't? Why the distinction? Does
Viagra have anything to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   There are similar regulations within the Department of Defense,
as well as the FBI and CIA. For some time now, America's secrets
have been leaking faster than a faulty radiator. But it seems to me
that the people who gave away those secrets _ people like Jonathan
Pollard and Aldrich Ames _ didn't do it through bedroom dalliances;
they did it for money.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt America must protect its secrets, and I also
don't doubt that sex is a way to pry out some of those secrets. But
to provide a list of countries the U.S. says likely has nuclear
weapons and say those are the ones to avoid doesn't make sense to
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Maria, it's so nice to see you again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, Marvin, let's have sex.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ho-ho-ho, Maria, your country does not have the bomb, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right, Marvin.''
</P>
<P>
   Five steamy minutes later:
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvin?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, my dear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Explain to me, from the beginning, how an atom is split.''
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
