w e BC-IVOR-BROOKE-SHIELDS-I     09-02 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-BROOKE-SHIELDS-IN-SUDDENLY-SUSAN-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY SINGLE: A TOUGH YEAR FOR BROOKE SHIELDS
</HEADLINE>
   (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Brooke Shields
in ``Suddenly Susan.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``It's been one of the roughest years of my life,'' says actress
Brooke Shields, who recently showed up at Los Angeles' Ritz-Carlton
Hotel to talk about how major surgery had saved the life of her
ailing series ``Suddenly Susan.''
 &HT;    At 34, the former child star seems more poised and polished than
ever: Shields is stunning in a coral silk jacket worn over a
billowing black silk dress, which falls to her sandal-clad ankles.
 &HT;    Her famous locks are streaked blonde now, and they fall to a
mature shoulder level.
 &HT;    Some call it the best hair in Hollywood.
 &HT;    In the last few months, Shields has survived a series of
difficult personal experiences which, in combination, might have
felled a less balanced individual.
 &HT;    Her ``annus horribilus,'' to use Queen Elizabeth's phrase, began
late last year, when a London newspaper ran an erroneous front page
story, complete with photograph, alleging that she had been
arrested at France's Nice Airport and charged with drug possession.
 &HT;    In fact, the picture showed airport police acting as Shields'
private escort as she dodged the paparazzi.
 &HT;    The daily ran a front-page apology, but Shields had been deeply
hurt.
 &HT;    Then, in March 1999, her ``Suddenly Susan'' co-star David
Strickland hung himself in a seedy Las Vegas motel after an
alcohol-and-drugs binge.
 &HT;    Shields was shattered: Strickland had been more than just a
professional colleague. The two had become firm friends, and she
was bereft.
 &HT;    ``When your best friend dies,'' she says, ``you know your life
will never be the same again. You go through rites of passage,
intellectual and emotional. That definitely stopped me and slowed
me right down.''
 &HT;    Shields used her clout on the show to insist that the final
episode of the season be a tribute to Strickland.
 &HT;    Then, in April, she became ``suddenly single'' when her
29-year-old tennis superstar husband Andre Agassi filed for
divorce.
 &HT;    Their fairy-tale marriage had lasted a little under two years.
 &HT;    As if that weren't enough, she learned that NBC, citing poor
ratings, was on the verge of dumping her show.
 &HT;    But the network thought twice, and Shields was granted a
reprieve: ``Suddenly Susan'' would get a major makeover, new
characters would be introduced and joie de vivre would be the order
of the day.
 &HT;    The show returns to the network on September 19.
 &HT;    ``I'm so glad it's not finished,'' Shields says. ``We've gone
over it with a fine-tooth comb because we've gotten off the track a
little bit. Everything we fell in love with originally, we wanted
to make sure that would be revisited.''
 &HT;    Shields is upbeat and energized, talks cheerfully about her
comings and goings, though she is more guarded than usual and
chooses her words carefully when it comes to her private life.
 &HT;    Professionally, she's delighted to be getting a new love
interest on the show (``Melrose Place's'' handsome Rob Estes). And
Susan's San Francisco-based magazine will have a frenetic new boss,
played by Monty Python's Eric Idle.
 &HT;    ``I'm thrilled Eric's joining the show,'' Shields enthuses.
``I've been a Monty Python fan since I was a kid.''
 &HT;    About her ``darn cute'' love interest on the show, she adds:
``Sure there will be romance, but we didn't want to put Susan into
a long-term relationship yet.
 &HT;    ``I wanted her to be able to discover who she really is without
a man in her life. Susan is still stumbling through life and trying
to find herself in this world.''
 &HT;    Shields pauses to re-gain control of the interview, which
appears to have strayed a little close to home.
 &HT;    `` A lot of my friends seem to think I'm very much like Susan.
And it's usually after I've just run into a wall or something.
We're both klutzy, but she's less jaded than I am,'' Shields says.
 &HT;    ``And when I say that I mean I feel like I've been around longer
and I think I've seen more. And she's so much more willing at the
beginning of every situation to implicitly trust people.
 &HT;    ``And I think that over the years, although I want to stay as
open as she has, I have to work at it a little bit harder,'' she
adds.
 &HT;    When asked point-blank about her relationship with Agassi, she
says softly:
 &HT;    ``We're best friends _ we always will be. You can't spend so
much time with someone and then just walk away.''
 &HT;    Ironic, considering that it was Agassi who decided to end their
marriage. In court papers, the tennis star insisted there was ``no
possibility of reconciliation,'' adding that the two no longer had
anything in common.
 &HT;    In the past, Shields has admitted that the pressures of her
television career, coupled with Agassi's struggle to regain his
youthful power on the court, had brought too much pressure to bear
on their marriage.
 &HT;    In addition, Shields' influential mother had made no bones about
her distaste for Agassi, whose sun-baked tennis court manner and
taste for Las Vegas casinos seemed worlds removed from Shields'
well-pressed Ivy-League background.
 &HT;    ``I was putting in 12 to 14-hour days on a sound stage in
Hollywood, while Andre was trying to put his tennis game back
together again. It was not a good prescription for a happy
marriage,'' Shields told a co-worker while in the throes of her
break-up with the tennis ace.
 &HT;    But this June, following a series of professional setbacks,
Agassi bounced back to win the French Open and subsequently made it
through to the Wimbledon finals, losing to Pete Sampras but
emerging as the world's number-one seeded tennis player.
 &HT;    And Shields flew to London to be near him.
 &HT;    ``I guess you could say it was to console him,'' Shields
explains. ``I feel we are still so close that he needed someone to
be there for him. It's sometimes quite emotional, and I do love to
watch him play.
 &HT;    ``Obviously I can't be at every tournament. I want my career and
he wants his,'' she adds.
 &HT;    While Shields swears she no longer wants to be a ``tennis
groupie,'' she notes that many of her best friends have begun to
raise families, and she wants children.
 &HT;    The day after her interview, Shields is up in the UCLA stands,
watching her ex-husband compete in yet another tournament.
Reconciliation is in the air.
 &HT;    Says one close friend of the couple, well aware of their renewed
relationship: ``Andre can't live without her, and she can't live
without him. It's a strange combination.
 &HT;    ``But I wouldn't bet against them trying to make a go of it
again.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Suddenly Susan,'' consult the
NBC Website at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on Hollywood Stars and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
