<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8429 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TREK-KATE-MULGREW-IN-     09-02 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-KATE-MULGREW-IN-VOYAGER-ART-ADV13-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV13 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI 
 KATE MULGREW WARPS INTO ``VOYAGER'S'' SIXTH SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., SEPT. 13, 1999) 
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of actress Kate
Mulgrew in ``Voyager.'')
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Kate Mulgrew is psyched.
 &HT;    ``I'd say the tone of `Voyager' is much freer, much more
personal and much more dangerous as we get into season six,'' says
Mulgrew, who once again assumes the captain's chair as Kathryn
Janeway when ``Voyager'' returns to the airwaves on September 22.
 &HT;    ``There's also no question that we're going after a
broader-based audience now. We'd love to find more viewers, both
those who watched `Deep Space Nine' and anyone else who's willing
to see what we're doing.''
 &HT;    What they're doing is making space safe from deadly aliens, and
making Wednesday nights sacred for born-again trekkies.
 &HT;    ``When I say `Voyager' is more personal, that's precisely what
they've done. They're approaching the show from the inside out,''
Mulgrew say.
 &HT;    ``Anybody who tunes in will think, `Oh, that's interesting. What
is that woman B'Elanna (Roxann Dawson) doing that for?' It's no
longer just about the ship, the constraints of the ship and our
circumstances.''
 &HT;    Mulgrew, speaking by telephone from her home in Los Angeles on a
day off, pauses only long enough to breathe in some air before
continuing.
 &HT;    ``Our first episodes of the season have not only been more
personal, but they've been extravagant, more so than ever before.
And I mean that on every level,'' Mulgrew says.
 &HT;    ``We've worked longer and harder hours, and we've probably spent
much more money per episode. Everyone is, in a sense, bending over
backwards to extend themselves to this larger audience by getting
across, as best we can, these pretty interesting stories.''
 &HT;    Season six kicks off with ``Equinox, Part II,'' which resolves
the fifth-season cliffhanger.
 &HT;    Matters looked rather bleak for Capt. Janeway and her crew when
last seen, as aliens closed in and Capt. Ransom (John Savage) of
the U.S.S. Equinox seemed ready to sacrifice everybody on Voyager
in order to get himself and his crew back home.
 &HT;    What happens in ``Equinox, Part II''?
 &HT;    ``I don't die, I can tell you that,'' Mulgrew says, laughing.
``It looks like there's a lot of me with (actor) John Savage, but
that's editing, because it's mostly me on the bridge acting against
a lot of things that weren't there and being extremely technically
proficient.
 &HT;    ``In terms of the story, it's Janeway assuring Ransom and his
people that I'd go down with the ship rather than let him take
over. In the end, of course, he doesn't, but why he doesn't is
interesting.
 &HT;    ``It's the kind of twist that's typical of the first six
episodes you'll see this season.''
 &HT;    Another intriguing development on tap: Janeway should finally
beam some romance into her hectic life.
 &HT;    ``It'll be a very big romance, very powerful and
heartbreaking,'' she says. ``I want it long-lasting. I want it so
unpredictable that it throws Janeway for the biggest loop you've
ever seen her thrown for.''
 &HT;    Speaking of romance, Mulgrew recently wed Cleveland-based
politician Tim Hagan. They met in Ireland just before Mulgrew
landed ``Voyager,'' but the timing didn't work out.
 &HT;    Mulgrew went on to a relationship with frequent ``Trek''
director Rick Kolbe. When that ended last year, Mulgrew's mother
suggested to Hagan that he call Mulgrew. He did, they got together
and love bloomed anew.
 &HT;    The relationship, not to mention Mulgrew's guilt over missing
major events in the lives of her two sons, led the actress to very
publicly hint that she might not return to ``Voyager.''
 &HT;    Her comments sent shockwaves through ``Trek'' fandom.
 &HT;    Ultimately, the ``Trek'' producers agreed to coordinate
Mulgrew's schedule with ``extra vigilance.''
 &HT;    That meant fewer days sitting at home idly, waiting to be called
into the studio, and fewer instances of shooting a single scene on
a given day.
 &HT;    ``The acknowledgment of my need for time was crucial, and they
did acknowledge it,'' she says. ``They stepped up to the plate.''
 &HT;    Now a happy camper personally and professionally, Mulgrew is
fervent in her commitment to ``Voyager.''
 &HT;    She's deep into season six and signed for a seventh year. And
she has her eye on the future.
 &HT;    ``After `Voyager,' Kate Mulgrew lives her life,'' she says. ``I
will be immersed in my marriage and family. If I have any courage
at all I'll be quiet for a while and be reflective.
 &HT;    ``Perhaps I'll write about my seven years on `Voyager.' I may
move to Cleveland. Then, after some time has gone by, if I'm still
desirable to the theater, I'll go to New York and do a play.''
 &HT;     -0- 
 NEXT WEEK  
 &HT;    David Nutter previews ``Roswell.'' 
 -0- 
