<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8430 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-TOBACCO-DISASTER-NYTS     09-02 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-DISASTER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALK ONE UP FOR THE TOBACCO GOLIATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Health Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By STEPHEN L. COHEN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The story of the greatest public health disaster in U.S. history
is not a happy one. But it has all the ingredients of the best
Hollywood thrillers: sensational battles, ruthless power plays,
spine-tingling suspense and more than enough life-and-death
struggles to go around.
 &HT;    It all started innocently enough. The captains of the tobacco
industry probably saw little cause for alarm when the first
tentative shots were fired in their direction five years ago.
 &HT;    They'd been shot at before, after all, but their indomitable
domain had never been successfully breached, despite repeated
attacks over the years.
 &HT;    But all that was about to change. Indeed, when FDA Commissioner
David Kessler began his assault on the cigarette companies in 1994,
he set in motion a chain of events that would change the course of
the tobacco wars forever.
 &HT;    Under his leadership, the anti-smoking forces would go on to win
some major, unprecedented victories on the battlefield. They
actually defeated Big Tobacco in multiple arenas -- in the courts,
in Congress and in the battle for public opinion.
 &HT;    These victories culminated in the approval of the McCain bill
last year in the Senate Commerce Committee. The bill called for
severe penalties on the cigarette companies and was vigorously
opposed by the industry.
 &HT;    For a while, it looked as though the industry was in for a
devastating defeat, but in the final showdown on the Senate floor,
the tobacco lobby was able to prevail.
 &HT;    Following an industry-funded advertising blitz (estimated to
cost $40 million), the full Senate allowed the McCain bill to die.
With this defeat, any hope for an imminent end to the tobacco
blight died too.
 &HT;    Reeling from this unexpected setback, the anti-smoking forces
regrouped and tried to assess the damage. Recriminations filled the
air. Some blamed public health advocates like Kessler for pushing
too hard for tough legislation. Others cited the impact of the
tobacco industry's multi-million dollar ad campaign.
 &HT;    But no one could deny a pivotal reality: that any ambitious
anti-smoking legislation faced an uphill battle in the Republican
Congress. This was because any measure that expanded government
regulation or taxation, however important, would be suspect for
those reasons alone.
 &HT;    From the outset, then, the McCain bill was hampered by the fact
that the very measures needed to attack smoking -- from increased
cigarette prices to FDA regulation -- ran against the grain of
Republican thinking in the Senate.
 &HT;    For this reason, the debate shifted from the real issue -- the
health of the country -- to a debate about tax increases and Big
Government. The end result was a tragedy for the nation.
 &HT;    Since the defeat of the McCain bill, 46 states have reached an
agreement to settle claims against the tobacco industry for $206
billion. Four other states reached separate settlements for a total
of $40 billion. At this point, these settlements are the only
legacy of the failed McCain legislation.
 &HT;    So what happens now? Is there really no way to prevent the
single most preventable cause of death in the country? What are we,
a bunch of morons?
 &HT;    Hopefully not. But for more than 40 years, one could be forgiven
for coming to that conclusion. The reasons are all too clear.
Smoking kills more than 400,000 Americans a year and is responsible
for about 20 percent of all deaths in the United States. It's a
killer of staggering proportions. Yet we've allowed this wound to
fester for decades.
 &HT;    The question is, why have we done so little about one of the few
conditions that we actually know how to cure?
 &HT;    The tobacco companies have obviously had a huge impact. Since
evidence of the dangers of smoking first surfaced, the companies
have used their immense financial and political clout to fight
virtually any anti-tobacco initiative, from new cigarette taxes to
anti-smoking ordinances.
 &HT;    They've also mounted massive campaigns to refute the evidence
that smoking is hazardous to one's health, despite overwhelming
evidence to the contrary. In the final reckoning, history is
unlikely to look kindly on an industry that worked so hard to the
detriment of so many.
 &HT;    But who else shares responsibility for what is arguably the
greatest public health debacle in U.S. history? The cigarette
makers clearly didn't operate in a vacuum. So where were those
charged with protecting the public's health -- the nation's
government and medical leaders, for example -- all these years?
 &HT;    According to Kessler, officials at the Federal Trade Commission
did try to address the tobacco problem, but they were stymied by
higher authorities, including FTC commissioners and congressional
opponents.
 &HT;    Former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop also worked to foster
anti-smoking activism during his term in the Reagan administration.
 &HT;    But Kessler acknowledges that his own agency, the FDA, never
focused a great deal of attention on tobacco prior to his arrival,
and that government research on subjects like nicotine addiction
(involving self-administration of nicotine) was about five years
behind industry research.
 &HT;    Members of the medical establishment played a role in
maintaining the status quo regarding smoking as well. In the
academic community, researchers accepted grants from the Committee
for Tobacco Research, an industry-funded group, to do studies on
tobacco. By engaging in industry-supported research, these
scientists provided cigarette makers with added credibility at a
time when the industry was vigorously disputing the evidence that
smoking was dangerous.
 &HT;    Organized medicine played a role, too. Kessler cites a 1964
British report on smoking and health that found that the American
Medical Association appeared ``more concerned with safeguarding the
financial interests of doctors through political lobbying than with
the doctors' patients.''
 &HT;    From his own study of the issue, Kessler concludes that
organized medicine in the '60s seemed more interested in courting
its relationships with tobacco state congressmen (to fight the
passage of Medicare) than in fighting smoking.
 &HT;    Of course, there were also dedicated anti-smoking advocates
through the years who pushed for measures like warning labels on
cigarette packages and the elimination of tobacco ads on
television. But for decades, no one was able to mobilize the
anti-smoking forces into a coalition that could effectively take on
the tobacco lobby.
 &HT;    As a result, the most lethal, preventable malady of the modern
age was allowed to kill millions of Americans with little effective
resistance from the government or the medical establishment.
 &HT;    In contrast, over the same period, enormous energy and resources
were expended to fight a war against poorly understood diseases
like cancer. While this effort was obviously very important, it
leads to an inevitable question: If a similarly aggressive war had
been declared on smoking, a killer whose cure is much more
straightforward (medically, if not politically), how many more
lives might have been saved?
 &HT;    In the final analysis, shouldn't conquering the tobacco lobby
have been easier than conquering cancer? And if so, have we missed
a grand opportunity?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.1999 Stephen L. Cohen
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Stephen L. Cohen, M.D., is a medical journalist based in New
York.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
