 Thursday, Sept. 2, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BEANIES (Undated) _ Is it time to say goodbye to Butch the Bull
Terrier, Cheeks the Baboon, and Beak the Ty-dye Kiwi Bird? It could
be, according to a cryptic announcement by stuffed toy make Ty Inc.
of Oak Brook, Ill. Some collectors viewed the announcement with
skepticism. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MILLIONAIRE (Undated) _ ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' was
a summer smash, an intelligent, compelling game show imported from
England that produced monster ratings. It also had some weird
demographics. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-TRADING (San Francisco) _ Online trading is creating a
monetary boon for Internet brokerage firms, which are rewarding
their new customers with shabby treatment, according to a new study
released by Jupiter Communications, a New York-based Internet
market research firm. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-APPLE (San Francisco) _ Apple Computer Inc.'s new Power
Mac G4 ``supercomputer'' may not be that super after all. And Steve
Jobs' use of that term to describe his company's newest desktop
computer is making some waves in the industry. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SCHOOLS (Albany, N.Y.) _ NY Wired, an Internet venture,
is trying to create a market of school children, parents and
teachers who will visit the new, education-oriented Web site. The
site will collect and disseminate lesson plans, homework help and
other services for free. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SEASONING (Albany, N.Y.) _ Seasoning is everything. With little
effort it can take a dish from ho-hum to holy cow. It's just a
matter of knowing which seasonings work with which foods. That
takes practice and experience. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-SQUASH (Albany, N.Y.) _ It used to be in summer you ate
zucchini, yellow crookneck squash and the UFO-shaped pattypan
squash. In winter, you ate acorn squash and butternut squash. In
the fall you ate potatoes and in the spring you ate asparagus, you
didn't eat squash. These days, you'll find summer squash available
all year, and that just widens your choices of dishes to serve. By
RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   STORING-SQUASH (Albany, N.Y.) _ Practices for buying and storing
squash vary depending on which season of vegetables you are dealing
with. Here are some tips on how to store the versatile vegetable.
By The Albany Times Union.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ About managed health care, I
have a dream. An ugly dream. Of the day all hell breaks loose. It
starts right after lunch on a seemingly normal afternoon. The point
of spontaneous combustion is between my HMO and all my ``health
care providers.'' (What ever was wrong with ``doctor'' and
``nurse''?) By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-ADVOCATE (San Francisco) _ If you are even thinking
about getting sick, don't! Due to the demands and limits set up
mainly by HMOs, medical care has become sort of the Russian
Roulette of client services. If you happen to push the right
button, you get care. If not, you wait, you wait, you wait and you
wait. Just getting in to see your primary care physician (a.k.a.
doctor) is difficult. And if you need to see a specialist, don't
think you can just make an appointment. By RUTH SHERMAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
