<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8443 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES0     09-02 0244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: The Yogi Berra principle
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The care and custody of freedom of speech seems to depend these
days on whose freedom you're talking about. Mine is inviolable.
Yours is probationary.
</P>
<P>
   Recent surveys show people like freedom of speech very well _
for themselves. Multi-media moguls, newspaper publishers and movie
producers get meager public support. The Internet is a special
category. There, people are themselves the publishers. Internet
buffs are terrified of censorship.
</P>
<P>
   New York City is the latest _ no surprise _ battleground. A
federal judge has ruled that the city can't ban a rally because of
the sure prospect of hate speech. Even hate speech, the judge said,
gets First Amendment protection. The judge is wrong. Hate speech is
just about the only speech needing protection. Something is always
hateful to someone.
</P>
<P>
   A calendar over my desk quotes President Woodrow Wilson: ``The
wisest thing to do with a fool is to encourage him to hire a hall
and discourse to his fellow citizens. Nothing chills nonsense like
exposure to the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The same calendar also quotes Yogi Berra: ``You can observe a
lot by watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Thought I'd throw that in.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN03-COX     09-02 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some books worth reading during dog days
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Summer is nearly gone, and none too soon
for those of us who live behind the Pine Curtain, where the
temperature and humidity each vie for hitting the century mark in a
hellish monotony that can't leave soon enough to suit all but the
most thin-blooded residents.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much to do about the weather except whine about it.
Best to find a cool spot _ either in the air conditioning or
outside as the sun finally sets and the ceiling fan provides enough
of a breeze to make it tolerable _ and settle down with a good
book. Here are a few that helped me get through the dog days of
August:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Children'' by David Halberstam (Random House, 783 pp.,
$29.95). This is not a book one can comfortably read while lounging
on the beach. It's too danged heavy, for one thing. But Halberstam,
one of our best popular historians, does a masterful job of
recounting the sit-ins of the 1960s that energized the nascent
civil rights movement. At the time, Halberstam worked for The
Nashville Tennessean, one of the rare Southern newspapers that
spoke out against segregation and Jim Crow laws.
</P>
<P>
   What struck me about these young men and women was their courage
in the face of unspeakable brutality. They endured beatings,
arrests and innumerable dignities to ultimately win the right to
eat at the same lunch counters as whites at stores that were more
than happy to take their money while shopping, to vote, and to be
paid comparable wages for comparable work.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam manages to capture the spirit of those heady times
and to tell readers what happened to these ``children,'' as he
calls these teen-agers who adopted the nonviolent credo of Mahatma
Ghandi to change our society. I found ``The Children'' nearly
impossible to put down.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Blue Light'' by Walter Mosely. (Little, Brown &AMP; Co., 296
pp., $24). Mosely made a name for himself with his Easy Rawlins
series, featuring a black man in the 1950s who, though not a
detective per se, finds himself solving crimes. The Rawlins series
captures Los Angeles and Texas during the Eisenhower era. A few of
his books _ ``Devil in a Blue Dress'' _ for example, have been made
into films.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mosely has tried his hand at science fiction in a radical
departure. Those of us who love the Rawlins series might find
themselves a bit disconcerted at ``Blue Light,'' which is a booger
book of sorts, to steal a term a fellow book reviewer uses to
describe books that make him nervous. Like books by Stephen King or
Dean Koontz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Light'' is tough to read but ultimately worth the effort,
though I had my doubts for a while. Still and all, I'm looking
forward to the next Easy Rawlins adventure.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Billy Straight'' by Jonathan Kellerman. (Random House, 467
pp. $25.95). One of my great delights is discovering an author who
has cranked out a bevy of books, none of which I've read. Such is
the case with Kellerman, who I've heard of but never read until
trying ``Billy Straight.'' This is one to take to the beach, though
you risk getting a sunburn while turning pages, since it's hard to
put down. The two main characters are the 12-year-old namesake of
the title, a winsome runaway who witnessed a woman being stabbed to
death. The murder is being investigated by Petra Connor, a tough
L.A. homicide detective whose heart goes out to young Billy. Chief
suspects are the TV actor ex-husband, his misogynist manager, and a
few other characters thrown in for good measure. Kellerman in the
jacket blurbs is called a master of the psychological thriller.
Certainly he's of a rank with Austin writer David Lindsey. I'm
looking forward to hitting the library soon to check out earlier
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, here's a delightfully trashy paperback: ``Breach of
Promise'' by Perri O'Shaughnessy, a non de plume used by two
sisters. The main character is a female attorney/single mother
named Nina Reilley who lives in glitzy Lake Tahoe. If you're stuck
in an airport and hope to drown out the incessant loudspeaker
announcing flights and messages, you could do worse than ``Breach
of Promise.'' The plot centers around a palimony case with Ms.
Reilley representing a woman who, it turns out, isn't legally
married. When her ``husband'' takes up with the secretary, she's
tossed out of the multi-million dollar spa business that she had a
key part in building.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's better than it sounds, especially if you've ever spent
any time in Tahoe, which is a beautiful place even if
over-populated by people with more money than sense. No Pulitzer
Prizes for fiction here, but it's not a bad way to while away the
time while in an airport terminal, which is exactly what I did.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy, and be patient. Cooler weather will come, eventually. You
have to believe that.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
