<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release FridaY, September 3, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ During the course of a
week, I get a lot of advice. Some of it is very good, some of it is
horrible and most of it falls somewhere in between. Here's an
e-mail submission I received that offers up some good advice from a
Texas point of view. And keep in mind that no self-respectin' Texan
pronounces the ``g'' in ``ing-endin''' words. (Ernest Murray is
managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News) EMBARGOED for Sunday.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ The care and custody of freedom of speech
seems to depend these days on whose freedom you're talking about.
Mine is inviolable. Yours is probationary. (Rosenfeld, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ There's not much to do about the weather except
whine about it. Best to find a cool spot _ either in the air
conditioning or outside and settle down with a good book. Here are
a few that helped me get through the dog days of August. (Gary
Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.)
EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ A nice lady phoned
the other day, concerned about the fate of the Lost in the '50s
Roadhouse, which is threatened by the new interstate. A fellow I
know just up the highway, whose home is so close to the bridge that
he figures to lose his property regardless of which way things go,
has been keeping in touch with the highway department as close as
most anybody. And he says without a doubt the roadhouse will
survive. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ WACO, Texas _ Recently the high
schooler in our house, who wants to write music, went into a
creative sensory-purge mode. He pushed every musical instrument he
owned out the front door _ guitars, amp, stereo, keyboard. It's OK.
They're with family. (John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WOOTEN-COLUMN _ The most mystifying story extant in the Dog Days
of summer _ that Texas Gov. George W. Bush used cocaine _ is
without source or substance. So far as anybody can tell, its origin
is the rumor mill and its engine is political opponents goading
news-starved reporters to report the rumors. And now this
bewildering episode is carried to new levels. Democratic activist
Jesse Jackson has a policy proposal. The widely reported rumor
presents an opportunity for the nation to change its ``extreme''
anti-drug policies. (Wooten, Atlanta Journal)
</P>
