<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the
current week.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0831 -- I'm standing atop Half Dome, a sheer
granite cliff soaring impressively above this awesome park. I can
think of nothing but throwing up. My brother convinced me I could
stop along the way and read if I got tired. It was an empty
promise. It's the type of lie in which both parties consent, for
motivational purposes. (Bierman, Palm Beach Post) Art includes
3-column color photo hikers proceeding through the woods with a
llama. Includes 4-column color photo of hikers overlooking Half
Dome in Yosemite National Park and one color headline illustration
with six color mountains.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: YOSEMITE BOX -- Tips for if you go hiking in Yosemite
National Park (Bierman, Palm Beach Post) Art includes 1-column B&AMP;W
map graphic of the park and a 1-column color photo of hikers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DESTINATIONS -- The legendary British Colonial Hotel,
built by Henry Flagler in 1899 and later rebuilt after a fire, is
reopening in September after massive renovations. (Blackerby, Palm
Beach Post) Art includes 2-column color photo of The British
Colonial Hotel)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- Amtrak plans to put a
customer-satisfaction guarantee into effect by the end of the year.
Passengers dissatisfied with the service, food or other aspects of
their trip will be able to get a voucher with a value equal to the
trip's cost. (N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   END OF COXNET PAGE
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRAZIL _ Part II of Wendell Brock's travel series on
Brazil focuses on Ouro Preto. The gold mining town in a storybook
mountain setting is a U.N. world heritage site, with one of the
world's richest deposits of gold-encrusted Baroque architecture.
The region of Minas Gerais also has a vibrant, African-inflected
culinary tradition that parallels that of the American South, with
collards, corn meal and pork in wild abundance. A colorful scene
piece with nice photographs and a complete guide to the markets,
shops, restaurants and hotels. (Brock, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ROCKWELL _ In his famous song, ``Alice's Restaurant,''
Arlo Guthrie immortalized a hole-in-the wall restaurant in
Stockbridge, Mass. But the refrain applies to all of the
Berkshires. You can get anything you want here, from avant-garde
art museums to antique silver, all in the idyllic surroundings of
manicured, small-town New England towns set like gems in a ring of
verdant hills. (Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-CENTERPIECE
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-JACKETS _ Jackets are long on style these days. Lengths
extend past the knee or down to the ankle, providing a more
dramatic andrefined, feminine look than the traditional blazer.
(Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for
the current week.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0904: HIGH FLYIN' CHICKS _ The Dixie Chicks
have plenty of reasons to cluck. The perky country music trio is
hotter than a sparkler _ media darlings du jour. They are
everywhere, from the pages of Seventeen magazine to giggling sound
bites on ``Entertainment Tonight.'' Move over, Garth Brooks.
(Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes one 5-column
color photo of the group in concert)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DIXIE CHICKS BOX _ A look at the history and hits of the
Dixie Chicks.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STAR FILE _ Meshell Ndegeocello is hoping the title of her
naw CD, ``Bitter,'' doesn't convey anything other than optimism
about her musical future. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
Art includes 1-column color photo of singer Meshell Ndegeocello.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS _ ``Party Monster,'' which first made waves
at the Sundance Film Festival, traces with a coolly intimate
descent of a drug-happy teen from gory ironist to gory killer.
Also, reviews of ``Dracula,'' ``The Celebration'' and ``La
Separation'' (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS _ If you bought February's ``Trio II,'' the
superb CD that paired Linda Ronstadt and Emmylou Harris with Dolly
Parton, keep this in mind: ``Western Wall'' isn't an encore
performance. The songs here are much more experimental and
introspective, sparsely produced and virtually country-free. Also,
new releases from Richard Thompson and the compilation
``Violator.'' (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes
18-pica color photo of Linda Ronstadt and Emmylou Harris.
</P>
<P>
   MARLON _ ATLANTA _ Is there life after the Jackson 5? Michael's
older, less flamboyant brother Marlon thinks so. He's putting his
money and show business experience behind the Major Broadcasting
Company, an Atlanta-based cable television network. Working with
investors and fellow celebrities such as Evander Holyfield and
Cecil Fielder, Jackson hopes to offer family-oriented programming
with religious and secular themes. Although the upstart network is
only available to satellite customers in Atlanta, MBC is in
negotiations to be picked up by local cable providers. We spoke
with Marlon about his new business venture, his family, and a
possible J5 reunion. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Michael Skube on Eugene Robinson's race book,
``Coal to Cream.'' (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Don O'Briant's book notes. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NONFICTION _ A roundup of what's new in nonfiction,
including ``Kosovo Crossing'' by David Fromkin, ``Learning the
Ropes: An Apprentice on the Last of the Windjammers'' by Eric
Newby, ``Disco Bloodbath'' by James St. James, ``The World of
Words: An Illustrated History of Western Languages'' by Victor
Stevenson, ``Remembering Muscle Beach'' by Harold Zinkin.
(Harrison, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-CHAPPELL _ Review of Fred Chappell's novel, ``Look Back All
the Green Valley.'' (Drennen, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MCCULLERS _ Review of Carson McCullers' autobiography
``Illumination and Night Glare.'' (Weaver, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of a recently released book.
(Milner, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the
current week.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0831 -- ``Wars and Peace: The Memoir of an American
Family'' is author Rory Quirk's story, his parent's story and, on
still another level, the story of a generation that sacrificed
without complaint. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes 3-column B&AMP;W photo from book and a 6-pica color photo of
book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AMERICAN CULTURE -- Michael Kammen is one of the
better-known historians practicing these days. His new book is an
extended commentary on the fate of culture in a modern democracy.
(Bernstein, N.Y. Times News Service) Art includes a 6-pica color
photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MONTY PYTHON -- ``Monty Python Speaks!'' is an oral
history of the group that encompasses all five survivors. As the
story emerges from a collage of reminiscence, Monty Python was a
true collaboration of six different kinds of people, united only in
their quest to delineate the suppressed rage and madness that exist
beneath all that unflappable English calm. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
Art includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket and a 2-column B&AMP;W
photo of the comedy troupe.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WILLIAMS BIO -- Actress and swimmer Esther Williams shares
colorful stories she's collected during her 45-year career, some
harrowing, some heartbreaking, some humorous. (Janich, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 6-pica color photo of book
jacket and a 1-column color photo of author.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   FILM
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-GIBSON _ A scene piece/report on movie actor Mel Gibson
arriving on the set of ``The Patriot,'' a Revolutionary War movie,
in South Carolina, where they will film some scenes. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-BROOKS _ Interview with Albert Brooks, who wrote and
directed ``The Muse.'' (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
