<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8452 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX     09-02 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aquarian teens share wheels, walls, peanut butter and whatnot
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Recently the high schooler in our house, who wants
to write music, went into a creative sensory-purge mode. He pushed
every musical instrument he owned out the front door _ guitars,
amp, stereo, keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   It's OK. They're with family.
</P>
<P>
   Those who will keep the instruments until his muse summons a
return are members of the Couch-Peace Commune.
</P>
<P>
   The Couch-Peace Commune is a mobile, docile community of
16-year-olds. They have expanded on the concept of the nuclear
family. Each of their families remains nuclear, but their homes _
our homes _ serve as communal pads. In the process the attached
families become extended kin.
</P>
<P>
   Couch-Peace Commune has no walls except those of cells that
serve such purposes as homework and sleep. Otherwise, when as a
family, Couch-Peace moves as a group. In cell terms, the commune is
a protoplasm the size of a midsize Texas town.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, members are mobile. But true to their name, they also have
inert stages. The Couch-Peace group will spend long hours on any
given couch, coexisting in peace. Sometimes they will sit in a row.
Sometimes they will be draped over each other. Occasionally one
member will be positioned with feet slung over the back of the
couch, head toward the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Other times they will be spread along the floor like just-fed
lions, yawning.
</P>
<P>
   The feeding of the Couch-Peacers is a zoological marvel.
</P>
<P>
   They are comfortable with any refrigerator in any house in the
commune. No cupboard is alien to them. They operate under the
proven principle that anything that comes from someone else's home
tastes better _ be it white bread, stale peanut butter, month-old
frankfurters _ anything.
</P>
<P>
   Within a biome, they serve a certain ecosystem function, which
is to never let anything stay in the fridge too long.
</P>
<P>
   The Couch-Peace Commune came into being this summer with freedom
and newfound driving privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The friends had spent a lot of time together before. Now, being
auto-mobile, they became a commune, not in a '60s, back-to-the-farm
sense, but in a '90s, ``We'll be over at (fill-in-a-blank)'s
house'' sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you going?'' we ask the commune.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Jeff's for a while, and Suncy's, and Keith's.''
</P>
<P>
   As a commune, they are a physics quandary: always in motion, yet
going nowhere in particular; always somewhere, just no place in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   The new school year has altered this pattern, at least during
weekdays, but not completely.
</P>
<P>
   Because as juniors they have open-campus lunch opportunities,
they have experimented with communal dining rather than whatever
experiment the cafeteria is serving.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you have for lunch today?'' I ask my son.
</P>
<P>
   (Day 1) ``Peanut butter and jelly at Natalie's.''
</P>
<P>
   (Day 2) ``Taco Bell at Jenny's.''
</P>
<P>
   (Day 3) ``Cold pizza and grapes at Kevin's.''
</P>
<P>
   (Day 4) ``Peanut butter and jelly and milk and crackers at
Keith's.''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, not all of these names I associate with Couch-Peace,
but hey, it's a mobile society.
</P>
<P>
   He describes these meals with relish. It's the old Seinfeld
thing. Dining is not just food, it's convening.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other types of sharing generally associated with '60s
commune life, we exert '50s controls. Regardless of where they're
communing, members of Couch-Peace return to their cells at or
before a designated hour.
</P>
<P>
   As for the musical instruments expelled from our home, an
acoustic guitar returned the other night signalling the beginning
of the end of the creative purge. An electric, an amp, a stereo and
a keyboard are still out somewhere. I trust they will be kept in
the family.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
