<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-PIERCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLY PIERCE NO LONGER GREEN WITH ENVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The village of Fanore sits on the west coast of Ireland. Most
people outside County Clare have never heard of this rural outpost
in the Burren. Farmland criss-crossed by stone walls, a one-room
schoolhouse, and a general store that doubles as the post office
fill the town. The bus to the big city leaves only on Tuesdays and
Thursdays, making several stops before it reaches Galway 40 miles
to the north.
</P>
<P>
   It's an unlikely place to start fulfilling big-time dreams.
</P>
<P>
   But American Holly Pierce found her way from Fanore to the
Football Association of Ireland (FAI). Saturday, the 23-year-old
soccer player and her Irish teammates will face the US women's
national team at Foxboro Stadium. Pierce will start at center
midfield while family and friends from Oregon cheer from the
stands. She will compete against former teammates from college and
US developmental programs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pierce planned to compete for the red, white, and blue,
she realized the talent pool at home was too large and the timing
not good enough to give her a chance with the reigning world
champions. The former University of Portland standout knew that
once her college career ended, her soccer opportunities were
limited. If she did not make the national team before graduation,
there would be nowhere to play and gain the notice of US coach Tony
DiCicco and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   So Pierce became one of a growing number of talented US women to
export her soccer talent. Having an Irish mother allowed the
midfielder to obtain dual citizenship. An unsolicited e-mail caught
the eye of Irish team administrator Sean Brodie, and a May tryout
followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing it for a lot of reasons,'' said Pierce. ``Without a
professional league in the US, you can't play anywhere if you're
out of college unless you're on the national team. I wanted to play
at a high level. That's the way I enjoy playing. Also, I love
Ireland. I thought I would try it and see how the experience was.
The players and the team are great. I love to play soccer, and so
far this is a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to joining the Irish team, Pierce traveled through Europe,
making stops to play professionally in Russia and Germany. She did
not stay long in either country, citing cultural and contractual
differences as her reasons for leaving teams. The midfielder left
soccer behind and continued touring.
</P>
<P>
   When she reached Paris, Pierce decided to visit Ireland for the
first time. In January, she arrived in Fanore with a job that
combined work in the Burren and waitressing at the village's only
restaurant. Though she hadn't played soccer in months, Pierce was
still looking for opportunities to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Once Pierce accessed the Internet on a computer at a nearby bed
and breakfast, she sent a message to the FAI. It's not uncommon for
the FAI to receive e-mails from perspective female players, but
most of the requests for tryouts come from young women of Irish
parentage living in England. The message from Pierce was much
different.
</P>
<P>
   The American listed her college credentials, which included
earning all-league honors all four years at Portland and seeing
plenty of NCAA tournament action. At Tigard High School, playing
for her mother, Kit, Pierce led the Tigers to three consecutive
Oregon 4A state championships and was named one of the country's
``Super 11 Recruits.'' The clincher, however, was the two years
Pierce spent on the US under-20 national team. The Irish team
organizers understood they had happened upon a rare talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that immediately attracted me was that she had made
the US national under-20 team. You don't go much further than that
in terms of a reference,'' said Brodie. ``Her credentials were
perfect. I spoke to the manager and told him we had this e-mail,
and we brought her up for a trial. She probably could have arrived
in Dublin faster from New York than from where she was in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``For players of her caliber, soccer is a passport. It's brought
her all around Europe and brought her to Ireland and now brought
her to the Irish international team. Players of her caliber will
seek out top-level football where possible. It's not really a
question of advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   With soccer as her ticket to European travel and the Irish team,
Pierce needed to make several cultural adjustments. Women's soccer
in Ireland runs much differently than it does in the United States.
Listening to Irish music from the Chieftains and watching
Irish-themed films did not prepare Pierce for the way her new team
and country would approach the game she'd played since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The differences in philosophy and financial resources between
the two countries are great. The Irish women's program does not
have the funds or the youth programs to compete with the US. In
addition to Pierce's experience on the US under-20 team, Brodie and
manager Mick Cooke liked the fact she was based in Ireland.
Otherwise, they could not have afforded to fly her over from the US
for a tryout.
</P>
<P>
   Costs also keep the team from holding long training camps, and
most players train on their own all over the globe. Pierce
currently works out with a boys' high school team in her hometown
of Tigard and will join her Irish teammates Thursday in Boston,
where they will reunite for the first time in a couple of months.
The Irish will have only two practices together _ one at Babson
College and one at Foxboro Stadium _ before facing the World Cup
champions.
</P>
<P>
   After playing two games for Ireland and then returning to
Oregon, Pierce does not know her new team well. However, the coach
has already seen the midfielder's play bring out the best in her
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's certainly a welcome member of the squad and has settled
in very quickly and is very much liked by everybody,'' said Cooke.
``She adds experience and brings a stability into midfield. She's
very comfortable on the ball, doesn't waste anything, and is
extremely fit. She actually brings out confidence in the other
players around her by her style of play.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the main objective of the Irish women's national
program is to increase the number of female soccer players across
the country. They are hoping to more than double the number of
participants in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The player base isn't sufficient,'' said Brodie. ``Even when
it comes to national selection, no matter how many players would
show up for a trial, realistically there's only about 25 players
pushing for the 18 spots. Now you compare that with the States, who
have (7 1/2 million) registered players. If somebody isn't
performing, they just make a phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce added that women's sports rarely get the same respect as
men's sports in Ireland. The American-raised player said that
expectations for female athletes are not as high in Ireland. Games
played by the women's national team get poor publicity. Fans seldom
pay to watch matches featuring the women's national team. More than
likely, the visitors will experience culture shock Saturday with
close to 30,000 expected at Foxborough for the doubleheader that
includes the Revolution's game against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know when I'll be able to play the US team again,''
said Pierce, equally excited and anxious about the opportunity. ``I
think the most I've played in front of is 4,000 or 5,000. It's
pretty surreal. I can't even comprehend it. The only thing I'm
thinking about is the game and how I can prepare myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true Irish soccer player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
