<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO RED SOX 101 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The streets around Fenway, always unnavigable, are a
study in still life, anger, and frustration. Parents and boyfriends
attempt to carry mattresses up four flights of stairs, and you
can't find an available U-Haul or telephone guy inside Route 128.
</P>
<P>
   Good morning, Boston. It's the beginning of September, the
weather is easy, the living is hard, the students are back, and the
Red Sox are in a (wild-card) pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox Wednesday won their sixth straight, helping them remain
two games ahead of Oakland in the playoff chase. A new class of
incoming freshmen (many from outside New England) gets to
experience Boston in the fall when the Red Sox contend. There is
nothing like it. Fenway Park should be in the
BC-BU-MIT-Harvard-Simmons-Emmanuel-Wheelock-Northeastern-Emerson
brochures. The Class of 2003 is a lucky lot.
</P>
<P>
   As a service to those who may not yet have enjoyed the Boston
baseball experience, we present a Fenway Freshman Orientation to
you new kids on the Kenmore block. Clip and save:
</P>
<P>
   --The Red Sox' new closer has never played in a band with
Stephen Stills or Graham Nash. He only looks like David Crosby. His
name is Rod Beck, an ex-Cubbie.
</P>
<P>
   --Pay no attention to hysteria about the final days of Fenway
Park. Fenway will still be standing when you graduate _ even if
you're in school for a Blutoesque seven years. The Sox have plans
for a new park, but it won't get done until sometime between the
end of the Big Dig and the beginning of the 22d century.
</P>
<P>
   --Buy peanuts outside the park.
</P>
<P>
   --There is no such thing as a Fenway sellout until (if) the Sox
make it to the playoffs. You can always get in the park via
bleachers or standing room. Warning: Do not buy tickets in any
section numbered 1-7. Better you should go for the bleachers or
standing room.
</P>
<P>
   --Red Sox manager Jimy Williams is not putting you on. He always
talks like that. And he's no dummie. Jimy can do the Times
crossword puzzle faster than you. The one ``m'' in ``Jimy'' is no
typo. Don't ask. He just likes it that way, OK?
</P>
<P>
   --Nomar Garciaparra is the Sox' everyday star. Chicks dig him
and no one touches his stuff. Watch how he puts both feet on each
step every time he goes up and down the dugout stairs. Nomar makes
Dustin Hoffman's Rain Man look like a spontaneous guy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pedro Martinez is the star pitcher. Many strikeouts. Few
walks. The Globe offers a handy-dandy Spanish story whenPedro
pitches at home (not Ramon, not yet). Also, do not break into
Pedro's house or he will shoot you.
</P>
<P>
   --No beer sales 2 1/2 hours after the start of the game.
</P>
<P>
   --The guy bolting on and off the field between innings is third
base coach Wendell ``Send-'Em-In'' Kim. Mike Barnicle in 1986 said
that if former third base coach Rene Lachemann worked as an air
traffic controller, there would be fuselages all over Boston
Harbor. Wendell's had that kind of year.
</P>
<P>
   --Tourists call it ``The Green Monster.'' Locals know it as
``The Wall.'' The ladder on The Wall is in play.
</P>
<P>
   --Please, no beachballs and no wave. And no leaving early to
beat the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   --When Brian Daubach is announced, stand up and say, ``Who needs
Mo? This guy gives you more for $80 million less.'' If a Sox
official hears you, he might give you tickets to an upcoming game.
</P>
<P>
   --First base and right field get the most sun during day games.
And the bleachers, of course.
</P>
<P>
   --Do not mock the organ music. Not even ``Copacabana.''
</P>
<P>
   --Unless you can eat glass and swallow barbells, wear no New
York team garb to Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   --Fenway can be a Love Boat. More than a few married couples met
at Fenway or had their first date there.
</P>
<P>
   --If you're on a Riverside train, get off at Kenmore, which is
actually closer than the Fenway Park stop.
</P>
<P>
   --Troy O'Leary is not Irish.
</P>
<P>
   --All this talk about 1918 has nothing to do with the first
World War or the post-Russian revolution.
</P>
<P>
   --It would take too long to explain, but avoid fighting words to
avoid fights. Fighting words include: Buckner, Dent, McNamara,
Schiraldi, Willoughby, Galehouse, Nanette, Frazee, Curse, and
Bambino.
</P>
<P>
   --Deposit all loose change in the Jimmy Fund boxes.
</P>
<P>
   --Pay homage to the Citgo sign. It will help you find home more
than once during the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
