<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8503 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     09-02 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX VALUE INVESTOR: DAN DUQUETTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Dan Duquette ever decides to switch careers, he could always
find a home on Wall Street. Whether he knows it or not, the Red Sox
general manager is a superb value investor.
</P>
<P>
   Value investors are bargain hunters. They buy stocks that are
out of favor, stocks whose price has been beaten down because the
company has reported disappointing earnings or because the economy
is in a slump. They buy on the expectation or the hope that their
investments have potential that the rest of the world doesn't
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine investing in Boston real estate in 1991 or in the stock
of bankrupt Filene's Basement today and you have some idea of the
kind of gambles value players routinely make.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes real fortitude and skill to be a value investor
because you have to buy when the news is bad,'' says Ned Riley,
chief investment officer at BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Like when a pitcher is coming off shoulder surgery; or when a
player has toiled in the minor leagues for years and has been
written off by the rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like anyone you know, Red Sox fans?
</P>
<P>
   Duquette's decision to replace Mo Vaughn with Brian Daubach at
first base this season could earn the general manager a spot in the
value hall of fame. Think about it: Vaughn, now a member of the
Anaheim Angels, earns about $13 million a year. Daubach, a
perennial minor leaguer, will get $215,000. Yet as of the moment,
Daubach and Vaughn have roughly an equal number of home runs and
RBIs _ and Daubach has a much higher average.
</P>
<P>
   If Daubach is a value home run, then some of Duqette's other
deals qualify as doubles, at least. In 1995 Duquette acquired
pitcher Tim Wakefield a few days after he was dumped by the
Pirates. The Red Sox signed him to a minor league contract, which
means he earned peanuts. The deal paid dividends immediately.
Wakefield went 16-8 for the Sox that year and helped the team make
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   That same year Duquette plucked Troy O'Leary off the scrap heap.
The outfielder had been let go by the Milwaukee Brewers. O'Leary
has since become the team's most dependable outfielder and could
drive in 100 runs this year.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Wakefield nor O'Leary is much of a bargain anymore.
Their success has translated into multiyear, multimillion-dollar
contracts. Just like stocks, ballplayers don't stay cheap once the
world sees what they can do.
</P>
<P>
   Need more evidence of Duquette's value skills? How about the
1997 trade he engineered with the Seattle Mariners? We gave them
relief pitcher Heathcliff Slocumb and they gave us catcher Jason
Varitek and reliever Derek Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   When he departed, the Globe wrote of Slocumb: ``That peculiar
form of torture known as Heathcliff Slocumb will no longer practice
in Boston.'' Slocumb went on to torture Seattle with his
inconsistent pitching. Varitek and Lowe, both nobodies at the time,
have since become the Red Sox's starting catcher and top relief
pitcher, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, Duquette's decision to sign Nomar Garciaparra
to a five-year, $23 million contract after his rookie year doesn't
seem to fit the value style. But remember: Value is a relative
term. If Garciaparra continues his All-Star ways _ he is currently
leading the American League in hitting _ his $5 million a year
paycheck may come to be seen as a bargain. Microsoft looked like an
expensive stock a year ago. It has doubled in price since then.
</P>
<P>
   Because investing is an art, not a science, even the best
investors stumble sometimes. Duquette is no exception. He gave
third baseman John Valentin a long-term contract at $6 million a
year. Valentin is probably worth one-third of that. Pinch hitter
Reggie Jefferson makes a lot of money for a part-time player.
Duquette's deal with Jose Offerman _ $26 million for four years _
looks pricey too, but it may be too early to make a judgment.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know if Duquette comes by his value instincts
naturally or by necessity. Duquette's boss, Red Sox president John
Harrington, has been reluctant to pay the salaries it takes to
acquire superstar players. The one obvious exception was the
decision to pay pitcher Pedro Martinez $75 million over six years.
</P>
<P>
   Fans would love to see Duquette add a few more growth stocks
like Martinez to his portfolio. In the meantime, however, the
general manager is sticking to his discipline.
</P>
<P>
   This week the Red Sox picked up Rod Beck, a relief pitcher
coming off elbow surgery. Thursday night, another reclamation
project, Ramon Martinez, who last year had rotator-cuff surgery,
will make his Red Sox debut.
</P>
<P>
   Has Duquette found two more value gems? Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
