<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8504 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     09-02 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... Nativity scene.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each spring some annuals sprout unbidden from seeds in the
ground, including a few petunias that trace their lineage to Father
Ubaldis DePrizio, who worked the garden many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When DelPriore started volunteering at the garden, there were a
couple of older men in charge, but they became ill and the wife of
one of them asked DelPriore, he recalled, ``with her husband
perhaps on his deathbed'' to take over, so that the garden was
waiting for him to get better. And he did get better, but not well
enough to take back the garden.
</P>
<P>
   And so DelPriore was left stranded in paradise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy it,'' he says. ``It's very different from the office.
But it's frustrating, getting no help, except from the maintenance
man who waters some mornings. People say they'll pitch in, and they
never show up! I think it's more a question of commitment than
anything else. It's not something you can do once in a while. It's
unrelenting. Things die if you don't show up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Old North Church
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What gets 4.5 hours of light a day and 600,000 visitors a year?
</P>
<P>
   The Eighteenth Century Garden at Old North Church.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it seems that cooperative gardening is an oxymoron,
that all gardens are one-man-shows (even those devoted to
brotherhood and peace), I stroll by Old North Church. And here I
find two beautiful gardens maintained by veritable gangs of people.
</P>
<P>
   Strong leadership is one key. Being a historic national shrine
doesn't hurt either. Old North Church still has the capacity to
inspire citizens to unite for our common welfare.
</P>
<P>
   On the north side of that church, where two lanterns signaled
the start of the Revolutionary War one fated night, is the
Washington Memorial Garden. It was created by the Beacon Hill
Garden Club 50 years ago, using funds from their famous annual
``Hidden Gardens'' tour. It is a low-maintenance garden that has
held up extraordinarily well since its most recent redesign in
1993, says Jennifer Wilson, one of eight club members who quietly
tend it.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Eighteenth Century Garden on the south side of the
church is in fact the newer garden. Here eight to 10 fast-track
professionals from all over the city converge on foot and by subway
for a brisk, well-orchestrated, work-study stint each Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The organizational mastermind behind this garden is attorney and
North End resident Marcia Casey. Hers is one of about 125 families
who worship at Christ Church in the City, a.k.a. Old North. Six
years ago the south garden was languishing when the previous vicar
gratefully greenlighted her project to turn it into a garden of
plants grown in the 18th century to fit in with the period of the
church. She did a ton of research and seemed to be having so much
fun that others soon joined her. Now the squad is up to 20.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you get volunteers to show up to weed?
</P>
<P>
   Casey runs the Eighteenth Century Garden like a 21st-century
company with e-mail schedules of upcoming projects. She speaks of
volunteer gardeners with ``different management styles and people
with different skill sets, such as growing seeds.'' She also makes
a point of pairing an experienced gardener with a newer gardener.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sign-up calendar so we don't all show up at the same
time. It's a great mix of people from 20 to 60, men and women, and
we see different people each time we come. We have parties, with
prizes for garden hats, it's fun, and we get hooked,'' says Lisa
Ayres, the current vicar's wife and a volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that gardening with antique herbs and flowers
has developed tremendous cachet, too. ``Marcia's always teaching us
about the 18th-century plants, the history, the botanical names,
says Ayres.
</P>
<P>
   Social events such as potluck suppers keep the volunteers
connected even in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   But now the pink mallow is still in bloom, the antique sweetpeas
are climbing their tepees, the black-eyed Susans are robust, and
the love-lies-bleeding is hugh and hanging just as it should with
droopy chenille-like flower clusters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard work at the beginning of the season but it pays off
when the tourists compliment us,'' says ``seedling coach'' and
volunteer, Deni Findlay. ``We're getting away from the pressure of
daily life, and so are they.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tourists are enchanted and delighted because they're on
vacation. Some from far away and some from Quincy. But their joy is
another dynamic that supports the project,'' said Casey in her
characteristic business-speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``They peer in through the fence and say, `I love the garden!'
and we say, `Where do you live?' We say, `Join us!' We tell them
they don't have to have any experience. It is magical. And it's
highly spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, in fact, another one of those miracles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR CHURCH GARDENS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are tips we gleaned from our success stories on creating
church gardens that are not devilishly hard to maintain:
</P>
<P>
   --Plant low-maintenance trees, shrubs, ground covers, and bulbs,
not annual and perennial flowers.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't try to run a garden by committee. It's much better to
have a single authoritative person in charge who is committed to
ensuring success (and who will train their own successor).
</P>
<P>
   --Install an underground irrigation system with a
battery-powered timer.
</P>
<P>
   --Reserve at least half of any garden contribution for
maintenance expenses.
</P>
<P>
   --Have garden maintenance as part of the church budget, rather
than be dependent upon volunteers and special donations.
</P>
<P>
   --Hire a knowledgeable crew for spring and fall cleanup and
pruning. Don't be like the suburban church that tried to save money
by hiring a prison work detail that ``pruned'' trees by cutting
them to the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
