<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION CLEANUP EFFORT SHOULD BEGIN SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to the paralyzing effects of central planning, the safety
net of the lack of relegation, and other MLS oddities, the
Revolution are in playoff contention in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But there are few signs they will remain in this state of grace
for long. In fact, if form holds they should be effectively
eliminated either after Saturday's game against Tampa Bay or
following their visit to Miami Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution could well remain in mathematical contention for
one of the four playoff berths after those games, but unless they
win at least once in regulation time they should start planning for
next season. Lately, there has been no indication they are even
capable of doing that.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, even should the Revolution rally in the final seven
games of the season, they will have to make wholesale changes to
the team next year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the players who have been involved in the last two
dismal seasons should be sent away, both for the team's and their
own good. This means some very good performers, along with mediocre
ones, will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Joe-Max Moore, for instance, will certainly play his final
Revolution game this season. Moore, though, will have a chance to
return to Europe, where he played for Nurnberg before joining MLS
in 1996. Moore's contract with the league expires after this
season, and his transfer should be negotiated simply.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have failed the last two seasons because they
simply have too many weaknesses and not enough variety. The very
elements that might have saved the team have been excluded or
ignored. The team has enough defensive midfielders, though Leonel
Alvarez is a welcome addition, and complementary hard workers. It
needs some experienced, skillful performers who can make everyone
else better, starting in central defense.
</P>
<P>
   Player-coach Walter Zenga is taking most of the blame for the
Revolution's current plight. And Zenga has surely made mistakes,
but none bigger than when he took over the team last August and
overestimated the players and his ability to transform them. Even
Zenga's spectacular goalkeeping has not enabled the Revolution to
find a winning formula.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between the Revolution and other top teams was
graphically illustrated during a 2-1 loss to the Chicago Fire last
Saturday, the ninth consecutive game in which the Revolution failed
to win in regulation time.
</P>
<P>
   This is Zenga's first coaching position. But most other
experienced coaches would have handled Revolution personnel
similarly. They would have been convinced that the Revolution had
enough talent to solve their own difficulties, and if they tried to
change the equation, the holdover players would have resisted. And
that coach would have been sacrificed.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution management has tried changing coaches and importing
several foreign players. The problems remain.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the Revolution require a change of philosophy.
They need to go in a different direction. Team management simply
rejected Edwin Gorter, Francis Okaroh, Welton, and Andy Williams _
all creative players who had been successful and would go on to
have more success _ and the Revolution's core group of players
seemed to approve of the moves either tacitly or otherwise. Others
who might have helped were frozen out, or simply did not ``fit in''
with the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution could have been on the way to solving their
problems had they acquired defender Joseph Addo last month, but
instead will have to start over next year. That was a mistake
general manager Brian O'Donovan will either have to live with or
attempt to correct, because Zenga clearly preferred Addo over
striker Ariel Graziani.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding can be a long process. The sooner the Revolution
begin, the better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
