<HEADLINE>
CLEANING TIPS FOR SOAPSTONE AND GRANITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How can I clean an old soapstone sink? It doesn't leak, but
looks pretty tired. Also, how can I clean smooth granite tiles that
have oil stains?
</P>
<P>
   JOE DORAN, Westford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Clean the soapstone with paint thinner. Put it on liberally
so that it can dissolve the dirt, but do not let it evaporate.
Scrub with a sponge or Scotch pad, then wipe clean with a dry
cloth. That will clean it, but it might be pretty light in color.
To condition the soapstone, which will turn it black or dark green,
according to the type of soapstone, wipe mineral oil on the surface
liberally, wait 15 minutes, rub with your hands, and then wipe up
all that will come off with a dry cloth. Unwiped, the oil could
stay sticky for years. You can repeat this technique any time.
</P>
<P>
   As for the granite, it may be difficult to remove the oil stain.
As hard as it is, the granite has absorbed the oil. To remove, wet
it with paint thinner, then sprinkle lots of baking soda on the wet
stain. Leave it for an hour, then sweep up and dispose of.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walter Mucha of Brookline, Mass. called to sympathize with
people trying to find old, dicontinued, and obsolete tiles for
their kitchen and bathroom renovation projects.
</P>
<P>
   He also shared this information on removing old adhesive and
grout from the tile: ``I use tile nippers to take the hard grout
off the edges of the tile. That's the easy part. For removing old
adhesive, I make a mix of chemical paint remover and liquid
paintbrush cleaner, and submerge the tiles for three or four days.
After that, the adhesive comes off or is easily scraped off.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Walter, for the great ideas. Actually, I think
scraping the grout off the tile edges is easier and faster with a
utility knife. But the adhesive idea is brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman has done a similar thing with spool bed spindles.
Those spindles are the very devil to remove finish from because
they are spooled. So the handyman stole his wife's long cake pan
(borrowed, really, but after what he did with it, the pan was not
worth returning). He filled it with chemical paint remover and
dropped in the spindles, which, of course, had to take them out of
the bed frame in the first place. That was the hard part. The easy
part was rubbing the spindles with steel wool after a day or less
in the soup. Everything came out very nicely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My concrete driveway is very old and in some sections is
pretty beaten up, cracked, and no longer level. Should I repair
those sections or cover the whole thing with asphalt?
</P>
<P>
   MARK McLANEY, Malden, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If some of the sections are still in good shape, why not keep
them that way and replace the sections that are not. A concrete
driveway is usually poured in sections, with expansion joints every
6 feet or so. So, cut out the beaten up concrete, excavate deeply
enough to put down 6 inches of crushed stone under the new
concrete, and pour a sectional slab 4 to 6 inches thick. Six is
better than 4; in fact, I am guessing that the slab failed because
it was only 4 inches thick. And, to prevent cracking and failure in
the future, install 6-inch steel reinforcing mesh or 3/4-inch steel
reinforcing rods (rebars) in the center of the slab's thickness.
</P>
<P>
   You will have to set up enough of these sections so you can
order concrete for pouring. A minimum order of concrete is usually
2 yards.
</P>
<P>
   All this is better than putting asphalt on top of a partially
unstable base. And, if you do it yourself, you can do one section
at a time, doing others whenever you feel like it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My pine dining room table is pretty seedy-looking. I have
used furniture polish on it once a month. How can I clean it and
make it a bit shinier, without refinishing it?
</P>
<P>
   P.C., Winthrop, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The table got seedy-looking from overuse of furniture polish,
which in the handyman's opinion, mostly dulls the finish.
</P>
<P>
   To restore the finish, clean it with paint thinner, which will
dissolve the polish so it can be wiped off. Apply the thinner
liberally, let it sit on the surface for a few minutes (add some if
it starts to evaporate), scrub with a cloth, then wipe off
everything with a dry cloth. The paint thinner will dull the finish
more than it is now, but you can restore most of it by buffing with
a dry cloth.
</P>
<P>
   A varnished, lacquered, or shellacked finish does not need
polishing or waxing, or any protection at all; it is its own
protection. So go very easy with the polish. Not at all or at most
once a year, and sparingly, as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
