<HEADLINE>
BOSTON, FROM GHOST TO GHOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who knows what evil lurks in the heart of Boston? The
Gravedigger does.
</P>
<P>
   And so does the Caretaker. Solomon the Gravedigger and Revere
the Caretaker are your horrifying hosts on one of Boston's newest
and most unusual tours, ``Ghosts &AMP; Gravestones.'' The two-hour
nighttime excursion in a black trolley takes you to graveyards and
streets where many a strange tale was born.
</P>
<P>
   Revere, wearing a hood and dressed all in black, is the driver
and caretaker _ ``and you'll need all the care you can get,'' he
says. Solomon, who carries a lantern and wears a stovepipe hat with
funeral ribbon attached, is the gravedigger _ ``and I really dig up
the dirt.'' He keeps that promise as he leads you from the trolley
to explore on foot (and with flashlight) these three places:
</P>
<P>
   --Boston Common. Centuries ago, Solomon says, this was a place
where happy crowds gathered _ to watch hangings from an elm tree.
There wasn't much to do for recreation in those days, he explains,
so an execution took on a celebratory air, with vendors selling
pies and sweetmeats. Meanwhile, what today is the Frog Pond was in
the 1600s a muddy spot where miscreants were forced to take a
ducking via a dunking stool.
</P>
<P>
   --The Granary Burying Ground. Several Revolutionary War patriots
are buried here, including Paul Revere, who identified the corpse
of his friend Dr. Joseph Warren (which for a variety of reasons was
often disinterred), and James Otis, who correctly predicted he
would die by a thunderbolt. Many gravestones are marked with a
winged death's head, a solemn symbol in times past. And from the
graveyard there is a view of the Boston Athenaeum, where you can
peek in to try to spot the ghost who is said to quietly sit and
read there _ a ghost first spotted by author Nathaniel Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   --Copp's Hill. This North End site provides excellent views of
the steeple of the Old North Church and Bunker Hill. But it is the
burial ground that holds dozens of stories, including how two
strangers came to share a gravestone and how one woman ended up
buried with dozens of sailors. Cotton Mather, so prominent in the
Salem witch hysteria, lies here, too.
</P>
<P>
   The stories don't stop there. As Revere takes you from place to
place in the Black Dahlia, as the trolley is named, he tells tales,
too. You hear about the man who in the 1700s somehow ``flew'' from
the Old North Church steeple, firing pistols as he landed. And
about the true incident behind Edgar Allen Poe's grisly story ``The
Cask of Amontillado.'' And how the human spirit was scientifically
shown to weigh 6 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Revere points out notorious sights, such as the
home of the last victim of the Boston Strangler. There is a bit of
mock gunplay and swordplay as well, and passengers get to practice
banshee screams. There is even a look at the frightfully expensive
Big Dig road project. And there is music, including ``The Monster
Mash,'' ``Ghostbusters,'' ``I Put A Spell on You,'' and the Lizzie
Borden song that contains this practical advice: ``You can't chop
your mother up in Massachusetts . . . it's a far cry from New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   As you may have surmised, there are chuckles along with the
chills. After all, as Revere notes, the first three letters of
``funeral'' are f-u-n.
</P>
<P>
   (The ``Ghosts &AMP; Gravestones'' tour is presented by Historic
Tours of America, via Minuteman Tours. It departs at dusk from in
front of the Trolley Stop at Charles and Boylston streets Thursday,
Friday, and Saturday nights, with the possibility of more days to
come, through October. The price is $28 for adults and $15 for
children and includes a mini-flashlight. For reservations, call
617-269-3626. And let's give credit where it's due: Revere is
played by Bob Roland, and Solomon is portrayed by Graeme Marsden.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What are the only two US states named after women?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Australians really don't care all that much for the term
``down under.'' (That, however, won't prevent us from using it.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``I believe that (the) endless search for beauty in
surroundings, in people and one's personal life, is the headstone
of travel.'' _ Juliette de Bairacli-Levy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's fractured English lesson: The Hotel Prusija in Klaipeda,
Lithuania, advertises that ``clients meeting at Lithuanian airports
can be ordered.'' (With thanks to Blanche Vogel of Canton and
Elaine Frick of Attleboro.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Parade of the parrots: The Mandalay Bay Resort &AMP; Casino in Las
Vegas is ``the newest, most deluxe, and exotic resort on the
Strip,'' writes veteran Boston public relations man C. Paul Luongo
in the Travel Smart newsletter. One of the unusual features of this
lush, 3,700-room resort are the Bird Girls ``who parade through the
lobby at various times in tropical-colored bikinis, carrying a
parrot or macaw on their arms.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: To our list of humorous sayings by airline personnel,
Richard Caffelle of Brockton, Mass. adds this gem, heard on British
Airways: ``Although Paul Simon taught us 50 ways to leave your
lover, there are, unfortunately, only three exits on this
aircraft.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Virginia and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
