<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSCOLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CEDRIC WASHINGTON, THE TIME IS NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He has patiently served his time _ sitting and
watching, watching and sitting _ as a backup to Omari Walker,
Quinton Lee, and Mike Cloud, who last year rushed for 1,726 yards
and 14 touchdowns to become Boston College's all-time leading
rusher with 3,597 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But Cedric Washington waits no more.
</P>
<P>
   When the Eagles open their 101st season of football Saturday
afternoon by hosting Baylor at Alumni Stadium, the 5-foot-11-inch,
201-pound junior from Holyoke will finally get his chance to emerge
from the shadows of his high-stepping predecessors and step into
the spotlight as BC's starting running back.
</P>
<P>
   With senior Carlton Rowe still nursing a pulled groin and
freshman sensation William Green still coming along, it will be up
to Washington, who was second on the team last year with 37 carries
for 173 yards, to handle the bulk of the work in BC's rushing
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be nervous,'' Washington admitted Wednesday.
``Last year, I don't think I was nervous one time going into a game
because Cloud was carrying the load, but now I'll be starting for
the first time, and I'm getting nervous just thinking about it
right now. I'm just looking to have a big day and try to put our
team in a position to score.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Green, a highly-touted recruit from Atlantic
City who was impressive in preseason camp, will only add to
Washington's sense of urgency. He realizes that if he is not
productive, then Green, the thoroughbred waiting in the wings, is
capable of taking the ball and running away with the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every college football player has to deal with that, a
highly-recruited freshman coming in,'' Washington said. ``You've
got to perform or else you're going to take a back seat. Willie
Green, he's a great running back and he's young, but he's got to
learn the offense first before he can do anything. He's going to be
a hell of a running back for us in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But not quite yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the present,'' Washington said, smiling. ``So now it's
my chance.''
</P>
<P>
   And Washington is hoping to make the most of it, the same way
Cloud made the most of his opportunity, bursting onto the scene two
years ago as a junior and rushing for 211 yards against West
Virginia as a substitute for the injured Walker. It served as a
springboard to Cloud's senior year, in which Washington was
promoted to backup when Lee was kicked off the team after his
arrest for public drunkenness and disorderly conduct following a
31-7 victory over Temple Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   So what lessons did Washington learn from watching Cloud?
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, when you get your chance, you've got to shine, and
that's what he did,'' Washington said. ``I'm in the same situation
now. He had to wait around three years, and his (junior) year he
finally got in there and rushed for something like 800 yards, and
that started everything.''
</P>
<P>
   And while it was an extension of Cloud's equally phenomenal high
school career, the numbers paled in comparison to the astronomical
figures Washington put up at Holyoke High, where he set a state
record with 2,881 yards, including five 300-yard games and 41
touchdowns, to lead his team to an 11-0 record and the Western
Mass. Super Bowl title with a 46-17 victory over Greenfield. In
that game, Washington recalled, ``I carried the ball about 45
times, had something like 300-350 yards, and scored five
touchdowns. All on hard runs.''
</P>
<P>
   On weekend trips home to visit his girlfriend, Jamie Gonsor, and
their 2 1/2-year-old daughter, Jordyn, Washington dealt with
persistent questions about why he wasn't producing the same numbers
at BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that motivated me,'' said Washington, who was
recruited by Notre Dame, Nebraska, Syracuse, and North Carolina
State before committing to BC. ``Being from Holyoke, a small town
that no one really knows where it is, I want to try and put that
place on the map, and this is my chance to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he can be as productive at the college level as he was
in high school is another matter. While he expects to get more
carries than the three per game he averaged last year, Washington
knows he'll absorb a greater amount of punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could take its toll physically because my body's not used
to taking that pounding,'' Washington said. ``That's why it's so
important to me to have Carlton and Willie ready to give me a
break. I'm not like a power runner; I'm more of an elusive runner.
I want to try and get one-on-one with a safety, make some moves,
and put on a show. I'll be nervous, but after that first play I
think I'll be fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
