<HEADER>
A8512 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-SPENCE-ART-     09-02 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-SPENCE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SUPERINTENDENT SPENCE, FROM SUPERB TO SUBLIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It would seem to be the equivalent of
starting out in the penthouse, so when Bill Spence tells you his
first job in the industry was at Pebble Beach, he is fully prepared
for looks sent his way.
</P>
<P>
   Quizzical. Perplexed. Disbelief. As in, ``How could you ever
leave?''
</P>
<P>
   There is a slight grin on his face as Spence delivers an
explanation that speaks volumes about what he is all about. ``Being
superintendent at Pebble Beach isn't what you think,'' he said. ``I
was always in the office. I had three superintendents working for
me. I never got my hands dirty and never spent one day working on
the course.''
</P>
<P>
   So, after 3 1/2 years, Spence left a place that many golfers
would swear is heaven on earth. And they may be right. ``Carmel was
the most beautiful place to live,'' said Spence. ``I took my wife
out of Carmel in tears.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent 7 1/2 years at Kansas City CC in Kansas, then made
another move, this time with his wife's blessings. The former Mae
Nickerson had grown up in Jamaica Plain, had spent many wonderful
days walking at Lars Anderson Park and now her husband was going to
be superintendent at The Country Club in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   For her, a return home to New England with her husband and three
boys. For him, arguably one of the premier jobs in his industry,
one that would allow him to get his hands dirty. But a job, now
that the Ryder Cup is virtually upon us, that surely is causing
sleepless nights, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction (when it was announced a few years ago that
TCC would host the Ryder Cup) was to be excited for my staff,
because they are young and have never experienced something like
this before. I've been through it, though this is the biggest.''
</P>
<P>
   Bigger than the 1977 PGA Championship at Pebble Beach. Bigger
than those annual Bing Crosby Pro-Ams. Even bigger than the 1988 US
Open at The Country Club, an event Spence was very much a part of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to The Country Club in 1984, and that August they
agreed to host the '88 Open,'' said Spence. Rees Jones has been
brought on board to restore the course, and it was Spence's job to
see that those plans were carried out throughout 1985-86. ``The
first, fourth, and 17th greens were completely redone, and we
enlarged 10 other greens that had been made smaller during the war
years to save money.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, said Spence, the Jones restoration included 25
bunkers, the re-leveling of 16 championship tees, and a new
irrigation system.
</P>
<P>
   The '88 Open, he said, was a huge undertaking, but the Ryder Cup
is even bigger. It is 11 years later and the sport has become that
much more popular. More exposure. More people. More corporate
tents. More television cable.
</P>
<P>
   But at least, said Spence, no more restoration. This time, the
preparation was all his.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have done is refine (the earlier project). We've
reshaped 96 bunkers and put in new sand. We've widened fairways in
some spots by (a mere) 12 inches, just to let the ball roll better.
But it's the same course. The same great course.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ben Crenshaw, captain of the US Ryder Cup team, shares Spence's
love of The Country Club. ``Ben may know the course and its history
as well as anyone,'' said Spence.
</P>
<P>
   But a golf course, even one that is rich in tradition, is only
as good as its caretakers, a fact that both Crenshaw and Spence
point to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The superintendent (Spence) is a naturalist,'' said Crenshaw,
``and that's so important to keeping the place special.''
</P>
<P>
   Spence credits the genius of those who built the place more than
100 years ago, as well as the members who have nurtured it through
the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course is a work of art. Beauty is different to
different people, but The Country Club members are secure in their
love of the place, so if someone doesn't like the course, it won't
bother them.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a crisp fall day almost a year ago when Crenshaw
walked the course with Spence. They discussed philosophies and
pointed out quirky subtleties that make the course a ``classic'' in
every sense. Crenshaw's genuine love of the event and of the course
shined through, said Spence.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, he said to me, `We could play this thing right
now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Spence and Crenshaw did not meet face to face Monday when the
captain and eight of his players were at The Country Club for a
practice round, but Spence took that as a promising sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``No news is good news, I guess. I heard they generally liked
what they saw. If there were problems, I probably would have heard
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that Spence and his crew have had an easy
summer. It's just that he's been at this business a long time and
knows some things are out of your control, namely the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winter and lack of spring combine to offer the most
difficult hurdles every year. Last year we got 50 inches of rain
(in the spring) and there wasn't a brown blade of grass on the
course. Back in 1988 we had a cool, wet May. The course was
perfect. Then we got blasted with really hot weather and there
wasn't much rough for the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   This year? ``We did OK. My three assistants _ Greg Barker, Jeff
Baker, and Scott Lagana _ and my great staff (including Emma, the
border collie) never stopped.'' It got hot and there wasn't much
rain, but remember, Spence is a superintendent who believes:
``Brown grass is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   You know, the naturalist. The naturalist who also happens to be
a devoted weather-watcher. Has to be in his line of work. As early
as April this year he confessed to the one thing that concerned
him: ``The long-range forecast called for the most active
(hurricane season) in memory.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that season upon us, Spence is still paying attention.
``I'm going to the radar right now to see about (Hurricane)
Dennis,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spence will tell you that he's been most fortunate in his jobs.
``I met Jack Neville (the man who designed Pebble Beach) once. He
was 90 and I remember thinking, `I can't believe I'm sitting here
with the guy who laid this thing out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At Kansas City CC, a certain member who could lay claim to five
British Open titles used to go out of his way to say hello and talk
about all things golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason Tom Watson stayed there,'' said Spence, ``is that
it was one of the few places where they would leave him alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, to get the chance to understand the game of golf from
one of the premier players was an amazing opportunity, and I
learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty impressive for a guy from New Jersey, a self-confessed
``golf nut,'' whose first love was journalism. That changed at the
University of Massachusetts where, in addition to meeting Mae,
Spence studied for four years in the turf management program,
graduating in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided what I wanted to do was be outdoors,'' said Spence.
``It was the back-to-nature thing of the '60s.'' It led to a job
with Monmouth County Parks in New Jersey, then to Pebble Beach, to
Kansas City, to Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny,'' he said. ``We had a lot of visitors in Carmel, but
none in Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be familiar faces at The Country Club during the
Ryder Cup, though they won't be visitors. His eldest sons _
Christopher, a senior at Williams College, and Ryan, a sophomore at
Franklin High School _ will be working with him at The Country
Club. Will, a fifth-grader, ``could care less about golf,'' said
Spence.
</P>
<P>
   So let the show begin, said Spence. ``The place is a
character-builder. It will be a great match-play course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
