<HEADLINE>
SADLER'S A BOOST FOR THE LEAD-FOOTED RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Can we all agree on this much anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Sadler can run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's put such life into the team,'' Mike Stanley says. ``He
puts down two bunts, and both times the guy barely bobbles the
ball, and anybody else would still be out. Not Donnie. He's on
first. And (Jose) Offerman hits a 200-foot fly ball down the line
the other night. (itals)Nobody(unitals) else on this team, and very
few people in the league, could hope to score on a ball like that.
But he did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about offense,'' says Jimy Williams. ``Watch him go
after popups.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Sadler is a baseball type, and it is a type seen in these
here parts about as often as Republican in the mayor's office. He
is one of those pesky, faster-than-a-cheetah, disruptive types
usually found in the (itals)other(unitals) manager's dugout. If
this 24-year-old, 5-foot-6-inch Texan is not the single fastest
player ever to wear a Red Sox uniform, than, by God, he's among
'em.
</P>
<P>
   But right now he is merely another type. He is the
inexperienced, unpolished, dripping with potential, teasing type.
Run? Oh, can he run. Catch it? Without question. Throw? His arm may
be as amazing as his speed. Hit? Well . . .
</P>
<P>
   It's the oldest saw in baseball: (unitals)You can't steal first
base.(itals) Then again, Sadler isn't so sure. He is on record as
saying that if he hits a routine grounder to short he has a 50-50
chance of beating it out. So the idea would be for Sadler to hit
enough ground balls and line drives to get on base at least 175-200
times a season. Throw in some walks _ and a glance at his resume
doesn't exactly suggest the second coming of Eddie Yost _ and
you're talking about somebody who could score 120-plus runs in a
season. You think maybe you'd like a guy like that leading off here
for maybe the next 10 years?
</P>
<P>
   He was at third base in place of the ailing John Valentin
Tuesday night, and it wasn't solely because of his phenomenal
speed. ``He's hit a couple of balls through the hole lately,''
explains an approving Williams, who would benefit more than anyone
if Sadler could justify his presence in the lineup on a regular
basis. ``And the other night he drove in a couple of runs on a ball
up the middle. He realizes what he has to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That, according to Sadler, is no accident. ``I got a taste of
the major leagues last year,'' he says. ``I saw what it took to
play at this level. I went home last winter and worked on certain
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as?
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting down on my swing,'' admits the powerfully-built second
baseman/shortstop/center fielder/third baseman/whatever. ``I didn't
really make any other changes. I just realized I had to put the
ball in play.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the veterans are fascinated with Sadler, because they
have seen these speedball types before, and not all of them have
made proper use of their tools. ``I'd probably put Donnie in the
ultra-speed category,'' says the thoughtful Darren Lewis. ``Tom
Goodwin comes to mind. He can get down the line in less than four
seconds, and Donnie is right there. But the thing I'd like to see
him do is learn how to get a jump stealing bases. If he doesn't
learn to do that he won't be using one of his primary assets.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to steal second, however, a man must be on first, and
that's where batting coach Jim Rice comes in. ``There are things he
needs to learn,'' Rice points out. ``And if he can learn them, look
out. If he can hit balls to make the infielder move two or three
steps left or right, instead of surrounding the ball, he'll have 40
to 50 infield hits a year. If the shortstop has to go into the hole
by two or three steps, he has no chance to throw out Donnie
Sadler.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no questions about Sadler with a glove on his hand,
and it really doesn't make any difference where you put him. His
natural position is shortstop, but that position appears to be
occupied at the moment. His second base play draws raves from
everyone, especially in the range department. ``He had Jimy
laughing last week in Minnesota,'' points out Stanley. ``Jimy was
hitting fungoes and he couldn't believe how far from Sadler he had
to hit the ball to get it by him.'' Third base for Sadler will be,
as the legendary Eddie Pellegrini used to say, like ``camping
out.'' And while he really doesn't like playing in the outfield, he
has a chance to be a Gold Glover.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was out there in right field at times during infield
practice during spring training,'' says Stanley, ``and he has by
far the best outfield arm on the team, and one of the best outfield
arms you'll see anywhere. If you put him out there, he would shut
down running games.''
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while a guy comes here with some speed. Tommy
Harper stayed around long enough to set the club stolen base record
(54). Jerry Remy got people excited with his legs before knees
terminated his career prematurely. Otis Nixon gave the Red Sox one
dazzling year in center and on the basepaths.
</P>
<P>
   None of them were signed and developed by the Red Sox. Sadler is
that rarity of rarities _ a blue chip Red Sox prospect whose
calling card is speed. How far back would you have to go to find
someone like that in this town? Tris Speaker?
</P>
<P>
   Sadler is so tantalizing. Speed. ``It puts pressure on the
opposition,'' muses Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Speed. ``It makes so many things happen,'' adds Stanley. ``There
was a ball hit to left with Donnie on second the other night, and
with anyone else (third base coach) Wendell (Kim) is holding his
hands up. He waves Donnie home and we get a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed. ``That speed,'' drools Williams. ``He has a chance to be
an exciting player.''
</P>
<P>
   He's halfway there already. He's exciting, all right. But is he
a Player? A salivating Red Sox Nation is eager to find out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
