<SLUG> BC-IMPORTED-APPLES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN GROWERS LAUNCHING A MAC ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; HARVARD, Mass. _ Forget the drought. It's the People's
Republic of China that has New England apple growers really
worried.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to survive a glut partly caused by a dramatic rise in
Chinese apple production, local growers are promoting the McIntosh
apple as something as much a part of New England as clam chowder or
lobster stew.
</P>
<P>
   New billboards around Boston celebrate the McIntosh, which
accounts for about two-thirds of the region's apple crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taste New England,'' the billboards say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make the McIntosh a niche apple,'' says Frank
Carlson of Carlson Orchards Inc. in Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   As this year's harvest begins, local growers have a lot more
things to fret about than drought, hail, and kids who don't want to
follow them into an ever more difficult family business.
</P>
<P>
   Excess supply, flat demand, mergers in the supermarket business
_ all have made life harder for US apple growers.
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest challenge may come from China, now the world's
largest apple producer. In 1998, China grew about 40 percent of the
global crop, an amount nearly four times US production.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the US apple industry looks to marketing as a way
to
</P>
<P>
   get Americans to eat more apples, and to be willing to pay
higher prices for niche apples including the McIntosh.
</P>
<P>
   As local McIntosh growers urge consumers to ``taste New
England,'' a $40-million marketing campaign from Washington state
aims to convert consumers into apple connoisseurs. Accounting for
about half of the US apple crop, Washington state wants folks to
think of Red Delicious and Granny Smith apples in the same way a
wine lover regards a fine Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   ``A banana is just a banana,'' says Jim Thomas of the Washington
Apple Commission. ``They all taste pretty much the same.'' But an
apple? ``It's more like wine,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   With about 2,500 varieties to choose from, the marketing pitch
is that the apple offers discerning gourmets a rich diversity of
enjoyable and healthful eating.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting apples is hardly new. In the apple annals of the early
1800s, the legend of John Chapman looms large. Better known by the
nom de pomme of Johnny Appleseed, he ranged far from his native
Leominster, planting apple trees wherever he roamed. If Chapman
were alive today, he might well be found hard at work in China.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, China has increased its annual production of apples
by nearly 70 percent, according to Kraig R. Naasz, president of the
US Apple Association, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   And some of that increased production has found its way into the
United States in the form of apple-juice concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   In only three years, the Chinese share of the US market for
apple-juice concentrate grew from 1 percent to 18 percent, Naasz
says. During the same period, the average price US growers received
for a ton of juice apples fell from $153 to $55, a price so low
that some growers concluded it was better to let some apples rot on
the trees than pay the cost of picking them.
</P>
<P>
   According to Naasz, China is so eager to gain a foothold in the
US market that it's guilty of dumping _ selling its products below
cost. His group is lobbying the US government to impose tariffs on
Chinese apple imports.
</P>
<P>
   In the industry, juice apples used in processing are
distinguished from fresh apples, or the eating apples that are sold
on supermarket shelves. New England, which accounts for about 3
percent of US production, grows mostly fresh apples.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the Chinese juice glut, many US growers in other
states that grow a lot of juice apples are switching more to fresh
apples. One result: New England now faces stiffer competition from
New York and Washington growers.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese competition has hurt in another way. Traditionally, a
quarter of the US crop has been exported. Once US growers owned the
apple markets in some Asian countries, but the landscape has been
rearranged by new rivals and devalued foreign currencies that can
make US apples too pricey overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to dominate Thailand,'' says Thomas of the Washington
state apple group. ``Now we have to fight for market share with New
Zealand, China, Australia, and France.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrinking foreign markets mean a larger fraction of the US apple
crop has to be absorbed by the domestic market. Throw in excess
supply caused by West Coast bumper crops, and the money US growers
got for their apples fell from $1.58 billion in 1997 to $1.29
billion in 1998, Naasz's group says.
</P>
<P>
   By Naasz's lights, 1998 was a Murphy's Law of a year that found
the industry in ``an economic tailspin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that could go wrong did go wrong,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Even more things went wrong in New England. For openers, a wet
spring discouraged bees from pollinating the trees, and regional
production in 1998 fell sharply as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the troubles of domestic apple growers can be traced
to the Chinese, bad weather, and balky bees, however.
</P>
<P>
   At the supermarket, consumers now have more choices. With fast
shipping and new techniques for preserving freshness, the apple is
just one fruit among many fighting for shelf space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be you couldn't get raspberries in December, and
who ever heard of clementines?'' says executive director Russell
Powell of the New England McIntosh Growers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many supermarket chains are consolidating in an
effort to defend themselves from incursions by Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
into the food business.
</P>
<P>
   For growers, consolidation means fewer places to sell apples and
less bargaining power when dealing with bulked-up chains.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers in the supermarket industry have ``really tightened the
screws'' on apple growers, says Gerald White, an agricultural
economist at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   To lessen their dependency on supermarkets, many local growers
run roadside fruit stands and pick-your-own orchards.
</P>
<P>
   With a petting zoo and a farmer's market, Echo Hill Orchards in
Monson seeks to be a sort of theme park for apples.
</P>
<P>
   Touting apple-picking as family entertainment, Echo Hill relies
almost entirely on revenues from tourists and city dwellers and no
longer sells apples to supermarket chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a supermarket calls up, I say no,'' co-owner Richard
Krupczak says. ``They pay so little.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gloom and doom, Powell of the New England growers
group thinks the McIntosh apple is the key to regional survival.
</P>
<P>
   The McIntosh's chief selling point is the distinctive
sweet-and-tart taste it gets from New England's odd mix of weather
and soil. It's a taste hard to duplicate elsewhere, Powell claims.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback: The McIntosh is more delicate than most apple
varieties and requires careful handling by consumers. On the plus
side, it's less vulnerable to gluts. There may be too many Red
Delicious apples on the market. Indeed, supply and demand are out
of whack for many apple varieties because they can be grown in so
many different places.
</P>
<P>
   But the supply of McIntoshes is more often in line with demand,
says Ned O'Neill, an executive at Joseph P. Sullivan Co. in Ayer,
one of the region's largest apple packers.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's prescription for a New England rebound? Focus on
growing quality McIntosh apples and market them relentlessly.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, let China be the Budweiser of apples, making
juice for the global masses. But there will still be room for a
well-promoted quality McIntosh, the apple equivalent of a
microbrewed beer.
</P>
<P>
   Says O'Neill: ``The McIntosh is our niche.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
