<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME-SHARING UPDATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two decades ago, firms like Microsoft Corp. taught us that
software is something you buy. It comes in pretty boxes with
confusing, badly written manuals. Every year or two, you buy a new
version with brand-new bugs that won't get fixed until you buy yet
another version.
</P>
<P>
   It's come to be an annoying yet vaguely pleasurable habit, like
smoking. But it's a habit that a host of new companies are trying
to break. They're called ``application service providers'' or ASPs,
and they want businesses to stop buying software and start renting
it.
</P>
<P>
   ASP operators like Andover-based Navisite Inc. say buying and
running business software makes no sense for many firms. The stuff
costs a fortune, and you have to keep updating it. Besides, you
must buy computers to run the programs and hire workers to oversee
it all. Why not simply rent a network connection to the ASP's
powerful server computers and let them process your data?
</P>
<P>
   As new ideas go, it's one of the oldest. Computer
``time-sharing'' was hot stuff in the '60s, when somebody noticed
that mainframes can do a dozen tasks at once. Firms began renting
time on them to businesses who couldn't afford machines of their
own. The ASP concept is time-sharing, updated for the era of PC
servers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the second coming of the moribund boomlet in network
computing that swept the industry a couple of years ago. We were
all supposed to give up on expensive ``fat'' desktop computers
stuffed with costly software from the likes of Microsoft Corp.
Instead we'd use ``thin client'' machines connected to a powerful
server, sitting in another room or another city.
</P>
<P>
   I bought into this fad, but it flopped, partly because desktop
computers are about two-thirds cheaper than three years ago. Still,
I've kept the faith. Network computing is bound to catch on in some
form, because it dramatically simplifies life in a computerized
world.
</P>
<P>
   Traver Gruen-Kennedy, chairman of the ASP Industry Consortium in
Wakefield, calls the ASP concept ``the revenge of network
computing.'' But this time around, ASPs aren't in the hardware
business.
</P>
<P>
   First-wave network computer firms like Sun Microsystems Inc. and
IBM Corp. hoped to make a fortune selling specialized thin-client
devices. Nobody wanted them. But ASPs are happy to let us keep
using our Pentium IIs, as long as they're linked to the ASP's
servers.
</P>
<P>
   There's another good sign for the ASPs: Larry Ellison is keeping
his mouth shut. Ellison, the CEO of database maker Oracle Corp.,
almost single-handedly discredited network computers with grandiose
claims that millions of ordinary consumers would buy them, relying
on slow telephone modems to download whatever software they might
need.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is claiming that ordinary folks will use ASP-based
programs in the near future; that would be as unprofitable as it is
impractical. The big money will be earned as companies play host to
business computer services. Clare Gillan, vice president for
applications research at International Data Corp., figures it'll be
a $2 billion market by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of firms want a piece; Sun Microsystems just bought German
office software firm Star Division, to offer Star's office software
as a rentable Internet application for firms that don't want to
spend $300 a pop for Microsoft Office.
</P>
<P>
   Is Microsoft worried? Probably not, at this early stage. Yet by
accident, the company landed a blow against network-based software
this week. The break-in at Microsoft's Hotmail free e-mail service
exposed the messages of 50 million users, and reminded us it can be
dangerous to store data on somebody else's computers. ASP customers
might also fret about last month's network collapse at MCI
WorldCom, an outage that disconnected thousands of corporate users.
Firms that count on ASPs will always be at their network's mercy.
</P>
<P>
   But then, we're all at the mercy of the Internet these days.
Many of us now wonder how we ever did business without it. The ASP
people hope that in a few years, firms will ruefully recall the
Dark Ages, when they spent a fortune every year buying and
upgrading software, when they might have been renting it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(E-mail Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
