<SLUG> BC-FILM-TWINFALLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOAP-OPERA TOUCHES MAR MOODILY EFFECTIVE `TWIN FALLS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the myriad symbols of singularity, duality and solidarity
in ``Twin Falls Idaho'' is a TV screen displaying the title of ``A
Tale of Two Cities.'' It's a fitting reference, because ``Twin
Falls'' is the best of movies, and it's the worst of movies.
</P>
<P>
   In its peak moments, it's one of the most aching cinematic
portraits of loneliness in recent memory, a film that inspires an
almost physically painful melancholy. At other times, it's one of
the more plodding movies in recent memory, and it inspires musings
about how it might be a TV movie dressed up in an art-film suit.
</P>
<P>
   The loneliness emanates from its three main characters:
Conjoined twins Francis and Blake Falls (played respectively by
director Michael Polish and his brother Mark; they also co-wrote
the screenplay), and Penny, the dime-store prostitute who arrives
as a birthday gift and stays on as the troubled brothers' lone
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer Michele Hicks' Penny has the fortune or misfortune _
depending on your point of view _ of looking like a young, goth
Demi Moore. She even has some of Moore's mannerisms, and she's
stuck with one of the most hackneyed roles in Hollywood: the hooker
with a heart of gold. But that doesn't keep her from being the key
to everything that works about ``Twin Falls.'' She gives a
performance of unusual compassion, her searching eyes convincing
you that although she's curious about the connected twins, it's not
because she sees them as a curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine this movie without Hicks, because it's hard
to imagine anyone else empathetic enough to make you believe that
she could dig into the psyche of the Falls brothers (who live in a
dingy hotel on Idaho Avenue, hence the movie's title). As played by
the Polish brothers, they're cut off, more innocent than alienated,
steeped in an almost palpable sadness. They're also morose; little
of the movie's rare humor comes from them. And although fused
together, their personalities are a little too indistinct: Blake,
the dominant one who provides sustenance for the ill Francis, is
only marginally more effusive than his pain-racked brother.
</P>
<P>
   During its first hour, the movie concentrates on the growing
relationship among the twins and Penny, who especially relates to
Blake. As long as the focus is there, everything's fine. But when
the movie strays to other characters, it leans on cheap comic or
dramatic touches.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as troublesome is a subplot about a woman (Lesley Ann
Warren) who may or may not be the mother who abandoned the brothers
at birth. Despite being stuck with a particularly unflattering
makeup job that gives her a sickly green pallor, Warren does what
she can to make this character sympathetic. But her character's
appearance, coupled with Francis' mysterious disease-of-the-week,
only underscores the soap-opera elements.
</P>
<P>
   If a director's job is to steer his film around such story
potholes, Michael Polish's first feature film is a misfire. But if
his job is to create and sustain a mood, Polish's debut is a
triumph; despite all the movie's flaws, it has the rare ability to
give you that heavy feeling in your chest, the one that comes from
having your heart moved and your breath taken away,
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``Twin Falls''' mood wins out over its flaws, a
victory of sadness over schmaltziness. Any two people are likely to
have radically varying reactions to it, some lauding its lyricism
while others lament its slow-paced self-consciousness. It's a movie
where difference makes all the difference _ but it's not as
different as it looks. Or as it thinks it is.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Twin Falls Idaho''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Michael Polish
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Michael Polish, Mark Polish, Michele Hicks
</P>
<P>
   Length: 105 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ profanity and adult subject matter
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
