<HEADLINE>
_A DRINK A DAY MAY BE A CARDIAC RISK REDUCER  
 _COUNTING SHEEP? TRY FOCUSING ON THE WOOLENS  
 _HUB STUDIES THROW LIGHT ON WOMEN'S DIET, HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 A drink a day may be a cardiac risk reducer
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The martini might not replace the apple in health adages, but in
a study this week, Boston researchers suggest that light to
moderate alcohol consumption lowers the risk of sudden cardiac
death for men.
</P>
<P>
   Several large-scale studies have found that people who have
about one glass of beer or wine or a mixed drink a day have a lower
overall risk of death and a lower risk of death from heart disease
and stroke. But other research has documented a higher risk of
breast cancer among women who have a drink a day.
</P>
<P>
   The new study in the journal Circulation, led by Dr. Christine
Albert of Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the largest to look
specifically at light to moderate alcohol consumption and sudden
cardiac death. Earlier studies had found that heavy drinking, or
more than five drinks a day, increased the risk of sudden cardiac
death.
</P>
<P>
   In their report, the Boston researchers found that the risk of
sudden cardiac death for men who drink between two and six drinks a
week was 60 to 79 percent lower. The report, which followed more
than 21,500 men in the Physicians Health Study for 12 years,
included 141 cases of sudden cardiac death.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden cardiac death is the most common cause of death in adults
younger than 65.
</P>
<P>
   If the mechanism behind how alcohol appears to reduce the risk
of sudden cardiac death can be unlocked, it ``could lead to the
development of preventive therapeutics that have the benefits of
alcohol without the accompanying risks,'' the authors write.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Counting sheep? Try focusing on the woolens
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You've tried sleeping pills, drinking a glass of warm milk, and
counting sheep, but none of them helps you get to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Try socks and mittens.
</P>
<P>
   In the current Nature, researchers from the Chronobiology and
Sleep Laboratory in Switzerland report on an experiment that shows
that warm feet and hands are the best physiological predictors that
sleep is coming on quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our findings provide further insight into the thermoregulatory
cascade of events that precede the initiation of sleep,'' write the
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, studying a sample of 18 healthy young men, took
measurements of heart rate, body and skin temperature, and other
factors. Sleepiness was rated every half hour.
</P>
<P>
   The physiological factor most able to predict whether sleep was
coming rapidly turned out to be the dilation of blood vessels in
the feet and the hands, which the researchers suggest can be
brought on by keeping the extremities warm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Hub studies throw light on women's diet, health
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women who want to decrease their risk of heart disease could eat
two to three servings of whole grains a day.
</P>
<P>
   People who have been diagnosed with breast cancer and want to
improve their chances of survival could eat a diet rich in protein
other than from red meat and not worry so much about the foods
being low in fat.
</P>
<P>
   Those are among the findings this week, in two different
publications, reported by the Nurses' Health Study based at Brigham
and Women's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   One study, reported Wednesday in the American Journal of
Clinical Nutrition, found that women who ate two to three daily
servings of whole-wheat bread, popcorn, oatmeal, or brown rice had
a 27 percent lower risk of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The other study, published Wednesday in the journal Cancer,
found that a diet rich in proteins from poultry and dairy products,
not red meat, appeared to lower the risk of death among breast
cancer patients by up to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found, contrary to common belief, that women who
ate a low-fat diet after being diagnosed with breast cancer did not
have a better survival rate. They also noted that eating more
vegetables seemed to help, but only for women whose cancer had not
spread.
</P>
<P>
   Some earlier studies found a higher breast cancer death rate
among women with the highest total fat intake. The authors of the
new study say their research looked specifically at a woman's diet
after she was diagnosed, not before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diet after diagnosis is very important to study, because for a
woman who has breast cancer, it is only diet after diagnosis that
can be changed,'' said Dr. Michelle Holmes of the Brigham, who led
the study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
