<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8525 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-CHOCOLATE-TEX     09-02 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHOCOLATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEXY FARCE ASSEMBLES THE RIGHT ELEMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's odd that men have always been perceived as the more
sex-obsessed gay gender, especially when the new lesbian comedy
``Better Than Chocolate'' has more blush-inducing moments than the
gay-themed ``Get Real,'' ``Edge of Seventeen,'' ``Trick'' and the
upcoming ``Steam'' combined.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Chocolate'' may hold the record for most ``marital
aids'' displayed in a feature film; maybe that'll wind up as a
category on the MTV Movie Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with a little provocative humor.
Lesbian sexuality has remained somewhat of an enigma to both
straight men (whose only exposure to it is within the ridiculously
unrealistic confines of pornographic films) and gay men (who'd
rather not think about it). And ``Better Than Chocolate'' director
Anne Wheeler manages to broach the subject with tenderness and
humor, but also an ample amount of heat.
</P>
<P>
   Karyn Dwyer is the soft-spoken, 19-year-old Maggie, a college
dropout who spends her days working at a lesbian bookstore and her
evenings performing at the local watering hole.
</P>
<P>
   When Maggie encounters an attractive, artistic drifter named Kim
(Christina Cox), the two become fast friends, heating up rapidly on
their way to something more.
</P>
<P>
   But their budding romance is put on hold when Maggie's brother,
Paul (Kevin Mundy), and her mother, Lila (Wendy Crewson), show up
unexpectedly after Lila's marriage hits the skids. Mom, of course,
is unaware of of the changes in her daughter's life, apart from her
desertion of higher education. But their new living arrangement
promises to be educational for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Paul starts dating the sexually adventurous Carla (Marya Delver)
while Lila is befriended by transgendered nightclub singer Judy
(Peter Outerbridge), who she thinks is a woman. Judy, meanwhile, is
in love with the androgynous Frances (Ann-Marie MacDonald),
Maggie's repressed boss.
</P>
<P>
   The title comes from Lila's nervous obsession with noshing
chocolates, a habit she's able to break only after finding a
suitable substitute. You'll have to learn what that is for
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler has assembled a terrific cast of unknowns, and everyone
is up to the challenge of pulling off this sexy farce _ Outerbridge
(last seen as an uptight FBI agent on ``Millennium'') is
particularly engaging. But the picture would benefit enormously
from tighter editing; as it stands, its almost two-hour running
time should push the patience of even its most devoted target
audience.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Better Than Chocolate''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Anne Wheeler
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Christina Cox, Karyn Dwyer
</P>
<P>
   Length: 103 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ nudity, sexual subject matter, erotic imagery,
profanity and violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
