<HEADLINE>
JFK HELPED SAVE HIS CREW MATES ON PT-109
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What were the names of the crew members who served with Lt.
John F. Kennedy on PT-109 when it was rammed by the Japanese ship?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.L.M., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: When PT-109 was broken in two by the Japanese destroyer
Amagiri on Aug. 2, 1943, Kennedy and 12 other crew members were
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Two crewmen, Andrew Kirksey and Harold Marney, were killed in
the collision. The survivors were Raymond Albert, Charles Harris,
William Johnston, John Maguire, Edgar Mauer, Patrick McMahon,
George Ross, Ray Starkey, Leonard Thom and Gerald Zinser.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 hours in the water, Kennedy and the other survivors
reached a small island three miles from the crash site. They later
swam to another island in search of food, and were rescued on Aug.
8 after encountering island natives who contacted a New Zealand
camp at Rendova.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who towed McMahon by swimming with the injured
crewman's life jacket strap in his teeth, was awarded the Navy and
Marine Corps Medal and the Purple Heart Medal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a Boxing Hall of Fame?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.D., Joshua, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: In 1989, the International Boxing Hall of Fame opened in
Canastota, N.Y., the hometown of world champions Carmen Basilio and
Billy Backus.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Boxing Writers Association and sport historians
vote new members into the hall, who are honored at a ceremony each
June.
</P>
<P>
   This year, six new inductees were in attendance: boxers Jimmy
Bivins, Khaosai Galaxy and Eusebio Pedroza; promoter Bob Arum;
matchmaker Mickey Duff; and press agent Irving Rudd. Eleven others
were recognized posthumously.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (315) 697-7095 or write to
International Boxing Hall of Fame, Box 425, Canastota, NY 13032.
The hall also has a Web site: www.ibhof.com
</P>
<P>
   CORRECTION: A reader in Wilkes Barre, Pa., noted an error in a
previous column about Geronimo. The circumstances of his surrender
were incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1886, Geronimo surrendered in Skeleton Canyon,
Ariz., with a small band of Apache. Eight years later, he arrived
at Fort Sill, Okla., as a prisoner of war with 300 others from his
tribe.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
