<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2TAKES-     09-02 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRACLES OF FAITH BLOOM IN THE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Who says miracles don't happen? Everytime a volunteer
shows up to weed a church garden, that's a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Though many church gardens have been designed and planted, often
financed by a congregant's gift in the name of a departed loved
one, the results are usually fleeting. Unlike, say, a memorial
stained glass window, a garden is the gift that keeps on costing,
either in terms of volunteer time for weeding and watering or in
money to hire maintenance crews. So the magnificent perennial beds
or the carefully labeled collection of plants that enjoy mention in
the Bible usually quietly vanished a few years after their proud
installation.
</P>
<P>
   Landscape architect Joe Hudak of Westwood has learned by
experience that so-called ``cast iron'' plants that need almost no
care are the best choice for most church landscapes. ``I find it
disappointing that so many of the gardens don't get the upkeep they
deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing this only makes me appreciative of those few church
gardens that manage to be both ambitious and well cared for. Each
one is, in its way, a miracle of faith. And each has a story. Not
about how the garden came to be built, but about who is keeping it
alive and why. Here are several such miracles in downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Church of the Advent
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gardening in the city ain't easy. Ask Diane Britton who fights
an ongoing battle at the Church of the Advent on Beacon Hill to
keep several small streetside landscapes healthy and serene despite
storms, weeds, litter, building renovation, and periodic work on
the pilings under the church.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, John, contributed much of the money for
garden construction in 1991 in memory of their son Peter who had
died the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a named space. The church doesn't do that. But on the
Sunday after it was planted, Father Mead came out with the whole
parish and blessed the garden,'' said Britton of the garden's
memorial overtones, quietly adding, ``A lot of people don't know.
But I know.''
</P>
<P>
   However, paying for the garden turned out to be only the first
babystep. The garden was soon flattened by trucks digging a well to
pump water into the foundational piers that are a chronic problem
for many historic Back Bay buildings constructed on fill. Then,
after many meetings, the garden was replanted. Then they had to
build a wheelchair ramp in 1997. Britton has now developed skill at
heeling in temporarily displaced shrubbery and then replanting it.
</P>
<P>
   When in 1995 the rector and his gardening wife moved away,
Britton inherited primary responsibility for the garden, under Kenn
Stephens, director of the Advent's Flower Arranging and Garden
Guild. This meant not only weeding but moving sprinklers around and
turning them on on her way to work each summer morning and then
calling the church so someone else would turn the water off.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer help always proved surprisingly hard to find, so
Britton, who lives near the church, discovered it was quicker to do
the weeding herself than to ``make the phone calls to coordinate a
work crew to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the garden has become an important part of the community
over the last decade and things have gotten easier. Now there's an
automatic irrigation system. And the church has started hiring
gardening help at key times of year ``so I don't have to spend my
whole life weeding. The garden is valued by the church now, and
it's in the budget, not just dependent on donations.''
</P>
<P>
   The shady nooks burst with color from April through June and
then recede into restful green the rest of the year. It is one of
the few public spaces on Beacon Hill, and Britton thinks it has
influenced more neighbors to beautify the fronts of their houses.
She should know. She's traded plants over the fence with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real challenge to urban gardening, but it's so
rewarding! Just see what's happening along Commonwealth Avenue and
Beacon Street! And it isn't like people are trying to outdo each
other. They're just trying to create proper city gardens. And I
think Mayor Menino has had a big effect. We've lived in the city 14
years and it just gets prettier and prettier.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to really intrepid people like Diane Britton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
St. Leonard's Church
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The roses of St. Leonard's Garden of Peace at the corner of
Prince and Hanover streets are to the eyes of this city what the
cannoli at Mike's Pastry are to its lips. And both are integral to
the North End's Italian identity.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how difficult it is to make cannoli, but St.
Leonard's has got to have the most labor-intensive church garden in
town, with 50 rosebushes and hundreds of annuals of cheerfully
mixed color and parentage surrounding still white statues of saints
and children. The statues are praying, but the flowers are dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and then there's Angelo DelPriore. He's neither praying nor
dancing. He's watering. He loves the garden but, well, feels a bit
put upon. ``I have to be there seven nights a week. I spend at
least 20 to 25 hours a week weeding and watering, pinching back the
annuals, and trimming the roses. I'm a CPA with a full-time job,
but I squeeze it in. I work in the area. Sometimes I go over for
lunch and pinch (the flowers) a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   A volunteer, or more accurately the volunteer, DelPriori spends
two hours a day hand-watering so the thousands of tourists who come
through don't get soaked by sprinklers. (Here's a man who does
things right, no matter what the personal cost.) ``I've had several
tourists from Texas and Tennessee, gardeners who said it was
incredible that one person takes care of this garden.''
</P>
<P>
   It was begun by one of the parish priests during the Vietnam War
25 years ago as a gesture toward returning veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Now one side of it is sinking because it was built over a cellar
hole that was not properly filled in. Talk about the vicissitudes
of urban gardening! If your foundation piers aren't drying out and
rotting, your garden is falling into a cellar hole.
</P>
<P>
   St. Leonard's wants to mount a fund-raising campaign to restore
the garden.
</P>
<P>
   I have no doubt that any congregation with the brio to plant a
church garden of annuals will raise all the money it needs. Annuals
are the most work of any type of gardening because they must be
constantly watered, fertilized, pinched, and dead-headed. But if
they are, they produce constant color. St. Leonard's blazes with
snapdragons, zinnias, and coleus. Annuals are also employed because
each fall the garden can be stripped of plants and the precious
open space used for a Christmas Nativity scene.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8532 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-02 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DID THE `AUTOMOBILIST' SAY TO THE FIDGETY HORSE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writing about cars, and loving cars, is a lot like writing about
baseball, or loving baseball.
</P>
<P>
   I look with a delightful sense of hope toward the future _ and
with all the changes electronic on the horizon, those changes will
compound like interest owed a loan shark; yet I am also, as
Fitzerald said of Gatsby, drawn inexorably to the past.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is why a new book by Will Anderson, a Maine writer,
caught my eye. The last book of his I read was called ``Was
Baseball Really Invented in Maine?'' and it was a fascinating
record of minor-league ball and major-league players with ties to
that state. Now comes Anderson with another book about _ you
guessed it _ cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Auto See Maine'' is a wonderful romp through one state's
cultural car history.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson chronicles auto dealers and their offerings, come and
gone, or still with us; he gives us great dry jokes infused with
Maine logic and humor, and news accounts that reflect the ascent of
this newfangled machine, the automobile, on the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   It is a book set in Maine, but it is a book that could have been
written in any state.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, advice given by a newspaper columnist on what an
``automobilist'' should do when encountering a horse: ``Stop the
vehicle and, if the horse is frightened, turn off the engine. If
there is any difficulty, the driver of the automobile should lead
the horse himself or have him led past the automobile.'' Keep a
human between the car and the beast, he continued, and if the horse
remains fidgety, say, ``Whoa.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news account from the Portland Daily Advertiser of December
1903, a meeting of the Brewer City Council is reported. The purpose
of the meeting was to discuss ``good roads,'' but our correspondent
noted ``after they had got at the topic they found that there were
no good roads to discuss, and so they changed the subject to bad
roads.''
</P>
<P>
   We learn that on Middle Street in Lewiston in 1905 you could buy
a Jackson, five-passenger Model C with perfect balance and perfect
alignment, sold under the slogan ``No sand too deep, No hills too
steep.'' Anybody seen a Jackson lately?
</P>
<P>
   We learn that in 1924 _ I see a trend here _ the Forest City
Filling Station in Portland installed an automobile vacuum cleaner
. . . useful in getting all the dust out of closed car
upholstery.'' Could the car wash be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   And finally, for those who want to reach out and touch a bit of
the old car culture, Anderson offers up tangible relics of that
past: diners and drive-in theatres.
</P>
<P>
   ``For diners, there's the Palace in Biddeford (Maine's oldest
diner, opened in 1927), the Deluxe in Rumford (in operation since
1928), the Miss Portland . . . and the Brunswick. There's also the
storied Moody's in Waldoboro and the Maine Diner in Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``For drive-in theatres, there's the Saco Drive-In (opened in
1939 and one of the oldest extant drive-ins in the world), the
Skowhegan, Prides Corner in Westbrook, the Bridgton, and, way
upstate, the Skylite, in Madawaska.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who besides baseball has written books about beer,
roadside delights, cafes, and old-time Maine, strikes a chord with
this book on autos, if only because its snappy recount of news and
humor, its use of old ads and photos, allows any who read it to be
drawn inexorably to the past. And surely, all auto enthusiasts
enjoy looking into the rear-view mirror on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Auto See Maine'' is available from Anderson &AMP; Sons'
Publishing Co., 34 Park St., Bath, Maine 04530.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John White, who has left this space, has not left the world of
automobiles, and he recently spent time chasing some of the steam
cars that made ascents up Mount Washington.
</P>
<P>
   White writes to us:
</P>
<P>
   It was the ultimate game of King 'O the Hill and the British
won, 3-2, scoring an automotive first in the process _ afather-son-in-law team driving two steam cars in succession to the
top of Mount Washington in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Aug. 13, Basil Craske of Norfolk, England, piloted
his Like-A-Mobile (a replica of a 1903 Locomobile) to the
6,288-foot summit in an hour and 10 minutes. He was accompanied by
his father-in-law, John Liming, also of Norfolk. After a brief
celebration, both descended in a modern car, and Liming, assisted
by Craske, drove his 1911 Stanley up the mountain in less than half
the time of the '03, finishing with an astonishing burst of speed
up the final stretch of 22-percent grade to the top. Liming built
both cars, incorporating original parts.
</P>
<P>
   In the interval between those ascents, Gerry Stoneman, of
Tiverton Devon, England, reached the peak in a 1922 Stanley _ three
of the six British-owned steamers shipped from the United Kingdom
for this event made it to the summit. Only two of 79 American-owned
steamers got to the top in the weeklong celebration of the
centennial of the first car up Mount Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Four years in the planning, the commemoration and weeklong steam
tour were organized by the Stanley Museum, Kingfield, Maine, with
major support from the Mount Washington Auto Road Co., owner of the
road to the summit. The event attracted 85 steamers _ mostly
Stanleys _ and 300 museum members from four continents.
</P>
<P>
   The British drivers spent about $27,000 of their own money, plus
about $7,500 put up by the Auto Road Co. and Audi, official car of
the road, to transport their steamers across the Atlantic for the
celebration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
