<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DVR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DVRS ARE BEING TOUTED AS A TV REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a, e and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most hot new companies insist their product is going to change
the world, but two California start-ups promising to revolutionize
the way people watch television are beginning to attract a lot of
believers.
</P>
<P>
   Their revolution, as measured by sales of so-called digital
video recorders, hasn't really begun yet. But the companies' goal
of using computer hard drives to give people greater control over
their TV viewing _ including instant replays, putting live TV on
hold, and recording shows all year long with one click of the
remote _ has shaken up the broadcasting world and spawned
soul-searching about the future of TV.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, some of the biggest names in the
entertainment and Internet world have showered millions of dollars
on the two companies selling DVRs, TiVo Inc. of Sunnyvale and
Replay Networks of Mountain View. WebTV, owned by Microsoft, is
expected to enter the market later this year in an alliance with
satellite broadcaster Dish Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's caught everyone in the industry by surprise,'' said Peg
Murphy, vice president of business development for NBC Interactive,
which has invested millions of dollars in both TiVo and Replay
Networks. ``It's one of the few interactive TV applications to come
along in the last few years that makes sense because it actually
makes watching TV easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The bugs are still being worked out of the technology, but there
is a growing buzz about how DVRs will allow consumers to escape the
straitjacket of network schedules and possibly avoid TV
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to make a complete change in the way people
watch TV,'' said Josh Bernoff, TV analyst at Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass. ``What you're seeing here is the beginning of an
enormous change in the way TV works.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a videocassette recorder, a digital video recorder records
and plays back TV shows, but without tapes or any complicated
programming. All you need to know is the name of the show; there's
no need to know when it's on or the channel. A couple of clicks
with the remote and it's done. You can direct the machine to record
the show every time it comes on. It even sets its own clock.
</P>
<P>
   The digital video recorder captures the incoming TV signal,
compresses it, and records it on a computer hard drive. The machine
plugs into a telephone jack and downloads up-to-date channel
lineups for the coming two weeks in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   DVR users can view a show from its beginning while it's
recording, unlike users of a videocassette recorder, who must wait
until a recording is done to start watching. Say you want to record
the ``Sopranos'' on HBO at 9 p.m. on Wednesday and watch it that
same night, but the children aren't put to bed until 9:30. Just
click on the ``Sopranos'' when the house is finally quiet and start
watching from the beginning while the DVR continues to record the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're not recording a show, the digital video recorder
is always recording some of whatever show is being watched. That
can come in handy. Say you're watching a live broadcast of a
baseball game and your mother calls. You can hit pause, take the
call, and later resume watching where you left off. Or you can hit
instant replay and watch Nomar Garciaparra make a play at shortstop
again. DVRs put the viewer in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The first reaction of most people is that a DVR is nothing more
than a souped-up, computerized VCR without the capability of
playing taped movies. Reviewers so far have liked the technology
but been turned off by the price.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $500 to $1,500, depending on the recording
capacity, which runs from eight to 30 hours using the poorest
recording quality. Recording capacity drops dramatically as the
quality of the recording _ or the amount of data recorded _ is
increased. TiVo and WebTV also have monthly subscription fees of
$9.95 and $24.95, respectively, although TiVo offers a lifetime
subscription for $199.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of US homes have VCRs, but the machines haven't
really changed the way people watch TV. Only a third of VCR users
tape a TV show at least once a week, and just under a third never
tape anything, according to a survey released earlier this year by
the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts think DVRs will change that and end up
changing TV in the process. They think DVRs will become portals to
television, much the way America Online, one of many TiVo
investors, has become a major access point for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of watching live TV, consumers may increasingly select
shows they want to watch days or weeks in advance and use their
DVRs to watch them whenever they want. The TiVo machine monitors
your viewing habits and records shows it thinks you might like.
ReplayTV allows users to customize their own networks around a
theme or a favorite actor.
</P>
<P>
   Bernoff of Forrester Research predicts DVRs will be the
fastest-growing consumer electronics product in history, with four
out of five homes having one within 10 years. The impact on TV will
be enormous, he says. ``Primetime'' could become increasingly
irrelevant as more shows get recorded for later viewing, while
middle-of-the-night time slots could become hot properties in an
environment where time-delay TV is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Bernoff's boldest prediction is that the millions of people who
will watch TV on a DVR will skip through the commercials, knocking
the economic pins out from under the broadcast networks. Certainly
DVRs make it easy: ReplayTV lets the user skip forward in 30-second
increments, while TiVo offers a high-speed fast forward. A decade
from now, Bernoff predicts, ad viewing will be cut in half, as
consumers decide it's more efficient to watch NBC's three-hour
Thursday night lineup in two hours and 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ent of Boston, who bought a TiVo DVR, says the ease of
recording has changed his viewing habits. He now records his
favorite shows and watches them whenever he wants, almost always
zapping through the ads. ``I'm sort of out of sync now with live
TV,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is convinced. Karen Agresti, senior vice
president and director of broadcasting at Hill, Holliday, Connors,
Cosmopulos, said the same gloom-and-doom network scenarios were
popular when VCRs came on the market. ``This is technically not a
new idea,'' she said. ``The majority of people still watch shows
when they air.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ryan, the head of Pro Media Inc., a Natick, Mass.
media-buying firm, says it will be hard to change entrenched
viewing habits. ``That's really not how people view TV,'' she said
of the DVR time-shifting philosophy. ``And, besides, some people
like to watch the commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy at NBC Interactive said the network continues to believe
programming will be ad-based, but she acknowledges it may not
revolve around 30- or 60-second spots five years from now. ``We
don't think this is going to be revolutionary overnight,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that media titans like NBC, CBS, Showtime, Walt Disney,
Time Warner, Liberty Media, Comcast Corp., and Cox Communications
are investing in TiVo and Replay Networks may have an impact on the
debate. Officials at TiVo and Replay Networks are downplaying their
machines' ad-zapping capabilities and stressing a willingness to
work with broadcasters and the advertising industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give viewers more control, but we're very sensitive
to the business issues of our partners,'' said Stacy Jolna, vice
president of programming and media partnerships at TiVo. ``There is
a happy medium there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Jolna says, the onus will be on advertisers to make
sure people continue to watch their ads. General Motors, for
example, is working with TiVo on targeting ads at specific TiVo
owners. In other words, GM might run an Oldsmobile ad during ``60
Minutes,'' but as TiVo users replay the show at a later time GM
might substitute ads that would be more appropriate for each user.
Families might see a minivan ad, while singles might see an ad for
a sports car.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone acknowledges that DVR technology and programming
is in its infancy. Recording time is limited, channel switching is
sluggish, and DVRs make an annoying, crackling computer sound
constantly. But improvements are expected. In less than two years,
Bernoff predicts that a machine with 24 hours of recording time
will cost less than $500. The machines themselves could disappear
as the technology is incorporated into cable TV set-top boxes and
satellite broadcast receivers, and coupled with on-screen Internet
access.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
