</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW'S NEW STATION WAGON INSPIRES CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when the station wagon was the minivan or the
SUV of American car culture. That time was in the 1950s, when the
big family wagon was a symbol of comfortable suburban life: haul
the kids to Little League games, haul the family on vacations.
</P>
<P>
   America was on the move and families were on the move _ in their
wagons.
</P>
<P>
   How things change. Today, minivans, SUVs, and four-door pickup
trucks, purchased with the idea of carrying family, gear, and
goods, rule. Yet the station wagon is making a subtle comeback, and
it is coming from unexpected quarters: foreign luxury car makers.
</P>
<P>
   While Taurus, Sable, and Saturn continue to crank out wagons in
what for them is a shrinking domestic market, BMW, Saab, Mercedes,
Volvo, and Audi all offer new wagons. Subaru has long been a solid
player at the lower end of this niche. BMW will add a 3 Series
wagon early next year to move toward the lower end of the market.
At the upper end, there are rumors that Jaguar has a wagon on the
drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   None of what's out there will haul the goods and passengers that
a big SUV or minivan will haul; these are more like the smaller
SUVS _ such as Toyota 4-Runner _ in their capacities.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of them is the BMW wagon, available in the 528i and 540i
models _ 6 and 8 cylinders respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days in the 528i _ five-speed manual transmission _ revealed
it to have more in common with luxury sports sedans than the
classic notion of a station wagon. Yet there was all that space
behind.
</P>
<P>
   It drives like a luxury sports sedan because, excepting the box
that is its rear end, that's what it is. It rides on typically
stiff and nimble BMW suspension: struts, coil springs, twin-tube
gas shocks, and antiroll bars up front; 4-link integral suspension
with coil springs, twin tube gas shocks, and antiroll bar in the
rear.
</P>
<P>
   The disc brakes, front and rear, are nearly a foot in diameter,
and when the aluminum calipers clamp onto them, the car comes to
sure, straight, and sudden stops.
</P>
<P>
   Dynamic stability sytems aid both in keeping traction just right
and in braking.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-cylinder aluminum block engine cranks out nearly 200
horsepower and makes the car most responsive as you work the
five-speed transmission with a moderate-throw, relatively stiff
shift lever.
</P>
<P>
   With much of my travel done on highways, the car got about 24
miles per gallon _ quite respectable given its powerful
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, this is a car that inspires confidence. Stomp the gas,
and a controlled rumble moves right up through the seats. This is a
tight car and a quiet car.
</P>
<P>
   The multifacted, stiff suspension means that the 528i provides
some moderate jarring on bumpy roads, yet the swap is that on
smoother, faster roads it is remarkably firm and free of
side-to-side lean when passing, and it clings to corners with
almost no body roll. It is so well-balanced, in fact, that it is
subtly fast, and at least twice it crept up to 90 miles per hour by
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Its traction-control system was effective, though a little
annoying in that it kicked in _ and chirped a warning _ far earlier
than I felt it needed to.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 528i is billed as a five-passenger car, when the
passengers are adults, it is really more suitable for just four.
Even three young children on the rear bench seat got antsy and
feeling crowded on a four-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that this wagon is a luxury beast abounds on the
inside: leather on the dash; leather trim on the doors; broad, firm
leather seats that adjust electrically and can be programmed to
remember who you are and how you like your seat set.
</P>
<P>
   Storage space is only adequate _ door bins are thin, a tiny
rolltop bin opens in the console between the front seats (I wonder
now what takes up all the space beneath the top of the console.)
</P>
<P>
   Typical of BMW, the gauges _ bathed at night in that wonderful
orange glow _ are simple but useful. Tachometer, speedometer, and
other gauges are clearly visible through the upper spokes of the
steering wheel. Four of the five windows that sit below these
gauges are dark, except when they flash a warning _ door open,
problems with lights _ while the fifth is an electronic font of
information that can be scrolled by using a button on a stem off
the steering column. It tells you, in sequence, mileage on the car,
mileage on a particular trip, outside temperature, average fuel
consumed, how many miles to go before fuel is gone, and average
speed for your trip.
</P>
<P>
   Buttons built into the steering wheel operate cellular phone,
radio, cruise control, and can switch air supply from outside to
recirculate.
</P>
<P>
   In the heat of day, or cold of night, zoned climate control lets
each front-seat passenger get as hot or cold as they want.
</P>
<P>
   The rear of the car is easily accessible through a lift-up
hatch. The flat floor makes loading and unloading easy (a nifty
roll-out floor that extends like a table is an intriguing option)
and cargo cover and luggage net keep loads contained.
</P>
<P>
   The rear seats fold down, and for two people on, say, a long
weekend of antiquing, this would be a comfortable, useful auto.
</P>
<P>
   If the load gets too heavy on the rear springs, those gas shocks
sense the load and pneumatic pressure is applied to bring the rear
end up to its normal height.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The finger-wheel operation of the dash vents that control the
flow of air.
</P>
<P>
   --The way the front seat rises as you move it forward with the
controls, the assumption being that if you need to be closer to the
pedals, you are probably also a bit shorter and could use the extra
boost.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The cup holders, which look like an afterthought and are
virtually useless. They emerge from the dash less than a half-inch
from the platform on which a drink rests _ and that means they hold
nothing effectively.
</P>
<P>
   --The rear-view mirrors _ way too small. Coming down an entrance
ramp, I found myself hunching my face forward of the steering wheel
to find traffic approaching from behind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NUMBERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $40,700 &QL; 
Price as tested: $45,000 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 193 hp/ 206 lbs.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 111.4 inches/ 189.2 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 70.9 inches/ 56.7 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 3781 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8536 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-02 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMEAR VICTIM FIGHTS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF JACOBY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why does Jack E. White insist on using his pulpit in Time
magazine to squirt racial poison into the nation's public
discourse? When he chooses to, he can write columns that are
thoughtful and humane; a piece he did earlier this year on Jesse
Jackson's penchant for negotiating with dictators was a fine and
sensitive piece of work.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to politics, White pens some of the ugliest
commentary around. A favorite brand of venom is to accuse political
conservatives of being racists. Mind you, he never offers actual
evidence that they are racists; it is enough for him that they are
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when the New Liberty Baptist Church in Alabama was torched
in 1996, White wrote this:
</P>
<P>
   ``All the conservative Republicans from Newt Gingrich to Pete
Wilson . . . should come stand in the charred ruins . . . and
wonder if their coded phrases encouraged the arsonists.'' Burning
churches? Blame the GOP. ``There is already enough evidence to
indict the cynical conservatives who build their political careers,
George Wallace-style, on a foundation of race-baiting. They may not
start fires, but they fan the flames.''
</P>
<P>
   White has suggested that Clarence Thomas is ``an intellectual
slave'' who is ``lavishly rewarded for serving . . . conservative
white Republicans.'' Newt Gingrich is ``one scary white man . . .
one very scary white man.'' He has mocked ``Newt the slasher, Bill
the waffler, and Jesse (Helms) the crank'' as ``white men who make
black people uneasy.'' In February, he wrote that the GOP
resurgence after 1964 was built on ``opposition to civil rights.''
Republicans might be ``too genteel for a sheet-wearing bigot like
David Duke but (are) all too willing to embrace bigotry if it's
dressed in a suit and tie.''
</P>
<P>
   White and Time get away with this stuff because the victims of
these smears never fight back. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   In Time's Aug. 30 edition, White wrote about David Horowitz, a
noted conservative activist. In the '60s, Horowitz was a militant
radical; famously, he later had second thoughts and moved to the
political right. A prolific writer, Horowitz has dissected the
cruel and antidemocratic instincts of ``progressives'' in several
riveting books, among them ``Destructive Generation'' and ``The
Politics of Bad Faith.'' He operates a lively Web site, Front Page,
and runs (with Peter Collier) the Center for the Study of Popular
Culture, which publishes Heterodoxy, a journal on political
correctness.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Horowitz also finds the time to generate a fortnightly
column for the liberal Web magazine Salon. On Aug. 16, he wrote
about the NAACP's plans to sue gun manufacturers on the grounds
that firearms are a leading cause of death among young black men,
who are nearly five times as likely to die of bullet wounds as
young white men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I alone,'' Horowitz wondered, ``in thinking this a
pathetic, absurd, and almost hilarious demonstration of political
desperation by the civil-rights establishment?''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to lacerate the leftist mindset that holds that
``there cannot be a wound the black community inflicts on itself
that is not ultimately the responsibility of malicious whites.'' If
nearly half the prison population is black, Horowitz wrote, ``that
cannot be allowed to suggest that the black community have a
problem when it comes to raising its children as law-abiding. . . .
Oh, no. Such a statistic can only be explained by the racism of
(the) criminal justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a blunt and angry column. Perhaps Horowitz's ire was
fueled by his lifelong passion for civil rights, which began 51
years ago at a demonstration against job discrimination. Perhaps it
was fueled by the work he has done for charities that concentrate
on at-risk minority kids _ Operation Hope, School on Wheels,
Angel's Flight. Perhaps it was fueled by the same commitment that
led him to invite five leading black figures to a conservative
conclave, ``to tell Republicans,'' as he put it, ``that they were
not doing enough for African-Americans and other minorities.''
Perhaps it was fueled by his love for his black daughter-in-law and
his three granddaughters.
</P>
<P>
   Well, White read the column and came to a different conclusion.
His usual conclusion. The column ``reminded'' him that ``blatant
bigotry is alive and well'' on the Internet, even at liberal
Webzines. He pronounced Horowitz guilty of a ``blanket assault''
that outdid ``the antiblack rantings'' of other conservatives.
Worst of all was the headline: ``A Real, Live Bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   White's accusation is scurrilous. But the damage such a libel
can wreak is massive. ``To be labeled a `bigot,' particularly in
the wake of Buford Furrow, is a verbal death sentence,'' Horowitz
says. ``That column is a calculated attempt to prevent anyone from
ever again listening to what I have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not taking it passively. He fired off a blistering letter
to Time, demanding an apology. He posted an appeal for support and
his letter to Time _ on Front Page (www.frontpagemag.com). He is
talking to lawyers about a libel suit. In short, he is making a
stink. If more conservatives did that when they are slandered as
racists and bigots, maybe the slanders would stop.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Horowitz has no intention of censoring himself to
please the Jack E. Whites of the world. His forthcoming book, due
in November, is titled ``Hating Whitey and Other Professive
Causes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jeff Jacoby is a Globe columnist; his e-mail address is
jacoby(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
