<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8538 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-02 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING THE DOOR TO HAPPINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every time you follow your heart, you open a door. Every door
you open reveals a world you never dreamed existed.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe me, listen to this.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, my friend John Ruggiero received a sport kite as a
gift. He set out for Nahant Beach, and before he knew it, the other
kite fliers were sharing everything they knew about putting a kite
through its tricks, and he was hooked. That's not the end of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   It's just the turning of the doorknob.
</P>
<P>
   John gave a sermon on flying kites at our Unitarian-Universalist
Church. He described the as-yet-unsuspected world he entered when
he sent that first tethered creature up into the sky. This is what
he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never much of a dancer. I'm about as graceful on my feet
as a water buffalo. Flying that dual-line kite was like dancing,
but no one was looking at me. They were watching my kite. People
would stop by while I was flying my kite and walk away smiling. I
smiled a lot too. I have flown kites during snowstorms, and I
wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a video of a professional kite flier flying a kite in a
gym. There were no fans and no wind. It looked like fun, so I
decided to try to fly a kite indoors to music. It took most of the
day to learn to keep the kite in the air for 45 seconds. The kite,
which is very light in weight, is pretty much flown by thought
alone. I let my feelings just flow up the lines and watch, as
amazed as the audience, as the kite interprets the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flew a kite inside the Newport, R.I., Marriott lobby to Sara
McLachlan's song `Angel,' and when the crowd applauded, I had tears
in my eyes. I didn't want the song to end. Indoor flying removes
the limits of the wind and makes the kite a part of you. I could
never imagine myself dancing in front of people, but flying a kite
indoors lets me soar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also ride a kite-powered buggy, which is a three-wheeled
stainless steel cart that you steer with your feet. I've had some
of my most spiritual experiences while on a buggy. Sometimes birds
follow the kite, and I admire the ease with which they fly.
Sometimes there is no one around at Nahant Beach and the sounds of
the ocean are all I hear. Sometimes I ride at night and watch my
kite cruise the stars while I listen to the music of the sea. One
night, in Wildwood, N.J., I looked down to see the green glow of
phosphorus trailing my wheels. I felt like I was riding a comet. In
the desert, we push 50 miles an hour on these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some real danger involved. People like me are just
good enough to be dangerous. I'm learning tricks like riding on two
wheels, riding backward, and spinning. After destroying four
bicycle helmets, I wear a kayaking helmet that is designed for
multiple impacts. I guess I sometimes feel a little too close to
God on a buggy.''
</P>
<P>
   John travels on business, but hardly ever needs to buy dinner.
Instead, he contacts other kite fliers through the Internet and
accepts their invitations to eat with them and fly kites together _
in British Columbia, Belgium, and throughout the United States.
He's come to the conclusion that the best people in the world are
the ones at the end of the strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does this insanity qualify as a spiritual experience?'' he
asks. ``There is a vast community of people who care deeply for one
another. We are dependent on the blending of earth, air, and water,
along with the fires of our passion and the sun. We help one
another and work for charity. We find peace and tranquillity in the
harmony of the lines singing in the wind. We play. We dance for the
joy of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything I've done has made me feel more for those around
me, it is kite flying. It has opened my eyes to the beauty of the
beach, the open field, and the desert. I've learned to respect
people for their skills and learn from them. I've found unqualified
support and friendship. After a while, spending time with the
people at the beach became as important to me as flying the kites.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a Chinese tradition of a flying kite representing the
evil spirits in your life. You cut the lines and the evil spirits
float away. At the end of the day, I can take all the evil spirits
from disease, work, and frustration and, like the Chinese, make
them fly away while my kite dances in the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   For John, a passion for kites was the key that opened the door
to a new kind of freedom in his life. It brought him noncompetitive
friendships with other men and women and taught him a new way of
communing with nature. I believe that an infinite number of keys
open an infinite number of doors to an infinite number of fully
elaborated, life-giving, mind-blowing realities.
</P>
<P>
   This is the secret of happiness: Just choose one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
