<HEADLINE>
WE HAVE SEEN THE FUTURE AND IT IS . . . RIPPLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What one item would you like to have on hand if you were
stranded on a desert island? Water? Food? Matches? A knife? Beer? A
cell phone? A solar-powered TV?
</P>
<P>
   If you are like 49 percent of people recently surveyed by the
Kimberly-Clark Corp., the one thing you couldn't survive without on
a desert island is toilet paper.
</P>
<P>
   I learned this from a press release sent along to promote a new
feature of Kleenex Cottonelle toilet paper. Cushy Ripples have been
added. That's right. Cushy Ripples, designed with a ``patented
technology'' to make you feel . . . special. According to the press
release, Cottonelle with Cushy Ripples is _ trumpet flourish,
please _ ``The Toilet Paper of the 21st Century.''
</P>
<P>
   The relase continues, ``We can only imagine what the next 100
years holds in store for toilet paper. Just like our grandparents
and great-grandparents probably never would have pictured toilet
paper as it is  &UR; today &LR; , it's hard to envision what it will be like
in the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people worry about the Y2K problem, others worry about the
future of toilet paper. And which is more important, really?
Kimberly-Clark asked those surveyed if they thought toilet paper
would change in the next 100 years. Only one-third said they
believed it would change ``very little.'' What about the other
two-thirds, the toilet paper visionaries? What did they foresee?
Virtual toilet paper? Diagnostic toilet paper? Interactive toilet
paper? Shouldn't we be told?
</P>
<P>
   The survey also revealed that we take toilet paper for granted.
It topped the list of ``small but important conveniences of the
20th century that most people take for granted but can't live
without,'' coming in ahead of the zipper, frozen foods, the paper
clip, and hair spray.
</P>
<P>
   Hair spray? People can't live without hair spray? Where did they
conduct this survey? Dallas?
</P>
<P>
   But back to the subject at hand. We may take toilet paper for
granted, but it is never far from our thoughts. On another page of
the press release, under the heading ``Toilet Paper Tidbits,'' is
the following fascinating factoid: ``Running out of toilet paper is
one of the biggest concerns in American households. The average
family has eight rolls in reserve to make sure there are no
emergencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Only eight rolls? I never feel secure unless I have a stash of
at least 20, and I've never thought of myself as above average,
except maybe when it comes to changing rolls of toilet paper. It
used to annoy me that I was the only person in my house capable of
finding and installing a new roll of toilet paper. Now, after
reading this press release, it gives me a strange feeling of power.
</P>
<P>
   Under the heading ``The History of Toilet Paper Rolls Into the
21st Century,'' the press release provides a capsule chronology of
toilet tissue evolution. In prehistoric times, leaves and sticks
served the purpose, although geography affected the material of
choice, to wit, ``Mussel shells were popular in coastal regions,
and people who lived in tropical climates probably used coconut
shells.''
</P>
<P>
   You can well imagine how those folks would have appreciated a
few Cushy Ripples.
</P>
<P>
   The brief history skips forward to the Renaissance, when
``royalty were known to have used wool or lace,'' then on to
Colonial America, when ``corn cobs and newspaper were among the top
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Colonial women worry about running out of corn cobs?
Probably. We must be grateful to be alive on the cusp of the
millennium, at the dawn of a New Age of toilet paper technology.
Who knows what the future will bring? Thanks, Kimberly-Clark, for
sharing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White's e-mail address is white(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
