<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK-TO-SCHOOL BLUES SHOULD PASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If your child has nothing to say when she comes home from the
first day of school, if she's so tired she wants to lie down, of
all things, it's not because they ran her ragged in phys ed. She's
emotionally exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Any child starting a new year typically sets off on the first
morning feeling grown up to be in a new grade and excited to see
friends. She's also likely worried about any number of things, from
whom she'll sit next to to how strict the teacher will be.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, the first day goes well enough; maybe the second
one does, too. But the honeymoon has to end sometime, typically by
the fifth day. That's when exhilaration turns to apprehension: Back
to school isn't just for one day or one week, (itals)it's for nine
whole long months.(unitals) It isn't just for fun, it's tests and
homework and projects and friends who aren't friends after all and
(itals)what if I can't do the work?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   In the first two weeks of school, worries like these are normal,
says child psychologist Gil Noam; after all, kids are rusty from a
summer of non-academics, and it's hard to settle back into school
routines. He tells parents to expect that most children, including
those in upper elementary and middle-school grades, will exhibit
some out-of-the-ordinary behavior during these weeks, from
aggression to regression.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, how out of the ordinary does it have to be for
us to do something about it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it happen once or twice and then diminish, or does it
become more frequent, more intense?'' asks Noam, a professor at the
Harvard Graduate School of Education. He considers the first two
weeks a wait-and-see period, when we need to be supportive, not
panicky. ``By the end of Week 2, if it starts to wane, it was a
transitional blip. Let it go,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Week 3 watershed
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Week 3, however, anything not tapering off deserves
attention; by Week 4, action. Before we can do anything, however,
we need to know that something's wrong. Unfortunately, children
don't always know and can't always tell us what's troubling them.
We need to look instead at their behavior:
</P>
<P>
   --Physiological complaints. With children under 8, anxiety tends
to manifest itself physically, says developmental psychologist Amy
Susman-Stillman, coordinator of the Children, Youth and Family
Consortium at the University of Minnesota. Look for anything from
headaches and stomachaches to not eating or sleeping well, or any
other complaint that is not typical of this child and intensifies
over time. Sympathy is appropriate, but in the absence of a fever
or other serious symptoms, send him to school anyway, lest you feed
into school phobia.
</P>
<P>
   --Regression. Thumb-sucking, bed-wetting, nail-biting, and
crying are also common in early elementary ages. With a fourth
grader or older, you may see cranky behavior that reminds you of a
temper tantrum, excessive dawdling before school, extreme
irritability after school, and sleep difficulty. ``You may even
notice that he's frequently tearing up, or maybe he leaves the room
so you don't see him cry,'' says Ann E. LaForge, author of ``What
Really Happens in School'' (Hyperion).
</P>
<P>
   Regression tends to pass within weeks. Assume this is a symptom
of anxiety and don't make a big deal out of the behavior; that
obscures the real issue. ``Set appropriate limits around
inappropriate behavior,'' says LaForge, ``but go gentler on
discipline: `You seem really out of sorts. Why don't you take some
time to think about what will help you feel better?' ''
</P>
<P>
   --Sibling squabbles. Children of all ages tend to take their
frustrations about school out on siblings, says pediatric and
family psychologist Peter Goldenthal. If fights increase from one
or two a day to five or six; if they are not just about one
specific thing (``He's teasing me about my hair again!'') but about
anything and everything, including issues that a week ago wouldn't
have gotten any reaction; and if you need to intervene all the
time, that's likely what's happening. What the squabbles look like
can tell you a lot. ``If he picks on one sibling in particular
every time he sits down to read or do his homework _ `You're
turning into a nerd!' _ he could be anxious about some aspect of
his own academic achievement,'' says Goldenthal. He is the author
of ``Beyond Sibling Rivalry'' (Henry Holt).
</P>
<P>
   --Accelerated aggression. You may not see this firsthand, but
you may hear about it, either via a note from the teacher (somewhat
unusual this early in the year), or indirectly from the child: His
shirt is torn not once but two or three times because he ``got into
a fight'' (not his fault); he talks about school but not about the
work or the teacher; homework is ``stupid,'' school is ``boring'';
friends don't call to play. If you were in the classroom, you'd see
him picking a fight as class breaks into study groups or during a
particular subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a teacher at the start of a year, this looks like
defiance,'' says Susman-Stillman. Her research shows something
else, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aggression often is a diversionary tactic,'' she says.
``There's something he doesn't feel competent about, so he acts up
to take attention away from the fact that he can't do it.'' In the
first few weeks and especially if there's no history of aggression
or it's more intense than usual, she suggests translating what's
going on: `` `I don't know how to do this work and I don't know how
to tell you that I don't know how.' ''
</P>
<P>
   --Withdrawn behavior. This is the trickiest clue, especially in
a preteen who typically wants more privacy. ``Just because she does
her homework in her room and not at the kitchen table doesn't mean
she's trying to hide that she can't do the work,'' says
Susman-Stillman. But it could be, if she is also less involved with
friends, uncharacteristically unenthusiastic about school, looking
for other ways to be alone, and easily upset.
</P>
<P>
   When young children withdraw, it's frequently because something
scares them, like a bully on the bus. ``They don't complain because
they're afraid of getting into trouble, so they shut down,'' says
LaForge.
</P>
<P>
   --Relational aggression. The fourth- to seventh-grade girl who
seems to be purposefully mean so that friendships are in turmoil
may be struggling socially, academically, or both: If she feels out
of it socially, she typically can't concentrate on the work. But,
says Susman-Stillman, ``She doesn't realize what she's doing. She's
upset and acting on it without knowing it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Time for action
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When any of the above symptoms stretch into Week 3 or 4, it's
time to take action. With a first- to third-grader, the strategy
Susman-Stillman prefers is to tell a story about your child, but in
the third person: `` `There was once a first grader who came home
from school every day feeling sad and mopey and picking fights with
her sister. But when her mother asked what was wrong, she just
didn't know.' What advice would you give that mother?'' LaForge
tells parents to be supportive _ ``It seems like you're feeling
lonely this year, without Jennifer in your class. Is there anyone
you sort of like and want to invite over?'' _ but not to overreact:
``It makes me so angry that you and Jennifer aren't together!''
</P>
<P>
   With an older child, Goldenthal recommends ``nurturant
confrontation'': ``Let him know you sense something is wrong: `I
love you, you're a great kid, but the way you're behaving just
isn't you. What's going on?' ''
</P>
<P>
   That will get some children to open up but prompt others to tell
you to leave them alone. Now comes the confrontational part, says
Goldenthal: `` `If you tell me, `You're right, Dad, but I don't
want to talk now,' that's fine, I can wait. But I can tell you're
upset, and it's not fair to claim privacy and act this way. I love
you. I'm not going to give up, because maybe, just maybe, I can
help you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the behavior, Susman-Stillman and others urge
parents to call or send a teacher a note in Week 3 or 4: ``Just
want to check in and see if John is getting off on the right
foot.'' Do this even if your child is adjusting well. ``It tells
the teacher you care, and that's important,'' says LaForge.
</P>
<P>
   Noam urges: ``Don't wait for a crisis,'' and don't assume a
teacher will come to you this early in the year, even if he wonders
about something. More likely, he'll wait for the conference, which
means your child could suffer for months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A family task
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One way to head off problems before they begin is to make it
clear as school starts that there's a transition period not just
for each child but for the whole family. ``The more you approach it
as a family task, the less alone a child feels and the more willing
he is to communicate,'' says Noam.
</P>
<P>
   Planning a special family dinner for the first night of school,
for instance, or celebrating the end of the first week are ways not
only to give a child something to look forward to but also to build
in a structure for talking about school.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --By the fourth week, difficulty doing homework that goes beyond
the usual complaining can signal learning issues. Try some
adjustments _ modify the homework routine to break it up into
smaller pieces; find out from the teacher how long she expects
homework to take; see if he understands instructions _ and talk to
the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   --When a child doesn't want to go to school, be clear that is
not an option but also let him know you will work with him to solve
any problem. Let the teacher know he doesn't want to go.
</P>
<P>
   --Hold off on starting extracurricular activities until the
second month.
</P>
<P>
   --Feeling disorganized prevents a child from functioning well.
Does he have systems to deal with papers and assignments?
</P>
<P>
   --In middle school, self-esteem can plummet in the first weeks.
Take any sign of unhappiness even more seriously than you would
have in elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended reading: ``Creating Ceremonies:
Innovative Ways to Meet Adoption Challenges'' by Cheryl A.
Lieberman and Rhea K. Bufferd (Zeig, Tucker &AMP; Co, Phoenix).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz is author of ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell). She
welcomes letters and comments and can be reached via e-mail at
meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
