<HEADLINE>
A DASH OF SEASONING CAN BRING OUT THE REAL TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Seasoning is everything. With little effort it
can take a dish from ho-hum to holy cow. It's just a matter of
knowing which seasonings work with which foods. That takes practice
and experience. Here are a few combinations to help you get
started:
</P>
<P>
   _ To jazz up a pot of corned beef and cabbage, add red pepper
flakes to pot before cooking.
</P>
<P>
   _ To give beef chili intensity, tie a few cloves and a bay leaf
into a cheesecloth bag and add to the pot before simmering.
</P>
<P>
   _ To add a depth of flavor to chocolate sauces, add a dash of
nutmeg.
</P>
<P>
   _ To bring out the sweetness of red bell peppers, add a bit of
kosher salt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add fresh chopped parsley to fillings in lasagna, ravioli and
manicotti to bring out the flavors of the cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Toss finely chopped fresh parsley or salt and pepper on green
salad to intensify the flavors of the vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   _ For fancy French toast, add vanilla extract and cinnamon to
the egg wash.
</P>
<P>
   _ For a little zip, add a dash of cayenne pepper to the flour
when frying chicken or fish.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add instant espresso powder to chocolate cakes or cookies to
give them an edge of coffee flavor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make meringues with brown sugar instead of white for a
toastier flavor.
</P>
</TEXT>
