<HEADER>
A8545 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-SUMMER-SQUASH-HNS &LR;      09-02 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-SQUASH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUASH IS NOW A YEAR-ROUND TREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ED: With STORING-SQUASH.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Somehow along the way, summer and winter became
interchangeable. At least, they did if you determine the seasons by
the kind of squash you eat.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be in summer you ate zucchini, yellow crookneck
squash and the UFO-shaped pattypan squash. In winter, you ate acorn
squash and butternut squash. In the fall you ate potatoes and in
the spring you ate asparagus, you didn't eat squash.
</P>
<P>
   These days, you can buy acorn squash in August and zucchini in
January. Confusing, only if you're very strict about eating with
the seasons. Otherwise, you'll find having summer squash available
all year just widens your choices of dishes to serve.
</P>
<P>
   As vegetables go, squash is one of the easiest to prepare. They
don't require peeling, like potatoes can, or stringing like beans.
</P>
<P>
   Winter squashes, the ones that have hard rinds and cavities
filled with large seeds inside, can simply be halved, seeded and
baked to a glorious tenderness. To help retain moisture during
cooking, bake the squash halves cut side down. Once tender, you can
turn the squash over, brush the cut areas with butter and sprinkle
with brown sugar and cinnamon. Continue baking just until the sugar
has formed a glaze and serve in bowls with the pan juices.
</P>
<P>
   Summer squashes usually have thin skins and the seeds are small
enough to cook and eat. Perhaps the easiest way to prepare any type
of summer squash is to slice it and grill the pieces over a hot
fire. Drizzle the cooked slices with olive oil and sprinkle with
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Squashes of either season can be seeded and stuffed such as in
the following recipe for Blue Cheese Pattypans. The trick with
these recipes is to partially cook the squash before stuffing so
you're not biting into hunks of raw vegetable when you get to the
middle of the squash. That's the thing about squash, it's not very
tasty if it hasn't been cooked through.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, here are a few recipes for cooking squash. No
matter what time of year it is.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLUE CHEESE PATTYPANS
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   Pattypans are a round, saucer-shaped summer squash variety. They
are sometimes available at farm stands and farmers markets. If
unavailable, substitute two zucchini, cutting them in half before
baking.
</P>
<P>
   4 large pattypan squash
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Italian-seasoned bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup crumbled blue cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Wash squash and cut off tops. In a
large casserole, bake squash 30-45 minutes or until slightly
softened. Meanwhile, cook bacon, drain and crumble. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Remove squash from oven and let cool enough to handle. Scoop out
seeds and meat inside of squash, leaving a 1/2-inch thick shell.
Place scooped meat into a bowl and combine with bacon, bread crumbs
and blue cheese. Season the squash shells with salt and pepper.
Stuff shells with cheese mixture. Return to oven and back 10 to 15
minutes more until squash is tender and stuffing is browned.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GLAZED ACORN SQUASH RINGS
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1 large acorn squash (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons grated lemon rind
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Orange slices
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Cut squash into 3/4-inch slices.
Remove seeds. Place in a greased 13-by-9-2-inch baking dish. Bake
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan, combine juice, sugar, syrup, butter, lemon rind
and salt. Bring to a boil and simmer 5 minutes. Pour mixture over
squash. Bake uncovered for another 15 to 20 minutes, basting as
needed. Garnish with orange slices.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Butternut squash may be substituted if desired.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``The Albany Collection: Treasures and Treasured
Recipes'' by the Women's Council of the Albany Institute of History
&AMP; Art
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RATATOUILLE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 10 servings)
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup red or green bell peppers, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 summer squash, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 zucchini, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 small eggplant, cubed
</P>
<P>
   1 (28-ounce) can plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Salt Bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   Saute garlic and onion in olive oil in a medium-large casserole.
Add peppers, summer squash, zucchini, eggplant, tomatoes, salt, bay
leaf and basil. Cover and simmer until vegetables are tender, 15 to
20 minutes. Remove bay leaf before serving.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from the ``Eater's Choice Low-Fat Cookbook'' by Dr.
Ron Goor and Nancy Goor (Houghton Mifflin, 1999)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
