<HEADER>
A8546 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-BUGS-BOS &LR;      09-02 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-BUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE OF BUGS AND VINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beware of birdseed!
</P>
<P>
   We all like to feed our little feathered friends, so we buy good
things for them to eat, like sunflower seeds, and niger and peanut
hearts and millet. Birds are smart and they soon figure out which
hand feeds them, so they cheer us with their chirping and
fluttering of wings to keep our rapt attention, and of course our
outstretched hand.
</P>
<P>
   But beware! Birdseed can carry the eggs of meal moths. In hot
weather these varmints hatch, eat starch, then pupate and turn into
small tan moths with black markings. You can tell if you have them
by the telltale sticky webs in seeds or crumbs or flour.
</P>
<P>
   Then they fly into your kitchen cabinets in search of places in
which to lay another generation of eggs. Once inside the cabinets,
you've had it, for they are almost impossible to get rid of. You
have to throw out all your food boxes, clean the cabinets, and
start over.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I know. Chopped sunflower hearts were my undoing. I use
sunflower hearts, because, according to my bird chart, everything
except hummingbirds eats them.
</P>
<P>
   During the heat wave of June we kept seeing all these moths, and
it took a while to identify the source _ two bags of sunflower
hearts. There were larvae (small, tan) pupating in picture frames,
in envelope flaps, where the wall meets the ceiling. And every few
days more moths would appear.
</P>
<P>
   They are slow and easy to swat, but it's the ones you don't see
that do the damage. I put bags of bread crumbs as bait near the
birdseed corner for them to lay their eggs in, changing them every
two weeks since their life cycle is about 30 days. I tried spraying
those I saw flying, but they never dropped dead; they just hid in
dark places.
</P>
<P>
   But they found the food cabinets and were even in the toaster.
So a long-needed cleaning is now in progress. The moral: If you
must feed the birds, store the birdseed in the garage in an
air-tight jar.
</P>
<P>
   While on the subject of bird feed, don't put it on the ground
because it can attract raccoons and other carriers of dreaded
rabies. Also, in bear country, set feeders away from the house. If
the bears find them, it's prudent to stop putting out feed. Bears
are large, dangerous animals, not cuddly teddies. Their population
has become quite large, and since they are protected, they do not
fear humans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beware of vines as ground cover.
</P>
<P>
   Think carefully when choosing a ground cover. If you have bare
ground but don't want more lawn (and the high maintenance),
evergreen ground covers are very good.
</P>
<P>
   They spread slowly, while neat reddish bark mulch serves as the
lady-in-waiting. These plants are not cheap, and they don't provide
instant landscaping, but they're a good long-term investment, not
to mention an attractive design element.
</P>
<P>
   But problems arise when climbing vines, such as ivy and euonymus
are planted as ground covers, because when they finally become
established, they begin to climb. They climb on everything, trees,
houses, rocks, mulch piles, and in the woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   Then begins the time-consuming task of regularly pulling them
off everything.
</P>
<P>
   This problem came home to roost here as I tried to remove a
euonymus vine out of my fine, beautiful myrtle. When I first
designed the garden, I thought a nice creeping vine of variegated
euonymus up one tree would be interesting. A big mistake! For lo
these many years I have regularly been pulling it out.
</P>
<P>
   This time, I decided to eradicate it. I started and yanked. Long
fat-rooted tendrils had spread everywhere under the myrtle, far and
wide. The more I pulled, the more there seemed to be. I filled a
large garbage can with rooted sections. To buy just one of these
choice plants would cost $4 or $5. Yet I was throwing out a hundred
that had become invasive weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Now ivy and euonymus are both fine plants, if kept in bounds
with frequent pruning. However, without regular maintenance, these
vigorous non-natives tend to spread into the countryside, where
they smother our native plants. And as they climb trees, they
produce seeds, which birds spread even farther.
</P>
<P>
   One can avoid this by choosing ground covers that do not vine
and climb. One of the best is myrtle. With shiny, delicate
evergreen leaves and blue spring flowers, in the shade it remains
an elegant plant that can cover large areas. Evergreen pachysandra
is useful for shady areas as is the ever reliable (though
deciduous) hosta. Ajuga tolerates both sun and shade, while
creeping juniper needs a sunny location.
</P>
<P>
   As this information age comes of age, the gardeners of old who
did maintenance have become almost nonexistent or prohibitively
expensive, which means that more and more we have to do it
ourselves. So when making landscaping decisions these days,
consider future maintenance, and beware the vining ground covers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ruth S. Foster has been a landscape consultant in the Boston area
for many years and has written numerous articles on gardening in
New England.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
