<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORING-SQUASH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUASH: FRESH FOR THE EATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Practices for buying and storing squash vary
depending on which season of vegetables you are dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few tips from ``Vegetables'' by James Peterson
(William Morrow, 1998):
</P>
<P>
   _ Winter squash such as acorn, butternut, buttercup, hubbard and
delicata is actually picked in the fall and stored through the cold
months. Choose squash without any soft spots, which indicate that
the vegetable may have been improperly stored.
</P>
<P>
   Winter squash will keep for up to a week in a paper bag in the
refrigerator; for several weeks in a cool (50-degree), airy place;
and for up to three months if hung in a net bag that will allow air
to circulate. Do not store in plastic bags, as they tap moisture
and may encourage rot.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need four (1-pound) winter squash or the equivalent to
feed four people.
</P>
<P>
   _ Summer squash such as pattypan, zucchini and yellow crookneck,
are best when they are young and quite small (cigar-shaped squash
are best if cooked when eight inches long or less). Select squash
that aren't dented or gashed and don't have any soft spots.
</P>
<P>
   Store summer squash in a ventilated plastic bag in the
refrigerator for up to three days. Before cooking, scrub well with
a brush or rough sponge.
</P>
<P>
   As summer squash are mostly water, you'll need two pounds of
whole squash to feed four people. One pound of zucchini or summer
squash will yield 3 1/2 cups sliced squash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
