<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MILLIONAIRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT GAME SHOW HAS SOME DISTURBING DEMOGRAPHICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' was a summer smash, an
intelligent, compelling game show imported from the United Kingdom
that produced monster ratings.
</P>
<P>
   It also was overwhelmingly white _ and male.
</P>
<P>
   The contestants selected for an opportunity to be on the show
were male by a 4-to-1 ratio. As for those who actually sat in the
``hot seat'' opposite Regis Philbin, the numbers were more
staggering: 15 men, two women.
</P>
<P>
   This is not good when the television industry has been
rightfully slapped around for its lack of diversity. The question
for this show is why the homogeny?
</P>
<P>
   Contestants had to get through on a 900 phone line and quickly
and correctly answer three questions posed by a computer to get
onto a panel, then be the fastest with a correct answer _ the
``fast finger'' playoff _ to get into the hot seat. The system was
designed to ensure an equal chance for everyone to get on during
the 13-show run, the network said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some people squawked about not getting through or on
_ there is a million bucks on the line. That was expected. But the
female question has the show's makers flummoxed. I'm at a loss,
too. I've heard some suggestions, like men are more likely to
instinctively blurt out answers, which is why they could have an
advantage in the phone and ``fast finger'' rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why our daughter is going to an all-girls high
school,'' my wife said. Of course, this was after I had shouted out
my guess, again, at the TV before she had a chance to respond. I've
heard of this phenomenon in other homes.
</P>
<P>
   So guys are quick on the trigger, right or wrong (must be all
that practice with the remote control). But what about
``Jeopardy!''? That show requires quick responses, and women have
done well there. So that isn't necessarily it.
</P>
<P>
   This is where I'm supposed to make some insightful, sly or silly
conclusion. The truth is I just don't have one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Yes, there should be a
question mark, and, no, there isn't) will return in November,
either for a short run like the one just passed, or as a
replacement series. I vote for the former; keep it an event.
</P>
<P>
   But before the leaves fall, somehow, some way, the producers
better figure out what is going on with the lack of females, or it
will be women screaming at the TV.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GOODBYE SUMMER, HELLO JERRY
</P>
<P>
   Summer is not over when school starts, or when the leaves turn,
or when football comes back. Summer is over when Jerry Lewis sweats
and cries in a tuxedo, giving everything he has for a cause.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Lewis' annual Labor Day weekend Muscular Dystrophy
telethon, a fund-raiser that has netted $1.6 billion since its
debut in 1966. Despite his recent bout with viral meningitis that
felled him in July on tour in Australia, Lewis plans on being
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go through with it,'' Lewis, 73, told Larry King
on CNN last week. ``I cannot not do it. The responsibility is so
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis' telethon sidekick for 32 years, Ed McMahon, said both
he and Lewis are getting smarter as the years go by, recognizing
that a telethon is a marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, he started listening to me a few years ago,'' McMahon
said in a recent interview. ``So in the middle of the telethon we
take a short break. You are much stronger at the end of the
telethon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wear yourself out, no matter how strong you are,'' said
McMahon, the former ``Tonight Show'' sidekick who is still going
strong at 76. ``Most of the money comes in that last three or four
hours of the show; you have to be at your strongest.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon said he met with Lewis two weeks ago as the entertainer
was preparing to meet with local telethon hosts from around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed weak as I met him in the hallway,'' McMahon said.
``But as the thing progressed, he seemed stronger and stronger and
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is the plan after Lewis, after McMahon? McMahon said he
did not know, since neither one plans on going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old Marine. That helps,'' McMahon said. ``I will keep
going as long as I'm around. I'm not going to retire, and I don't
think Jerry is going to retire. It's not his nature.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
