<HEADLINE>
TAX CUT DEBATE HINGES ON ROLE OF GOVERNMENT DEFINITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 5)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E.THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ We are about to witness a classic
liberal-conservative, Democrat vs. Republican debate over the use
of taxpayers' money and the federal government's role in protecting
the aged, the very young and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Gone for the moment is the good gray atmosphere in which
conflicting ideologies often are accommodated and policies
compromised by the opposing sides.
</P>
<P>
   Observers may find it difficult to penetrate the cloud of
bombast and hyperbole that will permeate Capitol Hill when the
opposing forces again square off this week. But they will have no
difficulty discerning that the end goal the two sides are fighting
for is victory in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was set for the coming showdown when, as Congress
prepared early last month to depart for its summer vacation, the
GOP majority in both houses passed a 10-year, $792 billion tax cut
and President Clinton vowed to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare that a president of one party and a Congress
dominated by the other party confront each other on an issue that
so clearly defines their philosophical differences.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we often hear the assertions that there is little
difference between the two parties. Sometimes that criticism is
valid, especially when arch foes on Capitol Hill put pragmatic
politics ahead of partisan dogma to solve legislative disputes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it should be noted that, despite the desires and
demands of their leaders, the two parties are rarely monolithic. On
such matters as abortion, gun control, and campaign spending,
usually a few liberal Republicans will cross party lines to vote
with Democrats, and some conservative Democrats will vote with
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The current dispute grows out of a question that Congress and
the White House have not had to answer for the past three decades:
What do you do with a budget surplus? Since the flow of red ink has
been halted, government officials speculate that the surplus could
reach $3 trillion over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are betting, therefore, that when voters trek to the
polls next year, they will favor the party that sought to give them
a healthy tax break and less government.
</P>
<P>
   As Bill Archer, the Texas Republican who heads the House Ways
and Means Committee, explained: ``Americans are paying the highest
taxes as a percentage of the nation's economy since World War II.
We should give it back to them before it gets spent by the
bureaucrats.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats are wagering that voters, most of whom are
enjoying the most robust economy they've ever known, would prefer a
much smaller tax cut (something around $300 billion) and use of the
surplus to save Social Security and Medicare, give more aid to
education and the environment and pay down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Although both parties have cut and raised taxes over the years,
Ronald Reagan made tax reduction an article of faith for
Republicans in the 1980s, just as Franklin D. Roosevelt, during the
Great Depression of the 1930s, made big, benevolent government a
symbol for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's successor, George Bush, undercut his own credibility
and that of his presidency when he agreed to a tax increase after
saying, ``Read my lips. No new taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever remote chance Walter Mondale had of defeating Reagan in
1984 evaporated when, at the Democratic Convention in San
Francisco, he declared: ``Mr. Reagan will raise taxes and so will
I. He won't tell you. I just did.''
</P>
<P>
   That line drew a thunderous ovation from the assembled
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   After some soul searching and poll taking by the White House,
however, Reagan announced quite firmly that he would not boost
taxes. He went on to carry every state but Mondale's Minnesota and
the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan experience, in which an across-the-board tax cut in
1981 produced economic expansion and a decline in joblessness, is
one the Republicans cite as their model. But the Democrats point
out that the Reagan tax cut, coupled with sharply increased defense
spending, boosted the deficit and the national debt far beyond
previous records.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Reagan left the White House, the national debt was
over $2 trillion and the interest on that debt was $150 billion.
After national defense and entitlement programs, interest on the
debt was the third largest item in the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting taxes is popular and important. The American people have
a right to feel oppressed by massive, costly government. A cut in
taxes can influence entrepreneurs to invest money in business
expansion, which, in turn, creates more jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But it should be recalled that despite all the grumbling over
Bill Clinton's 1993 tax increase on the wealthy, which did not win
a single Republican vote in the Democratic-dominated Congress, the
economy has surged to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows when it might careen downward, wiping out the
surplus and bringing an end to the euphoria that now grips the
country. When that happens, a tax cut might be just the remedy to
get the economy moving.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, our leaders would do well to channel the lion's
share of the government's excess revenue into protecting vital
programs such as Social Security and Medicare and diminishing the
national debt before they approve an enormous tax cut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
