   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-CONGLOMERATES (Pupyong, South Korea) _ For the last two
years, President Kim Dae Jung of South Korea has been waging a
battle to restructure the giant, octopus-like conglomerates that
dominate the economy. Now, as Daewoo Group, the nation's
second-biggest conglomerate, is slowly being broken up, and as
other conglomerates, or chaebols, are undergoing overhauls, many
Korean and foreign investors have begun to say that the twilight of
the chaebol is finally becoming a reality. And that will mean an
end to the days when the industrial chairmen wielded total, and
often totally secret, decision-making power over their empires. By
Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ELECTRIC (Seoul) _ Korea Electric Power says it will split
its generating facilities into six businesses and sell all but its
nuclear plants as it gives up the near-total monopoly it has
enjoyed since 1961. By Samuel Len.
</P>
<P>
   HSBC-REPUBLIC (London) _ HSBC says that investigations of a
Republic New York securities unit in New York and Japan may delay
its $10.3 billion acquisition of Republic. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-LABOR (Undated) _ Boeing's largest union has voted
overwhelmingly to accept a proposed new three-year contract,
averting a strike that would have dealt a blow to the company's
efforts to recover from an embarrassing financial downturn. Boeing
will also take a third-quarter charge of $225 million because it
has not booked as many orders as hoped for its F-15 fighter jet. By
Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-APPOINT (Undated) _ Microsoft announces executive
appointments and discusses Internet efforts. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ Ford Motor reports its August sales. By
Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
