<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-REBELS-FIGHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 WILL THE SIREN SONG of ISLAMIC UNITY CHARM DAGESTAN?  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By PAVEL PALAZCHENKO  
 c.1999 Metro International, Helsinki  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Judging by commentaries in the Western media, many observers
seem to be equating the hostilities between Russian armed forces
and Muslim separatists in Dagestan with the 1974-'76 war between
Russia and Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But despite some superficial similarities, lumping together the
two fights is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton went so far as to liken the Russian
president, Boris Yeltsin, to Abraham Lincoln, a defender of his
nation's integrity, when Yeltsin sent Russian troops into Chechnya
five years ago on a misguided adventure that only made all the
problems in Northern Caucasus far worse than before.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the relatively free Russian media are not even asking
obvious questions that might clarify what's behind the escalating
crisis in Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   For example, how is it that Russia's elite special services and
intelligence organizations failed to foresee or even to monitor the
onslaught of hundreds of armed Chechen fighters led by the warlord
Shamil Basayev into Dagestan? Some Russian troops actually were
withdrawn from Dagestan a few months prior to the rebels' attack.
Why?
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Russia's integrity is hanging in the balance.
During Yeltsin's debacle in Chechnya, the prestige of Russian
troops was badly damaged, but also very significantly, the fighting
fueled the rise of militant Islam there.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are important questions to be asked: Will people in
Dagestan be lured by the siren song of Islamic unity sounded from
Chechnya? Will the call for a free Islamic state win over more than
just a few villages?
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Sergei V. Stepashin said, just a few hours
before he was fired by Yeltsin: ``We may well lose Dagestan'' _ not
exactly the sort of news the Kremlin wished to hear.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened in Dagestan? And why so much ignorance now
about what's really at stake?
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, the world's attention span is short, and this part
of the world has not been on everybody's mind. Since 1976, when its
war with Russia ended, victorious Chechnya has turned into a
humanitarian disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The population in Chechnya has dropped from about 1 million to
perhaps 300,000. Its economy has become virtually non-existent.
Theft of oil from the Russian pipeline, robberies, kidnapping,
ambushes and ransom seem to be the only viable industries.
Officially, unemployment in Dagestan amounts to 20 percent;
unofficial figures put it as high as 80 percent. Youth unemployment
stands at about 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Russia lost the war, but the Chechnyans cannot win the peace. No
wonder the example of Chechnya has not proved attractive to the
majority of Dagestanis. While the benefits of independence from
Russia remain dubious, the chaos, dislocation and rampant crime in
Chechnya are there for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Stepashin, the current prime minister, Vladimir
Putin, on Aug. 7, confidently stated that the separatists in
Dagestan would be crushed in two weeks. Moscow did claim victory
over the rebels a little more than two weeks later. As of Aug. 31,
however, the air strikes and artillery raids were raging, with
eight Russian soldiers killed and 31 wounded _ and, by Russia's
count, about 80 rebels dead.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that no government can afford to stand idly by as
bands of armed terrorists try to foist the banner of Islamic
fundamentalism on a population that, for the most part, wants no
part of it. A strong military response is needed, but in Dagestan
it is a disaster to think that will cure the problem.
</P>
<P>
   During the war in Chechnya, many Dagestanis volunteered to fight
the rebels alongside Russian troops. The battle now being fought in
Dagestan is not merely military, and its outcome is by no means
clear.
</P>
<P>
   If Dagestan is vulnerable to fundamentalism, it is not out of
religious ideology. The government needs help in building a better
life for its 2 million people. Its population is a patchwork of 34
ethnic groups. In some villages, the people speak two or three
languages. Stability in such places depends on deft political
footwork but also _ and perhaps most of all _ on economic
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   All of the republics of Russia's Northern Caucasus are in dire
straits. It is here that the Russian government has been failing in
the most miserable way. About 87 percent of Dagestan's budget comes
from Moscow, making the republic virtually dependent. Given the
state of Russia's economy, however, those transfers do not amount
to much.
</P>
<P>
   What is Russia to do? So far as these republics are concerned,
there can be no benign neglect. In fact, neglecting them could have
explosive consequences. Islamic extremism characteristically gains
strength in areas of massive poverty and powerlessness. Moscow
needs to act fast to develop and implement a workable economic
strategy. Yet the government in Moscow can barely take care of
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in this battle, Russia deserves at least moral support
and understanding. In Chechnya the issue was secession; in Dagestan
it is invasion. All of Russia's political parties and leaders,
including critics of the war in Chechnya, have spoken in support of
the efforts to eject the invaders, who include foreign mercenaries,
from Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, even if Russia can come up with a program to
ensure stability and economic control, it is by no means clear that
the people of Dagestan will respond gratefully and reject the call
for Islamic unity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Pavel Palazchenko is the author of ``My Years With Gorbachev
and Shevardnadze: The Memoir of a Soviet Interpreter'' (1997). His
columns have appeared in Moscow News; Metro International,
Helsinki, and other publications. He teaches Russian language and
contemporary politics at Colgate University; he has also taught at
Moscow Linguistic University. From 1980 to 1991 he served in the
Russian Foreign Ministry, before which he was an interpreter with
the United Nations in New York.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
