<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE REACHES OUT TO TEACHERS, STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Internet venture NY Wired is trying to create
a market of school children, parents and teachers who will visit
the company's new, education-oriented Web site.
</P>
<P>
   NY Wired also hopes to create a magazine or cable television
channel. The new Web site will collect and disseminate lesson
plans, homework help and school-Web site tools to the public for
free.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the site gets a share of the profits from
commercial goods sold through http://www.nywired.net, said
co-founder Brian Lee. E-commerce sales of clothing, computers,
household supplies and even on-line courses for teachers will
subsidize the whole venture, which is soon to go national, Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet retailer conducting business on the Web site, Value
America/E-Store, is selling computers and Internet access for $20
per month to help NY Wired reach a wide market. The initial
computer purchase can be made over the phone, and the retailer said
it can finance parents with poor or no credit histories.
</P>
<P>
   And, in an additional publicity boost, Gov. George Pataki helped
unveil the Web site at a news conference in downtown Albany on
Wednesday. Pataki said the Web site helps his administration's
efforts to raise ``educational standards across the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he wasn't endorsing the choice of commercial
retailers hosted on the site, only focusing on the Web site's
educational potential. Pataki noted the Web site will make
available free to teachers 250 multimedia lesson plans _ developed
by other teachers _ that meet the standards of the state Education
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Executives involved in the venture would not reveal sales goals,
but Lee said the breadth of content offerings on the Web site
should set NY Wired and its national counterpart, US Wired, apart
from 20 or 30 competitors in the educational market.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site also will offer special software to protect
youngsters from accessing obscene material. NY Wired is licensing
that software feature from an Elmira company, Exotrope Inc.
Software developed and licensed by the Albany Times Union will
allow schools and districts to create their own secure Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, NY Wired may broaden the spectrum of content or
services, said Lee, whose own company employs seven people.
</P>
<P>
   Additional for-profit vendors may also get onto the site and
compete with ones already there, noted Tom Starnes, president of
the Virginia-based Value America.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, his company sells IBM, several IBM-compatible
brands and Apple computers. But Value America doesn't carry
computers from popular manufacturers Gateway or Dell Computer, he
said, so he expects those vendors may also be included on the Web
site to afford customers a broader choice.
</P>
<P>
   NY Wired is going to do similar launches of Web sites in
California, Texas and Florida, said Lee, under the name US Wired
for Education.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he'll also look for support from governors of those
states, including Texas Gov. George W. Bush, currently running for
the Republican nomination for president, and his brother, Florida
Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
