<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Monday, May 10, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PEACE _ ALEXANDRIA, Egypt _ Israeli and Palestinian
leaders, despite a push from U.S. President Bill Clinton and a
visit by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, were unable to
reach an agreement to jumpstart the stalled Wye River accords and
possibly signal a regionwide effort to bring peace to the Middle
East. What does it mean? Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA _ ATLANTA _ Uganda has suffered through the Idi Amin
years of the '70s and a series of political crises well into the
1980s. It has recently been embroiled in the clash in Congo. And it
has the fifth highest number of children who are HIV positive. Yet,
it is trying to right itself and by 1997 had the fastest growing
economy in Africa. An interview with Prime Minister Apollo
Nsibambi, who visits Atlanta Thursday for a meeting on investment
at the Carter Center and a gathering of Ugandans from around the
United States. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   WACO _ WASHINGTON _ As Attorney General Janet Reno prepares to
announce an independent probe of why the FBI failed to disclose
information about the Waco raid, the White House issues a strong
statement of support for her. (Shepard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POGO _ WASHINGTON _ A little-known whistleblower's lawsuit has
exposed what plaintiffs contend is a billion-dollar conspiracy by
the big oil companies to defraud taxpayers out of royalties on oil
and gas taken from public lands and offshore oil and gas fields.
And it has pushed a little-known public interest group, the Project
on Government Oversight, into a new world of wealth and
controversy. (Nesmith, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-SNIDER _ WASHINGTON _ What Congress and the U.S. Energy
Department gave, the Internal Revenue Service wants back. That's
the claim by lumber companies in Texas and Georgia that used
federal tax credits to develop alternative energy projects.
(Moskal, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-EDWARDS _ WASHINGTON _ If Archie L. Edwards' estate had its
way, the Internal Revenue Service would play a different tune. The
estate of the late owner of Carolina Music in Greenville, N.C.,
filed a petition asking the U.S. Tax Court here to overturn an IRS
demand for $1.54 million in back taxes and penalties for 1991. (Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EDUCATION _ LOS ANGELES _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush uses a
Hispanic business forum to make what his staff is calling a major
policy announcement on education. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY _ CLEVELAND _ Bill Bradley hits Cleveland and Columbus
today. (Hershey, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WORKERS-CONTAMINATED _ Seven workers face weeks of medical
monitoring after they were contaminated with plutonium at a federal
nuclear weapons facility. Officials at the Savannah River Site, on
the Georgia-South Carolina border, said particles of the
radioactive metal were found on the workers' clothing and skin, but
they have not determined whether the plutonium penetrated the
workers' bodies. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BARTON-DISAPPEARANCE _ ATLANTA _ It's clear the Atlanta police
department has not done any kind of review concerning Mark Barton's
disappearance from the site of his random killings and his
whereabouts for several hours, until he was cornered north of the
city and committed suicide. Will there be an investigation? (Longa,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RAVINE _ ATLANTA _ Following developments in slaying of
17-year-old girl beaten and left to die in a ravine for four days
before two men and a teenage woman cut her throat on the fifth day.
Seeking to learn more about Covington-Athens suspects, and about
victim. (Farber, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SANTACLAUS-MURDERS _ ATLANTA _ Awaiting what should be a
slam-dunk verdict in Jerry Scott Heidler's murder trial in the
December 1997 slaying of most of a family in Santa Claus, Ga.
Defense lawyers rested Wednesday without presenting any testimony,
saving their case for the penalty phase in which they will argue he
is too mentally ill to be executed. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINMARY-LAWSUIT _ CONYERS, Ga. _ A federal court case has
emerged from a dispute between Nancy Fowler, who claims to receive
messages from the Virgin Mary, and a group set up to organize
massive gatherings held for eight years at her Conyers farm. Until
the dispute is resolved, neither Fowler nor her former allies is
allowed to publish a book of divine messages, ``Be Children of
God.'' (Farber, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLYSCI _ ATLANTA _ Congressman John Lewis is featured speaker
at the American Political Scientists Association's annual meeting.
Also news from the meeting. (Pruitt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
