<SLUG> BC-FILM-ANIMALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``ALL THE LITTLE ANIMALS'' NEVER QUITES CLICKS INTO PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a producer, England's Jeremy Thomas has had a distinguished
career and is responsible for such worthy films as Nicolas Roeg's
``Bad Timing,'' Stephen Frear's ``The Hit'' and Bernardo
Bertolucci's ``The Last Emperor'' _ for which Thomas took home the
1987 best picture Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   With this adaptation of Walker Hamilton's 1970 novel, ``All the
Little Animals,'' Thomas has finally taken a stab at directing,
and, not too surprisingly, it's a movie brimming with good
intentions, solid production values and searing performances.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, however, it never quite clicks into place with any real
satisfaction. The ingredients all seem to be there for a rich,
emotionally engrossing movie experience, but the storytelling flair
and directorial ``touch'' are not.
</P>
<P>
   It's about Bobby (Christian Bale), a young man from a wealthy
London family who has been somewhat mentally handicapped since a
childhood automobile accident, and has compensated by developing a
strong love for animals, especially his pet mouse.
</P>
<P>
   When his mother dies, his wicked stepfather (Daniel Benzali)
wants him to sign over his claim to the family department store.
When he refuses, the stepfather kills the pet mouse and threatens
to have Bobby committed to an asylum.
</P>
<P>
   He runs off to Cornwall, and soon meets Mr. Summers (John Hurt),
a eccentric hermit who loathes humanity and wanders the winding
roads of the province burying the road kill, because he believes
``all living things are of equal value.''
</P>
<P>
   The two are a match made in heaven, and the rest of the movie
has these soulmates confessing their tortured pasts, forming their
own little family unit (based on their mutual love of animals), and
struggling to set Bobby free from the lingering threat of his
stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good cast _ Bale is winning, and so is Hurt, who has more
than his usual moments of power and poetry. Though its morality is
dubious (killing bad people seems to be OK, killing irritating rats
and cockroaches is not), it's hard not to like the film's larger
ecological sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   But its basic situation never quite leaps to life with any
credibility, it soon becomes predictable, and when its last act
makes a big turn toward pure melodrama _ and a lengthy chase
sequence that might have been borrowed from a bad James Bond movie
_ it becomes a bit ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   All the Little Animals. Directed and produced by Jeremy Thomas.
Screenplay by Eski Thomas. Cast: John Hurt, Christian Bale, Daniel
Benzali. Lions Gate Films. 110 minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
