<SLUG> BC-FILM-BRIDGES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVERS ON THE BRIDGE' IS BOTH RHAPSODIC AND MADDENINGLY
FRUSTRATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This 1991 film is the current cause of Miramax Zoe and
director/film restoration advocate Martin Scorsese.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, they have rediscovered the ``lost'' French
films ``Purple Noon'' and ``Belle du Jour'' and brought them to
American audiences. Now, it's the turn of ``The Lovers On the
Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is directed by the quixotic Leos Carax, whose latest,
``Pola X,'' a tale of obsessive love starring Catherine Deneuve,
caused a stir at this year's Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lovers on the Bridge'' is both rhapsodic and as
maddeningly frustrating as any film can be that is hell-bent upon
wreaking havoc on traditional story structure and heightening the
poetry ascribed to the cinema as a visual medium.
</P>
<P>
   Carax goes against cinematic cliches by making his protagonists
an unattractive, unlikely pair. One is Michele Stalens (Juliette
Binoche), a self-destructive painter who is going blind. The other
is Alex, a violent, fire-blowing street performer thug with an
innocent's heart.
</P>
<P>
   The homeless pair meet and fall in love on the Pont-Neuf bridge,
the oldest landmark in Paris, while it is undergoing restoration.
It's a metaphor for their love, that oldest emotion in the world
that must continually be restored if it is to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Carax, always an anarchic director, repaints the sugar-coated
film romances of other popular French directors such as Jacques
Demy with a grittier primer (though in the end, all these
characters are not very far apart _ they just approach love from
different angles). He cares more about the physical world in which
his characters live than in whether they're likeable.
</P>
<P>
   That's a blessing and a curse for this overly long, difficult
film. The challenge is not intellectual _ it's sitting through
two-plus hours with people without enough history or credibility to
believe in.
</P>
<P>
   Their violent romance is forced and the ending betrays
everything that's come before. It feels false and Binoche, who
apparently begged for the role because she did not want to be seen
``as a pristine angel'' in the movies, is totally out of her league
as a rich woman who chooses the streets over the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Lovers On the Bridge'' is breathtaking when it
relinquishes control of its fractured story to cinematographer
Jean-Yves Escoffier's incredible palette of lights, color and
fantasy. His perfect eye makes this film difficult to dismiss. His
shots of Binoche water-skiing against a Niagara Falls-like set on
the Seine, of fireworks blasting against the lovers standing in awe
upon the bridge, of missing person's posters with Michele's face
filling the subway and being set afire by Alex are extraordinary,
breathtaking and desperately alive. They almost compensate for the
negatives of the film.
</P>
<P>
   But Carex ultimately proves we still need information and story
in order to identify with people who are a discomfort to us. While
we can admire him for his courage, we can't connect to his wayward
vision of such desperate, delinquent love.
</P>
<P>
   The Lovers On the Bridge (Les Amants du Pont Neuf). Directed and
written by Leos Carax. Cast: Juliette Binoche, Denis Lavant,
Klaus-Michael Gruber. Miramax Zoe. 125 minutes. Unrated. In French
with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
