<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-TRADING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS ON-LINE BROKERS NEED TO BOOST CUSTOMER SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On-line trading is creating a monetary boon for
Internet brokerage companies, which are rewarding their new
customers with shabby treatment. That's the conclusion of a new
study released by Jupiter Communications, a New York-based Internet
market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, on-line brokerage assets will top $3
trillion by 2003, up from $415 billion spent on Internet trading in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   However, the study found, that success has not translated into
customer care. Fewer than 40 percent of financial service Web sites
responded to customer inquiries within one day, ``which is
inadequate for such a service-intensive business,'' Jupiter said in
a statement released with the study.
</P>
<P>
   The survey is based on a test of 125 leading Web sites that
service a number of electronic commerce categories, including the
Web retail market, which scored a 64 percent response rate to
customer inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   That customer response score is actually an improvement over a
survey done earlier this year, when Jupiter found that only 24
percent of financial service Web sites could give a one-day
response to customer e-mail queries. However, the study stated,
``it is still too low for companies that control consumer on-line
finances.''
</P>
<P>
   That poor performance could, in the long run, put a cap on the
on-line financial market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing that new on-line financial services customers
are mainstream, risk-averse consumers who have far less tolerance
for technology issues and customer service issues,'' said Rob
Sterling, a Jupiter analyst. ``Key players are going to have to
think more like retailers and invest in the infrastructure to help
support a more mainstream customer base.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Alban, a spokesman for Menlo Park-based ETrade, a leading
on-line trading site, said the company had already heeded the call
for customer service by tripling the number of customer service
agents and providing educational Web pages for neophyte traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customer service is an important aspect of this industry, and
we intend to fulfill that need,'' Alban said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
