<SLUG> BC-TASTE-MEAT-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Back-to-School Bologna Flunks   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  With most schools back in session, bologna seemed
a logical candidate for Taster's Choice. It's a popular choice for
kids' lunches, and many adults like a good fried bologna sandwich
now and then.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Panelists seemed to like the idea; most of them had good
childhood memories of bologna. But when they tasted the 10 meat
bolognas, they were seriously disappointed and found the category
underwhelming. One panelist said he was going to find out if his
wife was feeding it to their children, and if she was he's asking
her to stop.
</P>
<P>
   The main complaint was the texture. Most of the meats were slimy
and many had an almost grainy quality.
</P>
<P>
   All the bologna was made with beef or a combination of pork and
poultry, and included low-fat and fat-free varieties as well.
(Bologna made exclusively from poultry products was tasted
separately; the results will run soon).
</P>
<P>
   Tasters liked  &UR; Safeway &LR;   &UR; Regular &LR;  (16 ounces, $1.99) best. One
panelist liked its peppery flavor; another liked the smoky taste.
But a third panelist described the flavor as metallic, and still
another thought it had the flavor and texture of liver. One would
buy it, two might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Russer Beef Bologna &LR;  ($4.89 per pound at Safeway) came in
second. One panelist thought the meat tasted less processed than
other brands; another described the flavor as balanced. But others
found the meat too mealy. Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Third place was a tie between two of the light bolognas:
 &UR; Oscar Mayer Light &LR;  (eight ounces, $2.19 at Andronico's) and
 &UR; Russer Beef Bologna Light &LR;  ($5.29 per pound at Safeway).
</P>
<P>
   With the Oscar Mayer brand, three panelists objected to the
texture (``mushy and slimy''), but one panelist thought it had a
``nice bite.'' Two enjoyed the flavor, one even calling it
``classic.'' One would buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   Three panelists thought the Russer was rubbery, but two others
liked its firmness. One liked the meaty flavor. Two would buy it,
three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Oscar Mayer Beef Bologna &LR;  (16 ounces, $2.19 at Andronico's)
came in fifth. Four tasters thought it was too salty; two thought
it was mushy. But another thought the texture was okay and liked
the slightly smoked flavor. Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Oscar Mayer Fat Free, Oscar Mayer Light
Beef, Oscar Mayer Regular Bologna, Bar S and Safeway Beef Bologna
but they scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Roland
Passot chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in
Larkspur and Menlo Park; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; an
Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
