<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 WINE POTPOURRI: Dessert Lovers Warm Up to Ice Wines   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Dessert wines are such a small part of the wine
market that most people don't know they exist. Now thanks to the
efforts of some patient and enterprising Canadian and New York
wineries, interest in these wines is looking up.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dessert wines are sweet and can be enjoyed either with dessert
or as a dessert by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For many collectors, French Sauternes and Barsac are the
ultimate in sweet wines. Others prefer German Auslese or Hungarian
Tokaj.
</P>
<P>
   The German style, using Riesling or a handful of other white
grapes, produces wines of sublime balance and complexity. Canadian
winemakers, mainly in Ontario and British Columbia, have adopted
this style, but instead of Riesling are using grapes like
Ehrenfelser and Vidal. Many of the resulting wines are made in the
German Eiswein style.
</P>
<P>
   Eiswein (ice wine) is made from the concentrated juice of frozen
grapes. It's a risky business because the slightest glitch in the
weather can ruin an entire grape crop. There is also the issue of
botrytis, a beneficent mold that attacks the grapes at harvest when
weather conditions are right and causes the berries to shrivel.
This transforms the grape juice into an ultra-sweet nectar.
Sauternes and German eiswein are always affected by botrytis.
</P>
<P>
   Because of international laws protecting place names, most sweet
dessert-style wines made outside France and Germany are called Late
Harvest or Select Late Harvest Botrytized. Late Harvest wines may
or may not be botrytized.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet wines took center stage at one event held during the
Kapalua Wine &AMP; Food Symposium in July in Maui. Six sweet wines were
paired with desserts, including a coconut mousse cake, a mango
Bavarian and a chocolate tart.
</P>
<P>
   Among the wines tasted were Joseph Phelps 1997 Special Select
Late Harvest Riesling, Grgich Hills 1995 Violetta Late Harvest and
Lafaurie-Peyraguey 1995 Sauternes. But the two that caused the most
excitement were Inniskillin 1996 Icewine VQA from Ontario, Canada
and Hunt Country 1997 Vidal Ice Wine from New York. Both were made
from Vidal grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Vidal is a hybrid grape grown mostly in the eastern United
States and Canada, and used for dry as well as sweet wines.
</P>
<P>
   The Inniskillin Icewine was viscous and sweet with luscious
tropical fruit flavors, excellent acidity and enough botrytis to
add complexity and depth.
</P>
<P>
   The Hunt Country Ice Wine, from New York's Finger Lakes, offered
many of the same attributes, but leaned more to ripe apricots with
a lovely sweet/tart balance. Both were good choices with the mango
Bavarian.
</P>
<P>
   Next time you're racking your brain for a different dessert, try
serving a chilled ice wine from Canada or New York with fresh
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The best places to find these wines are in fine wine shops, or
ask your wine merchant to order them for you.
</P>
<P>
   The Ice Wine Quarrel
</P>
<P>
   With the growing popularity of Canadian sweet wines, Vintners
Quality Alliance, the Canadian wine authority, last year filed to
make terms like Icewine, Vin de Glace, Eiswein and Special Select
Late Harvest official trademarks to protect the image of Canadian
Icewine. The problem is, other trade organizations _ like
California's Wine Institute and the French Institute National des
Appellations d'Origine _ object because the regulation would limit
export of their wines to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Wine Q &AMP; A
</P>
<P>
   Q: Henry B. Meyer of San Francisco is the owner of the following
three old European wines and he wonders about their drinkability
and value.
</P>
<P>
   A: Zeller Schwarze Katz (Black Cat) is made from a number of
individual vineyards, around the town of Zell on the Mosel River.
It is a white wine made for early consumption, so it is unlikely
that the 1957 Schwarze Katz is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Gilis 1933 St. Emilion Light Bordeaux is a mystery to me,
although at 66 years old, I would think that any ``light'' wine
must now be an undrinkable curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Caraco &AMP; Benitez Malaga Oro, may be the keeper of the lot.
Malaga is a sweet dessert wine from the Costa del Sol region of
Spain. Some Malagas age well, but since there is no way of knowing
the true age of your wine, I'd pull the cork. If you decide to
drink the Malaga, I'd like to hear your impressions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: C. Earlenbaugh of Oakland inherited a bottle of Charles Krug
1972 Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon and is curious about its value
and if any restaurant has an interest in adding his Cabernet to its
wine list.
</P>
<P>
   A: Not knowing the history of the particular bottle, I can only
offer general advice. Vintage 1972 was not that good in the Napa
Valley for red wines, and most of the best wines were already
tiring by the early 1990s. Since any remaining '72s are not
generally on collector's lists, I suggest gathering together a few
friends to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, restaurants can not legally purchase wine from a
private party.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Janne Mahan of Menlo Park wants to know where to purchase
1995 Signorello Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   A: Signorello reports the wine is mostly sold out, but
Andronico's may still carry some. Or, call Linda at Signorello,
(707) 255-5990, for more help.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few weeks ago, a reader asked about the availability of
Barbera Blanc, a blush-type wine made from the Barbera grape.
</P>
<P>
   A: Readers have informed Potpourri that a Barbera Blanc called
Imbianco is available for $9.50 at Viansa Winery, 25200 Arnold
Drive in Sonoma and at Viansa's Lo Spuntino tasting room on the
square in Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   Hemp Wine
</P>
<P>
   I recently read an item in The Wine Trader that renews my faith
in the ingenuity of the American entrepreneur. Nirvana Homebrews in
the Finger Lakes region of New York State is selling Hemp 'n' Wine,
red and white grape wines blended with hemp oil. Jim Castetter of
Nirvana Homebrews says it is not liquid marijuana. ``There is no
THC in our hemp wine _ none,'' he emphasises.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on hemp wine, log on to  &LR; www.hempwine.com &LR; 
or call (888) 520-9463.
</P>
</TEXT>
