</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 CRUSH '99: Harvest Starts With Sparklers   By Janet Fletcher  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 NAPA, Calif. _  Trucks loaded with yellow picking bins began
lumbering up the Silverado Trail last week as the annual grape
harvest got under way in Napa Valley. First out of the starting
gate are the sparkling wine producers, who pick early to get grapes
that are still high in acid.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The crop looks on the light side,'' says Zach Berkowitz, vice
president of operations for Domaine Chandon. ``And I know people
say this every year, but this year the fruit's really delicious.
With the cool season we had, it's got good acidity and lots of
flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   To a large degree, the short crop can be blamed on rainy weather
in the spring of 1998. That's when the vines, in a two-year cycle,
began determining how many bunches they can produce in the fall of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Beckstoffer, one of Napa Valley's largest growers, says his
crop is down, too. But last year's weather may not be the only
explanation. The extensive replanting in the valley due to
Phylloxera may mean lower crops routinely, he says, as growers
replace University of California at Davis clones known for high
yield and disease resistance with French clones selected for
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Beckstoffer says he has warned his client winemakers not to try
to slip away for a week's vacation. After a slow growing season,
the crop is coming on faster than many expect. ``We think people
are a little more relaxed than they should be,'' the grower says.
``If it keeps going with 95- and 100-degree days, it's going to be
one of those harvests where everything is ready at the same time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
