<SLUG> BC-SECRET-RIBS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Insalata's Ribs Owe Allegiance to Spain   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  With ingredients such as chocolate, orange and
sherry you might think that Heidi Krahling was making a dessert
rather than a main course. But when the meaty short ribs come out
of the oven after three hours they're rich, juicy and absolutely
delicious.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Krahling, who owns Insalata's restaurant in San Anselmo, has a
homey rustic style that draws inspiration from Spain, France, the
Mediterranean and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The ribs have lineage to the Catalan region in Spain. The meat
is first browned in oil, removed from the pan and replaced with
onions, carrots, celery and garlic. After the vegetables are well
caramelized, red wine is added and reduced over high heat. Finally,
the ribs are returned to the pan and they're baked in a 300-degree
oven for three hours.
</P>
<P>
   By that point the wine sauce is already bursting with flavor.
But even more character is added with chocolate, sherry, fresh
herbs and the zest of two oranges. These additions create a
wonderful, aromatic sauce that coats the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Although the recipe calls for homemade beef stock, there's so
much going on that if you cheat and use the canned variety, I'm not
sure even Krahling would know the difference.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant, which also has a carry-out counter where you can
pick up some of the popular dishes to take home, has become one of
the best places for a great meal in Marin County. The expansive
space, dominated by the open kitchen, has an upscale, but relaxed
ambience.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Insalata's, 120 Sir Francis Drake Blvd. (near Barber), San &LR; 
 &LR; Anselmo; (415) 457-7700. Lunch Monday-Saturday; dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; The sauce. &LR;  Most recipes consider a red wine sauce used for cooking
the ribs as good enough, but at Insalata, the sauce is further
enriched with bitter chocolate, orange zest and sherry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Oven roasting &LR; . Cooking the ribs slowly for about three hours
infuses them with flavor and makes them exceptionally tender.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; INSALATA'S SPANISH-STYLE SHORT RIBS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   5 to 51/2 pounds short ribs of beef (21/2 inches wide)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 yellow onions, quartered, then halved
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 celery rib, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, smashed
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   141/2-ounce can whole plum tomatoes, chunked
</P>
<P>
   1 thyme sprig
</P>
<P>
   12 cups beef stock
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsweetened chocolate, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons chopped marjoram leaves
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 2 oranges
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Season the ribs with a generous amount of salt and pepper. Warm
the olive oil in a heavy-bottomed casserole. Add the ribs and saute
until browned on all sides, turning as needed. Remove the ribs from
the pan and set aside. Add the onions, carrot, celery and garlic to
the pan and saute until caramelized, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the red wine and cook over high heat until it has reduced by
half. Add the tomato paste, tomatoes and thyme. Stir with a wooden
spoon to combine. Add the reserved ribs and the stock to the pan.
Bring to a boil, cover, place in the oven and bake for 3 hours, or
until the meat easily pulls away from the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the meat from the pan; then strain the cooking liquid.
Return the liquid to the pan, add the sherry and cook over
medium-high heat until reduced by a third. Once reduced, add the
chocolate, thyme, marjoram, orange zest and butter. Season with
salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Return the ribs to the pan and simmer for 2 minutes, just to let
the flavors blend.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with your favorite potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 875 calories, &LR;   &LR; 66 g protein, 16 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 44 g fat (18 g saturated), 173 mg cholesterol, 271
mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
