<HEADER>
A8738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BEDROOMS-FILM-REVIEW-     09-02 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEDROOMS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEDROOMS AND HALLWAYS': THE DISSOLVING BOUNDARY BETWEEN GAY AND
STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to believe that the upscale London bohemians who
frolic through Rose Troche's comedy ``Bedrooms and Hallways''
actually exist to marvel at their easygoing sexual fluidity.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which aspires toward the playful sophistication of a
Noel Coward romp (but without the sharp class distinctions and with
a lot more sex), imagines a brave new world in which the
distinctions between gay and straight have begun to dissolve. In
this semi-utopian urban environment, whose characters live in
improbably spacious, well-decorated apartments, those who are so
inclined can experiment sexually without feeling the need to
declare a final, fixed orientation.
</P>
<P>
   What triggers this giddy comedy of erotic manners is the arrival
of Leo (Kevin McKidd), a love-starved 30-year-old gay artisan in an
ostensibly heterosexual men's consciousness-raising group. At a
ritual during which something called ``the honesty stone'' is
passed around and the members are encouraged to bare their most
intimate secrets, Leo confesses his attraction to his fellow group
member Brendan (James Purefoy). Although Brendan is momentarily
nonplused, his curiosity quickly triumphs over his initial
embarrassment. Suddenly Leo, who has been pining for a lover, finds
himself sleeping with the man of his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie's cleverest sequences, before their relationship
has been consummated, Brendan invades those dreams, sometimes in
period costume from Jane Austen. (It depends on what book Leo has
been reading that night.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Bedrooms and Hallways'' would end right here were it not for
Brendan's long-term relationship with Sally (Jennifer Ehle), who
works with him in a restaurant-bakery. When she visits the house
Leo shares with Darren (Tom Hollander), a flouncy gay
flibbertigibbet, Leo is shocked to discover that the woman with
whom Brendan is breaking up is his very own high school sweetheart.
Leo can't bring himself to tell Sally that he is sleeping with the
man who is leaving her, although the truth eventually comes out. At
the same time, he and Sally discover that they still have
``chemistry'' and begin taking a high school flirtation that was
never consummated to the next step.
</P>
<P>
   Having set several plots in motion, the movie does a fairly good
job of keeping them in the air. One subplot involves Darren's
relationship with a dominant real estate agent who has sex with him
in his clients' empty houses but who, to Darren's frustration,
refuses to be seen in public with him. Lesser subplots involve the
relationships and lives of the other men's group members.
</P>
<P>
   The movie takes easy potshots at a ``wild men's gathering'' in
some very tame woods where the participants avidly beat on drums
but prove so inept at foraging for their dinner that their leader
has to put in an emergency phone call for Chinese takeout. The most
superficially macho group member (who also discovers his gay inner
child) becomes hysterical when caught in some brambles.
</P>
<P>
   But having begun to explore the ins and outs of bisexuality,
``Bedrooms and Hallways'' loses its nerve and turns into a shallow
sitcom in which everyone is abruptly and mechanically paired off.
The potentially incendiary conflicts that the movie had begun to
explore are inexplicably dropped. The letdown is so steep it is
almost as though the film ran out of time and money before it could
be completed, and a frantic last-minute wrap-up was improvised to
save the day.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `BEDROOMS AND HALLWAYS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rose Troche; written by Robert Farrar; director of
photography, Ashley Rowe; edited by Chris Blunden; production
designer, Richard Bridgland; produced by Ceci Dempsey and Dorothy
Berwin; released by First Run Features. Running time: 96 minutes.
This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Kevin McKidd (Leo), Hugo Weaving (Jeremy), Jennifer Ehle
(Sally), Simon Callow (Keith), Harriet Walter (Sybil), Tom
Hollander (Darren), Julie Graham (Angie), Christopher Fulford
(Adam), James Purefoy (Brendan) and Paul Higgins (John).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
