r e BC-TITANIC-DVD-LADN &LR;      09-02 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-DVD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO-FRILLS DVD VERSION OF `TITANIC' RELEASED 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By ROB LOWMAN 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Yes, Jack and Rose's story goes on and on. Earlier
this week Paramount finally released the DVD version of the
Oscar-winning, all-time box-office winner ``Titanic'' (suggested
price $29.99).
</P>
<P>
   The good news is the digitally remastered, effects-laden film
looks spectacular on the DVD. But for those of you looking for the
extras that are usually found on DVDs, forget it, which means real
``Titanic'' fanatics will have to wait for a future deluxe package
that might include those behind-the-scenes featurettes on the
``making of,'' cast bios and even historic features.
</P>
<P>
   Since DVD player prices are likely to dip below $200 (there are
already a few priced below $250) by the year's end and sales are
expected to boom, releasing the movie now is probably a profitable
move on Paramount's part. But since the studio hasn't committed to
a special-edition DVD ``Titanic,'' fans probably won't wait.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Paramount has also released episodes of the original
``Star Trek'' television series with William Shatner (Capt. James
T. Kirk), Leonard Nimoy (the half-Vulcan Mr. Spock) and the late
DeForest Kelly (Dr. Leonard ``Bones'' McCoy). The special effects
hardly look special by today's standards, but the crew of the
Starship Enterprise never looked better. Each DVD contains two
episodes at a suggested retail price of $19.95 each. So far,
Paramount has released two volumes, with ``Where No Man Has Gone
Before'' and ``The Corbomite Maneuver'' on the first and ``Mudd's
Women'' and ``The Enemy Within'' on the second. It plans to issue
four more volumes this fall and the remaining 34 in the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, for those looking for historical significance, ``The
Enemy Within'' marks the first time Spock uses the Vulcan neck
pinch to incapacitate a foe and McCoy utters the classic line,
``He's dead, Jim.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
