<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALL THE LITTLE ANIMALS': LEAVING OUT CHEESE FOR MICE AND
COCKROACHES? 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't be deceived by the sweetly benign title of Jeremy Thomas'
film ``All the Little Animals.'' This contemporary moral fable,
dressed up as a heart-in-your-throat psychological thriller,
accumulates the lingering force of an especially vivid and
terrifying bad dream.
</P>
<P>
   The film, adapted from a novel by Walker Hamilton, suggests a
modern-day Charles Dickens tale in which a young man cowering in
the shadow of an implacably cruel and treacherous stepfather flees
home to be rescued by an eccentric, life-loving woodland hermit.
</P>
<P>
   Modernized with an aggressive animal-rights agenda, the movie
poses troubling, unanswerable questions about the relative value of
human life in relation to other species and the extremes to which
people should go to protect life.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, it flirts with a storybook sentimentality.
(Somebody has to protect those sweet innocent cockroaches.) And in
its crowning and disturbing irony, the heroes who bend over
backward to avoid harming a mouse or a cockroach, act homicidally.
</P>
<P>
   The unalloyed malevolence of Bernard De Winter (Daniel Benzali)
and the gentleness of his 24-year-old stepson, Bobby (Christian
Bale), who has suffered brain damage from a childhood head injury,
lend these characters the mythic intensity of fairy-tale figures.
But the primal emotions the story stirs up and the all-out violence
unleashed insure that ``All the Little Animals'' is not a family
film.
</P>
<P>
   Benzali's hulking, scowling, baldheaded stepfather is too scary
for children. This is a man who in the movie's grimmest scene
orders his stepson to dig his own grave. Think of the Wicked Witch
of the West as a smooth-talking sadistic thug, and you get an idea
of the intensity of the menace he exudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Little Animals'' is narrated by Bobby several months
after the events the movie describes. On the day of his mother's
funeral in a London suburb, the young man is summoned to the office
of his imperious stepfather, whom he refers to as ``The Fat,'' and
ordered to sign papers giving De Winter control of the fancy
department store his wife owned. Weeping and stuttering, Bobby
refuses, saying that his mother, whose wasting away he blames on De
Winter's bullying, told him not to.
</P>
<P>
   De Winter then gives Bobby an ultimatum: If he doesn't sign by 4
p.m. the next day, he will have Bobby committed to a mental
hospital for the rest of his life. Returning home, Bobby discovers
his beloved pet mouse, Peter, is missing.
</P>
<P>
   When De Winter appears in the doorway holding a plastic bag
containing the dead pet, Bobby, devastated, runs away from home
with only the clothes on his back. Hitching a ride to Cornwall with
a trucker, he precipitates a calamitous accident when the driver
gleefully tries to run down a fox in the middle of the road and
Bobby grabs the wheel to prevent him.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby is miraculously discovered and taken in by a kindly,
wizened man known only as Mr. Summers (John Hurt), who appears at
the scene of the accident and takes Bobby back to his cabin in the
woods and cares for him as though he were a wounded animal.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Summer's life is devoted to what he calls ``the work,''
which consists of burying the bodies of dead animals that have been
hit by cars. His magic cottage is a miniature utopian ecosystem in
which he leaves out cheese for the mice and the cockroaches.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Bobby is assisting Mr. Summers in his work, which
also consists of guerrilla actions like the pair's raid on a
lepidopterist's illuminated tent.
</P>
<P>
   But their idyll is threatened when Bobby runs into his
stepfather's lawyer and his family vacationing on the beach.
Eventually. Bobby and De Winter have a confrontation in which the
stepfather is revealed to be not just a greedy, bullying tyrant but
the murderous incarnation of pure evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Little Animals'' would seem hokey if it didn't have
powerful, extraordinary central performances and cinematography
that lends the English landscape around Cornwall a mythical cast.
</P>
<P>
   Bale's Bobby is sympathetic but deeply, scarily troubled, given
to desperate tantrums and episodes in which he curls into a ball
and becomes a quivering vegetable. Hurt gives Mr. Summers the right
mixture of fanaticism, misanthropy and adult dignity.
</P>
<P>
   As for Benzali, with his gleaming pate, twisted little sneer,
predatory eyes and wattled chin, dressed in a $2,000 suit and
grimacing behind the wheel of a Rolls-Royce: he is a child's worst
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Little Animals'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has a gory knifing
scene.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ALL THE LITTLE ANIMALS'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Jeremy Thomas; written by Eski Thomas,
based on the novel by Walker Hamilton; director of photography,
Mike Molloy; edited by John Victor Smith; music by Richard Hartley;
production designer, Andrew Sanders; released by Lions Gate Films.
Running time: 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: John Hurt (Mr. Summers), Christian Bale (Bobby), Daniel
Benzali (De Winter), James Faulkner (Mr. Whiteside), John O'Toole
(Lorry Driver), Amanda Boyle (Des) and Amy Robbins (Bobby's
Mother).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8749 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-02 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 THE DAY HMOs MEET THE DEVIL  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ About managed health care, I have a dream. An
ugly dream.
</P>
<P>
   Of the day all hell breaks loose.
</P>
<P>
   It starts right after lunch on a seemingly normal afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The point of spontaneous combustion is between my health
maintenance organization and all my ``health care providers.''
(What ever was wrong with ``doctor'' and ``nurse''?)
</P>
<P>
   In the office of my primary care physician, his tireless medical
secretary is the first to explode and ignite. A woman with 100
times the patience of Job, she has been patronized every day for
years by countless formula-following HMO functionaries.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, she is patronized one time too many.
</P>
<P>
   Still holding the phone, the secretary begins to shriek like a
wounded orangutan. In a flash, she rips the multiline unit out of
the wall and hurls it through the little open window of her office
and into the crowded waiting area.
</P>
<P>
   At that very moment, my doctor goes over the edge in his office.
The sort of intelligent and caring healer you thought went out with
house calls, he has just read his 861st ``denial of appeal'' letter
from an HMO. It is the last.
</P>
<P>
   His initial request for authorization for this patient's
procedure was turned down by a formula-following HMO functionary
without a medical degree; the appeal was denied by a physician who
has not practiced medicine since lasers were invented.
</P>
<P>
   Silently, but viciously, my doctor uses his bare hands to shred
all the insurance files in his office. His eyes blank and glassy,
he tears the lid off his laptop computer and tosses it out the
window to a loading zone below.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he lurches into his waiting room to break the chairs
and sofa into toothpicks, his medical secretary, associate and
half-a-dozen patients have taken to the halls _ along with the
staffs and patients from every other office in the building.
</P>
<P>
   All over town, in the offices of my dermatologist, my OB-GYN, my
orthopedist, the physical therapists who rehabbed my knee, the same
scene occurs. Everyone reaches the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as quickly as a wildfire eats up dry pine, the phenomenon
spreads. Throughout California. Across the West. Over the Rockies.
Into the Plains. Down into Texas. Up to the Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
   In seconds, the fire of rage that began in my doctor's office
meets up with a now-out-of-control rage that had begun in a
pediatrician's office in suburban Baltimore. Before the chief
executive of any health maintenance organization can do a thing
about it, before the stock market can react, before sufficient
numbers of cops can be deployed to quell the uprising, the entire
country is engulfed.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the overwhelming anger and frustration that is suffered
in isolated pockets, thousands of times each day by every ``health
care provider'' and every ``health care consumer'' has reached
critical mass.
</P>
<P>
   Every person who ever futilely begged an HMO for an MRI, five
extra psychiatric sessions or a night in the hospital after their
baby was born goes ballistic. So do all senior citizens who
received a form letter in the mail announcing that they would be
dropped from their HMO in 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the movie ``Network,'' people across the country start
screaming, ``I'm mad as hell and I'm not going to take it
anymore!'' The folks on phone hold, listening to Kenny G or ``Eine
Kleine Nacht Musik,'' go especially nuts. As if commanded by some
unseen general, they jump in their cars, flag down cabs, grab buses
or just start walking to the nearest office of their HMO.
</P>
<P>
   The medical secretaries and the people who must ask
semi-conscious, bleeding emergency room patients for their
insurance cards beat everybody else there.
</P>
<P>
   Each HMO building in every state is surrounded. Though no one
strikes a single match, the buildings burst into flame from the
force of all the collective anger. No one inside is hurt because
they, too, can no longer stand to participate in such a hated,
hideous industry; they join the people outside.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the selfish pirates who insist that compassionate
medical care can coexist with maximized profits comprehend what is
happening, it's all over. Every HMO office has been burned to
ground and nearly every American is without insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Congress meets the next day and finally has to do something
besides talk about health care.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
