<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another Horror To Contemplate
</P>
<P>
   Bubbling all summer with ``The Blair Witch Project,'' the horror
genre gained another prized ingredient this week with the video
reissue of Tod Browning's ``Dracula'' (1931), with a new score, by
Philip Glass. For more phantasmagoric developments, however, there
is the continuing adventure of a little film via the New Jersey
Pine Barrens called ``The Last Broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   For several weeks last month, Stefan Avalos and Lance Weiler's
movie, a digital production made for $900, was a selection of the
Amazon.com Advantage for Video program, which provides filmmakers
with no other distribution channel an opportunity to offer their
wares. ``Virtual shelf space,'' said Weiler, who added that 1,000
copies of his film had been sold from Aug. 4 to Aug. 24, when the
tape was taken off line.
</P>
<P>
   That's a large number for such a short period. In fact, he said
``The Last Broadcast,'' about strange killings deep in the New
Jersey woods, was outselling many new main-line titles. Amazon
doesn't release sales figures, but Paul Capelli, a company
spokesman, said ``The Last Broadcast'' moved briskly. Weiler said
the tape was withdrawn when arrangements were made to distribute
the film in video stores later this month.
</P>
<P>
   By now, of course, killings deep in the woods have a certain
familiarity. A diverting concoction despite its obvious
contrivance, ``The Last Broadcast'' bears an uncanny resemblance to
``The Blair Witch Project.'' Both films are fictional documentaries
about fatal encounters with an unknown deadly force. Both use
hand-held video cameras, sometimes wielded on the run, to track or
flee from alarming developments in the bush. Weiler, whose film has
a more involved plot than ``Blair Witch,'' calls the similarities a
twilight area. ``It's a crazy parallel universe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the connection helped ``The Last Broadcast'' on
Amazon.com, it did little to close the gap with ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' which has made nearly $125 million at the box office and
is to be released on video on Oct. 22. If it's any consolation to
Avalos and Weiler, their film does have an interesting production
history. Shot with digital cameras and processed with desktop PC's,
the film has never been on celluloid. In a most unusual release, it
was beamed to a satellite and beamed back again to the rooftops of
theaters in five cities, downloaded through cable onto a hard drive
and run through a digital projector onto the screen. Weiler and
others in his company, Wavelength Releasing, near Doylestown, Pa.,
have demonstrated the process at many festivals and call it the
future of film distribution.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, there is video tape (a DVD is also planned).
Weiler said that Wavelength Releasing has prepared 17,000 cassettes
of ``The Last Broadcast'' for its store debut. ``In the end `Blair
Witch' was one of the best things that happened to our film,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Other Sister
</P>
<P>
   Superlative performances save Garry Marshall's lumbering,
overlong movie about a 24-year-old mentally retarded woman and her
determination to make her own way in the world. Discharged from a
special school, the headstrong Carla (Juliette Lewis, left, with
Giovanni Ribisi) wants a real job and her own apartment. That's
simply not possible, says her overpowering mother (Diane Keaton),
who would have Carla settle down for the rest of her life in the
family's protective cocoon. Soon, though, Carla has enrolled in
technical school, found a place of her own and landed a boyfriend (
Ribisi), an earnest and likable young man who is retarded, too.
Mother is not pleased, nor is she comfortable with the fact that
her other daughter is a lesbian. But, Stephen Holden wrote in The
New York Times, ``for all its disease-of-the-week television movie
inclinations, `The Other Sister' has a core of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   1999. Touchstone. $104.16. 130 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Mod Squad
</P>
<P>
   Based on the television series of the late '60s and early '70s,
Scott Silver's film reaches for the countercultural currents of
those years. In this case, why bother? To recapitulate, three young
lawbreakers (Claire Danes, Giovanni Ribisi and Omar Epps) are saved
from jail by a kindly police captain (Dennis Farina) and sent to
work undercover in clubs and bars. But soon the captain is dead,
some cocaine is missing from an evidence locker, and the mod squad
is handling its own investigation into murder and police
corruption. But rebellious youth given a second chance doesn't
resonate these days, and that's not the only problem in a film
``devoid of original plotting or suspense, clumsy in exposition,
played by unbelievable principals and ill-defined subsidiary
characters'' (Lawrence Van Gelder). _1999. MGM. $104.16. 94
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHAPLIN'S ESSANAY COMEDIES. &LR;  After leaving Keystone, Chaplin
signed in 1915 with the Essanay Film Manufacturing Co. and in 16
shorts refined his screen persona as a vagabond, underdog and
wistful lover of beauty. Produced by the film preservationist David
Shepard, the collection features ``The Tramp'' (1915), generally
regarded as his first masterpiece, in which he rescues a farmer's
daughter from hoodlums. Other titles, from 1915 to 1918, include
``The Champion,'' ``A Woman'' (Chaplin's last female
impersonation), ``Shanghaied'' and ``The Bank.'' Kino. Four
cassettes of four films each. $19.95 each. 95 to 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST OF `THE CHRIS ROCK SHOW.' &LR;  Sketches from the
comedian's HBO show includes ``Taxi Driver's Confessions,'' Ike
Turner's ``Rules,'' ``When Animals Attack in High-Speed Chases II''
and reflections on ``if Maya Angelou wrote a tribute to Marion
Barry,'' the former Mayor of Washington. 1999. HBO. $19.98. 59
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEEPING UP APPEARANCES and THE DUCHESS OF DUKE STREET. &LR;  The BBC
series ``Keeping Up Appearances'' stars Patricia Routledge as a
status-conscious suburban London housewife for whom a picnic by a
river becomes a ``waterside supper with riparian entertainments.''
1999. BBC Video. One cassette with three episodes new to video,
``Entertaining the Hyacinth Way,'' $19.98. In ``The Duchess of Duke
Street, Series 2'' produced by the BBC in 1977 and shown on
Masterpiece Theater and A&AMP;E, a scullery maid rises to higher
position prior to World War I. 1999. Six cassettes, $99.98. 14
hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
