<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8759 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-YES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-02 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`YES WE HAVE NO': AN ENGLAND NEITHER MERRY NOR OLDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The England in Nik Cohn's new book isn't the stuffy old England
of tea cozies, cardigan sweaters and sensible shoes. Nor is it Tony
Blair's Cool Britannia of new-wave fashion designers, cutting-edge
movie makers and hip young bands.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn's England is a darker, more desperate place _ a place
peopled by ``the jobless, the homeless,'' the disenchanted:
``miners and dockers and steelworkers who would never work again,
and school-leavers who would never work at all''; disaffected
immigrants, angry soccer fans, rhapsodic techno freaks, ``bikers,
fetishists, faith healers, visionaries, squatters, druggies,
lunatics and street heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohn is perhaps best known for writing the magazine article that
became the basis for the John Travolta movie ``Saturday Night
Fever'' (he later acknowledged that the article's central character
was a composite figure), and in ``Yes We Have No'' he uses the same
modus operandi he employed in his 1992 book, ``The Heart of the
World.''
</P>
<P>
   That book created a jazzy, street-smart portrait of the New York
demimonde by giving the reader a series of profiles of Broadway's
more colorful denizens, and ``Yes We Have No'' similarly pivots
around portraits of people Cohn met during his travels.
</P>
<P>
   This approach results in a certain overlap with English
travelogues written by Paul Theroux (``The Kingdom by the Sea'')
and Jonathan Raban (``Coasting'') during the 1980s. Once again we
are treated to depressing descriptions of blighted mill towns and
cutesified tourist meccas _ glimpses of a country merchandising its
past, even as it struggles with unemployment, poverty and a lost
sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn, however, focuses more insistently than his predecessors on
the eccentric, the bizarre and the outrageous, and as a result, his
portrait of England feels livelier, more menacing and less
representative than theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, his ``other England'' is a realm of millennial madness,
a world of Elvis impersonators, Hell's Angels and phony New Age
shamans that often seems to have more in common with American
tabloid culture than anything one usually associates with Britain.
</P>
<P>
   It's a world animated by rage and disappointment and defiant
hope, a world defined by the stories Cohn sees in the local papers:
``A man in Carshalton breeds tarantulas in his greenhouse, a man in
Milton Keynes is arrested for sexually molesting a Child of Prague,
a man in Leighton Buzzard claims he can communicate with ET's by
banging out a secret code on his satellite dish, and a Peterborough
grandmother, out walking her Lhasa Apso of a night, sees the Virgin
Mary, nestled among the pork chops and lamb kidneys, in the window
of her family butcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohn's companion on his travels through this surreal England is
a feisty young woman named Mary Carson who plays Virgil to his
Dante, guiding him through the lowlife maze of London's East End,
and accompanying him on a meandering tour through the cities of
northern England. Ms. Carson is not only an eager adventurer, but
as Cohn notes ``has never learned how to patronize,'' and her
infectious enthusiasm makes her a human magnet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment she stops racing, decides to give her boots a
break, people start to gather around her,'' Cohn writes. ``Drunks,
derelicts, Romeos and wide-boys on the make, storytellers,
argufiers and every manner of craicsmith come flocking to feed off
her batteries. Her energy and hunger act on them like instant
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   From King's Cross in London _ a neighborhood where cleanup crews
spend every morning removing ``last night's crop of ads from the
phone boxes'' (``Exotic Asian temptress,'' ``Paula, blonde
transvestite,'' ``Young English Rose'') _ Cohn and Ms. Carson head
off for the ``loafer's paradise'' of Bristol and Cornwall's Fraggle
Rock, a ``New Age travelers' site'' that provides a refuge for
those who have lost their jobs, their homes, their former lives.
</P>
<P>
   Next, it's on to Blackpool, ``a genial, tacky place, peopled by
gypsy fortunetellers and comic landladies,'' and Liverpool, a once
mighty port now reduced to selling its vanished past to the tourist
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester, too, has metamorphosed since Cohn's last visit:
``The mills are gone; so is the grime. The black row houses have
all been sandblasted and are now a tasteful shade of cream.'' As
for the city's moral climate, it seems to have changed as well:
``When I drop into a corner pub,'' Cohn reports, ``the girl pulling
pints is wearing a halter top, cut-offs and no bra. She tells me
that it's a dead-zone here. `No work, no money, no nothing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other people Cohn and Ms. Carson encounter during
their travels are Laurence, a London School of Economics dropout
who has been strung out on crack and smack; a woman named Mary who
has spent the last four months looking for her missing boyfriend
and living on the streets; an Elvis impersonator named Paul Chan
who owns three clubs named Graceland; a right-wing anti-Anti-Nazi
who believes in ``Britain for Britons''; a model named Jess who
supports herself doing S&AMP;M shows, and an artist by the name of
Fista who is serving a five-year term for graffiti banditry.
</P>
<P>
   Because Cohn tosses off these portraits so rapidly, because he
puts so much body language on his prose, because he dwells so
insistently on the most melodramatic aspects of his subjects'
stories, the reader has little opportunity to get a real sense of
who these people are.
</P>
<P>
   They appear less as individuals, interviewed for their own sake,
than as brightly colored pieces of a larger mosaic _ a mosaic meant
to illustrate the author's own idiosyncratic vision of England as a
manic-depressive country: ``a land full of trouble, violent and
dispossessed,'' but also full of ``passion, energy, humor, rage.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `YES WE HAVE NO: Adventures in the Other England'
</P>
<P>
   By Nik Cohn
</P>
<P>
   328 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
