<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS HER PERFECT CRIME UNTIL THE MURDERER CONFESSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review. Time,
channel are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(th) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before its opening credits, ``Happy Face Murders'' displays this
written prologue: ``Most of what you are about to see is true. The
stuff that isn't true is the stuff that's most believable. Go
figure.''
</P>
<P>
   These words, shown among big, yellow smiley faces while an
upbeat singer croons ``Put On a Happy Face,'' promise a story of
quirky wit. And while the film, Showtime's Sunday night feature,
does display some imaginative flair, it can't quite keep its
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, most of what happens in the film is not true but was
invented by the screenwriter, John Pielmeier, whose stage credits
include ``Agnes of God'' and the current Broadway drama ``Voices in
the Dark.'' He began, however, with the real story of a 60-ish
Oregon woman who set out to rid herself of an abusive 40-ish
boyfriend by implicating him in the gruesome murder of a young
woman that she knew he did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony was so convincing that the boyfriend was convicted
for the killing. But she seemed to know so much about the crime
that she was found guilty of being an accomplice. They were in
prison when the real murderer began confessing in anonymous letters
adorned with smiley faces.
</P>
<P>
   Pielmeier changed the location to Michigan and named the woman
Lorraine Petrovich and the boyfriend Rusty Zuvic. Rusty is
portrayed by Nicholas Campbell as a one-dimensional monster: even
if he isn't a murderer, he's rotten enough to be one.
</P>
<P>
   Lorraine, who ought to be the story's center, is portrayed as a
no-dimensional cipher by Ann-Margret. She plays against type as a
dowdy grandmother whose ruse is inspired by ``Matlock'' and ``Perry
Mason.'' But in place of her usual perky sexiness, she exudes,
well, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   What does Lorraine really feel about Rusty and what she has done
to him? How does this seemingly simple, passive woman find the sly
intelligence to mislead the authorities so convincingly? If
Ann-Margret has any ideas, she's not telling.
</P>
<P>
   She is telling her ever changing story of the events surrounding
the death, and that inspires Rusty to keep changing his own version
of the fateful night. He even confesses in a vain attempt to save
himself. Then, for some unexplained reason, Lorraine confesses,
too. Each retelling is dramatized in every grim, gory detail until
the viewer gives up trying to look for the truth.
</P>
<P>
   In the production's publicity notes, the director, Brian
Trenchard-Smith, describes the film as ```Rashomon' meets `Fargo'
by way of `Twin Peaks.''' What, no ``Gone With the Wind'' or ``The
Brady Bunch'' elements?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Trenchard-Smith, whose own films include ``Dead-End
Drive-In'' and ``Leprechaun 4 _ In Space'' was aiming too high. But
he and Pielmeier offer too many stretches of soapy, standard-issue
dramatics where the mordant wit should be. Still, while this effort
never quite comes together, it has its redeeming elements.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them are the wholly fictitious characters of the
investigators who at first believe Lorraine's story and finally
begin to see the holes in it. As a counterpoint to Lorraine and
Rusty, Pielmeier has created another older woman-younger man pair,
but a younger older woman-younger man pair.
</P>
<P>
   Jen Powell (Marg Helgenberger) is a tough, dedicated police
detective (``This job is about passion, not ambition'') with a
heart that's soft enough to take in stray dogs. (One piece of
genuinely quirky humor: She gives the dogs names like Jesse Helms,
Kenneth Starr and Janet Reno.)
</P>
<P>
   Another stray is forced on her when a naive young criminologist,
Dylan McCarthy, becomes her unwanted assistant. Dylan, played by
Henry Thomas (the alien's little pal in ``E.T.''), is a nail-biting
mess when Jen takes him under her wing. In the course of the movie,
the two build a rapport, both professional and personal, as she
helps make a man of him.
</P>
<P>
   In a film that more than earns its R rating with depictions of
sadistic sex entwined with brutal, bloody violence (plus nudity and
coarse language), the only real sexual tension flows between Jen
and Dylan, who genuinely like each other and never so much as
touch. These two characters, and these two actors, could easily
carry a television series.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't quite compensate for the shortcomings of this
movie. When it's over, you understand how much effort went into it,
but you somehow don't care. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HAPPY FACE MURDERS'
</P>
<P>
   Showtime, Sunday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   Written by John Pielmeier and directed by Brian Trenchard-Smith.
Music by Elmer Bernstein. Bert Dunk, director of photography; Ellen
Burditt, co-producer. John Cosgrove and Terry Dunn Meurer,
executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Ann-Margret (Lorraine Petrovich), Marg Helgenberger (Jen
Powell), Henry Thomas (Dylan McCarthy), Nicholas Campbell (Rusty
Zuvic), Rick Peters (Billy Lee Peterson), David McIlwraith (Alan
Sanford), Bruce Gray (Ephraim Quince), J.C. Mackenzie (Ed Baker),
Emily Hampshire (Tracy Billings), Christina Collins (Nancy Severn),
Sean Calvin Dick (Charlie Severn) and Lynne Deragon (Virginia
Billings).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
