r e BC-ANIMALS-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      09-02 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALL THE LITTLE ANIMALS' TOLD SIMPLY, BEAUTIFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Our rating: 3 stars 
By MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
LOS ANGELES _ Against all odds, ``All the Little Animals'' works.
The film combines a first-time screenwriter, Eski Thomas, and a
first-time director, Jeremy Thomas. Granted, the husband-and-wife
team aren't exactly film neophytes: Jeremy Thomas was born into a
filmmaking family and has produced such critically acclaimed
independent films as Bernardo Bertolucci's ``The Last Emperor'' and
David Cronenberg's ``Naked Lunch.'' Still, the two turn what could
have been a heavy-handed manifesto on environmentalism into an
honest and affecting story of a young man's awakening to both his
human potential and the beauty of nature.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The film is based on the book of the same name by Walker
Hamilton, written two decades ago. Bobby (the fine Christian Bale
of ``Metroland'' and ``Velvet Goldmine'') is an upper-class young
Londoner who's somewhat slow and childlike because of a head injury
he suffered in a childhood accident. When the film starts, his
mother, who has been his loving protector and friend, has just
died. He's left in the care of his hateful stepfather, played by
the well-cast Daniel Benzali (of TV's ``Murder One'').
</P>
<P>
   After undergoing some psychological torture by his stepfather
that is, mercifully, fairly brief, Bobby runs away from his
family's palatial London estate. On the road, he meets Mr. Summers,
played by John Hurt with his usual, powerful subtlety. Mr. Summers
has dropped out of society to live in a cabin in the woods; he's
made it his mission to protect animals, and to bury those that have
been killed by cars on the roads.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Summers turns out to be a bit of a case himself: We find out
that he broke from society after committing a murder and taking
money from the bank where he worked. But his kindness toward Bobby
turns out to be just what the young man needs. Bobby comes out of
himself, becoming a much happier and better-adjusted person in his
life with Mr. Summers. There are some lovely moments here, along
with some beautiful nature photography.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Bobby's idyll comes to an end. His stepfather, who
he calls ``The Fat'' but whose real name is De Winter (a bit of
heavy symbolism, glossed over in the film) makes one last attempt
to crush his spirit and his life. But Bobby escapes, and ends up
carrying on the ``work'' of Mr. Summers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fairly simple story, nicely told. Much of it is a little
painful to watch, but in the end, the message is one of hope. The
film's lovely images and gentle message linger. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``All the Little Animals'' (R; violence). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  John Hurt, Christian Bale. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed and produced by Jeremy Thomas.
Screenplay by Eski Thomas. Based on the novel by Walker Hamilton. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 50 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
