u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-02 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOSTALGIA'S SHELF LIFE IS SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John F. Kennedy Jr. died only seven weeks ago, and
his face still adorns slick magazines and quickie paperbacks
seeking to capitalize on the sentimental orgy that followed his
plane crash on a dark night off the coast of Martha's Vineyard,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But the summer's outpouring of grief and nostalgia is already
fading, replaced by the unromantic, gritty reality of the tragedy's
aftermath. His magazine is in such financial trouble that his
sister Caroline may have to ride to the rescue. His mother-in-law
is positioning herself for a possible wrongful death suit. And
training standards for private plane pilots are being scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   We have moved beyond the overblown mourning and myth-recycling
that marked the loss of America's prince and his wife Caroline
Bessette Kennedy on July 16. Our emotions are drained. The
long-running Kennedy family saga still fascinates, but its
relevance to our own busy lives is inherently remote.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar happened in Britain on Tuesday when the second
anniversary of the death of Diana, princess of Wales, passed with
barely a notice. The outpouring of public adoration immediately
after her death with her boyfriend Dodi in a Paris automobile crash
turns out to have been had a short shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy family conducted itself with sorrowful dignity after
JFK Jr.'s death, carefully controlling media access and avoiding
either an overt display of emotion or a regal chilliness that could
have fueled public passion. The Kennedys ducked the public
relations circus that would have been inevitable had they buried
him at Arlington Cemetery near his father and mother, tactfully
sending his body back to the sea instead. They kept television
crews at a distance and refused to authorize high-visibility
commemorative events.
</P>
<P>
   And thus far there is no indication that grim secrets of JFK
Jr.'s private behavior will come tumbling out to tarnish an
admirable image of a decent, if pampered, young life well-lived.
</P>
<P>
   The memory of Diana as glamorous superstar, by contrast, has
been sharply revised by post-mortem revelations that portray her as
erratic, selfish, paranoid and a bit batty. A recent book,
``Diana,'' by Sally Bedell Smith makes a strong case that the
princess was not only a congenital liar but had a borderline
personality disorder and was in desperate need of psychiatric
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Her funeral drew the largest global television audience in
history _ as had her fairytale wedding to Prince Charles 18 years
earlier. People queued up for as many as 16 hours to sign books of
condolences, and 1.3 million bouquets were laid at the steps of the
royal palaces. A memorial fund was set up to provide money for her
favorite charities, and her brother established a for-profit museum
at Althorp, her family home, where she is buried.
</P>
<P>
   But this year there were no special prayer services, no flag was
lowered to half-staff and only a handful of the curious showed up
to peer at the royal palaces. Her charitable fund is dying, plans
for a monument have been shelved and tickets to Althorp go begging.
British bookstores report that Diana biographies are longer big
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles, once the ogre of this story, is now viewed more
kindly and seen frequently in public with his lover Camilla Parker
Bowles. The British, who disapproved of her while Diana was alive,
still don't care much for her but are increasingly receptive to a
possible marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst may be yet to come. Princess Di had admitted to
having an affair with James Hewitt, a cavalry officer who played
polo with Prince Charles. Hewitt has cranked out a kiss-and-tell
book due for publication next month that reportedly includes love
letters written to him by a besotted Diana. The book raises the
possibility that her younger son, Prince Harry, is Hewitt's rather
than Charles' child.
</P>
<P>
   The Windsor family tree has many illegitimate branches, but a
scandal of this megabomb magnitude would polish off Diana's
reputation for good. If DNA tests proved Hewitt's paternity,
motherless Harry would be bumped from the line of royal succession
and the only father he has ever known would be suddenly not
genetically related at all.
</P>
<P>
   Insofar as we know, nothing as dramatic and sordid will appear
to destroy JFK Jr.'s memory now that he is not around to defend
himself. He wisely remained single until he found the woman he
really wanted to marry. He may have used bad judgment on his final
airplane flight but he was not an irresponsible airhead, as Diana
clearly was.
</P>
<P>
   But who knows? President Kennedy's biographies certainly rewrote
history. And the JFK Jr. biographies have yet to be written.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
