<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-ADVOCATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENTS NEED HEALTH ADVOCATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SHERMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you are even thinking about getting sick,
don't! Due to the demands and limits set up mainly by HMOs, medical
care has become sort of the Russian Roulette of client services.
</P>
<P>
   If you happen to push the right button, you get care. If not,
you wait, you wait, you wait and you wait. Just getting in to see
your primary care physician (a.k.a. doctor) is difficult. And if
you need to see a specialist, don't think you can just make an
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   No, first you have to get approved to get a referral. Then you
have to actually get the referral. If it turns out the specialist
never got the referral from your doctor, odds are you won't be seen
on the day of what you thought was your appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the country, medical systems are overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Costs are rising. To help eliminate these problems, the best
thing to cut out, apparently, is the patient. The drill goes like
this: You have a problem with your foot and you need to renew a
prescription painkiller. First you have to call your primary care
physician. You call.
</P>
<P>
   You get a recorded message with a menu of options. All of them
lead to being put on hold. You then wait anywhere from 10 minutes
to half an hour. Once you do get through, you usually speak to a
harried desk person who tells you the doctor has no appointments,
will only be in two days that week, is in surgery or is on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   As to your prescription renewal, you're flatly informed that you
cannot speak directly to your doctor (in case you have a question
about why, after taking your pills, your foot seems to be turning
interesting colors or you have a peculiar tingling feeling when you
wiggle your toes).
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky, you're told you'll be called back by a nurse or
nurse practitioner (don't hold your breath). If you're not so
lucky, you get cut off, and the whole process starts again.
Recently, I tried to renew a painkiller for my husband. He just had
his shoulder rebuilt. He needed more than a bullet to bite on to
relieve the pain. When I called his doctor, I got the usual
plethora of message options.
</P>
<P>
   I tried all of them. What I got was either recorded messages
that cut me off, or references to other recordings (which also cut
me off). When I did manage to reach the prescription renewal line,
that recording informed me that I should call my pharmacist, who,
in turn, should fax the request to the doctor, who would then fax
them the authorization (I never did get to speak to a real person).
</P>
<P>
   After conducting a small (admittedly, unscientific) survey of
pharmacists in the San Francisco Bay Area, I found out that up to
40 percent of doctors now refuse to speak directly to pharmacists
and insist on communicating solely by fax. This means that if the
staff is busy, or in extended meetings (as happened to us), then
they may not even get to the faxes until late that night or the
following day.
</P>
<P>
   Some medical providers are starting to come up with innovative
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser system has instituted an urgent care program for
cases that are not true emergencies but need immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
   You can get an appointment the day you call. It's a step in the
right direction.
</P>
<P>
   But it's only the beginning. What people actually now need are
advocates who can cut through the obstacles and get patients help.
This is true for in-patient (hospital) care as well as for
out-patient cases.
</P>
<P>
   Having an advocate can actually be even more crucial in the
hospital, where patients often are scared and disoriented.
</P>
<P>
   I saw this happen with my father. He had gone into the hospital
solely for observation for possible neurological problems. I was
there when a nurse bustled in, carrying an armful of medical
paraphernalia. When I questioned what she was doing, she said she
had to give my dad a cardiac catheterization.
</P>
<P>
   Being a medical, as well as a general writer, I knew about that
test and told the nurse he didn't need it. Obviously under
pressure, she became angry and ordered me to get out of her way and
out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   When I refused and asked to speak to a doctor, the nurse dashed
out, with a look of intense hate in my direction. She returned 10
minutes later, muttered, ``Wrong patient,'' and fled the room.
</P>
<P>
   Now what would have happened if I hadn't been there to be my
father's advocate that day? It's possible, as he was in a weakened
state, this invasive test could have killed him.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard similar stories from friends and acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   I believe we are left with a clear mandate to push for more
humane care.
</P>
<P>
   We have to pragmatically study how to cut costs without cutting
out the patient. This is why we have legislators and oversight
groups. We can't wait for someone else to get the ball rolling.
It's up to each of us to speak up and push for change.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ruth Sherman, of San Francisco, is a free-lance writer and
filmmaker.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
