<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8782 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SARAH-JESSICA-PARKER-     09-02 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARAH-JESSICA-PARKER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERSATILE ACTRESS DOING ALL RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's a season of extremes for Sarah Jessica
Parker. The summer has been filled with both good news and bad for
the petite, versatile actress, but as she'll be the first to admit,
variety is the catalyst for creativity.
</P>
<P>
   First, the good news. ``Sex and the City,'' the uncensored HBO
comedy series on which she stars and serves as executive
consultant, has earned two Emmy Award nominations _ for outstanding
comedy series and for Parker's own lead performance. Her
actor-husband Matthew Broderick is also having a great year with
the kiddie hit ``Inspector Gadget'' and the critically acclaimed
``Election,'' as well as the successful New York stage run of
``Night Must Fall'' to his credit.
</P>
<P>
   But one of Parker's former boyfriends _ John F. Kennedy Jr. _
died tragically and another _ Robert Downey Jr. _ has been
imprisoned for his drug addiction. And in a far less devastating
development, Parker's own kiddie comedy, a live-action version of
Jay Ward's cartoon classic ``Dudley Do-Right,'' bombed at the box
office.
</P>
<P>
   While she understandably does not wish to dwell on Kennedy's
death and Downey's imprisonment on drug-related charges _ ``I hope
you understand, I think it's inappropriate and vulgar the way
people have talked about all this stuff,'' she says, apologetically
but succinctly _ Parker is typically enthusiastic and loquacious
about other matters.
</P>
<P>
   Even ``Do-Right,'' a broad slapstick farce that's leagues away
from the stage-trained actress's sophisticated norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeal was, as always, to do something different,'' says
Parker, 34, whose films have generally run along the more adult
lines of ``Ed Wood,'' ``Honeymoon in Vegas,'' ``L.A. Story'' and
``Do-Right'' director Hugh Wilson's ``The First Wives Club.''
``There aren't a lot of opportunities for women to do comedy, and
there are fewer opportunities for women to do slapstick comedy. And
it was just, simply, fun _ liberating and silly and a great way to
make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Stalwart Brendan Fraser, who plays the straight-arrow, dimwitted
title Mountie opposite Parker's updated, self-assertive
damsel-in-distress Nell Fenwick, confirmed that the actress was fun
to work with but nonetheless a pro all the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sarah is so funny,'' he says, ``but so intelligent in her
choices. She always has a cool head about her and a real eye on the
ball _ all the time _ when she's making a film.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker's professionalism goes back to childhood, when she began
acting, singing and dancing in stage and television productions in
the Cincinnati area (where, ironically enough, her mom didn't let
her watch TV programs like ``Dudley Do-Right''). She headlined
``Annie'' for two years and, later, enjoyed brief runs on such
acclaimed network series as ``Square Pegs,'' ``A Year in the Life''
and ``Equal Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Parker has focused primarily on film and
Broadway, where she's won raves for ``Once Upon a Mattress,''
``Sylvia'' and the revival of ``How to Succeed in Business Without
Really Trying'' with Broderick.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2-year-old ``Sex in the City'' has brought Parker back
to the tube in a big way, albeit a far different one than she
remembers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change is that there's HBO,'' she says of the cable
network, which is increasingly betting on risky, adult-oriented
original series such as ``The Sopranos'' and ``The Chris Rock
Show,'' and winning plaudits and ratings points by doing so. ``I'm
not opposed to working for network television, but with HBO there
is more freedom. We can straightforwardly discuss sexual issues
from a female point of view and, hopefully, do it in a way that's
really smart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the intensity and the concentration of conversation
that's different,'' Parker says of ``City,'' which co-stars Kim
Cattrall, Cynthia Nixon and Kristin Davis and is very loosely based
on Candace Bushnell's New York Observer column. ``We just haven't
heard women talk this way, which is not like talking in a dirty way
but just sharing and revealing in a funny way _ in an offhanded way
and a serious way and a focused way.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as the title indicates, a sexy way. Copulation and nudity
commonly punctuate the half-hour comic gabfests, although Parker's
character, Carrie _ a sex columnist like Bushnell _ has managed to
remain covered-up and kept her lovemaking techniques to viewer's
imaginations through the first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Sex and the City'' is considered part of the vanguard
of television's new age of explicitness, a label Parker finds
somewhat unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel misunderstood,'' she says with a self-joshing laugh.
``It's easy to make assumptions, because people don't see our show
as much (as they would if it were on a broadcast channel). They
hear `Sex' in the title, which is very provocative and titillating.
But, in fact, if the show were merely soft-core porn, then it
wouldn't have gotten an Emmy nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``And my character has, basically, been with one guy for two
years,'' she adds, correctly. ``I constantly see poor Matthew on
talk shows getting asked, `How do you feel about your wife jumping
in and out of bed on TV?' I think, women jump in and out of bed on
television all the time, and I don't even take my clothes off. But
it's this idea, rather than anything actually seen on the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the attention a hint of scandal brings can be a good
thing, too. Parker is still amazed that her little cable show _
which is shot on film in New York, where she's lived and worked for
more than a decade _ has been appreciated by the L.A.-based Academy
of Television Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   As has she.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my first Emmy nomination, and it's thrilling,'' Parker
says of being a contender for the outstanding actress in a comedy
series statuette (the Emmy Awards will be presented Sept. 12).
``The whole thing was just so unexpected and a wonderful surprise.
I have no illusions about the reality of winning, but in our case,
that old saw of `it's great just to be nominated' really, I feel,
applies. We were so far away, and I didn't know people out here
were paying attention to the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, to have it acknowledged is a thrill. And to be sitting in
the company that we'll be in that night _ we just need to go there
and have a blast, because it may never happen again. Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   With an attitude that sunny, it's little wonder that nothing
much gets Parker down. But can the same be said for Broderick
whenever Parker gets so much attention, actors' egos being what
they are and all?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been making Norman Maine jokes since the day we met,''
Parker laughs, referring to the ``A Star Is Born'' character whose
career self-destructs as his wife's blossoms. ``I still think
they're funny, by the way ... and then I say, (in a tremulous,
melodramatic voice) `I'm Mrs. Matthew Broderick!' But you know
what? Matthew's at a beautiful time in his career. He always
pretends like he'll take any job that comes along, but he only is
not working now because he's picky. It's sort of this routine,
acting like he'll never work again.''
</P>
<P>
   As for herself, getting a taste of producing responsibilities on
``Sex and the City'' may mean Parker will not be working quite the
same way she has in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice _ it's nice! _ to feel that you're part of
something, that you aren't just an actor for hire,'' she says.
``That you have something at stake, and you have some
responsibilities. It makes you care a lot more about everybody
around you, their welfare and their well-being, and the quality of
the show and how it's received.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to go back to just acting; it's like putting a gag
on your mouth. But there is a time and a place for everything, and
I think I can separate the two. I hope so.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
