 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, Sept. 3. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Alexandria, Egypt) _ On her maiden trip to the
Middle East since Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak came to power,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright hit her first snag when the
Israelis and Palestinians failed to deliver a new agreement that
she had hoped to preside over at a signing ceremony Thursday. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ The Kosovo Liberation Army,
scheduled to be dismantled within a few weeks under the U.N.
resolution for demilitarization, is to continue under a different
guise while retaining much of its military command structure. NATO
and U.N. officials, in complex negotiations with the KLA
leadership, have come up with a plan to turn the core of the army
into a civilian emergency service. But KLA leaders inevitably see
the new force as a potential core of a future national army. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LIKUD (Jerusalem) _ Ariel Sharon is poised to complete a
remarkable political comeback if he is elected head of the Likud
party. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WACO-INQUIRY (Washington) _ Developments in the renewed inquiry
into the fatal fire at the Branch Davidian compound near Waco,
Texas, and the FBI's role. By Neil A. Lewis and David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-RENO-FREEH (Washington) _ Janet Reno and Louis J. Freeh
were once portrayed as one of the capital's perfect power pairings
_ a tough, down-to-earth attorney general who was delighted to have
the earnest former prosecutor and judge as the chief law
enforcement officer by her side. But officials who know them both
said the image never really matched the reality. Disclosures that
the FBI failed to produce information from its files about the use
of inflammable tear gas during the 1993 assault on the Branch
Davidian compound has split open a jagged seam of discontent,
seriously dividing Ms. Reno, Freeh and their two agencies. By David
Johnston and Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE-PRICES (Washington) _ As Americans prepare for the last
big long-weekend of summer, experts say the price of gasoline is
about 20 percent higher than it was a year ago. They give two
reasons: refinery fires and OPEC's renewed aggressive pricing. By
David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WINE-ORIGINS (Undated) _ A scandal to shock wine
connoisseurs to the last drop of their being has been uncovered by
the same kind of DNA test as is used in paternity cases. The
Chardonnay grape, considered one of the world's greatest wine
varieties, is a cross between the princely Pinot and a grape deemed
so coarse that it is no longer grown in France, according to an
analysis by American and French scientists. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MARCH (New York) _ City will sharply scale back its police
presence at the Harlem youth rally this year compared to last year,
Police Commissioner Howard Safir told community leaders. The police
will deploy only half the number of officers that were used during
last year's event, and the city will not take several restrictive
measures, like shutting down nearby subway stations. Decision comes
after Harlem leaders called for a muted police response, and
Federal judges recommended a limited police presence. By David
Barstow.
</P>
