<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8831 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SHORTER-CDS-LADN     09-02 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHORTER-CDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LPS GETTING SHORTER AND SHORTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By FRED SHUSTER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Short and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be the motto of more and more artists and producers
today. With compact discs able to hold around 75 minutes of music,
some albums are matching vinyl and clocking in at 40 minutes and
under.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the new Tricky release, ``Juxtapose,'' comes in at
35 minutes. And the recent Latin Playboys disc, ``Dose,'' holds a
little more than the same amount of music.
</P>
<P>
   Latin Playboys member and co-producer Tchad Blake says it's a
case of quality over quantity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like short records,'' Blake said. ``We don't like going
over 45 minutes _ even on someone else's albums. It's been said
that in this case, size (ITAL)does(END ITAL) matter. We like things
that leave you wanting more.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Dose,'' the theory worked.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who is joined in the Latin Playboys by frequent producing
partner Mitchell Froom, plus David Hidalgo and Louie Perez of Los
Lobos, says one of the reasons for the length of the moody ``Dose''
was the way the music was created.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very spontaneous,'' he said. ``We were continually
surprised. Mistakes took us down entirely different avenues than we
expected. We wanted to use only the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   We agree it's always better to have a fully realized record
rather than a couple of good tracks and a lot of filler. But with
the price of CDs averaging between $12 and $17, it would be better
for consumers if music makers aimed for a bit more of the good
stuff. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
MEGA MAN
</P>
<P>
   Top-rated morning show ``John London and the House Party'' has
moved to Mega 100 _ KCMG-FM (100.3) _ from sister station the Beat.
</P>
<P>
   London has appeared on hip-hop station the Beat _ KKBT-FM (92.3)
_ since 1991 and has remained one of the area's most popular
morning hosts for almost three years. Both Mega 100 and the Beat
are owned by Dallas-based AMFM Inc., the nation's largest radio
broadcasting company with 460 stations in 104 markets.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rivers, AMFM's programming chief, said Mega 100's
``jammin' oldies'' format is the best place for the London show to
``expand its audience and gain further exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   London said that ``short of experiencing euphoria, I couldn't
imagine anything more rewarding than continuing to entertain my
fans at ... Mega 100.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1705EDT &QL; 
