<HEADER>
A8859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      09-02 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Mild-Mannered Mountie Turns (Whoops!) Dastardly
</P>
<P>
   Dudley Do-Right
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Fraser, Sarah Jessica Parker, Alfred Molina, Eric Idle,
Alex Rocco, Robert Prosky
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Hugh Wilson
</P>
<P>
   PG _ 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Being Dudley Do-Right ( Fraser), the dim Canadian Mountie based
on Jay Ward's animated character, it's a given that he climbs on
his horse backward and smashes himself in the face by stepping on
loose floorboards. But if he is to best the crafty Snidley Whiplash
(Molina) and secure the affections of Nell Fenwick (Ms. Parker),
Dudley needs a personality do-over.
</P>
<P>
   Snidley is such a popular mustachioed bad guy that his gang is
too large to fit into a bank during a holdup and must crowd around
in the street awaiting word of what is happening inside. In his
role as illegitimate businessman he seeds the streams of Semi-Happy
Valley with enough gold to start a rush that will enrich his many
interests.
</P>
<P>
   What Do-Right can't understand (or part of what he can't
understand) is why everybody loves Snidley. Even Nell hedges her
bets and rides Snidley's arm at the lavish Las Vegas-style floor
shows he puts on with the Kumquat Indians. Then Dudley's ragtag
prospector friend (Idle) comes through with this piece of useful
advice: Quit being so nice and get dangerous. Suddenly in black
leather, Do-Right jumps on a big dirt bike and rallies the Kumquats
for a battlefield showdown. At least Nell gets a kick out of it.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ Snidley does things like set up meetings between the
railroad and the bank president _ i.e., tying the bank president to
the tracks _ and he stages a Normandy-type frontal assault on
Dudley and the Kumquats, who take to the trees and throw rocks. But
these are buffoons at play in a plainly unreal context, and if
people are hurt, they don't stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ Whiplash is after what Nell has to offer in this
department and Dudley, if he is even aware of sex, might be too,
but despite some passing references (``Is Dudley studly?'') nothing
develops.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ An off-color exclamation or two, but really none to
speak of.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 _ They're a little young, but some children get some
big laughs from the simpler silly business.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-10 _ They'll love it.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP _ Viewers reared with the Ward characters Rocky,
Bullwinkle and George of the Jungle will appreciate some of the
subtler elements here. Some teen-agers will gravitate; others
won't.
</P>
<P>
   A Dog of Flanders
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy James Kissner, Jesse James, Jack Warden, Jon Voight,
Farren Monet, Madyline Sweeten, Cheryl Ladd
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kevin Brodie
</P>
<P>
   PG _ 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Another film version of Ouida's classic tale hits every
conceivable he's-up-he's-down element of children's heroic
storytelling with total predictability and overwhelming
sentimentality. First there is a mother, Anna (Ms. Ladd),
staggering with a babe in arms through a blizzard to Grandpa's
cottage, where she expires after exhorting the old man ( Warden) to
raise the boy, named Nello, with her memory in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Anna was an artist of unrecognized talent, and it is apparent
that her small son (played by both Jeremy James Kissner and Jesse
James) has the same bent and then some. But for the most part
Nello's life is restricted to Grandpa's milk run.
</P>
<P>
   So call central casting. Cue the little friend, Aloise (Farren
Monet and Madyline Sweeten), and a large, shaggy dog, Patrasche,
who is found beaten by the roadside. Cue the nasty landlord, who
threatens to boot Nello and Grandpa into the street if they don't
come up with the rent. Cue Patrasche's brutal and drunken former
owner, who wants the animal back.
</P>
<P>
   On the brighter side, Nello gets noticed by the renowned painter
Michel La Grande ( Voight). Everybody worships Peter Paul Rubens
(the artist having come from these parts) and with Michel's fervent
encouragement, Nello decides to enter the Rubens competition.
``Genius is a greatness that burns like an eternal flame,'' says
Nello's new benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   Right, but stand by for a packed agenda of bad turns and good:
an accusation of arson; the actual eviction, with Nello getting
tossed out into yet another blizzard; the appearance of Rubens in a
feverish vision. Is Nello really a rich kid?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ Defending Nello, Patrasche attacks his former owner
and kills him (by accident, naturally), and the maltreatment of
people is violent in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ None.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE _ In a film headed quickly for the video racks, a sense
of deja vu may stem from the fact that this story has been aped, or
at least cannibalized for parts, by other children's stories. In
any event, it all seems shopworn by now.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 _ Anna's death and some of Nello's other tribulations
will upset small children, who will be at sea anyway, particularly
during all the tiresome moralizing.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-10 _ Younger viewers in this category may sit still, but
many older ones will be longing for the exit.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP _ Too gloppy and paralyzingly old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   Chill Factor
</P>
<P>
   Cuba Gooding Jr., Skeet Ulrich, Peter Firth, David Paymer
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Hugh Johnson
</P>
<P>
   R _ 110 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Some standard very-late-summer action fodder finds two low-end
heroes, Arlo ( Gooding) and Mason ( Ulrich), trying to keep a
chemical weapon container from rising above 50 degrees. Otherwise
it will blow and kill three million people. Make that five million.
</P>
<P>
   That's right _ ``Speed,'' only Fahrenheit. Standing between the
boys and their bags of ice cubes is Brynner ( Firth), an embittered
Army man who wants to sell the material for $100 million. Unjustly
held responsible for a slight eruption of the weapon (18 dead)
during tests on a Pacific island, Brynner served 10 years at
Leavenworth. Now he has emerged with a murderous crew of commandos
and without much of his sanity.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, a fly fisherman and soda jerk with an arrest record
(vagrancy and the like), is a nice enough lad. Arlo does a lot of
mugging (to suit Gooding), talks in obscene cliches and comes with
an ice cream truck, which is handy for refrigeration. The
government sends in the Rangers. Yes, we're up to 49 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ Flesh melts at contact with the chemical, and there
are plenty of explosions, shootings and throat slashings.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ Base and plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 11 _ The heroes are overgrown adolescents and the film
is often played for laughs, which will make it appealing. But no.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-14 _ Remember the R rating, but this film is no more
objectionable than countless others just like it. That doesn't make
it suitable, however. Parents' decision.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP _ It's the usual story: children who want to see
the film probably will.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
