<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JAR-THEATER-2TAKES-NY     09-02 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAR-THEATER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLING IT LIKE IT IS, KNOCKING 'EM DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps the funniest moment in ``Jar the Floor,'' a
play packed with insults, put-downs and four generations' worth of
familial invective, comes without a word being spoken.
</P>
<P>
   It happens midway through the first act. Lola, a snappy
grandmother, and MaDear Dawkins, a feisty great-grandmother, are
shocked into near-paralysis by the appearance of Vennie, Lola's
bald granddaughter, and her friend, an over-eager divorcee whose
first stab at rapport involves an offer to show off her mastectomy
scar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor to meet you, Ms. Dawkins,'' the visitor says.
``Would you like me to take off my shirt so you might have a better
look?''
</P>
<P>
   MaDear's mouth drops open, Lola's eyes go wide, and the
audiences generally go crazy.
</P>
<P>
   The women responsible for this stunned silence are Lynne Thigpen
(as Lola) and Irma P. Hall (as MaDear), two accomplished actresses
receiving some of the best reviews of their careers as a mother and
daughter with plenty to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   The revival of ``Jar the Floor,'' a serious family comedy by
Cheryl L. West at the nonprofit Second Stage, has been extended
through Sept. 12, and there is talk of a longer, commercial run at
a larger theater. Set around MaDear's 90th birthday party, ``Jar
the Floor'' tells the story of four generations of African-American
women, each with a few opinions about how the others are living
their lives. The title refers to MaDear's belief that her dead
husband's spirit can rattle the floorboards.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been praise for the rest of the five-woman
ensemble, which includes Regina Taylor, Welker White and Linda
Powell, many critics have singled out the work of Ms. Hall and Ms.
Thigpen.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in The New York Times, Peter Marks said the play left
audiences ``feeling unexpectedly lighthearted,'' an effect that
``can be traced to the vitality of the performances, starting with
Ms. Thigpen's dynamite Lola and extending to Ms. Hall's
cantankerous MaDear.'' David Kaufman of The Daily News wrote that
``both Hall and Thigpen are giving performances bound to be
remembered at awards time.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways Ms. Thigpen and Ms. Hall seem to represent two
stock characters in theatrical mythology: the veteran and the
newcomer to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thigpen, after all, has adorned stages both on and
off-Broadway for nearly 30 years, dating to a role in the original
production of ``Godspell.'' In 1997 she won a Tony for her work in
``An American Daughter,'' by Wendy Wasserstein.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hall, may be a new face to New York audiences, but she has
had considerable experience elsewhere, both in the living theater
and the theater of living. A grandmother and former Dallas
public-school teacher, she followed a roundabout path over almost
30 years that led her from amateur theatricals in Texas to the New
York stage, where she is making her debut.
</P>
<P>
   On the set of ``Jar the Floor'' it is Ms. Hall who is the
veteran, and with good reason: not only has she played the role of
grandmother in real life, but it is her eighth production of the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the character, but I don't know her completely,'' said
Ms. Hall, 64, speaking of the 90-year-old MaDear. ``But I've been
studying her a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of ``Jar the Floor,'' Marion McClinton, said Ms.
Hall also offered a dose of realism for the other cast members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Irma is that she carries a history for an
entire generation of women with her,'' McClinton said. ``She is the
real deal. There's a lot of actresses that attempt the Southern
matriarch, but she knows what that is because she is one.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thigpen, he said, offered another type of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's like having Magic Johnson on the team,'' he said.
``She's seeing the whole play, not only her character. There
weren't too many times I had to explain anything to her. She'd say,
`Oh, I got ya,' and then come back with something even better than
I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. West says the play is not autobiographical, but that the
characters are made up of ``bits and pieces of people I've known.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are recognizable women, women you may have passed on the
street,'' she said. ``But oftentimes they are only secondary
characters in plays and movies.''
</P>
<P>
   First produced at Parkland College, in Champaign, Ill., in 1989,
``Jar the Floor'' has played in more than two dozen regional
theaters but has never been seen in New York. For several years
after her play ``Before It Hits Home'' was poorly received at the
Public Theater in 1992, Ms. West avoided having any New York
productions of her work. But at Second Stage, where `'Jar the
Floor'' began in late July, crowds have been running at
near-capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. West's most flamboyant creation is Lola, a former good-time
girl whose first remark to her daughter _ ``You look like somebody
walked on your face last night and they left tracks'' _ pretty much
sums up her attitude toward mothering.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thigpen says she embraced the role of Lola immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's big, and she lives large,'' said Ms. Thigpen, with a
mischievous smile. ``My first impression when I read it was, `How
do you get the energy to do her?' But it's like a locomotive train:
it just gets on track and goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of Ms. Thigpen's career. She arrived in
New York in 1971 as a graduate-school dropout with dreams of
acting, and just three months later landed her first job, in a
little off-Broadway musical called ``Godspell,'' composed by
Stephen Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start singing until I got to New York,'' Ms. Thigpen
said. ``I went to one singing teacher. He said: `What do you want?
You can sing.'''
</P>
<P>
   She appeared in the off-Broadway run of ``Godspell'' as well as
the national tour and the film. She finally quit the show _ ``I had
enough `Godspell''' _ and suffered her first, and only, serious
doubts about her choice of profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no job for a year,'' she said. ``I couldn't pay someone
to hire me.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The drought was broken by her Broadway debut, in ``The Magic
Show,'' another show with music by Schwartz. Other Broadway roles
followed, including one in ``Timbuktu!'' with Eartha Kitt.
</P>
<P>
   Her critical breakthrough came in 1980, in ``Tintypes,'' a
pastiche of early-20th-century songs performed by actors playing
the entertainers, politicians and other public figures of that era.
(Critics have since said it seemed to be a forerunner of the
musical ``Ragtime.'') The show's reviews were mixed, but one
performer stood out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her name is Lynne Thigpen,'' wrote Walter Kerr in The New York
Times, ``and I don't even have to tell you to keep an eye on her
because you'll find it impossible not to.''
</P>
<P>
   With a strong jaw, piercing eyes and an aura of perpetual poise,
Ms. Thigpen still cuts a striking figure. Her voice suggests deep
reservoirs of control and passion, elements on display in her
performance in ``Jar the Floor'' and ones that have also led to a
successful career as a voice-over artist.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thigpen was nominated for a Tony for ``Tintypes,'' and the
stream of acting jobs continued, including parts in August Wilson's
``Fences'' on Broadway and on the television shows
``Thirtysomething'' and ``L.A. Law.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s she took on a role that made her famous, to
children at least. The part was Chief, the dogged detective on the
PBS show ``Where in the World Is Carmen Sandiego?,'' inspired by
the computer mystery-quiz game in which a master criminal is
stalked to exotic locales. The show ran from 1991 to 1996, a period
during which Ms. Thigpen was nominated for four Emmy Awards and
commonly stopped on the street with geography questions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hall was one of her fans. ``It does just happen that I love
geography,'' she said. ``I'd been watching it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hall's career involved a little traveling, too. Born in a
rural Texas town in 1935 and reared in Chicago, Ms. Hall says her
early life progressed pretty much according to plan: a husband, two
children, a job teaching French and Spanish at a local high school.
</P>
<P>
   But performance was in her blood; her father had been a
saxophone player, a side man in jazz clubs on Chicago's South Side.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, at the urging of Raymond St. Jacques, a director and
actor, Ms. Hall auditioned for a low-budget movie, ``Book of
Numbers,'' about a gambling racket in a Depression-era town.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that she helped found the Dallas Minority
Repertory, a community theater where she raised money during the
day and acted at night.
</P>
<P>
   She says she was not exactly sure what she was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd draw pictures of the stage for me,'' she said. ``I
didn't know upstage from outdoors.''
</P>
<P>
   With a sugary Texan drawl, grandmotherly demeanor and a quick,
infectious smile, Ms. Hall won small parts in an array of films,
plays and television shows, and on stage. By 1984, with her
children grown, she retired from teaching to pursue acting full
time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987 she returned to Chicago to care for her ailing parents.
When her mother died, her father delivered a playful ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `All right, time to go to work,''' Ms. Hall said,
noting that she had initially doubted that she had the acting
skills required for important national productions. But her first
major role, as a grandmother in the play ``Zandile,'' won her a
Joseph Jefferson Award, Chicago's highest acting honor. A year
later she won her second Jefferson Award playing a Trinadadian tap
dance student in ``Steppin' Out,'' at the Steppenwolf Theater
Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she's been working ever since,'' Ms. Thigpen interjected,
with a laugh and a note of pride. Ms. Hall laughed, too, and
bashfully said: ``It's true. I can't believe it, but it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of her stage time during the 1990s has been in productions
of ``Jar the Floor,'' including runs at the Old Globe in San Diego
and at Syracuse Stage. But none of those peregrinations led to New
York. In 1995 Ms. Hall received strong reviews for her performance
in the film ``A Family Thing,'' playing Aunt T., an 88-year-old
woman who eases the tension between a black man and a white man who
learn they are half-brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being all these different people,'' she said. ``So long
as they're old people. I love old people.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Ms. Hall and Ms. Thigpen say the ensemble of ``Jar the
Floor'' has become as tight-knit as the family on stage but without
the vitriol. Cast members often share jokes and smokes in the
stairwells outside their dressing rooms, and Ms. Hall has let them
all peek at her ``Me'n'book,'' a collection of photos of Ms. Hall
with fellow actors.
</P>
<P>
   In a play steeped in mothers, daughters and the detritus of
love, such a connection is almost inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all bonded very quickly,'' Ms. Hall said. ``This play
always seems to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
