<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MET-CHINESE-EXHIBIT-(     09-02 2019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-CHINESE-EXHIBIT-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: CHINA'S PASSION, BRUSH STROKE BY BRUSH STROKE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is no art in the world more passionate than
Chinese painting. Beneath its fine-boned brush strokes, ethereal
ink washes and subtle mineral tints flow feelings and ideas as
turbulent as those in any Courbet nude or Baroque Crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have always understood art's power. Through it,
rulers advertised their political might and artists registered
their loyalty or resistance. In the ceaseless copying of ancient
masterworks, a unified cultural identity _ some essence of
Chinese-ness _ was invented, reconfirmed, exalted and passed on,
like DNA, from one generation to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, through painting and the closely related art of
calligraphy, the most intense personal emotions, however lofty or
abject, are given voice. Joy and fury, pride and regret, hilarity
and fear are all within its ken, and cannot be as forcefully
expressed in any other medium.
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder that the practice of art in China is regarded as
a total-immersion vocation, that collecting is an obsessive and
intensely competitive pursuit and that the field of connoisseurship
_ the sorting out of good from bad, real from fake and the many
shades between _ is potentially explosive terrain.
</P>
<P>
   All of these passions, heightened by the aftershocks of a recent
furor, figure in ``The Artist as Collector: Masterpieces From the
C.C. Wang Family Collection,'' an exhibition of nearly 100
paintings, many of exceptional beauty, that opens Friday at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Maxwell K. Hearn, curator of Asian art, the
paintings fill the museum's Chinese galleries and trace the
evolution of the phenomenally coherent art tradition of which they
are a part. They also share another bond; with two exceptions, they
all are, or once were, the property of the artist and collector
C.C. Wang.
</P>
<P>
   Wang, 92, was born in Suzhou, studied art in Shanghai, has had a
long and fecund career as a painter and now lives in Manhattan.
(Nine of his works appear at the end of the show.) But he is best
known locally for having amassed one of the world's premier private
collections of Chinese classical painting.
</P>
<P>
   Painting, collecting and dealing in art have traditionally gone
hand in hand in China, and Wang has sold much of his collection
over the years. (He has also invested in real estate.) Many of his
pieces have found a home at the Met, including 60 works in the
show. These have been supplemented for the occasion by a handful of
Wang-provenance works from other institutions, loans from the
collector himself and a group of 12 paintings bought in 1997 by a
Met trustee, Oscar Tang, who has promised them to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   One of these gifts _ a towering ink-on-silk scroll over seven
feet tall, titled ``The Riverbank'' and depicting a mountainous
landscape about to be engulfed by a storm _ set off controversy
when it made its public debut two years ago with the opening of the
museum's new Chinese galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The Met introduced it as a work by the 10th-century painter Dong
Yuan, a near-mythical figure who shaped one of the foundational
styles of Chinese landscape tradition. As such, it represented a
tremendous museological coup. But almost immediately sharply
dissenting opinions were heard.
</P>
<P>
   James Cahill, retired professor of Chinese art at the University
of California at Berkeley, who had expressed doubts about the piece
as early as 1980, publicly denounced it as fake and assigned it to
the 20th-century painter, collector and forger extraordinaire Zhang
Daqian (1899-1983). Sherman Lee, retired director of the Cleveland
Museum of Art, backed him up. Phrases like ``China-gate'' began to
pop up on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Debates about authenticity have always been part and parcel of
art in China, where ``originals'' are often chimerical things,
creative copies are revered as supreme masterpieces and
distinctions between copying and forging are fuzzy, sometimes
depending on questions of intention rather than on demonstrable
fact.
</P>
<P>
   But ``fake'' is a word that sends chills through Western
museums, especially when leveled at a high-profile work. The Met,
insistent that it has the genuine article in ``The Riverbank,'' has
put the painting front and center in the current show, accompanied
by a battery of supporting materials.
</P>
<P>
   These include the records of physical analysis to determine age,
and a full-size digital photograph to reveal the scope of
draftsmanship obscured by the darkened silk. (The details that
emerge are amazing.) Also on hand, borrowed from the British
Museum, is a bona-fide Zhang Daqian forgery, a ``10th-century''
landscape actually cooked up sometime around 1951.
</P>
<P>
   What to conclude?
</P>
<P>
   The museum's brief on behalf of its work is highly persuasive.
But for the present it may be wise to suspend judgment until Cahill
and Lee have made their case, which they are to do at a public
symposium at the Met on Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the results will probably be inconclusive. Arguments
like these can spin out forever and all kinds of peripheral
elements _ personalities, grudges, reputations, academic
in-fighting, not to mention the limitations of science _ have to be
considered. So the is-it-or-isn't furor is likely to rage (or
murmur) on.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though, the Met has surrounded its enigmatic colossus
of a scroll with some extraordinary company: a cluster of
distinguished guests, dozens of familiar faces (the show is
essentially a thematic rotation of the permanent collection with
things added), and a half-dozen of the Tang gifts making their
house debut.
</P>
<P>
   One new arrival is the ``Palace Banquet,'' a narrative painting
by an unidentified artist that has been dated to the politically
unstable years of the late 10th and early 11th century. A large
rectangular piece, delicately colored, it probably was once part of
a screen and depicts a flurry of activity taking place within an
imperial harem just before a ruler's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The narrative, paced with an eye to suspense, starts toward the
upper right corner, where a young girl is unbolting the gate to the
walled compound. Below, on an open gallery, a table is set with
wine cups and plates. Musical instruments stand at the ready. At
the very center of the picture a woman tiptoes into an inner room
to wake someone _ presumably the emperor's favorite concubine _ who
is seen asleep on a tousled bed.
</P>
<P>
   Various clues suggest that the dinner party is meant to
celebrate the Chinese equivalent of Valentine's Day, when two
prominent stars in the Milky Way move into amorous alignment. The
soft evening light and fluttering figures dressed in coral and
malachite green set up a buzz of slightly breathless sensual
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the real subject here may be a cautionary one. The women
wear the fashions of the earlier Tang dynasty, during which an
emperor had nearly lost his throne through his desperate
infatuation with a consort. (The woman was finally executed at the
insistence of a mutinous palace guard.) ``Palace Banquet'' may have
been a warning to future rulers not to let history repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The other standout figurative work in the show is of a later
date. Titled ``Liu Chen and Ruan Zhao in the Tiantai Mountains,''
it is an ink-on-paper hand scroll by the painter Zhao Cangyun, who
worked in the Yuan, or Mongol, Dynasty of the late 12th and early
13th century at a time when many artists felt that the China as
they had known it had come to a catastrophic end.
</P>
<P>
   The scroll tells of two ordinary men (one carries a basket and a
hoe) who stop one day to sample peaches from a roadside tree and
suddenly find themselves whisked off to a never-never Land
accessible through a cleft in a rock.
</P>
<P>
   There they are cosseted by nymphs and served ambrosial meals,
but they grow restless and ask to leave. A mistake. Once outside,
they discover that seven generations have passed in their absence;
the world is in chaos. They try to return to paradise, but cannot
find the way. Like the Chinese under the Mongol rule, the
implication is they are now strangers in a strange land.
</P>
<P>
   By this point in Chinese art, landscape had, in fact, supplanted
the figure in importance. Yet the narrative impulse never stopped.
One sees it at work in a hanging scroll by the Yuan artist Wu Zhen
titled ``Lofty Virtue Reaching the Sky.'' In it, willow trees
droop, bamboo shoots bend low, and lines of poetry fall like rain
to create an emblem of spiritual endurance against impossible odds.
There isn't a figure in sight, but the picture is saturated with
human emotion.
</P>
<P>
   No artist more distinctively transformed landscape into a state
of mind than Ni Zan (1306-1374), who experienced first-hand the
cataclysmic shift from the Yuan to the Ming Dynasty. He led a
harried existence, living on a houseboat to elude tax collectors.
His paintings are houseboat-size: small, neat-as-a-pin images of
slender trees _ he may have meant them as ``portraits'' of friends
_ set against immaculate expanses of water and sky. In his work, a
messy, violent, adversarial world is given order through art.
</P>
<P>
   Four paintings by Ni Zan are set side by side in the show; some
50 by him survive. It is hard to imagine a better candidate for a
one-man museum show, a la Vermeer, than this artist. He's a
``personality'' painter of a most engaging kind (cranky,
melancholic, funny); his style has instant recognition value, and
Western audiences long accustomed to the variations-on-a-theme mode
of the Impressionist landscape might well be persuaded to give him
a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The febrile, tuning-fork quiver that his work sets up vibrates
elsewhere in the show, sometimes amplified to a volanic pitch. In
``Simple Retreat,'' a tall, narrow scroll by Wang Meng, an artist
who survived briefly into the Ming period, piled-up mountains,
creased with deep, soft folds, resemble a giant beast in the throes
of a convulsion, exuding waterfalls like tears and gasping for air.
</P>
<P>
   It is, at least in part, a crushing, foreboding vision. (Wang
himself, accused of treason, died in a Ming prison.) But within its
tumult, there is joy. Toward the bottom of the scroll, a tiny man
takes a stroll with his pet deer. Another man feeds a snack to a
crane, who dances a little jig. A third man, inside a house,
cradles a magic plant in his hand and sits very still, as if
listening to something but unworried by what he hears. This is a
Peaceable Kingdom, Daoist-style, as carefree as summer even as
autumn touches the trees with vermilion.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition wall label notes the close resemblance in form and
spirit between this magnetic picture and ``The Riverbank.'' That
Wang Meng should closely emulate the work of the long-dead but
titanic master Dong Yuan makes perfect sense. Countless artists
before him had done so and countless others have since.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a set of album pages still owned by Wang, the 17th-century
virtuoso Shitao tosses off audacious riffs on a dozen Old Masterish
themes and creates a Brice Marden in the bargain. Wang himself,
under his Chinese name Wang Jiqian, carries the tradition into the
present.
</P>
<P>
   Of the paintings by him installed in the lobby just outside the
Chinese galleries, some emulate the luminaries of the past, Dong
Yuan, Ni Zan and Wang Meng among them. Others address the
particular dynamics of modern Western abstraction and retain only
the ghost of calligraphic forms.
</P>
<P>
   Wang is still painting (one piece on view was finished last
year) and though he has stopped collecting, his passionately
acquisitive, discriminating eye is still, directly and indirectly,
shaping the version of Chinese art seen in Western museums today.
</P>
<P>
   Can he have been deceived in ``The Riverbank,'' a work he has
long called his greatest possession? More will be revealed in that
department in December. Meanwhile the Met's Chinese galleries offer
a rich and unimpeachable experience for mind and heart alike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
