<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RAZZLE-THEATER-REVIEW     09-02 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAZZLE-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ON THE RAZZLE': FINDING A PERFECT MATCH, THANK YOU, WITHOUT
DOLLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine ``Hello, Dolly'' without Dolly Levi, written
by Tom Stoppard in a Catskills-comic style that makes his
``Shakespeare in Love'' script look like Chekhov, and you have ``On
the Razzle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up this morning feeling like a new man, so I got one,''
announces Zangler (Harris Berlinsky), the owner of a
fancy-groceries shop somewhere near Vienna in the 19th century.
When Sonders (Jolie Garrett) announces, ``I love your niece,''
Zangler responds, puzzled, ``My knees, sir?'' You get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Razzle'' is a little odd, but the Jean Cocteau
Repertory has given it a lively production, one that builds to a
satisfying fever pitch by the time all the mistaken identities are
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the actors are playing everything too broad, but if
you're in the mood for vaudeville, with a few touches of bawdy
double-entendre, you'll be in heaven. If not, you may need a quick
fix of ``Travesties'' to make the world right again.
</P>
<P>
   The story goes back to the original source of ``Hello, Dolly,''
not Thornton Wilder's play ``The Matchmaker'' but the 19th-century
Austrian farce that Wilder based it on: ``Einen Jux Will Er Sich
Machen'' (loosely, ``He's Out for a Fling'') by Johann Nestroy.
</P>
<P>
   The two young men on the town are Zangler's sales clerks:
Christopher (Tim Deak), a callow young apprentice, and the more
mature, more experienced Mr. Weinberl (Craig Smith), who, by the
way, is having an anonymous epistolary romance that began with a
lonelyhearts advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Zangler has just hired a new servant, Melchior (Jason Crowl, who
has exactly the right deadpan tone and attitude and steals most of
his scenes), and instructed him to arrange a romantic dinner for
Zangler and his fiancee, Mme. Knorr (Elise Stone), at the Imperial
Gardens Cafe in Vienna. Zangler has other things on his mind, like
his niece Marie (Jennifer Lee Dudek), whose guardian he is (``My
ward.'' ``My word!'' ``No, my ward.''), who reciprocates the love
of the far too poor Sonders.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Mr. Weinberl is posing as the husband of Mrs. Fischer
(Angela Madden, who is excellent), a customer of Mme. Knorr's, and
everyone ends up at the Imperial Gardens. Around this time the play
seems to deteriorate into one of the less funny sketches from ``The
Carol Burnett Show,'' but it recovers because Stoppard will beat
you over the head with silliness until you have to admit it's
funny.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sub-subplot about a coachman and a French maid. There
is some frantic concern about the dinner check. And there are
several mentions of an accident on a horse tram on the
Bahnhofstrasse, which leads to a revelation (reminiscent of last
year's romantic summer film ``You've Got Mail''), and just about
everyone ends up happy and paired off.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the niece, who has run away to Vienna, wearing a
long Scotch plaid cape. (Things Scottish having been all the rage
at the time, as the audience learns.) ``I think,'' Mr. Weinberl
pronounces, ``the tartan fad has had its fling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Razzle'' continues at the Bouwerie Lane Theater, with a
schedule that varies from week to week, through Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ON THE RAZZLE'
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Stoppard; directed by Scott Shattuck; sets by Robert J.
Martin; costumes by Susan Soetaert; lighting by Giles Hogya; music
composed by Ellen Mandel; production manager, Jonathan R. Polgar;
sound by Jason Crowl. Presented by the Jean Cocteau Repertory,
David Fuller, producing artistic director. At Bouwerie Lane
Theater, 330 Bowery St.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Craig Smith (Weinberl), Tim Deak (Christopher), Jolie
Garrett (Sonders), Harris Berlinsky (Zangler), Jason Crowl
(Melchior), Jennifer Lee Dudek (Marie), Angela Madden (Mrs.
Fischer) and Elise Stone (Mme. Knorr).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
