<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8893 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-CHAPPELL05-COX     09-02 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CHAPPELL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chappell's Kirkman finale heartfelt but hesitant
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    By Eileen M. Drennen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At his best, North Carolina poet laureate Fred Chappell crafts
the kind of novels other writers greet with envy. A natural
storyteller who hails from Appalachia, he weaves together tall
tales, dreams and visions, and page upon page of pitch-perfect
dialogue into a style that's like the white-lightnin' cousin of
magical realism.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, ``Look Back All the Green Valley'' isn't Fred
Chappell at his best. The fourth and final chapter of the Kirkman
family story cycle _ which has unfolded in the luminous novels ``I
Am One of You Forever,'' ``Brighten the Corner Where You Are'' and
``Farewell I'm Bound to Leave You'' _ is the weakest link. But
perhaps it was foolish to think he could top the heights of those
books, where fact and fiction danced into hills and hollers, and
nature was a mirror of the human heart.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three books, Chappell's fictional alter ego, Jess
Kirkman, acted as central observer of one of the wildest family
trees in recent memory. As a child, most of what he recounted of
kin near and far came straight from the mouths of his grandmother
Annie Barbara, mother Cora or father Joe Robert, and readers grew
accustomed to a rich stew of voices.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Valley,'' Jess is all grown up, a teacher of English at a
North Carolina college, poet and fledgling translator of Dante. His
pen name is Fred Chappell, he likes cabernet in the afternoon and
drives a yellow Toyota called Buttercup. In 1979, he has returned
to the mountain town of his boyhood to help his sister Mitzi tie up
a few loose family ends: what to do about their mother's failing
health; how to unravel the riddles of their father's cobwebbed
workroom, still intact 10 years after his death; how to ensure that
their parents' wishes to be buried side by side are honored _ even
though the family cemetery claims to be out of room.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Jess visits his father's workroom, he is
overwhelmed by ``an ache of loss ... particular sudden moments of
sorrow that hurt like saw teeth across a careless thumb.''
</P>
<P>
   He looks up from the dusty collection of notebooks and
half-formed inventions, out the window into a sunlit meadow, and
realizes, ``The past is never obliterate; it has a patient,
enduring existence where it collects like groundwater in holes and
crevices and hidden lodgements _ in attics and basements, in sealed
trunks and stubborn drawers, in closets and pockets and in
cardboard folders. In these places, its visible colors are bland,
but its secret strength gathers like thunderheads.''
</P>
<P>
   Jess looks for the patient, enduring existence of his father's
inner life in what he left behind, in hopes of bringing him back,
in a way. He goes on wild goose chases through mountain towns named
Featherbed and Sassiefat, enlisting friends and relatives to help
him retrace his father's last travels and encounters. If he can
only connect the dots, he seems to think, he can puzzle out the
riddle that was Joe Robert Kirkman.
</P>
<P>
   One of his father's burning quests was to transform the way
humans understood time. It wasn't, he believed, neat units ticked
off in seconds, hours and days, but ``a living thing, connected
with the cosmos.'' He labored to invent something he called a
``sympathetic horologue'' that could track the motion of time more
organically. If he could succeed, clock shopkeeper and old friend
Dilly Elden confides to Jess, ``it would enable us to live two or
more lives at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Chappell's gift has been that he's allowed us to share so many
memorable lives over the course of this tenderly constructed cycle
of stories. He brought the past to life in a way that was original
and true. In the present of 1979, he seems at a disadvantage. Maybe
the main problem is that the adult Jess does too much of the
talking, and not in the easy prose of the earlier works but in the
self-conscious style of someone who's trying too hard to be
natural.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, when Chappell resorts to the supernatural _ as
when the wind blows the clocks awry in the house where his
grandmother lies dying in ``Farewell I'm Bound to Leave You'' _ it
has been in the service of a larger emotional truth. Time is
forever altered when someone you love dies. But here, his
surrealistic denouement _ involving space travel, roses and a
graveyard joke _ feels uncharacteristically forced. He's in the
same landscape of love and sorrow, but he's lost his footing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Look Back All the Green Valley. By Fred Chappell. Picador. $24.
279 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An uncharacteristic misstep.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen M. Drennen is Dixie Living editor for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
