<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8894 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-NONFICTION05-CO     09-02 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NONFICTION05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biblical scholarship among works of nonfiction
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Jesus: Apocalyptic Prophet of the New Millennium by Bart D.
Ehrman (Oxford University Press, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Amid the simmering debate about teaching the Bible in public
schools, few pundits point out the obvious: The Bible is chock-full
of history that is independently and multiply attested to in
non-theological sources. You won't find many people railing against
the teaching of history.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrman, a professor at the University of North Carolina, uses
some of those historical facts to bolster his theory that Jesus was
an apocalypticist. He asserts that Jesus believed that the world
would come to an end within the lifetime of those to whom he
preached.
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting theory and one that Ehrman puts forth
convincingly. The most interesting aspect of his book, however, is
his entertaining examination of the evidence. It's as fine and
succinct a gathering of the voluminous Jesus scholarship as you're
likely to find.
</P>
<P>
   He begins with a short history of apocalyptic prophesy in
reverse chronological order, from recent times to the years just
after Jesus' death. There follows a page-turning cataloging of what
we know, historically speaking, and what we don't or can't know. He
explains the biblical sources in a clear and understandable way.
Even more remarkable for a work of this type, he enlivens the way
with welcome doses of levity among the erudition.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For Common Things: Irony, Trust, and Commitment in America
Today by Jedediah Purdy (Knopf, $22).
</P>
<P>
   Alanis Morissette was castigated for misusing the word
``ironic'' in her song of that title, but Purdy understands it all
too well _ although he's not very fond of it. At the tender age of
24, Purdy has written a thoughtful treatise on the masks we hide
behind, the feelings we quash with ironic detachment and the
detrimental effects of living life at a remove from reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of irony is a quiet refusal to believe in the depth
of relationships,'' Purdy asserts, ``the sincerity of motivation,
or the truth of speech _ especially earnest speech.''
</P>
<P>
   The precocious Purdy _ home-schooled in West Virginia coal
country before continuing his education at Phillips Academy,
Harvard and Yale _ calls for re-engagement in political and civic
life. The widespread notion that public life, especially politics,
no longer matters is a sobering but not surprising one. Cynicism
and a loss of trust in our political leaders are rampant. Irony
shields us from consequence, keeps us from investing too much hope
in things that may fail us.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of our society's ironic disengagement, Purdy
offers Jerry Seinfeld, whom he calls ``irony incarnate. Autonomous
by virtue of his detachment, disloyal in a manner too vague to be
mistaken for treachery.'' We have degenerated into blindered
self-interest, refusing responsibility and a commitment to the
``common things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Disco Bloodbath by James St. James (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23).
</P>
<P>
   An acidic romp through the underworld of New York nightlife in
the early '90s, St. James' chronicle repels and fascinates. A
fellow traveler in the New York club scene with uber-club kid
Michael Alig, St. James relates the tales surrounding the grisly
murder of alleged drug dealer Angel Melendez, a crime that sent
Alig and another clubland denizen to prison. No one in the story is
particularly likable, but it has some of the same car-crash allure
of ``The Jerry Springer Show'' at its trashiest. It's also a
frightening example of how inured much of our society has become to
murder.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The David Story: A Translation With Commentary of 1 and 2
Samuel by Robert Alter (Norton, $30).
</P>
<P>
   A splendid new translation of one of the Bible's greatest
stories. Alter, whose masterful translation of Genesis was
much-lauded, brings the tale of Israel's first king to life in this
clear and meticulously annotated volume. He manages to retain the
musicality and poetic beauty of the King James version while
incorporating his own ideas about translating ancient Hebrew and
the prodigious amount of biblical scholarship that has transpired
in the centuries since that landmark volume.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Learning the Ropes: An Apprentice on the Last of the
Windjammers by Eric Newby (Times Books, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Prolific adventure writer Newby signed on to the Moshulu, a
square-rigged, four-masted ship, as an apprentice in 1938. Less
than a decade later, none of these ships would remain, having been
sunk in World War II or scrapped. He took a camera with him, and
those photographs are mementos of a lost tradition. Even without
Newby's gripping tale, these photographs have a narrative drive of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  QUICK HITS: It's hard to believe that ``Patti Smith: An
Unauthorized Biography'' by Victor Bockris and Roberta Bayley
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) is the first full-length life story of the
poetess of punk. More than any figure in pop music in the past 25
years, Smith has lived a life worthy of the biographical treatment.
... Michele Weldon spent 12 years in an abusive relationship and
she reflects on it in ``I Closed My Eyes: Revelations of a Battered
Woman'' (Hazelden, $15 paperback). This potent and painfully honest
chronicle describes an experience to which, sadly, many women will
relate.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Remembering Muscle Beach: Where Hard Bodies Began :
Photographs and Memories'' (Angel City, $26.95), Harold Zinkin and
Bonnie Hearn take us back to a time before steroids and the
hyper-inflated, cartoonlike proportions of body builders. Zinkin
was among the muscle boys on the Santa Monica, Calif., beach in the
1930s and '40s, and his enthusiastic reminiscences and the terrific
collection of photographs are as refreshing and fun as a romp in
the surf. ... Boston University professor of history and
international relations David Fromkin sheds light on the American
involvement in the Balkans with ``Kosovo Crossing: American Ideals
Meet Reality on the Balkan Battlefields'' (Free Press, $21). The
author of the authoritative ``A Peace to End All Peace: Creating
the Modern Middle East, 1914-1922,'' Fromkin argues that, to a
great extent, both sides in the conflict are still dealing with the
repercussions of that era's policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World of Words: An Illustrated History of Western
Languages'' by Victor Stevenson (Sterling, $29.95) gives a lively,
colorfully illustrated tour of our evolving modes of verbal
communication. ... Brooke Kroeger, journalism professor and former
reporter and editor for United Press International, examines the
life of an often overlooked author and activist in ``Fannie: The
Talent for Success of Writer Fannie Hurst'' (Times Books, $30). A
best-selling author in the 1920s and '30s, Hurst's work was made
into movies by Hollywood 31 times. She used her clout to further
admirable causes such as advancement for women and civil rights for
African-Americans. She was a friend and literary advocate of Zora
Neale Hurston and Dorothy West, and a frequent White House guest of
Eleanor Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
