<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8895 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-BROOKS03-COX     09-02 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BROOKS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outsider Brooks follows his muse
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since he's never played the big-studio games, writer-director
Albert Brooks didn't lose sleep wondering whether his Hollywood
satire ``The Muse'' would ruffle feathers in the film industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, the one advantage of not being a darling here
is that I don't care,'' he says by telephone from Los Angeles. When
a friend warned him that mocking the status quo could lead to a
fall from grace, ``My answer was, I've never been to grace. I don't
feel like I have anything to lose. I was born and raised here, but
I always felt like an outsider _ which, by the way, if you want to
be creative is a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brooks as a once-hot screenwriter, ``The Muse'' is all
about the creative impulse _ and the lengths some people will go to
to get a little inspiration. In this case, it comes in the costly
form of a woman (Sharon Stone) who claims to be a daughter of Zeus,
and one of the actual, mythical Muses responsible for artistic
invention.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks knew the movie would need a ``name'' actress to have
commercial appeal, and Stone was on the short list of possibilities
_ even though she's built her career on edgy dramatic roles.
``There's two exciting things you can do in a movie like this,'' he
says. ``You can cast a brand-new person that no one's ever seen, or
you can take an established person and show them in a new light.
That was the case here. And she's good at it. She knows how to poke
fun at herself and be light, and yet her roles have been very heavy
and dramatic over the years. She was a comedienne waiting to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   From his first feature through his last, Brooks has fostered a
satiric style that hasn't broken any box office records, but that
has earned him some loyal fans, including the fellow filmmakers who
have cameos in ``The Muse'' playing themselves: Rob Reiner, Martin
Scorsese and James Cameron. But just because other directors like
his work doesn't make it any easier for Brooks to get funding for
it. ``In this day and age, you can sooner get a lot of money for a
teenage sex comedy or a horror movie than you can for something I
do,'' Brooks says.
</P>
<P>
   Today's successful screen comedies rely not on the irony and sly
wit Brooks specializes in, but on the slapstick crudities you get
from the Farrelly brothers or Adam Sandler. ``You know what, God
bless Adam,'' Brooks says. ``He does what he does, and Lord knows
he's certainly successful at it. I don't happen to do that style of
comedy, but it doesn't mean I'm snobbish about it or anything.
Listen, whatever makes you laugh is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   He compares it to a car factory: If there were only one car
manufacturer, and it cranked out nothing but lemons, no one would
know to ask for something better. ``You've got to show people
something else, something better, and then they'll start to expect
it. But Hollywood is not in that business. Hollywood is all about
finding what currently works, and giving audiences more of that
until they can't take it any more.''
</P>
<P>
   He uses the ``The Blair Witch Project'' phenomenon as an
example: ``You can bet right now, every studio is saying, `Maybe
all we need to do is get a hand-held camera and send three of our
people into the woods.'''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks probably wishes those three were some of the Hollywood
executives he mocks in ``The Muse.'' And that they'd never come
back from the woods.
</P>
<P>
   THE ALBERT BROOKS VIDEO FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Out of Sight'' (1998; R) _ Going bald for this riveting,
sexy George Clooney-Jennifer Lopez caper.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mother'' (1996; R) _ Cutting through the orange sherbet's
protective layer while supping with Debbie Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Defending Your Life'' (1991; PG) _ Stumbling through
purgatory and falling for Meryl Streep.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Broadcast News'' (1987; R) _ Sweating through his big chance
at anchoring the news.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Lost in America'' (1985; R) _ Explaining the intricate
concept and vital importance of ``nest egg'' to Julie Hagerty.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Real Life'' (1979; PG) _ Filming the all-American family in
a blistering satire decades ahead of ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Taxi Driver'' (1976; R) _ Trying to talk to Robert De Niro's
seriously disturbed cabbie Travis Bickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Muse''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Albert Brooks, Sharon Stone and Andie MacDowell.
Directed by Brooks. Rated PG-13 for language, sexual innuendo and a
brief glimpse of Stone's nude back. At metro theaters. 1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict (from AJC movie critic Eleanor Ringel Gillespie):
Always amusing, sometimes hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
