<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Pine Mountain, Ga. _ Callaway Gardens' first Labor Day Weekend
Sky High Hot Air Balloon Fest is Friday through Sunday. Event
includes balloon glow and launch, tethered balloon rides, antique
car show, entertainment and children's activities. 1-800-225-5292.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Newnan, Ga. _ The Powers' Crossroads Country Fair and Art
Festival Saturday through Monday features arts and crafts by more
than 300 exhibitors, bluegrass and jazz, clogging, children's
activities and food. 770-253-2011.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rome, Ga. _ Running Water Powwow, Cherokee Homecoming and Ripe
Corn Festival Saturday and Sunday includes dance competition and
exhibition, Native American arts and crafts, blowgun competition,
storytelling, drumming, music and food in Ridge Ferry Park. 706-
</P>
<P>
   232-1714.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Juliette, Ga. _ The annual Labor Day Folk Life Celebration at
Jarrell Plantation state historic site on Monday features folk
crafts demonstrations, blacksmithing and farm chores. 912-986-5172.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Macon, Ga. _ Sweet Georgia Jam Sept. 10-19 celebrates Macon's
musical heritage with performances, street parties and church
concerts throughout the city. Featuring Otis Redding III, Clarence
Carter, Billy Joe Royal, Divine, T. Graham Brown and the Macon
Symphony. 912-743-7136 or www.maconartsalliance.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ The Tennessee Valley Railroad Museum hosts ``A
Day Out With Thomas'' Friday through Monday and Sept. 10-12. The
event features train rides pulled by Thomas the Tank Engine of PBS
fame from Grand Junction Station. Sir Topham Hatt, Thomas' boss,
will greet visitors. Also, Thomas videos, coloring sheets and shops
with Thomas merchandise. Reservations required; call 423-894-8028.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lake Junaluska, N.C. _ The Smoky Mountain Folk Festival Friday
and Saturday features traditional music and dance of the southern
Appalachians by the area's finest fiddlers, banjo players, string
bands, ballad singers, buck dancers and square-dance teams as well
as the sounds of dulcimers, harmonica, jew's-harp, bagpipes,
spoons, saws and folk ensembles. Also, children's show and jamming
both nights. 828-452-1688.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hendersonville, N.C. _ The North Carolina Apple Festival
Friday through Monday brings Main Street to life with the King
Apple Parade, arts and crafts, entertainment, sporting events and
about 200 vendors. 828-697-4557.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Franklin, Tenn. _ The 10th annual Franklin Jazz Festival
Saturday through Monday offers free music on two stages, portrait
artists, jugglers, stilt walkers and street performers on Main
Street. 615-791-9924 or www
</P>
<P>
   .historicfranklin.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gatlinburg, Tenn. _ The Arrowmont School of Arts and Crafts
presents traditional and contemporary baskets in ``American
Basketmaking: Tradition and Innovation,'' an invitational exhibit,
and ``All Things Considered,'' a juried show, both sponsored by the
Duluth-based Handweavers Guild of America. Through Oct. 10.
770-495-7702.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dothan, Ala. _ The Wiregrass Museum presents ``Tiffany Silver
Flatware, 1845-1905: When Dining Was an Art'' through Oct. 31. The
400 pieces in the exhibit are part of a collection owned by Dr.
William P. Hood Jr., a Dothan cardiologist. 334-794-3871 or
www.snowhill
</P>
<P>
   .com/(tilde)wmuseuma.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
