<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8897 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-02 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHILE GOING THROUGH THE TRASH YOU LEFT AT MY HOUSE ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people these days have become absolutely paranoid about
giving out personal information. They can go ballistic, for
example, if a bank or some similar business asks for a Social
Security number.
</P>
<P>
   Their identifiers, they fear, might be put to illegal or at
least irritating uses. Perhaps, for example, someone could forge
their credit cards or tap into their bank accounts. At the very
least, they could wind up on some telemarketer's or junk mailer's
list.
</P>
<P>
   Although such wariness can be carried to extremes, it does pay
to err on the side of excess caution in that regard rather than not
enough.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is the man who dumped his garbage bags on my
curb the other day. You heard me right: This guy in a pickup just
drives up and offloads two plastic bags of refuse on the curb next
to mine.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, you say. That's what I said. But then I _ make that
we _ began to think about what he had done. And then my lawn work
supervisor and irrigation specialist became a little worried about
it.
</P>
<P>
   At first the wife and I didn't see what he actually did. We were
otherwise preoccupied with a dispute over the finer points of
edging. By the time we realized that the man had stopped and done
something in the vicinity of our garbage, he had driven away
without acknowledging our collective existence.
</P>
<P>
   We assumed that the guy was just another of the junk scavengers
who drive through the neighborhood and rummage through refuse for
metals and other salvageable items.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the edging had progressed to the other side of
the driveway that the lawn-cutting supervisor perceived that we had
more garbage bags at the curb than we had put there.
</P>
<P>
   ``No big deal,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he could have asked,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he didn't think we'd mind,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he missed the garbage truck at his house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I thought we were going to leave it at that. But then she asked:
</P>
<P>
   ``Why us?''
</P>
<P>
   And I knew where she was going. Not very many people who look
like us live on our street. And he saw us in the yard. After the
obscene graffiti visited upon us a couple of times and the cap with
the Confederate battle flag that was hung in one of our trees ...
well, I knew where she was going.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, don't go there,'' I said. ``You can't read a racist motive
into every idiotic action of some inconsiderate fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Then I turned paranoid and posed the possibility to the lawn
supervisor that the man might have been disposing of some kind of
criminal evidence _ human body parts, even.
</P>
<P>
   I said that half in jest. But the more I thought about it, the
more paranoid I got. I had to see inside those garbage bags. With
trembling fingers, I untied the first of them. It was ripe with
discarded food scraps. I was not about to rummage through that.
</P>
<P>
   The second bag, however, was mostly paper _ junk mail, discarded
bills and other documents from banks, credit card companies, his
church, etc.
</P>
<P>
   We learned his name, his address, his wife's name and just about
anything that any crook, private detective or government
investigator would need to know to take advantage of him or to
start a file on him.
</P>
<P>
   He had just dumped all of that personal information at the
curbside of strangers. It was hard to believe that anyone these
days could so carelessly toss around stuff like that.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the supervisor called the man, who, we discovered lived
four blocks to the north and two blocks to the west of us.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't think we'd mind, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he could have asked, she said. And she promised that if he
did it again, she just might call the police and get him cited for
illegal dumping.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed. But it was not the laughter of someone who was
amused. It had a worried edge.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisor asked me if we should report him anyway because
of his rudeness. I advised against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your warning was sufficient,'' I said. ``But if he does it
again, I can find a slew of mailing lists to put him on. Real
trashy ones.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
