<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8899 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS05-COX     09-02 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The hue and cry of skin color vs. race is redefined
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you take your coffee with two teaspoons of cream, you know
something about Eugene Robinson. Whatever color you'd call your
coffee, you know Gene Robinson is black.
</P>
<P>
   Color has shadings, but race knows only black and white, yellow,
red and brown. And mostly black and white. African-Americans
understand this better than whites, who set up the crude taxonomy
of race in the first place. Robinson descends from a family that
ranges, as he says, from coal to cream, and within it he can
identify the ``rich cocoa brown'' of his sister, the ``milk
chocolate'' of his mother, the ``maple tones'' of his father's skin
and the ``oakwood brown'' of his own.
</P>
<P>
   But in the United States and most places, these shades are still
black any way you cut it, and so Robinson, a reporter for The
Washington Post, sought refuge in a tour of duty that would take
him to Brazil. He had tired of the racial straitjacketing in the
United States. If a racial rainbow existed anywhere, it was Brazil.
Colonized by the Portuguese, populated from the start by
copper-skinned Native Americans, darkened by generations of slaves
from Africa, Brazil knew color more than it knew race, and was
happier for it.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's rainbow landscape
</P>
<P>
   He could see it at once. A friend invited him to a party on the
beach in Ipanema, and he no longer saw the world in black and
white. ``All around us,'' he writes in ``Coal to Cream,'' ``was the
wonderful Brazilian racial landscape, a melange of blacks and
browns and and tans and taupes, of coppers and cinnamons and at
least a dozen shades of beige.''
</P>
<P>
   In such a kaleidoscope, who was really black and who was white?
Did it even matter? ``Here,'' after all, ``was a place where a kind
of benign racial anarchy seemed to rule, a lubricious, frictionless
chaos into which one could simply disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to a woman whose predominant features clearly were
African, he asked what it was like being black in a place like
this?
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not,'' the woman answered, surprised at the question.
``I'm not black.''
</P>
<P>
   If she was surprised, he was even more so.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you must be,'' he said. ``I'm black, and you're as dark as
I am.''
</P>
<P>
   They did the arm test, and hers was darker by a couple of
shades.
</P>
<P>
   ```But this color isn't black,' the woman says. `This isn't
black at all.'''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson had gone to Brazil to escape race, only to find a
reversal of what he had known in the United States. One drop
colored you black where he'd come from. Here, a drop of cream and
you could call yourself anything you wanted. Whatever it might be,
you weren't ``black.''
</P>
<P>
   An integrationist come full circle
</P>
<P>
   This was only the beginning of his disillusionment: ``I had
looked at a milieu that Brazilians thought raceless and I had seen
race _ black people at the bottom of society's barrel.'' For all
the commingling of colors, each shading seamlessly into another,
race defined one as an individual in Brazil, too, and it largely
determined a social stratification that was easy to overlook.
</P>
<P>
   Put in this way, it seems an unoriginal observation, even to
someone who's never set foot in South America. But Robinson's real
point is a larger one than racial relations in Brazil. It took a
disillusionment with what he found there for him to acknowledge
that color will always be one thing and race another:
</P>
<P>
   ``When we speak of race in America, we speak in the terminology
of color _ we say black and white and yellow and brown _ but we
don't really mean color at all, not the way they mean color in
Brazil. What we really mean is racial identification, in the sense
of group identification. We mean people who share a history, who
share a culture, who share a status in society, who even by and
large share a political point of view. ... We associate the word
`black' with speech patterns, taste in clothing, sense of humor,
attributes that would seem to have little to do with skin color. We
see race as something absolute and immutable, and we recognize no
in-between.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to read into this resignation, even implied
separatism. To the contrary, ``Coal to Cream'' is the story of an
integrationist come full circle _ but an integrationist who no
longer denied what he was. He had sought refuge in what he thought
must be a racial rainbow, only to find he was as black as he ever
was. And that was OK, even if not everyone else on the beach in
Ipanema was as willing to acknowledge that the coffee can be good
with or without the cream.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coal to Cream: A Black Man's Journey Beyond Color to an
Affirmation of Race. By Eugene Robinson. Free Press. $24.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
