<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-JACKETS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flattering jackets graze knee, calf
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 5
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jackets are long on style these days.
</P>
<P>
   Lengths extend past the knee or down to the ankle, providing a
more dramatic and refined feminine look than the traditional
blazer.
</P>
<P>
   Designers are pairing long jackets with sheath dresses, slender
skirts and narrow pants for styles that transition easily from work
to evening and special occasions. When worn with a matching dress,
the jacket can even replace the basic suit for a job interview.
</P>
<P>
   The jazziest of jackets come with hidden buttons and zippers,
panels that extend the length of the back, and simple details that
don't distract from the suit.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing about the new look is the fit.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly tailored at the waist and softly unstructured at the
hip, the jacket offers a long straight line that most women can
wear. It can hide a wide bottom as easily as it can accentuate a
petite frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty flattering to most body shapes. It's a very
forgiving look,'' says Anita Finkelstein, fashion market editor for
Women's Wear Daily.
</P>
<P>
   Although it looks a lot like a coat, don't treat it like one.
This lightweight jacket should be worn as part of an outfit and
kept on all day.
</P>
<P>
   But don't mistake its versatility as a permanent replacement for
a standard jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just a new option to a blazer,'' says Susan
Forehand, fashion director at Saks Fifth Avenue. ``It's a wonderful
piece to have in your wardrobe to add excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
