<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8902 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-BRAZIL1STTAKE0     09-02 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRAZIL1STTAKE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baroque in Brazil
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OURO PRETO, Brazil _ Most travelers arrive home loaded with
throwaway phrases and tiresome photographs. Rarely do they tell you
what really happened. For instance, a person returning from the
legendary Vila Rica de Ouro Preto _ or ``Rich City of Black Gold,''
as it was named in 1711, after gold was discovered nearby _ is
liable to say something like: ``The architecture was amazing. And
the food _ you haven't lived!''
</P>
<P>
   But of course.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this city, just 271 miles northwest of Rio de
Janeiro, is known for its ostentatious array of 18th-century
Baroque art. For years, tourists and poets have rhapsodized about
Ouro Preto's 13 storybook white churches with gold-frosted
interiors, while students of gastronomy have prattled on about the
state of Minas Gerais' obscenely rich, African-inflected cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   New ways to eat okra, collards, corn and pork? Don't think I
won't go there.
</P>
<P>
   But before you hear about the wizened produce ladies and their
poignant bundles of cabbages ... the green soapstone faces posing
as fountains ... or how I foiled a pickpocket with my
lightning-bolt reflexes ... yes, before all that, I'm going to tell
you how I almost didn't get here at all.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding that this was to be an important stop on my two-week
journey to this South American nation, I penciled it in after Rio,
bought a ticket to Belo Horizonte, the closest major city, and
asked my Brazilian friends to book me a room. I figured it would be
easy to hop a bus for the final leg of the trip. After all, I speak
a little Spanish, which is similar to Portuguese, and I have landed
in far more exotic destinations with far less planning. No sweat.
This would be an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   So naturally, I was somewhat befuddled not to find my luggage
when I got off the jet. ``Wait,'' I said, gesturing to a Varig
Brazilian Airlines employee, ``you can't let the plane leave! My
luggage is still on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, senhor, this is Goiania. Belo Horizonte is the next
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Talk about a circuitous route:
</P>
<P>
   Going to Goiania to get to Belo Horizonte is kind of like going
to Chattanooga to get to Savannah. I guess the Varig staff was so
busy making sure I paid the airport tax that it forgot to mention
the stopover. And it didn't help that Portuguese plays by its own
rules. For example, bom dia (``good morning'') is pronounced
``bohn-GEE-uh.'' Rio, as in ``de Janeiro,'' is pronounced
``HEE-oh.'' Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   When I finally got to Belo Horizonte (``BAY-loh hori-ZONTCH''),
I was afraid to get off the plane _ literally. My luggage? It
wasn't there. This time, I was so tardy that it had been stashed in
a Varig office. And wouldn't you know, the bus station was another
40 minutes away. I was as out of my depth as the Beverly
Hillbillies trying to drive to Los Angeles _ but while they had
already struck black gold, I was far from it.
</P>
<P>
   After a high-speed taxi ride so that I wouldn't miss the day's
last bus, after a two-hour bus crawl through the mountains to Ouro
Preto, where I had to catch another cab to my hotel, after numerous
other delays and annoyances that I won't bore you with, I finally
arrived at my destination, Hotel Mirante.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that I began to understand Elizabeth Bishop's
cryptic line to Marianne Moore. No wonder Bishop ended up buying a
house here. It was probably easier than getting back home. But that
was just 46 years ago; I was about to step back three centuries in
time.
</P>
<P>
   A sensual dreamscape
</P>
<P>
   From any vantage point, Ouro Preto is a net of jewels.
</P>
<P>
   In the smoky first light of morning, looking down from the
surrounding hills, it is a blanket of red tile roofs shot through
with splotches of white _ church towers glowing with the creamy
patina of rose-colored quartz. By noon, the structures have
sharpened into cross-spangled castles of pure crystalline white,
with niches for bells and clocks _ and towers that remind you of
onion domes, spinning tops or skybound rockets. This 18th-century
Portuguese Baroque style has a vaguely Russian aura, but here in
the tropics, the buildings are fringed with leafy curtains of
banana trees and palms, hibiscus and roses, morning glories and
jasmine.
</P>
<P>
   Move closer in, and you see houses of pink, purple and blue;
sea-foam green, mustard yellow and shoe-leather brown. A pickup
sits in the town square, sagging under the weight of a load of
oranges. Water spurts from the grotesque faces of ancient soapstone
fountains. Flower and herb vendors _ the same old women pictured in
one of my guidebooks _ have set up shop right on the street,
surrounded by buckets of zinnias and daisies, crates of lettuces
and radishes.
</P>
<P>
   Early one Sunday morning, I wandered into the truck farmers'
market on Barra square to smell the perfume of limes, oranges,
watermelons, baby tangerines and bananas, miniature apples, grapes,
ginger, garlic, chives, onions, shallots, okra, green beans,
cucumbers, peppers, gourds, pumpkins, melons, potatoes, prunes,
raisins, eggplants, green tomatoes, coconuts, pears, papaya, stalks
of sugar cane and carrots as big as a man's forearm.
</P>
<P>
   I saw a perfect still life: trays of immaculate white eggs
stacked behind a bank of yucca roots, which had been cut open to
reveal their milky interiors. Everywhere, I saw baskets of beans _
black, red, speckled _ to be scooped up, bottles of cachaca (sugar
cane liquor) to be bought and drunk, faces to look at _ and faces
of farmers looking back happily, in the way that Brazilians do.
</P>
<P>
   Though I chose to hoof it up and down the formidable hills,
another option is to hire an English-speaking guide who can give a
brief history of the town. Gold was discovered in the state of
Minas Gerais (General Mines) in 1694. Shortly afterward, there were
encampments known as Ouro Preto, Ouro Podre (Rotten Gold) and Ouro
Fino (Fine Gold). Today the gold is gone, but the churches _ and
the history _ remain. In 1980, the city was designated a historic
world treasure by UNESCO, the cultural arm of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant historic figures are Tiradentes, who mounted a
revolt against the Portuguese crown and went on to become a
national hero after he was hanged in 1792, and the artist Antonio
Francisco Lisboa (1738-1814). The Michelangelo of Brazil, his
genius was to integrate the overwrought ornamentation of European
Baroque with the earthiness of the common man _ miners, slaves and
natives. Because he suffered a degenerative disease of the hands
and feet, he was known as Aleijadinho (``the little cripple'').
</P>
<P>
   The sanctum sanctorum of his craft is the Church of Sao
Francisco de Assis, begun in 1776 and wreathed, inside and out,
with cherubs. It is a landmark, known as much for the cheesy
soapstone craft market in front _ miles of aisles of vases and
bookends, lidded jars and bric-a-brac _ as for its artistic riches,
its balconied ivory interiors tooled in gold leaf.
</P>
<P>
   This church is everyone's first stop. Afterward, you may orbit
the village, stopping to shop, eat, nap or look at more churches at
your leisure. Just to the west of the church, in a shop where
tourists dress up in period costumes to have their pictures taken,
I met a set of rosy-cheeked young men from the local university,
dressed in top hats, ruffled shirts, bow ties and fancy jackets.
They were about to sit for a portrait with their begowned and
bejeweled mother.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the dizzying interiors _ dusted with gold dust and just
plain dust _ one of the best is Our Lady of Pilar (1711). I loved
the way its little tinkly chandeliers are suspended from golden
brackets jutting from the walls like birds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
