<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8903 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-BRAZIL2NDTAKE0     09-02 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRAZIL2NDTAKE05-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   OURO PRETO, Brazil _ from the walls like birds.
</P>
<P>
   I loved the keyhole-design second-story window, streaming with
the magnificent brightness of morning. Underneath it was a
starburst gilt mirror surrounded by four angels. Amid all this
loveliness, on a wide-brimmed balcony overlooking the church, I
stood to admire the chapel. It was chockablock with gold, in the
way that Ouro Preto's churches are.
</P>
<P>
   You could spend days wandering in and out of churches and shops
by day, ducking into cozy little bistros by night. On a Friday
night, I happened upon a capoeria demonstration tucked inside a
university room off the main square. To the syncopated thud of
congas, tambourines and berimbau, young martial arts students in
all-white outfits tumbled and kicked to the Afro-beat. Though the
art form is known for its tough, streetwise sensibility, these
gentle warriors waved no machetes.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, couples kissed in doorways, or waited in line at the
cinema to see ``Orfeu,'' the remake of ``Black Orpheus,'' with a
new soundtrack by Brazilian pop star Caetano Veloso. Later on, I
was lured into Spaghetti Pizzeria, on Rua Conde de Bobadela, by the
guitar-strumming Rubinho Santos, who was soon joined by a young
woman in a black beret and miniskirt. Together, they swayed through
his bossa nova songbook, and everyone in the subterranean shotgun
room sang along, in the way that Brazilians do.
</P>
<P>
   Down the same street, at O Profeta, I listened to Veloso
sound-alike Celso Alves, and enjoyed a bowl of caldo verde
(literally, ``green soup,'' a Minas specialty of pureed potatoes,
collards, garlic and bacon). At one point, I saw a tipsy girl on
the street mumbling the Beatles lyric, ``Help! I need somebody!''
</P>
<P>
   There was even a conference of Elizabeth Bishop scholars, who
sat in restaurants looking witless and bored, worrying about the
politics of publishing, announcing that the licor de jabuticaba (a
local cordial made of grapelike berries and offered in good health)
tasted like ``fermented prunes.'' Quite a contrast to the smiling
Brazilians who traded convivial thumbs-up signs with bumbling
tourists _ or the Tropia family, who welcomed me into their
apartment above Restaurante Chafariz when I stopped to buy a bottle
of their homemade jabuticaba liqueur.
</P>
<P>
   The only sour note to this sojourn was on the final morning. It
was sunrise, and I decided to take one last stroll to admire the
view. What was first just a lit cigarette on two legs became a man
with a backpack. He stopped to ask me directions and proceeded to
brush into me awkwardly. I sprang off him like a rubber band, and
headed up the street to my hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I was just paranoid to think he was a thief; perhaps he
had just arrived and was really lost. Certainly, I could relate.
</P>
<P>
   I shrugged it off and headed back to the hotel. I had a lovely
stash of stories to tell, new friends to meet and, since I'd
planned ahead, a private car to drive me to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   Though Oct. 12, Delta is offering a $1,181 round-trip fare to
Belo Horizonte, the closest major city to Ouro Preto (Delta:
1-800-241-4141). Make sure you book a flight to Belo Horizonte's
Pampulha airport, not Confins. From the airport, it's a short bus
ride to the city bus station, where you may purchase a ticket to
Belo Horizonte.
</P>
<P>
   Visa: To travel to Brazil, you must have a tourist visa. For an
application, contact the Consulate General of Brazil in Miami
(305-285-6200; www.brazilmiami.org). There is a $45 charge.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hotel Mirante. This immaculate, moderately priced hotel just
north of town has beautiful rooms with aquariumlike glass-encased
showers, stupendous views and a good breakfast. English is so-so.
377 Rua Pandia Calogeras, Barra neighborhood, near the
Sunday-morning market. 011-031-551-2773.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Solar Nossa Senhora do Rosario. This four-star hotel, in a
stunningly renovated 19th-century building near the Church of Our
Lady of Rosario, is probably the best in the city. But avoid the
restaurant at all costs, even if the hotel tries to include dinner
with your room rate. By Brazilian standards, the dining room is
very expensive, and my dinner was one of the worst I had in Brazil.
Hotel is highly recommended. 270 Rua Getulio Vargas.
011-031-551-5200.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO EAT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restaurante Chafariz. This all-you-can eat buffet has
superlative versions of all the regional specialties. Tutu a
Mineira, a rich puree of black beans, is always served with an
extravagant feast of various pork cuts, including sausage, pork
roast and fried cracklings. It is the local version of feijoada,
the national dish of pork and black beans, and this particular
rendition is excellent. Here, as everywhere, it is accompanied by
white rice and sauteed kale (couve). On the dessert table, check
out the preserved green-mango curls. 167 Rua Sao Jose.
011-031-551-2828.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Casa do Ouvidor. In a lovely, second-story room overlooking
one of the main streets, you can try all the Minas standards. The
frango com quiabo (chicken with okra) was particularly good. For
dessert, get the amendoim con coco (coconut-peanut mush) with a
glass of jabuticaba liqueur. 42 Rua Direita. 011-031-551-2141.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO SHOP
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Casa da Arte Popular. This consortium of artists' studios is
one of the prettiest spaces I saw in Ouro Preto, with brightly
colored handmade work for sale. Owner Sergio Tropia is friendly and
full of helpful advice for tourists. 165 Rua Sao Jose.
011-031-551-1011.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
