<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8904 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-ROCKWELL05-COX     09-02 1916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ROCKWELL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cultural riches in Rockwell country
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKBRIDGE, Mass. _ In his famous song ``Alice's Restaurant,''
Arlo Guthrie immortalized a hole-in-the-wall restaurant in
Stockbridge, Mass. But the refrain applies to all the Berkshires.
You can get anything you want here, from avant-garde art museums to
antique silver, all in the idyllic surroundings of small, manicured
New England towns set like gems in a ring of verdant hills.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its back-in-time appearance, this section of western
Massachusetts is quite sophisticated, thanks to its proximity to
Boston and New York City. Both before and after Norman Rockwell _
one of the most famous residents _ artists and writers considered
it the perfect retreat, as have the wealthy city folk who built
palatial ``cottages'' in which to spend their summers and weekends.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is rich in cultural offerings. Autumnal beauty
makes September and October the busiest months in the Berkshires.
Tourists fill the many inns and bed-and-breakfasts to take in the
fall color, shop, hike and hang out.
</P>
<P>
   Each town has its own character and specialty. Lenox, one of the
larger villages, is the place to do some serious shopping and
dining. Williamstown, home of Williams College, is the epitome of a
college town. You can go from place to place with ease using U.S. 7
as the spine, and, because it's a small area and well-marked, it's
nearly impossible to get lost.
</P>
<P>
   This is definitely Rockwell country. The Manhattan native fled
New Rochelle, N.Y. (too suburban), for this remnant of old-time
America, where you can still walk down Main Street, and where even
the post office has enough pride to set flowers out front. The
virtues Rockwell extolled and the Colonial stock he depicted live
on in these ruddy faces and simple-seeming places.
</P>
<P>
   The beloved illustrator spent 15 years in Arlington, Vt., about
30 minutes north of the Massachusetts border in the Green
Mountains, and the last 25 of his life in Stockbridge. Both have
museums honoring their favorite son, and every native seems to know
a spot or a person from one Saturday Evening Post cover or another.
Indeed, a visit to western Massachusetts and southern Vermont can
become a Rockwell pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Norman Rockwell Museum. Built in 1993 as a take on a
traditional town meeting hall, Robert A.M. Stern's columned design
is intimately scaled inside in keeping with the homespun vision of
the subject. The tiny Stockbridge museum includes galleries devoted
to the permanent collection of paintings made for magazine covers,
posters and memorabilia as well as exhibitions on other
illustrators. Docents doubling as guards offer anecdote-filled
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss the studio, which was moved from Rockwell's
Stockbridge back yard to this glorious 36-acre site along the
Housatonic River. The studio is set up as close as possible to the
way Rockwell left it. The easel stands in the middle, with a
bouquet of carefully cleaned brushes and paint tubes at the ready.
The space also contains his well-stocked library, reproductions of
artwork that interested him (including Picasso!), props and
souvenirs from various travels. For more information: 413-298-4100
or online at www
</P>
<P>
   .nrm.org.
</P>
<P>
   One of the paintings in the gallery, ``Main Street in
Stockbridge,'' is a partial map for the next step of your tour. You
can return to town and check out the bank where ``The Marriage
License'' is set, dine at the Stockbridge Inn _ a favorite
breakfast spot for Rockwell, who lived around the corner _ or peer
into the storefront where he had his first studio. Down the street
is the cemetery where he is buried under a modest headstone.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Arlington Gallery. When Rockwell lived in West Arlington, Vt.,
he was an energetic part of the community. As he did in
Stockbridge, he used many townspeople as models in his work. The
Arlington Gallery fills a former church with contemporary photos of
Rockwell's models juxtaposed with reproductions of the works in
which they appeared. Marge Brush, one of the docent-models who
works here, recounts her experience posing in her doctor's office
with her family for the 1947 ``Country Doctor,'' which hangs by the
front door. She'll autograph a card or poster, too.
</P>
<P>
   There's not an original in sight, but this place is a lot of fun
and long on human interest. It offers a lively 15-minute video to
the accompaniment of Arlo Guthrie music and lots of tidbits about
Rockwell and his work. A state-by-state recounting shows two pieces
set in Georgia: a Coca-Cola ad and a 1946 portrait of Mrs. Effie
McGuire teaching in a country school in Carroll County.
802-375-6423.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Rockwell, other points of interest to round out your
visit include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chesterwood. Chester French, sculptor of the Abraham Lincoln
Memorial in Washington, lived and worked on this Stockbridge
estate, whose gardens and woodland walks he also designed. His
studio is fascinating, not only because it is filled with plaster
casts and molds, but also because it reveals how the studio
functioned as a living space. The artist relaxed, entertained and
did business in an anteroom stuffed with furniture. A wide veranda
frames pristine views in the back, and the grounds double as a
contemporary sculpture garden. 413-298-3579.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Naumkeag. Joseph Choate, a prominent New York lawyer and
ambassador to the Court of St. James's, built this Stockbridge
house in 1886 as a retreat for his family. Designed by the famed
Stanford White, the 26-room, turreted-shingle-style manse perches
on Prospect Hill, affording wonderful views of the countryside,
which included Choates' working farm. A wonderful example of Gilded
Age taste, the home is surrounded by delightful gardens.
413-298-3239.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Edith Wharton Home. The author actively participated in the
design of this Lenox lakeside villa in 1902. 413-637-1899,
www.edithwharton.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hancock Shaker Village. From 1790 to 1960, the religious
community built and occupied this village in Pittsfield, Mass. The
20 restored buildings and demonstrations of cooking, farming,
carpentry and such illuminate a humble way of life that produced a
widely admired sense of design. The famous circular Round Stone
Barn, designed for maximum efficiency, is an architectural
must-see. The red-brick Dwelling, where the Shakers lived,
demonstrates the elevation of simple functionality to the realm of
art. 1-800-817-1137, www.hancockshakervillage.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sterling and Francine Clark Institute. The Clarks collected
all sorts of things, from antique silver to Flemish altarpieces,
but the heart of their collection is the 19th century. The
Pittsfield museum is rich in both traditional and avant-garde
expressions of the period. Female nudes predominate, from the
smooth-skinned women in academic Bougereau's canvases to the fleshy
beauties of Renoir. The Clark Institute also hosts a program of
temporary exhibitions. 413-458-9545, www.clark.williams.edu.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Williams College Museum of Art. Robert Venturi designed the
classical entrance and an addition that connects seamlessly to the
beaux arts original of this fine college museum in Williamstown. It
rotates its permanent collection and also offers a stimulating
selection of temporary exhibitions. 413-597-2429.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Village Beautiful, as Williamstown is called, should
include a walk around the 206-year-old Williams College campus, the
epitome of an ivy-covered New England college.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MASS MoCA. This contemporary art center (the full name is the
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art) in North Adams, Mass.,
was once a complex of factory buildings. The striking renovation
retains the gritty character while providing space for monumentally
scaled art that has trouble finding a home elsewhere. With its
acres of art _ even if it isn't your cup of tea _ MASS MoCA is
worth a visit just for the setting. 413-664-4481, www.massmoca.org.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Getting there
</P>
<P>
   It's easiest to fly to Albany, N.Y., 40 miles northwest of
Stockbridge, $258 round trip. Delta offers three nonstops daily;
Continental, Northwest, USAirways and United offer connecting
service. A 14-day advance purchase and a Saturday night stay are
required.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red Lion Inn. The Red Lion opened in 1773 as a stagecoach
tavern. Rebuilt after a fire in 1896 and enlarged by additions, it
offers 110 rooms and several restaurants. The decor is Victorian
eclectic. Bric-a-brac fills every available mantel and cornice.
Guests relax in wicker chairs on the broad veranda, read the paper
and watch other tourists walk by this Berkshires landmark.
Stockbridge. 413-298-5545, www
</P>
<P>
   .redlioninn.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Inn at Brookside. For a quieter experience, try this elegant
1805 home on 5 1/2 acres, replete with elegant gardens and a
babbling brook. The home is beautifully appointed with antiques.
Stockbridge. 413-298-3099, www.innatbrookside.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Arlington Inn. The faded script in the guest book proves that
this Greek Revival mansion has been in operation since 1888.
Decorated in charming Victorian fancy, the inn boasts a
sophisticated dining room. Arlington. 1-800-443-9442,
www.arlingtoninn.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Inn at Covered Bridge Green. A bed-and-breakfast in Norman
Rockwell's Arlington home. Built in 1792, the house faces the old
green and one of Vermont's remaining covered bridges. New owners
Clint and Julia Rusin-Dickens plan to restore Rockwell's backyard
studio. They keep a stash of old magazines and out-of-print books
on the artist. You can even sleep in his bedroom. 1-800-726-9480,
www.coveredbridgegreen
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing and other water activities available nearby. Also
shopping in East Arlington and outlets in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   Summertime specials
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 venues stage performances of dance, music and
theater during the summer, including:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tanglewood Festival. A highlight for music lovers for more
than 50 years. The Lenox haven is the Boston Symphony Orchestra's
summer base and features an impressive roster of guest performers _
classical, pop and avant garde. You can sit in the covered,
open-air hall or lie on the lawn and stare up at the stars. Come
early to walk the 500-acre estate. 413-637-1666.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jacob's Pillow. What Tanglewood is to music, this Becket,
Mass., venue is to dance. America's oldest dance festival hosts
performances by internationally known contemporary dance companies
and unusual ethnic troupes. 413-243-0745.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Berkshire Theatre Festival mounts plays on two stages in
Stockbridge. 413-298-5576.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Mount. Shakespeare, plays by new American playwrights and
those by Edith Wharton are performed at Wharton's Lenox home.
413-637-1899.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Williamstown Theatre. Shakespeare would have loved Gwyneth
Paltrow in ``As You Like It.'' She is one of the big names who
performs classics and contemporary plays here in the summer.
413-597-3400.
</P>
<P>
   This winter
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stockbridge Main Street at Christmas, Dec. 3-5. Decked out in
holiday trimmings, Stockbridge has created a weekend event with
arts and crafts shows, concerts and cars from Rockwell's era.
</P>
<P>
   Information
</P>
<P>
   Stockbridge Chamber of Commerce, 413-298-5200;
www.stockbridgechamber.org. Lodging hotline: 413-298-5327.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
