<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      09-02 1541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOT SUMMER FOR HIT FILMS; ALESSANDRO NIVOLA HEATING UP; HAMPTON
FRANCHER FINDS DIRECTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The summer movie season is just about finished and
there are a lot of happy, happy faces in black Armani suits sitting
around the patios at Spago Beverly Hills and the Ivy. For once, for
some reason, almost everything has been clicking for filmmakers
here.
</P>
<P>
   Before the summer started the betting money was that the
juggernaut of ``Star Wars: Episode I'' would dominate the season so
thoroughly that the film might squelch all but a handful of
competitors, save perhaps ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged
Me,'' ``Wild Wild West'' or one of the Julia Roberts comedies.
</P>
<P>
   Instead it has become a season for the record books, with
box-office grosses up 20 percent over last summer's record take.
When the season ends on Monday night, the summer's box-office take
could well hit $3 billion. It was done not through the dominance of
a few big films, as is often the case, but by a steady parade of
hits that just kept on, in almost every genre from almost every
studio appealing to almost every age.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the biggest summer of all time,'' said Paul
Dergarabedian, chairman of Exhibitor Relations, a company in Los
Angeles that monitors film-release schedules and box-office
performance. ``To have this kind of summer, you really need to have
movies with across-the-board appeal, to all age groups and to all
parts of the country. And that's what we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Missing, he said, was ``a preponderance of action films, another
`Armageddon' or `Lethal Weapon' or `Die Hard.''' Instead, the
record has been built _ beyond the $425 million made by ``Star
Wars,'' with characters like Darth Maul (above) _ on an unusually
large number of mid-range, character-driven genre films, not all of
them, for a change, pitched at young audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise turned out to be the back-to-back,
late-summer successes of ``The Blair Witch Project,'' the tiny
independent horror film that became a phenomenon for young
audiences, and ``The Sixth Sense,'' a psychological horror film
that surprised almost everyone, including its studio, Disney, by
becoming the breakout hit of August. If the Exhibitor Relations
projections are correct, ``Sixth Sense'' could eventually reach
about $210 million at the box office, edging it ahead of the $205
million projected for the ``Austin Powers'' sequel as the summer's
second most popular film.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other big hits were the animated ``Tarzan'' (an
estimated $170 million), the Adam Sandler comedy ``Big Daddy''
($160 million), the special-effects-filled remake of ``The Mummy''
($155 million) and the re-teaming of Julia Roberts and Richard Gere
in ``Runaway Bride'' ($145 million).
</P>
<P>
   An astonishing 11 films released this summer have already
grossed more than $100 million each _ a benchmark never before
reached by somany films in one summer _ and a 12th film, ``American
Pie,'' is less than $3 million away from that mark and almost
certain to cross over it. A 13th film, ``Inspector Gadget,'' is
still in theaters; with more than $87 million already in the bank,
it has an outside chance of going over the top, too.
</P>
<P>
   There were nine weekends in a row between mid-June and early
August when there was a different No. 1 film every weekend,
something that hasn't happened in at least 10 years. ``We're still
going back and checking all the records, but I don't believe it's
ever happened before,'' Dergarabedian said.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen?
</P>
<P>
   He has a theory. ``There was a momentum created at the beginning
of the summer by `Star Wars' and it got everyone into the
theaters,'' he said. ``And they saw all the trailers and they were
exposed to all this movie marketing and it created a strong sense
among moviegoers that there was a lot to see and they just kept on
going. At the beginning of the summer, people were afraid that
`Star Wars' would absorb all the interest, but all it seemed to do
was whet everyone's appetite for more.''
</P>
<P>
   SUDDEN EXPOSU &UR; RE FOR ALESSANDRO NIVOLA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There are these strange confluences in the lives of actors when
they suddenly seem to be appearing in all sorts of films at once.
Even though the movies were often made months or years apart, the
vagaries of release schedules put them before audiences one after
the other and an actor who might have otherwise had just one swing
at the plate is given two or even three chances to catch the
audience's attention.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Alessandro Nivola finds himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very strange because I've been working steadily these
past couple of years and nobody's seen any of it, and now it's all
starting to come out at once,'' he said. ``It's strange, but it's
also good, because now the audience and the people in the industry
will get a chance to see me in three very different roles, one
after another. Maybe the three together will make more of an
impression than just one of them alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Nivola, 26, pecked away at his ``full fry'' breakfast at Hugo's
on Santa Monica Boulevard one morning this week, swirling around
the chunks of poached egg and gesturing with a bit of potato
impaled on a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Nivola has probably made his biggest impression as Pollux Troy,
Nicolas Cage's psycho-genius younger brother in John Woo's
``Face/Off.'' He will have major roles in at least two and possibly
three films between now and the end of the year, beginning with the
lead role opposite Reese Witherspoon in ``Best Laid Plans,'' set
for release on Sept. 10, a modern noir from the director Michael
Barker full of plot twists and betrayals and dark emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Then he will play Henry opposite Embeth Davidtz in ``Mansfield
Park,'' the Jane Austen novel adapted by the director Patricia
Rozema, which is scheduled for release on Nov. 5. He plays the king
in Kenneth Branagh's semimusical adaptation of ``Love's Labour's
Lost,'' in which the Shakespeare play is interspersed with Cole
Porter and Irving Berlin songs. The film is scheduled to open in
the spring of 2000, but Nivola said that the actors have been told
that there may be a limited release late this year to qualify for
the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Nivola, a Yale-trained actor, spent three years in regional
theater before his Broadway debut opposite Helen Mirren in ``A
Month in the Country,'' which led to the role in the action film
``Face/Off.'' He moved to Los Angeles from New York to make the
film for Woo, but has hardly been in California since then, making
three out of five subsequent films in England. He said he got one
job _ Michael Winterbottom's ``I Want You'' in 1998 _ and it led to
a second and third. He did not plan to be an American actor in
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did do was turn down a bunch of jobs right after
`Face/Off' that were, you know, kind of big sci-fi things or movies
where people wanted to cast me as a villain,'' Nivola said. ``I was
afraid that if I did that, I would be stuck in that forever. So
since then I've been on a progression toward much more romantic and
brighter characters.''
</P>
<P>
   The last bit of English muffin disappeared. ``I find gratuitous
violence sort of hard to stomach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAMPTON FANCHER FINDS DIRECTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hampton Fancher has wanted to direct a film since he was 22. He
finally got the chance, at age 61. Fancher has had a long career as
a television actor (appearing in episodes of ``Gunsmoke,'' ``Perry
Mason'' and other programs of the 1950s and early 60s),
choreographer, film actor (``Parrish,'' ``The Other Side of the
Mountain''), fiction writer, acting coach, screenwriter (``Blade
Runner,'' ``The Mighty Quinn'') and producer (``Blade Runner'').
But he had never gotten one of his own film projects off the ground
_ until ``The Minus Man'' came along.
</P>
<P>
   The project started several years ago when he found the book of
the same title and a partner and wrote the screenplay in five
months. He waited two years while money was being raised, put
together a truly amazing, ``how did these people get in the same
room together'' cast (Owen Wilson, Brian Cox, Janeane Garofalo,
Sheryl Crow, Dwight Yoakum, Mercedes Ruehl), shot the film and
finished cutting in January. This week he took a breather from the
festival circuit and roamed the offices of the film's production
company, the Shooting Gallery, in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was drawn to the story because it is about the proximity of
good to evil,'' Fancher (above) said. ``We long for darkness. We
are attracted to what can destroy us.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is about a young, attractive and affable psychopath (
Wilson) who wanders into a town and kills people, a modern-day
Shane as serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the duality of his character that was so interesting,''
Fancher said. ``The juxtaposition of the light and the dark. There
are some moviegoers, some people who want to know exactly what is
in front of them. I would rather swim through voluptuous water in
the darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   What took so long for the chance to direct a movie?
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged. ``I've been in preproduction before twice, but the
money fell out,'' he said. ``Perhaps some people aren't interested
in the same things I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
