<P>
   &UR; FOCUS (Available by 2 p.m., Fri., Sept. 3) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS INCLUDES SEVERAL COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGING SOUTH: Next to barbecue joints scattered across the
South, you find Mexican bakeries and Spanish-language record shops.
Attracted by jobs and a more tranquil lifestyle, Hispanics are
venturing into the Southern states in record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CHANGING POLITICS: As North Carolina's Hispanic population
increases, politicians are reacting. For the first time, a House
member, Democrat Bob Etheridge, has organized a Hispanic outreach
committee to establish a link to his new constituents. The state
government, meanwhile, has created a Hispanic liaison position and
is reaching out to Hispanic businesses.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CHANGING IMMIGRANT: A profile of Juvencio Peralta, who
came to North Carolina 12 years ago to work in the fields and is
now an associate housing manager for Carolina Turkey, the largest
turkey producer in the country.
</P>
