A8925 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CONGRESS-ELECTION-$AD     09-02 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ELECTION-$ADV05-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES URGE HOUSE MEMBERS TO STAY PUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 5)   (FILED in ``p'' and ``w'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Democrats mounting a major challenge to topple
the Republicans as the majority party in the House, lawmakers on
both sides have been hearing this message from their leaders:
``Hold onto your seats!''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the party that wins the most open seats, those
vacated by incumbents, could win control of the chamber next year.
</P>
<P>
   And the message is getting through. Members appear to be
hunkering down and holding on at a time when the razor-thin
five-vote margin in the House is the narrowest it has been in 45
years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans now hold 222 House seats, compared with 211 for
Democrats and one independent, Bernard Sanders of Vermont, who
often sides with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Open seats are viewed as wild cards, especially if the vacancies
are in closely divided districts where it's tough to predict how
voters will respond to new candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic leaders are edgy because they know
that the party of a retiring House member has retained control of
the seat that's up for grabs 74 percent of the time since World War
II. That's a big drop from 94 percent of the time when an incumbent
runs for reelection.
</P>
<P>
   So strategists in both parties are begging, cajoling and
arm-twisting to persuade their members to stay put. They may
promise committee chairmanships, pledge to help candidates raise
campaign dollars or try to discourage members from running for
higher office if their chances of success are slim.
</P>
<P>
   John Feehery, spokesman for House Speaker Dennis J. Hastert,
says flatly, ``The Republican leadership doesn't want GOP members
to retire. You don't want to defend a lot of open seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Feehery says his party's leaders are touting the strong showing
of Republican presidential frontrunner George W. Bush, telling
colleagues there is a good chance of pairing a GOP Congress with a
GOP president.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are also pushing to keep their incumbents firmly
planted at their posts.
</P>
<P>
   John Del Cecato, a spokesman for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, says a big incentive for House Democrats to
remain in office is the hope that they can regain control, which
they lost in 1994. ``It's absolutely in sight,'' he insists.
``We're on the doorstep of retaking the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading the Democrats' House effort is Rep. Patrick Kennedy,
D-R.I., who decided to forego a run for the Senate so he could take
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that the hang-in-there warning has been heeded is the
fact that so far in the 106th Congress just 13 Republican and six
Democratic seats are open because of members retiring or seeking
higher office. The death of Rep. George Brown, D-Calif., earlier
this year left his seat empty.
</P>
<P>
   While there is still more than a year to go before elections,
these 19 vacancies fall well short of the 33 open seats last year
and the 53 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But among the 19, several are in swing districts, and experts
are predicting nail-biter fights for the seats. They include those
of Republican Reps. Tom Coburn of Oklahoma, Jack Metcalf of
Washington, who are honoring term-limits pledges, and Rick Hill of
Montana, who is leaving because of complications from eye surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking higher office from other competitive districts are Reps.
Bill McCollum, R-Fla., Debbie Stabenow, D-Mich., and Ron Klink,
D-Pa., who hope to ascend to the Senate, and Reps. Dave McIntosh,
R-Ind., and Robert E. Wise, D-W.Va., who want to move into their
state governor's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic House members trying to hold onto their seats yearn
for majority-party status so that their side can dictate the
legislative agenda in the chamber and control such details as when
members leave for recess and how many serve on a committee.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, the specter of losing all that power is
horrifying. ``It's like being on a superbowl team and then being
traded to an expansion team,'' says Amy Walter, an analyst at the
Cook Political Report, a nonpartisan newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Jacobson, a political scientist at the University of
California at San Diego, predicts pressure from both parties on
members to stay will make the coming election a ``low retirement''
one.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson notes that the House has a lot of new blood _ members
who were elected since 1992, making the period an era with the
highest turnover of House seats in more than 50 years. ``There are
a lot of people who aren't ready to retire yet,'' Jacobson says.
</P>
<P>
   He also points to the fact that House members tend to try to
hold their seats through the end of a decade, after which
congressional districts are redrawn to conform to new Census
counts. Then, two years later, after district lines have been
redrawn and reelection prospects are more uncertain, the number of
retirees jumps markedly.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1990, 27 House members retired, compared with 65
retirements in 1992, he says.
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans lose the House next year, many of them will bolt,
predicts Paul Herrnson, professor of government and politics at the
University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who were in the majority don't like the indignities
associated with being in the minority,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Even those in the majority may join the exodus if they fail to
win chairmanships. ``If you are passed over for a chairmanship,
then your power amounts to peanuts,'' Herrnson explains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0210 </DOCNO>
