<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOLLYWOOD-EDGE-760(2T     09-02 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-EDGE-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: SUMMER COMEDIES TEETERING ON THE EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Albert Brooks, playing a successful middle-aged
screenwriter in ``The Muse,'' is bluntly informed by a baby-faced
executive reptile at Paramount Pictures that his writing has lost
its ``edge,'' it is the career equivalent of a death sentence. Only
magic of a particularly glitzy and silly Hollywood sort can help
him regain it.
</P>
<P>
   Edge. Oh to have it! To be on the cutting edge, to be, as they
say, edgy! If you're pitching a movie or a television show to a
Hollywood baby mogul nowadays, it had better have edge, or you're
history, kiddo. But what is that exactly? After running neck and
neck with the sweet old-fogyish ``hip'' to evoke what's
progressive, contemporary and (excuse the cliche) ahead of the
curve, edge seems to have pulled ahead. It has, as they say, the
edge.
</P>
<P>
   And what about hip? Does hip have a future? Perhaps not, at
least in contemporary Hollywood, unless the project is steeped in
1960s and '70s nostalgia. One of the funniest of this summer's
unexpectedly delicious crop of movie comedies, the Watergate satire
``Dick,'' exemplifies classic hip comedy of the ``Saturday Night
Live'' school, circa 1976. That may be one reason why ``Dick''
bombed at the box office. Where hip carries connotations that
suggest a heart and an ethical value system beneath a facade of
cool (the movie ridicules Richard Nixon and his White House crew as
hypocritical baddies), edge is so hip it doesn't need a heart. All
it needs is an edge.
</P>
<P>
   Where hip implies a suspicion of wealth and power as the
ultimate goals in life (and a tolerance bordering on fondness for
recreational drugs), edge is about winning, scoring, cashing in and
getting there first. It's being under 30 and on the inside of an
IPO. It's being head of production for a major movie studio at 29.
It's pulling off a brilliant stunt like the summer's biggest box
office and marketing phenomenon, that no-budget pseudo-student
documentary ``The Blair Witch Project.'' Or coming up with the
whopping (and whoppingly sentimental) must-see surprise ending in
the summer's other unexpected blockbuster, ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it's putting one over on the Motion Picture Association
of America by convincing the ratings board that the deliriously
potty-mouthed animated film ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and
Uncut'' deserves an R, rather than an NC-17 rating.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Brooks with pointing out the latent cruelty of the word
``edge'' in his new comedy. Underneath its deceptively sunny
surface ``The Muse'' is so bitter that its mockery of Hollywood
lingo could conceivably spell the beginning of the end of edge as a
power-lunch cliche.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, who wrote and directed the movie, is Steven Phillips, a
screenwriter whose career heads down the toilet once that baby
reptile cancels his three-picture deal and kicks him off the lot.
Desperate to regain his status, Steven is forced to spend a fortune
hiring Hollywood's hottest muse, Sarah (Sharon Stone), an extremely
charming, spoiled, high-living beauty who claims to be the daughter
of Zeus and struts around Los Angeles in filmy powder-blue gowns
waving a fan. During Sarah's travels, several of her top clients,
including Rob Reiner, Martin Scorsese and James Cameron, do amusing
walk-ons.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stone is hilarious as the fickle, self-centered, whorish
embodiment of the Hollywood dream, an inspiration-for-hire psychic
friend who ``knows everybody'' and can only be had for a very high
price. Sarah is so pampered and finicky that she won't begin
working her magic for Steven until he installs her in a
$1,700-a-night suite at the Four Seasons Hotel. As he discovers to
his embarrassment, gifts from Tiffany's (not $50 key rings but
$3,500 bracelets) are de rigueur offerings to the muse to keep her
interested.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, she moves into Steven's house, appropriating the
marriage bed he shares with his cookie-baking wife (Andie
MacDowell), whom she coerces into becoming a professional baker,
even hooking her up with that redoubtable superstar chef Wolfgang
Puck.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah eventually revives Steven's career with a ridiculous
high-concept notion for a Jim Carrey comedy about a man who
inherits an aquarium full of sick fish. Presented with this piffle,
Steven's agent naturally goes bananas with excitement. And so does
every other Hollywood producer who reads the script. So much for
seriousness, taste and judgment in contemporary Hollywood, Brooks'
movie sneers. Having edge really means coming up with the
equivalent of the next ``Ace Ventura.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Butting heads at the box office with Brooks' comedy is Steve
Martin's equally funny but more soft-toothed Hollywood satire,
``Bowfinger.'' Directed by Frank Oz and starring Martin, who wrote
the screenplay, ``Bowfinger,'' like ``The Muse,'' is essentially a
likable one-joke comedy aimed at Hollywood and stretched almost to
the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   Martin plays Bobby Bowfinger, a sleazy self-deluding Tinseltown
hustler with no taste and no shame. Bobby is obsessed with making a
ludicrous sci-fi movie called ``Chubby Rain'' starring the
extremely paranoid Hollywood superstar Kit Ramsey (Eddie Murphy).
The plot has something to do with aliens who secretly invade the
earth concealed in raindrops.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to make the movie even without Kit's cooperation,
Bobby and his film crew follow Kit around Los Angeles, hiding in
the shrubbery, dispatching cast members to cross paths with the
star, then surreptitiously filming these encounters. Bobby
eventually completes the movie without Kit's becoming aware that he
has been filmed. Only one final touch is missing. Kit never utters
the screenplay's crowning punch line: ``Gotcha, suckers!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bowfinger'' also has its own resident guru in the person of
Terence Stamp playing a cult leader for a Scientology-like
organization called Mind Head to which Kit belongs. The concept of
edge doesn't figure in the film. But at the end when ``Chubby
Rain'' has its Hollywood premiere to an appreciative audience, it's
clear that this inept, amateurish garbage is deemed to have the
same edge as Brooks' aquarium farce.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that both ``The Muse'' and ``Bowfinger'' satirize
Hollywood suggests the genuine anxiety and fear felt by filmmakers
of a certain age when confronting Hollywood's youth culture and the
booming teen-age market.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, in his sarcastic, self-lacerating way, and Martin in his
genially wacky one, are both gambling that a young American
audience weaned on Hollywood gossip and trade information will be
titillated by an insider's comic view of their company town and its
nutty values.
</P>
<P>
   For all their thematic similarities, the two movies are unlike
in crucial ways. ``The Muse,'' like Brooks' other films, maintains
a style of heightened comic realism that places the star, his
neuroses and anxieties front and center. Brooks' Steven is a
tightwad, a worrywart and a whiner with an oversized (but easily
deflatable ego). He is barely likable.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Brooks may hate being thought of as the Left Coast
Woody Allen, he has compiled a powerful body of work by embodying
the same sort of urban Jewish neurotic who wears his hang-ups on
his sleeve. By making his stand-ins so abrasive, Brooks is nastier
to his screen alter egos than Allen is to his. ``The Muse'' could
be seen as Brooks' answer to Allen's even more dyspeptic
``Celebrity,'' though Brooks' movie seems more acutely in tune with
the nuances of the culture he is savaging.
</P>
<P>
   Allen and Brooks really don't seem to know how to end many of
their comedies. After taking us inside the head of an alter ego,
they often don't know how to get out again. Having invented the
fabulous Sarah, Brooks is at a loss as to how to explain her, and
in the movie's only major blunder he invents a prosaic earthly
resume for her. He needn't have bothered.
</P>
<P>
   Where Brooks' comedy is essentially introspective and heavily
dosed with Freud, Martin's humor doesn't aspire to that kind of
psychological realism. Melding ``Saturday Night Live'' sketch
comedy with observational humor in the tradition of '70s Blake
Edwards and Paul Mazursky movies, Martin adds a third element, a
whimsical literary humor descended from S.J. Perelman.
</P>
<P>
   For all its contemporary touches, Martin's Tinseltown is as much
Hollywood past as it is contemporary. Daisy (Heather Graham), the
ingenuous Hollywood hopeful picked to star in ``Chubby Rain''
moments after arriving on a bus from the heartland, exudes a 1940s
freshness that is amusingly at odds with her matter-of-fact
bartering of sex for a juicier role. By having her span decades,
Martin sees her as an enduring Hollywood archetype.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who plays two roles in the movie (both brilliantly),
embodies the same double vision. While the jumpy, hypersensitivity
of his paranoid movie star with bodyguards and entourage seems
completely of the moment, his other role as a dumb, grinning, Kit
look-alike who graduates from gofer to unwitting stunt double on
the project is a timeless comic goofball from another, more
innocent era.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Martin may look down on the industry mentality that
spends millions creating movies that are only marginally less silly
than ``Chubby Rain,'' in ''Bowfinger'' you also sense him standing
back and observing the madness with an avuncular grin. He has been
around the block long enough to be able to let go. Brooks, by
contrast, takes the absurdity of Hollywood personally. Beneath the
laughs, you can feel the pain and desperation.
</P>
<P>
   How much edge do these movies have? Not too much, at least by
Hollywood's ruthless commercial standards. ``The Muse'' fared
disappointingly at the box office on its opening weekend, doing
about half the business per screen that Martin's film had done a
few weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Neither movie begins to compare with the successes of this
summer's comedy blockbusters, Adam Sandler's ``Big Daddy'' and the
teen-age grossout movie ``American Pie,'' an upscale ``Porky's.''
The success of ``American Pie'' and the failure of the much funnier
and more sophisticated ``Dick'' sharply illustrates the generation
gap that also hurt ``Bowfinger'' and ``The Muse.'' While audiences
over 35 found the loss-of-virginity contest in ``American Pie''
puerile, audiences under 35 were mystified by ``Dick,'' a political
comedy set in the dark ages of the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Even having the teen-age stars Kirsten Dunst and Michelle
Williams appear in ``Dick'' didn't help much. Consider the fact
that today's 17-year-olds were born in 1982, fully a decade after
the Watergate break-in. To this generation, Watergate is as much
ancient history as the Depression was to the baby boom audience
that lapped up ``Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar fate befell ``Election,'' a very grown-up and
disturbing satire of the American success ethic revolving around a
student election in a Nebraska high school. The presence of
teen-age actors couldn't sell a film that many critics have deemed
an American classic but that Paramount Pictures couldn't figure out
how to market.
</P>
<P>
   The other significant comedy trend of the summer was the
ascendance of romantic comedy or rather romantic comedy starring
Julia Roberts, whose two hits, ``Notting Hill'' and ``Runaway
Bride,'' each grossed more than $100 million. Hugh Grant, Ms.
Roberts' winsome co-star in ``Notting Hill,'' also demonstrated
modest box office clout later on as the star of the flighty Mafia
comedy ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' in which he plays a dapper art
auctioneer about to marry into the mob.
</P>
<P>
   In surveying the summer comedy sweepstakes, let us not forget
the one and only ``South Park,'' arguably the year's funniest
comedy and the best movie musical in years. With more smutty,
tittering humor and flatulence than you might find in a half-dozen
Jim Carrey or Adam Sandler movies, ``South Park'' certainly has
edge. With risque songs that parody everything from Rodgers and
Hammerstein to Alan Menken and a portrait of Satan as the sex slave
of Saddam Hussein, ``South Park'' is the first mainstream animated
movie that might be described as an anti-Disney musical in its
humor, which deliberately went up against nervous, politically
correct sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   With its fearless embrace of black, Jewish and gay stereotypes
and its ridicule of adults as hypocritical, hysterical warmongers,
``South Park'' managed to be hip as well as edgy. But although it
fared well at the box office, earning about $50 million, it didn't
do a third of the business of the Disney blockbuster ``Tarzan.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial lesson of ``South Park'' could be that after all
is said and done, there might be such a thing as too much edge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
