<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA DREAMING
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, Aug. 9)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The longing may have lessened since our last rumbling of the San
Andreas Fault, but my Michigan friend seems to believe that if she
lived in California her life would be better.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I think she has a pretty fine life, including a husband and
daughter who make her laugh and a cat. She can walk from her house
to restaurants and book stores and she has generous friends who
have a cabin on the lake. She can get on the train and go to
Chicago when she's bored. There are fireflies in the summer and
snow in the winter. She can grow peonies.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe her corner market doesn't have our vast wine selection,
but I've been to her restaurants and they're fine about sauvignon
blanc and they know about olive oil and goat cheese.
</P>
<P>
   She and I both read a recent study on personal happiness that
looked at whether people are happier in California or the Midwest
and concluded that there is no real difference. But, there is an
imagined difference. People in California and the Midwest THINK
that people are happier in California.
</P>
<P>
   See, I told her. If she were here she'd have to be acting like
she was always thrilled, while back in Michigan she can get away
with grousing and no one thinks she's ungrateful.
</P>
<P>
   I tell her that I know lots of unsettled Californians, including
two, in fact, who just moved to New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The same research study noted that people who live in France and
Italy are less happy than those who live in Denmark, even though
much of the world thinks Italian and French people are delighted
with who and where they are. I guess we think the same of Danes,
but no one makes much of it.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern California we are so smitten with Italy and France
that we sometimes act like pretenders, referring to ourselves as
the Provence of California and going on about our Tuscan-like
hills. We don't often pretend to be Danish.
</P>
<P>
   Many think Californians are happy because we have wonderful
weather, which begs the question _ particularly on an August
morning when both the car heater and headlights are necessary _
what's so wonderful?
</P>
<P>
   The weather factor, often determined by the number of sunny
days, weighs heavily in those studies that rate the best places to
live. Weather is right up there with economy, crime rates and good
schools. Mayors and chambers of commerce get pumped up over these
ratings and the local newspaper is always obliged to print the
results if their city gets named, but I don't know anyone who has
ever been motivated by such lists to sell the house and take off in
a big yellow truck.
</P>
<P>
   They might if the studies included other qualities. Is there a
vet in town who makes house calls? Is the farmers market as popular
as the mall? Is there any place to go when the movie lets out?
</P>
<P>
   The Utne Reader once did a ranking of Most Enlightened Towns
that included how well they recycled. Arcata, Ca., Burlington, Vt.
and Madison, Wis., did well. The last two also showed up in a list
of top Latte Towns where people linger over coffee and prefer small
businesses to superstore chains.
</P>
<P>
   There used to be a list of the best art towns _ places to live
if you like to be around artists and go to poetry readings. The
price of real estate was an important measure because even slightly
successful creative types rely on funky places to work and live.
Several California towns showed up on that list, but the way real
estate is going here there's not much left for bohemians.
</P>
<P>
   I pointed that out to my Michigan friend, who happens to live in
a house with a full basement, attic and a sun porch which I covet
along with her warm nights. She said warm nights aren't all they're
cracked up to be.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
