<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES FALL SHARPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities fell sharply Thursday on
continuing worries that the Fed is not quite finished with its
current cycle of tightening.
</P>
<P>
   With economic reports showing no significant signs of weakening,
the 30-year bond fell 21/32 to a price of 100, or par, and its
yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose to 6.13 percent,
from 6.08 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Traders' fears were stoked early in the session after Edward
Kelley, a Federal Reserve Board governor, said in an interview with
Market News Service that the Fed remained ``intensely vigilant,''
even though it has already raised the federal funds rate a half
percentage point since late June. That is the rate that banks
charge one another for overnight loans. Kelley said it would be
premature to assume that the Fed would wait until next year to
raise rates further.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst for Chase Asset Management,
said that if the latest statistics released this week were any
guide, the Fed ``could soon tighten again despite the good deal of
recent market chatter to the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   Data over the last few days have produced steadily rising bond
yields, and Kelley's comments Thursday reinforced that trend.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's labor market data will be crucial for both near-term
bond market behavior and the Fed's next policy decision on Oct. 5,
Fine noted.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast for unemployment rates seems to be split between
assuming no change at 4.3 percent and expecting a modest drop to
4.2 percent, while projections for average hourly earnings and
nonfarm payrolls are for increases of three-tenths of a percent and
215,000 new jobs added to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The economy still has plenty of vigor, analysts say, but while
the inflation rate must still be characterized as subdued and
benign, it is no longer falling, ``and indeed appears to be slowly
rising,'' Fine said. ``While the extent of these movements is still
unknown,'' he added that the Fed's ``gumption'' is likely to be
tested over the near term.
</P>
<P>
   A report Thursday on manufacturers' orders provided further
evidence that the manufacturing sector is bouncing back, according
to Marilyn Schaja, an economist with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   Orders placed with manufacturers increased 2.1 percent in July,
after rising .8 percent in June. The increase was the largest gain
in durable goods orders in more than 18 months, while demand for
nondurables was almost flat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
