<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTOPHER-LEE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTOPHER LEE RECALLS A LEGENDARY ACTING CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (bl) 
 By TERRY PACE   The TimesDaily (Florence, Ala.)   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRYSTAL CITY, Va. _ When Christopher Lee decided to become an
actor, the first person he told was his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her reaction was straight out of Victorian melodrama,''
recalled the 77-year-old master of movie menace. ``She reeled back
with one hand to her brow and the other one holding onto the door.
She said, `You can't! You can't! You can't! Think of the shame
you'll bring upon the family _ and think of the people you will
meet!' ''
</P>
<P>
   In a screen career spanning 52 years and more than 200 features,
the British actor has encountered unforgettable people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met most of the giants, and I worked with many of them,''
Lee said during a rare personal appearance at Monster Rally '99, a
worldwide gathering of horror and science-fiction fans this August
in Crystal City, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has been directed by Laurence Olivier, John Huston, Orson
Welles and Billy Wilder, as well as modern moviemakers Steven
Spielberg, Joe Dante, John Landis and, most recently, Tim Burton.
He's acted alongside stars ranging from Bette Davis and John
Gielgud to Peter Sellers and Johnny Depp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some wonderful actors today, but there are no
giants,'' Lee said. ``People say to me, `What do you think of these
people, or those people?' I never have an answer for that. I like
to say, `They come, and they go' _ the golden boy, the golden girl,
the flavor of the month, making millions. How long will they last?
In this day and age, the way films are made and people are cast,
not long.''
</P>
<P>
   Monster Rally '99 marked the U.S. release of ``Tall, Dark and
Gruesome,'' a revised and updated edition of Lee's critically
acclaimed 1977 autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   With Lon Chaney Sr. and Jr., Bela Lugosi, Boris Karloff, Vincent
Price, Peter Cushing and John Carradine all dead and gone, Lee
remains the sole survivor of classic horror cinema's elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boris Karloff was a dear friend of mine, and for a time we
lived next door to one another in London,'' Lee said. ``It was said
that the bodies were collected daily.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee remains best-known for his portrayals of Bram Stoker's,
Dracula. Lee first assumed the role in Terence Fisher's 1958
shocker, Hammer Films' ``Horror of Dracula.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing that part was a tremendous launching pad for me,''
said Lee, who would reprise the Dracula character in six
increasingly inferior Hammer sequels. ``I wasn't a name, I wasn't a
face, although I'd been around 10 years. That was an important part
for me _ an enormously important part.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's first ``Dracula'' also marked one of many teamings with
his friend Cushing, who played the vampire slayer Professor Van
Helsing. The actors first joined forces for Hammer's 1956 ``Curse
of Frankenstein,'' in which Cushing played the ruthless baron and
Lee portrayed his creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met this quiet, reserved, extremely courteous, delightful
man,'' Lee said. ``My first reaction was, `This man is a real
actor. I can learn a lot from him.' He says I burst into his
dressing room _ looking like nothing on earth, literally _ shaking
the script and saying, `I haven't got any lines!' And he said,
`You're lucky. I've read it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cushing, who died of cancer in 1994, and Lee teamed up in
chillers for the next three decades. In their last film together,
``House of the Long Shadows'' (1983), the British duo shared
shudders with Americans Price and Carradine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gradually over the years Peter and I developed a professional
partnership, and I came to love him _ dearly,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after ``Horror of Dracula,'' Lee again donned black
cape, fangs and blood-red contact lenses to play the Transylvanian
vampire in Hammer's ``Dracula _ Prince of Darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   With each successive sequel, released between '66 and '73, Lee
grew progressively frustrated as screenwriters carried the
scenarios farther away from Stoker's 1897 novel. ``In that second
film, I did not say one word _ I flatly refused to, because I'd
read the script,'' Lee recalled. ``I said what I've always said:
`Why don't you use Stoker's words?' They never did, or hardly ever
did. There was no way I was going to burst into the room and shout,
`I am the apocalypse,' and things like that. Unbelievable. So I
never said a word.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``Dracula'' films and his partnership with
Cushing, Lee's favorites include ``The Devil's Bride'' (Hammer's
spine-tingling 1968 adaptation of Dennis Wheatley's occult novel,
``The Devil Rides Out'') and his role as Lord Summerisle, the ruler
of a secluded island of mysterious pagan worshipers, in the 1973
thriller ``The Wicker Man.''
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed a long association with Sir Arthur Conan Doyle's
detective, Sherlock Holmes. Lee played Holmes in a 1962 German film
and two 1990s made-for-TV movies. He portrayed the endangered Sir
Henry (opposite Cushing as Holmes) in Hammer's 1959 ``Hound of the
Baskervilles'' and also played Holmes' brother, Mycroft, in Billy
Wilder's ``The Private Life of Sherlock Holmes'' in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a beautiful picture,'' Lee said. ``Wilder was
everything you've heard _ a perfectionist. He said, `I spent two
years writing this, and you're going to get every word right.'
Believe me, we got it right. Thanks to Billy Wilder, my Mycroft was
infinitely better than my Holmes.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor's other mainstream credits include the James Bond
movie ``The Man With the Golden Gun'' (1974, with Lee as the
villainous assassin Scaramanga), the swashbucklers ``The Three
Musketeers'' (1974) and ``The Four Musketeers'' (1975), Disney's
fantasy ``Return from Witch Mountain'' (1978), Spielberg's comedy
``1941'' (1979), ``Serial'' (1980, with Lee as a gay biker) and
Dante's ``Gremlins 2: The New Batch'' (1990, with Lee as evil
scientist Dr. Catheter).
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Lee moved to the United States, and joined a cast _
headed by Jack Lemmon and James Stewart _ for a half-airborne,
half-underwater disaster thriller, ``Airport '77.'' Soon afterward,
Lee hosted NBC's hit late-night comedy series ``Saturday Night
Live!''
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent said, `You've been approached by the most popular
television show in the United States,' '' Lee said. ``I had never
heard of it. He said, `They want you to host. It's live
television.`' I said, `Oh no, I'm not doing live television.' ''
Lee relented, but with considerable misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at the New York studio, he immediately joined a
script-reading session. The script featured sketches spoofing Lee's
popular associations with Dracula, Holmes and Bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat down, opened the scripts and started to read,'' Lee
said. ``They all stared at me _ not a smile _ and I thought it was
going to be a catastrophe. It turned out to be a joyful experience
....''
</P>
<P>
   Lee returned to England in 1985, and his film career has
remained busy, including an upcoming cameo in Tim Burton's spin on
Washington Irving's ``Sleepy Hollow,'' which will be released to
theaters in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Burton is an actor's dream _ he directs with such
enthusiasm,'' Lee said. ``I only have a small scene _ two or three
minutes at the most. But my scene is with the star of the film,
Johnny Depp, who has renewed my faith in the star system. He is
such a good actor. I think he's as good as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, the 6-foot, 4-inch actor, doesn't rule out another
screen outing in cape and fangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I would do it _ but only if it was Stoker,'' Lee said,
``what he wrote and what the character said. Not word for word, but
using his lines and his story, because it has never, ever been
done.''
</P>
<P>
   (Terry Pace is the entertainment editor of the TimesDaily in
Florence, Ala., which is a member of The New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group. This article was distributed by The New York Times
News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
