A8941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BUDWEISER-RECALL-NYT &LR;      09-02 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDWEISER-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDWEISER RECALLS 5.7 MILLION BOTTLES OF BEER IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By AL GOODMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ Anheuser-Busch Cos., the world's largest brewer,
said Thursday that it was recalling 5.7 million bottles of its
Budweiser and Bud brands from 12 European nations after consumers
complained that glass slivers had broken off the rim of some
bottles when the twist-off caps were removed.
</P>
<P>
   The brewer, based in St. Louis, said the recall covered less
than 1 percent of its beer sold annually in Europe. The move
involves all 25-centiliter and 33-centiliter twist-off bottles sold
in Spain, Belgium, Portugal, Germany, Denmark, Sweden, the
Netherlands, Switzerland, Latvia, Cyprus and Malta, and
25-centiliter bottles in France.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of the beer is not the problem, Anheuser-Busch said
in a statement. The company traced the defects to two glass
suppliers, one in Madrid and the other in Portugal, where faulty
manufacturing equipment caused the rims of some bottles to extend
slightly more than normal, making them susceptible to breaking off.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch said that a small number of bottles filled in
Spain but sold in Britain had also been recalled. But the company
said that twist-off Budweiser bottles filled in Britain were not at
risk, nor were those sold in Italy, Ireland or Greece, which use
glass from a different source.
</P>
<P>
   A man from Ireland on vacation in the Canary Islands of Spain
complained to the company on Aug. 11 after apparently swallowing a
piece of glass, and nine more complaints have come in since Aug.
25, including reports from France of one person cutting a hand and
another cutting a lip, said William H. McNulty, vice president and
managing director for Europe for Anheuser-Busch European Trade Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working very diligently'' on the recall, McNulty said in
a phone interview from his Brussels office. ``Everyone understands
the importance of this.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 11 percent of the 5.7 million bottles were collected
on Wednesday, the first day of the recall, with special attention
to Spain, the most affected country, where 3.2 million bottles were
recalled, McNulty said.
</P>
<P>
   France and Belgium have the next highest number of bottles to be
collected. Budweiser is sold under the Anheuser-Busch B brand name
in Germany and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   He said Anheuser-Busch had been on a ``higher level of alert''
since the company received a single complaint in February about a
bottle problem at the Portuguese glass plant, called Barbosa
Almeda, followed by a complaint in May about the Madrid plant,
Vicasa.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch has no ownership stake in nor management control
of the two glass companies, which supply bottles to a Spanish
company in Barcelona that brews the Anheuser-Busch brands for the
12 nations affected by the recall.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch's statement said the manufacturing problem was
caused by ``uneven wear and tear on the bottle-forming mold
equipment,'' but McNulty said he did not know why both bottle
suppliers, in separate countries, would have similar
quality-control defects other than the possible use of their
equipment too long before replacing it.
</P>
<P>
   The two glass plants ``are working to help resolve the problem
by revising their production equipment that will assure the problem
will not recur,'' Anheuser-Busch said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second significant drink recall in Europe this
summer. Coca-Cola Co., the world's largest soft-drink maker,
withdrew millions of cans across Europe in June after hundreds of
people reported illnesses from drinking the company's products.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch's revenues in Europe are less than 5 percent of
the parent company's total, McNulty said. The brewer exported beer
to Europe for decades before establishing a presence in 1984 in
Britain with a licensed brewery arrangement and has since expanded
across the Continent.
</P>
</TEXT>
