<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CLONEDBULL03-COX     09-02 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLONEDBULL03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A&AMP;M will introduce calf cloned from adult bovine
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ralph Fisher wanted a second chance for his
famous bull named Chance, and Texas A&AMP;M University gave him one: a
clone that will be mugged for the cameras Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Second Chance, a 24-day-old calf that was trotted out at an
Aggie news conference in College Station, is only the second bovine
to be cloned from an adult animal in the United States. There are
several others in the world, and they are being touted as a
potential boon for the cattle industry _ a quick way to reproduce
the traits in a prized animal that, left to nature, would take
years.
</P>
<P>
   Chance died last September, but not before Texas A&AMP;M researchers
took cells from his skin. They later injected one of the cells into
a cow egg and implanted it in a surrogate mother. She gave birth to
Second Chance Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's the oldest bull that's ever been cloned, and
it's the oldest male animal,'' said cloning project leader Mark
Westhusin, an associate professor of veterinary physiology and
pharmacology at Texas A&AMP;M. ``We're glad we got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Connecticut got there first. In
June, they introduced Amy, a 94-pound Holstein, the first calf
cloned from an adult in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher doesn't care who was first. He is thrilled that his bull,
Chance, will live on in a clone that will be returned to him when
Texas A&AMP;M is finished studying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I care about my baby,'' said Fisher, who is 55 and put himself
through college as a rodeo clown. ``The hair stands up on the back
of my neck when I hold him and squeeze him. It's a miracle of
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the original, Second Chance is playful, and the researchers
want to see if he'll look the same and be as gentle as Chance.
They're also interested in how quickly he'll age.
</P>
<P>
   Chance was a 2,000 pound Brahman bull _ the kind with the hump
and hanging skin _ who traveled the rodeo and celebrity circuit and
was photographed with politicians, beauty queens and celebrities,
including former Houston Mayor Bob Lanier, Dan Rather, Connie
Chung, Willie Nelson and the late Sonny Bono. Chance appeared in
commercials and on the David Letterman show 10 years ago. Sandra
Fisher, Ralph's wife, said he also ``starred'' in a movie with Kate
Capshaw and Ashley Judd.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a big old, wonderful, fuzzy . . . tame breeding bull I
turned into a pet and a business partner for years,'' said Ralph
Fisher, who photographed Chance at all of the events. He has
similar plans for his Second Chance.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Chance unusually gentle, he looked different than
today's Brahman cattle, which have been changed by selective
breeding, Fisher said. Chance had a larger head and hump, much
bigger horns and more skin hanging from his neck and belly. Those
traits have been diminished in modern Brahman cattle to reduce the
amount of waste when the animals are made into steaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's part of a dying bloodline,'' Fisher said, adding that
he's not trying to revive the breed. ``I'd just like to have him in
the same capacity as before, as a partner in the business,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, an alumnus of Sam Houston State University, said he took
Chance to Texas A&AMP;M for various surgeries over the years and grew
to trust the vets. Fisher told them that Chance would be a great
animal to clone, and Westhusen is leading a $2.3 million effort to
clone the first dog _ Missy, a mixed-breed border collie.
Researchers in Scotland have also cloned a sheep named Dolly from
an adult animal.
</P>
<P>
   When Chance died, Fisher cried, his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said he couldn't bear to bury Chance. ``I could have left
him in the pasture for the buzzards to get him or I could have
buried him with a front end loader, but . . . I just couldn't throw
him away.'' Fisher spent about eight hours removing Chance's skin,
and then took it to a taxidermist to mount and stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said he had no qualms about having Chance cloned. ``I
don't think it would be a good idea for the human species, but if
it's used in the right way with animals, they can eliminate
diseases we've had for years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In religious circles, most mainline denominations have taken a
stand against human cloning, but the lines are still fuzzy when it
comes to animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``How far do you go?'' said the Rev. John Leies, director of the
Center for Professional Ethics at St. Mary's University of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
