<HEADER>
A8949 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-UNREST-475&AMP;ADD-     09-02 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-UNREST-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVILIAN MILITIAS TAKING CONTROL IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ In an eerie, silent pre-dawn exodus, hundreds
of frightened East Timorese walked through dark streets Thursday
morning to board a giant ferry that docked here just long enough to
pick them up, then left again.
</P>
<P>
   With Indonesian security forces apparently under orders to do
nothing, this tiny provincial capital is coming increasingly under
the control of brutal, hard-eyed civilian militias, and people here
_ both local and foreign _ are terrified.
</P>
<P>
   Many are fleeing, driving across the border into neighboring
West Timor or trying to charter aircraft to fly out.
</P>
<P>
   The worsening situation is creating a diplomatic crisis, with
some nations threatening to send in their own troops to maintain
order and with the Indonesian government promising _ for at least
the fifth time _ to assert itself and bring order.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wiranto, the armed forces chief of staff, promised Thursday
to provide extra security for U.N. workers, who are counting the
ballots from a referendum Monday in which East Timor was to choose
whether to break away from Indonesia, which invaded and occupied it
in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   A huge turnout of nearly 99 percent of registered voters, in
defiance of a campaign of terror by the militias, has led many
experts to predict a strong vote for independence.
</P>
<P>
   President B.J. Habibie said he might be open to the deployment
of a U.N. peacekeeping force _ an extraordinary admission that his
own armed forces were not executing his stated policy of
controlling East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Condemnation of Indonesia's actions in East Timor came from
around the world. Citizens of some 70 nations have been taking part
in the U.N. program to organize the referendum and many are now
stranded here, unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. diplomat, Assistant Secretary of State Stanley Roth, said
there was no excuse for Indonesia's failure to bring order to this
tiny territory of 800,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions by the Indonesian police and military have been
unacceptable,'' he said. ``They can't say they don't want the
international community to come in with peacekeepers if they're not
going to provide the security themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   With the words and deeds of Indonesian officials seeming to have
little relationship to each other, a key question has become where
the chain of command has broken down _ between the president and
the armed forces chief, between the chief and his generals, or
between the generals and their forces on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   With its long history of counterinsurgency here, the Indonesian
military has many means of asserting itself, some of which have
only a tenuous connection with the chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   But the sudden calm on election day, after intense pressure from
abroad to curtail the pre-election violence, seemed to demonstrate
that the authorities can switch the violence off and on as they
choose.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since early this year, the military has sought to undermine the
possibility of independence for East Timor by creating and arming
the militias. Some of these groups are believed to answer directly
to military officers.
</P>
<P>
   The police _ never known for their competence or professionalism
_ have been placed in an impossible situation, with the task of
controlling armed irregulars that are acting as surrogates for the
military.
</P>
<P>
   Looking on helplessly as militia members threatened to kidnap
one East Timorese man Thursday, a police colonel expressed his
frustration after four years of service here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chessboard with 14 players and 30 spectators, all
with different agendas,'' said the officer, Lt. Col. J.J. Sitompul.
``And on the chessboard are two dogs, all ready to fight. We, the
police, have to keep the two dogs apart, and both the dogs can bite
the police. That is my philosophy. The words are polite, but the
feelings are bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   As the police stand aside, the militias have become increasingly
brazen and visible in Dili since the voting.
</P>
<P>
   They have begun watching the hotels where foreigners from around
the city have gathered for safety. At one point Thursday two armed
men entered the Turismo Hotel, shouted threats and kicked a
Canadian election observer.
</P>
<P>
   They have made the airport their turf, wandering unimpeded
through restricted areas and seeking to prevent East Timorese from
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   In their black T-shirts they roam the streets on motorcycles,
sometimes displaying weapons. They have set up roadblocks around
the city and the countryside, peering at passengers inside vehicles
and sometimes seizing East Timorese who do not please them for one
reason or another.
</P>
<P>
   There were both police and military officers present on
Wednesday when the militias threatened the U.N. compound and killed
three people in a running battle with pro-independence thugs on the
street outside.
</P>
<P>
   But the police did little to control the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that we would not be in a position to have
prevented the worst violence if the mob had indeed attempted to
attack the compound itself,'' said Ian Martin, chief of the U.N.
mission here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
