<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CARS-SAFETY-TECHNOLOG     09-02 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-SAFETY-TECHNOLOGY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO TECHNOLOGY: SHIFTING AWAY FROM `PRNDL' AUTOMATIC
TRANSMISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JIM McCRAW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some 30 years now, the shift pattern for an automatic
transmission hasn't varied much from Park, Reverse, Neutral, Drive
and Low, a PRNDL pattern from which Detroit has coined a word:
Prindle. That's because Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 102
says the pattern must be consistent, for safety reasons _ mainly to
prevent motorists from misshifting when they start to drive away.
</P>
<P>
   Before that standard was issued in 1966, manufacturers were free
to develop any sequence they wanted for automatic shifters, and
some used unusual patterns in places that may seem odd today.
Chrysler Corp.'s cars of 1955-56 had levers that protruded from the
instrument panel, followed in 1957-64 by push-button shifters at
the left side of the dashboard. Ford Motor Co.'s ill-fated Edsel of
1958-60 had shifter push buttons mounted in the hub of the steering
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   But now, at a time when technology is rapidly changing the way
that cars work and the ways that drivers control them, some
manufacturers would not only like to alter the pattern, they'd like
to put the shifter somewhere besides the steering column or the
floor console, the two places the federal government requires.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, BMW petitioned the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration to change vehicle standard 102. The German
manufacturer would like to free up space on the center console for
things like in-car entertainment systems, cellular telephones, CD
changers, navigation systems _ even televisions and electronic
games.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Patterson, a BMW staff safety engineer, said that most
modern automatic transmissions are shifted electronically anyway,
and that the shifter simply activates electric solenoids rather
than moving cables or levers to change gears. He says the
electronic technology exists to use smaller, lighter push buttons,
a key pad, or a rotary display. He says that the push buttons, a
key pad or a rotary display could then be mounted on the dashboard,
on the console _ or even on the steering wheel like the shifters
used in Formula One racing.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, until the federal standard is changed, no
manufacturer is free to relocate the shifter or change the
traditional Prindle pattern, which reads left to right on a
column-mounted shifter or front to back on the console.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of opinion as to what the standard actually
says,'' Patterson said. ``The standard doesn't say you must use
PRNDL. Logic and industry practice says that park must be next to
reverse, and neutral must be between reverse and drive, and you
have to have a means for low. It's a matter of logic that you get
to PRNDL in terms of requirements, and it's written with a
gearshift lever in mind. That's what we asked NHTSA to clarify, and
that's why we want to have a new rule. We'd really like to do
this.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The industry's two largest lobbying groups, the American
Automobile Manufacturers Association and the Association of Import
Automobile Manufacturers, have filed a joint comment in support of
a change.
</P>
<P>
   The comment says, in part, ``We note that nonserially shiftable
designs, such as joysticks, key pads and touch screens, can be
designed to provide a functionally equivalent `dead zone' between
forward and reverse gears.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NHTSA's mandatory 90-day comment-gathering period, during
which industry, government, the public and safety lobbyists can
express their views, expired Sept. 2, and now the agency is in the
throes of deciding whether to accede to the industry's wishes or
keep standard 102 as it is. Officials at the agency had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MCCAIN-DEWINE03-COX     09-02 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-DEWINE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEWINE ENDORSES MCCAIN FOR PRESIDENT
 &HT;    330&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bucking a tide of support for Texas Gov. George W.
Bush throughout the GOP and his own state of Ohio, Sen. Mike DeWine
on Thursday endorsed Sen. John McCain for president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine spoke with reporters by telephone about his decision
before boarding a plane to New Hampshire, where he will appear with
the Arizona senator to formalize the endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``My strong, strong belief is that the next president has to be
a great leader in foreign affairs,'' DeWine said. ``When you're
dealing with foreign affairs, this is the man in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   In siding with McCain, DeWine joins a dark-horse campaign in a
year when the front-runner, Bush, has lapped the field in raising
money and gaining endorsements. In Ohio alone, Bush has gained the
support of the governor and nine of 11 Republican members of the
U.S. House. The highest-ranking holdout is Sen. George Voinovich,
who hasn't endorsed anyone.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine will become one of six national co-chairmen for the
McCain campaign. The others are Sens. Fred Thompson of Tennessee,
Chuck Hagel of Nebraska and Jon Kyl of Arizona, as well as former
Sen. Warren Rudman of New Hampshire and prominent New York
businesswoman Georgette Mosbacher.
</P>
<P>
   McCain issued a statement praising DeWine as he accepted the
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike and I have fought to reform the way the federal
government works, take better care of our citizens and reduce the
tax burden on America's working families,'' McCain said. ``With
Mike's help, I know my campaign of independent conservative reform
will be successful next year in Ohio and across the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWine wouldn't talk about the other Republican candidates in
the race, but he repeatedly discussed McCain's experience in
international matters, which is considered a Bush weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a very perilous time that I don't think most
Americans fully appreciate,'' DeWine said, ``so foreign policy for
me is absolutely the deciding factor.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   DeWine cited the matter of America's military presence in
Lebanon in the early 1980s. He said he still remembers a powerful
speech McCain made when he and DeWine both were in the House,
opposing then-President Reagan's decision to stay in Lebanon. A
month later a terrorist bomb destroyed a U.S. military barracks and
killed 241 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He voted one way, most of us voted the other way,'' DeWine
said. ``He was right, I was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is a former fighter pilot who became a national hero
after spending six years in a Vietnam prison camp, refusing to
accept early release because his father was a Navy admiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``To know him is to be inspired by him,'' DeWine said in a
statement before taking questions. ``I know that when John McCain
leads, people follow. He is decisive, he has guts. He leaves no
room for ambiguity and uncertainty in his reasoned policy
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is seen around Washington as a maverick who has almost
gleefully challenged leaders of the Republican Party on such things
as campaign finance reform. Despite the best efforts of party
leaders, McCain has pushed a bill that would ban unlimited ``soft
money'' contributions to political parties, used to circumvent
spending limits for individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine opposes the McCain bill and said he hasn't changed is
opinion on the matter. He said his endorsement of McCain is based
on their lengthy friendship, which began in 1982, when they both
first entered the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying by this endorsement is I've watched this
man,'' DeWine said. ``This man is a leader and he's a man who I
want to be commander in chief.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
