<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-02 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: SRI LANKA; NORTHERN IRELAND; RUSSIA; COLOMBIA;
MEXICO; ISRAEL
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: 3 DIE IN BLAST
</P>
<P>
   An explosion tore through the headquarters of the People's
Liberation Organization of Tamil Eelam in Vavuniya, killing three
people, including Nagalingam Manikkadasan, the leader of the
political party's militia. The group has three members in
Parliament and has cooperated with the government in fighting
against the Tamil Tigers, a separatist guerrilla army.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: JOURNALIST LOSES
</P>
<P>
   A Belfast journalist lost a legal bid to overturn a court order
directing him to give police notes of an interview with a former
Protestant paramilitary man arrested in June in the murder of Pat
Finucane, a well-known Catholic human rights lawyer, in 1989. The
killing has attracted international attention because of charges
that the Royal Ulster Constabulary may have helped the murderer. Ed
Moloney, Northern Ireland editor of The Sunday Tribune of Dublin,
has 10 days to appeal the ruling and says he will go to jail rather
than turn over the notes.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: DWINDLING POPULATION
</P>
<P>
   Russia's population of 146 million, already down more than 2.5
million since 1991, could lose 8 million more people by 2016, the
Russian Statistics Agency reported. High mortality, a plummeting
birth rate and rising emigration are behind the drain; the nation
lost 346,700 citizens in the first five months of 1999 alone.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: STRIKE CALLED OFF
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions have called off an indefinite general strike after
more than 70 people died in armed clashes in the first two days of
the work stoppage. Right-wing paramilitary forces were reported to
have killed at least 20 people in one such attack, which came after
a separate battle between the army and left-wing rebels claiming to
be acting in solidarity with the estimated 1 million workers and
peasants who had joined the strike.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: MAYORAL RIVALS
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Silva Herzog, a former treasury secretary and Mexico's
former ambassador to Washington, and Roberto Campa Cifrian, a
former leader of the governing party's Mexico City organization,
are campaigning for the Institutional Revolutionary Party's
nomination for mayor of Mexico City. A primary will be held on Nov.
7.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: ARAB HELD IN SLAYINGS
</P>
<P>
   A 20-year-old Israeli Arab man was arrested after he is said to
have confessed to the stabbing murders of a young Orthodox Jewish
couple in a nature reserve near Megiddo. Although Hamas, the
militant Islamic group, had belatedly claimed responsibility, that
claim was not verified. The arrested man, Abdullah Ighbaria, comes
from a village in northern Israel, according to the Israeli army
radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
