<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8961 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EAFRICA-INVEST03-COX     09-02 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAFRICA-INVEST03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More U.S. investment in East Africa encouraged
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The prime minister of Uganda issued an appeal Thursday
for more U.S. investment in East Africa, pointing to political and
economic reforms that have swept the three-nation market of 80
million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is common knowledge that in the past many credible
investors avoided Uganda because life was short, brutal and
nasty,'' Prime Minister Apollo Nsibami told an East African
investment conference at the Carter Center in Atlanta. ``The past
mistakes are being addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Idi Amin and Milton Obote dictatorships were blamed for the
slaughter of 800,000 Ugandans during the 1970s and 1980s. Nsibami
noted that a new politically stable government led by President
Yoweri Museveni replaced ``the erratic and brutal political
regimes'' in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Uganda, Tanzania and Kenya are all pressing forward with
political reforms and dismantling ``corrupt monopolies'' as well as
establishing a free trade zone that will cover their combined
populations, Nsibami said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make good money in Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania, which
can be fully repatriated to the USA and elsewhere because
restrictions on currency transfers are disappearing,'' said the
University of Chicago-educated prime minister. ``Indeed, in Uganda,
there are no currency restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade summit was organized by Kenyans, Tanzanians and
Ugandans living and working in the United States. More than 100
people attended.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was sponsored by Coca-Cola Co., Western Union,
Delta Air Lines and other U.S. companies with African operations.
Ambassadors to the United States from the three countries took
part.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Powell, principal deputy assistant secretary of state for
African affairs, said U.S. trade and investment with Africa has
grown by leaps and bounds during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   But only 1 percent of all U.S. foreign investment is in Africa
and the continent is still ``the last frontier for U.S. trade and
investment,'' she said. ``U.S. companies are behind the curve.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is seeking to expand economic ties
with Africa by supporting African trade legislation in Congress,
beefing up Commerce Department staff stationed in African countries
and through debt relief and investment programs, Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater will host a U.S.-Africa
transportation summit in Atlanta on Sept. 27-29, also at the Carter
Center. The discussion will focus on aviation, highway and other
transportation issues, the Transportation Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8962 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SPENDING-$ADV05-COX     09-02 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPENDING-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS IS SHORT OF FUNDS FOR ITS LAST SPENDING BILL
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress opens its fall session Wednesday without
any agreement on how to avoid huge spending cuts next year in some
of the most popular federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds of programs that would be on the chopping block
include aid to public schools and college students, the operational
costs of Medicare and Head Start, nursing home inspections, medical
research, summer jobs for teens and retraining for dislocated
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats agree that the social and political
consequences of brutal cuts in those programs would be too
devastating to allow. In fact, Democrats want to increase spending
on education and Republicans want to increase spending on medical
research.
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders made no attempt during their August break to
agree on how to do that. Instead, they spent most of their public
appearances debating the pros and cons of a tax-cut bill that few
believe will ever become law.
</P>
<P>
   The programs at risk are paid for annually by an appropriation
bill for three departments: Labor, Health and Human Services, and
Education. Called the ``Labor-HHS'' bill for short, it is
traditionally the last of the 13 annual appropriation bills to get
through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The House is scheduled to start work on its version of the
Labor-HHS bill within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The budget arithmetic for the Labor-HHS bill is brutal:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mainstream education and medical research organizations are
lobbying for a $93 billion version, and President Clinton asked for
about $92 billion.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``freeze'' extending this year's programs for another year
without any adjustment for inflation would cost $89 billion.
</P>
<P>
   _ But under the budget plans Republicans adopted early this
year, the Senate has only $81 billion and the House has less than
$74 billion left for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The result could be program cuts of 10 to 18 percent below the
``freeze'' level, and deeper in many cases. For example, if
Congress decided that instead of cutting research funds for the
National Institutes of Health, it will freeze them, the other
programs would have to be slashed by an average of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking a way out, the Senate, the House and Clinton face two
unpalatable options:
</P>
<P>
   _ Offset the extra cost by spending less on other federal
programs, or by increasing federal receipts _ the opposite of
cutting taxes. Neither the administration nor Congress has accepted
the other's ideas about how to do that.
</P>
<P>
   _ Approve the extra money without offsets, perhaps using
creative bookkeeping to obscure that fact.
</P>
<P>
   The second option is the simplest. But it would require a delay
of at least one year in the fulfillment of pledges by Clinton to
``save Social Security first'' or by Republicans to create a
``Social Security lock box.''
</P>
<P>
   Those slogans are political shorthand for using the Social
Security surplus solely to pay down the national debt. The idea is
that as the debt _ and annual interest payments on it _ shrink, it
will be easier for the federal government to pay for Social
Security benefits when the baby boomers retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that everyone has made promises they can't
keep,'' said James Horney, who coordinated official budget
projections for Congress for seven years before joining the private
Center for Budget and Policy Priorities in July. ``I think
everyone's hoping for a miracle, but no one knows what it will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither party wants to be the first to suggest a one-year
extension of the long custom of borrowing a small portion of the
Social Security surplus to pay government operating expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president thinks we should use Social Security money,
he should let us know, and if he chooses to pay for it some other
way, he should let us know,'' Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., chairman of
the House Republican Conference, said in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic president won't be trapped by the ``cynical
and wrong'' strategy of the Republicans, according to John Podesta,
the White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Press Club, Podesta recalled news reports that
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, advocates ``underfunding
some of those important bills, like Labor-HHS ... in order to jam
the president into dipping into the Social Security Trust Fund,
which they have pledged not to raid.''
</P>
<P>
   Podesta said, ``Ultimately, I think, the Republican leadership
and the Democratic leadership and we in the administration are
going to have to sit down and try to work through this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not bent on a showdown with the president,'' Watts said.
``We're willing to work with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
