<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CARS-Y2K-NYT &LR;      09-02 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-Y2K-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO Y2K PROBLEMS FOR AUTOS, SAY MANUFACTURERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jan. 1 may or may not bring computer-induced apocalypse, but if
it does, you can still drive away, the auto companies say. Your car
will not turn into a pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   New vehicles have microchips running everything from
transmissions to air bags, the remote keyless entry system, the
AM/FM/stereo/CD player and the air-conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   But of these microchips, which can number about two dozen, ``the
vast majority have no date functionality whatsoever,'' said General
Motors spokesman John Ahearne. In other words, when it comes to the
date, these computers don't ask and don't care, and can't fall
victim to the Year 2000 bug.
</P>
<P>
   In cars that have a dashboard indicator for oil changes, the
computer still does not care about the date, the manufacturers say.
``If the car sits in your garage for a year, your oil light is not
going to come on,'' said Ford Motor spokeswoman Kathleen Vokes. It
counts miles, not days, she said.
</P>
<P>
   About the only computer that may track the date is the one that
displays the date as well as the time for the driver. Those too
will work properly, said Joseph Majcher, director of Engineering
Y2K Readiness at GM. He said his company had started putting
microchips in cars about 15 years ago, and for the last two years
has been checking that they were all ready for 2000. They are, he
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   That should leave no problems at all, except for the card-swipe
unit on the gasoline pump, the electricity to run the pump, the
street lights and your home garage door opener _ and, of course,
the computer that runs the traffic lights.
</P>
<P>
   The President's Council on the Year 2000 Conversion reported
Aug. 5 that power, telecommunications and most other vital
functions appeared highly likely to work just fine. But the 911
emergency system might not function normally in all cities, the
report said. It did not say anything about the computers that
process traffic tickets issued on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The car companies, of course, have other Year 2000 worries, like
whether their factories will keep running. Ms. Vokes said that Ford
did not think it would have problems but would have a special crew
on duty at its world headquarters in Dearborn, Mich., just in case,
and that that was where she would be spending New Year's Eve. To
prove that that her car was all right, she said, ``maybe I should
just drive around world headquarters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
