<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FRIDAY-PRAY-COX     09-02 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIDAY-PRAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some school districts to defy ban on pre-game prayers
 &HT;    By Becky Bell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ In the wake of a federal court ruling,
organized silence will help kick off the football season tonight in
the East Texas Bible belt where pregame prayers over the public
address system has long been looked upon as a sacred tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the U.S. Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals held that a
Texas school district's policy allowing invocations and
benedictions at high school football games violated the
Establishment Clause of the United States Constitution. The legal
opinion was handed down in the case of Doe V. Santa Fe Independent
School District.
</P>
<P>
   The court upheld a lower court's decision allowing limited
prayer at graduation ceremonies, but ruled out prayers or other
solemnizing ceremonies before football games.
</P>
<P>
   The Fifth Circuit Court has jurisdiction over Texas, Louisiana
and Mississippi, so the decision is binding on all Texas school
districts.
</P>
<P>
   The Longview News-Journal newspaper contacted school districts
in 11 counties this week to find out how prayer at Friday night
football games would be handled.
</P>
<P>
   Not one school gave the same answer, and no superintendents said
they were glad to see the tradition discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   And at a couple of school districts, the tradition will
continue, despite a warning from the Texas Association of School
Boards (TASB) that districts that continue to allow
school-sponsored prayer at football games are taking significant
legal risks.
</P>
<P>
   The statement from the association states that a person
challenging the practice could recover injunctive relief, monetary
damages, court costs and attorney's fees from the district.
Individual trustees and school district employees could face
similar penalties for allowing the practice, and immunity would not
be available, TASB said.
</P>
<P>
   Waskom Independent School District Superintendent Richard Cook
said the school board made a unanimous decision at a special
meeting Monday to continue prayer at football games, despite the
legal risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically most of the superintendents were going to continue
doing what they had done in the past until they got the TASB fax,''
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he shared the information he received about prayer,
including the TASB document, and told trustees they would be
breaking the law if they continued the practice. Cook said he gave
the board five options regarding the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first option was to not pray, the second option was to
have an announcement that said the Fifth Circuit ruling made
praying at the game unconstitutional, the third option was to have
a moment of silence, the fourth option was to have a student-led,
student initiated prayer and the fifth option was to have a school
board member conduct the prayer,'' Cook said. ``They chose the last
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting drew a larger than usual crowd, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally at our school board meetings, we have 15 spectators
maximum,'' Cook said. ``There were about 120 people, and we
specifically asked if anyone opposed it, because we wanted to hear
their particular concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook said no one spoke against school board members leading the
prayer before each game. Cook said he has the support of those who
matter most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should be a community decision. The community is
who the school is there to serve,'' Cook said. `` I don't think
someone outside the community saying what the community desires is
appropriate, and I don't think that's what's intended in our
particular government system.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilgore Independent School District Superintendent Jerry Roberts
said the district will continue to have prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the community will expect us to do as we always have
done, and that's how we've always opened our game,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said he did not know who would lead the prayer at the
game on Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Longview Independent School District officials who as recently
as Monday said they planned to allow the traditional pre-game
prayer, have reversed themselves. Wednesday, on the advice of their
attorney, Longview ISD issued a statement saying, ``Longview ISD
can no longer continue the inclusion of student-initiated prayer at
school sporting events.''
</P>
<P>
   The prepared statement said attorneys had warned the district
that ``activist groups and individuals may be vigilant in watching
for violations.''
</P>
<P>
   Longview Superintendent Arthur Culver said the district can't
risk breaking the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really regret that we can't continue the tradition
established here for quite some time. We don't like it, but we must
follow the law,'' Culver said. ``We can't afford to put the
district in a predicament where it could receive punitive damages
that could reach an extreme amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Gary Shaver, who represents several area school
districts including Longview, believes the prayer issue is causing
a furor because it's more than a legal issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ethical and moral issue for a lot of school
districts,'' Shaver said. ``In my own personal opinion, I don't
believe the expression of one's faith is offensive. I don't see how
that could possibly be.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell writes for the Longview News-Journal, Longview, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
