<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8971 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUTCARS-BMW-ART-$AD     09-02 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUTCARS-BMW-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW'S 3-SERIES COUPES: MORE OF EVERYTHING WITH TWO FEWER DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DAN NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news that BMW has begun building two-door versions of its
acclaimed 3-Series barely qualifies as news. The German company
routinely introduces a new series in sedan form _ in this case, the
so-called E46 platform, which arrived last year _ then elaborates
at regular intervals with coupe and convertible models.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the 3-Series coupe a wild departure from the sedan in
matters stylistic and mechanical.
</P>
<P>
   But it is by no means an insignificant car, just as no piece in
chess is insignificant. With the new coupe, BMW advances yet
another pawn to pin down opponents in yet another sub-segment of
the market. In the 2000 model year, BMW will offer everything from
bumblebee roadsters (the Z3 2.3) to Galaxy-class battleships (the
12-cylinder 750iL light-armored sedan); from compact wagons (the
emerging 3-Series wagon) to the X5 ``sport activity vehicle''; from
this fall's ferocious 400-horsepower M5 performance sedan to James
Bond's new grocery-getter, the stunning Z8 convertible.
</P>
<P>
   And, by the way, the company also makes motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   At every turn, BMW seeks to box in and triangulate its
competition with a multiplicity of platforms, options, engines and
trim levels. For instance, the new 328Ci, with a base price of
$34,560, nearly splits the price difference between the Saab 9-3 SE
($31,700) and the Volvo C70 ($40,000), its most likely rivals among
European sport coupes. In fact, if you went looking for a heads-up
competitor for the two-door BMW 3-Series _ front-engine,
rear-drive, two-door, manually shifted cars around $35,000 _ you
would find that particular square on the board unoccupied. In goes
the pawn.
</P>
<P>
   Yet BMW offers its customers something more ineffably satisfying
than the right car at the right price. This company has charisma.
It currently dominates big-time endurance racing (BMW won this
year's 24 Hours of Le Mans) and is wading into Formula One next
year _ racing being all about glory and only tangentially about
selling cars. It regularly commissions ``art cars'' painted by the
likes of David Hockney and Jenny Holzer. It blithely spends
millions to build the M Coupe _ a car of inspired homeliness _ just
to give auto writers a hotfoot.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to love attitude like that.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, it's considered bad form, a failure of imagination, for
a car maker merely to lop off the back doors of a sedan to create a
coupe. Witness the Toyota Camry Solara, which puts a lot of
stylistic ground between itself and its four-door sibling. But cars
like the M Coupe effectively inoculate BMW against that charge. The
3-Series coupe confidently mirrors the styling of the sedan. The
windshield is slightly more raked and the car is lower, due in part
to the coupe's standard, half-inch-lower sport suspension. And
while there is no sheet metal shared between sedan and coupe, the
subtle differences are a test of one's observational powers.
</P>
<P>
   As an addition to the BMW canon, the E46 coupe is pretty tame
stuff, nothing like the International-influenced 2000 CS and 3.0 CS
of the 1960s and 1970s. Still, it is a handsome car, taut and
balanced, a wound spring of road-going energy.
</P>
<P>
   Like the sedan, the coupe is available with in-line sixes of
either 2.5 liters and 170 horsepower, or 2.8 liters with 193 horses
(the 323Ci and 328Ci, respectively). Either of these all-aluminum
motors _ equipped with high-tech breathing apparatus like
infinitely variable valve timing _ produce abundant torque with
oily smoothness and a symphonic exhaust note. There is a wonderful
elasticity to these cars. In second gear _ the around-town gear, if
you will _ the car surges as if pulled by a snapping rubber band
from low revs through the redline. The 328Ci offers sparkling
acceleration, with 0-to-60 m.p.h. times of about 6 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   A five-speed manual transmission is standard equipment; but the
coupes are also available with a five-speed automatic with a
``Steptronic'' manual mode. In addition, both coupes and sedans
will come with Dynamic Stability Control, the company's
cornering-stability system, as standard equipment. Traction-control
assisted brakes, generous four-wheel ventilated disks, are also
standard.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the equipment that came with the sedans' optional Sport
package is standard equipment in the coupes. Larger alloy wheels
and tires (16 by 7 inch) are standard; in September, 17-inch tires,
the same as appear on the M3 performance coupe, will be available
as options.
</P>
<P>
   The coupes' suspensions are also borrowed from the sedans' Sport
packages. Firmer springs and shock absorbers at all four corners,
with calibrated increases in anti-roll bars, are standard.
</P>
<P>
   BMW's front-strut, rear multi-link suspensions are unsurpassed.
The moment you put your hands on the three-spoke steering wheel,
you are in instant mind-meld with the car, intuitively aware of its
balance and grip, an intuition that only grows more intimate as you
work the car from one arcing curve to the next. The rigid,
lightweight body, 50-50 weight distribution and communicative
rack-and pinion steering impart the lean athleticism of a quarter
horse. For pure driving pleasure, I think the 3-Series coupe
handily beats out the smaller and faster _ and twitchy _ M
Roadster.
</P>
<P>
   BMW has slathered the coupes with all manner of upgrades,
including the standard multi-function steering wheel encrusted with
buttons that control the audio system and cruise control. It also
comes with fog lights, onboard computer, and Automatic
Recirculation Control, which sniffs the outside air for pollution
and, when it finds it, switches to recirculated air. Multiple smart
air bags and inflatable head restraints, 10-speaker sound system,
keyless entry and security system are also all standard. As well,
much of the equipment formerly available only on top-line models _
on-board navigation, parking-distance alert _ can be bought as
stand-alone options.
</P>
<P>
   It's all good. But at the core of the BMW experience, there is
just a steering wheel, a seat, a gear shift and a motor, bending
and flexing the road ahead. For all its chess-like gamesmanship in
the market, BMW's wisest tactic is to protect the legendary driving
pleasure of its cars. That is the company's most valuable piece on
the board.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
