<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8972 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-TWIN03-COX     09-02 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TWIN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Misfits find bittersweet intimacy in dark yet hopeful `Twin
Falls Idaho'
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Blake and Francis Falls know from intimacy. The
way the identical twins limp abreast, whisper in each other's ears
and embrace in sleep like elderly lovers, you would think they were
joined at the hip. You'd be wrong: The brothers are yoked by an
island of stretched, bluish flesh that bridges the young men in
eternal union.
</P>
<P>
   Siamese twins, they share a third leg and the same blood supply,
pumped by individual hearts. That can get bothersome when one of
those hearts is summoned to matters of love.
</P>
<P>
   A queasy, darkly tender love story, ``Twin Falls Idaho'' (in a
titular reach, the Falls brothers reside in a flophouse on Idaho
Avenue) effectively lulls us into its alternate universe of dreamy
squalor and unsettling varieties of human closeness. Real-life
identical twins Mark and Michael Polish, 27, wrote, directed and
star in the film, which, once our morbid curiosity is satisfied,
becomes a moody meditation on intimacy, separation, risk and
dignity. This intensely odd work, ruffled by humor and heartache,
doesn't so much engage as it casts a spell.
</P>
<P>
   We meet the shy twins on their birthday. They have bought
themselves a chocolate cake and hired a prostitute named Penny
(Michele Hicks, she of the green lollipop eyes), who gets over her
initial revulsion with a vigor that leads to attraction. Francis,
the twin on the left, is not well, and Penny takes this as a cue to
place the courtly brothers in her care. They share pasts paved in
maternal rejection and social alienation. This happy little family
of three find common ground in empathy.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins in a spurt of indie film eccentricity, and
there's the ugly scent of gratuitous exoticism. Yet once the
sour-metal tang of cinema's twin weirdo Davids _ Lynch and
Cronenberg _ dissolves, a seriously affecting story emerges. Before
a backdrop of cruel oglers, vulgar proposals and the comic notion
that Halloween is ``the one night the entire year they're normal,''
Blake and Penny fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   The Polishes handle the relationship discreetly, maturely,
probably because its success hinges on Francis' deterioration. The
young filmmakers, whose long, ashen faces are like dolorous masks,
show a great sense of style and confidence in their debut feature.
They've created a fascinating metaphor for misfits at once
troubling and full of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
