<HEADER>
A8975 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      09-02 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Sept. 2 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867); phone: (888) 346-9867;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ On her first trip to the Middle East since the
Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, came to power, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright hit a snag when the Israelis and
Palestinians failed to deliver an agreement that she hoped to
preside over at a signing ceremony. She met with the Egyptian
president, Hosni Mubarak, who has been urging the Palestinians and
Israelis to agree, and then with the Palestinian leader, Yasser
Arafat. She later left for Tel Aviv. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ NATO and U.N. officials have
been enmeshed in complex negotiations with the Kosovo Liberation
Army's leaders over the last few weeks to persuade the 9,000 troops
to demobilize and have come up with a plan to turn the core of the
force into a civilian emergency service. As details are worked out,
the issue remains extremely delicate, not least because of the
implications for Kosovo Albanians' aspiration for independence and
for Yugoslavia's sovereignty over this province. Though NATO sees
the KLA of the future as a civil defense force, the army's officers
inevitably see it as a potential core of a future national army. By
Carlotta Gall. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-RENO-FREEH (Washington) _ Janet Reno and Louis Freeh were
once portrayed as one of the capital's perfect power pairings _ a
tough, down-to-earth attorney general who was delighted to have the
earnest former prosecutor and judge as the chief law enforcement
officer by her side. But officials who know them both said the
image never really matched the reality. Disclosures that the FBI
failed to produce information from its files about the use of
inflammable tear gas during the 1993 assault on the Branch Davidian
compound has seriously divided Reno, Freeh and their two agencies.
By David Johnston and Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EDUC (Los Angeles) _ Texas Governor George W. Bush says
that if elected president he would use the federal government to
force schools in poor areas to perform and threatens to take away
federal money from those that fail and put in the hands of parents.
By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MARCH (New York) _ New York City will sharply scale back its
police presence at the Harlem youth rally this year compared to
last year, Police Commissioner Howard Safir tells community
leaders. The police will deploy only half the number of officers
that were used during last year's event, and the city will not take
several restrictive measures, like shutting down nearby subway
stations. Decision comes after Harlem leaders called for a muted
police response, and federal judges recommended a limited police
presence. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WINE-ORIGINS (Undated) _ A scandal to shock wine
connoisseurs to the last drop of their being has been uncovered by
the same kind of DNA test as is used in paternity cases. The
Chardonnay grape, considered one of the world's greatest wine
varieties, is a cross between the princely Pinot and a grape deemed
so coarse that it is no longer grown in France, according to an
analysis by American and French scientists. By Nicholas Wade. 900
words.
</P>
</TEXT>
