<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8980 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WORKERS-CONTAMINATED0     09-02 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKERS-CONTAMINATED03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Workers contaminated at Georgia nuclear site face weeks of tests
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Officials at Savannah River Site in South Carolina
near Augusta on Thursday were trying to determine how seven workers
at the nuclear military complex were contaminated with radioactive
plutonium.
</P>
<P>
   The workers received the radiological contamination Wednesday
while performing a routine procedure in which radioactive material
is processed for long-term storage. Even in relatively small doses,
plutonium can cause organ cancers in humans when ingested.
</P>
<P>
   An alarm indicating airborne radioactivity sounded at 10:55 a.m.
during the operation.
</P>
<P>
   The employees were wearing prescribed protective equipment when
the incident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Following the alarm, the building, known as the FB Line facility
where nuclear materials are processed and stabilized, was secured,
said Paul Jones, spokesman for Westinghouse Savannah River Co.,
which manages the massive SRS complex for the Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   There was no external release of radioactivity outside the
facility, and there is no radioactivity hazard to other employees
or the public, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   DOE officials said Thursday they will launch their own
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't known if the radioactive metal entered the workers'
bodies, but tiny particles were found on their clothing and skin.
For the next four to six weeks, the workers must wait for results
of numerous urine and fecal tests that will determine whether they
inhaled or swallowed the metal.
</P>
<P>
   The employees were reassigned Thursday to work in nonradioactive
areas, and the area where the exposure occurred was sealed and
closed until officials determine how the contamination occurred.
</P>
<P>
   SRS officials said that the plant usually has low levels of
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Contaminations are not uncommon during SRS operations. Fran
Williams, Westinghouse's vice president for environment, safety and
health, said about 60 people each year are found to have
contamination on their clothing after performing radioactive work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-POGO03-COX     09-02 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POGO03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OIL COMPANIES ATTEMPT TO SETTLE FRAUD SUIT
 &HT;    560&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rebuffed by an appeals court, multinational oil
companies are lining up to negotiate settlements of a
multibillion-dollar federal lawsuit that accuses them of defrauding
the government.
</P>
<P>
   By conspiring among themselves to create artificially low
``prices'' for the crude oil they pump from publicly owned land and
offshore zones, the companies cheated taxpayers out of hundreds of
millions of dollars, according to a Justice Department lawsuit
pending in federal court in Lufkin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Chevron Corp., one of the defendants in the
suit, said Thursday the company is involved in ``good faith''
negotiations aimed at settling claims reported to be close to $100
million for its share of the alleged conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can confirm that we are engaged on ongoing royalty
settlement discussions with the government,'' spokeswoman Dawn
Soper said Thursday. ``We do feel that the discussions are
progressing in good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to say how much Chevron was offering to pay to
avoid fighting the case in court.
</P>
<P>
   Petroleum trade publications reported that another defendant,
Conoco Inc., was negotiating the government's claim of $28 million
against it.
</P>
<P>
   Occidental Petroleum Corp. agreed this week to pay $7.3 million
to resolve its share of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Michael A. Havard, a Beaumont, Texas, lawyer who originally
filed the lawsuits as a private action, declined to comment on the
settlement discussions by Chevron and Conoco. He said he would move
to drop Occidental from the suit because it had settled.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals refused in July to dismiss
the fraud suit, originally filed in 1996. The suit seeks $5 billion
in damages and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Mobil Corp. agreed to pay nearly $40 million rather
than fight the charges in court.
</P>
<P>
   Major companies such as Exxon Corp., Texaco Inc., Amoco Corp.,
BP America Inc. and Pennzoil Co. also are defendants in the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, originated by private whistle-blowers who were later
joined by the Justice Department, charges that the companies used a
variety of ``schemes'' to create paper trails of false prices for
the oil they took under federal oil leases, then used those prices
to calculate the royalties due the government.
</P>
<P>
   In one such scheme, the suit charges, two companies will agree
to ``sell'' each other equal amounts of oil at the artificially
depressed prices.
</P>
<P>
   In another purported scheme, a company ``sold'' crude oil to its
own subsidiary, refined it and sold the final product at market
prices. Only the sale between the two corporate entities at the
depressed price was used to calculate royalties, the suit charges.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1986 and 1996, the suit charges, the companies came up
with seven different arrangements for misrepresenting the value of
crude oil taken from public lands and offshore oil lease sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department's Minerals Management Service, which is
responsible for overseeing the production of crude oil under
government leases, has proposed new rules that would make it
impossible for oil companies to understate the royalties they owe.
</P>
<P>
   However, amendments attached to the department's appropriations
in the form of ``riders'' by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas,
have blocked implementation of the new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The suit exposing the allegedly fraudulent royalty schemes was
filed under the federal False Claims Act, which gives private
citizens the right to sue in the government's behalf if they know
of evidence the taxpayers are being defrauded.
</P>
<P>
   If the suit recovers damages, the private plaintiffs are
entitled to share them with the government. Defendants may be
forced to pay punitive damages, in addition to the amount of the
alleged fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The law was originally passed during the Civil War to deal with
contractors who were allegedly selling moth-eaten blankets and
weevil-infested flour to the Army.
</P>
<P>
   J. Benjamin Johnson Jr. of Plano, Texas, and John M. Martineck
of Carrollton, Texas, both former oil company executives,
originally filed the suits.
</P>
<P>
   The Project on Government Oversight (POGO), a plaintiff in a
subsequent suit, has charged that evaded royalty payments by 18
major oil companies amount to more than $65 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   By company, the annual evaded payments alleged by POGO are:
</P>
<P>
   Shell, $19,459,159
</P>
<P>
   Exxon, $7,993,222
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, $7,111,509
</P>
<P>
   Texaco, $6,375,000
</P>
<P>
   Marathon, $5,225,380
</P>
<P>
   Mobil, $3,978,051
</P>
<P>
   BP-Amoco, $3,565,187
</P>
<P>
   Conoco, $2,444,738
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, $2,334,420
</P>
<P>
   Amerada Hess, $1,446,901
</P>
<P>
   Pennzoil-Quaker State, $1,416,140
</P>
<P>
   Unocal, $1,358,282
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, $778,351
</P>
<P>
   ARCO, $718,384
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL-FINA, $520,605
</P>
<P>
   Coastal, $470,939
</P>
<P>
   Koch Industries, $342,222
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, $125,731
</P>
<P>
   Total, $65,664,221
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
