<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8987 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-0903-CO     09-02 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MIDEAST PLAYERS AFFIRM NEW WYE, KEEP PROCESS ON TRACK
 &HT;    525&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Egypt _ U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's
arrival in the Middle East suffered a setback Thursday with the
failure of Israeli and Palestinian negotiators to agree on a
reworking of the Wye River peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   She had hoped her trip could focus on larger issues of regional
peace, such as the status of Jerusalem and attempts to restart
talks between Israel and Syria. But, she found herself again mired
in the kind of peace process details she hoped to avoid with new
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night, Albright hustled to broker an agreement.
She met with Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat here in
Alexandria, where he had come in case there would be a peace
agreement to sign. Then, she headed to Jerusalem for after-midnight
talks with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month Albright postponed a visit in order to avoid
getting pulled back into the minutia of Palestinian-Israeli
dealmaking. This time, officials had hoped she could kick off the
trip with a signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day trip to the Middle East is intended to capitalize
on momentum from the May election of Barak, who has promised to
move quickly in reaching a final peace with the Palestinians, the
Syrians and the Lebanese. Arafat and Syrian President Hafez Assad
have indicated they are eager, in return, to settle issues with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday evening, the Israeli and Palestinian flags on hand
for use in an anticipated joint press conference here had been
deposited near a rolled-up carpet in a side hallway of the ornate
Ras It-Teen(CQ) Palace, where the signing was planned. A grand
salon overlooking the Mediterranean Sea had been prepared and hours
earlier workers had been dusting off the desk intended for the
signing.
</P>
<P>
   After the non-signing and a meeting with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, Albright talked about the obstacles and
opportunities facing her trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the road to true peace remains hard and uphill,'' she
said. ``The opportunity now to reach important new agreements has
been a long time in coming, but it is has arrived and we must seize
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian Foreign Minister Amre Moussa said he still hoped a deal
could be reached ``within hours or days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wye River Memorandum, signed last October, was itself a
refinement of the 1993 Oslo peace plan, in which Israel was
supposed to withdraw from lands conquered from the Arabs in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Moussa said an agreement on the Wye implementation is necessary
for a political climate that had been ``very much poisoned'' by the
stalling of the Oslo process.
</P>
<P>
   Albright acknowledged also that progress in the
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations could affect the chances of
starting talks between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Most political analysts believe a breakthrough with the
Palestinians would increase the pressure on Syria's Assad to make
peace with Israel. The theory is that he would be afraid Israelis
might not feel the need to offer as much to Syria once they feel
secure on their border with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is scheduled to visit Damascus Saturday, and her trip
would be boosted with an agreement on the Wye implementation before
then.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the diplomatic protests of U.S. officials, Barak's
predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu placed Wye on hold in January,
saying the Palestinians had not done enough to stop terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Barak campaigned against Netanyahu with promises to get Wye back
on track, but upon taking office he insisted on renegotiating it.
</P>
<P>
   A major issue in dispute concerns the release of Palestinian
prisoners from Israeli jails. Israel refuses to release those who
committed murders, but Palestinians see them as prisoners of a war
that is now ending.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides were reportedly differing just slightly, with
Israel offering to release 370 prisoners and the Palestinians
asking for 400, down from 650 originally.
</P>
<P>
   Also in contention were timetables for further Israeli troop
withdrawals from occupied Arab areas.
</P>
<P>
   Barak wanted to slow down the withdrawals and link them to
discussions of the largest issues still between the two sides.
Those so-called ``permanent status'' issues include whether Israel
will share Jerusalem with the Palestinians, remove enclaves of
Jewish settlers from the West Bank or allow the return of any
Palestinian refugees to their old lands in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
