<HEADER>
A8988 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CARSMART-BMW-TOURBIKE     09-02 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARSMART-BMW-TOURBIKE-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUICK, FAST LUXURY BIKE WITH ONLY ONE DRAWBACK: A $19,000 PRICE
TAG 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JIM McCRAW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last 20 years or so, there were only two choices among
luxury touring bikes: the Harley-Davidson Electra Glide or the
Honda Gold Wing. Both are very good long-distance bikes, and both
are made in America. These are motorcycles that come with AM/FM
radios, CB radios, tape players and cigarette lighters, in addition
to a large, powerful engine, the traditional windshield, saddle
bags, cargo box and plenty of cushy seat room for two. They are,
essentially, two-wheeled cars.
</P>
<P>
   Now BMW has created the K1200LT, the new absolute ruler of the
touring bike class. It is not simply a two-wheeled car, but a
two-wheeled BMW 740iL.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the wind-tunnel-tested bodywork is a
1200-cubic-centimeter inline-four engine, a five-speed overdrive
transmission, shaft drive and BMW's patented Telelever front and
Paralever rear suspension systems, mechanical guts shared by all of
the company's K-series motorcycles. The engine makes 100
horsepower, more than any other in the class, and 85 foot-pounds of
torque. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The $18,900 Custom comes with windshield, fairing, luggage, side
bumpers, antilock brakes, electronic cruise control, electric
reverse, an AM/FM cassette system with four speakers and two remote
controls.
</P>
<P>
   It also has two 12-volt outlets, a digital clock, electrically
heated hand grips, a four-function on-board computer, the first
six-CD changer ever offered on a motorcycle, and the first heated
seat system for motorcycles (front and rear seats heat
individually, with two ranges per seat).
</P>
<P>
   The Comfort Seat adds an extra inch of foam cushion, and the
chrome package adds brightwork to footrests, rub strips, windshield
housing, mirrors and centerstand handle.
</P>
<P>
   The less well equipped Standard sells for $16,900, and the
middle Icon model for $17,900. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first few minutes with the K1200LT Custom simply reinforce
the initial impression: Boy, is this thing big! It is almost 99
inches long, 42 inches wide at the mirrors, with a 64-inch
wheelbase. But once my passenger and I sat down on the plush
saddle, grabbed the substantial handlebar grips, eased up the side
stand and planted our feet on the ground, the Big K felt just
right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although it weighs more than 800 pounds (plus my own 220 and my
riding partner's 120), it moves off smartly, and the engine revs
easily to 7,000 rpm's. With electronic fuel injection and
electronic ignition, it springs to life easily on cold mornings and
is ready to go instantly. The engine is a horizontal in-line four,
rubber-mounted to combat vibration. We found the clutch a bit
clunky, but the engine was smooth, free-revving and powerful, even
with two on board plus luggage.
</P>
<P>
   The big surprise with the K1200LT was its handling ease and
cornering precision. This big bike will lean way, way over and cut
through curves and corners like a much smaller, lighter bike, then
stand up and motor away with no fuss. The suspension just laughs at
potholes and frost heaves. The brakes are large Brembo triple
disks, two front and one rear, with enormous stopping power and the
added benefit of the antilock function for motorcycles pioneered by
BMW, which is very useful for riding on slick surfaces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This bike is nothing if not flexibile. You can adjust the
rider's seat height, the passenger backrest position, the headlamp
height, the clutch and brake levers, and the front and rear
suspension. Even the windshield height is electrically adjustable
through a range of four inches. Add to that the thumb-flick
adjustment of the cruise control, sound system volume and program.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We tried the four-speaker sound system on radio, cassette and CD
changer, and it all worked very well indeed, with good clarity and
power at highway cruising speeds. The large, tank-mounted buttons
for the system offer bass, treble, fade, balance, six-station
memory, seek, scan, tape and disk. There is a lighted digital
display for the Radio Data System, which shows the call letters and
programming of radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   There is enough lockable storage on this bike to accommodate
most couples for a long weekend, although the CD changer steals
room from the right-side saddle bag. BMW offers optional soft
luggage made to fit inside the bags, making it easier to unload at
your destination. The rear box contains a vanity mirror, a lamp and
a compartment for documents; the tank has another storage space
that houses the cassette deck and a flashlight, with room for
sunglasses and toll money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
