<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-YELLOW-SUBMARINE-LADN     09-02 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELLOW-SUBMARINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATLES' `YELLOW SUBMARINE' WAS AN ANIMATED   VOYAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It has become a rite of autumn, as much as falling
leaves, shortened days and post-Labor Day Christmas displays.
</P>
<P>
   New Beatles product will soon be arriving in stores, just in
time to make the Christmas gift-giving season seem truly fab. In
recent years, we've seen the vaults raided for archival albums like
``The Beatles Live at the BBC'' and the ``Anthology'' series, as
well as special packaging efforts that have returned classics like
``The Beatles'' (White Album) to their original form (albeit a tad
smaller).
</P>
<P>
   This year's offerings will be a feast for the eyes as well as
the ears, as MGM has restored the Beatles' psychedelic celebration
of love, love, love, ``Yellow Submarine,'' for video and DVD.
Capitol Records will release a complementary ``songtrack'' album
that, for the first time, includes all 15 songs heard in the film.
And there will be the obligatory array of Beatles merchandise,
ranging from ``Yellow Submarine'' cookie jars and action figures to
a commemorative stamp from the U.S. Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   ```Yellow Submarine' is a living, breathing example of what the
Beatles were saying and believing in the late '60s, namely that
love is all you need,'' says rock journalist Bill Flanagan, who, as
editorial director for cable music channel VH1, has put together a
``Yellow Submarine'' special that will air on Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie touches into that part of the '60s counterculture
that was trying to preserve a youthful innocence,'' Flanagan
continues. ``Much of the counterculture seemed X-rated, but, at the
same time, there was a tremendous nostalgia for childhood. That
probably had a lot to do with the war and the draft and the fact
that when you turned 18, you were in danger of being shipped off to
the jungle and shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yellow Submarine'' was an unlikely artistic and commercial
triumph. The animated film was made in less than a year for a
paltry $1 million. (By way of comparison, Disney these days
typically spends four years and more than $100 million on its
animated movies.)
</P>
<P>
   And the Beatles themselves wanted nothing to do with the movie,
reluctantly contributing only four new songs that were more or less
throwaways. (Albeit Beatles throwaways, i.e. minor classics.)
``It'll do for the film,'' John Lennon would say of a song that
didn't live up to the group's lofty standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want to invest the time to make another movie,''
says Bruce Markoe, the MGM executive who spearheaded the ``Yellow
Submarine'' restoration. ``But they owed United Artists one more
movie, and they figured this was the easiest way to fulfill their
obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after making two movies with Richard Lester _ the
classic ``Hard Day's Night'' in 1964 and its follow-up, ``Help!''
the following year _ the Beatles struggled to find the time and the
inclination to go before the cameras again. At one point, it was
announced they would make a western titled ``A Talent for Loving.''
That was scratched in June 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea, ``Shades of Personality,'' had John Lennon playing
a man with three different personalities other than his own. (Talk
about ``Mind Games.'') Paul McCartney, George Harrison and Ringo
Starr, naturally, would play the multiple manifestations. Michael
Antonioni, coming off his acclaimed ``Blow-Up,'' would direct.
Sadly, the timing was off. The Beatles started their own company,
Apple, and made, gulp, ``Magical Mystery Tour'' instead.
</P>
<P>
   Other concepts: Remaking ``The Three Musketeers'' with Lester
(who later went on to make the movie _ and its two sequels _ with
Richard Chamberlain, Oliver Reed and Michael York) and a gay-themed
film that the group ultimately vetoed. ``It wasn't that we were
anti-gay,'' Paul McCartney said at the time. ``It's just that we,
the Beatles, weren't gay.''
</P>
<P>
   King Features, who was making a Saturday morning Beatles cartoon
series for ABC-TV, approached the Beatles' manager, Brian Epstein,
with the idea of making an animated movie based on a Beatles song.
The band agreed _ as long as they didn't have to provide their own
voices. Actors were hired, not that anyone noticed the difference.
Many reviews of the film erroneously praised the Beatles for their
vocal work.
</P>
<P>
   King Features subcontracted the animation to Britain's TVC
(Television Cartoons). Four writers (including Erich Segal of
``Love Story'' fame) are credited with the screenplay, which finds
the cartoon Beatles sailing the sea of green to help liberate
Pepperland from the gloomy Blue Meanies, an evil bunch of baddies
who suck the color out of people and whack them on the heads with
apples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yellow Submarine'' was the first animated feature made in
Britain in 14 years. Work began in 1967; the film premiered on July
17, 1968, in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the animation is very creative and ground-breaking,
and some of the work is very bad,'' says MGM's Markoe. ``They just
didn't have the time or the money to make everything perfect,
which, I think, is part of the movie's charm. And when you look
back on the kinds of movies that were being made in 1968, `Yellow
Submarine' comes off incredibly fresh and innovative.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. The five films nominated for the best picture Oscar
in 1968 _ ``Oliver!'' ``Funny Girl,'' ``Rachel, Rachel,'' ``Romeo
and Juliet'' and ``The Lion in Winter'' _ reflected the tastes of
an aging Hollywood power establishment increasingly out of touch
with younger audiences. ``Yellow Submarine,'' with its vivid
colors, exhilarating animation and make-believe worlds seemed, by
comparison, a revolutionary work of imagination. The movie made
year-end Top 10 lists in Time, Newsweek and most major newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The newly renovated version of the film (which will play for a
week in a few art house theaters, including the Nuart in Los
Angeles) digitally restores the first 40 minutes of the film,
bringing back faded colors to their full psychedelic intensity.
(``A lot of people think you have to be on drugs to watch the
movie,'' Markoe says. ``Maybe that was true at one time, but times
certainly have changed.'')
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference in the new print, however, is heard, not
seen. The songs have been remastered, giving them bigger, cleaner
mixes that isolate individual instruments in a glorious wrap-around
sound. The film's sound design has been digitally enhanced, and the
sound effects now perfectly match the wild visual landscapes on the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also reinstates an animated sequence featuring the
Beatles' ``Hey Bulldog,'' footage that was cut from the American
version and many British prints. (``Paul McCartney was rumored not
to like it,'' Markoe says.) An unreleased video of the Beatles
recording the song will be shown throughout the month on VH1.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Yellow Submarine'' helped many careers,
including one person who had nothing to do with the movie. American
pop artist Peter Max was frequently credited with the art
direction, and he did little to dispel the myth, often allowing
interviewers to incorrectly identify him as the movie's designer.
He was said to be honored by the mistake. (Talk about a Blue
Meanie.) Czech designer Heinz Edelmann actually did all the work.
</P>
<P>
   Modern animators like ``South Park'' creators Trey Parker and
Matt Stone and John Lasseter of ``Toy Story'' cite ``Yellow
Submarine'' as highly influential, Lasseter going so far as to
introduce it as his favorite movie at a recent film festival in San
Francisco. The surviving Beatles themselves now embrace the movie
and fully approve the newly restored film and its ``songtrack''
companion album.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, with the way the culture and the government are
now, it's all still happening now as it was in `Yellow
Submarine,''' George Harrison told Billboard editor Timothy White
in a recent interview. ``Except the Blue Meanies have got a bigger
stranglehold on the planet right now than they had back in '67.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the timing for the Beatles is _ as it always seems to be
_ perfect. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Yellow Submarine.'' &UR;  &QL; 
The video and DVD:  &LR; In stores Sept. 14. The DVD includes original
theatrical trailer, audio commentary track, storyboard sequences
and interviews. &UR;  &QL; 
The album: &LR;  Newly remastered ``songtrack'' that includes all 15
songs heard in the film. The songs: ``Yellow Submarine,'' ``Nowhere
Man,'' ``Eleanor Rigby,'' ``Love You To,'' ``All Together Now,''
``Lucy in the Sky With Diamonds,'' ``Think for Yourself,'' ``Sgt.
Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band,'' ``With a Little Help From My
Friends,'' ``Baby, You're a Rich Man,'' ``Only a Northern Song,''
``All You Need Is Love,'' ``When I'm Sixty-Four,'' ``Hey Bulldog,''
``It's All Too Much.'' In stores Sept. 14. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-MISSIONARY-ART-     09-02 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-MISSIONARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDERED MISSIONARY'S WIDOW RETURNS TO WORK WITH INDIA'S LEPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARIPADA, India _ All that awful morning, in the eternity of a
few hours, people gathered at the old yellow house to be near her
and to pray. By 7, the crowd had spilled out the front door and
onto the portico and then into the yard under the mango trees.
</P>
<P>
   Something terrible had happened _ but to whom? Gladys Staines
had not heard from her husband, Graham, a respected missionary, or
their two sons, Philip, 10, and Timothy, 6. They were at a
religious retreat in a village four hours away. Had they been the
ones killed by an anti-Christian mob, the ones burned beyond
recognition in a jeep?
</P>
<P>
   By 9:30, it was settled, the hesitantly feared now the
irrevocably tragic. What was there to say at such a moment? Mrs.
Staines, according to those there, shook with grief and, for a
time, moved very slowly as if she was struggling to part her way
through the air.
</P>
<P>
   She seemed to be impaled in the middle of a thought, which
finally, with quavering voice, she shared. ``Whoever did this, we
will forgive them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment _ that example of her living faith _ has been
widely praised in India, a nation often rent with religion-based
violence, most frequently between Hindus and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Judge D.P. Wadhwa, head of an inquiry into the
deaths, which occurred in January, and their link to a wider
outbreak of anti-Christian attacks, commended Mrs. Staines. ``By
her conduct, she has put to shame, if they have any shame, not only
the perpetrators of the crime but all those who directly or
indirectly may have sympathy for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gladys Staines, 48, returned last month from a respite in her
native Australia. She has decided to carry on her husband's work,
running a home for leprosy patients here in Baripada, a dusty,
traffic-clogged city of 25,000 in the eastern state of Orissa. She
will continue to tell people the ``good news'' as she confidently
calls it, that the blood of Jesus, God's son, can cleanse the world
of sin, and that God is fair and just and that divine purpose
exists in all that goes on, even if those purposes are at times
elusive.
</P>
<P>
   She has yet to fathom why God has taken her sons and husband.
Questions leap into her mind _ a tumble of thoughts _ but she tries
to set them aside rather than pursue answers. ``I ask myself, do I
dwell on the type of death they had?'' she said. ``There are so
many gray areas that no one knows: Were they killed first or burned
alive? I don't know. There were just three lots of bones found in
the jeep, though I'm told a bit of flesh was left on my husband.
Regardless of how they died, they aren't here and won't ever be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question goes through my mind: Am I angry? Am I not? I
don't know. I cope by not allowing myself to do much thinking. At
times, I become overcome with sadness. They're not here. I can't
play with my boys. Day by day, I start with the Bible, reading the
prayers. Previously, I could talk to my husband before going to
bed. Now I talk to God, pour out my heart to him and he gives me
the strength and wisdom to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Gladys Staines, both raised on dairy farms near
Brisbane, were never among life's spiritual hobos, off on some long
search for what to believe in. He was brought up in the Baptist
church, she in the Church of the Brethren. They were infused with
God and untroubled by doubt. They wanted to be missionaries and
spread their certitude.
</P>
<P>
   They met in India. Staines was 10 years older. When Gladys, a
nurse, made a trip to Orissa with a church group, he was already
there, not only looking after the leprosy home in Baripada but also
traveling village to village, handing out religious tracts and
showing film strips. He would woo her by mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Baripada area is home to thousands of Santhals, a tribal
people whose animist beliefs traditionally include idols and evil
spirits. The Staineses wanted to tell them about Jesus and his
great gift of redemption and the terrible consequences for those
who do not accept Christ as their personal savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the good news, isn't it, that there is forgiveness for
every sin through the vessel of Jesus Christ,'' Mrs. Staines said.
``He died on the cross for us, and that's why missionaries go all
over the earth, so people will know they have a choice. If you
don't go to heaven, you go to hell, and that is the essence of the
Christian message.''
</P>
<P>
   She is a tall woman, comfortable in saris. Tinted glasses help
her navigate through the sunshine. Of those who murdered her
husband and boys she said: ``I can forgive their deeds, but I
cannot forgive their sins. Only Jesus can forgive their sins. And
they will have to ask.''
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Jan. 22, Staines and his sons were sleeping in
their jeep. He had been identified as someone involved in
conversions, witnesses say. More than 30 men attacked the vehicle
with sticks and clubs. They refused to let even the small,
screaming boys escape. Straw was stuffed through smashed windows
and packed beneath. The fire quickly became an inferno. The mob
stayed to watch their victims die.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several arrests, but the alleged leader of the
group, a notorious Hindu militant named Dara Singh, has yet to be
captured. On Aug. 26, he killed again, the police say, leading a
mob that chopped off a Muslim's arms before setting him on fire.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of the Staineses came amid a spate of attacks
against Christians and it led to a burst of national introspection.
Many in India said the Bharatiya Janata Party _ the Hindu
nationalists who then headed the governing coalition _ were
responsible for creating a climate of religious intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Dara Singh was said to belong to the Bajrang Dal, a group
associated with the BJP.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wadhwa Commission report, publicly issued on Aug. 6,
found that Singh was not acting at the behest of any political
organization. This conclusion has been condemned by many as a
whitewash that ignores contrary evidence. The killings are now an
issue in the current round of elections. Christians make up 2.3
percent of the population. Many of their leaders have urged a vote
against any party with a religious agenda.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Mrs. Staines has resisted the political uses of
her tragedy. She has yet to read the 250-page report. ``Life has to
go on,'' she said. ``The work has to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   The leprosy home is a cluster of modest buildings on forested
land. She moves easily among the patients, many of them socially
ostracized, cast out because of their ugly skin lesions and
deadened limbs and missing toes and fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the patients had doggedly walked from this refuge to the
cemetery, joining the thousands who attended the Staineses'
funeral. Gladys Staines and her 13-year-old daughter, Esther, the
family's two survivors, faced the throng and sang a favorite hymn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he lives, I can face tomorrow,'' the words go.
``Because he lives, all fear is gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
