<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUTO-SALES-ART-NYT &LR;      09-02 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD MAKES IT OFFICIAL, AUGUST WAS THE BEST EVER FOR U.S. AUTO
SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can l purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Ford Motor Co. said Thursday that its sales in August
were even higher than expected, making last month the best August
ever for auto sales in the United States and the best month in the
1990s after adjusting for seasonal variations in demand.
</P>
<P>
   Ford posted an 8.1 percent increase in sales compared with those
in the period a year earlier. Car sales leaped 19.2 percent with
the introduction of new models and the purchase of Volvo's car
business. Sales of light trucks _ sport utility vehicles, pickup
trucks and minivans _ climbed seven-tenths of a percent.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in light-truck sales was particularly surprising
because Ford had sold an extraordinary number of light trucks in
August 1998, when a 54-day strike against General Motors Corp. had
just concluded and had left GM dealerships with few light trucks
left on their lots.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's Auto Info Bank, a market research service in Southfield,
Mich., calculated that the seasonally adjusted annual rate of sales
in August was 17.76 million cars and light trucks. That made August
sales the fourth-highest ever in seasonally adjusted terms, only
trailing September 1986, September 1985 and December 1986. The
expiration in the mid-1980s of tax deductions for certain car loan
expenses produced a brief but unsustainable spike in sales.
</P>
<P>
   August is traditionally a slow month in the auto industry. The
actual number of automobiles sold in August this year was fewer
than in May or June, but the seasonal adjustments for the May and
June sales made those numbers look weaker than last month's sales.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives attribute the brisk sales to rising household
incomes, soaring stock and real estate prices, low unemployment,
extremely strong consumer confidence, fairly flat prices for new
automobiles and the introduction of innovative vehicles like the
Lexus RX-300, which is a cross between a car and a sport utility
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto analysts have expressed concern that rebates and other
incentives may be contributing considerably to the boom in sales.
But that view is beginning to shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm beginning to believe there's something more structural
going on,'' as rising incomes outpace increases in vehicle prices,
making automobiles more affordable, said John Casesa, an auto
analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``I don't get the impression incentives
changed a lot from July to August.''
</P>
<P>
   The Autofacts Group of PricewaterhouseCoopers, which tracks
industry incentives, has not yet compiled August figures; in July,
incentives were 24 percent higher than in the month a year earlier,
but there were unusually few incentives in July 1998 because of the
GM strike. Incentives in July of this year were up only 1.5 percent
from June.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest section of the market in August was sport utility
vehicles, prompting executives to predict that the off-road
automobiles would remain popular. ``Consumer demand for SUV's has
outpaced every other segment every year of this decade, and we
believe this trend will continue,'' said Robert Rewey, Ford's group
vice president for marketing, sales and service.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition in March of Volvo Cars accounted for less than
half of Ford's improvement in car sales. Even without the
acquisition, Ford's car sales rose 12.6 percent compared with those
in the month a year earlier. The introduction of the Lincoln LS and
Jaguar S-Type sports sedans this summer and the earlier
introduction of the completely redesigned Mercury Cougar have
helped Ford, as have lower prices on the Ford Taurus and Mercury
Sable sedans.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler, GM, Toyota, Honda, Volkswagen and several
smaller auto makers all announced robust August sales on Wednesday,
while only Nissan posted slightly lower sales. GM's market share in
August was 29.8 percent, barely falling short of the company's goal
of a minimum of 30 percent but nonetheless a slight improvement
from recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, BMW &UR;  &LR; said that, like Ford, it had enjoyed its best
August ever. BMW's sales jumped 31.5 percent compared with those in
the month a year earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
