<HEADER>
A9002 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-RENO-WACO-HNS &LR;      09-02 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-WACO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL PRESSURE BUILDS AS RENO FENDS OFF GOP CALL FOR
RESIGNATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Partisan rhetoric for and against Attorney General
Janet Reno escalated Thursday on Capitol Hill amid increasing
evidence that FBI agents used incendiary gas canisters when they
raided the Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republican Fred Thompson of Tennessee joined two
Texas lawmakers who earlier suggested that Reno resign. The GOP
legislators called Reno's competence into question, saying she
should have known six years ago that the FBI, an agency within her
Justice Department, might have used flammable devices in the siege.
</P>
<P>
   The Texans, Sen. Phil Gramm and Rep. Pete Sessions of Dallas, on
Tuesday said the attorney general's credibility has been destroyed
in light of her six years of denying that federal lawmen used
pyrotechnic equipment during the raid on Mount Carmel. The FBI last
week contradicted Reno in acknowledging that agents might have used
the devices on a Branch Davidian facility away from the main
compound.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Texas defended Reno's
vow to ``get to the truth'' about whether FBI use of pyrotechnic
equipment contributed to the inferno.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, through a spokesman, said she had no plans to resign. Last
week, conceding her credibility was in question, she called for an
investigation of the siege to be conducted by someone with no ties
to the department.
</P>
<P>
   The White House deflected calls for Reno's resignation Thursday
and endorsed the selection of an independent investigator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has confidence that the attorney general and the
Department of Justice will get to the bottom of this,'' said
Clinton spokesman Jake Siewart. ``She's promised to do that, and
she's promised to do it in a way that is full and as timely as is
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Siewart added that Clinton is ``deeply concerned that the
attorney general appears to have been misled and may have been lied
to'' about what munitions the FBI used.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan flare-up followed the U.S. marshals' seizure
Wednesday, under Reno's order, of a previously undisclosed
videotape from the FBI. The Justice Department said the tape, made
by an aircraft flying over the site, might shed light on whether
FBI agents used flammable gas canisters and if that use helped
start the deadly fire that engulfed the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Reno last week acknowledged that FBI agents might have used some
flammable military gas canisters to penetrate the roof of an
underground bunker away from the main Branch Davidian building. But
she said she continues to believe their use did not contribute to
the inferno.
</P>
<P>
   At least 75 cult members, including leader David Koresh, were
killed by gunfire and the fire that erupted during the raid. An
earlier federal investigation, which Reno endorsed, concluded that
some Branch Davidians shot fellow members and deliberately set the
fires during the siege.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson, an outspoken Reno critic who has assailed the
attorney general's handling of alleged Clinton campaign
irregularities, said the earlier report cannot be believed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This last week at the Justice Department has a familiar ring
to it: proof of information withheld from Congress and the American
people; an inadequate internal investigation and an attorney
general unaware of what is going on in her own department,''
Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm and Sessions were more direct, calling for Reno to step
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general told Congress (in 1993) that she would
take responsibility for the events at Waco,'' Gramm said. ``Now she
says she didn't know what happened, and she wants an investigation.
If the attorney general cannot manage to find and tell the truth
about a matter as important as the Waco incident, she should step
aside and give someone else a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Sessions, echoing Gramm, said Reno ``has not acted properly.''
He added, ``I and other members of Congress ... are concerned about
how the investigation has been handled and why evidence is
apparently being withheld from congressional investigators and the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson Lee, a vocal supporter of Reno, assailed her
Republican colleagues for rushing to condemn the attorney general
before an investigation has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need not, in hysteria, immediately ask for heads to roll,''
Jackson Lee said. ``She (Reno) has the integrity to respond on her
own without members of Congress calling for her resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Also supporting Reno, liberal Democratic Sen. Patrick Leahy of
Vermont accepted the attorney general's pledge that she would ``get
to the truth'' of what munitions FBI agents used in storming the
cult's Mount Carmel compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``She clearly is troubled by the fact that relevant information
was kept from her before, and she is determined not to let that
happen again,'' Leahy said. ``I continue to believe that an
independent investigation is far preferable to the FBI
investigating itself in this case, and I welcome indications that
General Reno agrees.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
