<HEADER>
A9010 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WACO03-COX     09-02 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON BACKS RENO AS PROBE DECISION NEARS
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno got the backing of
President Clinton on Thursday as she prepared to announce an
outside investigation of how information contradicting the FBI's
account of the 1993 Branch Davidian assault remained undisclosed
during six years of public and private probes.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert said the president was
``deeply concerned that the attorney general appears to have been
misled and may have been lied to'' about the use of flammable tear
gas canisters during the assault near Waco, Texas, which ended in
the deaths of sect leader David Koresh and scores of his followers.
</P>
<P>
   Siewert said the president, who has often been at odds with Reno
over independent investigations, including one that led to his own
impeachment, ``has confidence that the attorney general and the
Department of Justice will get to the bottom of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the White House and Congress, which has
conducted extensive investigations of its own into the tragedy,
Reno is reportedly searching for an outside investigator to look
into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   An informal list of about half a dozen names has been circulated
at the Justice Department this week. It includes two former
Republican senators noted for their bipartisanship, Warren Rudman
of New Hampshire and John C. Danforth of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The White House vote of confidence in Reno came hours after U.S.
marshals impounded infrared tapes recorded by the FBI early on
April 19, 1993, the day the federal government's 51-day siege of
the Davidian compound came to a fiery end.
</P>
<P>
   The tape, which the Justice Department released Thursday,
includes an audio track on which an FBI commander can be heard
granting permission to use ``military rounds'' to ``penetrate the
construction project,'' a concrete bunker that was located about 50
yards from Koresh's compound.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``military rounds'' referred to the flammable tear-gas
grenades.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly seven hours after the grenades were fired, the largely
wooden compound erupted in flames. Koresh, his followers and 21
children perished during the inferno. Some of the 79 who died were
the victims of gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has long maintained that the fires in the wooden
compound were started by the Davidians themselves. Byron Sage, a
retired FBI supervisor who was the agency's chief negotiator with
Koresh during the standoff, noted Thursday that the infrared tape
confirms that the incendiary rounds were not directed toward the
wooden structure.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI has also long denied that it used combustible
tear-gas canisters in the assault at the compound.
</P>
<P>
   The tape released Thursday is the second piece of recently
discovered evidence contradicting the FBI's six-year denial. An
internal FBI memo disclosed last week referred to use of the
flammable canisters. The memo had been in the files of the FBI's
general counsel since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The tape was located in the files of the FBI's hostage rescue
team at Quantico, Va., and transferred to the FBI headquarters,
where it was impounded by U.S. marshals working for the Justice
Department on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Siewert said the marshals's actions were appropriate in order to
``protect the integrity of this material'' _ an admission that
underscored the increasing preference to turn over the
investigation to a private citizen rather than leave it to the FBI
and the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``An independent investigation is far preferable to the FBI
investigating itself in this case,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy of
Vermont, the ranking Republican on the Senate Judiciary Committee,
which has oversight responsibility for the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, the chairman of the Judiciary
subcommittee that specifically monitors the FBI, said the spectacle
of federal marshals seizing evidence from the FBI underscored the
``cowboy culture'' of the agency, which is largely independent from
the rest of the executive branch of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
