<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-KING-TOUR-ATLANTA-ART     09-02 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-TOUR-ATLANTA-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITING MARTIN LUTHER KING'S BIRTHPLACE AND HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(gm) 
 By LINDA CONLEY   The Herald-Journal, Spartanburg, S.C.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Rev. G.H. Williams is more than a guide on the
tour of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s home and birthplace. He
knows the facts of the civil rights movement firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a retired minister and spokesman for the National Park
Service, marched across the South with the slain civil rights
leader.
</P>
<P>
   And on a recent visit to Ebenezer Baptist Church, one of the
many sites on the Atlanta tour, Williams shared stories of his time
with King. He captivates tourists with his personal knowledge of
the struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we marched, we put a face cloth and toothbrush in
our pockets because we knew we were going to jail,'' he said,
recalling his arrest in Macon, Ga., while trying to integrate a
Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. King would call all of us ministers together from across
the state to find out about the problems we were having,'' said
Williams, who was a pastor in Macon when King began organizing
demonstrations across the region in the 1950s and '60s. ``Racial
injustices burned him, and he wanted to do something to change
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebenezer Baptist Church, the Martin Luther King Jr. Center for
Nonviolent Social Change, King's birthplace and grave all are
within a short walking distance from each other on Auburn Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   King preached at the church, where his father and grandfather
also served as pastors. For more than 80 years, ministers of the
church were from the same family. Pictures of King's grandfather,
the Rev. A.D. Williams, and his father, Martin Luther King Sr.,
have been added into the stained glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``This church has both fond and sad memories,'' Williams said,
as he greeted visitors to the historic site recently.
</P>
<P>
   The church, completed in 1922, became a national place of
mourning in April 1968 when King's body lay below the altar.
Ebenezer was marked with sadness again in 1974 when King's mother,
Alberta, was murdered while playing the church organ, Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebenezer became the focal point of community life in Atlanta
during the 1950s and '60s. King used the Gothic-style church as a
meeting place to discuss strategies for integration.
</P>
<P>
   STROLLING AUBURN AVENUE
</P>
<P>
   Just a short walking distance away, is King's birthplace at 501
Auburn Ave. The two-story Queen Anne style house was built in 1895.
</P>
<P>
   King's grandfather purchased the house 14 years later. It was
occupied by the Williams-King family for 32 years. The slain civil
rights leader was born in the house on Jan. 15, 1929. A marker with
information about the house's history stands across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling Auburn Avenue gives tourists a sense of the area's
importance and prominence during the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Auburn community was one of the wealthiest African-American
neighborhoods during the early 1900s and became a symbol of
achievement. Some of the structures date back to the 1800s and
efforts are under way to restore many of them.
</P>
<P>
   When King was growing up in the 1930s and '40s, Auburn Avenue
was lined with offices for banks, insurance companies, builders,
jewelers, tailors, doctors and lawyers. The community had its own
library, newspaper and business college.
</P>
<P>
   John Wesley Dobbs, who was a prominent political leader and
grandfather of former mayor Maynard Jackson, nicknamed the area
``Sweet Auburn.''
</P>
<P>
   FOLLOWING IN HIS FOOTSTEPS
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can stop by the National Park Service's visitors center
to plan their own walking tour. Or they can take an organized tour
of King's birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors' center features photographs, exhibits and video
that chronicle King's role in the civil rights movement.
International and national travelers visit the King Center each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Duol Rut, a native of the Sudan who lives in Clarkston, Ga., is
a regular at the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've visited several times, and I wanted my friends to see
it,'' Rut said, standing with a group from Sudan. ``This promotes
the history of a black person, and I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rut said the King Center dispels the negative stereotype images
that the media portrays of African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really touched by this exhibit because I have read a lot
about Martin Luther King Jr.,'' said Jock Paleak of Nashville,
Tenn. ``I've spent an hour and a half walking around, and I think
we need to do more to follow in King's footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   After viewing the visitors' center, tourists can stop by the
King Center's Freedom Hall Complex. The center was established in
1968 by Coretta Scott King and others to continue King's work
toward economic and social equality. Dexter, King's youngest son,
is the chief executive officer of the center.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the center stands King's crypt, surrounded by a water
fountain and a flame. Engraved in the white stone are the words:
``Free at last. Free at last. Thank God Almighty, I'm free at
last.'' The words are the ones he spoke during his ``I Have a
Dream'' speech.
</P>
<P>
   In August, 1963, King made that speech when he and 250,000
protestors marched to the Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C. The
U.S. Postal Service, which selected the speech as one of the top 15
events of the 1960s, is planning to unveil a new King stamp, which
will go on sale in February.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER DISPLAYS LIFE, INFLUENCES
</P>
<P>
   Inside the center, displays honor the accomplishments and lives
of King and his wife, Coretta, Rosa Parks and Mohandas Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
   Parks was a tired seamstress who refused to give up her bus seat
to a white passenger in December 1955 in Montgomery, Ala. Her
refusal became a rallying point for King and others to push for
integration of public accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Parks' life and involvement in the civil rights movement are
profiled through a series of photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi, a the religious and political leader, fought British
discrimination against Indians. King studied Hindu leader's
teachings and considered him a mentor. Gandhi was assassinated in
1948.
</P>
<P>
   The largest room in the center contains memorabilia and
artifacts from Coretta Scott King and her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Display cases contain the jacket and boots worn by King during
some of his protests. Beside the boots is the key to his room at
the Lorraine Motel in Memphis, Tenn., the place where King was
assassinated on April 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   There are several other places along Auburn Avenue, including
Fire Station No. 6, the oldest fire station in Atlanta and the
Sweet Auburn Curb Market, which was shopped by both black and white
residents during segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors could spend three to four hours viewing all the sites
and taking in the exhibits, which are free and open daily.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO:
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service visitor's center is open from 9 a.m.
to 5 p.m. daily. It provides information about exhibits, tours and
the historic sites.
</P>
<P>
   Tours of King's birthplace are provided daily. Guests can sign
up for a guided tour, which is limited to 15 people at a time. The
tours are provided on a first come basis.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the King tour, contact the
superintendent for the Martin Luther King Jr. National Historic
Site, 450 Auburn Ave., NE, Atlanta, Ga. 30312-1525 or call (404)
331-5190 or visit the Web site at www.nps.gov/malu.
</P>
<P>
   (Linda Conley writes for the Herald-Journal in Spartanburg,
S.C.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
