<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-CLASHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE CHANCE SEEN FOR RECONCILIATION IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ On Sunday, a militia leader and a guerrilla
commander, enemies in the long and bloody fight over independence
for this violence-wracked territory, exchanged a warm bear hug in
front of the international news media, promising to lay down their
arms.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, reporters saw Eurico Gutteres, the same
pro-Jakarta militia chief, wielding an automatic rifle in the
streets. And in the days since Monday's relatively trouble-free
vote on independence, his black-shirted militias have shot
opponents, chased observers and United Nations workers, blocked
locals from leaving the territory, and beaten journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have hugging and we have killing, and hugging and killing
don't normally go together,'' said Donald Emmerson, an Indonesia
specialist at the University of Wisconsin who observed Monday's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, two local UN employees were slain in Maliana, a
pro-Jakarta stronghold 80 miles southwest of Dili. On Wednesday,
five locals were believed killed in clashes outside the UN compound
in Dili.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no possibility of protecting either ourselves . . . or
anybody else,'' said Ian Martin, head of the UN mission in Dili.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people, including 25 journalists, were evacuated on a
military transport plane Thursday, following rumors that they would
be the next target.
</P>
<P>
   When the UN announces the results of the referendum in a few
days, the count is expected to overwhelmingly favor independence
over Indonesia's offer of autonomy within the farflung island
nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the chapter cannot close on the 24-year struggle between
those who want self-rule and those who want Indonesian sovereignty
until the sides reconcile and find a way to live together _ a
prospect that for now seems dim.
</P>
<P>
   This week's renewed lawlessness raised questions about the
stability of any future peace for East Timor's 800,000 residents _
a population that already endured civil war, human rights abuses,
starvation, and disease during the early years of Indonesian rule
in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later, pro-independence leaders, including former
guerrillas, look likely to take power through the ballot box, and
they have pledged to grant amnesty for political crimes committed
before the vote. They also welcomed non-Timorese Indonesians to
remain without fear of reprisal or discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   But pro-Jakarta militants show no signs of giving up the fight.
And there is a gaping disconnect between what some leaders say, and
what they do.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a reconciliation committee composed of two dozen
representatives of both sides met for the first time. The same
afternoon, a pro-Indonesia leader announced a boycott of the
committee. Only six members showed up, a showing that does not
augur well for harmony in the new East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers agree that if independence wins, it would not
only be impossible, but unwise, to marginalize pro-autonomy
leaders. But getting those leaders to play ball rather than act as
spoilers is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Emmerson draws a parallel between the beginnings of the
reconciliation process in the last week and what happened in 1975
in Vietnam, when it became apparent that North Vietnam would win
the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the handwriting on the wall became more and more legible,
there were a lot of (South Vietnamese loyalists) who were unable to
leave and who began to lay low, switch sides or try to camouflage
themselves,'' Emmerson said. ``We saw the same thing'' in parts of
East Timor, ``where pro-autonomy people were quietly making
promises'' to independence leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, pro-Indonesia militias have not renounced the fight.
But privately, said James Fox, an Australian specialist on
Indonesia who observed this week's vote, ``the autonomy people have
known for some time that the game was up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who knows leaders on both sides, says moderates have been
talking to one another for months. Apart from a few extremists,
most autonomy leaders are acting tough in the vacuum after the vote
as ``a way of saving face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If reconciliation has to be total, it'll never happen,'' Fox
said. ``But there are already people in the middle who have
privately reconciled.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the question of what Indonesia will do. It can
sabotage independence, try to co-opt the victors, or support them.
</P>
<P>
   There is a struggle in Jakarta's leadership over whether to let
East Timor go graciously or force it to stay. The outcome will go
far to determine how smoothly East Timor can make the likely
transition from Indonesia's 27th province to the world's newest
tiny nation.
</P>
<P>
   For 2 1/2 decades, East Timor has been the place where
Indonesian military officers made their careers, just as a
generation of American officers earned their stripes in Vietnam.
Many Indonesian officers married East Timorese, acquired land and
now control the island's business interests; and they are not eager
to cede their influence. Independence leaders have promised to
honor ``legitimate'' property rights, but there are cases of
ill-gotten wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The army is accused of training, arming, and doing nothing to
stop pro-Jakarta militias in campaigns of terror that cost scores
of lives this year.
</P>
<P>
   A defense ministry memo leaked in July proposed a slash-and-burn
campaign if East Timor chooses independence. At least one senior
Indonesian official has spoken of washing his hands of the
``ungrateful'' province, pulling out infrastructure, and curtailing
Dili's budget if it voted for independence.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the military's intransigence over losing East Timor
appeared to be fading, at least publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia sent hundreds of riot police to Dili, and top generals
said they would invite UN peacekeepers and withdraw Indonesian
forces if East Timor votes for independence _ a radical departure
from Jakarta's previous stand.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about veteran officers who are trying to hang onto East
Timor, Brigadier General Soedrajat told the Jakarta Post that ``all
parties with emotional ties'' to the province should view the
likely transition ``as historical fact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
