<SLUG> BC-PARIS-LASVEGAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRES MAGNIFIQUE! PARIS LAS VEGAS OPENS ON TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Embargoed until Sunday, Sept. 5) &HT;     By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ In Paris, as in all of France, those who insist on a
rigid time schedule are often held in disdain (or dismissed as
American tourists; same thing), whether the issue is the serving of
a second course, the reopening of a shop after lunch or the
summoning of a plumber.
</P>
<P>
   But the new Paris Las Vegas Casino Resort defied the traditions
of both Paris and the Strip this past week when it opened on
schedule _ and actually had everything up and running.
</P>
<P>
   It lit up its scaled-down Eiffel Tower replica and welcomed a
stampede of curiosity-seekers into a property that boasted all
rooms finished, all restaurants and shops open, a casino clanging
and whirring for all it was worth. And there was not a touch-up
construction worker in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was brought in on budget and, more importantly, on time,''
said Arthur M. Goldberg, president and CEO of Park Place
Entertainment Corp., the company that bankrolled the 2,916-room
hotel which lies directly across the Strip from Bellagio. ``More
importantly, we're not going to have three grand openings.''
</P>
<P>
   The term ``opening'' has undergone a dramatic redefinition
during Las Vegas' recent building boom. There was no trouble
launching an Italian lake resort 11 months ago, as Bellagio opened
on schedule, but since then, there has been trouble in both
Polynesia (the Mandalay Bay) and Venice (the Venetian). The
Mandalay Bay didn't have all its restaurants ready when it opened
in March, then had to shut down its wave pool because of a major
design flaw. The Venetian then opened in May ... and in June ...
and in July, as construction delays plagued such signature features
as its gondola canal.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Las Vegas, mindful of the public-relations fallout
suffered by the others, was determined to get it right. And when
the public poured in last Wednesday night, it didn't have to step
around scaffolding and drop cloths or peer into still-dark shops.
</P>
<P>
   What the customers found instead was a fairly impressive
offering _ if you're excited by knockoffs of famous cities built in
the middle of the Mojave Desert.
</P>
<P>
   Although much of the Paris Las Vegas focus has been on its
replicas of the Eiffel Tower, the Arc de Triomphe and such Paris
facades as the Louvre, Paris Opera House and Hotel de Ville, one of
the property's most popular features could prove to be its retail
and dining area. Le Boulevard District is laid out along a winding,
cobblestone alleyway under a perpetually blue, partly cloudy,
movie-set sky. Boutiques along the walk feature an impressive array
of French home furnishings, apparel and confections. The 85,000
squre-foot casino is designed in the motif of Paris street scenes
with cafes along the the edges and a park running through it.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, the route includes a boulangerie, a patisserie and a
fromagerie. In fact, the working bakery will furnish fresh bread to
all eight of the hotel's restaurants _ it's to be delivered by
bicycle twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Las Vegas, whose reported $790 million price tag was about
half the amount spent to build Bellagio ($1.6 billion) and the
Venetian ($1.5 billion), strains mightily to create an atmosphere
that conforms to the decor. Casino security guards are dressed in
gendarme uniforms, right down to the white belts. The cocktail
waitress costumes appear to be a derivation of Air France flight
attendant uniforms _ but only if a 14-year-old boy were permitted
to design them. Maintenance workers wear berets and vests.
</P>
<P>
   Employees of the resort underwent ``French cultural training''
so as to learn various words and phrases in the language. On any
walk across the hotel grounds, you're in danger of being bon joured
right into catatonia.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with Las Vegas' theme obsession, the place is pure
fantasy. No litter. No graffiti. No dog waste. No art. No history.
And all those smiling, cheerful salutations from the help bear no
relationship to what tourists routinely encounter in the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Las Vegas visitors are sure to love it _ at least until
next year, when Aladdin opens up shop next door as the latest Strip
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Las Vegas' most popular attraction is sure to be an
elevator ride to the observation deck at the top of the half-size
Eiffel Tower _ it can be had for $8. Anyone who walks beneath the
two-thirds scale Arc de Triomphe, meanwhile, might be startled to
find that this one, too, lists the names of all the towns that
Napoleon and his armies stomped through in 1805.
</P>
<P>
   But the real marvel of Paris Las Vegas remains the fact that it
did not have to push back its scheduled opening, or, worse, have
one or two ``soft'' openings followed by a supposed grand one.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Park Place Entertainment did in constructing a Paris (Las
Vegas) timeline was to put a cushion in there,'' said hotel
spokesman Andy Maiden, who added that the contractors actually
turned over the property three weeks ago, allowing ample time for
finishing touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided when we opened, we'd open completely.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Paris Las Vegas room rates range from $129 to $239, with
suites (295 of the hotel's 2,916 rooms) priced from $350 to $5,000.
Address: 3655 Las Vegas Blvd. South. Reservations: (888) 266-5687.
Web: www.paris-lv.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
