<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS RESUME THEIR SWOON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices resumed their late-summer swoon Thursday
in another session clouded by nervousness over a hyperactive
economy and whether the Federal Reserve will decide it needs to
raise short-term interest rates again to keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   As they braced for the government's report Friday on the August
job market, traders and investors had to contend with word that the
automotive industry sold cars and trucks last month at the fastest
pace since December 1986 and with a warning by Edward Kelley, a
Federal Reserve policy-maker, that it is ``premature'' to rule out
a third rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The compass continues to point in one direction,'' said
Jeffrey Applegate, chief U.S. strategist at Lehman Brothers.
``People are increasingly worried that the Fed is not on hold.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Dow Jones industrials were down 94.67 points,
to 10843.21, nearly erasing Wednesday's rally and making it five
losing sessions out of six since setting a record at 11326.04 on
Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's 0.87 of 1 percent decline compared with setbacks of
0.6 of 1 percent for the NASDAQ composite and 0.9 of 1 percent for
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, the latter two indexes heavily weighted
with expensive high-tech stocks that are especially sensitive to
rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest rates going up puts a lot of burden on price-earnings
multiples'' and on financial stocks, said Paul McManus, research
director at Independence Investment Associates in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   J. P. Morgan, down 3 11/16 to 125 15/16, and American Express,
down 3 1/8 to 135 7/8, placed first and third, respectively, in
contributing to the skid in the Dow industrials. Sears Roebuck,
which slumped 3 11/16 to 33 1/2 after warning of a profits
shortfall, was the second-biggest drag.
</P>
<P>
   Although 20 of the Dow's 30 stocks fell, these three issues
accounted for 55 percent of the total drop. Analysts attributed a
late rebound in the Dow, which had been down as much as 205 points
at one stage, to traders covering short positions and to the
activation of some buy programs.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, an unusually high total of 2,078
issues declined while 874 advanced, a ragged performance that added
to the general sense of market deterioration. Stocks making new
52-week lows, moreover, outnumbered those making new highs by more
than five to one _ 118_22.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, analysts noted that activity remained on the
light side, with 684.3 million shares changing hands on the Big
Board compared with 697.1 million during Wednesday's rally.
</P>
<P>
   Retailing stocks other than Sears were also hit Thursday,
reflecting fears of higher rates and a slowdown of torrid consumer
spending. Dayton Hudson fell 1 5/8 to 56 5/8, J.C. Penney 1 11/16
to 36 7/16, and Best Buy 10 1/2 to 61 7/16, after personal-computer
promotions failed to lift quarterly sales of the Minnesota-based
company as high as many had hoped. Wal-Mart, one of the few
merchants to buck the trend, rose 11/16 to 45 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Republic New York tumbled 7 3/16 to 62 3/16 after disclosing
governmental investigations of a client, which in turn prompted
HSBC Holdings to say this might delay its takeover of Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were caught in the general downdraft but few
of the losses were big. Rambus, however, slid 4 3/4 to 90 1/2 after
Intel said it would use a a less expensive, competing memory-chip
technology in response to demand by computer makers. Intel gained 1
7/8 to 85 5/16 to make the biggest positive impact on the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P finished 11.96 points lower at 1319.11. The NASDAQ
market was down 16.56 points at 2734.24.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks in major European markets fell by between 1 1/4 and 2 1/2
percent while Japan fell about 1 percent. Brazil's Bovespa,
however, advanced nine-tenths of 1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
