<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIT FINDS FAULT IN NASA COST OVERRUNS ON SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Congress prepared to cut NASA's budget to help
reduce domestic spending, a new audit criticizes cost overruns on
the international space station and the space agency's failure to
develop a long-term plan to control costs.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office audit estimates that the United
States will spend up to $26 billion over the next five years to
develop and assemble the orbiting laboratory and faults NASA for
not having a contingency plan to deal with future problems and cost
increases.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress returns next week, the House is expected to take
up a spending plan that recommends cutting NASA's 2000 budget by
more than $1 billion, including $100 million earmarked for the
space station.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Capitol, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has
proposed putting a cap on the U.S. share of the international space
station. ``Unfortunately, disturbing cost increases and delays show
no sign of slowing down,'' said McCain, chair of the Senate
Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA must stop operating under a blank-check mentality and
promptly provide a plan that shows their commitment to fiscal
accountability,'' said McCain, a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials point out that $200 million the House
Appropriations Committee wants to cut from the space agency budget
was requested to finance development of the long-term contingency
plan wanted by McCain and other congressional critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independent auditors have determined these contingency plans
are critical and we need to have them,'' said Dan Hedin, chief of
staff for NASA's office of space development. ``I don't think there
is any way Congress will not fund that. They understand the need
for contingency planning.''
</P>
<P>
   First proposed as an $8 billion project during the Reagan
administration, the space station went through a major redesign in
the early 1990s when Russia agreed to join the United States,
Canada, Japan and the European Space Agency in the venture and
agreed to build several components and share the costs.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months ago, the GAO forecast the U.S. share of the 16-nation
project would reach $24.7 billion. Fifteen months ago, the estimate
_ which is based on data provided by NASA _ totaled $21.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials blame most of the agency's added costs on
Russia's ongoing economic woes. Not only has the financially
strapped Russian space agency failed to meet deadlines for building
key components, a share of its costs has been paid by the United
States to ensure that the project would not falter entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really the schedule slippage that's causing this
appearance that there's significant program growth,'' Hedin said.
</P>
<P>
   The first segment of the space station, a Russian-built control
module, was launched in November 1998, a year behind schedule. The
second component, built in the United States by Boeing, was added a
month later. In late November, the Russians are to send aloft a
43-foot service module, or living quarters, which originally was
scheduled to be in orbit in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO noted that the service module, which included living
quarters for three, communications, navigation and life-support
equipment, will be launched with a series of problems that will
have to be repaired while in orbit 240 miles above Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the problems noted by GAO was the Russians' failure
meet NASA standards for withstanding small pieces of space debris
that might penetrate the module and cause it to lose pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Hedrin described the debris-protection question as
non-consequential, pointing out that in its 13 years aloft the
recently decommissioned MIR space station was never troubled by
space debris. Also, the international space station will be brought
up to NASA standards 3 1/2 years after it is in orbit, even though
astronauts are to begin living in the laboratory next March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel comfortable with what we're doing. That isn't a safety
issue,'' Hedrin said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
