<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-UGANDA03-COX     09-02 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Uganda seeking investment
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Americans may see Uganda as the land of Idi Amin, the
country that intervened in a complicated multinational war in Congo
and the place where eight gorilla-seeking tourists were slaughtered
in March with machetes.
</P>
<P>
   But Uganda's prime minister, Apolo Nsibambi, came to Atlanta on
Thursday to offer a different view. Uganda is a stable country with
a growing economy, he said _ and a place in which Americans should
consider investing.
</P>
<P>
   Nsibambi spoke at at a trade and investment conference at the
Carter Center called East Africa 2000. The summit was organized by
Kenyans, Tanzanians and Ugandans living and working in the United
States. More than 100 people attended.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, sponsored by Coca-Cola Co., Western Union, Delta
Air Lines and other U.S. companies, was designed to tout the
benefits of an East Africa Cooperation Treaty expected to be signed
soon by Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty will create a common market by eliminating trade
barriers and easing the movement of labor and capital across
national borders.
</P>
<P>
   The economic joining of the three countries will create a market
of 80 million people, Nsibambi said, a market more attractive to
investors than each country considered separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate of return in Africa is 29 percent,'' the prime
minister said in an interview, citing U.N. annual averages compiled
from 1990 onward. ``That is a great opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Uganda, a central African country about the size of Michigan
with a population of 22 million, has endured its share of troubles.
After gaining independence from Great Britain in 1962, it was
governed by two dictators _ first Prime Minister Milton Obote and
then Gen. Idi Amin, who was blamed for the deaths of hundreds of
thousands of his compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   The world's first known cases of AIDS were reported along the
shores of Lake Victoria in Uganda, and the disease has now driven
the life expectancy in the country down to 42.6 years. There are an
estimated 67,000 Ugandan children living with AIDS; more than 1
million children have been orphaned by it.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been progress, too. Amin was driven from power 20
years ago this summer. The rate of inflation, which was over 168
percent in 1986 has been pushed below 10 percent, Nsibambi said.
Since 1987, the economy has grown at 6 percent a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of public servants has been cut from 320,000 to about
half that _ Nsibambi called it ``right-sizing'' the public sector _
and spending on education has been greatly increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uganda is being transformed,'' the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
   Nsibambi offered these explanations of recent events that may
have concerned outsiders:
</P>
<P>
   _ Uganda's intervention in the civil war in Congo, on the side
of rebels trying to oust Congolese President Laurent Kabila, was
done in the name of stabilizing, not destabilizing, the area.
</P>
<P>
   The central government of Congo could not control the territory
or borders, Nsibambi said, leading to ``looters and vultures
thriving in a chaotic situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Uganda needed to prevent that instability from crossing the
border into its own territory. ``You want a stable neighbor,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The slaughter by Rwandan rebels of gorilla-watching tourists
at Bwindi National Park depressed tourism for a time, but visitors
are coming back, he said. New security systems have been put in
place, including instant communications, the training of a ranger
force and the posting of army troops in the area.
</P>
<P>
   _ Uganda has been one of the few countries in Africa to deal
openly with AIDS, and the rate of infection is dropping, Nsibambi
said. Uganda's population has been educated, and ``they're loving
carefully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister also said that a rebel insurgency is not
creating instability in Uganda any more than the Irish Republican
Army is creating instability in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   And he said President Yoweri Museveni, in contrast to Amin, has
supplied ``enlightened leadership'' that relates well to the
international community.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
