<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH OUTLINES PROPOSALS FOR EDUCATION REFORM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Presidential candidate George W. Bush, saying that
federal education programs allow schools to ``cheat poor
children,'' outlined Thursday his proposals for reforming education
that could shift millions of dollars out of low-performing public
schools to private and religious ones.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush said he would leave the day-to-day operations of
schools to local communities, his plan includes a series of federal
requirements on states and local districts. The plan, for example,
calls for all states that want federal money to test their pupils
and report to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a Hispanic business convention, Bush said the
reforms he would adopt if elected president next year would use
competition to improve the programs ``where educational failure has
its highest price,'' those designed to help disadvantaged children
in struggling schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say it is unfair to hold disadvantaged children to
rigorous standards. I say it is discrimination to require anything
less _ the soft bigotry of low expectations,'' Bush said to
applause.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor offered a narrow version of a voucher
program, a reform he has championed unsuccessfully at the state
level.
</P>
<P>
   Poor parents whose children are educated with the help of Title
I federal funding would be allowed to withdraw their children _ and
the approximately $1,500 a year the school gets from Washington per
child _ from schools that are rated low-performing for three years
in a row and use the money to educate them in private schools,
charter schools or at home.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Bush's plan, both Democratic and Republican,
complained that Bush would wait three years to punish failing
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he sits there with his cowboy boots on his desk for three
years and takes no action?'' said Kiki Moore, a spokeswoman for
Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential front-runner.
``He talks about leaving no child behind. We look at the positions
he's taking and see no money left behind for the children.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Kenneth Blackwell, national chairman for Republican
presidential candidate Steve Forbes, asked if Bush was ``kidding''
about the three-year probationary period and noted, ``Governor
Bush's education plan is too weak, too narrow, and it still leaves
big government in control of the education monopoly, not parents.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic Los Angeles businessman Henry Cisneros, the
former San Antonio mayor and Clinton administration housing
secretary, said Bush's ``heart and his head are in the right
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros praised Bush's advocacy of bilingual education and
phonics-based reading education for disadvantaged preschoolers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the Latin Business Association that he chose its
convention to unveil the first part of his education plan because
its members' personal successes shows how anyone with an education
can succeed in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You embody the permanent hope, the durable dream, of this
nation _ to build a better life for ourselves and our children,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the federal government has tried for years to solve
this problem with ``sacks of money and the best of motives'' but
without success. He said 760 different education programs
administered by 39 agencies have few known results ``because no one
measures them.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also noted there was no need for a ``national school
board'' with the president serving as principal. He said local
people know best how to solve their local educational problems.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's plan:
</P>
<P>
   _ Every federal program in teacher training, curriculum,
research and school safety would be required to prove their success
or lose funding.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said this means he supports any bilingual education
programs that works at achieving English literacy, be it English
immersion or traditional bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   In Spanish and to applause from the Hispanic audience, Bush
dismissed ``English only'' programs because they mean ``only me,
without taking into account others.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Providers of the Head Start preschool program would be
required to use phonics to teach reading to more than 840,000 of
its 3- and 4-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Head Start was originally intended as a literacy program,
designed to close the achievement gap between rich and poor. It
evolved into a day-care, health and nutrition program,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his administration would move Head Start from the
Department of Health and Human Services to the Department of
Education and emphasize academics.
</P>
<P>
   Those that do not measure up will have their contracts put up
for competitive bidding ``allowing someone, including churches and
synagogues and community groups, to serve kids better.'' All new
Head Start contracts also will be open to competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reform Title I, the $7.7 billion-year program that helps
schools educate low-income students.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the federal government would require states to test
schools that receive Title 1 money to show progress. Successful
programs will get special grants. Unsuccessful ones will get a
warning and three years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   After three years with no improvement, the school's Title 1
money will be divided among its parents. When matched with other
federal funds received by the state, each parent would have about
$1,500 a year that they can use to educate their children by any
other means, including spending it on private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a school, with ample time to change, continues to fail,
there must be some final point of accountability,'' Bush said. ``In
the best case, these schools will rise to the challenge and regain
the confidence of parents. In the worst case, we will offer
scholarships to America's neediest children.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas State Board of Education member Bob Offutt, one of the
board's most conservative members, said Bush's record on vouchers
does not bode well for his federal proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '94, candidate George W. Bush talked about educational
choice and for the most part, failed to deliver,'' Offutt said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said he would encourage states to adopt programs like
charter schools. Bush noted that five years ago only eight states
had charter schools, while today 35 states offer that option to
parents. Bush said 78 percent of the students in Texas charter
schools are minorities, not Anglos trying to flee the public school
system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said government-required tests was the best way to measure
a school's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Measurement makes some people nervous, but without tests there
is no pressure for progress,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He said 37 percent of the principals in low-performing Texas
schools have been replaced or retired each year after campus scores
were released.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his program is designed to strengthen, not give up on
the public education system.
</P>
<P>
   ``One-sixth of the American population is in public schools. The
content of their education will determine the character of our
country,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
