<HEADER>
A9059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DENNIS03-COX     09-02 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENNIS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dennis washes out holiday profit for N.C. businesses dependent
on tourism
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGS HEAD, N.C. _ Dennis, the storm that wouldn't die, threatens
to claim one more victim: The Labor Day weekend crowd on North
Carolina's Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've kind of thrown in the towel,'' said Pam Gladden, whose
family has run the Blue Heron Motel in Nags Head for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the motel's 30 rooms, about 200 feet from the
Atlantic Ocean, suffered water damage when rain collapsed ceiling
tiles. Sand washed into a breezeway for the first time anyone can
remember.
</P>
<P>
   What will today _ and the weekend _ bring? Gladden says she
doesn't have the faintest idea. The cable TV's been out for days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been listening to the radio in the car,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The motel is booked through mid-October. But the soldout holiday
weekend has been wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a significant hurt,'' Gladden said, ``because it's not
only Labor Day but it's going to end up being a least a good week
now'' before the motel is back in business.
</P>
<P>
   But even as a late afternoon squall buffeted the coast Thursday,
washing out periods of welcomed sunshine, Nags Head Deputy Town
Manager Rhonda Sommer said some businesses would be open today and
into the weekend. Traditionally, Labor Day is the second-busiest
weekend of the year behind the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina tourism officials were trying to get the word out
that Tropical Storm Dennis wasn't affecting the entire coastline.
Though Kitty Hawk and Cape Hatteras remained soggy, places like
Wrightsville Beach and Ocean Isle were typically picturesque.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though Dennis is affecting the northern part of our coast, the
southern part of our coast is having a beautiful day,'' said Chris
Mackey, spokeswoman for the North Carolina tourism department.
</P>
<P>
   Still, tourists worried, and skepticism that the coast was ready
for the Labor Day weekend extended to beach get-aways as far south
as Myrtle Beach, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbie Gentry, a tourist shop cashier in Maggie Valley, N.C.,
eight hours inland, canceled a weekend trip to Cherry Grove near
Myrtle Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really know what was happening,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Myrtle Beach expects about 400,000 people this weekend. That
could generate up to $55 million for the Labor Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's a beautiful day there and probably will be
Friday,'' Lou Fontana, spokesman for the South Carolina tourism
department, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He advised tourists bound for the Grand Strand to check weather
reports and to call their hotel today and through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to put people in jeopardy,'' Fontana said. ``But
we know businesses depend on this weekend to cap off a good season.
You've got to make your best guess. We don't want people to lose
money. If they cancel, they'll lose money unless there's a
mandatory evacuation.''
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, nearly 70 percent of the coastal population
in summer is made up of tourists. Many were evacuated when Tropical
Storm Dennis first skirted the coast as a hurricane Sunday and
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, tourists and travelers spend about $396 million in
Dare County.
</P>
<P>
   They generate nearly $35 million in tax revenue, split almost
evenly between local governments and the state. Overall, travel and
tourism has a $10 billion impact on North Carolina, which had 41
million visitors in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, whose beach-eroding tide surges stretched all the way to
Florida 400 miles to the south, remained within a hundred miles of
the Cape Hatteras coast and was drifting west and southwest.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, all but 500 of the 5,000 permanent residents of
Hatteras Island had power restored.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them stayed behind after officials ordered an evacuation
Sunday, then were stuck when N.C. 12, the island's only north-south
highway, became impassable.
</P>
<P>
   ``For over a mile, you don't see any blacktop,'' said Richard
Moore, state secretary of crime control and public safety. ``There
is some debate whether there is a roadbed there or not. It's beyond
the crisis stage. There are places where there are no dunes at all
and if you try to just throw blacktop down, you're throwing your
money away.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nags Head, prison inmate crews helped clear debris from the
beach and roads, including damaged stairways leading to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors have condemned 70 beach front homes in Nags Head, for
problems ranging from damaged septic systems to shorted electrical
systems and undermined pilings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want people to do is call and verify their
accommodations,'' Sommer, the Nags Head official, said. ``So many
rental homes have been damaged to the point of being
uninhabitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladden, the Nags Head motel operator, said it's not so bad when
she considers what could have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the last 30 years, the Lord has been very good to us,''
she said. ``This could have been a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
