<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-WINE-ORIGINS-ART-     09-02 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WINE-ORIGINS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA TEST DISCOVERS LOWLY ORIGINS OF THE GRAND CHARDONNAY GRAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., France)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A scandal to shock wine connoisseurs to the last drop of their
being has been uncovered by the same kind of DNA test that is used
in paternity cases. An analysis by American and French scientists
has found that the chardonnay grape, considered one of the world's
greatest wine varieties, is a cross between the princely pinot and
a grape deemed so coarse that it is no longer grown in France.
</P>
<P>
   The outcast parent is called gouais blanc, its name derived from
the word ``gou,'' an old French term of derision. Thus, chardonnay,
long thought by some experts to be a light-skinned version of pinot
noir, now turns out to be a cross between pinot and plonk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fascinating and surprising, particularly that one of
the parents is such an undistinguished grape variety,'' said Jancis
Robinson, a wine critic and editor of The Oxford Companion to Wine.
``It unsettles all our preconceptions about vine breeding. We would
normally assume you need two good-quality parents for a
good-quality progeny.''
</P>
<P>
   The previously unsuspected pinot-gouais liaison is also the
progenitor of 15 other varieties of grape that together account for
almost all the wine varieties grown in northeastern France. These
include gamay, from which all Beaujolais wines are made; melon, the
source of all muscadet, and another important Burgundy grape called
aligote.
</P>
<P>
   Though they have the same parents, the 16 grape varieties differ
from one another just like the children of a single family. Their
colors range across a spectrum from white-yellow and pink to amber
and blue-black.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis, reported in Friday's issue of Science, was
conducted by a team led by Dr. Carole Meredith, a biologist in the
Department of Viticulture and Enology at the University of
California at Davis.
</P>
<P>
   She started to explore the ancestry of the grape varieties in
the university's collection but, because many were derived from
French stocks, her inquiries soon led her to the French National
Institute of Agricultural Research at Domaine de Vassal, near
Montpellier, where many thousands of different grape varieties are
preserved.
</P>
<P>
   As she could not test them all, she selected some 300 varieties
that from their appearance and historical records seemed likely to
be related. Applying the same kind of DNA test used to identify
individuals in forensic cases, she and her colleagues uncovered the
long secret evidence of the pinot-gouais liaison.
</P>
<P>
   Even though most of the pinot-gouais' offspring are probably the
result of ancient crossings centuries ago, their ancestry can be
inferred from modern stock because grape varieties are propagated
vegetatively, meaning that each generation is genetically identical
with its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Pinot is no surprise as an ancestor; it is the oldest attested
variety in Burgundy and was referred to in the first century A.D.
by Columella, a Roman agricultural writer. Gouais, on the other
hand, was considered so mediocre that several districts tried to
ban it. Though not now cultivated in France, the grape was
preserved in the gene bank collection at Domaine de Vassal.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Meredith said that a colleague, Dr. John Bowers, succeeded
after a long search in finding a wine made from the gouais grape.
Called gwaess, the German form of gouais, it came from the Valais
region of Switzerland, where many unusual varieties are grown. ``It
tasted just like a decent white wine,'' Dr. Meredith said. ``There
doesn't seem to have been anything wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   How then did gouais get its bad reputation? Dr. Meredith noted
that it was very widely grown in the Middle Ages before being
replaced by what people considered the noble pinot. Popularity
``has always been suspect in France because of a belief that high
productivity and high quality were incompatible,'' Dr. Meredith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Condemned by elitism, gouais has evidently had the last laugh on
wine snobs by surviving as the unacknowledged parent of many
expensive wines.
</P>
<P>
   Many chardonnays used to be labeled pinot-chardonnay, but over
the last decade French lawmakers have discouraged the use of pinot,
largely because a leading expert declared on the basis of botanical
observation that there was no relationship between the two grapes.
``Just when they have got all mention of pinot off the labels, it
transpires you probably can call it pinot-chardonnay,'' Ms.
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Meredith earlier used the same method to identify cabernet
sauvignon, perhaps the most esteemed red wine grape, as being a
cross between two other varieties, cabernet franc and sauvignon
blanc. According to an article in Science by Michael Hagmann, the
application of DNA fingerprinting to vines was developed by Dr.
Mark Thomas, a grape geneticist in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Varieties derived by crosses are legally forbidden in France to
bear the prestigious label ``Appellation d'Origine Controllee.''
Alain Bouquet, a grape breeder at the French National Institute of
Agronomic Research in Montpelier, told Science that the appellation
system was based on the assumption that varieties obtained by
crossing were inferior to the traditional varieties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is erroneous in the case of crosses between old
European varieties as it is now proven that the two best varieties
in the world, cabernet sauvignon and chardonnay, are derived from
such crosses,'' Bouquet said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
