<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BARTON-DISAPPEARANCE0     09-02 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARTON-DISAPPEARANCE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investigation of Barton escape gaining support
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At least two Atlanta City Council members from
opposing camps said Thursday they would ask Police Chief Beverly
Harvard to start an inquiry into how Mark O. Barton slipped away
from more than 100 police officers after he killed nine people and
wounded 13 others in the Buckhead financial district July 29.
</P>
<P>
   While they have not read a 208-page police investigative file
that details the massacre, City Council members C.T. Martin and
Michael Julian Bond _ both members of the Public Safety and Legal
Administration Committee _ said they would ask Harvard about the
possibility of initiating the review. The review would amount to a
self-examination of how Barton eluded police after shooting his
victims at All-Tech Securities and Momentum Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point they're going to have to critique themselves,''
said Bond, a supporter of Mayor Bill Campbell. ``Doing this would
be the prudent thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, chairman of the Public Safety Committee and a Campbell
critic, said he would read the 2-inch-thick investigative file
released by police officials earlier this week, then arrange a
meeting with Harvard and Deputy Chief C.B. Jackson to discuss an
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect that you would want to go over something like
this to see how you could do better,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, Jackson told reporters that a review of how
Barton could pass undetected from the area where dozens of police
officers descended minutes after the massacre had not been done and
probably would not be.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said Wednesday that police commanders met the day after
the killings to assess their officers' actions at the crime scene.
The chief conceded that the meetings were limited to discussions
about whether radios and other equipment functioned properly,
response times by officers and how the department worked with other
police agencies called to the scene for backup.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, however, Lt. Calvin Moss, the chief's
administrative assistant, said, ``No determination has been made on
a specific review regarding Barton's means of escape.''
</P>
<P>
   The review also should be done ``if nothing else, to find out
what can be done in the future if such a tragedy should ever happen
again,'' said Council President Robb Pitts.
</P>
<P>
   Jabari Simama, Campbell's communications director, said the
mayor would not second-guess the Police Department's actions.
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Herder, who was shot in the back at All-Tech, had
plenty to say about the lack of a review on Barton's elusiveness:
``There was a lot of confusion that day and this is probably the
most complex crime scene this Police Department has ever handled.
You would think they would have done a review on how Barton got
away. It's something you would expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Julie B. Hairston contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
