<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WRESTLING-DEATH03-COX     09-02 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-DEATH03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrestling video may have influenced boy to fatally beat toddler,
officials say
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A 4-year-old Warner Robins boy blamed for kicking and
beating a toddler to death could have been imitating a videotape of
professional wrestling, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspect the child was acting out from watching a wrestling
video,'' said Capt. Jerry Stewart of the Houston County sheriff's
office. The video was of the World Wrestling Federation's ``Summer
Slam'' event, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-month-old Ramone Francois King, who died Sunday of a
fractured skull, also suffered liver damage and other injuries in
the attack Saturday, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old, along with King and five other youngsters, were
watching the video with their baby sitter, Earl Rose, 24, shortly
before the incident occurred, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby sitter was keeping children for three mothers who
were working,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rose later told police he put King to sleep in another room,
then left the older children watching the video while he went to a
neighborhood store for 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, the 4-year-old went into the room where the
baby was sleeping and began hitting and kicking him,'' Stewart
said. ``Three of the other children went into the bedroom when they
heard the baby crying and told (the 4-year-old) to stop, which he
did. Then the other children left and we think the beating
continued.''
</P>
<P>
   King was struck with a hard plastic toy and kicked off the bed,
Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was beat up pretty good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No charges were filed against the 4-year-old, but Stewart said
he has spoken to the juvenile judge and asked the Department of
Family and Children's Services to intervene ``at least to the point
that the child is evaluated.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the baby sitter could be charged with neglect for
leaving the children.
</P>
<P>
   Two Atlanta psychologists said violent videos can provoke
children to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between fantasy and reality is not that clear
at age 4,'' said Steve Garber of the Behavioral Institute of
Atlanta. ``Children this age still believe in Santa Claus and the
Easter bunny.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Blusiewicz said some wrestling programs are powerful
enough to even influence teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wrestlers are portrayed as heroes if they're successful in
knocking someone out,'' Blusiewicz said. ``It's really a
glorification of violent behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   She said such programs are misleading to youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't get that this is entertainment,'' she said. ``Until
puberty, and that can be age 14 or 15, children take things very
literally. They don't recognize window dressing or media hype.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, a 7-year-old Texas boy accidentally killed his
3-year-old brother after watching wrestling on television. The
older boy, asked to demonstrate what he'd done, backed up about 10
feet and ran toward a police detective who was holding a
toddler-sized doll. The boy forcefully stiff-armed the doll in the
neck, knocking it backwards. The 3-year-old died of brain injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
