<SLUG> BC-NCR03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCR buys world's largest ATM servicer
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ NCR Corp., the world's largest manufacturer of
automatic teller machines, bought Beavercreek-based Gasper Corp.,
which writes computer software to service ATMs, company officials
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal, which closed Wednesday, were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Gasper will be a wholly-owned subsidiary of NCR, allowing the
80-employee company to do work for ATMs manufactured by NCR,
Canton-based Diebold and other companies. The Gasper name and
management will remain.
</P>
<P>
   Gasper writes computer software that manages ATM service. The
software notifies ATM owners when machines need more money or
repairs and in some cases the software can remotely correct
malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   Networks that control about 20 percent of the ATMs worldwide and
half of the ATMs in the United States are managed by Gasper
software, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Founder David Gasper said Gasper Corp. and NCR are a good fit.
The deal instantly gives Gasper a presence in 125 countries, up
from the 31 nations where it now operates. NCR will be able to sell
Gasper's products and services around the globe, Gasper said.
</P>
<P>
   Gasper said he expects the company's staff and revenues to grow
under NCR. Last year's revenues were more than $6 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gasper founded the company in 1983 at age 27, a few years after
leaving NCR, where he worked for a short while as a software
developer for ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bray, NCR's vice president for worldwide service and
infrastructure, said the deal brings together the leaders of ATM
manufacturing and ATM service. ``We could see the synergy right
away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gasper said, ``I'll remain as president of Gasper. I expect to
continue to set the direction and make sure it's compatible with
NCR.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
