<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9086 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FLEET-APPROVAL-BOS &LR;      09-02 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-APPROVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET-BANKBOSTON DEAL GETS LEGAL OK FROM US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Department of Justice Thursday gave its approval
to the biggest bank divestiture in US history, requiring that Fleet
Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp. sell customer deposits
totaling $13.2 billion as a condition of merging.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials confirmed Sovereign Bancorp Inc. of Philadelphia
would buy the vast majority of Fleet's business on the sale block
under the Justice Department's agreement, which is a crucial step
toward completing the biggest banking merger New England has ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Sovereign would enter the New England
market armed with $12.4 billion in deposits from 278 branches in
Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island, and New Hampshire, as
well as hundreds of loan accounts and a network of more than 500
automated teller machines.
</P>
<P>
   The approval concludes a difficult phase of negotiations
involving the merger partners, bidders for Fleet's assets, and
regulators. Before the deal is closed, Fleet must also win approval
from Massachusetts officials and the Federal Reserve Board. The Fed
has scheduled consideration of Fleet's request for approval to
merge at a meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department became involved in the merger of Fleet
and BankBoston, New England's largest banking companies, to ensure
that competition in New England banking would be preserved through
the sale of some business to a large, out-of-region bank.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Justice's approval, some analysts questioned whether a
$24 billion Sovereign would be strong enough to battle a combined
Fleet-BankBoston, a behemoth institution with $165 billion in
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant US attorney general Joel Klein said, ``These
divestitures should ensure that customers continue to get the
benefits of competition _ competitive loan rates and the best
banking services.''
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, _
echoing views expressed by other public officials in recent months
_ said he would've ``preferred'' the single big chunk of assets be
sold to a bank in Massachusetts, which would immediately be in ``a
position to compete.'' Meehan added he was ``satisfied'' that the
government had ``reviewed the competitive implications'' of selling
Fleet's business to Sovereign.
</P>
<P>
   But Meehan and other members of a Washington delegation that
lobbied to ensure small banks would be allowed to bid on Fleet
branches got what they wanted: The Justice Department said 28
branches would be sold to small banks in Massachusetts, 15 of them
on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Once the sale to Sovereign is signed, Fleet plans to finish
negotiating the sale of additional branches _ which hold about $810
million in deposits _ to numerous community banks, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice confirmed we don't need to sacrifice the future of
community banks in Massachusetts to ensure that Fleet has enough
competition in the region,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department agreement has numerous conditions aimed
at ensuring Fleet has competitors, said Connie Robinson, director
of merger enforcement for the department.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet would sell nearly all of its 500-plus ATMs to Sovereign,
but the merged entity would retain all of the BankBoston ATMs.
Sovereign, by taking over the ATMs, would gain a key component of
Fleet's retail banking business, officials said. One source said
even ATMs at One Federal Street, the current location of Fleet's
headquarters in Boston, would go to Sovereign. (Fleet would keep a
handful of its own ATMs, including one at the FleetCenter.)
</P>
<P>
   On the loan side of the business, officials said the branches
targeted for sale ensured that Sovereign would acquire a huge part
of Fleet's portfolio of small and mid-sized loans, mainly loans in
the $1 million to $10 million range. In a novel twist, Justice also
said Sovereign would be permitted to hire the loan officers who
handle those accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That middle market was kept intact,'' said Massachusetts
Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly, who confirmed Sovereign was the
winning bidder for the bulk of Fleet's business.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said Sovereign still would not have the critical
mass of some local competitors. In Massachusetts, for example,
Sovereign would pick up $2.3 billion in commercial loans _ only
slightly more than half of Citizens' commercial loan portfolio in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who oversaw negotiations with Fleet, declined to
discuss Sovereign specifically. ``We know who the buyer is, and we
concluded the buyer could compete in this market,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``Size isn't always a determinant of how competitive
a bank is. What's important is that someone has the assets and the
wherewithal and the desire to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Justice said Fleet would sell branches in
four states: 204 branches and $8.6 billion in deposits in
Massachusetts; 50 branches and $2.3 billion in Rhode Island; 39
branches and $1.8 billion in Connecticut; and 15 branches and $544
million in New Hampshire. Branches being sold in Massachusetts are
mainly Fleet's, while the Connecticut and Rhode Island branch sales
are mainly sales of BankBoston branches.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign would faces numerous hurdles when it enters a new
market where must compete against Fleet, Citizens and other local
banks, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign has demonstrated its resourcefulness in competing in
Philadelphia in the wake of a merger between First Union Corp. and
CoreStates. In that deal, too, Sovereign purchased a big chunk of
the divested assets.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Sovereign's executives unfamiliar with New
England's market won't be able to jump in as a strong competitor
right away. And neither Sovereign, Citizens, nor any other bank
would be able to compete in advertising or ATM access against the
financial might of a sprawling Fleet-BankBoston empire.
</P>
<P>
   But banking analysts said the national banking market is
changing rapidly, and the Fleet-BankBoston deal is one of numerous
mergers among banking giants.
</P>
<P>
   These big commercial banks now must compete against firms such
as Merrill Lynch and GE Capital. Smaller banks _ from Sovereign to
Cape Cod Bank &AMP; Trust _ will be left to serve small businesses and
retail customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole purpose of'' of merging with BankBoston ``from
Fleet's perspective, is to eliminate another major competitor,''
said Larry Cohn, a bank analyst for Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. in Livingston,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``Sovereign has been a good competitor in
Philadelphia, and I'd think they would be effective in Boston as
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
