<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS ON THE BUS GO ROUND AND ROUND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Riding westward on Muni on Wednesday evening, Personals
overheard a driver talking to an acquaintance sitting behind him,
who was reading the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signed up to work on New Year's Eve,'' he said. ``Mmm,'' she
said, or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But maybe I'll call in sick,'' he said. A few more stops
passed, they chatted a bit more, she turned a few pages of the
paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what does it say there about the mayoral debate?'' he
asked. ``What did they talk about?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the usual problems,'' she said, ``Muni ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you can't fix anything overnight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Three neighbors told  &UR; Scott Shafer &LR;  of KQED's ``California
Report,'' who was leaving the event, that city cleaning crews had
come by three times that day to spiff up the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARENTS DEAREST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If your ex-spouse isn't around for the children you had
together, the DeadBeat Collection offers a 12-page catalog of 95
greeting cards. Some of these cards, designed to send to parents
who are neglecting their children financially or emotionally, are
cajoling, funny and almost friendly; most of them, however, range
from angry to nasty to insulting.
</P>
<P>
   The line includes specialized greetings for holidays (``It's New
Years Eve! I just wanted you to know. ... You're now another year
behind on your child support''), occasions (``If this birthday card
costs $2.95 and a stamp is 33 cents ... then that is still more
than you have ever spent on your children'') and general messages
of disdain (``Great sex can be exciting as lightning and thunder!
... Unfortunately, I have better odds of being struck by
lightning'').
</P>
<P>
   The purveyors of the line, which is at
www.deadbeatcollection.com, say that 5 cents a card will be donated
to children's charities.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The online greeting card company Sparks.com is donating $1
from every sale for the next two weeks to the Susan G. Komen Breast
Cancer Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; George Hamilton &LR; 's representative has confirmed that the
actor and  &UR; Danielle Steel &LR;  are dating, reports next week's People
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   - Perusing the quarterly report for Legg Mason's Value Trust
Mutual Fund,  &UR; Joey de Vivre &LR;  was struck by the company's investment
strategy, which he calls ``alphabetical diversification.'' ``We
sold Compaz and Conseco,'' says the report, ``reducing by 50
percent the number of companies beginning with `C' in the fund. We
still own Chase and Citigroup.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Suzy Chiazzari &LR; , author of ``Nutritional Healing With Color''
(Element Books; $16.95), told Weight Watchers magazine that wearing
a red T-shirt to a  &LR; the gym could accelerate your heart rate; also,
she said, eating a red apple gives your body a different kind of
energy than a green apple.
</P>
<P>
   - Academics:  &UR; David Eisenhower &LR; , who is married to  &UR; Richard &LR; 
 &UR; Nixon &LR; 's daughter  &UR; Julie &LR; , is teaching a ``Watergate _ Behind the
Scenes'' class at the University of Pennsylvania, reports the
Chicago Tribune. And  &UR; Chris Rock &LR; 's humor magazine is at Howard,
not Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; READERS ARE SUFFERING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you're prone to reading in bed, beware of contracting
 &UR; Stephen King &LR; 's wrist, a condition described by San Francisco
physician  &UR; Rudolf Noble &LR;  in the Western Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor describes a patient complaining of pain in her wrist;
a physical exam reveals some weakness in the hand's grasp. ``Upon
further questioning, it was learned that the patient had for the
previous three nights been engrossed in the latest Stephen King
thriller, a 702-page paperback novel.'' The woman had been holding
the book tightly in her left hand, &LR;  and reading, in bed, for two to
three hours before sleeping. The doctor suggested that she stop
reading for a few days and alternate book-holding hands after that.
</P>
<P>
   King gave permission to name the disorder after him but
suggested, writes Noble, that `` `it could just as easily be called
 &UR; James Michener &LR;  wrist.'''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Shape magazine reports on the Brains and Brawn Workout at
the Meridian Sports Club in Los Angeles, where participants work
out on treadmills while discussing the latest book they've read,
listening to guest speakers (who are working out) or talking about
current events.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Jennifer Aniston &LR;  likes nothing more than taking a lunch
meeting in a sarong.''
</P>
<P>
   - Vogue magazine.
