<HEADER>
A9091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MINDSPRING03-COX     09-02 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring TV ads focus aim to reel in newcomers
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises rolls out phase one of its
first-ever TV ad campaign on Monday in 12 markets.
</P>
<P>
   The comic, low-key ads each end with the company's new tagline:
``You'd be happier using MindSpring.''
</P>
<P>
   The spots will run during network programming on over-the-air
broadcast networks, including ABC, NBC, and Fox. Viewers can look
for the spots during Atlanta Braves, Hawks and Falcons games, ABC's
``20/20'' and ``The Drew Carey Show'' and NBC's ``Just Shoot Me''
and a variety of other NBC sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that our users and people who are likely to become
our users are not heavy TV viewers,'' said Lance Weatherby,
MindSpring executive vice president of marketing. ``They are TV
viewers who tend to watch appointment TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Weatherby also says this is not a national ad buy, but rather
local spots during network shows. Weatherby says the local buys are
to make sure MindSpring is only advertising in markets where it can
provide its Internet access service.
</P>
<P>
   The two spots viewers will see next week, and the seven others
the company plans to roll out by the end of the year, are all
directed by Mark Pellington, best known as the video director for
Pearl Jam's ``Jeremy'' video.
</P>
<P>
   They all feature a twenty-something guy (stand-up comic Andrew
Donnelly) in a park with his dog, chatting with fellow
bench-sitters and passers-by about the many virtues of MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you,'' Donnelly's character tells a skeptical stranger
in one spot. ``MindSpring says that to me all the time. Well, not
in so many words but that's what they're feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Another spot debuting later this year pokes fun at the company's
modest West Peachtree headquarters. ``I bet if you looked up
reliability in a dictionary you'd find a picture of MindSpring,''
Donnelly says. ``Well, maybe not. Their offices aren't that much to
look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Each ad touts a different aspect of the company, from technical
support to high-speed capability.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring has built its reputation on customer service and
support and Weatherby says the understated and funny approach is
designed to communicate the idea that MindSpring is dedicated to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jumping into TV gives us the opportunity to present a unified
message that we didn't have before,'' he says. ``It's hard to set
the tone for your company or your brand with just print and
billboards. TV is a much better way to brand the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Weatherby estimates the total cost of the TV campaign is $1.2
million. Analysts place the total cost of MindSpring's fall
advertising blitz, which includes TV, radio, print and direct mail,
at about $90 million between the fourth quarter of 1999 and the
first quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherby won't say how much the campaign will cost, but he said
that MindSpring is comfortable with the analysts' estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The spots haven't been tested in focus groups or elsewhere prior
to their initial airing on Monday. MindSpring executives and staff
are anxiously awaiting viewer response. Weatherby hopes it will
generate new subscribers as part of the company's effort to reach
the 2 million subscriber mark by the middle of next year. The
company's goal is to be the second-largest ISP, trailing only
overwhelming leader America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very consumer-friendly promise,'' says Alex Kaminsky,
MindSpring's senior director of marketing communications. ``We
promise to make your Internet service as good as it can be. It's
not really a campaign in the truest sense, but really trying to let
people know we respect you and will treat you right.'' However, a
series of ads, no matter how quirky or funny they might be, are
designed to generate orders. If MindSpring can't accommodate the
new subscribers, the campaign will not only be a failure but an
embarrassment. Weatherby knows this all too well. He says that the
process of setting up service and support for the hoped-for
MindSpring newcomers was months in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``This quiet voice is making an enormous promise,'' Kaminsky
admits. ``If we tell people we deliver, we have to deliver. We are
putting ourselves on the line in a very big way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
