<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYSE-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: A DELAY FOR THE BIG BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bowing to regulatory concerns, the New York Stock
Exchange on Thursday delayed plans to convert to public ownership
until next year, and its chairman said it would consider making its
self-policing unit a separate entity.
</P>
<P>
   Backing away from his own aggressive prediction that the
conversion would occur by Thanksgiving, chairman Richard Grasso
said that ``very significant public policy'' questions remain.
Concerns about the structure of the regulatory unit and tax issues
led the exchange's board to vote to delay the possible initial
public offering, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if those issues are resolved, he said he expects the board
to vote sometime next year to transform the NYSE into a publicly
traded company, ending more than 200 years as a member-owned
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   A public offering could raise considerable funding for the
exchange and give it a currency useful for acquisitions as it faces
increasing challenges from electronic trading networks, data
companies and other competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion must be ``formulated through the lens of doing
what is right for the public user,'' Grasso said at a press
conference after the board's meeting. ``How do we engender the same
level of public confidence and support that we have enjoyed?'' The
exchange's success, he added, ``will be largely destined by the
public's confidence in the self-regulating process.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory unit can fine and discipline members, as well as
arbitrate disputes. But with public ownership, the exchange could
be placed in the awkward position of having its own regulators
attempting to discipline a major shareholder, or having Wall Street
firms influencing the regulatory unit's budget. That would create a
conflict between the exchange's fiduciary duty to stockholders and
its job regulating dealers and protecting investors.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, Arthur
Levitt, has told NYSE officials and those at the NASDAQ market,
which is also mulling a public offering, that he is concerned that
a public company may not give the self-policing units enough
independence, unless those units are separated from the exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Grasso said any option that would satisfy Levitt will
be considered, including a regulatory subsidiary ``with a public
board, with accountability to both the board of the NYSE and to the
public user, in terms of transparency of the financing of that
entity.'' Such a structure would be similar to that of the
regulatory board of the National Association of Securities Dealers.
</P>
<P>
   But Grasso said a spinoff of the regulatory unit is another
possibility. That could be done by itself, or it could lead to a
merger of the unit with its NASD counterpart, a proposal that has
been offered by NASDAQ officials.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt said in a statement Thursday, ``We share a common
interest in ensuring that any future self-regulatory structure is
consistent with the protection of investors and the maintenance of
fair and orderly markets.'' SEC staffers have said they do not
expect the regulatory matter to be a ``major impediment'' to a
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Optimally, they should have a completely independent
regulatory unit, in terms of comforting the SEC and comforting
investors,'' said Alan Bromberg, a securities-law professor at
Southern Methodist University in Dallas. Such a separation ``may
not be absolutely necessary'' if the unit were given ``an
incredible degree of independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, he said, ``I think they're going to have an uphill
battle to convince people that the policemen are really there, if
the policemen are working for the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Banking Committee expects to hold a hearing later
this month on the exchanges' plans to convert to public ownership.
</P>
<P>
   As contemplated, the initial public offering would give each of
the exchange's 1,366 seatholders a trading license and shares of
stock. Grasso said it has not been discussed whether the initial
public offering would raise money or simply allow members to sell
stock. Either way, having publicly traded stock would give the
exchange a currency it could use for acquisitions as it faces
increasing challenges from electronic trading networks, data
companies and other competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso said it would be a few months before the exchange hears
from the IRS, which will decide whether the exchange of stock for
seats would be tax-free for the seatholders.
</P>
<P>
   But fears that an adverse IRS ruling would doom the spinoff may
evaporate soon, depending on action in Congress. According to
Robert Willens, managing director of tax and accounting issues at
Lehman Brothers, President Clinton's budget proposal includes a
provision allowing partial swaps of assets and rights for stock to
be tax free.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRS could argue that because the members will retain the
right to trade on the exchange, the members have therefore
transferred less than all their rights, constituting a taxable
exchange,'' Willens said. But the Clinton proposal, introduced to
clarify the law after a court ruling challenged the IRS position,
could be passed this year. ``It would be a complete answer to their
problems,'' he said. ``Just a happy coincidence for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
