u w BC-COASTAL-WATERS-NYT &LR;      09-02 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COASTAL-WATERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFSHORE LAW-ENFORCEMENT ZONE IS DOUBLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Coast Guard and federal law-enforcement
agencies will be allowed to enforce American law and board foreign
ships up to 24 nautical miles off the coast, doubling the current
range, the Clinton administration announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which was ordered in a proclamation signed by
President Clinton, was hailed by environmentalists who say that it
should curtail rapacious fishing and pollution by foreign ships
operating off the American coast.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the decision, Vice President Al Gore said in a
speech in Boston that ``we can better protect America's working
families against drug trafficking, illegal immigration and threats
to our ocean environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting would-be smugglers and polluters on notice that
we will do everything in our power to protect our waters and our
shores,'' said the vice president, who hopes to make environmental
protection a central issue in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's move has obvikus appeal to the American fishing
industry, which has long protested over the fishing practices of
foreign vessels, and to voters in coastal states.
</P>
<P>
   The United States claims territorial waters that extend 12
nautical miles, or about 13.8 common miles, from shore. Until
Thursday, the contiguous zone, or the area in which the United
States claims the right to enforce its laws, also extended out 12
nautical miles from the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Under Thursday's move, the United States will expand the area in
which it enforces its laws another 12 nautical miles.
</P>
<P>
   The new limits will allow the Coast Guard to board foreign
vessels _ without seeking the permission of the nations where they
are registered _ that come within 24 nautical miles of shore and
are believed to be smuggling drugs, carrying illegal immigrants,
polluting the oceans or violating other laws. Twenty-four nautical
miles is about 27.6 common miles.
</P>
<P>
   The limits will also apply to the waters around American
territories, including Puerto Rico, Guam, American Samoa, the
Virgin Islands and the North Mariana Islands in the central
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1980s, the United States had a territorial limit of
only three miles. Traditionally, the United States preferred
shorter territorial limits for all nations in part because of the
desire of the U.S. Navy and other elements of the military to have
close access to the shoreline of potential adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   A 1982 U.N. treaty, which was ratified by most members of the
United Nations but not by the United States, permits nations to
claim territorial waters up to 12 nautical miles from shore, and a
contiguous zone up to 24 nautical miles from shore. The United
States has now adopted those limits as its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really good news, especially considering the
needs to have better enforcement of our fisheries management and
protected-species management,'' said Roger McManus, president of
the Center for Marine Conservation, an environmental group based in
Washington. ``This is also extremely important for law-enforcement
personnel who are charged with enforcing laws on drugs and illegal
immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance Thursday at the New England Aquarium in
Boston, the vice president announced the creation of a special
panel overseen by the National Security Council and the Council on
Environmental Quality to coordinate federal policy on the oceans.
He also announced that the federal government would provide $5
million to assist New England fishermen harmed by the depletion of
fish off the East Coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0297 </DOCNO>
