A9100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-POWERTEL03-COX     09-02 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERTEL03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powertel wireless plan lets phones have two numbers
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One phone, two numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Powertel has introduced a service that lets customers use one
wireless phone for calls using different numbers _ and they don't
even have to be in the same area code, so long as the customer
chooses area codes covered by Powertel's 12-state system, including
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Some wireless companies have offered similar features before,
although Powertel introduces some distinctive elements. For
instance, the customer holds only one calling plan, and air time
for both numbers counts toward the same total.
</P>
<P>
   ``You draw the minutes for both lines from the same bucket,''
said Mark Dlugozima, product manager for Powertel.
</P>
<P>
   A BellSouth service requires the customer to buy two calling
plans. BellSouth lets the customer choose different plans _ say,
one for heavy use and the other for the minimum. ``You get two
lines and two buckets of minutes,'' said Robert Haulbrook, director
of marketing for BellSouth Mobility in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   For many travelers frequently using wireless phones, the better
idea may be a one-rate plan that lets users roam, Haulbrook said.
For example, BellSouth has a $90-a-month plan that includes 600
minutes of nationwide use. Powertel also has flat-rate plans _
cheaper per minute than BellSouth's, although BellSouth contends
that Powertel is linked to a less-complete national network.
Powertel offers 120 minutes per month for $30, 600 minutes for $60
and 800 minutes for $80.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Powertel argues that some people will prefer a
two-number, one-phone arrangement, which costs an extra $4 per
month.
</P>
<P>
   The notion is pitched mainly at small businesses and families
whose members are in different cities _ college students, for
instance. For a business, two area codes let the company ``appear
local'' to callers from another city who will, in turn, not have to
pay long-distance rates to connect.
</P>
<P>
   A college student coming home now and then would likewise not be
a long-distance call at school.
</P>
<P>
   Powertel is also introducing a $6-a-month, two-number feature
aimed at users who want to separate business and personal calls
when they look at the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Customers choosing a two-number feature can program the phones
so that each number has a distinctive ring. When a call comes in,
the phone rings, regardless of which line it's arriving on.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas come with wireless phones reaching ever more people
and packing ever more features. Newer phones are increasingly
carrying data transmission, including Internet access. In fact,
Powertel offers up to four lines on its phones, two for voice, one
for faxes and one for data, Dlugozima said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 million Americans now use wireless phones,
according to the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
