<HEADER>
A9101 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     09-02 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RAMON MARTINEZ, GOOD ARM IS A GOOD GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- If we can go by the early returns, it's pretty clear
this isn't going to be like 1934 when Dizzy and Paul Dean won 49
regular-season games for the Cardinals, then won all four games of
the World Series against the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   With 134 games down and 28 to play, the Red Sox have 19 wins
from Pedro Martinez and zero from Big Brother Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Thursday made his first big-league appearance since June
14, 1998, and it resulted in a 4-2 loss to the lowly Kansas City
Royals. Big Brother's comeback concert did not inspire memories of
Luis Tiant, Tom Seaver, Mike Boddicker, or other Red Sox veteran
hurlers who emerged after the All-Star break and buoyed the hopes
of the fandom down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon (is he the first starting pitcher whose first name is the
name of his shortstop spelled backward?) lasted three-plus innings
and gave up four runs (three earned) on five hits two walks and a
hit batsman. He threw 61 pitches, 34 for strikes and was yanked
after yielding two singles and a homer to the first three batters
in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't disappointed,'' said Ramon, who had rotator cuff
surgery last summer. ``I was disapointed with the result, a loss,
but it was a good outing for me. I don't feel any kind of pain. The
only problem I had was that I walked a couple of guys and that was
it. But it was exciting. I liked the way I was out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams echoed the sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``His arm was free,'' said the manager. ``He had a real good
changeup. You could see the quality was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon needed only eight pitches to get out of the first inning,
1-2-3. When he fanned Carlos Beltran to end the perfect frame, fans
posted a Pedro K-Card on the back wall of the center-field
bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   The second inning was a test. Jermaine Dye led with a rocket
single off the Wall, then Ramon walked Dee Brown and Joe Randa to
load the bases with no outs. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan came out
for a visit and Tim Wakefield started throwing in the bullpen. When
Martinez hit the next batter, it looked as if Ramon might get the
early hook, but he got out of the jam like the old master that he
is _ striking out Sal Fasano, getting Jed Hansen on a foul pop, and
fanning Johnny Damon. He threw 27 pitches in the second inning, 14
out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro got nervous when I got the bases loaded and no outs,''
said a smiling Ramon. ``I said, `hey, relax. I've been through that
before.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon bounced a couple of pitches, but was otherwise
consistently high, and appeared to be aiming the ball. In the
third, Ray Holbert led with a single to center, stole second, and
scored on a one-out Wall double by Dye. Martinez got out of that
jam, but the fourth was too much. After a single by No. 9 batter
Hansen, the third straight hit of the inning, Williams popped out
of the dugout and Scott Hatteberg switched mitts to prepare for
Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon pointed to his heart as he came off the mound, then went
to the dugout, accepted some handshakes, and sat down next to his
younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get back out there and pitch a better game than
I did today,'' he said. ``But it was my first game in over a year
and there were a lot of things on my mind out there. I feel good I
was able to go back out there and pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have a pretty big decision to make regarding Ramon's
next start. The season is shrinking and they can ill afford any
more three-inning, four-run stints of a rehab nature. They are
lucky Wakefield is flexible, but can Boston afford to start Ramon
next week in Oakland?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to evaluate,'' said Jimywocky. ``I'm not going to make
that decision now. Wakefield pitched good, too. We're not into
tryout camps. I think Ramon pitched good enough to start again, so
I'm hedging. I'm on that fence. I guess I'm glad I've got my cup
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan said, ``We have to make a decision tomorrow. The only
way we can pitch him is to start him because it takes him so long
to warm up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon took the high road. ``I feel ready for my next start, but
I will respect whatever decision Jimy makes,'' he said. ``We're in
a pennant race, but if he wants me to go out again I go.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Brother says he will respect whatever decision Jimy makes.
He must have borrowed that attitude from Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
