<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-LAWSUIT03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge in Coke bias suit concerned about secrecy, issues a
warning
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The federal judge in the Coca-Cola racial
discrimination lawsuit declined to dramatically change his order
protecting the company's documents, but he expressed concern at the
volume of files being stamped ``confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' lawyers had complained that Coca-Cola was abusing
U.S. District Judge Richard Story's order governing what documents
can be made public. The attorneys said Coca-Cola so far has
indiscriminately marked as confidential virtually all of the 32,000
pages of documents the company has turned over to the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, four current and former employees accuse the
company of discriminating against African-American workers in pay,
promotions and performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola strongly denies the allegations in the suit, which
seeks class-action status.
</P>
<P>
   During a pretrial fact-finding process called discovery, both
sides are required to turn over documents to each other. Under
Story's protective order, documents marked confidential by either
party cannot be made public.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the order, Story said either party could designate as
confidential such documents that contain ``commercial information''
or ``individual personal information.''
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed in July, the plaintiffs asked Story to revise
his order to ``curtail the actual or potential abuse'' of it by
requiring the side that's seeking secrecy to justify its actions,
and they asked the judge to more narrowly define what areas can be
deemed confidential. Story declined to grant either request.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is concerned that Coca-Cola has designated as
confidential a large number of documents it has produced,'' Story
said in an order issued this week. ``If Coca-Cola abuses the
privilege of designating confidential information,'' the judge
indicated he will revisit the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Story did modify his order in one respect by allowing the
disclosure of confidential information during court proceedings.
But he said any party seeking to present such information in court
must first inform the opposing party and the judge so a procedure
protecting confidentiality can be agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   The limitations set out in his protective order, Story said,
``are intended to be strictly construed. ... Simply because
information may not be favorable to a party is not a reason for
designating it confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the data reflecting the employment of minorities at
Coca-Cola will be part of the evidence in the case and subject to
public dissemination, Story noted.
</P>
<P>
   Story said he entered the protective order to prevent
confidential disclosures that may harm the company as well as the
plaintiffs. He added that he is ``especially mindful'' of the
public's interest in employment discrimination litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public's confidence in the judicial process is directly
related to information made available to the public about that
process,'' he wrote. ``Therefore, every effort must be made to
disseminate to the public information relevant to these
proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyrus Mehri, the lead lawyer for the plaintiffs, said of Story's
order, ``We are pleased the court gave the parties guidance on this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Ben Deutsch said the company had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
