<HEADER>
A9105 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w BC-WACO-RENO-TEX     09-02 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-RENO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI TAPE REVELATIONS PUT RENO ON SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was April 28, 1993, and Attorney General Janet
Reno, in a dramatic standoff with Republican critics, had gone
before the House Judiciary Committee and claimed none of the
tear-gas devices fired at the Branch Davidian compound on the
tragic last day of the siege was capable of causing the inferno
that ended the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted and received assurances that the gas and its means of
use were not pyrotechnic,'' Reno said in a jammed House hearing
room before a panel considered the most partisan in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, after six years of insisting the government did
nothing to start the blaze at Mount Carmel where cult leader David
Koresh and about 80 of his followers, including 20 children,
perished, Reno acknowledged that she was ``very troubled'' by new
information she had received that pyrotechnic devices may have been
used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very, very upset,'' Reno said. ``I don't think it's very
good for my credibility. That's the reason I'm going to pursue it
until I get to the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday evening the Justice Department seized a previously
undisclosed infrared videotape recorded during the early morning of
April 19, 1993, that indicates FBI agents obtained permission to
lob pyrotechnic tear-gas canisters at a concrete bunker about 40
yards from the Davidians' compound.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials described Reno as furious over the
FBI's belated discovery of the videotape, made by FBI surveillance
aircraft using infrared radar. An audio track on the tape contained
the agent's request, and his boss' permission, to use the military
tear-gas rounds hours several hours before the cult compound went
up in flames.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from Reno's acknowledgement and the storm of
revelations that have followed it, have reignited passions in
Congress, rekindled calls for her ouster, and again raised
questions about the credibility of the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   At least three congressional committees are taking another look
at the 51-day siege and Reno is expected to name an outside
investigator today to examine why Reno and other ranking Justice
Department officials were never told that the pyrotechnic tear-gas
canisters were used.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the attorney general cannot manage to find and tell the
truth about a matter as important as the Waco incident, she should
step aside and give someone else a chance,'' Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, said, adding his voice to the chorus of lawmakers
demanding Reno's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI now admits it used M651 tear gas canisters in the
assault, but still contends that the fire that destroyed the
compound was started by the Branch Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and the FBI have said agents lobbed the military tear gas
canisers at the bunker hours before the Davidians' wooden building
was engulfed in flames.
</P>
<P>
   The move to end the siege by storming Mount Carmel has long been
the focus of criticism from Republicans on Capitol Hill and from
anti-government groups nationwide. Lawmakers, including House
Government Reform Committee Chairman Dan Burton, R-Ind., have
accused Justice officials of ``sitting on this evidence for six
years, all the while maintaining that it didn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Janet Reno owes us an explanation,'' said Rep. Kay
Granger, R-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's most complete explanation to date has come in
congressional hearings in both 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-day standoff was, in fact, already under way when Reno
took office March 12, 1993, and she began getting briefings from
the FBI on the matter that same day.
</P>
<P>
   She said in testimony that it was former FBI Director William
Sessions who first suggested the use of tear gas to end the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   During the week of April 5, 1993, two weeks before the final
attack, she met with Sessions, former FBI deputy directors Floyd
Clark and Larry Potts, and former FBI official Doug Gow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was briefed in all details about everything that had been
done up to that point in trying to resolve the matter peacefully,''
she said in testimony in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through it in detail. Then I started asking questions.
What about the gas? Would it be harmful to the children? I had real
concern about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pointed out to me that the gas was non-lethal.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she requested that Sessions study the safety issue
further and that the FBI officials suggested she meet with Harry
Salem, a top toxicology expert who was the Army's leading expert on
tear gas. Salem told Reno that the plan to use tear gas could not
lead to injury.
</P>
<P>
   She would later meet with Col. William G. Boykin, then commander
of the Delta Force, and Brig. Gen. Peter J. Schoomaker, then the
assistant division commander of the 1st Cavalry Division at Fort
Hood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their comments were instructive,'' Reno said. ``While
indicating that the plan appeared sound, one suggestion was that
rather than an incremental approach to use, as proposed by the FBI,
that gas should be inserted into all portions of the compound
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I preferred the FBI approach. It seemed to me that that would
be best to ensure the safety of those inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno went on to say, and has always contended, that she approved
the use of tear gas against the compound because the two sides had
reached an impasse, the difficulty of keeping the perimeter of the
compound secure, and the refusal of the remaining Davidians to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   She approved the operation on Saturday, April 17. The plan was
to insert gas periodically over a two-day period, beginning the
following Monday, the day Mount Carmel burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has denied any knowledge of the FBI's use of the
pyrotechnic tear gas canisters exposed on the seized videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Sage, a retired FBI official who acted as chief negotiator
in Waco, said that the tape, found at the FBI crime lab in
Quantico, Va., probably was lost in the mass of evidence the FBI
has relating to the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no sinister plot here and, ultimately, the tape
itself substantiates what the FBI has been confirming all along as
to the actions that day, which ultimately did not contribute one
way or another to the fire started by the Davidians.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Caddell, who has filed a multimillion-dollar federal
wrongful death lawsuit on behalf of nearly 200 Davidians and their
relatives, said the tape is evidence of a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that the government has not been forthcoming about
what happened at Waco,'' he said. ``There are people who clearly
knew about the existence of this tape. Somebody loaded those
pyrotechnics, somebody fired them on the morning of April 19th, and
those people have been remained silent for the last six years.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
