<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUGH DAY AT THE OFFICE FOR FANG LI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The US Open's girl next door has lost. In 66 minutes,
another major championship was over for the hometown hopeful, and
she got in her car and took the 5-minute drive home. She said her
husband would have a nice lunch waiting for her. Chinese. She
particularly likes his steamed-and-fried chicken wings.
</P>
<P>
   She describes him as an ``all-purpose'' husband _ ``cook, coach,
hitting partner, traveling companion, the other things.''
</P>
<P>
   When you're a young lady on the road most of your life, a roomie
for all seasons and reasons comes in mighty handy. But for now Fang
Li, the greatest professional tennis player in the history of the
Peoples Republic of China, is home in Flushing. The US Open is her
favorite tournament, even though she's won only two matches in
eight tries since 1992. ``It is nice to be home, sleep in our own
bed.''
</P>
<P>
   As the neighborhood's lone representative in its foremost annual
occasion, she had a rough-time second rounder Thursday on the paved
Meadow of Flushing. Falling behind world No. 11 Julie
Halard-Decugis of France, almost immediately, 2-0, Fang Li never
caught up and was beaten, 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Did any of her fellow Flushingians know she was their tennis
poster gal _ or grumble, ``There goes the neighborhood!'' when a
tennis player moved in? Doubtful. A mere sprinkling of customers
from the record gathering of 28,192, were witnesses at Court 11.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it's likely that more people watched that match
than will check in by television across the US for the
championships. ``It was live on Star TV, and will be repeated
Friday morning,'' says a spokesman for that network. ``We go into
Asia, principally India and China. Hundreds of millions may have
seen Fang Li.''
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for a dictatorial Chinese politician named Mao
Zedong, Feng Li might be the best-known product of the steel
milling city of Xian Tan in Hunan Province. ``Chairman Mao and
me,'' she laughs. ``So everybody in China knows the place _ most
for him. I visit his home, where he's born, when I'm a school kid.
A small farmer's house in the country, outside town.''
</P>
<P>
   Completing the circuit, on another traditional school trip, she
also visited the Chairman at his present residence, the elaborate
mausoleum in Beijing where, under glass, he stiffly holds court.
</P>
<P>
   Flushing is home to a sizable Chinese community. ``Many good
restaurants, as good as Hong Kong,'' she boosts her adopted
hometown. Better than husband Jin Cheng Zhang's wok work? She
smiles, ``He's very good, but they're professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   Like her 26-year-old self, in a 10th campaign. She has ranked as
high as No. 36 (last year), but dropped to her present No. 94
because knee surgery earlier in the year cost her several months
off the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Letting her dark hair down to well below her shoulders after
playing, Fang Li is saying that she'll rise again ``now that my
knee is OK.'' Her English is better than serviceable, and her
situation, US domiciled, is fine with the government. Not like that
of another Flushing resident, Li Hongzhi, the fugitive founder of
the recently outlawed Falungong religious cult.
</P>
<P>
   She smiles good naturedly that she doesn't want to talk about
such things, or Taiwan. ``I play for my country, Federation Cup and
the Olympics. We like the US. We live here four years with my
brother-in-law's family because it's much easier to travel. Many
more tournaments in this part of the world than Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Fang Li, playing conventional baseline stuff, doesn't chop with
her tennis sticks. In this Year of the Rabbit, she hasn't fully
recovered the speed that has been a strong asset. Maybe next year,
the Year of the Dragon, she'll snort fire and reassert herself in
the rankings, thus qualifying for the Olympics. ``That's my goal,
the Olympics in Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   She's happy with her brief Open. An opening-round win over
Bulgarian Pavlina Stoyanova assured her of second-round prize
money, $19,000. That's her heaviest check during a career that has
amounted to about $500,000 in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   She couldn't have imagined that as a steel mill laborer's
daughter in Xian Tan. But one lucky day, her third year in school,
8-year-old Fang Li impressed a government tennis coach named Xie
Feng Sen. ``She gave the class some tests. Running, movement,
athletic things, and select me to take tennis training. She was my
coach until I turn pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Jin Cheng Zhang took over when they were married. They met as
members of the national team, but she doesn't say if it was love at
first bite of his cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The People's Republic hasn't been a breeding ground of tennis
pros. Previous best was Hu Na, a woman who defected to the United
States in 1982, made it to No. 58 five years later, and is in New
York herself as a Taiwanese telecaster.
</P>
<P>
   Fang Li hadn't known that her townsman, Mao, was also a tennis
player, a hacker. Edgar Snow, in his biography of the Chairman,
reported that Mao and comrades played in camp when the Red Army hid
out in Shaanxi Province, readying to take over China. They did
until a goat ended his career by eating the net. Fortunately there
are no goats at the Meadow called Flushing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
