<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - There he was, dressed in his favorite
striped T-shirt, his little cargo shorts, his backpack slung over
one shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' my husband said as he took the steps down the front
porch. ``I'm going to school now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was killing me. Ripping my black little stone heart right in
two.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not really. Honestly, I couldn't wait for him to get out
of the house. By LAURI NOTARO. Story will move in the ``L''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
POOR (Phoenix) - The Center for Immigration Studies in Washington
is releasing a report that Arizona has the highest rate of
immigrant poverty in the country _ more than 40 percent of the
population. They used the national figure of a family of four
making less than $16,000 as being in poverty. The people at the
Center say this is interesting because the poverty rate statewide
has stayed about the same. They attribute it to a huge amount of
immigration to the state coupled with increasing job competition.
By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BROWN (Phoenix) - Former California Gov. Jerry Brown, now the mayor
of Oakland, is meeting Thursday with renowned Arizona architect
Paolo Solari, the builder of Arcosanti. Brown wants help designing
a 10,000-person village in downtown Oakland. Brown's aim is to
revitalize that East Bay community by creating a place where people
can live and work without commuting, and enabling the conservation
of open space. Those goals are the hallmark of Solari's philosophy
about creating `archologies'' - urban environments for people that
pose the least impact on the natural environment and enable people
to enjoy open spaces near where they live and work. By MIKE MCCLOY.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
