<HEADLINE>
MOST RETAIL CHAINS POST STRONG SALES FOR AUGUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attracted by trendy fashion items like inflatable dorm room
furniture and embroidered blue jeans, back-to-school shoppers
helped propel retailers to another strong month in August.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in stores open at least a year, a crucial industry
measurement, rose 5.1 percent in August, according to the Goldman,
Sachs retail composite index. While strong, the growth was a little
slower than the torrid pace of the first half of this year.
Analysts said the numbers indicated the beginning of a consumer
slowdown, but nothing severe. ``We have gone from a boom to what
you might describe as the next notch down,'' said Richard Burner,
chief U.S. economist with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``But the
fundamentals are still very good.''
</P>
<P>
   George Strachan, vice president of retail investment research
with Goldman, Sachs, agreed. ``Right now we are running among the
best results in 20 years if you take out last year's exceptional
numbers,'' he said. ``The consumer is still very healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the overall good news, shares of most retailers ended
the day down, largely driven by unexpected bad news from Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co. The retailer reported August sales rose 0.1 percent
but also said Thursday that it was lowering earnings expectations
for the third quarter to between 63 cents and 67 cents a share.
Analysts had expected Sears to earn 82 cents a share, according to
a survey by First Call Corp. Shares of Sears fell $3.6875, to a
52-week low of $33.50.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer, based in Hoffman Estates, Ill., blamed softness in
apparel sales and lower than-expected margins because of heavy
price cutting for the decline in earnings. ``We are selling a lot
of merchandise, but not at full price. Even new products were
coming in and being promoted very quickly,'' said a spokeswoman for
Sears, Peggy Palter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the problems at Sears were not a reflection of a
slowing economy but a confirmation of the company's longstanding
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The lowered estimate was announced in conjunction with a
shake-up of top management.
</P>
<P>
   Sears Credit president Alan Lacy will also oversee the company's
home services and e-commerce businesses. Julian Day, who has been
chief financial officer since March, has been named to the newly
created position of executive vice president and chief operating
officer responsible for finance as well as logistics and
information technology. Lacy and Day will join Sears chairman and
chief executive Arthur Martinez in a newly formed office of the
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Robert Mettler, the company's head of merchandising,
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Several other department stores also fared poorly in August.
J.C. Penney Stores reported that sales in stores open a year
declined 3.2 percent, a slide that was greater than anticipated.
Similarly Mervyn's and its parent, Dayton-Hudson Corp., had
slightly larger than expected negative sales numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The discounters, which have remained strong recently, seemed to
get even stronger as the rest of the retail sector pulled back a
bit. ``The dichotomy just got exacerbated for August,'' said Jeff
Feiner, a retail analyst with Lehman Brothers. ``On balance the
consumer recognizes in the price-value equation, value just got
more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores posted a very muscular 8.7 percent gain that
came on top of a very strong 7.6 percent increase in sales in
August of 1998. Target, the discount unit that makes up in excess
of 75 percent of the revenue at Dayton-Hudson, saw sales shoot up
6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Eich, a company spokeswoman, said the fashionable
discounter had done particularly well in fun home furnishings, like
the ``furry Cousin It lamp,'' for the college bound set, but that
sales for younger children were still to come. ``Ten years ago a
mom would do one big trip and now a lot of parents are waiting
until their kids are in school and seeing what other children are
wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick-and-easy fashion statements were also on the minds of
consumers. Specialty chains whose forte is a style statement for
consumers did well this month. Ann Taylor was up 9 percent in
August. American Eagle Outfitters rose 24 percent, on top of a very
tough 28.4 percent sales growth in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In what is turning out to be the turn-around story of the year,
The Limited Inc., whose subsidiaries include Express, Lane Bryant
and Lerner and which owns 80 percent of Intimates Brands, the owner
of Victoria's Secret, posted an impressive companywide gain of 12
percent last month.
</P>
<P>
   The real disappointment in the specialty-store category came
from Gap Inc. Although the company posted very respectable sales
growth of 8 percent, that number was powered by explosive returns
at its Banana Republic and Old Navy divisions. The Gap Stores,
which account for some 40 percent to 45 percent of Gap Inc.'s
revenue, actually saw sales decline 4 percent to 7 percent, while
Banana Republic rose 14 percent to 17 percent and Old Navy jumped
17 percent to 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weakness was in the Gap core business of basics,'' said
Warren Hashagen, senior vice president for international finance,
``the fashion business was stronger than expected, but we just did
not have enough merchandise.'' He said Gap was working on
``adjusting the assortment'' for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Gap have been down in recent months, but analysts are
confident the chain will work through its problems and they have
great faith in the track record of its chief executive, Millard S.
Drexler. ``I give management the benefit of the doubt because The
Gap has been most adept and creating and recreating brands,'' said
Maura Hunter Byrne, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
