<HEADLINE>
ROYALS SPOIL RAMON MARTINEZ' DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Maybe next time, Ramon. It is still too soon to count
on yet another pitcher named Martinez to play a major role in the
Red Sox' bid to make the American League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the older brother of Boston ace Pedro Martinez
pitched well enough in his AL debut to merit another look before
the Red Sox return home from a 10-game, four-city swing to Seattle,
Oakland, New York, and Cleveland. Hopefully, there will be more
support from his teammates than he received Thursday in a 4-2 loss
to Kansas City at Fenway Park in the finale of a seven-game
homestand. The Sox had won the first six.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the A's 9-3 loss to the Yankees, the Sox remain two
games ahead of Oakland in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Funny how things can change in a week. Only last Thursday, the
Sox were in a quandry about whether to rush Ramon, 31, into the
rotation or make a trade to fill a slot created by an injury to
veteran Bret Saberhagen. As it turned out, they did both. Trades
brought starter Kent Mercker and reliever Rod Beck to Boston and
Martinez was activated, mostly to determine how far along he is in
his recovery from shoulder surgery. Now they have a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows where we are,'' said Sox manager Jimy
Williams, who made the decision to give Martinez his first start
since June 8, 1998. ``We have to evaluate. To me Ramon pitched
good. But don't forget he's in the same slot with Tim Wakefield and
we're not into tryout camps. That doesn't mean he's not going to
pitch. I think Ramon pitched good enough to start again, so I'm
hedging. I'm on that fence.''
</P>
<P>
   The return of Martinez Thursday was a 61-pitch adventure that a
crowd of 31,387 was eager to witness but fearful of the
consequences. Ramon gave up four runs, walked two, and allowed five
hits, which is the bad news. The good news is the long fluid motion
and the velocity was also present. When healthy, Ramon Martinez is
almost as good as . . . his brother. Well, he might be one day. The
Red Sox don't seem worried. Neither does Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very exciting,'' he said. ``I'm back and I will try to
do better next time. I felt a little weird from not being there for
a long time. I'll be ready for my next start. But I will go by
whatever decision Jimy makes. We're in a pennant race. If he wants
me to be out there again, I'll be out there. It's different from
when you pitch in the minors. We're in a pennant race. You're not
allowed to make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals Thursday got good pitching from righthander Mac
Suzuki, and even better pitching out of relievers Tim Byrdak and
Chris Fussell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit some balls good today,'' said Williams. ``But it's not
reflected in the score and the number of hits we got. That's the
way this game goes. They jumped out in front and scored four. We
couldn't come back, so you tip your cap to their pitchers and their
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had only one easy inning, the first, in which he
retired the first three hitters on only eight pitches. Things went
from bad to worse in the second and third innings when Kansas City
scored single runs. Matrinez's control vanished in a 27-pitch
second inning. He wilted in the fourth, giving up two more runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first inning I was focused and excited,'' said
Martinez. ``I said, `Let's go right at them.' The second inning I
was just OK. In the third and fourth I went out there and kind of
had too much confidence. I forgot a few of the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez gave up a leadoff single in the second to Jermaine Dye
and then loaded the bases on walks to Dee Brown and Joe Randa. The
first run came home when Martinez hit Joe Vitiello with a pitch. In
the third, Martinez threw only 14 pitches. Ray Holbert hit a
leadoff single. Carlos Beltran lined to right. Then after Holbert
stole second, Dye came through with a run-scoring double.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's day ended abruptly after 12 pitches in the fourth
inning. Vitiello led off with a single and catcher Sal Fasano
followed with a home run into the left-field screen, his first of
the season. That gave Kansas City a 4-0 lead it never relinquished.
Martinez exited in favor of Wakefield after he gave up a single to
No. 9 hitter Jed Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramon just had the one inning when his control kind of left
him,'' said Williams. ``He got out of that even though he had the
bases loaded and one run was already in. He struggled. But you see
the quality is there. He knows how to pitch. His arm looked free.
That's what we were looking for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
