<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-COURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCI NAMES TWO VETERAN JURISTS TO HIGH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Praising their conservative views and ``uncommon good
sense,'' Governor Paul Cellucci nominated two battle-tested former
prosecutors to the state's highest court Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In his first step toward reshaping the court, Cellucci said
Superior Court Judge Judith A. Cowin and Appeals Court Justice
Francis X. Spina would bring intellectual depth and real world
experience to the Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each is an impressive individual who has been tested in the
crucible of the courtroom,'' Cellucci said before a crowd of
lawyers and judges at the State House. ``Each has been called upon
to make decisions about constitutional questions balancing the
rights of defendants, the rights of victims, and the interests of
the community so that justice is served.
</P>
<P>
   Cowin, 57, a Republican who has been active in party circles, is
a former Norfolk County prosecutor. Spina, 52, who is from
Pittsfield, is a Democrat, was an assistant district attorney in
Berkshire County.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said both come with strong backgrounds in the courtroom
as judges, defenders, and prosecutors who have been involved in
difficult and complicated criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   Cowin presided over the highly charged homicide case involving
two men convicted in the murder of 10-year-old Jeffrey Curley of
Cambridge in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said both nominees embrace conservative legal
positions, and support his criminal justice initiatives,
particulary minimum mandatory sentences, truth in sentencing, and
juvenile justice reform.
</P>
<P>
   Both Spina and Cowin said they support the use of the death
penalty for first degree murder cases and said capital punishment
is allowed under the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci said he did not use the death penalty as a defining
issue in making the judicial appointments.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to his nomination of associate SJC justice Margaret
Marshall, who is a death penalty opponent, as chief justice last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no litmus test,'' Cellucci said, who interviewed
finalists for the two vacancies along with Lieutenant Governor Jane
Swift.
</P>
<P>
   Spina and Cowin will replace former Chief Justice Herbert
Wilkins, who reached the mandatory retirement age of 70 last month,
and Charles Fried, a 1995 appointee, who left the bench in June to
return to his teaching post at Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   With two more SJC justices -- Ruth I. Abrams and Neil L. Lynch
-- scheculed to retire next year, Cellucci will have appointed four
of the seven members of the court and have chosen the next chief
justice in the first two years of his term.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whom they viewed as their role models on the SJC,
Cowin chose Fried, known for his outspoken conservative views.
Spina said he most admired associate justice John Greaney, a fellow
native of western Massachusetts who was appointed in 1989 by then
Governor Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Cowin was appointed to the Superior Court by former governor
William F. Weld, and has been active in the past in state GOP
circles.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, she was a staff aide to former US Senator Edward
Brooke. Her husband, William Cowin, served in top posts in the
Sargent administraiton in the early 1970's, and was chosen by the
party to run for lieutenant governor in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, pointing to his appointment of Cowin and elevation of
Marshall, touted his record of appointing women to the bench. He
said 40 percent of his judicial nominees have been females. He said
10 percent are racial minorities, a figure he said is too low and
that he plans to recruit minority candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Legal observers said Cellucci's choices are strong signals that
the governor intends to appoint judges who have experience in the
courtrooms from all perspectives, a sharp departure, they say, from
the more academic nominees appointed by his predecessor William F.
Weld.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Weld appointments were prosecutorial while Cellucci
is obviously turning to people who have a far broader sense of the
real world, with more balanced life experience,'' said Thomas E.
Dwyer Jr., president of the Boston Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer, who active in state and national Democratic circles, also
praised Cellucci for ``obviously focusing on judges who have both
experience and an understanding of the fraility of human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Cellucci has decided the best thing he could for his
legacy is to look for the best possible people and put ideology
aside,'' Dwyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiments were echoed by Martin Healy, general counsel of
the Massachusetts Bar Association, who praised the governor's
choices for the court, saying both Cowin and Spina have ``strong
legal practical backgrounds'' that would allow them to balance the
interest of criminal and defendants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
