<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9122 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-EDUC-ART-990(2TA     09-02 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUC-ART-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WOULD TAKE MONEY FROM BAD SCHOOLS; LET PARENTS USE IT FOR
PRIVATE SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BUSH-EDUC-TEXT) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said Thursday that if
elected president he would force schools in poor areas to perform
by threatening to take away federal money from those that fail and
allow parents to use it for private schools. Addressing a Hispanic
business association lunch, Bush, a Republican, dismissed most
existing federal educational programs as failures. But in a
departure from traditional Republican thinking, he outlined a
strategy that would increase the role of th% federal Department of
Education by adding to it the Head Start program for preschoolers
and using federal funds to reward high-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the conservative preference for local control, Bush
said Washington should stay out of the business of setting
standards for schools, leaving that up to state and local
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government must be humble enough to stay out of
the day-to-day operation of local schools, wise enough to give
states and school districts more authority and freedom, and strong
enough to require proven performance in return. When we spend
federal money, we want results _ especially when it comes to
disadvantaged children.''
</P>
<P>
   Education, which played only a modest role in the last
presidential election, has emerged as the top concern of voters and
the two parties are vying to demonstrate it has the means to
improve the nation's schools. Vice President Al Gore, who is
seeking the Democratic presidential nomination, devoted his first
major policy speech last spring to his plans for how the federal
government could bring about what he called ``revolutionary
change'' in education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has emphasized his performance in Texas, where testing and
accountability have led to improved schools. But he has not used
state money there to reward or punish schools in the way he is
proposing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush Thursday carefully avoided using the politically sensitive
expression school vouchers. Vouchers, backed by many conservatives
and strongly opposed by many liberals, involve giving credits to
parents that could be used to remove children from public schools
and placed in private schools partly or wholly at government
expense.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said in his speech here Thursday that he would withdraw
federal funding from schools whose students tested poorly and that
parents of the children in those schools would receive as much as
$1,500 that could be used to send children to private schools or
other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and other leading Democrats oppose the use of school
vouchers, insisting they would weaken public schools by siphoning
away needed government funding. Secretary of Education Richard
Riley reacted to the speech by saying, ``No matter how you dress it
up, how long you delay it, or what you call it, a voucher is a
voucher. ... Vouchers undermine our public schools _ which educate
about 90 percent of our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bush threaded together ideas of Democrats and
Republicans for his speech and many liberals reacted to Bush's plan
quite positively.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 80 percent are policies and initiatives we could support
and do support,'' said William L. Taylor, vice chair of the
Citizens Commission on Civil Rights. But he said that while he
favored the right of youngsters in failing schools to opt out and
go to schools that are succeeding, they should be restricted to
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would fundamentally alter two major federal
programs, Head Start, which offers everything from day care and
meals to poor children, and Title I, which is the main fund of
federal dollars for poor schools. He would refocus both on
improving reading ability and other basic skills. He added that he
would allow private agencies to compete for and administer some of
those programs, which currently involve almost $13 billion a year
in spending, if the children in them test poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my administration, federal money will no longer follow
failure,'' he said. ``Public funds must be spent on things that
work.'' Bush did not address whether the private agencies would
then be tested, what kind of bureaucracy would be required to
handle the bidding for the contracts or what would happen to the
schools that lost federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, regarded as the frontrunner among the Republican
candidates, described federal programs as involving ``high hopes
and low achievement, grand plans and unmet goals.'' Indeed, one of
the most frequently used words in his speech here Thursday was
``failure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to start where educational failure has its highest
price,'' said Bush. ``I want to begin with the disadvantaged
children in struggling schools, and the federal role in helping
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He promised to reorganize what he characterized as a confusing
maze of federal programs with little emphasis on measurable
results.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been criticized by some of his opponents for being
short on specifics about policy, and he said Thursday's address
would be the first in a series of policy speeches on education,
which he described as one of his highest priorities. He spoke to
the Latino Business Association at the Los Angeles Convention
Center, and peppered his remarks with Spanish to a highly
appreciative audience, made up largely of entrepreneurs and small
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   The line that drew that strongest applause was: ``Some say it is
unfair to hold disadvantaged children to rigorous standards. I say
it is discrimination to require anything less, the soft bigotry of
low expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ideas Bush outlined Thursday have been a part of his
educational strategy in Texas. He inherited some of those programs
from his Democratic predecessor, Ann Richards, as well as other
state administrations, but he has pursued testing and a focus on
teaching reading skills vigorously. Test results have risen
considerably in the state, particularly for minority students, but
the gap between white and minority children remains large.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not address many of Gore's education proposals. Gore,
for instance, has proposed making preschool universally available,
offering tax breaks to encourage saving for college, reductions in
the size of classes in public schools, testing of teachers to make
sure they live up to basic standards, and ensuring that students
develop a basic competency with computers by the eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by contrast, focused on teaching reading, particularly to
young children. He said that children should begin learning to read
at ages three and four, and he insisted that the best method was
phonics. He said that the Head Start program should be changed to
focus on teaching reading to these young children and that the
program should be transferred from the Department of Health and
Human Services to the Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush equated failure to learn to read at a young age with a
propensity to turn to crime later in life. ``More and more, we are
divided into two nations, separate and unequal, one that reads and
one that can't, one that dreams and one that doesn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush offered his clearest set of rewards and penalties for
schools that receive federal funds under the Title I program. He
said that the disadvantaged students at those schools would be
tested every year, with the tests written and administered by the
states, not the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that show improvement, he said, would receive additional
federal grants. Bush has said he strongly favors reducing taxes and
cutting the federal budget, and he did not discuss how he would pay
for the grants Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that test poorly, he added, would receive warnings. If
they continued to fail to show improvement for three years, the
Title I funds they receive would be divided up, matched by
additional federal money and given to the state. The state would
pass the money to the parents of the children in those schools _ as
much as $1,500 each per year _ and it could be used for tutoring,
switching the students to charter schools, semiautonomous public
schools, different public schools or private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any case, the federal government will no longer pay schools
to cheat poor children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Effective reform requires accountability. Someone
should be praised when schools succeed, and someone must be
responsible when schools fail.'' He also insisted that, in spite of
the breadth of these federal initiatives, control over schools
would be placed largely in local hands, a policy that is central to
the conservative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In calling for each state, and not the federal government, to
devise the standards by which each student would be measured, Bush
succeeded in allaying the fears of some conservatives who worry
about centralized control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is betting where I personally always bet, that state
policy-makers and parents are likeliest to do right by kids,'' said
Chester E. Finn, a senior fellow at the Manhattan Institute, which
studies educational issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sought to emphasize that he would remain flexible in
certain respects. He said that he would back bilingual education,
something many conservatives have fought bitterly, particularly in
California, if it proved effective in the form of better test
scores. He also said that he would back language immersion programs
if they could be shown to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``What matters is not the varying methods, but the common
standards and goals,'' Bush said. ``The standard is English
literacy. The goal is equal opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
