<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9132 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-770&AMP;ADD     09-02 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST STANDOFF REMAINS UNSOLVED AS ALBRIGHT VISITS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ On her first trip to the Middle East since the
Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, came to power, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright hit a snag when the Israelis and
Palestinians failed to deliver an agreement for a signing ceremony
in Egypt Thursday that she hoped to preside over.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiating atmosphere between the two sides that was
supposed to have substantially improved with the new Israeli leader
had not warmed sufficiently to allow the release of 50 Palestinian
prisoners now held in Israel. That issue stands in the way of
reviving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear whether the dispute over the
prisoners constituted a real crisis or a matter of each side
wanting to show their constituencies that they were reaching for
the best possible bargain on an emotional issue.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who had delayed her trip for two weeks at the request
of the Israeli prime minister met with Palestinian leader, Yasser
Arafat, and the Egyptian president, Hosni Mubarak, in Alexandria,
Egypt, and then flew here for a meeting early Friday morning with
Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, at the request of Barak, has taken
more of a back seat in the current negotiations, which cover
completion of a deal signed in Wye, Md., last fall in which Israel
agreed to give up West Bank land in exchange for greater security.
Being discussed is also the much broader question of a framework
for a permanent settlement.
</P>
<P>
   A failure to complete the agreement before the secretary leaves
for a scheduled visit on Saturday to Syria to meet the Syrian
President, Hafez Assad, in Damascus, would put a damper on her
ability to persuade Assad to restart negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Israeli desire for the Americans to keep a lower
profile and the administration's insistence that it was happy to
see both sides negotiating directly, Albright injected herself into
the process. She is to visit Jordan on Sunday and is trying to get
an agreement completed before she leaves the region for Asia later
that day.
</P>
<P>
   She met with Arafat, accompanied by one of his top security
officials, for more than an hour in Alexandria, and in the middle
of that meeting telephoned Barak.
</P>
<P>
   On the 40-minute flight from Alexandria to Tel Aviv, a senior
administration official played down the gravity of the logjam, and
said that both sides were making ``a very serious effort.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that only a few issues were left to resolve, and that an
agreement might be reached Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Albright was not playing the role of ``mediator'' but rather
conveying concerns and making suggestions, he said. ``They've done
the vast majority of the work,'' the official said of the Israelis
and Palestinians. They had been assisted a great deal, he said, by
the Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian foreign minister, Amr Moussa, standing beside
Albright at a news conference here after Palestinian and Israeli
flags that had been readied for a ceremony were put aside, said the
agreement could be completed in ``hours'' or ``days.'' When it was
ready, Moussa said he expected a ceremony to take place in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   The administration official declined to specify whether the
prisoner issue was the sole hurdle to be overcome, but suggested
that several other issues had become interrelated as the
negotiations went down to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis see the ``security prisoners,'' as opposed to
criminals, as terrorists, but the Palestinians view them as freedom
fighters who fought against the occupation of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In their negotiations, the Israelis agreed to release 350
prisoners but the Palestinians wanted 400 released. The Israelis
have insisted that they would not release any prisoner who murdered
an Israeli and that there were not 50 more prisoners who met their
criteria for release.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoner issue became suddenly even more sensitive for Barak
after a young Orthodox Jewish couple were found stabbed to death
last weekend. On Wednesday, the military arm of Hamas, an Islamic
fundamentalist group, claimed responsibility for the killings.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank and Gaza earlier this week, mothers
demonstrated with framed photographs of their jailed sons.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoner issue is also difficult because the types of
prisoners to be released was not specified in the original Wye
memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for the release of 750 prisoners, but other
details _ whether the prisoners to be released were criminals or
``security'' prisoners _ were decided in oral agreements among
President Clinton, Arafat, and Benjamin Netanyahu, Israel's prime
minister at the time.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the question of the turnover of land that was called for in
the Wye agreement, the current negotiations envision the Israelis
ceding 11 percent more of the West Bank to full or partial
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   The first 2 percent of the 13 percent called for at Wye was
turned over by Netanyahu who then stopped the implementation of the
accord.
</P>
<P>
   Barak wants to combine the final withdrawal of Israeli troops
called for in the Wye agreement into progress in the permanent
status negotiations. This is desirable for Barak because the last _
and largest withdrawal _ mandated by Wye would leave about 15
Jewish settlements virtually encircled by Palestinian-controlled
land.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the prisoner issue, Barak's call for a specific
date early in the new year for a framework on the permanent status
negotiations has also been a sticking point for Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, relieved at the election in May of
Barak as prime minister, and the defeat of Netanyahu, would like to
get the permanent status talks going as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary was accompanied here by the administration's top
Middle East negotiators - presidential advisor Dennis Ross, Martin
Indyk, who is the assistant secretary of state for the Near East,
and Middle East expert Aaron Miller.
</P>
<P>
   In the current negotiations, Barak is seeking a date early in
the New Year for a framework agreement on permanent status talks.
Arafat is said to be nervous about a defined date. These talks
would define the hardest issues of all _ the future of Jerusalem,
the return of refugees and the borders of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   These questions could be settled by the end of 2000, the
Israelis argue, a date that does not displease Clinton who leaves
office then and sees a permanent settlement in the Middle East as a
crowning glory of his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of the overall,'' Albright said about the final
status talks during her flight from Washington, ``this is a very
high priority for President Clinton. You can figure out the timing
for yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
