A9133 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SANTACLAUS-MURDERS03-     09-02 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTACLAUS-MURDERS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury convicts man of killing family in Georgia
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE, Ga. _ Jerry Scott Heidler's attorney asked the jury that
convicted him Thursday of the Santa Claus murders to ``extend mercy
to this pathetic young man,'' but a jailer testified that Heidler
told him he was a collector of souls _ and his collection was not
complete.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of seven men and five women is expected to decide today
whether the 22-year-old Heidler will spend his life in prison or
die in the electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   They took just 20 minutes to find him guilty of the Dec. 4,
1997, murders of Kim and Danny Daniels and two of their children.
They also convicted him of the seven other charges he was facing:
three of kidnapping, three of sodomy and molestation involving the
three girls he kidnapped, and one of burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors disregarded defense attorney Michael Garret's plea to
find Heidler guilty but mentally ill, which would not have spared
him the specter of the death penalty but would have indicated they
had some sympathy for him.
</P>
<P>
   Heidler was convicted of breaking into the home of the family
that had befriended him in the Toombs County village of Santa
Claus, taking one of Danny Daniels' shotguns and killing the
sleeping adults adults and Jessica, 16, and Brent, 8. He kidnapped
three more girls briefly and left two younger children, including a
10-month-old, alone with the blood-soaked bodies.
</P>
<P>
   In the penalty phase of the trial, moved to Walton County
because of heavy publicity, District Attorney Richard Malone told
jurors Heidler ``remains the same horrible killer that he was on
Dec. 4, 1997.'' Imprisoning him instead of executing him, he said,
would subject guards and inmates to ``the rages of this man for the
rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrett, who will present his major witnesses today, asked for
mercy for ``this very, very mixed-up, sick young man.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce LeBlanc, a booking officer at the Tombs County jail, said
he often had conversations with Heidler because the scrawny,
chapfallen killer ``gets a little antsy because he doesn't have
anyone to talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   One night, LeBlanc said, he noticed Heidler was wearing a
crucifix inverted on a chain around his neck. ``I asked him if he
didn't worry about his soul,'' LeBlanc said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he didn't worry about his soul any more. I asked him
why. He said he was a collector of souls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Jerry, what in the world are you talking about?' He
said he wasn't through collecting souls, and he showed me the
tattoo on his knuckles. It reads `Sandman.'''
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc said Heidler told him the Sandman was a movie character
whose soul belongs to the devil ``and who goes around killing whole
families in their sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Other jailers testified that they had found as many as 75 crude
weapons Heidler had made in the 20 months he was in the Toombs
County jail. They said he was constantly unscrewing wire cages from
smoke and fire alarms and on one occasion, even taking the lock out
of a jail door. They said he routinely threatened to kill jailers.
</P>
<P>
   Dean McManus, the GBI agent who lead the investigation into the
Santa Claus killings, said that almost a year later, he got a
collect call from a prisoner whose voice he didn't immediately
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   The caller told McManus he ``had a score to settle with him,''
and McManus began to suspect it was Heidler. Finally, McManus said,
the caller said: ``You don't know who this is, do you? I'll give
you a hint.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please do,'' McManus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine little piggies, four dead,'' the caller retorted. Moments
later, the agent said, a jailer at Toombs County came on the line
and confirmed the caller was Heidler.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
