<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-EDUCATION03-COX     09-02 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATION03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush proposes voucher plan for failing public schools
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ GOP presidential front-runner George W. Bush, who
couldn't get Texas legislators to divert state money to private
schools, on Thursday proposed what critics called a national
``back-door voucher'' plan that would use federal money to get kids
out of failing public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to cut the flow of federal money to schools that
continually fall short of state standards and use the dollars for
``whatever option parents choose.'' That could include other public
schools, charter schools, tutoring or private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to start where educational failure has its highest
price,'' Bush said. ``I want to begin with disadvantaged children
in struggling schools and the federal role in helping them.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan drew quick criticism from Vice President Al Gore, who
on Wednesday, during a trip to San Antonio, rapped the quality of
public schools in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the sweet talk in the world can't hide the fact that
George Bush wants to slam the door on the kids in America's public
school system,'' said Gore spokeswoman Kiki Moore. ``If there is
any money left for education after the Republican tax scheme, he
wants to yank it out of the public school system with his back-door
voucher program.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats and some national educational leaders also
criticized the plan. ``The American pubic does not support
vouchers. They know this is the beginning of the erosion of public
schools,'' said Roy Romer, general chairman of the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public schools should be held accountable, and so should
politicians,'' said Bob Chase, president of the National Education
Association. ``Governor Bush says he wants to invest in programs
that work, but he's willing to waste millions of tax dollars on
vouchers, which don't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush laid out his plan to the Latin Business Association in a
speech entitled ``No Child Left Behind.'' He will offer more
education proposals in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, said Bush, is to end government's education monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must recognize the essential role of competition in
achieving our goals, competition from charters and parental choice
and home schooling,'' he said. ``All monopolies are slow to reform
when consumers have no power to express their frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   While positioning himself as a champion of public schools, Bush
said too many of them are failing. He said the federal government
has backed programs that are ``sloppy and trendy, focusing on
self-esteem over basic skills.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to call his plan a voucher program, but declared,
``Federal money will no longer follow failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Adhering to a philosophy he has pushed in Texas, Bush said the
nation must find a way to stop paying for schools that don't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pigment and poverty need not determine performance,'' said
Bush, who has failed in three legislative sessions to win approval
for a pilot program under which parents of children in subpar
schools could get state dollars to pay private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   His new proposal calls for a landmark shift in the spending of
money from the federal Title 1 program that sends $7.7 billion a
year to schools with students from low-income families. The Austin
Independent School District receives about $11 million in Title 1
funds annually. About 52 percent of AISD's 78,000 students qualify
for such funds.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants all schools that get Title 1 funds, now about 44,000,
to offer annual exams to measure student performance on basic
academics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush received lukewarm support from one the nation's most
influential Hispanic groups, the National Council of La Raza.
``We're on track in terms of the concern, but we differ on a
solution,'' NCLR President Raul Yzaguirre said of how Title 1 funds
currently are spent.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of backlash from Republicans who oppose national
testing, Bush wants to allow each state to set the standards.
Schools that fail to show annual progress would get warnings from
the federal government. Three strikes would mean the school would
be out of federal Title 1 funds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the money would be given to the states, which would set
up education accounts for parents to use as they see fit. The
account would provide about $1,500 a year per student. The money
could be spent on private school tuition only in states that
approve such an option.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said parents could use the money ``for whatever offers
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the best case, these schools will rise to the challenge and
regain the confidence of parents,'' Bush said. ``In the worst case,
we will offer scholarships to America's neediest children, allowing
them to get the emergency help they should have. In any case, the
federal government will no longer pay schools to cheat poor
children.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of using public money to pay private school tuition won
support from Steve Rabago, a business consultant who heard Bush
pitch the plan. Rabago is the president of the Laguna Beach school
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be able to go elsewhere,'' he said of students in
low-performing public schools.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, John C. Bowman, with the Texas Public Policy
Foundation, one of the most vocal supporters of school vouchers
applauded the plan as ``a positive step to reinvigorating a
disengaged portion of our population who have largely been pushed
out of the public sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush predicted subpar schools facing the possibility of student
defections would find ways to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any case, the federal government will no longer pay schools
to cheat poor children,'' he said, realizing his plan could have
significant impact on urban schools that get massive doses of Title
1 money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also wants to apply his results-oriented approach to the
politically perilous question of how best to teach English to
students who grew up with another language.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a good immersion program works, I say fine. If a good
bilingual program works to teach children English, we should
applaud it,'' he said. ``What matters is not the varying methods,
but the common standards and goals. The standard is English
literacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also wants to move the Head Start pre-school program from
the Department of Health and Human Services to the Department of
Education as part of a plan to pump up the education component of
the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Head Start was originally intended as a literacy program,
designed to close the achievement gap between rich and poor,'' Bush
said. ``It evolved into a day care, health and nutrition program.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
