<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SNAG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS, PALESTINIANS FAIL TO RESOLVE ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Mideast-Mediate)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright arrived
Thursday in Egypt to the trappings of a signing ceremony that never
took place, as Israelis and Palestinians failed to bridge
differences on how to implement a critical phase of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   It had been hoped that Albright's tour of the region would begin
with a ceremony marking a new breakthrough in the long-delayed
peace process and from there Albright would seize the momentum to
reopen direct talks between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   But instead Albright was left fielding questions at a press
conference at a presidential palace in Alexandria about the latest
snag in the ``land for security'' deal signed nearly a year ago in
Maryland but never successfully implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Although Albright noted that both sides were still talking and
expressed hope that an agreement could come as soon as Friday, she
said, ``The road to true peace remains hard and uphill. . . . The
US and Egypt can be helpful, but it is up to the parties to make
the hard decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the opulent palace in Alexandria, Israeli and Palestinian
flags that were supposed to flank a signing ceremony were left in a
hallway as reporters grilled Albright and Egyptian Foreign Ministr
Amr Moussa about the significance of the latest hitch in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Albright met with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Palestinian Authority president Yasser Arafat briefly in
Alexandria, and then left for Israel where she planned to meet with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat had come to Alexandria amid hopes the sticking point on
the issue of the release of Palestinian security prisoners from
Israeli jails would be resolved at the last minute. But Barak never
arrived, as the Israelis refused to budge on the issue of releasing
prisoners who have been involved in killing Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock comes down to a disagreement over 50 Palestinian
prisoners. The Palestinians say they want 400 prisoners to be
released as is required by the Wye River agreement. But Israel said
it would release only 350, insisting that the other 50 had ``blood
on their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The prisoner issue is a resonant one with high domestic
political stakes for both Barak and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has seen conservative political forces in the country
become galvanized on the issue in recent speeches and
demonstrations, making it clear that if Barak releases any
Palestinians who killed Israelis he will pay a heavy political
price for it.
</P>
<P>
   And Arafat is aware of the Palestinian demonstrations calling
for the return of the detainees who are seen as patriots and
prisoners of war in the fight against Israel for the Palestinian
cause. Palestinian political sources say Arafat's repeated
concessions in the process are hurting his image and that the
release of prisoners has become an important threshold that
Palestinians are not willing to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the impasse, Egyptian Foreign Minister Moussa remarked on
the importance of moving forward soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere was very much poisoned in the last few years,''
he said referring to the setbacks that occurred in the process
under Barak's more conservative predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is our task to revive the peace process and introduce a
level of optimism in the region,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye River deal, brokered by President Clinton last October
at the Wye River plantation in Maryland, was signed in Washington
by Arafat and Netanyahu. But Netanyahu froze the interim agreement
only two months later after handing over just two percent of West
Bank land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, as originally conceived, called for the release of 750
Palestinian prisoners and a three-stage Israeli troop withdrawal
from a further 13 percent of the West Bank in return for further
security steps to be taken by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   If that 13 percent of the West Bank is ceded to the Palestinian
Authority, the Palestinians would be left with full or partial
control of roughly 40 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Under the emerging agreement, the next Israeli troop pullback
would begin in the next few days, to be followed by a second one
Nov. 15 and a third one at the end of the year or the beginning of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The calling off of the signing ceremony must come as a
disappointment to Albright, who will now have to devote much of her
time to trying to push the two sides to reach an agreement. Aides
say she had hoped to concentrate more on laying the groundwork for
a resumption of direct talks between Israel and Syria over the
Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is expected to visit Syria Saturday. The Israeli-Syrian
negotiating track was derailed in 1996. Syrians claim the Israelis
have promised in principle to a full withdrawal from the Golan
Heights, which they captured in 1967, but Israel disputes that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
