<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SIGN THREE; STATUS QUO ON DAFOE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As the clock ticks to the opening of training camp,
with all the Bruins on the ice together Sunday for the first time,
the club added three players to the fold Thursday. However, none of
them was free agent netminder Byron Dafoe, who said he will leave
town for his offseason home in Southern California this weekend if
no agreement can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the tension rises on that front, it was defused on
another as Boston signed goaltender John Grahame to a one-year
contract, defenseman Mattias Timander to a two-year deal, and left
wing Antti Laaksonen to a one-year pact.
</P>
<P>
   Grahame, who was a key reason the Providence Bruins won the
Calder Cup last season, is coming off a career year. He led the
American Hockey League in wins with a 37-9-1 record and set an AHL
mark with a 19-game winning streak. He tied an AHL mark for
postseason victories with a 15-4 record and 2.38 goals-against
average in 19 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Laaksonen was another big contributor to the Baby B's with 58
points in 66 games and led the AHL with a plus-40 rating. In two
recalls to Boston last year, Laaksonen had a goal and two assists.
Timander spent the first half of last season with Providence and
was recalled Feb. 10 to Boston, where he remained the rest of the
year and came on strong in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Hal Gill and left wing P.J. Axelsson, both restricted
free agents, remain unsigned with the players' demands far
different than the team's offers. Neither is expected for the
beginning of camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
