<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO EASE TENSIONS, NYC PLANS SMALLER POLICE PRESENCE AT
CONTROVERSIAL RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police Commissioner Howard Safir on Thursday
reassured anxious neighborhood leaders in Harlem that there would
be a substantially reduced police presence at this year's Million
Youth March.
</P>
<P>
   His pledge marked a retreat from the city's hard-edged stance
toward the organizers of the youth rally, particularly Khallid
Abdul Muhammad, whom Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has accused of
fomenting bigotry and violence by disparaging Jews and whites.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said the police presence would be reduced to comply with
both the desires of neighborhood leaders and the orders of two
courts, which ruled this week that the rally can go forward. Prior
to those court orders, Giuliani and other city officials had
pledged to use the full force of the Police Department to oversee
the event, which last year ended in violent clashes between police
and hundreds of rally participants.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood leaders, while condemning the rally as the
handiwork of anti-Semitic ``outsiders,'' said Thursday that they
were even more afraid that police would repeat the ``heavy-handed''
and ``insulting'' enforcement of last year's march. The enforcement
included squads of officers in riot gear, still more on horses and
in helicopters, and hundreds of barricades that severely restricted
the demonstrators' freedom of movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want community-friendly policing in which we are not
treated as the hostile enemy,'' said City Councilman Bill Perkins,
who last week said he had been assaulted by rally organizers and is
one of several Harlem politicians who have called upon residents to
boycott the march, scheduled to take place from noon to 4 p.m.
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel of Harlem, who had also called for a
boycott, said, ``We don't want to get hit on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with Perkins and other neighborhood leaders Thursday
morning at the Adam Clayton Powell Jr. State Office Building in
Harlem, Safir said that the event would be patrolled by fewer than
half the 3,000 or so officers who were assigned to last year's
Million Youth March. Safir also said that the officers would not
wear riot gear, nor would platoons of mounted officers be sent to
the rally area, on Malcolm X Boulevard between 118th and 124th
Streets.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Safir told the group, subway service to Harlem
would not be cut off as it was last year, and police helicopters
would not swoop over the rally, a tactic that provoked intense
criticism from many quarters.
</P>
<P>
   On another sore point, Safir said that a minimal number of
barricades would be used for crowd control, according to those who
were at the meeting. At last year's event, those who attended the
rally were directed into large barricade pens _ ``cattle chutes,''
they were called _ and some residents complained that they were
completely cut off from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Perkins said, Safir offered assurances that
police officers would not rush the rally stage at the end of the
event, as they did within a minute or two of last year's
agreed-upon ending time. ``They made it clear,'' Perkins said of
Safir and his aides, ``that they would not bum rush the parade the
way they did last time around.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, Safir said of the meeting, ``There was
not great support for this march, but there was concern that both
sides act reasonably. We intend to act reasonably. We intend to
have adequate police presence up there to make sure this is a safe
event. We would ask that Khallid Muhammad and his people do the
same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
