<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-REVENGE03-COX     09-02 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-REVENGE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Revenge: Drivers downplay retaliation but history suggests
otherwise
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the 1987 Winston race in Charlotte, N.C., NASCAR
driver Bill Elliott slammed into Dale Earnhardt's car during a
victory lap because Elliott was incensed about bumping from
Earnhardt late in the race.
</P>
<P>
   At Bristol in 1995, Rusty Wallace hit Earnhardt in the head with
a plastic water bottle after Earnhardt wrecked Wallace early in the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, at Watkins Glen, Sterling Marlin was fined
$5,000 after purposely running his car into Chad Little's car as
they approached the finish line, seconds after the race had been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   So the latest controversy between Earnhardt and Terry Labonte is
nothing new, especially for a sport that traces its defining moment
to Daytona in 1979. Then, a post-race fist fight between Cale
Yarborough and Bobby Allison became the highlight of the first
nationally televised live race.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, NASCAR officials are taking the latest flap seriously.
Earnhardt was booed by thousands of fans at Bristol on Saturday
night, when he won the Goody's 500 by pushing race leader Labonte
into the wall on the final lap.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR rules state that it is illegal to intentionally cause
another car to wreck, and most drivers believe that Earnhardt got
away with one. NASCAR rules also state that it is illegal to exact
revenge against another driver on the track, but most drivers think
it could happen as early as Sunday, when Darlington Raceway holds
its 50th Southern 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Earnhardt) had better tighten his (seat) belts,'' Labonte
said after the Bristol race.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get together again, I'd say Earnhardt's got him a
neck-stretching coming,'' Marlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt has taken the criticism in stride. Known as ``The
Intimidator,'' he has forged a career under a win-at-all-costs
philosophy. Earlier this year, he bumped his son, Dale Jr., out of
the way to win a Busch race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll apologize to Terry and do what we've got to do,''
Earnhardt said. ``If he sees he's got to stretch my neck like
Sterling Marlin says, we'll just have to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte has calmed down since the wreck, but he says he has lost
some respect for Earnhardt, a seven-time Winston Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
   Revenge, referred to as ``payback'' in the garages, is always a
major concern for NASCAR and its drivers. The sport's governing
body was heavily criticized for allowing Earnhardt to keep the
Bristol victory and claims to have an absolute ban on such acts.
Each case is reviewed individually, but punishments range from race
suspensions to deduction of points in the Winston Cup points
standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is talk of revenge in the garage area, our drivers
are the ones who are going to weed it out,'' NASCAR spokesman Tim
Sullivan said. ``They are not going to stand for it. With the
speeds these guys are traveling, there is no place at the track for
revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days of stock-car racing, before drivers jetted to
races and corporations paid $10 million to sponsor cars, revenge
was more common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, if you hit somebody, you could expect to be hit
back; that was pretty much the way things worked out then,''
veteran driver Dave Marcis said. ``You see some of that today, and
sometimes you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   It often depends on the drivers. ``Everybody has their own way
of handling things,'' Kevin Lepage said. ``We spend more time with
our fellow racers than we do with our neighbors, because we're on
the road and the track so long. I can't believe there is something
like (revenge) going on.''
</P>
<P>
   If Labonte chooses to retaliate for the Bristol incident, he
would have less noticeable ways than causing a wreck. Drivers say
the most popular revenge is making it hard for another driver to
pass at any time during a race. That form of payback can last for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think payback exists,'' said Ned Jarrett, a retired two-time
Cup champion. ``Most of the time when it (happens later), it has
been forgotten by the fans, media and people in racing. The drivers
know, though. I think that there have been paybacks in the past and
will continue to be paybacks in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
