<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS03-COX     09-02 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stefan remains unsigned to Thrashers; goalie Langkow has deal
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the majority of Thrashers arrive in Orlando,
Fla., for team photos today, a significant part of their future
will be missing.
</P>
<P>
   In what is shaping up as not quite the Kodak moment the team had
hoped for, top draft pick Patrik Stefan remained unsigned Thursday,
increasing the possibility he will miss the beginning of training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell said Stefan still could be
signed in time for the team's first practice Sunday at the RDV
Sportsplex, but admitted he and agent Steve Kotlowitz are no closer
to a deal than they were Tuesday, when both sides had indicated an
agreement was close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fairly close, but the problem now is we've taken our
ground as far as we can take it and (Kotlowitz) says the same
thing,'' Waddell said before boarding a flight for Orlando. ``We
have to find a way to resolve it. But to be honest with you, I
don't know how we respond at this point. I don't know who gives
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell had only a brief conversation with Kotlowitz early
Thursday and planned to talk to him again late Thursday night or
this morning. In the mean time, Stefan remained home in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The hangup in the three-year, $3.075 million deal is the bonus
structure. Kotlowitz is seeking to top last year's record deal for
rookies by Tampa Bay's Vincent Lecavalier. Waddell is looking to
tie some individual bonuses to team incentives.
</P>
<P>
   The day wasn't a total loss for Waddell. The Thrashers came to
terms with goalie Scott Langkow, leaving Stefan as the last
unsigned player. Langkow, acquired from Phoenix in an expansion
draft trade, signed a two-year, two-way deal with an option for a
third season that kicks in if he plays 45 NHL games. Langkow's NHL
salary was slightly raised from last year's $360,000. He will make
$125,000 to $150,000 in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   TV analyst hired
</P>
<P>
   Darren Eliot has been hired as a color commentator for televised
games on UPN Channel 69 and the proposed Turner South. He worked on
Anaheim radio broadcasts the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
