</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-PRICES-ART(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS LABOR DAY NEARS, GASOLINE PRICES ARE HIGHER THAN LAST YEAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Americans indulge in the last great driving
binge of summer, they are paying an average of 22 cents a gallon
more for gasoline than they were around Labor Day of 1998, says the
Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   The average retail price for regular unleaded gasoline was $1.23
cents a gallon as of Monday, compared with $1.01 on Aug. 31, 1998,
the department's Energy Information Administration said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices, which as recently as February were at an
average of 90 to 92 cents a gallon, have risen 12 cents a gallon
since June. The increases are being felt everywhere, although for a
variety of reasons gasoline continues to be most expensive in the
Far West and least expensive in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The American Automobile Association said that as of last week
the average per-gallon price for unleaded gasoline in New Jersey
was $1.17, compared with $1.32 in New York state and $1.37 in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the higher prices are not keeping people at home _
the Automobile Association expects nearly 35 million Americans to
travel 100 or more miles this weekend _ but they have produced
grumblings at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that we have to use our cars, have to get to work,''
Daniella Gobert complained the other day as she gassed her 1985
Oldsmobile at a Shell station in San Francisco, where the price of
regular unleaded has soared to more than $1.50 a gallon and the
premium price is flirting with $2. ``I don't believe we're getting
gas for cheap, if that's what they're saying.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``they,'' Ms. Gobert and legions of fellow complainers mean
the big oil companies. And, yes, the oil industry says gasoline is
still a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   To Mike Libbey, a spokesman for Chevron U.S.A., the complaints
reflect two misconceptions. ``One is that gasoline prices are
high,'' Libbey said, ``and the other is that we control all that.
If we controlled them, they'd stay up. But they go up, and they go
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The AAA said the average price for self-service regular unleaded
gasoline has simply returned to its levels of August 1996 and
August 1997, when it was almost exactly what it was a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The AAA gets its data from the Oil Price Information Service
newsletter, whose figures, because of sampling methods and timing,
were slightly different from the Energy Department's. The
association said the average increase from a year ago was about 18
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Discrepancies notwithstanding, the trend is unmistakable, and
people who work in or follow the oil industry offered several
reasons. For one, prices often rise before a summer holiday, when
demand goes up.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the 11 members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed March 23 to cut the production
of crude oil by 3 percent effective April 1. And the cartel
persuaded Norway, Mexico, Oman and Russian, four oil exporters that
do not belong to OPEC, to go along.
</P>
<P>
   The OPEC countries were reacting to an abundance of crude oil
that had driven down prices on the world markets.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last December, U.S. refiners paid just under $10 a barrel for
crude oil, the lowest price price since the Great Depression when
adjusted for inflation, according to Ron Planting, an American
Petroleum Institute expert on gasoline-price fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   By June, U.S. refiners were paying $16 a barrel, the effect was
being passed along the fuel chain, to American drivers. Now, crude
oil sells for about $20 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There has been grumbling even in Georgia where, despite the
price upsurge, self-service unleaded gasoline cost only $1.09 a
gallon in late August, the lowest average price in the country. ``I
don't like it,'' said Gregg Richey, who was gassing up in Atlanta.
``Gas is a major expense in Atlanta, where you're commuting long
distances.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason why Georgia has low prices is its tax of only 7.5
cents a gallon, the lowest state levy in the country. New Jersey's
state tax on gasoline is 14.5 cents a gallon, New York's is 29.8
cents and Connecticut's is 32 cents, the highest in the country.
(The federal tax is 18.4 cents.)
</P>
<P>
   California's state gasoline tax is 18 cents a gallon, and there
is an additional sales tax of 7 cents a gallon. Californians pay
some of the highest prices anywhere: $1.55 a gallon for
self-service regular unleaded, according to the Automobile
Association. Only Oregon, which has a state tax of 24 cents and
like New Jersey does not allow self-service, had a higher average
per-gallon price in late August, $1.56.
</P>
<P>
   California's strict air-quality rules, which demand
cleaner-burning gasoline that costs more to refine, also keep
prices high. Gasoline usually costs more in hilly San Francisco,
where service stations are relatively scarce because of zoning
restrictions and a shortage of suitable open land, than it does in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas F. Hogarty, an adjunct professor of economics at Virginia
Technical Institute who has studied the petroleum industry for many
years, said Asia's renewed economic prosperity, and the greater oil
consumption that goes with it, have pushed up crude oil prices. So
have several recent refinery fires and pipeline accidents in the
Far West, which curtailed supplies in the region and reduced the
oil available to other areas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The American Petroleum Institute and the individual oil
companies insist that gasoline is inexpensive compared with the
price of the many others things people need. The Consumer Price
Index published by the Labor Department's Bureau of Labor
Statistics supports their argument.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index for July showed that gasoline prices
had risen nearly 19 percent since December but were still 14.2
percent lower than they were in November 1990, after Iraq invaded
Kuwait, and lower than they were from October 1995 through April
1997.
</P>
<P>
   A comparison of gasoline prices to those of other commodities
tracked in the Consumer Price Index was striking. According to the
index, the cost of a wide range of goods and services used in
everyday life rose by two-thirds from a base period of 1982-84 to
July 1999. In other words, a shopping basket of goods that cost
$100 about 15 years ago would have cost $166.70 in July.
</P>
<P>
   But the price of gasoline was only 1.9 percent higher in actual
dollars than it was about 15 years ago. The same amount of gasoline
that cost $10 then would have cost $10.19 in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the recent price increases have upset some
truckers, whose diesel-fuel costs have also risen, and they have
produced calls for official investigations in some states,
including Oregon and Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Hogarty thinks prices will remain fairly stable and
could even decline again, as they typically do after a big travel
holiday. Historically, he said, the OPEC has had trouble keeping
discipline among its members, some of whom (Iran, Iraq, Kuwait)
have warred upon one another. If individual members cheat and
produce more oil, there could be another glut.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Hogarty conceded, another war in the Middle
East could send prices skyrocketing. Or perhaps something closer to
home, he suggested, saying, ``God forbid a huge hurricane should
hit some refineries along the Gulf Coast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
