r f BC-SUIT-SUIT_SFCHRON &LR;      09-02 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUIT-SUIT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Three D.A.s File Suit Against Pac Bell
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Three district attorneys filed a lawsuit against Pacific Bell
yesterday, alleging that the company gave customers false and
deceptive information to increase its sales of products and
services such as Caller ID, three-way-calling and inside-wiring
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In a suit filed in Alameda County Superior Court, district
attorneys from San Mateo, Alameda and Monterey counties said Pac
Bell is violating the state's unfair-business practices act and
should be forced to stop.
</P>
<P>
   The suit asks for at least $20 million in fines, plus
restitution for customers who were misled by Pac Bell into ordering
or changing a service. SBC Communications Inc., the parent company
of Pac Bell, also is named in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints in the suit are similar to ones lodged by
consumer groups against Pac Bell last year. Those complaints
prompted six days of hearings at the state Public Utilities
Commission in December, but no decision on that case has been
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell denied the allegations and said they merely rehash
old complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accusations being made here are nothing new. It's all been
litigated over there at the PUC,'' Pac Bell spokesman John Britton
said. ``We're kind of perplexed really that (the district
attorneys) wouldn't wait to see what the PUC would decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Lydia Villarreal, deputy district attorney for Monterey, said
the suit is independent of the PUC investigation and was prompted
by complaints from customers and consumer groups across California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the gravity of the problem and the enormity of the
continuing violations, we felt we had to take action,'' Villarreal
said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that:
</P>
<P>
   _To increase sales of Caller ID _ a box that hooks to a phone
and identifies the number of incoming calls _ Pac Bell hired a
telemarketing firm that allegedly misled customers about their
ability to have their numbers blocked on Caller ID systems.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell's sales of Caller ID have been slow because about 44
percent of Californians have requested ``complete blocking,'' which
prevents their own phone numbers from appearing on other peoples'
Caller ID boxes.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires that all phone companies offer complete
blocking as a free service. But the telemarketing firm, Business
Response Inc. of St. Louis, allegedly told Pac Bell customers that
complete blocking no longer existed or soon would be discontinued
and that they would have to switch to ``selective blocking,'' which
requires callers to dial 67 each time they make a call to block
their phone number from Caller ID boxes.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 customers switched from ``complete blocking''
to ``selective blocking'' following calls from BRI, said Thomas
Orloff, the Alameda County district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   After The Chronicle published a story about BRI in December, Pac
Bell canceled its contract with the telemarketer, saying it did not
condone the company's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday, the district attorneys produced internal Pac Bell
documents outlining a three-year marketing plan to ``overcome''
customer objections to Caller ID. Pac Bell stated that its goal was
to increase Caller ID penetration from 2 percent to 30 percent by
1999 _ which would increase the company's revenue by $210 million.
</P>
<P>
   One Pac Bell document stated that the company's goal was to
market selective blocking ``under the radar screen'' of consumer
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the evidence shows that the defendant elevated
corporate profits above the privacy interests of customers,''
Orloff said.
</P>
<P>
   BRI also was named as a defendant in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   _To sell more add-on features, the company allegedly directed
its employees to use misleading names such as ``The Basics'' and
``The Essentials'' for expensive calling packages with nonessential
features like three-way calling, call forwarding and distinctive
ringing.
</P>
<P>
   The suit said Pac Bell also directed service representatives to
make ``personal recommendations,'' supposedly based on an
individual's calling habits, that ``always end with the
recommendation that the consumer purchase more custom calling
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Britton said the name ``The Basics'' has been approved by the
PUC and that its use did not mislead customers.
</P>
<P>
   _The company attempted to increases sales of inside-wiring
insurance by failing to tell renters they did not need to purchase
it and by offering a cheaper inside-wiring plan only after
customers rejected a higher priced one.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also said Pac Bell failed to tell customers they can
get inside-wiring repairs done by companies other than Pacific
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said it is not Pac Bell's responsibility to inform
customers that they can go elsewhere for inside-wiring repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go down to Montgomery Ward to buy a washer-dryer, do they
tell me that I can also buy a washer-dryer at Sears? It's not our
responsibility to educate customers about all their options. It's a
competitive world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Pac Bell disputed all the charges, saying the
company did not mislead customers and has not engaged in deceptive
practices.
</P>
<P>
   But James Fox, San Mateo district attorney, said an extensive
investigation by the three counties proves that Pac Bell
systematically has been violating customers' rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pac Bell says, `The phone is your friend,' but the phone
company has not been a friend to consumers,'' Fox said. ``It's a
shame when corporate greed overcomes the obligations of a public
utility to protect the public.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
