r f BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT_S     09-02 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Microsoft Tabs Belluzzo to Head Net Units
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Tom Stein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Microsoft Corp. tapped former Silicon Graphics Inc. chief executive
Richard Belluzzo yesterday to run its Internet operations, just as
the company is poised to do battle over all things Web-related.
Belluzzo, 45, will take on the role of group vice president for
Microsoft's Consumer and Commerce Group, the unit charged with
spearheading the company's Internet efforts. Under Belluzzo's
purview will be the Microsoft Network, WebTV and all e-commerce
initiatives such as Expedia and Car Point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had some fits and starts as well as a lot of progress
in our Internet efforts,'' Microsoft President Steve Ballmer said
in a conference call yesterday. ``Rick (Belluzzo) is a great leader
and a focused and intense business manager ... who will complement
our online team.''
</P>
<P>
   Belluzzo will report directly to Ballmer, while Brad Chase and
Jon DeVaan, who formerly held the reigns of the Consumer and
Commerce Group, now will report to Belluzzo. Both Chase and DeVaan
were promoted from vice presidents to senior vice presidents
yesterday. Together, the three will form the core of Microsoft's
Internet division, which accounted for $2.4 billion of the
company's $19.7 billion in annual sales in fiscal year 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the opportunity to be part of Microsoft and
contribute to its online business,'' said Belluzzo. ``Brad and Jon
have laid out the foundation, and with my leadership, we plan to
extend that and deliver a rich consumer experience on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Belluzzo also pooh-poohed suggestions that he is not well-suited
to Microsoft because all his previous experience is with hardware
companies and not with software. ``I'll be drawing on my background
and experience of managing across lots of changing business
environments and business models,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining SGI less than two years ago, Belluzzo was a
leading light and potential CEO candidate at Hewlett-Packard, where
he worked for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that caught much of the high-tech industry by
surprise, Belluzzo bailed out of SGI last week, just weeks after
announcing his latest plan to turn around the troubled maker of
computer workstations. Analysts said Belluzzo had become
increasingly frustrated in his efforts to nurse SGI back to health.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry watchers believe that Belluzzo will face a similar
uphill battle at Microsoft, whose Internet division has been rocked
recently by executive defections and increased competition from the
likes of American Online and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft confirmed on Wednesday that Ben Silka, a
well-respected general manager in the Consumer and Commerce Group,
left the company to become director of information technology at
Amazon.com. Other departures this year include Steve Perlman, who
was president of WebTV, as well as Pete Higgins, who directed the
MSN community of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, Microsoft badly trails AOL in terms of Internet
service subscribers and the number of visitors to its Web
properties. And earlier this week, Sun Microsystems struck another
blow against Microsoft when it announced that it had acquired
software-maker Star Division Inc., and would start offering word
processing and spreadsheet applications for free over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This was interpreted by many as a direct attack on the Microsoft
Office software suite, which boasts 100 million customers and
accounts for roughly 40 percent of the company's total revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the threat from Sun, Ballmer said in the
conference call that Microsoft is working on its own ``Web-based
office productivity services, but we have no time table for that
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Parr, an analyst with International Data Corp., said
Microsoft appears to be moving away from Internet access and the
development of its own content and is concentrating more on
Internet software applications like instant messaging, e-mail and
electronic wallets.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, Microsoft still does not have a comprehensive
Internet strategy,'' Parr said. ``They still need to figure out
their role in the online world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
