</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-EBAY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 EBay Pulls Human Kidney Off Internet Auction Site
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By David Lazarus &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A human kidney was offered for sale on the Internet auction site
eBay, and the bidding went as high as $5.7 million before the
transaction was terminated yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an eBay prohibition against sales of body parts, this
also happens to be a violation of federal law, punishable by five
years in prison or a $50,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't monitor every item that goes on the site,'' said
Robert Chesnut, eBay's associate general counsel. ``Over 300,000
items go up every day.''
</P>
<P>
   If eBay had not been alerted by a user that a kidney was for
sale on the site, Chesnut admitted that it is possible the deal
could have gone through. He noted, however, that the whole thing
could have been a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, seven separate bids were received for the kidney
between August 26, when the auction commenced, and yesterday
morning, when the plug was pulled.
</P>
<P>
   The seller was identified only as ``hchero'' from Sunrise, Fla.
The minimum bid requested was $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fully functional kidney for sale,'' the item description read.
``You can choose either kidney. Buyer pays all transplant and
medical costs. Of course only one for sale, as I need the other one
to live. Serious bids only.''
</P>
<P>
   EBay said it was in contact with Florida law enforcement
authorities about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Had the sale been completed, it might have been tough for the
buyer to simply show up at a hospital with the kidney. Dr. Wade
Smith, chairman of the ethics committee at the University of
California at San Francisco Medical Center, said a tacit rule
exists among transplant surgeons not to perform operations
involving dubiously obtained organs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, we do not allow monetary gain from an
organ donation,'' he said. ``The system is well-designed to prevent
something like this from happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Roebuck, a spokesman for the California Transplant Donor
Network, agreed it would be virtually impossible for a kidney
transplant to occur in the United States outside established
channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a transplant to go through, a series of things need to
happen,'' he said. ``There's too much of a process that must take
place for something like that to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Roebuck acknowledged it is possible that the buyer of an
Internet-auctioned kidney might find a willing transplant surgeon
outside the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seller sounds like someone who knows there's a donor
shortage in this country and is taking advantage of the market,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from body parts, sales of all illegal goods are prohibited
by eBay. It is against the site's rules, for example, to offer a
nuclear bomb to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   But because users can list items without any screening, all
sorts of stuff ends up hitting the auction block alongside all
those Beanie Babies and Pez dispensers.
</P>
<P>
   To list an item on eBay, all a seller has to do is submit an
online form containing contact information, fill in the blanks for
the item's description and minimum bid sought, and pay a marginal
fee of no more than $2. The listing does not go through human hands
before finding its way to the Net.
</P>
<P>
   EBay has approximately 6 million regular users and has more than
2.6 million items up for auction.
</P>
<P>
   With such volume, the site relies on a ``community watch''
program whereby regular users police the various categories and
report any untoward activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We end hundreds of auctions every day,'' Chesnut admitted.
``It's not unusual for us to end 500 auctions in a day.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it would have been ``extraordinarily unlikely'' that
bidding on a human kidney would have closed without anyone spotting
it _ even though the kidney apparently was up for grabs for almost
an entire week before being pulled from the site.
</P>
<P>
   As of yesterday afternoon, the only kidney-related items for
sale included a steak and kidney pie ($20) and a 12-string
kidney-shaped guitar ($71).
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a teenager turned up on eBay auctioning off his
virginity to the highest bidder, but the transaction turned out to
be a prank.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a group of techies placed themselves up for sale for
$3.14 million _ which just happens to be the first three digits of
pi _ but withdrew the offer before bidding ended.
</P>
<P>
   Chesnut said there was no record of ``hchero'' offering any
other items for sale at eBay, and he did not know whether the
kidney seller had received a warning from the site about dealing in
prohibited goods.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat offenders will be suspended from the site, Chesnut said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
