<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT NAMES NEW LEADERS FOR TROUBLED NET BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Searching for a way to revive its beleaguered Internet business,
Microsoft Corp. named a new leadership team for its online group
yesterday and indicated that it would emphasize its technology
underpinnings and continue to move away from a media strategy.
</P>
<P>
   As anticipated, the company named Richard Belluzzo, a longtime
Silicon Valley hardware executive, as the new head of its Consumer
and Commerce Group. Belluzzo, who resigned in August as chairman
and chief executive of Silicon Graphics Inc. after a failed
turnaround effort at that struggling work station company, will
report directly to Microsoft president Steven Ballmer as group vice
president for the company's Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   The two longtime employees who have been leading the group, Brad
Chase and Jon DeVaan, have been promoted to the position of senior
vice president, Ballmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer declined to give significant details about the company's
strategy for catching America Online, the dominant Internet service
provider, and AT&AMP;T, whose Internet business, Worldnet, is also
larger than Microsoft's service, MSN. But he did give several hints
about the direction the company would take.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to focus on fewer things and do those things
well,'' he said. ``We're going to be unabashed about technology.
We're not a media company although we will develop media style
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Ballmer had been focusing on technology and on
controlling expenses to rein in the division's losses, estimated at
$500 million to $700 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really struck me today is when Steve said Microsoft was
going to rely on its strength as a technology company,'' said David
Readerman, a managing director at Thomas Weisel &AMP; Partners, a San
Francisco investment firm. ``The decision to bring Belluzzo was the
defining element in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part Belluzzo, who helped build Hewlett-Packard's laser
printer business as a longtime executive there, said he would rely
on his strengths in consumer businesses and his ability to master
the Internet's ``changing business models.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions, Ballmer appeared to step toward
closing the door on issuing a so-called tracking stock that would
reflect the value of the company's Internet business, saying that
although a final decision had not been made, there were no such
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer also acknowledged that a string of security flaws that
have plagued Microsoft in recent months _ including an episode this
week in which instructions were spread on the Internet for breaking
into accounts on its free e-mail service, Hotmail _ had hurt the
company's Internet brand. ``It's never good when your products fail
to to do what consumers want,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
