Lynne Thigpen, left, and Irma P. Hall, stars of ``Jar the Floor,''
at Second Stage. The actresses are receiving some of the best
reviews of their careers as a mother and daughter with plenty to
talk about. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- CARS-SAFETY, 09-02 -- Ford's
ill-fated Edsel had shifter push buttons mounted in the hub of the
steering wheel. Government regulations now require shifters to be
in steering columns or floor consoles. (Jim McCraw/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- WACO-RENO-FREEH, 09-02 --
Attorney General Janet Reno turns to the F.B.I. Director Louis
Freeh during a House hearing in 1997. In the early years, their
aides portrayed Reno and Freeh as one of the capital's perfect
power pairings. But officials who know them both said the image
never really matched the reality, and, in recent days, the
disclosures that the FBI failed to produce information from its
files about the use of inflammable tear gas during the 1993 assault
on the Branch Davidian compound has split open a jagged seam of
discontent, seriously dividing the two and their respective
agencies. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- GASOLINE-PRICES, 09-02 --
Americans using their cars to go on vacation prompted this 1963
Ford Country Squire Station Wagon ``concept car'', or prototype,
that transforms itself into a complete campsite with a dining tent,
rooftop sleeping tent, tailgate kitchen with gas stove and running
water. The car's roof doubles as a boat dock. the Push Button
Camper was conceived to be part of Ford's ``Recreational Fleet''
but was never actually offered for sale. As Americans prepare for
the last big long-weekend of summer, experts say the price of
gasoline is about 20 percent higher than it was a year ago. They
give two reasons: refinery fires and OPEC's renewed aggressive
pricing. (Ford Motor Company/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) DAVIS, Calif. -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- SCI-WINE-ORIGINS, 09-02
-- Chardonnay grapes growing at the University of California at
Davis. A scandal to shock wine connoisseurs to the last drop of
their being has been uncovered by the same kind of DNA test used in
paternity cases. The chardonnay grape, considered one of the
world's greatest wine varieties, is a cross between the princely
pinot and a grape deemed so coarse that it is no longer grown in
France, according to an analysis by American and French scientists.
(Carole Meredith/U.C. Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) VALLEJO, Calif. -- Sept. 2, 1999 --
ROLLER-COASTER-DEATHS, 09-02 -- Visitors to Six Flags Marine World
on last Friday lookup to the area of the Boomerang roller coaster
where a malfunction in the ride trapped some two dozen people days
earlier. The ride was closed while being inspected. A series of
fatal accidents on roller coasters and other thrill rides this
summer, including one last week in New Jersey, has the
amusement-park industry on the defensive. But an examination of the
deaths suggests they are more coincidence than the result of rides
getting faster, bigger, scarier. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DIX HILLS, N.Y. -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-SHOOTING,
09-02 -- Doris Busch-Boskey is assisted in leaving a funeral home
on New York's Long Island on Thursday. Busch-Boskey's son Gary
Busch, who was killed by New York City police Monday night after
authorities claimed he had attacked officers with a hammer, was
buried on Thursday. (Angel Franco/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- NY-SCHOOL-UNIFORMS, 09-02 --
Sheena Fray, 8, looks at uniforms earlier this week. Thousands of
students will head off to public elementary schools next week in
pleated jumpers, khakis and white button-down shirts as uniform
policy begins this school year in the city. (Nicole Bengiveno/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- KIDNEY-DONOR, 09-02
-- Marian Neal during an interview on Wednesday. Neal, an
unemployed woman who donated a kidney to a little boy she helped
care for, has been staying in a homeless shelter since being
evicted from a public housing project where she had been living in
violation of the rules. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS, 09-02 --
Angelo DelPriore pinches back some of the hundreds of annuals in
St. Leonard's Garden of Peace in North End. A volunteer, or more
accurately the volunteer, DelPriori spends at least two hours a day
hand-watering the garden so the thousands of tourists who come
through don't get soaked by sprinklers. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- GLF-RYDERCUP-SPENCE,
09-02 -- Bill Spence, head greens superintendent at The Country
Club, with his border collie and companion Emma. It would seem to
be the equivalent of starting out in the penthouse, so when Spence
tells you his first job in the industry was at Pebble Beach, he is
fully prepared for looks sent his way. (Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HARVARD, Mass. -- Sept. 2, 1999 --
IMPORTED-APPLES-ART-BOS, 09-02 -- Frank Carlson, of Carlson Apple
Orchards, examines his crop of McIntosh apples. Forget the drought.
It's the People's Republic of China that has New England apple
growers really worried. Looking to survive a glut partly caused by
a dramatic rise in Chinese apple production, local growers are
promoting the McIntosh apple as something as much a part of New
England as clam chowder. (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-BUSCH, 09-01 --
Netanya Ullman, Gidone Busch's fiancee, at a gathering of Orthodox
Jews in Brooklyn's Borough Park neighborhood on Tuesday. The police
officers who shot and killed Busch in Brooklyn on Monday evening
said Busch attacked them with a hammer outside his tiny basement
apartment. On that hammer, Busch, 31, a devoutly religious man who
prayed so loudly the neighbors complained, had carved the four
Hebrew letters signifying the name of God. (Edward Keating/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
