<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 09/02/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- SUB-TEN-USOPEN-5, 09-02 --
Unseeded American Jennifer Capriati digs out a backhand during her
match against Seda Noorlander of the Netherlands at the U.S. Open
on Thursday. Capriati came from behind to defeat Noorlander in
three sets, 5-7, 6-1, 6-4, to advance to the third round. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) OURU PRETO, Brazil -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 --TRAVEL-BRAZIL-2-COX, 09-02 -- The Capela do Padre Faria
(Chapel of Father Faria) in Ouro Preto dates from 1710. This city,
just 271 miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro, is known for its
ostentatious array of 18th-century Baroque art. (Wendell
Brock/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) OURU PRETO, Brazil -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 --TRAVEL-BRAZIL-1-COX, 09-02 -- The Capela do Padre Faria
(Chapel of Father Faria) in Ouro Preto dates from 1710. This city,
just 271 miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro, is known for its
ostentatious array of 18th-century Baroque art. (Wendell
Brock/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) ATLANTA -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 5 --
STYLE-JACKETS-COX, 09-02 -- Tailored at the waist and softly
unstructured at the hip, the roadster jacket offers a long straight
line that most women can wear. These days, lengths extend past the
knee or down to the ankle, providing a more dramatic and refined
feminine look than the traditional blazer. (Jean Shifrin/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-6, 09-02 --
Americans Venus, right, and Serena Williams pause for a chat during
their doubles match against Miho Saeki and Yuka Yoshida of Japan at
the U.S. Open on Thursday. The Williams sisters won their match.
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- WACO-RENO-FREEH-2, 09-02
-- Attorney General Reno and FBI Director Louis Freeh, left, just
before a hearing on Capitol Hill in July. In the early years, their
aides portrayed Reno and Freeh as one of the capital's perfect
power pairings. But officials who know them both said the image
never really matched the reality, and, in recent days, the
disclosures that the FBI failed to produce information from its
files about the use of inflammable tear gas during the 1993 assault
on the Branch Davidian compound has split open a jagged seam of
discontent, seriously dividing the two and their respective
agencies. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) DRESDEN, Germany -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 -- GERMANY-AMD-5-COX, 09-02 -- Michael Ashley, one of 30
Americans working at Advanced Micro Devices Inc.'s new plant in
Germany, says he's happy, though he confesses to missing American
football. ``It's been a great experience for me,'' he says, noting
that his first visit to Europe was a house-hunting expedition to
Dresden. (Bert Roughton Jr./Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) DRESDEN, Germany -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 -- GERMANY-AMD-4-COX, 09-02 -- A technician working in Fab
30's cleanroom. The $1.9 billion plant was built by Advanced Micro
Devices Inc. in Dresden. (AMD Saxony Manufacturing GmbH/Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) DRESDEN, Germany -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 -- GERMANY-AMD-3-COX, 09-02 -- The cutting edge,
copper-based Athlon microprocessor chip is Advanced Micro Devices
Inc.'s rock in the sling for its intended challenge of Intel Corp.,
the Goliath of chip makers. The chip is to be manufactured at Fab
30, the $1.9 billion plant built by AMD in Dresden. (AMD Saxony
Manufacturing GmbH/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) DRESDEN, Germany -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 -- GERMANY-AMD-2-COX, 09-02 -- Rising from transformed
farmland is an expansive new factory with a simple contemporary
design that would fit in nicely at any American industrial park.
Known as Fab 30, the plant was built by Advanced Micro Devices Inc.
(AMD) for $1.9 billion and bears a distinct resemblance to its
Austin, Texas, sister, Fab 25. (AMD Saxony Manufacturing GmbH/Cox
News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) DRESDEN, Germany -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 -- GERMANY-AMD-1-COX, 09-02 -- After nearly being destroyed
from Allied bombing at the end of World War II and enduring four
decades of Communist rule, Dresden is working hard to position
itself as the ``Silicon Valley of Saxony.'' Landing the $1.9
billion Fab 30 microprocessor chip-building plant (built by
Advanced Micro Devices Inc. of Texas) has been a key to the city's
success story. (Bert Roughton Jr./Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 5 --
BIZ-TOYS-R-US, 09-02 -- So far this year, Toys ``R'' Us has lost
four top managers. Its stock price has slipped. (Aaron Lee
Fineman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- INDIA-MISSIONARY, 09-02 --
Gladys Staines, background left, stands with her daughter Esther
and husband Graham Staines in a family photo. In the foreground are
the Staines two other children, Timothy, foreground left, and
Philip. An anti-Christian mob killed Graham Staines along with his
sons near Baripada, India, in January. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-4, 09-02 --
American Serena Williams enjoys a laugh during her match against
Jelena Kostanic at the U.S. Open on Thursday. Williams, the No. 7
seed, straight-setted the 128th-ranked Croatian qualifier, 6-4,
6-2, to advance to the third round. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-3, 09-02 --
American Monica Seles during her match against Italy's Silvia
Farina at the U.S. Open on Thursday. Seles, the No. 4 seed,
straight-setted Farina, 6-2 6-3, to advance to the third round.
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- CLINTON-HOUSE, 09-02
-- The Clintons, who are vacationing here and campaigning for Mrs.
Clinton's expected candidacy for the U.S. Senate seat from New
York, released a statement on Thursday saying that they had entered
into a contract for this five-bedroom house, built in 1899, on a
verdant 1.1-acre lot. The $1.7-million Georgian colonial, in New
York's Westchester County, was secured in cash by their chief
fundraiser, Terry McAuliffe. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-2, 09-02 --
American Andre Agassi lunging for a high backhand against Axel
Pretzsch of Germany at the U.S. Open on Thursday. Agassi, the No. 2
seed, demolished Pretzsch in straight sets, 6-3, 6-2, 6-1. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) ATLANTA -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- KING-TOUR-ATLANTA-NYTR,
09-02 -- Martin Luther King Jr. was born in a second story bedroom
in the house at left on Jan. 15,1929. The two-story Queen Anne
style house, located at 501 Auburn Avenue, was built in 1895. The
National Park Service has placed information markers across the
street from the house detailing the history. At left is the
Ebenezer Baptist Church where King preached. Both structures are
now two of several sites on a tour of Martin Luther King's
birthplace. (Linda Conley, The Spartanburg Herald-Journal/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-1, 09-02 --
American Andre Agassi lunging for a high backhand against Axel
Pretzsch of Germany at the U.S. Open on Thursday. Agassi, the No. 2
seed, demolished Pretzsch in straight sets, 6-3, 6-2, 6-1. (Chang
W. Lee/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ISRAEL-LIKUD-B&AMP;W, 09-02 --
Ariel Sharon during an interview in 1996. Sharon, the aging but
pugnacious former warrior, captured the leadership of the
opposition Likud Party in primaries tonight, replacing Benjamin
Netanyahu who quit politics when he lost his bid to be re-elected
Prime Minister in May. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- BUSH-EDUC, 09-02 -- Gov.
George Bush of Texas listens to questions from first graders during
a visit to Bennett-Q Elementary School on Thursday. Bush, the
Republican presidential candidate, said Thursday that federal funds
should be confiscated from the worst-performing schools and made
available to parents for private education, tutoring or ``whatever
offers hope.'' (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) RUMSON, N.J. -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 5
-- INVEST-WITH-WILBY, 09-02 -- Whether paddling in a New Jersey
creek, sailing to Bermuda or allocating assets worldwide, William
L. Wilby feels sure of the way. Wilby, 55, a former Federal Reserve
economist, has steered clear of the top-down economic analysis
favored by many global equity managers when allocating assets
around the world. ``I'm a theme-based, out-of-favor growth
investor,'' he says. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) ST. PETERSBURG, Russia -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., SEPT. 5 -- RUSSIAN-RARE-BOOKS, 09-02 -- Pytor Suspytsin at
his Russian publishing house, Rare Book of St. Petersburg.
Suspytsin, who gave up an export-import business, says he wants
``the atmosphere of a monastery'' in working to revive a tradition
of creating books so exquisite that each is a work of art.
(Jacqueline Mia Foster/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN MATEO, Calif. -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 -- VIDEO-GAME-DESIGNERS, 09-02 -- David T. Glenn, an
architect who was drawn into computer-game design by the industry's
need for traditional art skills, has been creating scenes for
Diablo II, the sequel to the hit game from Blizzard Entertainment.
Software for interactive games generated sales of $5.4 billion in
1998, according to the NPD Group. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 5 --
SENIORS-INTERNET, 09-02 -- Betty Fox and her grandson, David, in
1991. With the help of a son who had given her a WebTV and who
works in the technology field, she started her own site
(www.grandmabetty.com) for people over 50. It went online in
September 1998 and contains original material plus hundred of links
to other sites, all selected by Mrs. Fox based on what she thinks
are its visitors' interests. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 5 --
CARSMART-BMW-TOURBIKE, 09-02 -- BMW's K1200LT, the new absolute
ruler of the touring bike class. It is not simply a two-wheeled
car, but a two-wheeled BMW 740iL. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 5 --
ABOUT-CARS-BMW, 09-02 -- The BMW 3-Series coupe is in no way a wild
departure from the sedan in matters stylistic and mechanical. But
it is by no means an insignificant car, just as no piece in chess
is insignificant. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1999 -- JAR-THEATER-2, 09-02 --
From left, Welker White, Linda Powell, Irma P. Hall and Lynne
Thigpen in ``Jar the Floor,'' at the nonprofit Second Stage. This
serious family comedy by Cheryl L. West has been extended until
Sept. 12, and there is talk of a longer, commercial run at a larger
theater. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
