<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-PUC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 PUC Presses On With PG&AMP;E Probe
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Kenneth Howe &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
In the latest round of a regulatory power struggle, the California
Public Utilities Commission yesterday voted to continue its
investigation of last year's Pacific Gas and Electric power outage
that cut electricity to a million people, mostly in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, under political pressure, the PUC began to
consider a move to shut down its probe, leaving any further action
to the recently formed Independent System Operator.
</P>
<P>
   Since electricity deregulation reached the state last year, the
ISO, based in Folsom (Sacramento County), has been the state's
electric grid operator.
</P>
<P>
   In April, The ISO completed its own investigation and fined PG&AMP;E
$440,000 for the debilitating blackout, an amount consumer groups
characterized at the time as ``paltry.''
</P>
<P>
   In its decision yesterday, the PUC said it had ``the authority
and the obligation to investigate the outage'' but would
collaborate with the ISO. The PUC said it would hold hearings on
the matter beginning November 23. The seven-hour power outage in
December cost the local economy an estimated $400 million in
damages, according to a report commissioned by the PUC.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups and some local politicians, notably San
Francisco City Attorney Louise Renne, had urged the PUC to continue
its probe and not delegate its public-protection duties to the
semiprivate ISO.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, PG&AMP;E professed to be satisfied with the decision.
``It the PUC wants to collaborate with the ISO, that's fine,'' said
a company spokesman. ``We just don't want to be a political
football between these two agencies. We are working to make sure
customers receive energy safely and reliably.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2135EDT &QL; 
