</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SELES FEELS WINDY BLAST FROM PAST
</HEADLINE>
   (With TEN-USOPEN, TEN-USOPEN-AGASSI) 
(rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Somewhere along the line, she lost the Woody
Woodpecker giggle that punctuated her thoughts both profound and
trivial. She is a grown-up.
</P>
<P>
   After six years of torment, Monica Seles is at peace with just
about everything but the little cyclones whirling around Arthur
Ashe Stadium _ at least when she is playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``One side, you're just so much wind to wind,'' Seles said
Thursday. ``The other side, you're so into the wind. I've never
played on a single court in my life that has this much wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles made her comments after beating Silvia Farina of Italy,
6-2, 6-3, in the second round of the U.S. Open. She is quite
content to play in the wake of Hingis and Davenport and the
assorted Williamses, but she just does not like playing in her own
personal nor'easter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really weird,'' Seles said ``If you open the doors down
where the level is'' _ meaning courtside _ ``then there's no wind.
But if the doors are closed, the wind just gets stuck, and it's
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows what is truly terrible. She was stabbed in the back on
a court in 1993. Her father, who was her coach and her friend, died
in the spring of 1998. And this spring she watched on television as
NATO bombs destroyed the Danube bridges she crossed in her
childhood in Novi Sad in northern Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The wind is not so terrible.
</P>
<P>
   There is a history to the swirling gusts just south of Flushing
Bay. When the Jets played football in Shea Stadium, a quarterback's
bullet passes swerved like Phil Niekro's knuckleball. Visiting
teams shrugged and ran the ball on their annual visit to the cave
of the winds, but Richard Todd had to play half his season there.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible the same wayward winds have been trapped in the
towering new tennis stadium?
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a bowl effect,'' Jay Snyder, the tournament
director, said Thursday. ``The wind gets in at the top and it moves
downward. Sometimes the direction at the bottom is totally
different from the way the flags are blowing.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Snyder said, he had not heard any complaints about the
wind _ although, as part of his job he does hear complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you feel you're in a hurricane,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Snyder said he would look into the effect of
opening or shutting the four doors at court level. Seles was hardly
making a federal case out of it. She was just happy to have
something so mundane to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I enjoy it more than a year ago,'' Seles said,
``because probably the last four weeks of this summer, for the
first time in my life, I really have no outside problems. And it's
been really nice. If I can just have this for the next two years,
I'd be really happy.''
</P>
<P>
   She can look ahead to at least two more years of tennis, even
though her father is not there to guide her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly miss him at the tennis court and at my practices,''
Seles said. ``It's just really hard to find direction, where my
tennis game should be leading, where my dad would lead me.''
</P>
<P>
   She gave credit to Jimmy Arias, who is coaching her here but
will be going back on the over-35 circuit. She travels with her
brother, Zoltan, and a male hitting partner, and she insisted: ``I
really never enjoyed playing matches, even as a youngster. I just
love to practice and drill and that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't she enjoy matches?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hate the whole thought that one is better than the
other,'' Seles said. ``It drives me nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not correlate with the smiling-shark persona Seles
exuded when she was not wounded or in mourning. She always seemed
quite delighted at putting opponents away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe as a child, that's how I was brought up,'' she
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Does she lack a killer instinct?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' Seles said. ``It's survival out there. If I
don't, then the other person will, so you go into that automatic
mode. You have no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles was asked if she was too nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes am,'' she said, laughing for one of the few times.
``I've been working on that.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she has learned to say no to people making demands on
her time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just part of growing up, I think,'' she said. ``Not be such a
pleaser.''
</P>
<P>
   The language and the poise suggested a woman who has come
through fire and rain. What can a little wind do to her?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
