<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9183 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-ADVERSITY-     09-02 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ADVERSITY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The voice in the crowd _ what was left of it, anyway _ was as crisp
and sharp as one of the New York Mets' many hits in yet another
series lost against one of the National League's best teams.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You guys are going to get knocked out in the first round of
the playoffs again!'' the fan yelled during the late innings of the
Astros' 17-1 loss on Monday. ``That's if you even make the
playoffs!''
</P>
<P>
   While Joe Fan may prove to be psychic in the coming weeks, it
doesn't take a crystal ball to see the reality of the Astros'
season.
</P>
<P>
   It's right there in bold print in newspapers across the country.
Flip to the baseball page, focus on the NL Central Division
standings, and notice where the Astros are _ and where they have
been for most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It is indeed lonely at the top, and that's exactly where the
Astros have been for 126 of the 149 days of the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   But on the heels of last year's franchise-record 102 victories
and expectations that 1999 might be even better, somehow the
Astros' 95-win pace hasn't been enough to get all of the fans'
attention. Perhaps Houston sports fans spoil quicker than milk.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' roster is among the most injury-ravaged in baseball.
The Astros have used the disabled list 16 times, which explains the
majority of their 28 roster transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Quite frankly, the Astros aren't interested in using injuries as
an excuse, and with a .585 winning percentage, who needs excuses?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't get to where you want to get, you might say, What
if this or what if that?'' said center fielder Carl Everett, who
missed 20 games with an injury earlier this year and currently is
nursing a sore groin. ``But if you live by hypotheticals, you're
not going to get far. You have to live for what is, and that's what
we're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can say what they want, but the other teams (in the NL
Central) have been chasing us all year. I could see if we were down
and trying to climb back up, but everyone is chasing us. We just
have to keep playing good baseball from here on out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros left Thursday for a seven-game trip to Montreal and
Philadelphia. When they take the field against the Expos tonight,
they will have a 1{-game lead over the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   But you wonder if there would be much of a race if the Astros
had not played part _ or all _ of the season without Moises Alou,
Ken Caminiti, Ricky Gutierrez, Richard Hidalgo, Derek Bell and
Everett, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one said this was going to be easy,'' Caminiti said.
``We've gone through a lot this year, but we've battled and we're
still in first place. We're going through a little bit of a rough
time right now, but we just have to get out of it, and we will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have lost 12 of their last 22 games, including seven
of nine against the only decent teams _ the Braves and Mets _ they
have played during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in the way we're playing,'' manager Larry
Dierker said. ``But I have to be realistic. We don't have our whole
team. At the same time, we have just a few days left to win another
division title, and we're not going to do it if we don't start
playing better. On the other side of the coin, we could be losing
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Astros were losing four of six to the Mets over the
past 10 days, the Reds dropped five of six to the Braves _ so the
Astros actually gained a game in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of things to overcome and deal with this
season,'' second baseman Craig Biggio said. ``It's been a total
team effort, and we're where we are because of that. We still have
long way to go, but some of the younger guys we've had to play are
getting more experience and more confidence every day, and that's
good to see.''
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to note that in its four years of existence,
the NL Central has been won by teams averaging 90 wins. The Astros
could lose 16 of their last 27 games and still finish with 90
victories. Of course, the Reds would have to go into a tailspin,
too, for 90 victories to win the Central in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great group of players, and if we don't win it, the
excuse is going to be that we don't have a full team,'' Everett
said. ``But to me, you can't make any excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of little things are what has caused us to lose a lot of
games, and if you ask me, those things could be avoided. I'm
pleased with the season and the players. We've given everything we
can. I give no excuses. Everyone has picked everyone up.''
</P>
<P>
   And if they can continue to do so for the next 27 games, a third
consecutive division title is within the grasp of the Astros _
regardless of all the injuries and adversity that have defined the
1999 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
