s f BC-CONTRARY-COLUMN-$ADV0     09-02 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTRARY-COLUMN-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T CODDLE FARMERS. BUY THEM OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(jt) 
 By DANIEL AKST    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I live in a rural part of the Hudson Valley, where the weather
this summer has made me think I'm back in Southern California, my
previous home. Until some modest recent rains, the drought had
produced a landscape of lion-colored meadows and hillsides
reminiscent of the Santa Ynez Valley, near Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   The local farmers think this is bad news, and the federal
government has declared it a disaster, making farmers in designated
areas eligible for low-cost loans to help them through their
drought losses. The trouble, Jim Czub, a farmer in Schaghticoke,
N.Y., told Reuters, is that ``not only are we in drought, but those
of us who do have something, it isn't worth anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Far be it from me to take from the pockets of hard-working
neighbors, but shouldn't the drought be seen as a boon that the
government has no business mitigating? Normal rainfall, after all,
would mean even more overproduction of farm commodities, leading to
even lower prices and presumably more troubles for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The drought bailout, in fact, threatens to make things worse by
paying some farmers to produce just as Uncle Sam is contemplating
paying others not to. Last month, the Republican-controlled Senate
put aside its budgetary scruples to adopt a staggering $7.4 billion
farm aid package in response to low farm prices, after rejecting an
$11 billion Democratic alternative.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, neither party seems interested in alienating farmers
anywhere. And with Hillary Rodham Clinton the likely Democratic
candidate for Senator from New York, it shouldn't be surprising
that the executive branch has not chosen this time and place to
deviate from the government's record of irrational agricultural
interventions. So it's more of the same, even though the
never-ending need of American farmers, the world's most productive,
for federal help arises not from drought or global markets, but
from the bailouts, tax breaks and legal cartels that have come
before.
</P>
<P>
   But why just farmers? How can our leaders stand by as umbrella
manufacturers and raincoat companies, to cite just two examples,
struggle to stay afloat during the drought? Has anyone in
Washington tried selling aluminum gutters in this weather?
</P>
<P>
   And what about other kinds of droughts? For years, Americans
have watched TV instead of reading. How about low-interest loans
for writers afflicted by the drought of literacy? Things are so
tough that I've considered putting some of my 4.2 acres into
agricultural production. Not in hopes of selling produce, of course
_ just long enough for the Department of Agriculture to pay me to
take it back out again. Or could I just skip this step and go right
to the drought aid?
</P>
<P>
   But let's be realistic. Agricultural interests have too much
clout not to get tons of government money. Still, there may be a
better way to give it. Instead of paying drought aid or crop
support, why not just offer to buy out farmers altogether?
</P>
<P>
   Such a program would accomplish several goals, however dubious,
that everyone seems to favor. For one thing, it would help farmers
raise prices by taking land out of production. (If, like most
Americans, you buy food instead of growing it, tough luck.)
</P>
<P>
   But the plan would also be good for farmers' psyches, since it
could wean them from the seemingly bottomless public trough at
which agriculture has been feeding these many years. As a bonus, we
could reduce suburban sprawl by putting the former farmland into a
perpetual conservation trust. Communities could tap it to create
parks or wildlife preserves, or even community gardens _ as long as
the gardeners didn't dare try selling what they grew.
</P>
<P>
   Too expensive, you say? Hardly, given what we already spend to
make the problem worse. In one 10-year period, from 1986 to 1995,
federal farm policy cost taxpayers and consumers $370 billion,
enough to buy every farm in 41 states, according to James Bovard, a
critic of the policy who wrote the 1989 book ``Farm Fiasco.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, buying farms outright would save money. We could
even pay farmers over something like 20 years, the way we pay
lottery winners once they've read the fine print. Both would still
consider themselves lucky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
