<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-KOREA-DAEWOO-ART-2TAK     09-02 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-DAEWOO-ART-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DAEWOO'S PATH, TWILIGHT   OF KOREAN CONGLOMERATES 
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUPYONG, South Korea _ Transported by the whispers of workers
and housewives, a sense of impending doom is descending on this
auto factory town, whose fortunes have always marched in lockstep
with those of Daewoo Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the headlines have been filled with worrisome, if
hard-to-comprehend, reports of a showdown pitting heavily indebted
Daewoo, the nation's second-largest industrial conglomerate,
against the government and the company's many creditors. Finally,
last week came news so blunt that no one could mistake its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day before yesterday was payday, but for the first time we've
ever seen, no salaries were paid,'' said a young mother of three,
who lives in this company town, an hour's drive northwest of Seoul,
in a vast thicket of Daewoo-owned high-rise apartments a stone's
throw from the car factory where her husband has worked for seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there are rumors that no bonuses will be paid,'' she said,
asking not to be identified. ``What can I say except that this is a
very difficult time for everyone here. We are all afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to meet the payments on its $47 billion in debt _
more than the entire national debt of Poland or Malaysia _ Daewoo
was dismembered through a government-brokered plan in August. As
the woman here spoke quietly, the company was being ordered to
comply with a government-designed debt repayment program that
effectively stripped it of control over its own finances.
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the moment he came to power in elections in 1997,
President Kim Dae-jung has been waging a battle to restructure the
giant, octopus-like conglomerates that in a single generation had
helped transform a poor country into the world's 11th-largest
economy, only to thrust South Korea into a major debt crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Daewoo's effective demise, and similar restructuring
plans being forced upon its sister conglomerates _ globally
familiar names like Hyundai, the largest, Samsung, LG and SK _ many
Korean and foreign investors have begun to say that the twilight of
the nation's conglomerates, or chaebol, is finally becoming a
reality.
</P>
<P>
   The changes introduced by Kim's government include the breakup
of these huge enterprises into a collection of much smaller units
that must be run for the first time as totally separate companies.
</P>
<P>
   This means the ending of cross subsidization of weak industries
by strong ones, and of a pattern of borrowing in which companies
within the chaebol that have healthy balance sheets obtain capital
for others in the red.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, it means an eventual end to the days
when the country's industrial chairmen wielded total, and often
totally secret, decision-making power over their sprawling empires,
even though they controlled as little as 5 percent of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   The government has ordered all industrial companies to take on
outside directors, gradually building to majorities of their
corporate boards. The new measures also prohibit companies from
sharing executives or directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has been walking a very fine line,'' said Chung
In-moon, a political scientist at Yonsei University. ``Pushing too
hard on the chaebol could severely damage the Korean economy, while
not pushing hard enough would mean losing a historic opportunity
for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has already scored one huge victory in this struggle,
limiting the power of the chairmen as it never has been before,''
he added. ``This represents a brave new world for Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   While some of the country's chaebol, notably Daewoo, are widely
seen as resisting the changes sweeping over the economy, others
appear to be moving quickly to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to reform these enterprises,'' said Park Se-yong,
chairman of Hyundai. ``Not only because of the reasons the
government has asked us to do so, but because these changes will
serve as the basis for us being better competitors. Even the
chaebol have to live up to the principle of being willing to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   These huge conglomerates have been central to South Korea's
nearly ballistic economic ascent _ and to its recent crisis. Their
sheer scale is breathtaking. In terms of their impact within the
country, the largest could be likened to the product of an
imaginary merger between General Motors and General Electric, with
steel, computer chip and shipmaking thrown in for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   But as South Korea's economy took off, becoming an exporter of
cars and consumer electronics, steel and supertankers, this breadth
concealed a glaring lack of depth. Korean products tended to mimic
their competitors' rather than be innovative. Other problems ranged
from poorly established brand names to a reputation for stodgy
design and spotty quality that caused some to derisively refer to
the country as the ``land of almost right.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, though, the conglomerates' growth was made
possible only through heavy protectionism and continuous borrowing.
This necessitated a supportive, even pliant government and a
favorable international economic environment.
</P>
<P>
   What started out in the early 1970s as a system of force-fed
industrialization led by President Park Chung-hee ended up as a
system in which successive governments became virtual hostages of
huge, debt-laden conglomerates. Korean officials gave birth to the
accumulation of debt: A small number of entrepreneurs were
virtually ordered to start export industries and were given
government-guaranteed and heavily subsidized loans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their overwhelming importance to the economy and to
employment, these enterprises, it was felt, could not be allowed to
fail. The story of Daewoo, founded by Kim Woo-choong in 1967 with a
$10,000 family loan is, in this regard, typical.
</P>
<P>
   Within eight years, the company had gone from being a small
textile-trading business to an industrial conglomerate with 35,000
employees. It would soon boast the world's largest shipyard, and
earlier this year counted 100,000 employees and $80 billion in
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo's dizzying rise mirrored the seemingly miraculous quality
of South Korea's ride up the economic ladder. In the late 1960s,
the country was still emerging from the devastation of the war with
North Korea from 1950 to 1953.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to imagine the extent to which almost nothing
existed here when I first came,'' said Peter Bartholemew, an
American shipbuilder who has worked in South Korea for over 30
years. ``There were a little bit of textiles here, but basically
Korea had no manufacturing. There were no banks, no real
businessmen and very few people who spoke any foreign languages,
except Japanese, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost totally dependent upon aid from the United States, the
Korean economy received an unexpected boost from the Vietnam War,
which sprouted a number of industries that supplied the U.S.
military. The country's turn of luck and the easy money for
industry arranged by the government created a habit of success, and
though it would take years for it to show, bred hubris as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Daewoo, one of South Korea's spectacular success
stories, also proved to be perhaps the most spectacularly egregious
case of failure. In the midst of the Asian financial crisis of
1997, even as managing its own huge debt was becoming nearly
impossible, the conglomerate pressed ahead with expansion plans,
opening an opening an expensive new automobile factory in Vietnam
and buying a troubled Korean car maker, Ssangyong Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big ship never sinks,'' Kim, Daewoo's chairman, declared
last year. Early this year, however, he found himself unable to
meet the payments of the creditors, who responded to the company's
ballooning debt by imposing shorter and shorter terms on their
loans.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Since then, although Kim has become famous for wriggling out of
difficult situations, he has been forced to submit to a government
program that will leave him with six auto-related companies of the
conglomerate's more than 30 original affiliates. Even Daewoo
Motors, long his crown jewel, desperately needs a foreign partner
with deep pockets for it to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in this country say that Daewoo's founder, who
declined a request for an interview, felt that the government was
bluffing and would come to the conglomerate's rescue in its
struggle with its creditors to keep it from failing. According to
this line of thinking, a default would cripple the economy by
destroying South Korea's image of creditworthiness, and the
collapse of Daewoo would create domestic unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, Kim again signaled his government's
unwillingness to cover the company's overseas debts, throwing his
weight behind a complicated debt workout plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, there was a myth here that some companies were
too big to fail,'' said Hak Kuh-joh, a senior economic adviser to
the president. ``This myth is being shattered, and soon everyone
will recognize it.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's workers, who were indoctrinated for decades to
regard their corporate employers as their large extended family,
watched bitterly last year as the crisis everyone here calls simply
IMF, after the International Monetary Fund, seemed to strike
everyone hard except for the leaders of the country's
conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even though many sense the end of an era when the country's
industries were growing by leaps and bounds and stores filled
almost exclusively with Korean brands fed national pride, few are
shedding tears for the conglomerate's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crisis came about as a result of the monopolization of
information and of decision-making power, and for allowing that, we
have no one to blame but ourselves,'' said Han Ae-tack, 35, a car
plant worker and union official who showed a visitor around
Daewoo's gigantic housing project in Pupyong. ``Now the foreigners
with lots of capital are salivating as they prepare to swallow us
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
