<HEADER>
A9189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BOEING-LABOR-(TRIMS)-     09-02 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-LABOR-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGES FOR BOEING AFTER UNION APPROVES PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boeing Co.'s largest union voted overwhelmingly Wednesday night
to accept a three-year contract, averting a strike that would have
dealt a blow to Boeing's efforts to recover from a financial
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Of the votes cast by members of the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers, which represents 44,300 of
Boeing's 207,000 employees, 86 percent, or 26,842, were for the
contract. A simple majority was required for passage.
</P>
<P>
   Both the union and the company hailed the results, which headed
off what would have been the third walkout by the machinists in the
last 10 years. ``With this contract, the company and the union must
move forward together to capture productivity gains and
significantly improve the company's financial performance and
growth,'' said Peter Conte, a Boeing spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   That Boeing still faces large challenges was made evident
Thursday, when it announced that it was taking a $225 million
charge in the third quarter after losing crucial campaigns to sell
F-15 jet fighters to Greece and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Boeing announced a $45 million charge and
layoffs of 7,000 workers in St. Louis after Greece chose the F-16
made by Lockheed Martin Corp. over the F-15. The company said that
the additional charge reflected money it had invested in parts for
24 fighters it hoped to sell to Israel, which also chose to buy the
F-16 instead.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing stated that ``there is a limited near-term market'' for
the F-15, though it hopes that the U.S. Air Force will order some
this year, keeping the production line active for possible future
sales.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The company also said that the latest charge and the new labor
contract, which the company and the union said would make the
machinists the best-paid workers in the aerospace industry, would
not affect the existing estimates of future profits.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were uncertain whether the charge, which amounts to 17
cents a share, meant that they should lower their earnings
estimates for this year, which average $2 a share, according to
First Call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that what Boeing is telling us is that somewhere
else in the company there is another $225 million that we didn't
tell you about,'' said Joseph F. Campbell, a managing director at
Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has exceeded Wall Street expectations in each of the last
two quarters. But those expectations are much diminished in the
wake of production turmoil that began two years ago at Boeing's
flagship passenger jet division. That has resulted in lackluster
profits for the company at a time when demand for its jets has been
at a record high.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing plans to deliver a record 620 commercial airplanes this
year but promises profit margins of just 5 percent on projected
revenue of $58 billion. Some analysts and investors think that
Boeing's chairman Philip Condit felt he had little choice but to
give the machinists what they wanted because a strike would have
disrupted the company's delicate financial recovery.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This is a company that has come off a two-year disaster and
doesn't want to upset Wall Street expectations,'' said Steve
Binder, an aerospace analyst at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract raises hourly wages for machinists nearly 16
percent over three years, to an average of $24.35 an hour. The
contract also raises retirement benefits 25 percent and contains a
one-time 10 percent bonus that amounts to an average of $4,400 a
worker.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing abandoned an attempt to introduce weekend
shifts that would have reduced overtime payments, and it failed to
get the union to agree to have its members help shoulder the cost
of health insurance. The company also agreed not to lay off any
workers as a result of a decision to contract out some work to
other manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors were not too concerned about the
increased wages, a large portion of which will be passed on to
Boeing's airline customers in the form of escalation clauses in
their sales contracts. But they worried that by giving in to the
union on the issue of weekend work and subcontracting, Condit had
forsaken two important tools the company needed to increase its
efficiency as he has promised to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface this pact seems to limit Boeing's ability to
achieve large productivity gains,'' Binder said.
</P>
<P>
   The union, on the other hand, had exactly the opposite concerns.
While the leaders strongly endorsed the new contract, which Boeing
submitted early Saturday, they were disappointed that they did not
get more firm job guarantees from the company.
</P>
<P>
   An opposition faction within the union picked up on that theme
and campaigned against ratification, complaining that the
negotiators did not secure strong enough guarantees of job security
and did not win cost-of-living increases for retirees.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, most union members thought that the offer was
the best deal they were going to get without enduring a costly
walkout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
