<HEADER>
A9191 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CBS-VIACOM-ART-NYT &LR;      09-02 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-VIACOM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS AND VIACOM IN TALKS ON TV STATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds. note: this story is on the Times business front page) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viacom Inc. and CBS Corp. have held discussions in recent weeks
about a deal that could involve their television stations _
possibly in some type of merger _ several executives in the
entertainment industry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Like a number of companies with television-station holdings, CBS
and Viacom are seeking ways to benefit from a recent ruling by the
Federal Communications Commission that allows a company to own two
television stations in the same market under certain circumstances.
That ruling opens the way for cost savings and programming
flexibility not previously available to owners of television
stations.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has 15 television stations, with the acquisition of one more
pending. Viacom owns 19 stations. In five markets, both own a
station.: Dallas, Boston, Miami, Philadelphia and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   A deal to merge all the stations would face an obstacle. If CBS,
for example, were to buy all Viacom's stations, the reach of its
outlets would exceed the FCC's limits. The agency allows a single
company to own stations that reach up to 35 percent of the U.S. TV
market; CBS is already nudging that limit.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom and CBS are not the only companies in discussions and
both may also be in talks with other companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you took the 10 leading media companies since the Federal
Communications Commission decision, everybody has talked to
everybody more than before because there is so much more
opportunity for deals,'' said one industry expert.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Viacom and CBS would not comment on the possibility
of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Among other media companies, Barry Diller, the chairman of USA
Networks, has been reported to be in discussions with Walt Disney
Co.'s ABC network about a possible merger of television stations.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes the possibility of a deal between Viacom and CBS
particularly interesting, analysts say, is speculation that merger
talks have gone beyond simply the television station business to
include the two companies overall.
</P>
<P>
   Such a plot would have great appeal on Wall Street. The
companies could not only combine a number of their television
stations but their radio stations, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Both also have interests in music television: Viacom owns MTV,
and CBS owns Gaylord Broadcasting, which owns the Nashville
Network. And both are underleveraged, so that a merger would leave
them able to continue making other acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue, however, media executives said privately, was
management control. Some investors would favor the deal because
Sumner Redstone, who controls Viacom, is 76 years old and has no
heir apparent. A merger with CBS would assure that its chairman,
Mel Karmazin, would provide seasoned leadership into the future.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Redstone has shown no sign of slowing down,
and some executives who know Karmazin, himself a tough-minded
executive, cannot imagine that he would want to report to Redstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could never live in the same house,'' said one Wall
Street executive who knows both men. Another said he felt that
Viacom was more likely to strike a deal that would leave Redstone
in clearer management control.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom's own situation is particularly complex since it has
begun the UPN Network together with Chris-Craft Industries, which
itself owns 10 television stations. For several years, analysts who
follow Chris-Craft have hoped that the chairman, Herbert Siegel,
would either sell it or enter a joint venture with another company.
But he has seemed unwilling to make a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Siegel is being offered a high, inside pitch with bases loaded
because the new duopoly rules make his stations much more valuable,
and it is up to him to swing,'' said Mario Gabelli, chief
investment officer of Gabelli Asset Management, whose funds are
major shareholders in Chris-Craft.
</P>
<P>
   Chris-Craft also controls BHC Inc. and United Television Inc.,
both of which own television stations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
