</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIV-CRIME03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio univeristy to release names of students charged with
violent crimes
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The University of Dayton plans to start releasing
the names of students who commit rape, assault and other violent
crimes on campus.
</P>
<P>
   The new procedures, which began with the start of classes last
week, reverse a long-standing policy that had shielded the results
of cases brought before the UD internal disciplinary board.
Sanctions against the students also will be made public.
</P>
<P>
   University officials said an amendment to a federal law paved
the way for the new policy. The amendment allows universities to
release information from student disciplinary proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not it will have any deterrent effect, I don't
know,'' said William Schuerman, UD vice president of student
development and dean of students. ``But the more information you
can come forward with, the more confident the community is going to
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   In another departure from past policies, Schuerman said Dayton
police are now routinely involved in felony investigations on
campus. That could change somewhat, he said, as discussions
continue with the Montgomery County prosecutor's office and Dayton
police on how best to handle serious campus crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The policy changes at UD come seven months after a Dayton Daily
News story chronicled the school's confidential disciplinary
system, which frequently was used in place of the criminal courts.
Under the system, officials refused to reveal the names of student
offenders and the punishment they received.
</P>
<P>
   Event though the federal amendment to the student-privacy law
had been passed at the time, UD officials said the disciplinary
records were private ``contracts'' with their students and the
school refused to release the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cases forwarded to the disciplinary board last year
(but not initially turned over to the Montgomery County
prosecutor's office) was an alleged rape by a former UD football
player. The outcome of the university hearing was kept secret. In
court, prosecutors sought criminal charges but a grand jury
declined to hand up an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   By being more open, UD hopes to show its students and the Dayton
community that the school is holding offenders responsible for
serious offenses, Schuerman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will certainly provide people with information, which I
think in this day and age, they want to know,'' he said. ``It
allows us to keep up with a new level of sensitivity'' about campus
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations such as the Pennsylvania-based Security On Campus
Inc. and the media, particularly student newspapers, have been
pushing to open student crime and disciplinary records for years.
Howard Clery of Security on Campus said it is important for
colleges and universities to be frank about campus crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't do any good to hide it,'' Clery said. ``You can't
work on a problem if you hide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Clery isn't certain how many U.S. colleges and
universities have adopted policies similar to Dayton's, he said
more of them have begun to do so. Miami University, for example,
implemented the same policy as UD on Aug. 15, university
spokeswoman Holly Wissing said.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State and Wright State do not release information from
disciplinary hearings, officials at those schools said.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerman said student names on UD police reports will continue
to remain confidential, unless arrests are made and the reports are
forwarded to the Dayton police department for possible prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
