<SLUG> BC-ONTHEJOB-OFFHOURS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARPE DIEM, EVEN TO THE GRAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 1920s, when Calvin Coolidge declared, ``The business of
America is business,'' the expression ``24/7'' had yet to invade
the language. But as the following anecdotes illustrate, the nation
conducts business 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, and no site is
spared, even the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   When she was a human resources manager, Terri Schaeffer of New
York City also wore the hat of recruiter. And since good help is
hard to find, she kept her eyes and ears open, even when supposedly
off duty.
</P>
<P>
   One day, while seated on her regular perch at a Burger Heaven
counter, she overheard a young woman talking about her job search.
The woman had recently arrived from the Midwest, had consulted
employment agencies and had been sent on all kinds of dull
interviews. So there, among the burgers and colas, Ms. Schaeffer
introduced herself and began interviewing the woman.
</P>
<P>
   After determining that she had the skills necessary for an
entry-level job, Ms. Schaeffer arranged an official interview, and
the woman received a job offer.
</P>
<P>
   But she turned it down. She had decided to accept another
position _ as a recruiter for an employment agency.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, before he retired, Allen Leboff of Great
Neck, N.Y., was a partner in a Long Island accounting firm. While
on vacation in Venice with his wife, Irma, he was telling her about
the difficulty the firm was having in finding good young
accountants.
</P>
<P>
   A couple seated behind the Leboffs on a canal boat were
listening, and Leboff was soon interrupted by the woman, who
apologized and said: ``I know you won't believe this, but we have a
son who is an accountant and is thinking of changing his job. Could
he call on you for an interview?''
</P>
<P>
   Leboff said he could, and gave the woman his business card.
``The young man did call me,'' he writes. ``I did interview him; my
firm did hire him, and he has become, and still is, a partner in my
firm.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, a bachelor's degree firmly in hand, Bix Janni of
Brooklyn, N.Y., faced two big obstacles to joining corporate
America: His degree was in English, and he was prime fodder to be
drafted for military service.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the few employees who hired draft-eligible men was the
federal government,'' he writes. ``Reluctantly, I accepted a
position an office auditor with the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, a Westchester County man who had requested a change of
venue after a grueling interview with a tax auditor near his home
landed in Janni's Brooklyn cubicle. The man ``kept telling me I was
in the wrong profession,'' Janni writes. After the audit, ``he
handed me his business card, telling me to contact him if I wanted
a job with his firm. I looked at the company's name, smiled and
told him the company's campus interviewer would not even see me
when he visited my college.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The man smiled and told me not to worry,'' Janni says.
</P>
<P>
   He got the job.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is a postscript. Nine months after joining the
company _ IBM _ as a systems engineer, he was drafted and sent to
Vietnam. PPS: After Vietnam, he nabbed a job in publishing and was
finally able to put his English degree to work.
</P>
<P>
   Lee van de Velde of Philadelphia, an executive search
consultant, is used to meeting people in busy, uncomfortable
places, like train stations and hotel lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore, imagine my delight at meeting a promising candidate
on the chairlift to the top of Bromley Mountain in Vermont, with a
chill factor of minus 15,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ms. van de Velde discovered their potential mutual
interest only at the drop-off spot atop the mountain, she chased
the candidate down the slope on skis. As the woman prepared to ride
up again, Ms. van de Velde hopped in her chair. She considered but
rejected the idea of asking the woman to remove her goggles and
chin protector to see what she looked like _ presentability matters
in the workplace, after all _ and then wrote the contact
information on the lift ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, she eventually (after several non-goggled interviews) got
the job, and I got a good story,'' Ms. van de Velde writes.
</P>
<P>
   Business is often conducted in odd locations, but some sites are
odder than others.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was a gathering last fall at a cemetery to dedicate
the gravestone of Sara Nuss-Galles' mother-in-law, who had died a
year earlier, at 93.
</P>
<P>
   ``The small group attending included my husband Arie Galles'
childhood friend and her husband,'' an actor, says Ms. Nuss-Galles,
the writer of the magazine of Drew University in Madison, N.J. ``We
were touched at their presence.''
</P>
<P>
   As they returned to their cars, the actor handed Galles a
plastic folder. Inside were the actor's portfolio, head shots, news
releases, clippings and a detailed resume.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take Ms. Nuss-Galles long to guess where the actor
might hope the resume would land _ with her son, Jeremy Haft,
director of the 1997 movie ``Grizzly Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
