<HEADER>
A9198 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-TEX     09-02 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying the federal education bureaucracy is shortchanging poor
children, Gov. George W. Bush proposed on Thursday cutting funds
from low-performing programs and allowing some parents to use the
money to pay for private school.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, blasted by opponents as a federal voucher
program, was part of the most ambitious and detailed proposal Bush
has unveiled since he began running for president.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in Los Angeles that focused on disadvantaged
children, Bush also called for more student testing, ``bonus''
funds to schools that improve and a sharper academic focus to the
pre-school program known as Head Start.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years the federal government has tried to close the
gap of hope _ armed with good intentions and billions of dollars,''
Bush said. ``But sacks of money and the best of motives have made
little difference in the performance of disadvantaged children.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's plan, disadvantaged children in schools that fail
achievement standards three straight years could take an estimated
$1,500 in federal Title I funds and spend it on tutoring, private
school, or ``whatever their parents choose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the best case, these schools will rise to the challenge and
regain the confidence of parents,'' Bush said. ``In the worst case,
we will offer scholarships to America's neediest children ... in
any case, the federal government will no longer pay schools to
cheat poor children.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it is ``a scandal of the first order'' that the
average test scores of blacks and Hispanics at age 17 are equal to
those of Anglo 13-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say pigment and poverty need not determine performance,'' he
said. ``That myth is disproved by good schools every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he never said the word ``vouchers,'' that is exactly what
detractors are calling Bush's proposal on Title I money.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Chase, president of the anti-voucher National Education
Association, a teachers' union, said Bush's proposal is out of
touch with the American mainstream and would drain money away from
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush says he wants to invest in programs that work,
but he's willing to waste millions of tax dollars on vouchers,
which don't work,'' Chase said. ``For a fraction of the cost of a
voucher, we can put struggling students in smaller classes, where
all of them _ not just a select few _ will learn to read, write and
compute at higher levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also was hit from the right. The campaign of wealthy
magazine publisher Steve Forbes criticized the plan as ``too weak,
too narrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If parents find their kids trapped in public schools, Governor
Bush makes them wait three more years before they might be set
free,'' said J. Kenneth Blackwell, national chairman of the Forbes
2000 campaign. ``We need to set Americans free immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Education Agency in Austin said Texas this year
received $662 million in Title I funding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997-1998 school year, 1.8 million children in Texas were
involved in Title I program funding.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from allowing parents the option of taking their children
out of failing public schools, Bush would require that school
districts receiving Title I funds test children each year on the
academic basics.
</P>
<P>
   Under his initiative, schools that improve would get extra
funding, while federal programs that fail would be replaced by ones
that are proven successful.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would not require federal testing, instead leaving
it up to the states. It was one several instances in which Bush
walked a fine line between adhering to his principle of local
control while attempting to ensure federal oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have a national school board, and we do not need
one,'' Bush said. ``A president is not a federal principal, and I
will not be one.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, in a July swing to Milwaukee that highlighted school
choice issues, Bush said he opposed ``federalization of education''
and said presidents should ``encourage local folks to develop
accountability measures,'' the Houston Chronicle reported.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also turned his sights on Thursday on the Head Start
program, started in 1965 by President Lyndon B. Johnson. The $4.6
billion annual program serves 842,000 poor children and families.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed moving Head Start out of the Health and Human
Services Department and putting it under the Department of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   He said Head Start has strayed from its origins as a literacy
program to ``a day-care, health and nutrition program.'' He cited
studies showing it has not consistently helped children prepare for
school.
</P>
<P>
   Health Department spokesman Michael Kharfen disputed Bush's
description, saying Head Start helps children ages 3 and 4 prepare
for school and calling its results ``outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he criticized the focus on nutrition and health, Bush
did not propose cutting those programs. In fact, he said the
reforms could be accomplished ``without sacrificing Head Start's
important social and medical services.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told by the Bush people I talked to that they didn't
intend to change the health and the services aspect, or even the
nurturing aspect,'' said E.D. Hirsch, a professor at the University
of Virginia who was consulted by the campaign about the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch said proposing to move the program to the Department of
Education was symbolic, but he applauded the effort to put the
focus on cognitive development. He said changes made last year
already have begun moving Head Start in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   On a political level, William Bennett, a conservative leader and
former education secretary, said Bush wisely stepped away from the
issue of shutting down the education department as some
conservatives want.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that Bush had borrowed some of his ideas _
particular on vouchers _ from his brother Jeb, the Florida
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smart thing in this is, you put your opponents in favor of
keeping kids in failing schools,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
