r a BC-WACO-EVIDENCE-TEX     09-02 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-EVIDENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHISTLE-BLOWER PROSECUTOR ONCE ACCUSED OF COVERUP IN WACO
INVESTIGATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ The assistant U.S. attorney who has accused the
government of covering up the use of pyrotechnic devices at the
1993 Branch Davidian siege near Waco was once himself accused of
covering up other evidence in the standoff.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Bill Johnston announced that someone in the
Justice Department faxed him a document establishing that
pyrotechnic tear gas canisters were used on the last day of the
standoff, which ended when the compound burned to the groud. Cult
leader David Koresh and about 80 of his followers were found dead
inside.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI officials
have adamantly denied the use of the pyrotechnic canisters. But
last week, they confirmed that two, possibly three, of the
canisters were launched hours before the fire erupted and away from
the main wooden compound.
</P>
<P>
   The document, a three-page memo prepared by a paralegal, has
some handwritten notes on it with words to the effect of ``Do not
disclose,'' Johnston said. No explanation accompanied the fax,
Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston went public with the memo, he said, so the truth about
the Waco siege can finally come out. But four years ago, it was
Johnston who was accused of covering up information about some of
the events surrounding the deadly standoff.
</P>
<P>
   During his 1995 congressional hearing testimony, Fort Worth
defense attorney Tim Evans presented an internal ATF memo saying
that Johnston told ATF agents to stop their internal investigation
of the shooting that started the 51-day seige and left two
Davadians and four ATF agents dead.
</P>
<P>
   The memo said Johnston was fearful that it would create evidence
defense attorneys could use at the upcoming criminal trials for
some of the Branch Davidian survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston allowed ATF agents to interview one other agent, but
``no notes were created,'' the memo says.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Thursday, Evans said the documents ``speak
for themselves and they speak pretty plain language.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, defense attorneys should have been given the
information before the 1994 trials, or at least during them, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law requires the government to reveal this information
...'' Evans said. ``Any agent that knew it and any prosecutor that
knew it should have disclosed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said he understands that it looks somewhat hypocritical
for him to be accused of cover-up then accuse someone else, but
``this is an issue I dealt with fully at Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking for any breaks from anyone,'' Johnston said.
``This is fair game to bring up, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   As he said in his testimony then, Johnston explained that he
stopped the ATF shooting review because it was going to duplicate
the independent investigation he had asked the Texas Rangers to
conduct. Because of the controversy surrounding the shooting,
Johnston said, he did not think the ATF should investigate the
matter internally.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the attorneys who defended clients at the criminal
trials criticized Johnston for his previous actions, but commended
him for his recent turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think Bill Johnston made some mistakes in the past?
Absolutely,'' said Houston attorney Dan Cogdell, who represented a
Branch Davidian who was acquitted. Nevertheless, Cogdell said he is
pleased to know that Johnston has ``recognized that the truth is
bigger than him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's realized the errors of his ways,'' said Houston
defense attorney Dick DeGuerin. ``I'm glad he's seen the light.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
