<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-AGASSI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW IT'S UP TO AGASSI   TO KEEP LURING FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TEN-USOPEN) 
(DW) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andre Agassi has to sidestep all banana peels, steer
clear of suspicious sushi and avoid anyone with so much as a
scratch in their throat. Because any fall, food poison or friend
carrying a cold could spell doom for the popularity meters at the
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   With so much riding on him, Agassi might have to put his body
guard to good use and protect himself.
</P>
<P>
   After the injury exits of No. 1 seeded Pete Sampras,
fourth-seeded Patrick Rafter and eighth-seeded Carlos Moya, Agassi
is the people's choice to win the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   On his own, Agassi is the player still pulling people through
the turnstiles for the suddenly so-so men's draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hard to get the intensity, but it feels different,''
Agassi said of playing in a Grand Slam without Sampras, Rafter and
now Moya, who retired with a back injury Thursday night. ``I think
they added a lot to the game of tennis. They add a lot to the
tournament. The tournament misses them. It's still going to be a
good Open, and I'll do my part.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi did his part Thursday. Relentlessly, he slapped the lines
on the court raw with precise and clean strokes to usher Axel
Pretzsch out of Arthur Ashe Stadium before he could soak up the
moment, 6-3, 6-2, 6-1. With few wasted motions, Agassi converted 6
of 10 break opportunities and spent no more than 33 minutes on any
set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess in hindsight you can look back and say, `OK, well,
it's good it didn't take a whole lot out of me,' '' Agassi said.
``But you know, there's always a level of intensity that goes along
with a match, especially at the U.S. Open that always makes it feel
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The only hard part was keeping his patience with the line calls.
Midway through the third set, Agassi stewed over a call and let out
his aggression with a 113-mile-an-hour serve to go up by 3-0 in the
third set. A few minutes later, Agassi was gathering his things and
focusing on the third round.
</P>
<P>
   With no one seeded higher than Marcelo Rios, seeded 10th,
remaining in his half of the draw, most assume Agassi will skip
into the final and walk away from the National Tennis Center with
his second U.S. Open title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, opinions don't matter a whole lot, you know?'' Agassi
said. ``They really don't, not when it comes down to getting it on
out there on the court. All it takes is one bad match for the U.S.
Open dreams to be squashed. I'm not confused as to what's required
to win any match, regardless of who it is that I'm playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, no one still walking is playing as well as Agassi.
After refocusing and fine-tuning his body following his divorce
from the actress Brooke Shields, he won the French Open and reached
the final at Wimbledon only to lose to Sampras in three sets.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty months after falling as low as 141 in the rankings,
Agassi briefly took the No. 1 ranking from Sampras in July.
</P>
<P>
   But as quickly as his career started breathing again, Agassi
understands how fragile success can be and how any complacency at
the Open could end the remarkable run he has had this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take much for it to change,'' Agassi said. ``I
don't mean with me, I just mean with sports. A few windows of
opportunity, and somebody can take advantage of you, and you can
have an off day. It's hard to play seven great matches. So a
difficult match is coming and I'm mentally focused enough to deal
with that, and hopefully get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many are counting on Agassi to get through this Grand Slam and
stir the interest of the fans as well as bring happiness to the
television ratings' gods.
</P>
<P>
   If Agassi does not fall to an upset, injury or ailment, if he
follows the plan and finds his way to a title, he will not consider
it hollow without going through Sampras to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi said he felt there was a great chance to win the Open,
regardless of whether Sampras and Rafter were playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to boil down to how well you play at the right
times,'' Agassi said. ``And to be quite honest, it's hard to think
matches ahead. I know it's easy sometimes from the outside to think
matches ahead, but for players, it's truly the next match that's
important.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
