<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-WEBB03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Still no Webb, but predictably everything's OK
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Troy Drayton nodded in the direction of
a near-empty locker about 10 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then I look over to see if his clothes are in
there,'' the Dolphins' tight end said. ``I keep expecting to walk
in here and see him sitting there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one thing when that locker, which belongs to seven-time
Pro Bowl left tackle Richmond Webb, was empty July 30, the day that
veterans reported to training camp.
</P>
<P>
   That was expected. From the moment in February when the Dolphins
named Webb their franchise player for 1999, a designation that
basically prevented him from testing the free-agency market, nearly
everyone expected contract negotiations to drag into the
pre-season.
</P>
<P>
   But this far? Thursday _ the day of the exhibition finale at
Green Bay and 11 days before the regular-season opener at Denver _
little had changed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins have refused to budge from the offer they initially
put on the table _ three years, $11.5 million _ alongside the
one-year tender of $3.42million they were required to make to
designate Webb as a franchise player. Webb and his agent, Steve
Zucker, want a long-term deal that pays close to $5million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker gave Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson a new proposal this
week. And the Chicago-based agent hopes to meet with Johnson while
the team is in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the bottom line is the same.
</P>
<P>
   The locker remains empty.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the day before the team left for Green Bay, an
inevitable step in the negotiating process happened.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson began gushing about Brent Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Last pre-season, as defensive tackle Tim Bowens was holding out,
Johnson made backup Barron Tanner sound like the second coming of
Merlin Olsen.
</P>
<P>
   This pre-season, it was only a matter of time before Smith, who
has been starting at left tackle, earned rave reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, without being prompted, Johnson made a point to talk
about Smith, saying that the third-year player from Mississippi
State wasn't getting nearly enough attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brent has been doing an excellent job,'' he said, pointing to
Smith's play against Detroit defensive lineman Robert Porcher as an
example.
</P>
<P>
   When camp opened, Johnson said that would be the last day he
would talk about Webb. But when asked a question about the left
tackle position _ would he feel comfortable with Smith starting in
Denver? _ Johnson brought up the taboo name himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll volunteer it. ... I doubt if Richmond, if he came in
right now, would be prepared to play in the opener,'' he said.
``I'm not going to be firm on that. But the thought now would be
that Brent would be our left tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson is taking his hard-line negotiating stance,
insisting his team is fine without Webb, the players who surround
that empty locker tell a different story.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that they trash Smith's ability. To the contrary, they
heap wildly optimistic praise on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kid could go to the island in two or three years,'' said
left guard Mark Dixon, referring to the Pro Bowl in Hawaii.
``You're talking that kind of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, though, Dixon and seemingly every other
offensive lineman say this team needs Webb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the deal with Richmond, at least for me, is that he's
been through the fire,'' Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Right guard Kevin Donnalley said: ``When the games start to
count, he'd better be here, because he's one of the main reasons
Dan (Marino) has played going on 17 years. He's the guy who can
shut down Bruce Smith every week. Brent Smith is going to be a
great player, but it's only his third year. I think back on my
third year, that's when I first started at left tackle and it was a
tough, tough experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Smith scoffs at talk that he is ready to fill Webb's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Richmond's going to be here,'' he said. ``And I know
it's his position. I've just got to do the best job I can to hold
it down until he gets back.''
</P>
<P>
   When will that be?
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure. But Drayton listens to Johnson and has a sense
that it won't be long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think coach Johnson is factoring him into being with the
team next week,'' he said. ``I just have a feeling. ... I just
can't see us going into Denver without him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
