</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SC-COACHES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New eras may start slowly in S. Carolina
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The programs at South Carolina and Clemson had a
combined record of 4-18 last season, one of the worst performances
for the state's two major universities.
</P>
<P>
   Both schools hired new coaches in the offseason to undertake
herculean rebuilding jobs. It is possible both teams will lose
their openers Saturday, and neither is expected to have a winning
season. Why, then, are both sets of fans so excited?
</P>
<P>
   Simple. With Tommy Bowden at Clemson and Lou Holtz at South
Carolina, the future looks bright. Which is good, because the
present _ particularly Saturday _ looks bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, son of Florida State coach Bobby Bowden, makes his
Clemson debut at home against Marshall, which was a I-AA power when
the game was scheduled years ago. Today, however, the Thundering
Herd is the defending champion of the Division I Mid-America
Athletic Conference. The program, built by Georgia's Jim Donnan and
maintained by Bob Pruett, has won 101 games in the '90s, more than
any other college. Marshall returns 19 starters from a 12-1 team,
including quarterback Chad Pennington, a Heisman Trophy candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people are going to be surprised when
Marshall takes the field,'' said Bowden, who will try to become the
first Clemson coach to win his debut against a Division I school
since Frank Howard in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   The Lou Holtz era begins at South Carolina with an equally
daunting task. The Gamecocks, 1-10 a year ago, must travel to No.
24 North Carolina State. Playing the first game on the road is
tough enough, but now N.C. State has extra adrenaline from
Saturday's 23-20 upset of Texas in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, head coach at N.C. State 1972-75, arrives with a team
that began the preseason short on talent and then was decimated by
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had 28 guys to miss some practice because of injuries,''
said Holtz, returning to the sideline two years after leaving Notre
Dame. ``I can't tell you what the strength of our team is other
than we've worked hard. I have a lot of concerns, and I know we're
not a very good team right now.'' Holtz should have a pleasant
evening in Raleigh tonight, at a reunion of his former N.C. State
players. Saturday evening, however, could be less fun. The
Gamecocks' offensive and defensive lineups at times will include
two seniors, seven juniors, 10 sophomores and three freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   None of his previous 27 teams entered a season with so many
question marks, he said. ``I have absolutely no idea how we'll
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden feels the same about his team. Clemson doesn't return a
starter on the offensive line for the first time since 1943. Its
leading rusher from a year ago, Travis Zachery, has been suspended
for the first game. Bowden has installed a new offense but isn't
sure whether either quarterback, Brandon Streeter or Woody
Dantzler, can run it the way Shaun King did for him last year at
Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, which lost six players to the NFL, does not have a
real star at linebacker for the first time in recent memory. The
result is that Bowden would feel better opening against Wofford.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this first game will do is establish a barometer of how
far this program has to go,'' he said. ``I would prefer an opener
where I could make some mistakes and still win.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite sagging attendance in recent years, more than 75,000
will be at Memorial Stadium on Saturday looking for a sign that a
new era is starting in Clemson football. And they expect to go home
with a win.
</P>
<P>
   Those expectations come with the job, Bowden said: ``Patience is
not a word you hear a lot around here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
