u s BC-FBC-UT-HEAT03-COX     09-02 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UT-HEAT03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT sweats details to beat the heat
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Winds were suffocatingly calm and the
temperature hit a searing 95 degrees when the University of Texas
kicked off to North Carolina State last Saturday night at
Royal-Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't your stereotypical, crisp autumn Saturday, just a late
August evening in Austin, when high heat is a given. But despite
the heat and humidity, the Longhorn players, who had been working
out as a group outside all summer, suffered few heat-related
problems in the sweltering conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I was sweaty, but the kids handled it well,'' said UT
coach Mack Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday presents another heated test.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of ABC network officials, the game between Texas
and Stanford at Memorial Stadium was moved from an evening to an 11
a.m. kickoff. According to the early forecast by the National
Weather Service office in New Braunfels, the temperature at kickoff
will be in the mid-to-high 80s, with the humidity at about 60
percent. By halftime, temperatures will be in the low 90s and by
game's end, around 95. The heat index, which takes into account the
actual temperature and humidity, will be in the low 100s.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorn training staff is anticipating no severe problems,
but will be prepared with two dozen, one-liter bags of an
intravenous sugar and saline solution to give players who are
suffering from muscle cramps and other symptoms of heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the Stanford players? The team practices each day
in almost ideal weather conditions. The highs this week in Palo
Alto, Calif., have been in the low to mid-70s, with little
humidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys it was going to be hot,'' said Stanford wide
receiver Troy Walters, who spent his high school years at A&AMP;M
Consolidated in College Station. ``Coach has told us we don't have
to live there, just play there for three hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford coach Tyrone Willingham said: ``I think there will
probably be a lot said or made of the fact the ballgame is at 9 our
time, 11 their time, and it will be 99 degrees there and only 65
degrees here. For us, as far as the time, we're very fortunate that
. . . during two a days we've been practicing at a similar time, so
I think that helps in preparation. I don't think there's any
preparation you can do for 100 degrees, or 99 degrees. It's going
to be hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Chorley, an assistant professor at the Baylor College
of Medicine in Houston who specializes in sports medicine, said it
takes between 10 and 14 days for an athlete to acclimate to such
harsh temperatures. And that's only if the athlete exercises in the
heat each day for 30-45 minutes or longer.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Texas has used early home kickoffs in September to its
advantage. The Longhorns usually play a morning or afternoon game
at Memorial Stadium each September. In 1993, underdog UT was able
to pull off a 21-21 tie with then-No. 6 Syracuse. The Longhorns
followed that early September success with a 30-16 win over
Louisville in 1994 and a 38-27 victory over Pittsburgh in 1995.
There are ways to prepare players for the heat so that they don't
suffer from symptoms such as headache, dizziness and severe muscle
cramps.
</P>
<P>
   UT trainer Tom McVan said that he ordered players, starting five
days before the game, to drink as much water or noncaffeinated,
noncarbonated liquid as they could hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them to drink so much that they have to wake up at
night to go to the bathroom,'' McVan said.
</P>
<P>
   Players are urged to drink a cup of water every 20 minutes
during practice or whenever they get off the field during a game.
</P>
<P>
   UT also has purchased two Cool Capes, which literally are
uniform capes hooked up by three hoses to a air conditioning unit,
to keep the players cool. The cape is draped over a player, who
then feels the same effects of sitting in a well air-conditioned
room.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, UT has tried to schedule its September games for
an early evening kickoff. But television networks often get schools
to change game times in exchange for national exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ABC will show UT-Stanford to about one-third of the country,
which includes the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to turn down national exposure these
days,'' said Chris Plonsky, UT associate athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we thought about the heat, we are concerned about it as
we speak. . . . It's not like we're sitting here being mercenary.
But we have 20 sports to support. We have nice facilities and we
have to maintain those nice facilities. None of that is cheap _ we
have to pay our own bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
