<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hard case: Trump takes tortoise to task
 &HT;    By Trebor Banstetter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A family of gopher tortoises crawled
briefly between Donald Trump and the completion of his $40 million
golf course Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The never-shy celebrity hadn't balked at lavishing every luxury
on the 214-acre course across from the Palm Beach County Jail. And
he'd spent hundreds of thousands more planting royal palm trees
along the roads leading to the fairways.
</P>
<P>
   But he tried to draw the line at an extra $45,000 the county
required he spend afterbecoming the first person to get nailed with
new road landscaping rules.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the whole flap on the tortoises.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Trump International Golf Club in suburban West Palm
Beach has been under construction since 1997, the county only
recently asked the owner of Palm Beach's Mar-a-Lago to make room
for the endangered Florida gopher tortoises that live on the land.
</P>
<P>
   Trump had agreed to add another 3.1 acres to the project just
for the tortoise family. But he didn't expect to get snagged by new
rules county commissioners passed last week. They require any
developer who enlarges his project to landscape the traffic
separators _ narrow concrete barriers between lanes _ on adjacent
roads.
</P>
<P>
   That's just not fair, Trump representative Bob Bentz argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have to do this if the county hadn't come and
asked us to create this habitat for the turtles,'' said Bentz, a
land planner with West Palm Beach-based Land Design South.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of Trump's international reputation for excess,
that argument didn't win much sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Donald is known throughout the world for going first-class
on everything,'' said Zoning Commissioner Kevin Foley. ``I don't
know why he's trying to duck this condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The zoning commission ruled against Trump, 4-2. The decision is
final.
</P>
<P>
   Trump did not return telephone calls Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The legally protected tortoises have played havoc with projects
before. Earlier this year, Carver Middle School in Delray Beach had
to build portable classrooms on athletic fields because part of its
campus was fenced off to protect a tortoise nest.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, there were more tortoises in the state than
people. But their population has dwindled to less than 1 million,
and they've been an endangered species since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The county's environmental resource management department has
known about the tortoises for some time, said environmental analyst
Milton Battles.
</P>
<P>
   The exact number of family members is somewhat of a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Battles nor Bentz was sure why the county requested the
tortoise habitat so late into the development of the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   But Trump was also adding an additional acre for landscaping and
open space. Though Bentz disagreed, Zoning Commissioner Sherry
Hyman said that might have triggered the beautification rules
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sympathize, because it did come from the county,'' she said.
``But in the grand scheme of things, this isn't a whole lot of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Beautifying the narrow traffic separator will be difficult,
Bentz said, because a pipe will have to be installed under the road
to feed a sprinkler system.
</P>
<P>
   Bentz also pointed out that Trump didn't skimp on the
landscaping he's already done, lining the entryway with hundreds of
towering royal palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is drive down there and you'll see how
dramatically we've changed the area,'' Bentz said.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't disclose an exact price tag, but said that the trees
cost about $1,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Still, zoning commissioners insisted that the additional
landscaping is a must.
</P>
<P>
   ``That intersection looks like garbage now,'' Hyman said.
</P>
<P>
   Trump's golf club is tentatively scheduled to open in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Staff researcher Dorothy Shea contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
