<HEADER>
A9245 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LAD     09-02 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG CHALLENGE AWAITS GOLFERS IN HAWAII
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANEOHE, Hawaii _ Tell someone you are playing the Ko'olau Golf
Club, and if they are familiar with the course their reaction is
pretty much the same.
</P>
<P>
   A smile flashed across the face of our bellman at the Outrigger
Waikiki when I told him where I planned to golf as he was taking my
clubs out of the trunk of our rental car. He nodded and offered
some sage advice, a variation on the familiar refrain offered by
golfers around the world who have been humbled by courses to which
their games did not measure up: ``Take lots of balls.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, we've all heard that one before. Besides, I had a bag full
of balls.
</P>
<P>
   But the last thing Ko'olau (pronounced Ko oh low, as in cow)
general manager Rob Nelson said before I teed off made me wonder if
there was indeed something to this golf ball business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good luck. Do you have enough balls?'' he asked in a tone
devoid of mirth. It was as if he was asking someone going into
battle if they had enough bullets.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason. Ko'olau Golf Club is billed as ``the
world's most challenging golf course,'' a boast made by a number of
upscale venues around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, the folks at Ko'olau are not bragging.
</P>
<P>
   And they have the numbers to back them up.
</P>
<P>
   From the back tees Ko'olau, managed by Santa Monica-based
American Golf Corp., covers 7,310 yards and plays to a par of 72
with a slope rating, which measures the degree of difficulty, of a
whopping 162.
</P>
<P>
   American Golf could also call it one of the world's most
beautiful and unique courses and they would not be making an idle
boast.
</P>
<P>
   Ko'olau was carved out of a tropical rain forest below the
famous Pali Lookout. The course takes its name from the mountain
range that towers above the fairways and greens.
</P>
<P>
   The course was designed by Jack Tuthill and was originally owned
by a Japanese company that planned to sell memberships for more
than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   That would have also made it one of the world's most expensive
courses. The former owners got clobbered by the recession in Asia
and current owners bought the facility in a bankruptcy sale, then
hired American Golf to get it into shape.
</P>
<P>
   That process is still going on, but one thing that won't change
is the degree of difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   There are four sets of tees to accommodate various skill levels.
That way, golfers can shoot for the same landing areas. The
challenge is hitting them.
</P>
<P>
   It is target golf from tee to green.
</P>
<P>
   And it could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rebuilt every bunker on the golf course and grassed over 12
of them,'' Nelson said. ``The real challenge is from the back tees,
but every hole is unique.''
</P>
<P>
   American Golf is also using some psychology in setting up the
course. While there are four sets of tees, none are red, which
usually denote the women's tees.
</P>
<P>
   At Ko'olau, the tees are called forward (white), resort (blue),
championship (gold) and tournament (black).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a test, play the golds,'' Nelson said. ``But it's
probably going to be fun from the blues. If you play the right tees
for your game, it's going to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the course difficult is there's no out of bounds. The
fairways are lined with lush tropical vegetation, featuring an
abundance of Hawaiian flowers and critters.
</P>
<P>
   If you hit a ball past the rough and into the forest or ravine
that winds through the course, there is no chance of finding it.
</P>
<P>
   Ko'olau does have a big appetite for balls.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the course is not on the Pacific Ocean, as are
many of Hawaii's best courses, the views are astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   The course, which is about 20 minutes from Honolulu, could
easily have doubled as the set for Jurassic Park.
</P>
<P>
   Fairways tumble and climb through three climate zones and offer
views of cascading waterfalls or the Pacific in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Golf carts feature a Global Positioning System that lets golfers
pinpoint their location and distance to the green from any point on
a fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as spectacular as the course is the 125,000-square foot
clubhouse, which includes a Japanese hot bath in the men's locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   Greens fees for non-residents are $100 and $65 after 1:30 p.m.,
a bargain in this state.
</P>
<P>
   So how tough is this course, really?
</P>
<P>
   I shot a 111 and lost six balls in relatively benign wind
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   American Golf's Nelson says players usually do better the second
time around.
</P>
<P>
   I can't wait for my rematch. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-WACO-INQUIRY-NYT &LR;      09-02 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SENATOR COULD LEAD NEW WACO INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (See also WACO-RENO-FREEH) 
(mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Justice Department officials have held serious
discussions with former Sen. John Danforth, a Missouri Republican,
about leading a new broad-based inquiry into what happened at the
Branch Davidian compound in Waco, Texas, in 1993, Clinton
administration officials said Thursday night .
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that a final decision had not been made and
that there was at least one other plausible candidate, a former
U.S. attorney who is being thought of as a fall-back choice. They
noted that Danforth, who retired from the Senate in 1994, fit most,
if not all, of the requirements set by Attorney General Janet Reno
for the person who would lead the inquiry. Reno has emphasized to
aides that she is seeking to recruit a nationally known Republican
with a strong reputation for integrity to aid the credibility of
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, who now practices law in St. Louis, did not return
telephone calls to his office.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also disclosed Thursday that Reno believed that
the FBI had concealed from her a second audio recording made at
Waco on the day that the Branch Davidian compound erupted in
flames, killing some 80 people, many of them children.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Reno ordered U.S. marshals to enter the FBI's
headquarters across Pennsylvania Avenue from the Justice Department
and seize a tape recording of conversations between field
commanders and agents that dealt with the firing of pyrotechnic
tear-gas canisters on the day of the assault. It was the recent
disclosure that such canisters had been used despite years of
denials by the FBI and Reno that prompted her to complain that she
had been badly served by the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The second tape was made between 10 a.m and noon on the day of
the assault and officials asked to retain it to make a transcript
with their sophisticated playback machines. But Reno refused and
asked that the tape be turned over to the marshals along with the
one that dealt with the canisters.
</P>
<P>
   A transcript of the first tape, made between 6 a.m. and 8 a.m.
on April 19, details a sometimes inaudible conversation between two
FBI officials that culminates in the order to fire the canisters.
According to a transcript of the conversation, Richard Rogers, the
agent in charge from the bureau's elite Hostage Rescue Team,
questions a subordinate, Stephen McGavin, supervisory special agent
of the rescue team, about the feasibility of firing the canisters.
</P>
<P>
   The transcript shows McGavin suggesting that an agent armed with
the canisters can fire them ``at the construction project'' with
relative safety using a vehicle for cover.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers responds, ``You're talking about the block over top the
construction?'' That site has since been identified as a concrete
bunker some 25 to 30 yards from the wooden residence where the
Davidians resided.
</P>
<P>
   McGavin then says that the agent armed with the canisters
believes he can use a truck for cover and ``attempt to penetrate it
with military rounds.'' He then asks for permission to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that's affirmative,'' Rogers responds.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what is on the second tape, which was not
transcribed by officials until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials also spent Thursday hurriedly
pondering who should be asked to lead the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who returned to Washington Thursday from Panama, has
scheduled a news conference for Friday morning. It remained
unclear, however, if she and her aides would be able to move fast
enough to have someone in place by the time she meets with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Some candidates who were considered earlier had to be discarded
because of conflicts, as in the case of Dan K. Webb, a Chicago
attorney and a former high-profile federal prosecutor. As a private
lawyer, Webb has represented Larry Potts, a former senior bureau
official involved in the Waco standoff from Feb. 28, 1993, until
the fatal conflagration on April 28, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, who turns 63 on Sunday, was nicknamed by many in the
Senate ``Saint Jack'' _ to some a jovial appellation, for others a
rueful reference to his stern, sometimes righteous demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   He became best known to the public, however, in the summer of
1991, when he vigorously defended the nomination of Judge Clarence
Thomas to the Supreme Court. Usually mild-mannered, Danforth shed
his reserve to wage war on behalf of Thomas, who had once worked
for him and was a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions with Danforth, officials said Thursday night,
concerned the degree of independence he would enjoy and the reach
of the investigation's subpoena power.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery that the pyrotechnic canisters were used may have
touched off a major brawl between Reno and Louis Freeh, the FBI
director, and angered many members of Congress, but no one has
suggested there is any new evidence that the FBI started the fatal
fire. The canisters were fired six hours before the deadly fire.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said Thursday night that he
thought any new inquiry should be narrow in scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing might be getting out of hand,'' he said.
Perhaps the FBI behaved badly in not disclosing facts, but ``no new
facts have come out, certainly none that suggest there is anything
wrong with the main conclusion that David Koresh was responsible
for setting the fire,'' Schumer said, referring to the Branch
Davidian leader.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Rules Against U.S. in Waco Case
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Justice Department lost a bid Thursday to block an
order to turn over evidence related to the Branch Davidian case.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 9, Judge Walter Smith of U.S. District Court in Waco,
Texas, had ordered all agencies possessing any evidence ``in any
way relevant'' to the case to turn it over to his court.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers sought to block the order, but Smith
on Thursday denied their motion, saying the government must turn
over the evidence by Oct. 1. Beginning on Oct. 18, Smith is
scheduled to preside over a wrongful death civil lawsuit brought by
relatives of deceased Branch Davidian followers. Lawyers for the
plaintiffs have complained that the government has refused access
to evidence under its the control. The Texas Department of Public
Safety, which also controls evidence collected from the Branch
Davidian compound, had asked Smith earlier this summer to take
control of everything.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's order, Smith said that consolidating the evidence
with the court would not only make it accessible to all civil
litigants but also ``would, hopefully, deflect the suspicion
reported in the press, whether warranted or not, that there is a
massive cover-up regarding the evidence that was seized and
generated as a result of the Branch Davidian criminal case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
