<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LIKUD-ART-1STL     09-02 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LIKUD-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S LIKUD PARTY SELECTS SHARON AS ITS LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EXPANDS 3rd graf to add Sharon quote; SUBS 11th and 12th grafs to
change `massacres' plural to `massacre' singular; SUBS 15th graf to
update vote percentages) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Ariel Sharon, the aging but pugnacious former
warrior, captured the leadership of the opposition Likud Party in
primaries Thursday night, succeeding Benjamin Netanyahu, who had
quit after he lost his bid to be re-elected prime minister in May.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, 71, an energetic veteran of many Israeli military and
political battles, overwhelmingly defeated two leaders of a younger
generation of Likudniks: Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert, 54, and Meir
Sheetrit, 51, who served as chairman of Netanyahu's governing
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   While Olmert had made clear that he had his sights set on
becoming prime minister, Sharon had said that he would serve only
as the steward of a party left greatly demoralized by its defeat in
May. He promised to hold new primaries in two years to select the
Likud candidate for prime minister in the next national elections.
``Let's rebuild the movement and prepare the Likud to win the next
elections,'' Sharon told followers at party headquarters in Tel
Aviv early Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts theorized Thursday night that Sharon would
end up serving as a place-holder for a resurgent Netanyahu, who has
withdrawn from public view since he was trounced by Ehud Barak, the
new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   That expectation, nurtured by Sharon, certainly motivated many
followers of Netanyahu to vote for him. Indeed, when Netanyahu
showed up to cast his own vote Thursday, he was trailed by acolytes
chanting, ``He'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no question that this is also a comeback of sorts
for Sharon, a general, lawyer and gentleman farmer who is a
larger-than-life Israeli character.
</P>
<P>
   Always seeking to rehabilitate a reputation tainted by the 1982
Israeli invasion of Lebanon, which he directed as defense minister,
Sharon will for the first time take the helm of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   White-haired, portly and ever re-chargeable, Sharon has said he
hopes to revitalize the ailing Likud. As a low voter turnout
Thursday demonstrated, the the party is riven by internal strife
and an ideological identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Since Likud endorsed the most recent Israeli-Palestinian peace
agreement, it gave up its mantle as protector of the land of Israel
against territorial compromise and joined the large, amorphous
political center. In the May elections, it was greatly weakened,
capturing only 19 of the 120 seats in parliament, second to One
Israel/Labor's 26.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, a former foreign minister and defense minister, has
always brought out extreme emotions in Israelis. He is revered by
some and despised by others.
</P>
<P>
   On the world stage and in a good part of Israel, he never
succeeded in overcoming his responsibility for the invasion of
Lebanon and the massacres that followed. He will be always be
closely associated with the slaughter of Palestinian refugees by
Israel's ally, the Lebanese Christian Phalangists.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre cost him his job as defense minister, after a
government investigating commission held him liable for failing to
prevent the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon has bounced back politically over time _ partly because
many Israelis believed that the invasion of Lebanon was ultimately
redeemed by its success in crushing the Palestine Liberation
Organization's military structure. But he was always in someone
else's shadow, however outsized his hovering presence in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he will take over the main opposition party just as Lebanon
moves front and center in the Israeli consciousness once again.
Since the invasion, Israeli troops have occupied a 9-mile-deep
security zone in southern Lebanon. But principle campaign pledge of
Barak was to pull them out by next May.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, the vote tally gave Sharon 53 percent of the
ballots cast, to Olmert's 24 percent and Sheetrit's 22 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Olmert, a former parliament member and cabinet minister, had a
hard time living down what many party faithfuls perceived to have
been a traitorous act on his part. During the national campaign,
while Netanyahu was trying to sell himself as the only candidate
who could save a united Jerusalem, Olmert, a political rival of
Netanyahu, vouched for Barak's security credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Olmert's comments that ``Ehud Barak will not divide Jerusalem''
were used in Barak's television advertising. That image planted
itself in Likud Party members' heads; even a well-financed campaign
and a last-minute endorsement by former Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir failed to help Omert.
</P>
<P>
   Sheetrit, who, like many of the party's members is a Sephardic
Jew, offered himself up as the only candidate who cared about
social issues. Using Israeli code, he was playing the ethnic card,
but without success.
</P>
<P>
   When Sharon's son Omri inadvertently touched on ethnic issues
during the campaign, offending the party's working-class
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Omri Sharon and the Likud's director general, Uri Shani, said
during an interview with a leading newspaper columnist that
Sharon's government-issued Cadillac kept breaking down. But Sharon
was not planning to replace it, they said, because ``it makes a
huge impression on the Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Sharon, the damage did not last.
</P>
<P>
   It was barely apparent here Thursday that voting was taking
place, although 323 polls were open across the country. The apathy
within the party _ 33 percent of its 143,000 registered members
voted, which by Israeli standards is low _ was echoed in a
nationwide indifference to the leadership battle inside the
country's second-largest party. The primaries were barely mentioned
in the news.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, nostalgia for Netanyahu, whose charisma
earned him almost cult status among some Likudniks, grew during the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even in his absence, he dominated this election campaign. Some
prominent right-wingers supported Olmert, who is more dovish than
Sharon, because they feared the return of the former prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Now it remains to be seen whether Sharon can rebuild the Likud
Party without the former prime minister's active participation. But
just as Netanyahu, in his absence, dominated this campaign, his
influence on the Likud Party is bound to persist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
