<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWAII TRIP WILL BE NO USC HOLIDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ Dr. John Hubbard remembers the last time USC played
here, and his bittersweet memories persuaded him to stay home 21
years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first and last time I'll go there (for a game),''
said Hubbard, USC's school president from 1970-80.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans defeated the Rainbow Warriors 21-5 in 1978 and
then-president Hubbard's antics were probably the most memorable
moment of a contest that gave the Trojans a scare en route to the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, USC received a 15-yard ``non-contact
foul'' that negated a Trojans fumble recovery, when Hubbard
insulted a local official.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett was an assistant on the sideline that
December night, and still remembers Hubbard's infraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were mystified on that penalty,'' Hackett said. ``I
couldn't see anybody. (Hubbard) had gone behind the bench. We
didn't find out who it was until after the game.''
</P>
<P>
   A sheepish Hubbard can still recall Hackett's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as astonished as John Robinson was,'' Hubbard said.
``He couldn't figure out where that flag came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett has been assured that a Western Athletic Conference crew
of officials will work Saturday's game against Hawaii at Aloha
Stadium, but there are other pitfalls he's trying to avoid for what
is supposed to be a trip to paradise.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are doing their version of an island commando raid,
swooping into Honolulu on Thursday, barely 60 hours before kickoff.
Hackett doesn't want the Trojans to experience too much ``Aloha
Spirit'' before the game.
</P>
<P>
   It's a direct consequence of last year's embarrassing Sun Bowl
defeat to Texas Christian, when Hackett felt too many things
happened off the field to distract the players during their week in
El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have to say much. Because of El Paso, they
understand the magnitude of not preparing and the consequences,''
Hackett said. ``We will be very serious about this game.''
</P>
<P>
   No one will doubt that. There's USC's spartan itinerary, for
example, which includes a trip to Pearl Harbor and little else. A
trip to the Polynesian Cultural Center was scratched because of
time constraints _ and the Sun Bowl defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Even the players admit the trip to El Paso has influenced their
feelings about coming to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before El Paso, it would be a distraction, now it's just
another game,'' linebacker Zeke Moreno said. ``Honestly, before
that, I would say it would be a big distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's going to be hard not to do anything. I mean,
everywhere we go, even just driving to practice, we'll be taking a
scenic route. You can't ignore that. But I've been to Hawaii
already, so it doesn't matter that much to me.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one major difference between 1978 and '99. USC is
beginning this season on the islands, while the '78 team was
concluding its regular season before playing in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is different playing at the end of the year instead
of the beginning,'' said Paul McDonald, who was the Trojans'
quarterback, although he missed the Hawaii game with an injured
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald remembers in '78 that it was his first visit to Hawaii,
and most of the players underestimated their opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember how sheltered a life I had. I was walking around in
a velour shirt and it was 85 degrees,'' McDonald said. ``I had no
idea it was that hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were tough,'' McDonald said. ``We showed up and they were
hitting us in the mouth. You have to show up and bring it. We
definitely did not do it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something USC's current players promise will not happen
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is looking to come to Hawaii and take a vacation,''
cornerback Kris Richard said. ``No one's looking at them as a light
foe.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in case things do get tough Saturday night, the Trojans
might want to remember it could be a lot worse. Just ask Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, they were notorious about being homers,'' he
said. ``Hawaii and the officials are not noted for their
objectivity. You've got to understand you're not going to get every
call you deserve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9261 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RAVINE03-COX     09-02 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAVINE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 charged with killing teen in Georgia ravine
 &HT;    By Susan Gast
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Ga. _ When 17-year-old Krystal Archer crossed a Morgan
County cow pasture a month ago with her friends, she thought they
were out to gather mushrooms to make hallucinogenic tea.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Archer was tortured for days and killed _ supposedly in
an act of jealousy, authorities say. The crime was so horrendous it
has veteran lawmen shaking their heads and the townspeople of
nearby Madison, just 50 miles east of downtown Atlanta, talking
about little else.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is not a death penalty case, I've never seen one,''
said Maj. Michael Pritchett of the Morgan County Sheriff's
Department. Pritchett found Archer's body Tuesday after one of
three people later charged with the slaying told a law enforcement
agency he knew a woman had been killed by someone he knew.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Hubbard, 18, formerly of Athens, and Michael
Christopher Teal, 19, and Timothy Curtis Cole, 21, both of
Covington, are charged with aggravated assault and felony murder in
Archer's death, Pritchett said.
</P>
<P>
   The young men are being held in the Morgan County Jail; Hubbard
has been sent to Newton County because Morgan County does not have
a facility for women inmates, Pritchett said.
</P>
<P>
   Archer had been dating Cole, and Hubbard was dating Teal,
Pritchett said. The four had visited Madison to eat at a Chinese
restaurant, go to the Wal-Mart and spend the night at a motel, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard had been living with Teal in Covington, although her
family lives in Athens, Pritchett said.
</P>
<P>
   Between July 31 and the first week of August, the friendship
between the foursome changed.
</P>
<P>
   The exact dates that the events occurred are murky because the
suspects said they ``stayed high'' most of the time after the first
day, Pritchett said.
</P>
<P>
   According to statements Hubbard, Teal and Cole made to
investigators, the four young people jumped a fence one afternoon
sometime that week and crossed the field beside Brobston Lane,
south of Interstate 20. They told Archer they were looking for
mushrooms, something some of them had done there before. They
walked into woods 100 yards away. That's where the outing suddenly
turned violent, Pritchett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard physically attacked Archer because she thought the girl
``had been eyeing'' Teal, Pritchett said. Teal and Cole joined in
the fray, pushing Archer repeatedly down a 20-foot ravine into a
creek, the officer said. The three suspects spent four hours that
afternoon hitting Archer with rocks and branches, breaking bones
and bruising her, and pushing her back down the bank when she tried
to climb out, Pritchett said. They set her hair on fire, took her
clothes and left her naked, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The three returned the next day, beat her again, piled rocks and
sticks on her, then left her again, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   After days of lying in 6 to 8 inches of creek water, slipping in
and out of consciousness, with an eye so severely injured that she
could barely see, Archer thought help had finally come, Pritchett
said the suspects told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you find me?'' Pritchett said she asked, as she
crawled toward the people approaching her. But help had not
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the bad guys again,'' Pritchett said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer said Cole admitted that this time he approached
Archer and stabbed her in the back twice as she lay on her stomach.
Then he ``got her by the hair, slit her throat, turned her over and
left her,'' Pritchett said.
</P>
<P>
   By Aug. 4, Archer was reported missing by her father in
Elberton. Juvenile Court authorities investigating her
disappearance talked with the three friends because Archer was
known to have spent time with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that is what got them to decide they better
come out and say something, or if (Cole's) conscience got to
working on him,'' Pritchett said.
</P>
<P>
   Cole started telling a ``vague'' story about his knowing ``a guy
named Lance'' who had killed someone, Pritchett said. Cole did not
at first admit to involvement in the crime he was reporting.
Finally Cole went to the Madison County Sheriff's Department with
his story. The sheriff there contacted Morgan County authorities
and brought Cole there to lead them to the body Tuesday, Pritchett
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two other suspects were arrested Tuesday night, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The butcher knife used to kill Archer was discovered by Newton
County Sheriff's Department divers in the Yellow River in
Porterdale, 10-15 miles from where her body was found, Pritchett
said. The knife matches a set of knives belonging to Hubbard's
family in Athens, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Divers also recovered ``several'' firearms that Pritchett said
were reported missing earlier by Archer's father in Elberton.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy results were not complete Thursday, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Michael Gailey said he hopes to
bring the case to the grand jury next week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
