<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CLINTON-HOUSE-ART-     09-02 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-HOUSE-ART-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: SUBS thruout to include many additional details, including
the bidding process, the names of the sellers and the adjustable
interest rate.) THE CLINTONS SETTLE ON ANOTHER WHITE HOUSE  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKANEATELES, N.Y. _ President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton
on Thursday settled the question of where the first family will
live once their lease on the White House expires, signing a
contract to purchase a a $1.7 million, 11-room Dutch Colonial home
set in the wooded suburbs of Westchester County, north of New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of a home in New York removes one of the chief
obstacles in Mrs. Clinton's path as she prepares for a run for the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons, indebted by over $5 million in legal bills that
have accumulated because of the legal inquires that have marked the
Clinton presidency, were able to purchase the five-bedroom home in
Chappaqua after Clinton's chief fund-raiser, Terry McAuliffe,
personally secured the loan.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said that McAuliffe had put up $1.35 million of
his own money with Bankers Trust. Under the terms of the mortgage,
McAuliffe will receive the money back, with interest, once the
Clintons either pay back the mortgage or, as is more likely,
refinance it in five years.
</P>
<P>
   The interest rate on the loan is to be determined at closing,
which is set for Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution of where the Clintons would live was announced in
a three-paragraph statement issued by the temporary Press Office of
the White House _ a room in the Holiday Inn in Auburn, about seven
miles from the Clintons are vacationing.
</P>
<P>
   It apparently concludes what has certainly been one of the more
unusual house-hunting expeditions embarked on by any American
family, complicated by the Clintons' station in life, the fact that
they have now owned a home in 16 years, and Mrs. Clinton's
political ambitions in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased about the house,'' Mrs. Clinton said as she
left a fund-raiser for her presumed Senate campaign Thursday
evening in Cazenovia and headed to another one in Syracuse. ``It's
beautiful. We like it a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, emerging from the Syracuse fund-raiser, Mrs. Clinton
declared to cheers: ``As of today, Bill Clinton and I are the
newest homeowners in the state of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' she added, ``we're so happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice of a house came after the Clintons, trailed by a
presidential-size entourage of assistants, Secret Service agents
and reporters, toured homes in New Rochelle, Greenberg, Purchase,
Mamaroneck and Pound Ridge, all in Westchester County. They spent
two hours in the Chappaqua house last Saturday; Mrs. Clinton had
seen the home before, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about this was normal _ except that they are the
first family,'' said Kathy Sloane, a broker with Brown Harris
Stevens in Manhattan, who guided the Clintons through the process.
</P>
<P>
   The house was shown to the public for only three days. After
that, Dr. Jeffrey Weisberg and his wife Cheryl, who have owned the
home for just over 18 years, invited closed bids on the house. The
bids were opened at 3 p.m. on Sunday, and the Clintons were
informed shortly thereafter that the Weisbergs were prepared to
sell to them, according to family associates.
</P>
<P>
   Eight bids were submitted on the house, according to family
associates. It was unclear last night whether the Clintons, who
offered just over the $1.675 million asking price, had made the
highest bid.
</P>
<P>
   There was a clear sense of relief Thursday among Mrs. Clinton's
political advisers, who are concerned that charges of carpetbagging
could hurt the first lady, since she has never lived in New York.
Her likely Republican opponent, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, traveled to
Arkansas to underscore the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has begun to visit New York regularly, but her
trips have been marked by images that have made her campaign
advisers wince _ of her either leaving to return to Washington, or
spending the night as a guest of friends and supporters.
Accordingly, the first lady's advisers have been pressing her to
settle on a house as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The closing date is Nov. 1. Mrs. Clinton's aides said the first
lady would begin spending a good amount of time there as soon as
possible after that. (One complication of the Clintons' nomadic
ways is that they don't have enough of their own furniture to fill
a house, particularly one this size, a friend of the family said.)
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, said that for the
remainder of Clinton's term, the president and Mrs. Clinton
intended to treat their Chappaqua home much the way other First
Families have treated their own private residences. ``The Clintons
will continue to live in the White House,'' Lockhart said in a
telephone interview from Washington. ``As with other presidents,
this house will be their private home and they will spend as much
time there as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   New York elections tend to be decided in the suburbs, which Mrs.
Clinton will now call home. But Mrs. Clinton's aides said that
while political considerations entered the Clintons' deliberations,
they were not predominant. That said, the Clintons clearly avoided
communities like Scarsdale and Bedford, which are well-known across
New York as among the state's wealthiest suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chappaqua, if not quite as well-known as Scarsdale, is
known as one of the more exclusive, and upper-middle-class, bedroom
communities of Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, the Clintons will put down $350,000
on the $1.7 million house, drawn from their blind trust, Lockhart
said. That represents a down payment of about 20 percent. The
remaining financing comes in the form of a securities-backed
mortgage from Bankers Trust for $1.35 million.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the collateral on the loan is $1.35 million put up
by McAuliffe. Thus, this transaction seems to assure McAuliffe, who
is already one of the president's closest friends and supporters, a
significant role in Clintons' financial life after he leaves
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe has a reputation Washington as a singularly effective
fund-raiser, and he is largely credited with the fund-raising
successes of both Clinton and the Democratic Party during Clinton's
years in office. The fact that the president and Mrs. Clinton
turned to him now is hardly a surprise: McAuliffe is already
serving as the key fund-raiser for Mrs. Clinton's presumed Senate
race, the president's legal defense fund, and a $10 million
millennium celebration the Clintons are planning for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe did not return a page last night.
</P>
<P>
   The secured-mortgage arrangement was described by other real
estate brokers last night as slightly unusual, but not unheard of.
Most of all, it seemed a reflection of the Clintons' financial
bind: Notwithstanding the obvious earning potential of an
ex-president, White House aides said the family had assets of just
over $1 million and legal debts of about $5.2 million. As a result,
one of the president's associates said, banks were a little bit
wary about providing such a large a mortgage without some extra
security.
</P>
<P>
   This loan is a five-year balloon mortgage, which means that the
Clintons will have to refinance (or pay back the entire amount) in
five years. It is an adjustable rate that can change every six
months, and will equal one point above the London Interbank Offered
Rate, which is the rate that the most credit-worthy international
banks charge each other for large loans.
</P>
<P>
   The current rate is 5.52 percent. Based on this, the Clintons
would pay an interest rate of 6.52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that the White House counsel's office had ruled
that McAuliffe's guarantee did not fall under the provisions of
federal gift reporting laws and thus did not have to be listed on
the Clintons' annual disclosure report.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House counsel's office,
said he could not comment on whether that would change if the
Clintons defaulted on the loan, and McAuliffe lost his money.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a hypothetical question, and I don't have an answer to
that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
