<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TIGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' ZIMMERMAN RATTLED, AND TIGERS ROLL IN 8TH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Right-hander Jeff Zimmerman lost his composure.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not all the Rangers' All-Star middle reliever would
lose during yesterday's decisive eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman lost two fly balls to Tiger Stadium's matinee audience
and the ballgame after] shortstop Deivi Cruz crushed an 0-2 slider
for a game-winning, two-run home run during Detroit's 8-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed in what happened,'' said Zimmerman, who
inherited a three-run, eighth-inning lead. ``I didn't get the job
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The meltdown's origin could be traced to Detroit's first at-bat
of the inning. Designated hitter Bobby Higginson launched the
second of his two solo home runs on a 2-2 fastball intended to jam
the left-handed batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that \Rticked\S me off,'' Zimmerman said. ``I got
pretty angry at myself. I knew how I wanted to pitch him and made a
mistake. I got mad at myself, and I didn't get over it right away.
It affected the rest of my outing.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman flogged himself for what could have been a meaningless
home run and that set up an afternoon ``hard to describe,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers continued their rally with an ensuing double by Juan
Encarnacion, who coasted into second base after Rangers right
fielder Juan Gonzalez lost the fly ball in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Encarnacion eventually scored on a one-out single by catcher
Bill Haselman, and that brought yesterday's hero to the plate. Cruz
dug himself into an 0-2 count, and Zimmerman's attempt to throw one
of his usually devastating sliders backfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to strike him out,'' Zimmerman said. ``I figured I
needed the strikeout. I wanted to snap it off and put it in the
dirt and get him to swing at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The scorecard will show that Zimmerman went 1-for-3 in the
goal-setting department.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great learning experience,'' Zimmerman said.
``That's usually the case when you get \Rit\S handed to you.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the Rangers went in search of a game-tying run during the
ninth inning despite home runs from Royce Clayton, Rusty Greer,
Rafael Palmeiro and Todd Zeile earlier in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton set the table with a leadoff double and advanced to
third on a sacrifice bunt by Tom Goodwin. Yet, the Rangers failed
to score the runner from third with less than two outs. Detroit
closer Todd Jones recorded his 22nd save by retiring Mark McLemore
and Ivan Rodriguez with three-pitch strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   That signaled the end of a strange, strange afternoon in the
Rangers' final game at historic Tiger Stadium that produced:
</P>
<P>
   the fly ball Gonzalez lost in the sun;
</P>
<P>
   a seventh-inning fly ball that dropped between Greer and Goodwin
because of a miscommunication;
</P>
<P>
   a fourth-inning double by Encarnacion that scored Damion Easley
from first base despite Greer's claim that a spectator interfered
with a ball in play. Interference would have resulted in a
ground-rule double and prevented Easley from crossing the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the ``Twilight Zone'' out there,'' Oates said.
``It was just a weird day.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoring on Zimmerman, though, continues to happen with
increasing frequency. Zimmerman has been scored upon during six of
his past 14 appearances and has a 6.15 earned-run average for that
period.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 27-year-old rookie must show he can adjust to the
adjustments made by American League hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Randy Johnson has to change the way he pitches
sometimes,'' Oates said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
