r s BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     09-02 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RANGERS ASK WHY SO MANY SEATS EMPTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers president Jim Lites was talking
yesterday about his marketing Doberman, Jeff Cogen. He's the guy
who is paid for his butts-in-seats expertise at baseball and hockey
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how Cogen is,'' Lites said. ``Every empty seat is a
personal insult. An empty seat is his enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Give it a month, when the Stars begin another Stanley Cup
crusade, and Cogen will have nothing but ``friends'' at Reunion
Arena. All 41 home games are expected to sell out.
</P>
<P>
   But in the baseball half of Tom Hicks' sports empire, for which
Lites and Cogen pull double duty, life is not that comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the most recent Rangers' homestand against top draws
Boston and the Yankees, Cogen had some 48,000 enemies to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   The average attendance for those six games was 37,000-plus, and
only one crowd reached a 46,000 capacity at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not bad, but I can't say we weren't disappointed,''
Lites said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Lites was disappointed, and he was hardly alone. The best
marketing strategy in sports is a winning product on the field, the
court or the ice. Since the All-Star break in mid-July, no Rangers
team in 28 years has played better, even with the disaster in
Detroit this week. And the Yankees are the best road draw in the
game, with the Red Sox in the top five also.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I don't want to do is overreact, particularly not having
gone through a full season yet,'' Lites said. ``But we are doing
the most comprehensive surveys and studies that are available. We
want to find out what our fans think.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been well over a decade, going back to old Arlington
Stadium, since attendance ``problems'' have been mentioned in
conjunction with the Rangers. The overall fan base has always been
solid. Now, however, some concern is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   As a holiday weekend homestand opens tonight against the White
Sox, to be followed by the Indians, the gate is down 88,000 from a
year ago. But that's easily explained. In the prime attendance
month of June, the Rangers had only eight home games. The average
is usually 13 to 15.
</P>
<P>
   But with 17 August home games, when the team was on a tear, the
crowds averaged just over 32,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do want to find out why,'' Lites said.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of reasons are available _ the heat wave of August;
raising ticket prices for three consecutive seasons left the paying
customers feeling gouged; the Cowboys and the Stars have won four
world championships in the '90s and the fans now wait for the
Rangers to show their postseason worth.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the dumbest theory of all _ that the ballpark
should have been built in downtown Dallas. Hicks is going through
political hell over a downtown sports arena that barely passed at
the polls, and this was with a hotel-rental car tax. Financing a
ballpark in Dallas through a sales tax, as Arlington did, is
laughable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'd want to wager on that,'' deadpanned Lites,
who has been involved in the political wars for the downtown arena
since Day One.
</P>
<P>
   But have baseball ticket prices turned off the fans? A Tom Hicks
says no _ sorta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our surveys don't show that,'' the owner said. ``But this is a
partnership with the fans. In pricing tickets, you have to have the
right balance of what is right for us and what is right for the
fans. At the moment, it might not be in balance.''
</P>
<P>
   For next season, Lites promised a reduction in ticket prices,
but ...
</P>
<P>
   He also didn't promise that some seats wouldn't be raised even
higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at our seating, wanting to know where people
don't buy,'' Lites said. ``In certain areas of the park, prices
will be down \Rnext season\S. But where there's heavy demand, do we
raise those prices? I don't know yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a team that's going to have an $80 million to $90
million payroll. The fans want a competitive club. To achieve that
in baseball, tickets can't be cheap. But what's fair?''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, the Rangers lag miles behind a Cleveland or a
Baltimore in season-ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're under 12,000 for full-season \Rsales\S,'' Lites said.
``As of right now, the Stars will sell more full-season tickets
than the Rangers. Our most aggressive campaign of all will be in
season tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   But the shortage there leads to one of the large positives for
the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Lites said: ``I strongly believe the Rangers sell more
individual tickets \Rper game\S than any team in baseball. Or any
team in professional sports, for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Business is good. But more friends are needed.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
