<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9266 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY03-COX     09-02 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley tries to distinguish himself from Gore in Ohio
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley brought his
presidential campaign to Ohio on Thursday to advocate for campaign
finance reform and gun control, pick up an endorsement and raise
the dollars he needs to compete with Vice President Al Gore for the
Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohio is a very important state in the presidential election
this year . . . I will be back to Ohio often in the coming
months,'' Bradley said at Port Columbus airport.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said, however, that he expects the vice president, who
has been coming to Ohio for presidential campaigns since 1988, to
pick up more endorsements from officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   The former New Jersey senator and New York Knicks' basketball
star began his Buckeye swing in Cleveland, where he picked up the
endorsement of Cuyahoga County Commissioner Tim McCormack.
</P>
<P>
   While there, Bradley told the Associated Press that
taxpayer-funded vouchers won't solve the problem of poor quality
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think school vouchers are the answer to the problems
of public education,'' he said. A state-funded voucher program is
the subject of a court debate in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said such programs have problems, ``not the least of
which are issues of church and state,'' that must be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he voted twice for federally funded experimental
voucher programs. Neither bill became law.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Bradley, 56, was to attend a fund-raiser at the
home of Columbus attorney Harrison Smith. Those attending were
asked to contribute $1,000 each but Bob McAlister, an attorney and
Democratic party activist who helped coordinate the event, said he
did not know how many would be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been pleased to this point,'' said McAlister.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he differs from Gore on major issues, Bradley said he
has taken a tougher stand on gun control. He advocates registration
and licensing of all handguns, banning gun dealers from selling
weapons in residential neighborhoods and outlawing the manufacture,
sale, distribution and possession of cheap handguns known as
``Saturday Night Specials.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a position I had long before Columbine,'' he said,
referring to the April 20 incident at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., where two students killed 13 people and then
themselves in a shooting rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also said that his proposals for campaign finance reform
go further than the vice president's.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Ruvolo, former Ohio Democratic chairman who's helping
coordinate Gore's Ohio campaign, said that Gore is ``not soft on
guns'' and, like Bradley, has called for banning ``soft money'' _
unregulated and unlimited contributions to political parties _ but
only if Republicans go along.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to unilaterally disarm,'' Ruvolo said of
Gore and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   McAlister said that Bradley's ``winnability'' will help him
overcome Gore in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need a kind of restoration of the presidency. I
just don't see that happening with a continuation of this (Clinton)
administration,'' said McAlister.
</P>
<P>
   Ruvolo, who stressed that he is not an official spokesman for
the Gore campaign, said that a ``vigorous'' campaign before the
March 7 primary will be good for Democrats because it will stir
interest in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both good people,'' said Ruvolo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
