<HEADER>
A9360 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-ARKANSAS-BURLSWOR     09-02 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARKANSAS-BURLSWORTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARKANSAS RAZORBACKS CARRY MEMORY OF LATE TEAMMATE WITH THEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shoulder pads still sit on top of the locker, as if waiting
for Brandon Burlsworth to walk in, yank them down, and strap them
on one more time.
</P>
<P>
   The game uniform and distinctive red helmet hang inside the
locker, as they did during the four years Burlsworth spent molding
himself into a star at the University of Arkansas. Several pairs of
shoes are arranged neatly on the top shelf, along with the big
guard's trademark dark glasses.
</P>
<P>
   But although it sits in the middle of the Razorbacks' dressing
room, the locker _ now encased in glass _ is no longer functional.
It is a shrine ... a memorial to a lost teammate. The shoulder pads
will never move again, and Burlsworth is gone ... forever.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as Arkansas prepares to open the 1999 season against
SMU on Saturday night in the Cotton Bowl, it is almost as if
Burlsworth _ who died in a car crash 11 days after being drafted by
Indianapolis in April _ is as important to the Razorbacks in spirit
as he once was anchoring the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a feeling that a lot of what this team
accomplished last year came through Burls,'' said quarterback Clint
Stoerner, ``and that now, he is still a part of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was ... an unbelievable tragedy, but his memory
is still alive. I think Burls will be a part of Arkansas football
from now on. I don't think this school will ever forget him, and
that's fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The season has not been officially dedicated to Burlsworth, but
the ``Doing It The Burls' Way'' T-shirts worn by the team proved to
be the most visibly arresting sight during two-a-days. Arkansas has
retired only one jersey _ Clyde Scott's _ in its history, but
Burlsworth's No. 77 will be honored during homecoming ceremonies
this year.
</P>
<P>
   There is a feeling among many that he was the best Arkansas ever
had. Not the best player _ in spite of his All-Southeastern
Conference and All-America credentials and the conviction of the
Colts that he could start in the NFL as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Just the best, period. And it was that quality that added to the
shock of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up nearby to Fayetteville in Harrison, Ark., the child
of a broken marriage, he eventually reconciled with his father
while remaining devoted to his mother, Barbara. Together, they
bought him a car when he graduated from high school.
</P>
<P>
   He also developed a deep love for the Razorbacks, but when
Arkansas coaches first saw him, he was 6 feet tall and weighed only
200 pounds. Although he subsequently grew three inches, he was told
he needed to be a lot heavier to play at that level.
</P>
<P>
   The next time they saw him, as a walk-on nine months later, he
weighed 308 pounds. He finished his career at Arkansas with a
scholarship, two academic degrees, a 3.4 grade-point average, and
34 consecutive starts in the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, he never spent one day of that time behaving
like a star. Next to a question in the media guide, ``If you could
spend a day anywhere in the world, where would you go?'' he wrote,
``Harrison, because it's a nice town.'' He frequently drove back to
spend a night at home and go to church with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just seemed almost too good to be true,'' said Arkansas
coach Houston Nutt. ``He wasn't a talker, but he was the kind of
person that the others looked up to and followed _ probably because
they had never known anyone like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't drink, he didn't smoke, he never said a foul word
... he was totally unselfish. He had a work ethic that was just
unbelievable. He was always the first one out and the last one in.
He put in extra practice on his own. He did every drill, even if he
was sick or hurting. If you told him to do five sprints, he did
seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``With him, it was total dedication, total commitment. He came
here five years ago as a walk-on, became an All-American, and
earned his regular degree \Rmarketing management\S and a master's
\Rbusiness administration\S. But the biggest thing about him was,
he was just such a great person.''
</P>
<P>
   For Nutt, the Burlsworth memory that will stick with him from a
spectacular turnaround season (from 4-7 to 9-3) came in the team's
darkest moment _ when quarterback Clint Stoerner's late fumble
allowed Tennessee to escape almost certain defeat and salvage a
victory in a showdown of unbeatens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clint handled it well, standing there answering question after
question from the media during the postgame,'' Nutt said. ``But
after a few minutes, Burls stepped in and explained to everyone
that he had actually caused the fumble, because Clint stumbled over
his foot after taking the snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the truth, but the thing that impressed me was that
Burls wasn't going to stand there and let a teammate get crucified
alone. That's just the way he was.''
</P>
<P>
   For senior guard Jeremiah Washburn, it remains painful to
remember the way Burlsworth was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't cry for a month,'' he said. ``I just stayed in
denial; I couldn't believe it. Every day, I kept expecting him to
walk through the door, to prove that it wasn't true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never experienced this before. At our age, you sometimes
have to deal with the death of a loved one, but it's always someone
who's much older. This is the first time I've lost someone this
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a long time to accept the truth and break down. I
miss my friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess with everything that's been said and written about
him, people may have the idea that he was some kind of uptight `Mr.
Perfect' guy, but he wasn't that way at all _ he just didn't make a
big deal out of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really a laid-back person, having fun and enjoying life
and enjoying his friends, with a great future ahead of him. He was
a man's man.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, his mother's son. On the day he died, Burlsworth was going
home to have dinner and attend church with Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicably, on a road he had traveled countless times, his
Subaru drifted across the center line, bounced off a
tractor-trailer rig and ran head-on into another, which drove his
car 168 feet backward. At 22, his perfect life was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it mean, the stuff on the T-shirt?'' Stoerner asked.
``I guess it just means trying to do everything the way it should
be done. To help your team and your teammates, and to put that goal
above your personal achievements. But I hope that in the future,
what people remember is the way he lived his life, because that's
what's really important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to accept, and although I know what happened to
Burls, I still sometimes catch myself thinking that ... maybe he's
still out there somewhere, playing.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
