r s BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-SPECIAL     09-02 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-SPECIAL-TEAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M OOZES WITH CONFIDENCE ABOUT ITS SPECIAL TEAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ With hardly a qualifier, Texas A&AMP;M
coach R.C. Slocum said this week he would not break a sweat if he
knew that the Aggies' kicking game would be the determining factor
in either a repeat Big 12 championship or a national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd feel good about it,'' Slocum said, days away from the
season opener against Louisiana Tech in Shreveport, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got punt returners, kickoff guys, a great punter \RShane
Lechler\S who is one the best I've ever been around and probably
one of the top ones ever in college football. No one is going to
have a better punter. So that's pretty good right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum knows he can count on Lechler _ a returning first-team
All-American and consensus All-Big 12 choice. Dante Hall, Chris
Taylor and Jason Webster all are experienced hands at returning
punts and kickoffs. Sophomore Bethel Johnson eventually could add
an exciting dimension to either aspect.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two unknown elements in the Aggies' kicking game _
an incoming freshman deep snapper and a junior walk-on place-kicker
whose varsity experience is one extra-point kick in two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman walk-on Chance Pearce inherits the deep snapper's job
from four-year regular Kyle Lednicky _ whose reliability caused
Slocum to nickname him ``Jugs'' after the pitching machine of the
same name.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Terrence Kitchens became A&AMP;M's place-kicker this summer
after junior veteran Russell Bynum failed a random off-season drug
test that showed elevated levels of testosterone. Bynum has
appealed his suspension for medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said Pearce came highly recommended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw \Rformer legendary Brownwood coach\S Gordon Wood this
summer and we were talking about the fact we have three players
from Brownwood on our team,'' Slocum said. ``He said, `The guy who
is going to help you more than anyone is the snapper. He's really
good.' And I feel good about him, too. Chance has been very
consistent for us so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not seen Terrence kick \Ra field goal\S in a game, but
he's really been consistent this summer all during two-a-days, as
consistent as anyone we've had. At this stage, I feel every bit as
good about the overall kicking game as I did this time a year
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Bynum successfully kicked his first five field goals and
converted his last nine on the way to a 16-for-20 season in 1998.
He hit 30 of 31 PATs. Kitchens' lone contribution as a backup was a
PAT against North Texas after falling out of competition with a hip
flexor injury in the spring of '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's been asking me if I'm nervous,'' Kitchens said.
``Actually, I'm excited and anxious. I'm ready to get the season
started. Everyone's been real supportive and that's helped take the
pressure off. I feel more relaxed, more excited than nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Lechler holds for both PATs and field goals. He also kicks off
and is the long-range field goal designate. He isn't worried about
Kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   ``His timing is good, he has good leg strength and his accuracy
is good right now,'' Lechler said. ``He doesn't have more range
than Russell, \Rwhose\S leg had a lot of pop. But Terrance is more
consistent. From 40 yards in, you can almost mark it up. He'll hit
it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
