<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9364 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-WACO-RENO-FREEH-1STLD     09-02 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-RENO-FREEH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN BEFORE WACO TAPES, RENO-FBI RELATIONSHIP WAS STRAINED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS: Inserts `of the Clinton administration' in lede graf;
rewrites 2nd graf; inserts new 3rd graf; adds sentence to 9th graf,
bgng: It was over...)  (With WACO-INQUIRY) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the early years of the Clinton administration,
their aides portrayed Janet Reno and Louis Freeh as one of the
capital's perfect power pairings _ a tough, down-to-earth attorney
general who was happy to have the ex-FBI agent, former Mafia
prosecutor and federal judge as her chief law enforcement officer.
</P>
<P>
   But officials who know them both said the image never really fit
the reality, and, in recent days, the disclosures that the FBI used
heat-generating tear-gas canisters in the April 1993 assault on the
Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, and then failed to
produce tape recordings from its files confirming that fact, has
split open a seam of discontent.
</P>
<P>
   These tensions have grown slowly over the years as Freeh and
senior FBI officials effectively undercut Reno on high-profile
issues like the appointment of an independent counsel to
investigate political fund raising and the national security
inquiry involving the Los Alamos nuclear scientist, Wen Ho Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict between Reno, Freeh and their two agencies was
apparent Wednesday afternoon when Reno angrily dispatched agents of
the U.S. Marshal's Service to Freeh's headquarters to seize
previously undisclosed tapes that contained radio voice
communications of agents asking for and receiving authorization
from their operational commanders to fire the tear-gas rounds at
Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, FBI officials complained that Reno ordered the
marshals to take custody of the tapes in a way that left a powerful
impression that Reno no longer believed the FBI could be trusted.
``It was a heavy-handed thing to do,'' said one law enforcement
official. ``Like the FBI was going to destroy the evidence?''
</P>
<P>
   The White House sided with Reno in blaming the FBI for the
lapses that placed her in an extremely awkward position. ``The
president is deeply concerned that the attorney general appears to
have been misled and may have been lied to,'' Jake Siewert, a White
House spokesman, said Thursday. ``She has vowed to get to bottom of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reno's own credibility has been grievously damaged.
Republicans in Congress blamed her, not the FBI, for misleading
them about potentially relevant evidence. She had opened herself to
criticism because it was not the FBI, but the Justice Department,
that led what seemed to some officials like half-hearted internal
inquiries into Waco on which she based her long-held conclusion
that there was no possibility the FBI could have started the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the new evidence that has remained in the FBI files for
more than six years does not contradict Reno's conclusions. As FBI
officials reconstructed events, the two flammable tear gas rounds
were fired hours before the assault and landed harmlessly at a
bunker near the compound before the fire started that killed about
80 people, including many children.
</P>
<P>
   It was over Waco that Reno first encountered the powerful
bureaucracy of the FBI. She took office in March 1993 when William
Sessions was the FBI director. Freeh became director in September
1993, and led the agency through the aftermath of the Texas
assault.
</P>
<P>
   At first, FBI officials were skeptical of Reno, a moderate
former Miami prosecutor, but they were won over by her stalwart
defense of the agency's conduct at Waco. She took personal
responsibility for the outcome, blamed the Branch Davidians for
starting the fire and rebuffed all criticism of the FBI's
military-style tactics in the tear-gas assault operation.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, some associates of Reno and Freeh denied that there
was any personal animosity between the two officials or that they
would acknowledge that professional trust in each other had eroded.
But even these officials acknowledged that senior FBI officials had
gradually lost confidence in Reno and that she had grown frustrated
by the law enforcement agency's independence.
</P>
<P>
   Other current and former Justice Department and FBI officials
said the disclosures regarding the use of pyrotechnic tear gas at
Waco represented a final straw to Reno after years of simmering
disputes with the FBI over its independent dealings with Congress
in budget, legislative, national security and investigative
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship seemed to sour after news accounts reported in
1997 that Freeh had urged Reno to seek an independent prosecutor to
investigate how the Democrats financed their 1996 presidential
election campaign _ a position that badly undercut Reno, already
under heavy fire from Republicans in Congress who had attacked her
for refusing to refer the case to an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Reno's own prosecutor on the campaign finance
inquiry, Charles La Bella, resigned saying he agreed with the FBI
director on the issue of an outside counsel, Reno's credibility
eroded further. La Bella subsequently lost a bid to become U.S.
attorney in San Diego. Later, Freeh awarded La Bella the FBI's
distinguished service medal in a ceremony that Reno did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, tensions between top officials ignited again
in a bitter crossfire over the handling of an investigation of a
nuclear scientist at the Los Alamos laboratory in New Mexico. FBI
officials said they had appealed to Reno for permission to begin
electronic surveillance of the scientist, Wen Ho Lee, but Justice
Department officials rejected their request.
</P>
<P>
   Reno angrily replied that FBI officials, including Freeh, had
failed to inform her that the application for surveillance was a
top priority _ even as Republicans in Congress again assailed her
for holding back an inquiry into the suspected theft of highly
classified nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been too forgiving by nature,'' said one law enforcement
official with associates at the Justice Department and the FBI.
``There's a feeling that she just hasn't reigned them in and that
now it may be too late for her to take back control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
