<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 CLINTONS' VACATION RAISES MONEY, BUT DOES IT WIN VOTES? 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CLINTON-HOUSE) 
 (bl)  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKANEATELES, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton's theoretical
vacation moved toward its end Thursday with two fund-raisers that
brought the receipts from her 15 days of supposed respite to more
than $800,000 for her undeclared U.S. Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raisers, one at Mulrooney's Bar and Restaurant in
Syracuse and the other on the Cazenovia lakeside lawn of Edward
Green, a lawyer and Syracuse real estate developer, were the fifth
and sixth such events of Mrs. Clinton's vacation, after two last
weekend in Long Island's Hamptons and one each in Massachusetts'
Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard. Meanwhile, the largely Republican
citizens of this once quiet but now celebrity-struck village began
to complain that they hadn't seen enough of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of this community have put a lot into this visit,
and we haven't had any visiting time,'' said Kathleen Palmieri, 47,
a cardiovascular laboratory consultant and a registered Republican
who has spent much of the last four days waiting on Skaneateles
Street corners with her 9-year-old son for a sight of the first
lady, President Clinton or their daughter, Chelsea. ``I've been
doing it since he got here _ stalking! I feel like I've done
nothing productive. I have no billable hours this week, let's put
it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Palmieri's frustration was echoed up and down Genesee
Street, the village's gift-shop-heavy main thoroughfare, where in
the days before the Clintons' vacation many residents said they
were either bored or irritated by the visit. But after seeing the
presidential motorcade zoom through town, and watching the kind of
saturation coverage of the Clintons on local television that most
New York political candidates can only dream of, the village seemed
swept away by its small part in history. Irritated people now seem
to be those who feel they were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's not something that happens here very often, so
it's big news,'' said Ron Lombard, the news director of WIXT's
Channel 9, the ABC affiliate in Syracuse. On Monday, WIXT broke
into its regular programming three times with extensive live
reports of the Clintons' arrival in Syracuse and their visit to the
New York State Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Lombard said that the last sitting president to visit the
Syracuse area was Gerald R. Ford during a quick campaign stop in
1976, and that the last sitting president to visit the state fair
was Theodore Roosevelt in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Clintons' celebrity status upstate translates into
votes for the first lady is still a big question. While the
vacation has clearly brought Mrs. Clinton enormous and constant
front-page exposure _ The Post-Standard, the Syracuse morning
newspaper, even included the news that Buddy, the presidential dog,
escaped from the Clintons' borrowed home for a few minutes Tuesday
_ many voters said this week that, in essence, they were more
sophisticated than to vote for a woman simply because she had
chosen their village for a vacation, no matter how beautiful she
said it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was undecided before, and I'm still undecided,'' said
Shirley Whitbread, 60, who described herself as a retired homemaker
and an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Others were skeptical of the vacation itself. ``I think it's
nice that they came to vacation here,'' said Anne Alcott, 38,
manager of the Banana Republic store in Syracuse and a registered
Republican. ``I just hope that there isn't an ulterior motive _
which I think there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alcott said she was more impressed with New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, who is Mrs. Clinton's likely Republican opponent.
``He's not from Little Rock, you know?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Giuliani does not seem overwhelmingly popular here
either, and is seen by many as the personification of New York
City, which is often viewed as that big, bad city that considers
upstate New York of no more interest than Ohio.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I was in New York City once and it was a big mess,'' said
Curtis Quinn, 17, who was waiting Wednesday to see the Clintons
across the street from the Women's Rights National Historical Park
in Seneca Falls. Quinn, who will be old enough to vote in 2000,
when Mrs. Clinton presumably will be running, said he didn't like
Giuliani and was still mad because his car was towed while he was
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   One person who did seem to have some fun during Mrs. Clinton's
vacation was Mrs. Clinton herself. On Wednesday, while buying a
French vanilla decaf at the Vermont Green Mountain Coffee Specialty
Company in Skaneateles, Mrs. Clinton, who grew up in suburban
Chicago, told reporters that she was having a great time in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me so much of where I spent my childhood because I
spent every summer at the little lake in northeast Pennsylvania,''
she said. ``The nights were cool, and the mornings were cool, and
it warmed up. It's my favorite kind of weather. It's so nostalgic.
I called my mother last night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons are to leave Friday, by late morning, for
Washington and then Camp David, Md., where they are to spend the
Labor Day weekend resting from their vacation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
