u s BC-BBO-ESPN-NYT &LR;      09-02 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ESPN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ESPN EXPECTS TO WIN BASEBALL SUIT; COMEBACK FOR WIDE
WORLD OF SPORTS; COMEBACK FOR KINER'S KORNER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Yankees-Angels game on Sunday could be the final edition of
ESPN's ``Sunday Night Baseball.'' It will certainly be the last one
this season, pending the outcome of a simmering legal bout between
ESPN and Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect ESPN to mark the occasion with weepy speeches
by Jon Miller and Joe Morgan or a dramatic retrospective of
memorable Bat Speeds past.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us are thinking that,'' said Steve Anderson, ESPN's
executive vice president. ``We fully expect to have baseball back.
It's not just what I'm supposed to say, but from the production
side, we're producing a baseball product, and we feel we'll be
doing it next year. And with Wednesday night games and the
playoffs, we still have a lot of baseball left this year.''
</P>
<P>
   True. But there is the matter of a federal court case in
Manhattan, ESPN vs. Office of the Commissioner of Baseball. The
imbroglio began when ESPN acquired the rights to Sunday night
National Football League games last year. Having paid $600 million
a year for the higher-rated NFL games, ESPN chose to move three
Sunday night baseball games in September to ESPN2. Baseball
screamed and revoked ESPN's right to carry the games last September
and this September.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN argues that it can move the games to ESPN2, which has 11
million fewer subscribers than ESPN's76 million. Baseball says that
it cannot, that no event short of a nuclear attack is worthy of
moving the games to the smaller network.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN sued in May when baseball terminated ESPN's $40
million-a-year regular-season contract after this season, two years
before the contract expires. (The case does not threaten ESPN's
contract to carry playoff games through 2000.)
</P>
<P>
   A trial is scheduled to start Nov. 15. At a pretrial hearing
Tuesday, U.S. District Court Judge Shira A. Scheindlin discouraged
baseball from filing a motion for summary judgment to convince the
court that ESPN's case has no merit (which is pretty much what
baseball has been saying).
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe our rights will be upheld in court and we'll be
able to televise the games on ESPN2,'' Diane Lamb, an ESPN
spokeswoman, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still hope to resolve this,'' Richard Levin, a spokesman
for baseball, said. ``Both sides have talked.'' He did not know if
baseball would accept a settlement that falls short of restoring
all three games to ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   COMEBACK I: OLD `WIDE WORLD'
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, ``Wide World of Sports'' has existed as the brand
for ABC Sports events _ except for ``Monday Night Football'' _ but
not as the storied anthology show that began in 1961. Thankfully,
the grand old bizarre and eclectic days of Acapulco cliff diving,
bikini championships and horses on ice are returning on ESPN
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC Sports archive came with ESPN's acquisition of Classic
for $175 million exactly two years ago. While ABC's college
football games popped up quickly on Classic, the ``Wide World''
oeuvre took longer to revive because the rights to the original
programs belonged to myriad rights-holders.
</P>
<P>
   Classic has produced five hourlong ``Wide World'' shows (with 10
to 13 more in the works), which will be shown on successive Fridays
at 8 p.m., starting Friday with a compilation of seven Evel Knievel
motorcycle jumps. Next week's show features barrel jumping, Joie
Chitwood's auto thrill show and cliff diving, followed on Sept. 17
by Duke Kahanamoku surfing and wrist wrestling. ``The notion is to
get as much offbeat material as possible,'' Vince Doria, Classic's
executive producer, said. ``It's all the stuff that makes you think
about what `Wide World' was.''
</P>
<P>
   Some great heavyweight fights, including Muhammad Ali's, and
segments featuring Howard Cosell will be seen again.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than simply showing old ``Wide Worlds'' intact, Classic
is mining the best events from various shows, repackaging them,
interviewing participants like the host Jim McKay and using Chris
Fowler as the host.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of forget how interesting it all was _ how
interesting, campy and quirky,'' Doria said.
</P>
<P>
   COMEBACK II: `KINER'S KORNER'
</P>
<P>
   If you can resuscitate ``Wide World,'' why not bring ``Kiner's
Korner'' back to life? The original Channel 9 post-game Mets show
with Ralph Kiner as host was a classic: just Ralph and the star or
stars of a game having a cozy chat in a cramped Shea Stadium
studio. Kiner blended insights and malapropisms into a mix
reminiscent of Rocky Marciano's interview and boxing show, ``The
Main Event.''
</P>
<P>
   Channel 9 dumped ``Kiner's Korner'' several years ago, but it
will be back on Fox Sports New York after five Mets games,
beginning Wednesday afternoon. The Korner could return 15 to 20
times next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're 35-plus, and you have pleasant memories of the show,
it seems it would go over well with those folks,'' said Mike
McCarthy, executive producer of FSNY and the MSG Network. ``But
just to watch Ralph's eyes light up when I said we'd do it was
reason enough to bring the show back.''
</P>
<P>
   To be a guest on Kiner's program was ``a real badge of
achievement,'' McCarthy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was for the $50,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Korner's old musical theme will be revived and so may the
long-term sponsor, Rheingold beer. Perhaps Kiner will don a lovely
sports jacket from the Lindsey Nelson collection of plaids,
paisleys and loud colors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
