<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT FIGHT FOR UMPIRES IS OVER CONTROL OF UNION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the legal fight between the umpires union and Major League
Baseball awaits arbitration over the fate of the 22 lost umpires,
the next battle will be intramural _ between two factions for
control of the union.
</P>
<P>
   That fight, which could begin as soon as next week, will take
the form of a move either to seek decertification of the existing
union or certification of a new union to represent all of the
umpires. In either case, the status of the 22 umpires who lost
their on-field jobs at 6 a.m. Thursday will be critical to the
outcome of the move.
</P>
<P>
   Without the 22, the group of umpires opposed to Richie Phillips,
the union leader, believes it will prevail in any sort of vote of
the umpires' bargaining unit. At last survey, the group counted 39
umpires prepared to vote against Phillips. Without the 22 who have
lost their jobs, 32 umpires at most would support Phillips, the
only negotiator the Major League Umpires Association has had.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-Phillips faction is also moving ahead on another front,
intensifying its efforts to obtain information from Phillips on the
union's finances and the payments some umpires receive from Pilot
Air Freight, a Philadelphia company that Phillips operates that
transports much of the equipment for major league umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Phillips, an American League umpire who is no relation to
Richie Phillips, acknowledged Thursday that he wrote a letter on
his and other umpires' behalf to the union leader last week
requesting copies of the union's federal financial disclosure forms
and full disclosure on the Pilot payments. Some other umpires have
identified seven umpires as being on the payroll of the shipping
company: Jerry Crawford, the union president; Richie Garcia, the
vice president; Bruce Froemming, a former vice president; Gerry
Davis; Terry Tata; Steve Rippley, and Drew Coble.
</P>
<P>
   All seven umpires support Richie Phillips _ Garcia and Coble
have lost their jobs as a result of his mass resignation strategy.
Some of those who do not support Phillips contend that there is a
conflict of interest inherent in the Pilot relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Phillips did not return a phone call seeking comment on
the Pilot issue and the move to oust him.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Phillips said he had not received a reply to his letter
from Richie Phillips. ``He doesn't share information with us,''
said the umpire, who has been one of the more active members of the
group trying to change the union's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly looking at all of our options,'' Dave Phillips
said in a telephone interview. ``We have a big task at hand. We're
absolutely saddened that 22 guys lost their jobs by his failed
strategy. We wish he would take responsibility and resign in the
best interest of the union. He's the one who put these men on the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22 umpires were part of a mass resignation devised by Richie
Phillips as a negotiating strategy. The resignations remained in
effect as part of the union's settlement with baseball on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As new umpires began replacing the departed ones, the
anti-Phillips faction continued to plan its course of action. In
previous differences of opinion, Phillips has been able to defuse
the opposition. But this time his opponents appear more determined
to unseat the union's leader.
</P>
<P>
   Indications Thursday were that the anti-Phillips group was
leaning toward trying to have the union decertified, but it could
ask the National Labor Relations Board to oversee a certification
election. Under that scenario, another union, either an existing
one or one created by the insurgent umpires, would challenge the
Major League Umpires Association as the umpires' collective
bargaining agent.
</P>
<P>
   For either effort, the umpires would have to present the labor
board with cards signed by 30 percent of the bargaining unit. If
the insurgents have 39 umpires prepared to vote against Phillips,
they would represent more than 30 percent of the total number of
umpires, even if the 22 were included.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition group would opt for an election sanctioned by the
labor board rather than a vote within the union because of the
difference in the definition of union membership and a bargaining
unit. The union membership is anyone the union considers a member;
the bargaining unit is all the umpires who are working whether they
are union members or not.
</P>
<P>
   An internal union vote would give Phillips more supporters. He
and Crawford, the president, would count the 22 as voting members,
and 17 of the 25 new umpires could not vote because they have not
joined the union.
</P>
<P>
   But the bargaining unit lineup, one scorekeeper said, gives the
dissidents the edge: The anti-Phillips group includes 19
established and 12 new American League umpires and three
established and five new National League umpires, for 39 total. The
pro-Phillips bloc has 28 NL umpires, including eight who are new,
and four veteran AL umpires, making 32.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not involved in the counting of numbers,'' Dave Phillips
said, ``but I'm pretty confident we have a strong majority of our
membership adamantly opposed to Richie Phillips, his failed
strategy and what he's created in 22 guys being fired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
