<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-UMPIRES-LASTGAME-     09-02 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-LASTGAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HIGH TIME TO HOLD UMPIRES ACCOUNTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The four men strolled onto the field at Yankee
Stadium, three clad in red shirts and one wearing a blue shirt,
looking as anonymous as beer vendors. They toiled for almost four
hours, were in proper position, performed as if they cared and were
consistent. Besides Paul O'Neill's routine outburst, no one
complained about the umpires, which is what should happen every
day.
</P>
<P>
   It is unfortunate that 22 major league umpires stopped working
Thursday because it is unfortunate whenever anyone loses his job.
There are emotional stories from suddenly unemployed people about
sick family members, mortgage payments and children's tuition,
whether they are umpires who resigned, truck drivers who angered
the boss, or waiters who were laid off because their restaurant
failed. No one revels in anyone else's plight.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a positive that could and should emerge from the
silly labor strategy that resulted in one-third of the umpires
being released. The umpires have been humbled. They learned in an
emphatic manner that they are not the Ken Griffey Jr.'s of their
profession. They can be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a smattering of guys who have the attitude, `You
can't do that to me,''' Joe Torre admitted before Thursday's game.
``I don't like that. Any time you think you're bigger than the
game, you're not good for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be worthwhile if baseball instituted an evaluation
system in which umpires are judged and held accountable for their
work, like almost every employee in America. Sandy Alderson, the
executive vice president for baseball operations, wants all umpires
to be monitored as one group by Major League Baseball next season.
</P>
<P>
   There should be no more laziness on shots sprayed around the
park, no more inconsistencies on the strike zone, no more baiting
of players by moving toward them to invite confrontation. If these
changes are made, the umpires will enhance their reputations and
the game. The game is what matters, on the field, where the Yankees
pounded the Athletics, 9-3, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal long-term has been for baseball to have a group of
umpires who are well-respected for training, expertise and
integrity,'' Alderson said. ``We want our umpires to be regarded as
the best officials in the world. Right now, that's not the way
they're perceived.''
</P>
<P>
   Perception often becomes reality. It is unfair to characterize
all umpires as inferior, but all it takes is one umpire's
incompetence for an entire crew to be branded. If one ump does not
run into the outfield on a sinking liner, all four look sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not going to care about it, take it home,'' Andy
Pettitte said flatly. ``It's too bad it affected people's
livelihoods. But if anything good comes out of this, maybe it'll be
an evaluation system. All we're asking for is effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Richie Phillips, the embattled head of the umpire's union, has
said that baseball does not care about the game because it accepted
the resignations of umpires with more than 20 years of experience.
That is an easy remark for a desperate man to utter, but it is
untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson cares. He thinks umpires should be supervised more
strictly, wants to include off-season training and educational
seminars as part of their job, and feels the mandated rotation of
umpires in the post-season should be replaced by selection on
merit. If an umpire is ineffective, Alderson believes, baseball
should be permitted to dismiss him, just as in other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is trying to develop a computerized simulator that
would enable umpires to practice calling strikes the way they are
defined in the rule book. That sounds more appealing than the
current behavior of some umpires who, one baseball official said,
work just a few games each spring at their own discretion and then
jump behind the plate rusty in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I hope we can change is the image of the
umpire,'' John Hirschbeck, one of the umpires who led the
anti-Phillips faction, said recently. ``The fans need to know we
care about getting calls right and hustling on every play.''
</P>
<P>
   One umpire told an American League player that umpires who spend
10 years in the minors are like players who do the same and are not
talented enough to be promoted. That is highly questionable,
because there was little turnover among major league umpires before
these resignations. But the umpire insisted his view was accurate
and said all of the best umps were already in the majors. So the
player asked, ``How would we know?'' The umpire had no answer.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said he felt sorry for the departing umpires, and Mark
McGwire was cognizant enough of Frank Pulli's last game on
Wednesday night that he flipped him a game ball. It is a difficult
period for some, but it is also an important period for baseball to
improve the umpiring situation forever and make the game better.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is umpires should be held to the same scrutiny as
the rest of us,'' Torre said. ``Managers don't do their job, they
get fired. Players don't do their job, they go to the minors.
Umpires don't do their job, I don't know what happens. I'd like it
to be the same. Everybody put in a day's work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
