<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MD-MURDER-ISRAEL(TRIM     09-02 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MD-MURDER-ISRAEL(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL CONVICTS U.S. TEEN-AGER AFTER HE ADMITS TO MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Three judges in Tel Aviv on Thursday convicted an
American teen-ager of premeditated murder after he publicly
admitted his guilt in a grisly slaying in Maryland two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager, Samuel Sheinbein, formerly of Silver Spring, Md.,
now awaits sentencing, as the Israeli judges evaluate a plea
agreement in a case that American prosecutors have contended should
never have been tried in an Israeli courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein, who fled to Israel in an effort to avoid prosecution
in Maryland, responded Thursday with a plea of guilty to 10 charges
related to the 1997 strangling and dismembering of Alfredo Enrique
Tello Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Tel Aviv District Court Judge Uri Goren then handed down the
ruling, saying, ``Based on what the defendant admitted to, and
based on the testimony of his father before the grand jury in
Maryland, we convict the defendant of premeditated murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Before reaching a decision on punishment, the panel of three
magistrates presided over by Goren plans to review a report by
Sheinbein's probation officer. The report is not due until
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   But the judges made clear Thursday that they did not necessarily
feel bound by the plea agreement between prosecutors and
Sheinbein's Israeli lawyers, which recommended a sentence of 24
years. Though attacked by Maryland prosecutors as ``outrageously''
lenient, a sentence of 24 years is considered quite severe in
Israel for a crime committed by a minor. If the agreement holds,
Sheinbein, who has already been held for nearly two years, could be
eligible for parole in 14 years, at the age of 33.
</P>
<P>
   In their comments in the courtroom Thursday, Israeli prosecutors
dismissed American criticism of their handling of the Sheinbein
case, saying they had no choice but to work within the strictures
of Israeli law.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of their sensitivity to this unusual scrutiny, the
prosecutors, defense attorneys and presiding magistrates reached an
very unusual agreement to allow television cameras in the
courtroom, though under strict limitations. Though there was no
videotaping of comments by the defendant himself, the excerpts from
statements by lawyers and judges on the evening news tonight
represented the first time many Israelis had watched the
proceedings of a criminal court. In court Thursday, Sheinbein
answered repeated questions about his culpability with a quiet
``yes'' in Hebrew, a language he was not believed to have spoken
previously.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Though he had never visited Israel before arriving as a fugitive
in 1997, Sheinbein successfully claimed citizenship based on his
father's birth in what was then British-ruled Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli diplomats and law-enforcement officials made no secret
of their desire to send the accused murderer back to the United
States. Government lawyers argued that a claim of citizenship
should be based not just on parentage but also on having some
demonstrable ``affinity'' with Israel. The Supreme Court upheld
Sheinbein's petition, stating that Israeli law states clearly that
the child of a citizen also has the right to citizenship and that
the validity of Sheinbein's father's citizenship was never in
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   As a citizen, Sheinbein was protected by a decades-old amendment
to Israel's extradition law prohibiting the deportation of any
Israeli facing a possible death sentence for crimes that were not
capital offenses in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein was 17 when he and a friend strangled Tello and cut up
his corpse. The friend committed suicide while in jail awaiting
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Israel forbids life sentences for minors, but in Maryland,
Sheinbein could have been tried as an adult. Maryland prosecutors
have said they would have sought life imprisonment, not death.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Parliament has since revoked this exception to its
extradition treaties, though the exception continues to apply to
Sheinbein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
