<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SHOOTING-MENTAL-NY     09-02 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SHOOTING-MENTAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SLAIN BY POLICE FEARED OWN VIOLENT IMPULSES, RECORDS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JULIAN E. BARNES and SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Brooklyn man fatally shot by police Monday had
told doctors at a psychiatric hospital that he increasingly feared
his own impulses toward violence and repeatedly took cocaine and
psychedelic drugs, his medical records show.
</P>
<P>
   The records portray Gidone Busch as a troubled person who once
threw furniture around a ward and had to be physically restrained.
The accounts come from doctors, social workers and nurses who
treated him for months at a time over the last three years when he
was committed, sometimes involuntarily, for treatment of
depression, manic behavior and aggression.
</P>
<P>
   They said that when he was not taking his prescribed
tranquilizers and anti-psychotic drugs, Busch was delusional,
believed himself to be the messiah, and was capable of doing harm
to himself and others.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Busch attacked the officers with a hammer, striking
one, and that they opened fire because they feared for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But in the days since the shooting, the use of deadly force by
police to subdue an emotionally disturbed man has been harshly
criticized by community leaders and some politicians. And Busch's
parents, who live on Long Island, insist that while their son was
mentally ill, he was never violent and could not have been a threat
to police.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what Busch's psychiatric history shows, the
information is unlikely to quiet police critics who insist that the
officers should have been able to restrain him without deadly
force.
</P>
<P>
   That history, and whether Busch should have been kept off the
streets and in psychiatric hospitals, are also likely to be
subjects of inquiry by the Brooklyn grand jury investigating the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The records of three of Busch's involuntary admissions to the
Payne-Whitney Clinic of New York Weill Cornell Center of
Presbyterian Hospital indicate that at least in his coherent
moments, he believed himself capable of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The confidential records from the hospital, formerly called New
York Hospital, were obtained by The New York Times through a staff
member at the hospital. Busch's family has acknowledged that they
acted to have him admitted to hospitals against his wishes for
treatment of the manic behavior and sometimes debilitating
depressions. Doctors said he suffered from schizoaffective
disorder, which is characterized by mood swings and symptoms of
schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The last time he was admitted, in December 1997, Busch told
doctors that he had come close to knifing a man who was sharing a
room in a hostel with him in Israel earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse at the hospital wrote in Busch's records during that
stay that the ``patient stated he has been becoming increasingly
physically violent and he did not know how to stop this from
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Busch dropped out of medical school 10 years ago after learning
he had an incurable kidney disease and embarked on a meandering
journey through various sects and movements of Orthodox and Hasidic
Judaism. The quest took him to Israel, where he lived on and off
for about seven years, according to his family.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Busch was hospitalized for psychosis three times
between 1992 and 1995, a period when he became so fervently
entrenched in religious rituals that his family feared he had
fallen in with an extremist cult.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   According to the medical records, Busch repeatedly refused to
admit he was ill or to take his medication during his hospital
stays. Following a pattern often seen in the mentally ill, he
stopped taking his drugs shortly after each release from the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, the doctors' notes over the years showed, tried to
help him, but could not deal with him if he was not on medication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
