<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-AR     09-02 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SLAIN IN CONFRONTATION WITH POLICE IS REMEMBERED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIX HILLS, N.Y. _ A few weeks ago, after visiting his
grandparents' graves, Gidone Busch wrote a poem about finding peace
among the souls of his family at rest. Thursday, the man slain by
police Monday night in Borough Park, Brooklyn, was buried next to
his Nanny and Papa after a solemn service that focused on his
sensitivity and generosity rather than his violent struggle with
mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stepped around the beds of this one and that one, each with
a face, each with a life _ I felt loved by each one,'' read the
poem, which Busch's brother, Glenn, recited at the funeral. ``Not a
soul in this place has any objection to honesty, or any objection
to truth.''
</P>
<P>
   About 350 mourners, nearly all friends and family, packed into
the plain chapel of the I.J. Morris funeral home here for a
memorial devoid of the politics that have swirled around Busch's
death. Police were not mentioned; nor was the mayor. Instead,
Busch's two brothers and two rabbis swallowed back tears as they
spoke of his sense of humor, sharp insights and spiritual quest to
grow closer to God.
</P>
<P>
   At Mount Hebron Cemetery in Flushing, Queens, under a blue sky
muted by a layer of cottony clouds, mourners spent more than 15
minutes shoveling dirt to fill Busch's grave, according to Jewish
tradition. His mother, Doris Busch Boskey, shook her head again and
again, as her husband wrapped his arms tight around her chest.
Busch's fiancee, Netanya Ullman, mumbled her own personal prayers,
one friend's hand comforting her shoulder, another's clutching her
waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let his memory be a lesson to us,'' Rabbi Yakov Saacks, one of
his teachers, said at the funeral. ``There are people who need
help. There are people who need guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   Busch, 31, who was called Gary, was shot 12 times by four police
officers outside his basement apartment Monday evening after he
struck one of them with a hammer, which he had inscribed with the
four letters of God's name in Hebrew. Having dropped out of medical
school upon discovering he had kidney disease, Busch was
hospitalized at least four times in the New York area for violent
behavior and psychiatric problems and had become a devoted follower
of Rabbi Nachman, a Hasidic mystic.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's funeral reflected Busch's journey in Judaism from a
secular childhood to years studying Torah in Israel to life in the
Orthodox enclave of Borough Park. Most in the chapel wore the black
nylon yarmulkes handed out by the funeral home, indicating they do
not normally cover their heads, as observant Jews do. Scattered
among the crowd were the knitted skullcaps favored by the modern
Orthodox. And in the back row, marked ``men only,'' sat a dozen
Hasidim in black hats and robes.
</P>
<P>
   While the rabbis invoked Busch's commitment to studying the
Torah and observing its mitzvot, or commandments, his brothers
spoke of his abiding closeness to family, telling stories filled
with both his laughter and his pain.
</P>
<P>
   His brother Gregg Busch recalled a Thanksgiving when Gary had
noticed he was upset and told him, ``Life is too short, you need to
be happy.'' His other brother, Glenn Busch, said that Gary told him
he had ``realized how fragile life is'' after having a patient die
and witnessing something else tragic in the emergency room during
medical school.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Busch joked about how Gary would ask what his brother was
ordering for dinner before agreeing to come over to study (pizza
and Chinese food would lure him). More somberly, he recalled a
visit to the psychiatric hospital when Gary pointed out that he and
his brother were the same height, and suggested they switch
clothes, and places.
</P>
<P>
   At restaurants, ``he would order extra bread,'' Glenn Busch
remembered. ``He would take it out afterwards and grab the first
person he would meet on the street who seemed like he needed a meal
and give it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Saacks and Rabbi Chaim Bausk of Young Israel of East
Northport, N.Y., whose homes Busch visited for many Sabbaths,
described a bright, articulate man who sometimes succumbed to dark
moods.
</P>
<P>
   Bausk noted that Busch was killed shortly before the High Holy
Days, when Jews repent and ask to be inscribed in the book of life
for another year. According to tradition, the most righteous people
die during this period, to help argue for mercy on behalf of the
rest of the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gidone, I have to ask for mechilah,'' Bausk said, using the
Hebrew word for forgiveness that is a hallmark of the upcoming
holidays. ``We should have had you over more. I should have pushed
you and pushed you more in my direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
