<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9408 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     09-02 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO STUCK WITH QB PLATOON, FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Junior Drew Bennett, a former walk-on with 11
college passes to his name, will take the field Saturday evening as
UCLA's starting quarterback against Boise State.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Bennett's first start since high school, four years
ago. In the opener that season, he threw three interceptions. Among
Bennett's unproven qualities are toughness, resiliency, leadership
and moxie. Even Bruins coach Bob Toledo admitted Bennett has ``not
looked great in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the first half, Toledo will replace Bennett with
Cory Paus, who has one year in UCLA's system and no game
experience. Paus will play a few series or perhaps a quarter, then
Bennett will return. Or maybe he won't. Toledo isn't sure how the
platoon will work or how long it will last. But he knows one thing:
He hates it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you need a (starting) quarterback and have him get the
most repetitions,'' he said. ``I don't know how long we'll go with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Most coaches dread quarterback uncertainty of any kind, whether
it's an unproven starter or a veteran platoon. But UCLA and Pac-10
history show quarterback quagmires aren't necessarily a recipe for
defeat. Either the situation resolves itself _ usually through
injury or superior performance _ or the quarterback platoon
survives and thrives. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
On Sept. 18, 1965, UCLA opened the season at Michigan State with a
rookie quarterback. His name: Gary Beban, future Heisman Trophy
winner. After a 13-3 loss to Michigan State, Beban led UCLA to the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, after an injury to starter Steve Bono, the Bruins asked
a former walk-on to rescue them from an 0-3-1 start. His name: Rick
Neuheisel. He led the Bruins to seven wins in their last eight
games, including the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, former coach Terry Donahue watched two quarterbacks
compete for the starting job in spring practice and training camp.
Six days before the season opener, Donahue picked a strong-armed
transfer as his starter. His name: Troy Aikman. He led the Bruins
to 20 wins in two years.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1995 season opener, injuries forced the Bruins to insert
a true freshman, three months out of high school, against No.12
Miami. His name: Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   This decade alone, Pac-10 quarterback platoons have beaten
Nebraska in the Holiday Bowl (Arizona last year), won the
conference championship (USC in 1995), and won the national title
(Washington in 1991).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doable, particularly to start the season and get a feel
for which guy is the best in games,'' said former USC and current
Nevada-Las Vegas coach John Robinson, who rotated Brad Otton and
Kyle Wachholtz in '95.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public reaction tends to be negative, but I think (Toledo)
has made the intelligent move. Rotating Bennett and Paus gives him
a chance to see which guy will provide the intangibles.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Although the three greatest quarterbacks in UCLA history (Beban,
Aikman, McNown) emerged from uncertainty, there's no guarantee of
success. In 1989, Bret Johnson won the job over Jim Bonds and the
Bruins won just three games. In 1990, Johnson transferred during
training camp, Bonds failed in the opener, and freshman Tommy
Maddox took control of a five-win season.
</P>
<P>
   It takes secure players and sensitive coaches for a quarterback
platoon to thrive. The coaches cannot play favorites, the
quarterbacks must agree to their roles unconditionally and the team
must accept two leaders. But the most important ingredient, by most
accounts, is a dominant running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's paramount to having a two-quarterback system work,''
said former UCLA quarterback Tom Ramsey, who shared time with Jay
Schroeder in 1980. ``Life on the quarterback is much easier when
there's a big-time guy at tailback, because the defense has to
focus on stopping the runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``What UCLA has this year with DeShaun Foster is comparable to
what we had with Freeman McNeil.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, McNeil rushed for 1,105 yards. In 1987, tailback Gaston
Green made Aikman's life easier with 1,098 yards. Karim
Abdul-Jabbar did the same for McNown in 1995, gaining a
school-record 1,571.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true across town in 1995, when USC tailback Delon
Washington supported Otton and Wachholtz with 1,109 yards, and at
Arizona last year, when tailback Trung Canidate gained 1,220 behind
rotating quarterbacks Keith Smith and Ortege Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   For UCLA to survive its quarterback platoon this year, Foster
and the young offensive line must gain ground consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the quarterback has to win games, it's harder for
everybody,'' Robinson said. ``My sense is that UCLA will be able to
run the ball. If that's true, they won't have to say, `OK,
quarterback, go win the game for us.' Instead, they can say, `OK,
quarterback, just don't make any mistakes.' That's a big
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson didn't plan to platoon Otton and Wachholtz in 1995, but
after several games neither player had taken charge. Otton finished
with 256 attempts, Wachholtz 171. USC won nine games and, behind
Otton's hot hand, beat Northwestern in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stuff about needing one quarterback because you need one
leader, that's a load of (bull),'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The psychological game might be as important to quarterback
platoons as a successful running game. Midway through last season,
Arizona offensive coordinator Dino Babers approached Smith and
Jenkins separately and asked if they wanted him to name a starter.
Both said no; they preferred the platoon.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Smith and Jenkins enjoyed splitting time. More likely,
their responses reflected fear of being left behind. Either way,
the system wouldn't have worked without both players being in total
agreement. As with Bennett and Paus, Smith and Jenkins are good
friends. There was no jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used a set of rules,'' Babers said. ``If my office door was
shut, that meant I was talking personal. I never talked football
without both guys present. We never started a meeting without both
guys present. Kids are sensitive about those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practice, we split it down the middle and let them handle
their own rotation. They were always joined at the hip. We never
sent one guy here and one guy there.''
</P>
<P>
   Platoons may be harder on coaches than on quarterbacks. It's
tough enough preparing one guy to play _ to understand the system
and the opposing defense, to memorize alignments and recognize
blitzes _ much less two.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the starter gets 80 percent of the snaps in practice.
In a platoon, repetitions are split 50-50. The result is two
quarterbacks who aren't fully prepared. In the case of Bennett and
Paus, the Bruins have two (begin ital)inexperienced(end ital)
quarterbacks who aren't fully prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason nobody in the NFL does it, and it's because
it generally doesn't work,'' Bruins offensive coordinator Al Borges
said. ``It fails a lot more times than it succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone into seasons not knowing who the quarterback will
be, and it always works itself out. Drew and Cory are both
even-tempered kids with good discretion. We're just going to be
patient and see what happens. A lot of times, I've found, it talks
back to you.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's season hinges on the answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
