u f BC-HSBC-REPUBLIC-NYT &LR;      09-02 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HSBC-REPUBLIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HSBC'S DEAL FOR REPUBLIC TO BE DELAYED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Japan, Britain)  (js) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ HSBC Holdings PlC said Thursday that its pending $10.3
billion acquisition of Republic New York Corp. would be delayed
because of an investigation of Republic's securities unit.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Japanese officials are investigating whether the
securities unit inflated the net asset value of an investment fund
owned by large institutional investors in Japan, The Wall Street
Journal reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Republic, the holding company for the Republic National Bank of
New York, declined to comment on the investigation. In a statement,
it said that it was cooperating with investigators and that it had
suspended the chief executive of the unit, James Edward Sweeney.
Republic also said that it had replaced the manager of the futures
department.
</P>
<P>
   HSBC, which announced on May 10 that it would pay $72 a share
for Republic, said in a statement Thursday that it hoped to close
the deal but that ``as a result of this investigation, it may take
longer than originally anticipated to complete the regulatory
process.''
</P>
<P>
   HSBC, Britain's largest bank, said it was waiting for more
details from Republic and investigators before completing the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to know what kind of exposure is involved and
if it is material and all of the rest,'' said Richard Beck, a
spokesman for HSBC in London. ``We have to wait for Republic to
update us with new information.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Republic fell 10.4 percent, or $7.185, to $62.1875, in
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. In London, shares of HSBC
fell 2.6 percent, to (PS)7.46, or $12.03.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they expected that the purchase would be completed
but were concerned that it might drag on for several months. The
two companies had hoped to complete the deal by the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unlucky timing for HSBC,'' said Simon Samuels, a banking
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney in London. Indeed, earlier this
week, talks between HSBC and the South Korean government for HSBC
to take control of Seoulbank fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems that Republic might face, ``the industrial
logic of the deal is very compelling,'' Samuels added. ``It is
likely that it will delay the deal but not scuttle it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation stems from an inspection by Japanese
regulators of a Tokyo office that is affiliated with a client of
Republic's securities unit. Though Republic did not identify the
client, Bloomberg News said Thursday that the client was Princeton
Economics International, a New Jersey company. Princeton Economics
owns Cresvale International Ltd., which specializes in brokering
and underwriting equities and bonds in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Japanese regulators made an unannounced audit of
Cresvale's Tokyo operations as part of a wider scrutiny of foreign
securities firms.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Princeton Economics could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Princeton Economics is Martin Armstrong, who is
one of the largest individual traders of silver futures on the
Comex division of the New York Mercantile Exchange. He is also
involved in currency hedging in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who headed the Republic securities unit, had had
previous run-ins with regulators. In February, he agreed to pay the
Securities and Exchange Commission a $25,000 fine over accusations
that the unit had paid rebates to an investment advisory firm. In
settling with the SEC, the Republic unit and Sweeney neither
admitted nor denied the allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
