A9414 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LAD     09-02 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORBON RIDES OUT BUMPY STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers weren't exactly worried sick that
left-hander Pedro Borbon suddenly couldn't get anyone out, but they
were concerned. The situational lefty out of the bullpen was
perhaps a blown chance away from seeing his role diminish.
</P>
<P>
   Then he blew away Milwaukee lefties Geoff Jenkins and Jeromy
Burnitz in Tuesday's 5-3 win. A big sigh came out of Dodger
Stadium, partly because of Borbon's past. Before stunning everyone
and making the team out of spring training, Borbon hadn't pitched
in the big leagues since 1996 because of elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Borbon, by no means, is saying he's turned the corner and back
to his dominating pre-All-Star break form, when he led the staff
with a 1.64 ERA. But Borbon certainly believes he's done with the
horrific spell in which he had a 10.50 ERA since the break and saw
his ERA rise to 4.00 before his outing against the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was mental fatigue, but it hasn't been arm fatigue,''
Borbon said. ``It was just a lack of aggressiveness and doubting
myself a little bit. I expected the worst to happen and it did.
It's a lack of confidence. You really expect something bad to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But rarely does something bad happen when Borbon faces
left-handers, who are batting .136 (11 for 81) against him.
Right-handers are hitting .256 (22 for 86). ``I discovered it
wasn't mechanical, it was mental,'' Borbon said. ``I have to go out
and pitch like it's the seventh game of the World Series every
time. I hate to say it, but it shocked me when I didn't succeed. I
hit a bump in the road and I didn't know how to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehabbing righties: Dodgers right-handers Robinson Checo and
Antonio Osuna both came out of their rehab appearances Wednesday
with Single-A San Bernardino feeling fine.
</P>
<P>
   Checo, on the disabled list with a groin injury, allowed one hit
and struck out two in two innings of an 11-0 win against San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who's spurned a recommendation by Dr. Frank Jobe, struck
out one in a perfect inning of work. Osuna has pitched in five
games this season and had agreed to have reconstructive elbow
surgery before changing his mind a month ago. Osuna is trying to
pitch through a partial tear of a ligament in his elbow. Neither
player is expected to join the Dodgers on the six-game trip that
begins today in Chicago and finishes in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Not only did the Dodgers draw a
season-low 23,616 for Wednesday's twilight game against Milwaukee,
but the three-game series drew 84,907, an average of 28,302 per
game.... First baseman Eric Karros is on pace to hit 35 homers and
drive in 111 runs. The home runs would be a career-high and the RBI
would tie a career high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-99 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990902.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
