<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9417 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-BOEING-SPI &LR;      09-02 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING'S CONDIT STILL LEAVES OPEN THE POSSIBILITY OF FLEXIBLE
WORKWEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN AND JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A day after The Boeing Co. settled its biggest labor
contract, Chairman Phil Condit resurrected one of the thorniest
issues, suggesting the company could boost productivity by
experimenting with flexible workweeks.
</P>
<P>
   Condit envisions pilot projects with the International
Association of Machinists that would introduce alternative
schedules _ under which employees work shorter or longer shifts or
into the weekend _ as part of a broader plan to create a leaner
aerospace company.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of mandatory changes in the workweek was a flash point
during negotiations, and the union threatened to strike if the
company tried to force non-traditional schedules on its members.
</P>
<P>
   Condit, however, wants to ``experiment'' with the idea under a
7-year-old provision that requires both the company and the union
to agree before a schedule is changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can work with the union to say, `OK let's try a
couple ways; let's experiment,''' Condit said Thursday in an
exclusive interview with the Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   The union says it simply is not interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members don't want a non-traditional workweek,'' said Bill
Johnson, president of the union's District Lodge 751, which covers
the Puget Sound region. ``It's not an item of discussion. ... There
is no wiggle room on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit argued that many workers misunderstand the concept, in
which employees could work their 40-hour weeks in three or four
days, including weekends. They worry the company will force parents
to abandon their children on weekends and create other disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, both sides could discuss pilot projects that
might affect only certain workers and functions and could be
voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``not that we are going to come roaring in here with a
great big full-blown proposal,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   Altering the work schedule is only one line in Boeing's
blueprint to boost productivity, lower costs and win new airplane
orders. If the company fails, it will cede both customers and jobs
to its Toulouse, France-based rival, Airbus Industrie, Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, which addressed many of the union's concerns, was
another step in creating a more productive work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means people that you pay well have to be productive in the
context of the business,'' Condit said. ``I want a highly motivated
work force ... excited about what they are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Condit is eager to employ workshops that bring
together Machinists, engineers and others to devise better ways to
build airplanes. Those groups, known as Accelerated Improvement
Workshops, will examine a range of issues, such as why an airplane
part didn't fit initially and why a mechanic was forced to waste
time searching for tools and parts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most important for Condit, and the investors who buy and sell
his company's stock, is that Boeing must become more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   The aerospace giant can't allow planes worth more than $150
million to idle at its plants, as Airbus becomes an increasingly
potent competitor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A ``747 sitting on the flight line out there is $160 million
worth of stuff, and every day it sits there, we are holding it and
not getting paid for it,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing defused its most explosive labor situation Wednesday,
when Machinists approved Boeing's contract offer, and Condit
attributed much of the success to the fact that both camps have
been talking for two years.
</P>
<P>
   If Machinists had rejected the company's offer Wednesday, they
would have crippled Boeing's production lines as the company
recovered from two years of problems. Instead, workers embraced the
offer, passing it with an 86 percent margin.
</P>
<P>
   Condit made clear that although negotiating a good contract for
the company was important, it will mean little if Boeing isn't
competitive with Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two competitors,'' he said. ``We know who they are.
It's us and them. If we don't get the orders, they do. It's that
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   If Boeing loses to Airbus, nothing in the contract will protect
jobs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fail to win orders, if we are not competitive with
Airbus, the work here declines,'' he said. ``If we are competitive,
we have a real opportunity to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit said it's time that Airbus makes it on its own, without
help from the government subsidies that it has long enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, British Aerospace, one of the four companies
that make up Airbus Industrie, said it had asked Britain's
government for an $800 million loan to help fund its participation
in the A3XX, the planned Airbus superjumbo jetliner that will seat
more passengers than Boeing's 747.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1992 agreement between the United States and European
authorities, the Airbus consortium can get up to 30 percent of a
new plane's development cost from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus has said the A3XX will cost at least $12 billion to
develop, so it stands to get about $3.6 billion from the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has long argued the Airbus subsidies have created an
unfair playing field, and it has urged the U.S. government to try
to prevent subsidies from being used to help develop the A3XX,
which Airbus hopes will drive a stake through Boeing's 747
monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to pay it back (government subsidies),'' Condit said
of Airbus, ``but the conditions under which they pay it back are
very different from the world we live in.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than paying back the loan on a fixed rate regardless of
whether the market develops, as Boeing must do when it borrows from
a bank, Airbus pays back government loans when it delivers planes,
Condit said. And if the market does not develop, Airbus is off the
hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changes the fundamental financial equation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Condit said he is encouraged that the World Trade Organization
is moving toward rules-based trade requirements in a global
economy.
</P>
<P>
   `That's what the WTO is all about,'' he said. ``How do you build
a set of rules-based trade requirements that say, `We are going to
live in a global economy and there have to be rules'?
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, the faster we get there, the better
off we are. I'm also not going to stand around and say we can't
compete in the interim, because I think we can.''
</P>
<P>
   On other issues, Condit said:
</P>
<P>
   _He is a little more optimistic than he was about 747
production. Because of the economic downturn in Asia that saw many
airlines in that region delay or cancel orders for widebody jets,
Boeing had warned that production of the 747, the company's most
profitable plane, could be cut to one per month next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's looking better than it did,'' he said. ``I'm not
breathing easy yet, but I'm breathing better.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit said he continues to see signs that the situation in Asia
may be improving.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, China Airlines, Taiwan's largest airline, agreed to
buy 13 747-400 cargo planes for $3.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   _Condit defended his second in command, Boeing President Harry
Stonecipher. Stonecipher was a lightning rod for union members'
criticism during the past two weeks, as they blamed him for many of
the hard-line positions the company took in the early stages of the
contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry sometimes gets blamed for things that he had no part at
all in,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   _Condit said the contract represented a new chapter for Boeing,
but added.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't just turn the page, though, and say, `Everything is
now different.' There are opportunities there to work together
productively. And there is an opportunity to fail to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world will continue to change ... it won't look the same
three years from now. ... Airbus will change. We are going to deal
with new designs for airplanes. ... If labor is willing to work
with the company, I think we can be successful. If not, it's likely
that somebody else will get the jobs''
</P>
<P>
   Condit noted that a number of years ago, longshore workers'
union said they would never handle containers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what you discover is that's the only way stuff comes. If
you decide that's too hard, it all goes somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you say, nope, it's better to handle containers and have a
job than to be really strict about this. It's that change that's
always the hard part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
